<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-03 00:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5342 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-HSIA-TRIAL-1STLD-WRIT     03-03 1189
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HSIA-TRIAL-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER GORE FUND-RAISER CONVICTED ON 5 COUNTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to insert passage about Reno in 15th graf.)  
(mk) 
 By NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Maria Hsia, a longtime political fund-raiser for
Vice President Al Gore, was convicted Thursday of all five felony
counts against her for her role in arranging more than $100,000 in
illegal donations to the Democratic Party and its candidates in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   Of that amount, $55,000 was contributed to the Democratic
National Committee in connection with the vice president's
much-criticized visit to a Buddhist temple in the Los Angeles area.
The event, at the Hsi Lai Temple in the community of Hacienda
Heights, has shadowed Gore throughout the current political season,
with a variety of his opponents referring to it in efforts to
remind the public of the Clinton-Gore organization's fund-raising
embarrassments.
</P>
<P>
   As her federal jurors filed in Thursday, Hsia (pronounced shaw),
a 48-year-old Taiwan-born American citizen who works as an
immigration consultant in Los Angeles, consulted a Chinese
fortune-telling book to try to divine her fate. She then sat
impassively as the jury delivered its verdicts for what the
government had described as her masterminding an evasion of
election laws by disguising the true source of campaign
contributions.
</P>
<P>
   All five counts against Hsia, who did not testify at her
three-week-long trial, charged her with causing finance officials
of the Democratic National Committee and Democratic campaigns to
file false contribution statements with the Federal Election
Commission. Although conviction on these counts can mean a
years-long prison sentence, federal sentencing guidelines make it
more likely that she will serve only a brief term, if any.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of the Buddhist temple, Justice Department
prosecutors charged that Hsia had arranged for nuns and monks there
to write checks to make it appear that they were the donors to the
Democratic National Committee. In reality, they were only ``straw
donors,'' reimbursed by the temple itself, which, as a religious,
tax-exempt institution, is prohibited from making political
donations.
</P>
<P>
   In other cases, the $1,000 limit on contributions to
presidential campaigns was evaded by wealthy Chinese-Americans who
testified at the trial that Hsia had helped them find straw donors
for their contributions to the Clinton-Gore re-election committee.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's opponents have noted that his 1996 fund-raising efforts
also included 56 telephone calls he made from the White House to
solicit donations for the party, in apparent violation of federal
law and longtime practice. When those calls became public
knowledge, he insisted that ``no controlling legal authority'' had
barred them. He has also been faulted for holding 23 ``coffees''
for wealthy donors at the White House in addition to co-hosting
eight others with President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bradley, the former senator from New Jersey who is
challenging Gore for the Democratic nomination, has repeatedly said
that Gore will be especially vulnerable in the general election
because of his record on fund raising.
</P>
<P>
   During the trial, prosecutors portrayed the Democratic National
Committee, the Clinton-Gore committee and Rep. Patrick Kennedy,
D-R.I., who also received donations through Hsia, as unaware of her
actions and thus unwitting beneficiaries. Gore did not appear in
court but his name was mentioned throughout the trial and jurors
were shown a videotape of his April 29, 1996, visit to the Buddhist
temple.
</P>
<P>
   That tape could be troublesome for Gore during his presidential
campaign. Now that the trial is over, the tape is supposed to be
released publicly and Republican political operatives have already
asked for a copy, presumably to use in political advertisements to
embarrass Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Gore had initially described his visit to the temple as
``community outreach,'' part of the Democrats' effort to build
closer ties to the Asian-American community. He later acknowledged
that he knew the visit was ``finance-related.''
</P>
<P>
   In New York Thursday, where he was campaigning in advance of
Tuesday's set of important primaries, Gore told reporters: ``The
jury has rendered its verdict. It's a hard day for her. She has
been a friend and a political supporter but since this matter is
still in the courts I am not going to comment on it further.''
</P>
<P>
   The verdict, which came after nearly 10 hours of deliberations
over three days, was a much-desired victory for the Justice
Department's special task force investigating campaign finance
abuses that occurred in the 1996 election.
</P>
<P>
   Hsia has been only the second figure embroiled in the Democratic
fund-raising scandal to face a full trial so far.
</P>
<P>
   Other party fund-raisers, including John Huang and Yah Lin Trie,
have pleaded guilty to charges growing out of the scandal, and
Pauline Kanchanalak, another fairly obscure figure, is awaiting
trial. But no senior Democratic National Committee officials have
ever been charged, and Attorney General Janet Reno was roundly
criticized for deciding against the appointment of an independent
counsel to investigate the party's fund-raising.
</P>
<P>
   The only other figure to be brought to trial by the Justice
Department task force was Franklin L. Haney, a Tennessee
businessman, who was acquitted last July on 42 counts of disguising
his own contributions by using straw donors to Gore's campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   But Haney's case was unrelated to the heart of the larger
scandal about the Democratic Party's efforts to mine the
Asian-American community for contributions.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Paul Friedman has yet to rule on motions brought by
lawyers for Hsia (pronounced ``shaw'') to dismiss the five counts.
Because of that, he did not immediately set a date for sentencing.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Luque, Hsia's lawyer, noting that it was extraordinary for
a federal judge to defer a ruling on dismissal motions until after
a verdict, said, ``It's not over yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Luque had argued that the reports filed with the Federal
Election Commission _ false reports, according to prosecutors _
were filed by the campaign treasurers for the DNC, the Clinton-Gore
committee and Kennedy's re-election committee, none of whom Hsia
had ever met.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the five counts carries a five-year jail term and
$250,000 fine under the law. But if Hsia's conviction is upheld,
her sentence would be governed by complex federal sentencing
guidelines that weigh factors such as prior convictions, of which
Hsia has none. She would also benefit under the guidelines because
there is no allegation that any money was stolen. As a result she
could receive a relatively light jail sentence or perhaps even
probation.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Party Chairman Jim Nicholson said of the verdict,
``My faith in the jury system is once again restored.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicholson ridiculed the Justice Department's theory that the
vice president and the Democratic Party were unwitting victims of
Hsia's scheme. ``It's time to get beyond the small-fry and take on
the major players like Al Gore,'' he said in a statement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
