<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAX-BREAK-EDUC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE BACKS EDUCATION SAVINGS MEASURE 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By LIZETTE ALVAREZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate on Thursday easily passed a bill that
would provide modest tax breaks for parents who save for elementary
and secondary school expenses, including private school tuition,
but it faced a likely veto.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton vetoed similar legislation in 1998, calling it
``bad education policy and bad tax policy,'' and is likely to do so
again this year if it reaches his desk. The House is expected to
take up the bill later this year.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate passed the bill, which comes at a time when polls
show that voters rank education as their chief concern, by a vote
of 61-37, securing a modicum of bipartisan support for a measure
that Republicans have pushed unsuccessfully for three years. Nine
Democrats voted for the bill this time around, but that left it
still short of the number needed to override a presidential veto.
</P>
<P>
   ``With this legislation, no one gets hurt, everybody gets
helped: public, private, parochial, home, whatever,'' said Sen.
Paul Coverdell, R-Ga., who sponsored the bill with Sen. Robert G.
Torricelli, D-N.J. ``No one is being gouged. No one is paying a
price at the expense of somebody else.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill would allow family members, employers and other
sponsors to put as much as $2,000 a year for each elementary and
secondary school student into a savings account that could be used
for expenses related to education, including tutoring, computers
and parochial or private school expenses.
</P>
<P>
   The interest on the money and on the withdrawals from the
account would be tax-free and could be rolled over for college
expenses. The accounts, which would cost the federal government
$7.3 billion over 10 years, would be phased out for individuals
making more than $95,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans maintain that the bill simply expands on the popular
college savings accounts that Clinton signed into law with much
fanfare. ``This makes that account four times larger,'' Coverdell
said in a recent floor debate.
</P>
<P>
   And they argue that while the bill's small tax breaks do not
solve all the woes facing the nation's schools, it offers a fresh
approach that, at the very least, could persuade parents to save
and give them a greater say in their child's education.
</P>
<P>
   That tug between greater private or local control and greater
federal control is at the heart of the parties' philosophical
differences over education, and it provides endless fodder for
campaigning politicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have never argued that offering this special savings
account would solve every education problem in America,''
Torricelli said. ``But they are the opening shot in a revolution in
American education.''
</P>
<P>
   But most other Democrats, in what has become a perennial
showdown over the bill, said the savings accounts were nothing but
covert school vouchers that would redirect taxpayer money from
public schools to private schools.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have made vouchers one of their crusades for
revamping ailing schools, arguing that by offering parents a choice
between public and private schools, public schools would be forced
to improve.
</P>
<P>
   The notion is anathema to most Democrats and is staunchly
opposed by teachers' unions, which say it would simply drain
resources away from public schools, which teach 90 percent of the
nation's children.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is to strengthen public schools, not abandon them,''
said Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, the Massachusetts Democrat who has
spearheaded the bill's opposition in the Senate. ``Our goal is to
help all children get a good education _ not deny them the extra
help they need to meet the goal.''
</P>
<P>
   Senator Coverdell disputed the pronouncement that the savings
accounts were like vouchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not a voucher,'' he said. ``It will help people in
public schools, but statistically insignificant is the number of
people who might, because they have a savings account, change
schools. I am sure it will happen, but it would be insignificant.''
</P>
<P>
   Knowing that voters view them as the guardians of education,
Democrats clearly relish the debate every year. They hammer away at
the bill, arguing that it benefits mostly wealthier Americans with
children in private schools since few low-income parents can afford
to sock enough money away to make the tax breaks worthwhile.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, they say the money could be better spent on more
pressing needs, including building more schools, renovating
existing ones, hiring more teachers and improving teacher training.
Efforts by Democrats to address those issues through amendments
were defeated.
</P>
</TEXT>
