<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS' TAYLOR GOES SHOPPIING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Kings general manager Dave Taylor returned
Thursday afternoon from the NHL general manager's meetings in Palm
Springs without the gritty forward he is seeking, but he says he
expects plenty of action league wide before the March 14 trading
deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor, whose team is sixth in the Western Conference, has
softened his stance over not trading for a player that will be a
free agent at the end of the year. That means Montreal's Shayne
Corson and Atlanta's Kelly Buchberger, two players with
considerable playoff experience, is still being considered.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can make a move to improve the team we will,'' Taylor
said. ``It will depend on how it will affect us financially in the
short term and the long term.''
</P>
<P>
   The Canadians, disappointing most of the season, made a move
late last month, but have dropped off lately. Wednesday night, they
traded disgruntled defenseman Vladimir Malakhov to New Jersey for
Sheldon Souray and a draft choice.
</P>
<P>
   Malakhov was suspended by the Canadiens last month for skiing
while rehabilitating a knee injury, but the trade could mean
Montreal is ready to keep dealing.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor said he recognizes the need for balanced scoring from his
top two lines. But he refused to confirm that the club has been
trying to move second line winger Donald Audette, who has struggled
since returning from six weeks on injured reserve (sprained left
ankle).
</P>
<P>
   The Kings second unit has faltered in the past two weeks and
Audette's return to the line has been questioned by some teammates.
Audette, earning $2.3 million this season, will be an unrestricted
free agent at the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping it going: It wasn't surprising Carolina scored the first
goal Thursday night. They got four in the third period Wednesday
night in a 7-5 loss at Phoenix, the first of a three-game trip.
</P>
<P>
   The Hurricanes fell behind 6-1 in the third and allowed a
short-handed goal to Jeremy Roenick. Rod Brind 'Amour and Gary
Roberts both were a minus 5 in the game. It was Roberts first
action since missing seven straight with a groin strain.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts was back in the lineup Thursday against the Kings. Brind
'Amour, who came over from Philadelphia in exchange for Keith
Primeau, has been struggling, although he did have an assist in
Sami Kapinen's first-period goal. In his first 16 games with the
Hurricanes, Brind 'Amour had two goals, five points and a minus 11.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
