r f BC-GM-EVRECALL-LADN     03-03 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GM-EVRECALL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GM RECALLS ITS FIRST ELECTRIC VEHICLES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY CHRIS SIEROTY 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ General Motors Corp. said it was pulling the plug
on its first-generation electric vehicles, recalling about 900 cars
and trucks because they could catch fire while being recharged.
</P>
<P>
   About 450 Generation I EV1 electric cars are being permanently
taken off the road because of excessive heat that builds up while
their batteries are being recharged. They were primarily leased to
customers in California and Arizona between December 1996 and
August 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem with the charge port on the Generation I EV1 is
not fixable,'' said Bob Purcell, executive director of GM's
advanced-technology group, on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The sleek, futuristic looking cars will be picked up from
wherever they are garaged. GM will also provide rental cars for EV1
owners until other arrangements can be made, Purcell said.
</P>
<P>
   Also recalled were 450 Chevrolet S-10 Electric pickup trucks,
which were sold to fleet customers between May 1997 and December
1999 nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Owners of the S-10 electric pickups will be offered repairs to
their trucks or the opportunity to purchase, at a reduced price,
another GM vehicle, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   The charge port on the vehicles has a design flaw that only
affects recharging and doesn't cause a problem during driving or
when the vehicles are parked, Purcell said.
</P>
<P>
   The defective part is a 10-pound piece that would have to be
redesigned.
</P>
<P>
   ``To find a space to package a fix into is very difficult,''
said John Hepke, director of propulsion engineering for GM's
advanced technology vehicle. ``Every inch is taken up in the
vehicle.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Generation I EV1, the charge port is located just below
the vehicle's hood, while on the S-10 pickup, it is below the front
license plate.
</P>
<P>
   GM has begun notifying owners of these vehicles and asked them
to disconnect their cars from the charging ports. The company
wouldn't estimate the cost of the recall.
</P>
<P>
   ``A few people ... used (the EV1) as their primary vehicle. Most
customers have more than one car at home,'' Purcell said.
</P>
<P>
   GM's 1999 Generation II EV1s were not affected by the recall. GM
began leasing those vehicles in December, and they continue to
market the electric cars in several states, including California.
</P>
<P>
   Democrat Assemblyman Scott Wildman of Glendale, an EV1 driver
who is campaigning for the 21st District Senate seat being vacated
by state Sen. Adam Schiff, D-Pasadena, said his first-generation
EV1 electric vehicle has been in the shop for more than a month
because the car's range had dropped from 70 miles to around 40
miles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't aware they were being recalled,'' said Wildman, whose
three-year lease was about to expire. ``I am now exploring hybrid
and other alternative fuel vehicles.''
</P>
<P>
   Southern California Edison operates about five or six
first-generation EV1 models and about 13 Chevy S-10 pickups.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will just replace them (EV1s) with regular gasoline
vehicles until they are replaced,'' said Diane Whittenberg, vice
president of corporate communications for the company based in
Rosemead, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   As for the utility's fleet of S-10s, Whittenberg said, ``We will
wait to see what they do to fix the charge ports.''
</P>
<P>
   Dave Ashuckian, supervisor of the light duty vehicle program for
the California Energy Commission, said the state operates more than
100 electric vehicles. He does not know how many are affected by
the recall.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Van Amberg, vice president of marketing for CalStart, an
advanced transportation technology consortium headquartered in
Pasadena, said the recall is difficult for GM.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this recall is a tough one for General Motors,'' he
said. ``Toughest because they have a good product out there now
that isn't affected by the recall.''
</P>
<P>
   GM announced it was building the EV1 in 1996 and has spent $350
million to develop the electric vehicle. EV1 leases cost between
$400 and $600 a month, and for the money their owners get a range
of about 70 miles. The 1999 EV1s have about a 100-mile range.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike more conventional vehicles, the automaker's EV1
production has always been built in blocks of 500 cars. GM built
its first 500 vehicles in 1996 for the 1997 model year and built
another 500 in 1998 and 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``We remain committed to advanced-technology vehicles,'' Purcell
said. ``While it (the EV1) may be small in number, it is large in
enthusiasm in terms of the customer base.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael P. Ward, an automotive analyst with Salomon Smith Barney
in New York, said the recall was ``not big enough to pay attention
to.''
</P>
<P>
   GM shares fell 31 cents Thursday to close at $73.31.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
