<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-03 00:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5353 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-REPUBS-DEBATE-1STLD-W     03-03 1095
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPUBS-DEBATE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
  
 BUSH AND McCAIN TRADE CHARGES OVER POLITICS AND RELIGION  
 (Subs for rewriting throughout) 
 (sw) 
 By TODD S. PURDUM and ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The setting was surreal, with Gov. George W. Bush
standing at a lectern and his main opponent, Sen. John McCain,
beaming from a television monitor a few feet away. Yet all the
bitterness of the Republican presidential race was on full display
on Thursday night as the rivals rehashed mutual recriminations in a
debate four days before a round of critical primaries across the
country.
</P>
<P>
   Capping weeks of acrimony, McCain defended the telephone calls
that his campaign made to Roman Catholic voters in Michigan,
alerting them to Bush's appearance at Bob Jones University, while
Bush once more protested about being characterized as
anti-Catholic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to tell people exactly what Governor Bush had
done,'' McCain said, arguing ``I did not call him an anti-Catholic
bigot.'' McCain said he had simply pointed out that Bush appeared
at the school and waited weeks to repudiate its anti-Catholic
teachings, ``a factual statement and one that I stand by.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush quickly shot back, ``Yeah. I appreciate that. If you don't
think those phone calls labeled me an anti-Catholic bigot, then you
weren't paying attention to what your campaign was putting out.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The clear message,'' Bush added, ``was I was an anti-Catholic
bigot. That's why people all over the country were wondering about
my heart for a while. The good news is that America rejects that
kind of politics.''
</P>
<P>
   The charge and countercharge came even as each man started out
trying to stand above the fray and present a positive case for
himself in a debate that ranged across foreign policy, education,
gun control, the death penalty and abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Bush called himself ``somebody who's been a proven leader,
someone who has set an agenda, somebody who has risen above
politics.'' And McCain, who used a satellite link-up from a studio
in St. Louis to participate, turned a question about his
characterization of some leaders of the religious right as ``agents
of intolerance'' into a statement that ``ours is a message of
inclusion.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain, who is struggling to win the support of core
Republicans, also took pains to say that he would not follow the
model of his hero Theodore Roosevelt by bolting the party if he was
not nominated, declaring: ``I am a loyal Republican.''
</P>
<P>
   Alan Keyes, the third candidate, was often asked questions
seeking his reflections on the nation's moral health, but he made
his most pointed remarks when he accused McCain of not vigorously
opposing abortion, and said he could never support his candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   By far the testiest moments in the hourlong debate concerned the
tussle between Bush and McCain over religion and politics.
</P>
<P>
   Bush once again said he regretted that he did not speak out
against the teachings of Bob Jones University when he visited the
institution in South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked about bringing people together,'' he said, ``so
America can achieve its greatness. I talked about lifting the
spirit and the soul of this country. I regret I did not speak out
against that school's anti-Catholic bias. I missed an
opportunity,'' he said. ``I make no excuses. I make no excuses.''
</P>
<P>
   But then he turned to McCain and said, ``What I regret is the
politics of smearing somebody's reputation. That's what I regret.
And I don't appreciate it one bit.''
</P>
<P>
   When McCain asked for time to respond under debate rules
allowing rebuttals to attacks, Bush said, ``I didn't attack Senator
McCain.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain on Thursday night gave his most detailed explanation for
his sharp attacks on Jerry Falwell and Pat Robertson, by describing
how they differed with him in their views of President Clinton, for
example. ``I voted to impeach President Clinton,'' McCain said. ``I
don't believe he's a murderer. Mr. Falwell believes that he's a
murderer. Mr. Robertson has espoused some cockamamie theories about
the Freemasons. I believe they have led some very good and
wonderful people in a message of intolerance.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain and Bush each seemed uncomfortable at times on issues of
domestic policy. Asked what he had accomplished on education across
18 years in Congress, McCain had to reach back to his years in the
House of Representatives to cite his service on the House Education
Committee and spoke vaguely of ``being involved in the effort in my
state for reform in many ways.''
</P>
<P>
   The answer was so vague that the Bush campaign promptly put out
a statement mocking it.
</P>
<P>
   Bush seemed equally uncomfortable on the issue of gun control.
Asked about whether trigger locks on guns should be mandatory, he
responded, ``Ask about education, will you?''
</P>
<P>
   Then he said that while he didn't mind trigger locks, ``the
question is, how do we enforce it? Are we going to have trigger
lock police knocking on peoples' doors, saying `Show me your
trigger lock?'''
</P>
<P>
   Bush and McCain also exchanged sharp words on the issue of
campaign finance. Bush repeated his charge that McCain, who rails
against the ``iron triangle'' of special interests in Washington,
was ``ringing it like a dinner bell with all those fundraisers with
lobbyists.'' McCain countered: ``I don't think so,'' and added:
``If I'm ringing it like a dinner bell, you've got both feet in the
trough.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain was asked about his temperament, and whether he sought to
portray those who disagreed with him as not just wrong, but wicked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it should be a source of worry,'' McCain said.
Speaking about his campaign, he added: ``I believe that I've
conducted it with honor, with dignity and a way that has made me
and the people surrounding me proud. That's why we have attracted
so many young people, so much enthusiasm to _ to our banner.''
</P>
<P>
   The face-off came four days before the critical Super Tuesday
primaries, including the powerhouses New York and California. With
polls showing Bush leading by nearly 2 to 1 among Republicans in
California and McCain pinning more of his hopes on New York, the
Republican race has become increasingly contentious, and the debate
itself, sponsored by CNN and The Los Angeles Times, almost became
the victim.
</P>
<P>
   In a week of feint and parry, McCain said he would not debate
because he had planned a campaign schedule in New York and New
England when Bush had earlier refused to commit. Then the senator
abruptly changed his mind and agreed to participate by satellite.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
