<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOT-COMS ARE HAVING A DRAMATIC EFFECT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: Although consumer e-commerce remains minuscule in
retailing's grand scheme of things, The Economist recently
conducted an exhaustive survey of the phenomenon and concluded that
``most companies must become Internet companies if they are to
survive.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not enough, the editors cautioned, to add a Web site to an
existing business, because ``the whole business needs to be
redesigned around the cost-saving, communication-easing properties
of the Net.''
</P>
<P>
   At this point in the process of evaluating the Internet's
business potential, the magazine's in-depth exploration of
dot-commerce was a much needed extension of the dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   The importance of dot-commerce at this point in its history
isn't about its still modest sales volumes or the wild stock market
rides it provides investors in its fledgling ventures. One of the
key conclusions reached by The Economist is that the Internet's
importance in the here and now is its increasing influence on how
business is transacted.
</P>
<P>
   Surveys conducted in America last year, for instance, showed
that while less than 3 percent of all new-car sales were made over
the Web, fully 40 percent of new-car buyers used the Internet to
research their purchase.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes last month published a ``Best of the Web'' special
edition, including a segment about how ``car dealers are both
fighting the Internet and embracing it.'' Even as dealers pursue
state laws barring purchases direct from manufacturers, they still
must deal with better-informed consumers made savvier by Internet
comparison shopping. Forbes listed five Web sites under the heading
``Honk If You Hate Haggling'' and urged taking advantage of the
Internet to become a more efficient shopper.
</P>
<P>
   What most consumers probably don't realize is that Internet
commerce is still very much the province of the corporate world.
About 80 percent of last year's estimated $150 billion worth of
worldwide e-commerce was the business-to-business variety, The
Economist noted. Consumer e-commerce, meanwhile, is only about 1
percent of U.S. retail sales.
</P>
<P>
   These numbers no doubt have fooled some business managers into
not taking the Internet as seriously as they probably should. Even
though e-companies are for the most part hemorrhaging money serving
tiny market shares, the trend is what's important.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the early players don't survive, the trend points toward
a watershed event in marketplace history. The failures, after all,
of many pioneering enterprises in the railroad, auto and airline
businesses didn't make the rise of those industries any less
important to the progress of the Industrial Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   And so it's likely to be with the Internet. Many business
traditionalists resent the dot-com companies for their otherworldly
stock valuations and blame them for what they perceive as a
misallocation of capital as their own stocks get hammered.
</P>
<P>
   Die-hards, however, ``ignore the Internet at their own peril,''
The Economist warned.
</P>
<P>
   Even when the dot-com bubble deflates, as it certainly will
sooner or later, the signals currently being sent by
Internet-related commerce should be heeded as an early warning of
future challenges.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-03-00 0041EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
