<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STOCK-OPTIONS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGENCY RULING JEOPARDIZES EMPLOYEE STOCK OPTION PLANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: Business executives told a congressional subcommittee
Thursday that their companies would not offer stock options to
hourly employees if opinions expressed in a Department of Labor
advisory letter are put into effect.
</P>
<P>
   The advisory letter, issued last year in response to a company's
inquiry, said the value of employees' stock options should be
factored into their regular pay rates for the purpose of overtime
calculation.
</P>
<P>
   The opinion said in part that an employee's profit from
exercised options must be allocated over the period of time in
which it was earned, ending with the workweek in which the option
was exercised and going back to the date of the employee's right to
purchase the shares.
</P>
<P>
   J. Randall MacDonald, GTE's executive vice president of human
resources, was among corporate officers who prepared testimony for
the U.S. House Workforce Protections Subcommittee. MacDonald
warned, ``The practical fact is that unless this problem is fixed
quickly, nonexempt employees will lose access'' to stock option
programs.
</P>
<P>
   Human resource officials and labor leaders say the threat to
employee stock option plans is wrongheaded at a time when equity
stakes for workers are considered to be effective tools for
motivating and retaining employees.
</P>
<P>
   T. Michael Kerr, administrator of the Labor Department's Wage
and Hour Division, said the department did not intend to freeze
hourly workers out of stock option benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Kerr said the department would work to amend provisions of the
Fair Labor Standards Act, which sets the overtime pay requirements
that influenced the advisory letter's opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Companies such as GTE indicated they would stop offering
employee stock options rather than undertake the burdensome
overtime pay calculations that would be required.
</P>
<P>
   According to an analysis by the Employment Policy Foundation, a
nonprofit research organization, as many as 26 million blue-collar
workers could lose stock options if the costs and complex
calculations associated with implementing the advisory opinion
become law.
</P>
<P>
   The Employment Policy Foundation says implementation of such a
ruling could mean an average annual loss of $1,737 in equity value
for employees who participate in equity programs such as employee
stock purchase plans, stock bonus and grant programs, or stock
appreciation rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over a 35-year career, this loss amounts to $60,000 in nominal
stock'' for the average participating employee, the foundation
concluded. If stock values continue to rise at historic rates, the
loss for the typical worker could be worth about $470,000, the
foundation said.
</P>
<P>
   Labor Department spokesmen say the intent of the advisory
letter, written last year to one company in response to a specific
question, was not to dissuade companies from offering stock options
to hourly employees. There could be other cases in which stock
option gains would not have to be included in retroactive overtime
pay calculations.
</P>
<P>
   Labor Department advisory letters do not carry the weight of
law, but they are often viewed as indicators of future policy.
</P>
<P>
   Public attention to such letters heightened earlier this year
when employers protested a different opinion. That advisory letter
indicated that companies were responsible for meeting the same
Occupational Safety and Health Administration standards for
employees working at home as they were for employees working in
their offices.
</P>
<P>
   Several weeks of national outcry caused the department to
withdraw the guidance letter and issue an overriding policy
statement. The statement said employers would not be liable for
meeting the same OSHA standards for employees working at home.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-03-00 0043EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
