<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-FIGHT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRINIDAD-REID FIGHT IS INTRIGUING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The fight between Felix Trinidad and David Reid tonight in Las
Vegas lost some of its drama when Oscar De La Hoya decided he'd
rather fight Shane Mosley than Trinidad in June.
</P>
<P>
   However, in purely boxing terms, this pay-per-view matchup at
Caesars Palace has intrigue to spare.
</P>
<P>
   In one corner is Trinidad, the unbeaten Puerto Rican who ended
up on the fortunate side of a controversial decision against De La
Hoya last September. Trinidad (36-0, with 30 knockouts) won't admit
it, but he must resurrect, at least to some extent, the damage to
the pristine reputation he had built since he started his
professional career in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   He was that bad against De La Hoya, who baffled his rival with
his boxing skills for eight-plus rounds only to throw the fight
away by running the rest of the way.
</P>
<P>
   Trinidad, the undisputed welterweight champion who will be
fighting at 154 pounds for the second time, would rather be seeking
redemption by fighting De La Hoya again, but the camps have been
unable to reach an agreement on a weight and how they would split
$80 million over two fights, said Bob Arum, De La Hoya's promoter.
</P>
<P>
   So Trinidad, 27, is stuck with Reid and the opportunity to win
another world championship, Reid's WBA junior middleweight title.
</P>
<P>
   He's also left with a purse of $4 million, according to a
knowledgeable source, a pittance compared to the riches he might
never see if he doesn't beat Reid and meet De La Hoya again.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I overlooked David Reid, I wouldn't be doing my job,''
Trinidad said. ``This is a very important fight and I'm taking it
very seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there's Reid, whose very presence in such a fight is
remarkable.
</P>
<P>
   The kind-hearted street kid from Philadelphia, now 26, has the
amateur credentials: He won the United States' only gold medal in
the 1996 Olympics when he stopped Cuban Alfredo Duvergel with a big
right hand in a fight he was losing badly.
</P>
<P>
   However, he has only 14 pro fights - all victories, seven
knockouts - and hasn't looked spectacular in many of them.
</P>
<P>
   How can he hope to compete with a fighter of Trinidad's ability
and experience? With brawn, brains and De La Hoya-like quickness,
the last of which many believe will be the key in the fight in
light of the challenger's plodding performance against De La Hoya.
</P>
<P>
   The oddsmakers like Trinidad's experience - he's about a 2-1
favorite - while a poll of boxing writers and broadcasters give
Reid the edge: 26-21-2.
</P>
<P>
   ``Felix is a good fighter,'' Reid said. ``But Oscar exposed him.
Oscar proved that he has trouble with speed. Felix comes straight
in to wear you down.
</P>
<P>
   ``... I won't run from him like Oscar did, though.''
</P>
<P>
   Which means anything is possible.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-03-00 0045EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
