<DOCNO> NYT20000303.0011 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-03 00:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5363 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-DEPUTY-SHOOTINGS-KAN &LR;      03-03 0819
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEPUTY-SHOOTINGS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTHORITIES SEARCH FOR ANSWERS IN FATAL MEETING OF DEPUTY,
RUNAWAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN L. PETTERSON  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HIAWATHA, Kan. _ Law officers in Kansas and New York searched
for clues Thursday that might explain what led a runaway from
Buffalo, N.Y., to a deadly encounter with a part-time sheriff's
deputy halfway across the country.
</P>
<P>
   Vincent A. Smith, 16, the son of a Buffalo police lieutenant,
apparently shot and killed Todd Widman, 21, a deputy sheriff in
Brown County, Kan., on Wednesday night in Hiawatha. About three
hours later, Smith was shot to death by two Kansas Highway Patrol
troopers.
</P>
<P>
   Smith was reported missing Tuesday afternoon by his father, Lt.
Thomas C. Smith, a 29-year police veteran in Buffalo. A
missing-person report said the youth had taken his mother's 1988
Ford Tempo and a Walther PPK semiautomatic pistol owned by his
father, according to Lt. Larry Baehre, a Buffalo police spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all scratching our heads as to why he was heading that
way and what this was all about,'' Baehre said.
</P>
<P>
   He said there was no indication of problems in the Smith home.
</P>
<P>
   The Buffalo News reported that Smith apparently was distraught
over bad grades, but authorities in Kansas and Buffalo said they
could not confirm that.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a nonviolent kid,'' said Sam Carroll, a classmate at
Buffalo's Bishop Timon-St. Jude High School. ``Never got in
scuffles. He was just easy to get along with.''
</P>
<P>
   The Brown County Sheriff's Department said early Thursday
evening that there were no reports that Smith was involved in any
other incidents as he made his way toward Kansas. His mother's car
was found abandoned just off Interstate 29 in northwest Missouri,
near the Kansas state line, according to Special Agent Scott
Teeselink of the Kansas Bureau of Investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Early Wednesday evening, Widman responded to a report of a
suspicious person walking along U.S. 73 north of Hiawatha, a town
of about 3,600 in extreme northeast Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Believing the individual was a runaway juvenile, the deputy
attempted to transport the individual to the Brown County sheriff's
office for further investigation,'' Sheriff Lamar Shoemaker said.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes later, about 7 p.m., Widman radioed from his car that he
had been shot. Emergency medical crews took him to the Hiawatha
Community Hospital, where he died from gunshot wounds, authorities
said.
</P>
<P>
   Sgt. John Eichkorn of the Kansas Highway Patrol said Widman was
shot while in his car.
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear whether Smith had been searched before the
shooting. The gun may have been in a duffel bag Smith was carrying,
authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   State and local law enforcement agencies converged on the area
after the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Smith was spotted near a Wal-Mart store at the west edge of
Hiawatha, and there was an exchange of gunfire. No one was hit, and
Smith escaped, Shoemaker said.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes later, Shoemaker said, Smith was seen walking west of
Hiawatha along U.S. 36. A Highway Patrol helicopter and airplane
joined in the search, and tracking dogs were brought in.
</P>
<P>
   About 9:45 p.m., officers who were searching the area were fired
on by the suspect after he emerged from a field.
</P>
<P>
   ``The officers immediately returned fire,'' Shoemaker said. ``In
this exchange of gunfire, the suspect was struck and fatally
injured.''
</P>
<P>
   Two veteran Highway Patrol troopers have been placed on
administrative leave while the shooting is investigated. The
procedure is routine in such cases.
</P>
<P>
   A day after the shootings, the American flag outside the Brown
County sheriff's office flew at half-staff, and officers wore
strips of black tape across their badges.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at a midmorning press conference on Thursday, Shoemaker
said Widman had worked part time for the department for the last
several months, serving court papers and working in the jail.
</P>
<P>
   He was a 1997 graduate of Hiawatha High School and was
completing a degree in criminal justice at Washburn University in
Topeka, Kan. He had not yet taken the state-mandated law
enforcement training course.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a very fine young man,'' said John Severin, Hiawatha's
school superintendent. ``He was well-liked by the students in his
class and the students in the school.''
</P>
<P>
   Widman's sister is a junior at Hiawatha High School, and his
mother is employed there.
</P>
<P>
   Since graduating from high school, Widman had worked for the
school district's maintenance crew during the summers, Severin
said.
</P>
<P>
   Counselors were available for students and staff at the school
and for Widman's colleagues in the Sheriff's Department.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about Widman's colleagues, the sheriff said, ``They are
holding up as well as they can.''
</P>
<P>
   Eichkorn said: ``We all tend to take law enforcement for
granted. It really shines light on the fact this is a dangerous
occupation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
