<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-DEBATES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH, KEYES, MCCAIN SPAR IN L.A. DEBATE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICK ORLOV 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ With the pressure of ``Super Tuesday'' looming
over the Republican primary, the three remaining GOP candidates
clashed Thursday over who is most electable as they continued to
feud over issues ranging from campaign reform to religion.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George Bush, Arizona Sen. John McCain and former
Ambassador Alan Keyes spoke at a debate hosted by CNN and the Los
Angeles Times, each seeking to make the case that they are the
candidate who can defeat the Democratic nominee. Bush and Keyes
were in Los Angeles for the session, while McCain appeared via
television satellite from St. Louis, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we approach next Tuesday, which may be a seminal event in
this campaign, the question is who is the most fully prepared to be
president of the United States and who is the most capable of
wining a victory in November,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   California and 12 other states will be holding Republican
primaries and caucuses Tuesday in the first true national test of
the field of candidates.
</P>
<P>
   McCain is staking much of his campaign on the appeal he has made
to independent and moderate voters. In California, however, he is
faced with the prospect of winning the election but losing the GOP
delegates, because only Republican votes will be used to determine
who wins that party's primary.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he believes he also is capable of attracting
independent voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``America wants a proven leader,'' he said. ``People are looking
for a fresh start after a season of cynicism in Washington. I'm
going to reach out to Democrats and independents.''
</P>
<P>
   Keyes, who complained he has been excluded from media coverage
of the race, said he is the one who speaks to conservative
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know I am the one who speaks for you,'' Keyes said. ``Why
don't you get in the voting booth and stand for what I believe
in?''
</P>
<P>
   Taking up most of the session were sometimes sharp exchanges
between Bush and McCain in their 12th debate of the campaign season
and the final one before the ``Super Tuesday'' elections.
</P>
<P>
   Bush sought to distance himself from some of the criticism he
has received for appearing at Bob Jones University in South
Carolina, an institution that bans interracial dating and has
criticized Catholics and Jews.
</P>
<P>
   ``I regret that I didn't speak out about that school's bias,''
Bush said. ``What I also regret is someone ascribing to me opinions
and views that are not my views, calling me an anti-Catholic bigot.
It is not right.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush was referring to telephone calls to Michigan voters, paid
for by McCain, questioning his appearance at the university, and _
at first _ denying that the McCain campaign had paid for the calls.
</P>
<P>
   McCain was asked about his campaign's attack on the Christian
Coalition, in particular about his comments against Pat Robertson
and Jerry Falwell.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the fact is I have rejected the leadership of those
two individuals, who have led the party in the wrong direction with
their message of intolerance and exclusion,'' McCain said. ``I want
to put out a message of inclusion. A message of, `Come to our proud
conservative banner. Come take part in this noble experiment.'''
</P>
<P>
   Bush and McCain also differed over campaign reform, which McCain
has attempted to make a cornerstone of his campaign by eliminating
soft-money donations to political parties in elections.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he believes part of the problem has been the lack of
prompt reporting of donations.
</P>
<P>
   Also on Thursday, McCain picked up the endorsement of Los
Angeles County Sheriff Lee Baca, while Bush picked up the
endorsement of Orange County Sheriff Michael Carona, Ventura County
Sheriff Bob Brooks, Orange County District Attorney Anthony
Rackauckas and former San Diego County Sheriff Jim Roache.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
