<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONLINE-LONGDISTANCE-2NDTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHAWNEE, Kan. _ to choose from.
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen-year-old Brian Fitzpatrick made the 913 mistake in
early December.
</P>
<P>
   Brian, a seventh-grader, couldn't access AOL when 10-digit
dialing started in the metropolitan area on Dec. 4. He clicked on
AOL and asked for access numbers. The software offered him three
numbers in Wichita and one in Leavenworth. He chose the Leavenworth
number, not realizing it was a toll call.
</P>
<P>
   Brian racked up $290 in toll charges with Southwestern Bell
before the bill arrived.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got the bill and just about fainted,'' said Brian's father,
J. Kevin Fitzpatrick.
</P>
<P>
   Fitzpatrick said a Southwestern Bell billing manager in Topeka
said the company has too many complaints from AOL customers to
waive charges.
</P>
<P>
   The toll charges aren't Southwestern Bell's problem, said Ellen
Pantaenius, a spokeswoman for the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do advise customers to go back to the (Internet service
provider) and make arrangements to get reimbursed or whatever,''
Pantaenius said.
</P>
</TEXT>
