<HEADER>
A5370 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-ONLINE-LONGDISTANCE-2     03-03 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONLINE-LONGDISTANCE-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIRL RACKS UP $3,190 PHONE BILL USING AOL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID HAYES  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHAWNEE, Kan. _ Wow, talk about a wrong number.
</P>
<P>
   Lilly Colclasure, 11, ran up a $3,190 long-distance telephone
bill in a little over a month using America Online.
</P>
<P>
   The problem was caused by a software snag that can affect AOL
customers in Johnson and Wyandotte counties in Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   When Lilly, who lives with her parents in Shawnee, signed up for
an account in early December, AOL's software offered her only three
telephone numbers to access the service _ one in Leavenworth, Kan.,
two in Wichita, Kan.
</P>
<P>
   All three were toll numbers. But Lilly didn't know that.
</P>
<P>
   And she used those numbers more than 320 times in 37 days
between Dec. 4 and Jan. 9.
</P>
<P>
   ``She knows all about computers, but she doesn't know about
long-distance numbers,'' said her mother, Patty Colclasure.
</P>
<P>
   And Lilly isn't alone. Southwestern Bell doesn't keep statistics
but said the company gets enough complaints about toll charges
caused by online service glitches to say that it's a problem.
Thirteen-year-old Brian Fitzpatrick, for instance, ran up a $290
long-distance bill in December at his parents' home in Overland
Park, Kan., using the Leavenworth toll number supplied by AOL.
</P>
<P>
   America Online, used by an estimated 120,000 or more families in
the Kansas City area, contends the service isn't responsible for
the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``We repeatedly caution members they need to check with the
local phone company to ensure that the number they have chosen is
local for their calling plan and area,'' said Rich D'Amato, an AOL
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato also questioned how the problem occurred, contending
that AOL offers subscribers telephone numbers in the 913, 316 and
816 area codes when someone in the 913 area asks for a number.
</P>
<P>
   When told it didn't do that for either the Colclasures,
Fitzpatricks, on three computers in The Kansas City Star's offices
or on a computer at a Star reporter's home, he said, ``That doesn't
describe what should be the user experience.''
</P>
<P>
   However, D'Amato said, it still is the customer's responsibility
to make sure he or she isn't tying into a long-distance line.
</P>
<P>
   ``As more and more kids are setting up these things, we
recommend that parents participate in every stage,'' D'Amato said.
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato noted that a disclaimer on the screen where members are
supplied phone numbers to access the service says: ``Note: members
may incur telephone charges on their phone bill, depending on their
location and calling plan.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the next screen tells the customer to select ``at least
two'' numbers from the list. In the 913 area, all three are
out-of-town numbers.
</P>
<P>
   The solution? Customers have to know to key in 816 and look for
a Kansas City number.
</P>
<P>
   AOL hasn't offered to reimburse the Colclasure or Fitzpatrick
families for the charges. And their telephone companies _ AT&AMP;T and
Southwestern Bell _ have refused to waive those charges.
</P>
<P>
   Patty Colclasure said she allowed Lilly to use AOL for a
one-month free trial, primarily so she could download software for
the free NetZero Internet service.
</P>
<P>
   Lilly, a sixth-grader, wanted online access for school, to
search for music, and to chat online with friends.
</P>
<P>
   When she received the bill, Colclasure said she thought it was a
mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought this must be a Y2K thing,'' she said, referring to
the Year 2000 computer problem.
</P>
<P>
   Colclasure said calls to AOL and AT&AMP;T left her frustrated and
angry. She said AT&AMP;T told her they attempted to call her home twice
to alert the family to the long distance charges, but couldn't
reach her because the line was busy. Those calls, on Dec. 14 and
Dec. 15, came when the bill had reached $890.
</P>
<P>
   Colclasure said the family's average long-distance bill is
closer to $10.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T spokeswoman LeAnn Kuster confirmed the company had tried to
call twice without success. Kuster said AT&AMP;T doesn't put dollar
limits on the accounts of customers in good standing unless they
ask for one.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's incumbent on the customer to know how to set up the
service,'' Kuster said. She offered to work with the family for
extended payments.
</P>
<P>
   Colclasure said the bill is ludicrous.
</P>
<P>
   ``I bought a 1986 Honda Accord for $3,500 last year. They're
wanting almost a car,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, free Internet provider NetZero does offer a local
number when a user keys in the 913 area code to sign up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Free Internet can do it and AOL can't? That doesn't make
sense,'' Colclasure said.
</P>
<P>
   David Cassell, editor of AOLWatch, an online newsletter that's
critical of AOL, wasn't surprised by the Colclasure's situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``AOL has shown a remarkable lack of responsibility for problems
like this _ blaming the phone company, blaming the customer,''
Cassell said. ``The bottom line is, AOL does things the way they
want to.''
</P>
<P>
   AOL subscribers in other parts of the country have had similar
problems.
</P>
<P>
   The Maine Public Service Commission criticized AOL in January
1999 for a similar problem. Residents in both Maine and New
Hampshire complained that AOL defaulted to a toll number when they
signed up for the service. One consumer in Maine complained about a
$1,200 bill that resulted from the glitch.
</P>
<P>
   And a Florida woman filed a class-action lawsuit in February in
federal court in Tampa, Fla., accusing AOL of using unfair trade
practices, fraud and misleading advertising. Marguerite Miles said
AOL sells service where the company doesn't have access lines,
costing consumers long-distance charges.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is an old one for residents in the Kansas City area.
</P>
<P>
   The metropolitan area straddles the state line. AOL's ``modem
pool'' for metro Kansas City is on the 816 area code side of the
line. Tens of thousands of AOL's subscribers are on the 913 area
code side. When customers sign up for AOL, the service asks them
for their area code, then automatically gives them a list to choose
from. MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
