<HEADLINE>
RANK DOES HAVE ITS PRIVILEGES
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  SAN FRANCISCO _ This is Pothole City, but I found one block
that is as smooth as a baby's cheeks. It's Clay, between Jones and
Leavenworth, recently paved, beautifully done, you could play
championship marbles on it.
<P>
   ``Driving this block used to be like an amusement park ride,''
says Nob Hiller Judi Basolo.
</P>
<P>
   The new pave job stops at the east end of the block. Going west,
Clay is only partially redone. This one block is the pride of the
city.
</P>
<P>
   By bizarre coincidence, the mayor lives on this block.
</P>
<P>
   THIS JUST IN from Gov. Gray Davis: Any California resident who
is not in philosophical and political alignment with the governor
is asked to turn in his or her license plates and guacamole bowl
and move out of the state ASAP.
</P>
<P>
   HAIL TO THE CHIEF and the Chef:
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton hosts a cozy fund-raising dinner Friday night
at the home of Susie Tompkins (former Esprit boss), with Alice
Waters on kitchen duty.
</P>
<P>
   The produce is from the Garden Project, crops raised by former
S.F. jailbirds. So it's dinner with a social conscience, featuring
French radishes and green garlic.
</P>
<P>
   No fried pork rinds, Alice?
</P>
<P>
   QUIT YER GRIPING. Gas is $1.9999 9/10 per gallon, but as one
e-mail spammer points out, Gatorade and Snapple go for about $10 a
gallon, milk for about $12, Evian for $21.
</P>
<P>
   And Paul Dombey, just back from England, notes that petrol there
is selling for just under $5 a gallon (though they don't call 'em
gallons and dollars).
</P>
<P>
   INVESTMENT TIP? Tanya Efremov saw a parked van, coated with dust
in which someone had finger-written ``washme.com.''
</P>
<P>
   THE HIP MEAT of the new millennium? Might be buffalo. At
Eastside West in Cow Hollow, owner/chef Scott Damman ships the buff
in from Wyoming, whips up ``a big old buffalo chop on a plate.''
Lean, high in iron, and gives you the urge to go out and trample
settlers.
</P>
<P>
   SEVERAL ALERT READERS (sorry, that's redundant) point out that
LSD was invented by Swiss chemist Albert Hofmann in 1943. The
innovation was accidental, the result of a lab spill.
</P>
<P>
   IT'S A SMALL THING, but Stan Dorsey wishes the person who gives
the PA announcements at the Montgomery Muni station would not say,
``Attention, Muni patrions.'' (cq)  &LR; But what better name for
patriotic Muni patrons who have come to visit Metreon?
</P>
<P>
   OVERHEARD in a downtown elevator, by Kevin Crilly, two 20ish
women:
</P>
<P>
   ``I was at my friend's party, she works for Organic.''/``Dot
com?''/``Yeah.''/ ``Is it pre?''/``No, it's gone.''/``How long has
she been there?''/``Since before it went. She has plenty of options
and she's stoked ...''
</P>
<P>
   So who wants to marry a multimillionairess.com?
</P>
<P>
   IN NEW YORK, the new thing is Broadway theaters selling their
names to sponsors. The Selwyn Theater is now the American Airlines
Theater. Says Matt Regan, ``You check your coat, it winds up in
Frisco?''
</P>
<P>
   And when a production flops, the producers can find out what
happened by recovering the black box.
</P>
<P>
   ANOTHER TV LOW, lower than ``Who Wants to Marry'': They've
cheapened the sport of monster truck racing. It's a semi-legit
sport, enjoyed by kids and me.
</P>
<P>
   So this week there was a one-hour special _ five minutes of
racing and 55 minutes of soft-core T&AMP;A and hokey ``plots''
scavenged from the WWF writers' reject bin. Sad.
</P>
<P>
   NEWEST SINGLES CLUB: Desperate to get in on the new ballpark
action, more than 100 people have purchased one-seat season tickets
for Giants games.
</P>
<P>
   WHO'S CHECKING those new dot-com company names for suitability
in public advertising? Like: mofo.com, and eFUCT.com.
</P>
<P>
   WHERE THE ELITE EAT: Liza Minnelli dining at the Black Cat,
after rehearsal for her local opening ... Robert Altman sipping
coffee (who gulps it?) at the Rose Cafe ... Kenny (Snake) Stabler,
who did a commercial for the stuff, ordering a Miller Lite at the
Fat Lady in Oakland, causing old Raider fan Bobby Reman to do
double-take. Be true to your brew.
</P>
<P>
   THE U.S. OPEN (golf) will be at Pebble Beach in June, and Darryl
Glen reports that homes near the course are offered for rental at
up to $50,000 for the week. Considering that you can sit on your
veranda with a quadruple martini and shout ``You da man'' at Tiger
Woods, that's a bargain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
