<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-ADS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 CANDIDATES' RECYCLED TV ADS GET POOR REVIEWS IN CALIFORNIA  &HT;     By JOHN KING 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   As California's primary campaign enters its final weekend, at
least $8 million has been spent on television advertising by the
four major presidential candidates.
</P>
<P>
   But as large as that number sounds, it pales alongside the
commercial barrages unleashed by other statewide candidates in
recent years. And what startles many political and media analysts
is how the money has been used: on a haphazard mix of ads either
aimed at a nationwide audience or left over from past primaries.
</P>
<P>
   Unless something unexpected happens in the next four days,
analysts say the result could be ad campaigns remembered as nothing
more than expensive sideshows that most voters ignored _ or did not
even notice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm surprised you don't see any California-specific ads yet,''
says Evan Tracey, president of Campaign Media Analysis Group.
``Clearly, California's the big enchilada for all the candidates,
but there hasn't been an obvious strategy for the state.''
</P>
<P>
   The challenge that faces each campaign is daunting _ on two
fronts. In California, where conventional wisdom says that
television advertising is crucial, candidates must grab voters'
attention in a week when the airwaves already are crowded with
commercials for ballot measures. At the same time, Super Tuesday's
other 15 primaries demand attention and resources.
</P>
<P>
   But even if California cannot command the focused attention seen
in earlier primary states, such as South Carolina, observers say
they are struck that little effort seems to have been put into
anything beyond getting ads on the air.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of the advertising by any of the candidates breaks new
ground or provides new information to the voter,'' says Roy Behr of
Greer Margolis Mitchell Burns and Associates, a political ad firm
with offices in Los Angeles. ``It doesn't seem to be having much
impact at all.''
</P>
<P>
   According to tracking done by Tracey's Virginia-based firm, $8.2
million has been spent so far to buy television advertising time in
California by the presidential campaigns of Bill Bradley, George W.
Bush, Al Gore and John McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Other observers put the figure higher. Bill Carrick, a political
advertising expert working on Dianne Feinstein's Senate re-election
bid in California, estimates that the amount spent by the
presidential campaigns already approaches $12 million.
</P>
<P>
   To put these admittedly large numbers in context, the 1998
primary campaign of Democratic gubernatorial hopeful Al Checchi
used roughly two-thirds of its $40 million budget on television
advertising. And the television budget for some of this year's
ballot measures should exceed $20 million.
</P>
<P>
   Short of a Checchi-like budget, it is impossible to blanket
California with ads. Instead, the individual campaigns are
concentrating on specific regions.
</P>
<P>
   McCain and Bush are focusing on Southern California, where most
of the state's Republicans live. Each has invested about $1.3
million there, according to estimates by Campaign Media Analysis
Group.
</P>
<P>
   In the Bay Area, by contrast, McCain has a minimal presence. His
campaign has spent only $80,000 on television advertising here,
compared to Bush's $350,000.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats Bradley and Gore, meanwhile, have almost ignored the
conservative San Diego area. Instead, Bradley has plowed $1.8
million in ads into the vast Los Angeles market, with Gore spending
$1.2 million so far.
</P>
<P>
   In the Bay Area, Bradley has spent $650,000 and Gore has spent
$425,000. This translates to roughly 310 Bradley ads and 250 for
Gore. Large numbers _ but when the rule of thumb is that any ad
must be seen eight to 10 times to make a strong impression on a
viewer, they are hardly overwhelming.
</P>
<P>
   Except for Spanish-language ads, all the commercials shown in
California so far were filmed for nationwide use or date back to
earlier primaries.
</P>
<P>
   One sign of the haphazard approach to California is that the
lone Bush ad criticizing McCain is from the time of the South
Carolina primary.
</P>
<P>
   So California viewers may be mystified when Bush complains that
``John McCain compared me to Bill Clinton and said I was
untrustworthy. That's over the line.'' He's discussing an ad that
aired _ briefly _ three weeks ago and 2,000 miles away.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like we're stepping into the middle of a novel,'' Carrick
says of the older ads and their themes. ``Presidential campaigns
come to town, and suddenly they realize they've got to get
something on the air.''
</P>
<P>
   Applying such a one-size-fits-all method to a state as distinct
as California baffles observers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would think at some point you would see (Gov. Gray) Davis on
screen saying he supports Gore,'' Tracey says. ``And McCain has the
backing of the top Republican in the state, (Secretary of State)
Bill Jones. You'd expect to see McCain's campaign use him.''
</P>
<P>
   At this point, it is questionable whether even a major burst of
ads could make a strong impression.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't come in in the last two weeks, even with a heavy
advertising buy, and shake things up,'' says Behr, whose firm is
involved in ads opposing Proposition 28, which would roll back a
voter-approved cigarette tax. ``It's difficult for a campaign to
break through.''
</P>
<P>
   That was not the case in South Carolina, where Bush and McCain
together spent $6 million on advertising in a market where $1
million buys 2,300 ads _ more than four times the number that a
similar amount of money would buy in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``South Carolina, they had saturation between Bush and McCain
the last few weeks,'' Tracey says. ``You would have had to be
living in a trailer with a radio not to see those ads.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-03-00 0114EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000303.0020 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-03 01:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
