r a BC-NEWYORK-PRIMARY-SFCHR     03-03 1162
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWYORK-PRIMARY-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 MCCAIN NEEDS VICTORY IN NEW YORK  &HT;     By CAROLYN LOCHHEAD and MARC SANDALOW 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When John McCain decided not to show up in person at
Thursday night's debate in Los Angeles, it was less a snub of
California than a bow to the state where he stands his best chance
of winning a big pot of delegates.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 16 states holding GOP presidential primaries or caucuses
Tuesday, none is as likely as New York to provide the Arizona
senator the opportunity to capture Republican votes and burnish his
image as the GOP candidate most able to win the White House.
</P>
<P>
   So when the sun rises in the East Friday morning, McCain will be
with the ``Today'' show's Katie Couric riding through the streets
of Manhattan on his ``Straight Talk Express'' bus, en route to a
live interview with radio host Don Imus, before holding a noon
rally on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush will not be far behind, racing from
California on a red-eye flight to attend rallies in GOP-vote-rich
Syracuse and Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   The Empire State has been losing clout to California since
before the Giants and Dodgers moved west, but it is in New York
that McCain has been forced to draw a line in the sand. Were McCain
to lose in New York and California, it is hard to see how his
Straight Talk Express could roll on to the following week's
primaries in Texas and Florida _ where the governors are named Bush
_ and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; McCain's New York Edge
</P>
<P>
   The polls, which show McCain down by as much as 20 percentage
points in California, give him a slight edge among registered New
York Republicans, who are the only voters eligible to participate
in the state's GOP primary. Bush leads in conservative strongholds
upstate, while McCain leads in New York City and the suburbs. New
Hampshire is the only other state where McCain has been able to win
a majority of Republican voters.
</P>
<P>
   After California, New York is the biggest prize on Super
Tuesday, with 101 of the 1,034 delegates needed to win the GOP
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``McCain has to do something here to counter what may be a
not-so-hot showing in California,'' said New York pollster John
Zogby.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, McCain's brand of politics is well suited for this
state, where many Republicans are pro-choice and pro-gun control.
</P>
<P>
   Although McCain is against legal abortions and gun control, his
opponents in states such as South Carolina and Virginia have
successfully portrayed him as wobbly on conservative issues.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Moderate N.Y. Republicans
</P>
<P>
   Those attacks may not work so well in New York, where Republican
Gov. George Pataki and Republican Mayor Rudolph Giuliani of New
York City both support legal abortions and gun control.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things couldn't look better right now,'' said Guy Molinari,
the Staten Island Borough president and former congressman who is
heading McCain's New York campaign. ``We think the spread may even
be greater. McCain's support is very, very hard, very dedicated,
very committed. We know the McCain people will come out and vote. I
don't think they have that intensity on the Bush side.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bush also has considerable advantages in the state,
including the backing of the party apparatus. Cumbersome petition
requirements make it extremely difficult for anyone without the
support of the party's leaders to appear on the ballot, which
explains why New York has not had a contested presidential primary
since 1976.
</P>
<P>
   McCain made a spectacle of the restrictive rules, staging an
event in January outside the Russian consulate in Manhattan and
charging that voters in Moscow and St. Petersburg have more open
elections than those from Staten Island to Schenectady.
</P>
<P>
   The party bosses, headed by Gov. Pataki _ a Bush supporter _
backed down after McCain's huge victory in New Hampshire. Still,
the ballot favors the establishment's favorite.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than simply offering voters statewide a choice between
Bush, McCain or former U.N. Ambassador Alan Keyes, the ballots in
each of the 31 congressional districts offer three delegates
aligned with one of the candidates.
</P>
<P>
   The names of the delegates _ who in Bush's case are well-known
GOP figures such as Teddy Roosevelt IV _ appear in large bold type,
while the name of the presidential candidate they support appears
in tiny type below.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew it was going to be bad, but I was appalled when I saw
it,'' said Molinari, who had just caught a glimpse of his wife's
absentee ballot. ``You can hardly make out McCain's name. You need
a magnifying glass to do that. And that's deliberate _ that's part
of the effort by the New York state Republican hierarchy to control
the outcome of the election.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonsense, said state Sen. Roy Goodman, a Manhattan Republican
and a Bush backer. ``The names are easy to read unless you are
myopic.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Goodman, whose name is on the ballot as a Bush delegate,
concedes that after 16 terms in the state Legislature, there may be
some loyal constituents who vote for Bush simply because they
recognize Goodman's name.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a possibility,'' he said. ``That is why I think Bush
has a slight edge.''
</P>
<P>
   Like other primary voters, New Yorkers have focused less on
specific issues than on questions of character and electability.
</P>
<P>
   Catholics make up an astonishing 46 percent of registered
Republicans, a reflection of the state's history as a magnet for
immigrants from predominantly Catholic countries such as Italy,
Ireland and Poland and now Latin American nations.
</P>
<P>
   Neither camp knows which way Catholics will go Tuesday, but
their importance doubtless underlies the continuing brouhaha over
Bush's visit to Bob Jones University in South Carolina more than a
month ago, which has been followed by escalating charges and
countercharges between McCain and Bush about who is stirring more
outrage among Catholics and fundamentalist Protestants.
</P>
<P>
   It was no accident that Bush directed his letter of regret over
the Bob Jones visit to New York's Archbishop, Cardinal John
O'Connor, saying he should have denounced the college's
anti-Catholic views.
</P>
<P>
   In the past few days, Bush supporters have charged that McCain's
crusade against pork-barrel spending in Washington has been
disastrous to New York.
</P>
<P>
   One Bush TV commercial features the leader of a Long Island
breast cancer advocacy group who attacks McCain for opposing funds
for breast cancer research. Bush supporters also have faulted
McCain for opposing federal relief for a 1998 ice storm and a bill
to help the state's dairy farmers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there were such a thing as an anti-New York caucus, he
would be the head of it,'' said U.S. Rep. John Sweeney, R-N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   New York political observers say the final days of campaigning
will be pivotal in a state that takes its politics seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``In California, election day is an afterthought,'' said one
Republican official. ``In New York, it is a day of holy
obligation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-03-00 0121EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
