<DOCNO> NYT20000303.0021 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-03 01:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5385 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-DEBATE-GOP-SFCHRON &LR;      03-03 1072
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEBATE-GOP-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH, MCCAIN PUMMEL EACH OTHER OVER CAMPAIGN FINANCE REFORM IN 
 LATEST DEBATE
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By CARLA MARINUCCI and JOHN WILDERMUTH 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush and Arizona Sen. John
McCain squabbled over education, foreign policy and campaign ethics
Thursday night, but saved their toughest punches for campaign
finance reform in the last debate before Tuesday's primary.
</P>
<P>
   A tightly controlled format left little room for interaction and
allowed the candidates to give their well-rehearsed stump speeches
on many contentious issues.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the hour-long event provided the candidates an
opportunity to rev up their war of words as they close out their
campaigns in crucial California, where 162 GOP delegates are at
stake for the winning Republican candidate in the blanket primary.
Fifteen other states, including delegate-rich New York, also have
primaries or party caucuses on the same day.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, whom polls show to be 10 to 20 percentage points behind
Bush among GOP voters, continually stressed his Republication
credentials, which he said are rooted in Abraham Lincoln, Theodore
Roosevelt and Ronald Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   And Bush, whom McCain has recently accused of negative
campaigning, tried to portray himself as a reformer and a uniter, a
candidate who could provide ``a fresh start'' after an era of
political cynicism.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, who appeared with Bush and former Ambassador Alan Keyes
via satellite, was severely disadvantaged by his own decision not
to participate in person in the CNN-Los Angeles Times forum held in
the Harry Chandler Auditorium in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he was seen by viewers in a surreal ``Max Headroom''
fashion via a television mounted on a third podium next to two live
participants. That allowed Bush to interact with both questioners
and the audience _ underscoring his presence by leaning on the
podium, emerging from behind it and, at one point, standing
mischievously next to Keyes.
</P>
<P>
   The former ambassador, whose campaign has become a virtual
footnote in the race, spent most of the evening lecturing both his
competitors and the press on issues of morality.
</P>
<P>
   But the focus of the night belonged to Bush and McCain, who were
both forced to tackle recent religion-themed controversies that
have dogged their campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, in a question about his recent scathing criticism of
Christian televangelists Pat Robertson and Jerry Falwell, was asked
if he could win the GOP vote if he appeared to be declaring war on
a substantial faction in his own party _ the Christian right.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have rejected the leadership of these two individuals, who
have led our party in the wrong direction,'' said McCain, who
decried what he called Robertson and Fallwell's ``message of
intolerance and exclusion, rather than inclusion.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, for his part, was forced to address the lingering
controversy over his visit to Bob Jones University, a private South
Carolina institution whose founders have voiced anti-Catholic
rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
   ``I follow a long tradition of both Republican and Democratic
candidates (who went there) to lay out their vision,'' he said. ``I
talked about bringing people together so America can achieve its
greatness.''
</P>
<P>
   While Bush sidestepped the question about whether he regretted
going to the university, he did acknowledge: ``I regret I did not
speak out against that school's anti-Catholic bias. I make no
excuses.''
</P>
<P>
   But then he turned on McCain and said, ``What I regret is the
politics of smearing somebody's reputation. That's what I regret.
And I don't appreciate it one bit.''
</P>
<P>
   When McCain asked for time to respond, Bush said, ``I didn't
attack Sen. McCain.''
</P>
<P>
   Another animated and contentious moment came over the issue of
campaign finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   Bush maintained that individuals must, as a matter of free
speech, have the right to donate any amount they want to political
campaigns. He argued that disclosure is the real answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my state ... individuals can give to a candidate what they
want to give, so long as there's disclosure,'' he said. ``We ought
to know who's given to whom (via the Internet) and we ought to do
it in real-time basis, (so there's) nothing to hide.''
</P>
<P>
   But McCain _ who has made campaign finance reform and ``breaking
the iron triangle of big money, lobbyists and legislation'' a
cornerstone of his campaign _ used that opening to call the Texas
governor's campaign finance reform plan ``bizarre.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe that explains why there's been the sleepovers in Austin
of the Pioneers,'` said McCain, referring to Associated Press
reports of eight $100,000 Bush donors who have slept at the
Governor's Mansion in the Texas capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``You talk about people staying with me,'' Bush retorted.
``These are my friends, John, these are my relatives. ... You talk
a lot about the iron triangle, and you're ringing it like a dinner
bell with these all fund-raisers with lobbyists in Washington,
D.C.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm ringing it like a dinner bell, you've got both feet in
the trough,'' McCain fired back.
</P>
<P>
   Bush became almost passionate on questions of education, and the
issue allowed him an opportunity to pound the message that he is
``a reformer with results.''
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, he said, ``we hold people accountable'' for school
system improvements. ``You must prove the children are learning to
read and write and add and subtract. ... I won't accept
mediocrity,'' he said. ``A system without accountability is a
system that quits on our children.''
</P>
<P>
   And, he added, ``I know what I'm talking about ... because we've
done it in my state.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain, in contrast, seemed to stumble with a rambling,
unfocused answer when asked his most important contribution on
education.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably in leading the effort in my, being involved in the
effort, in my state for reform in many areas,'' he said, without
providing many specifics.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said he is ``certain Christian conservatives from all
over the country will flock'' to his reform banner, while Bush said
he would ``reach out to Democrats and independents'' if he is the
nominee, as he said he has done in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the harshness of the nomination campaign, McCain said he
would support the eventual nominee and ruled out bolting the party
when asked if he might.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a loyal Republican,'' he said. ``The Republican Party is
my home.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
