<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-03 01:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5388 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-WEBMUSIC-CONGESTION-S     03-03 0961
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEBMUSIC-CONGESTION-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISCORD AT UNIVERSITIES AS STUDENTS JAM INTERNET LINES TO 
 DOWNLOAD POP MUSIC
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By TANYA SCHEVITZ 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  Universities across the country are pulling the plug on
music-hungry students who have clogged campus computer networks
using a new way of downloading and sharing songs on the Internet.
<P>
   San Francisco State University and the University of California
at Berkeley are among more than 100 institutions that have blocked
or limited access to a San Mateo Web site
 &UR; (www.napster.com)  &LR; that they say is largely to blame for the
problems.
</P>
<P>
   Started last year by an 18-year-old college student, Napster
allows users an easy way to search through hundreds of thousands of
popular songs over the Internet and download them free of charge
using the company's software.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't bought a CD since I got to Cal,'' said UC Berkeley
freshman Julian Kapoor, 18, who acknowledges a song-a-day habit
with Napster.
</P>
<P>
   University officials say the software use is overwhelming campus
computer systems, disrupting e-mail and academic uses of the
Internet and sending connection costs soaring.
</P>
<P>
   UC Berkeley officials blame Napster for a dramatic jump in the
residence halls' share of campus Internet traffic _ to 50 percent
in January and February from about 10 percent in November.
Connection costs have rocketed to $18,000 a month from $6,000.
</P>
<P>
   The university decided to limit access to the site by capping
the traffic that the 6,000 students in the residence halls could
exchange with off-campus sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was going to break the budget this year, that is where it
was headed,'' said Cliff Frost, director of communication and
network services at UC Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco State cut off access to the site after students
using Napster ate up the entire Internet bandwidth available to the
campus several times in November, preventing anyone else from using
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to do something,'' said Steve Smith, the campus network
analyst. ``We don't have an enormous pipe to the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Other institutions from Brown University to the University of
Texas have taken similar actions.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Hawkins, president of EDUCAUSE in Boulder, Colo., which
represents computer systems workers at 1,700 colleges and
universities, said he has never seen anything on the magnitude of
Napster use.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we've had an application that has singularly
done something like this before,'' Hawkins said. ``There is no
doubt that this tool is disrupting the primary reason those
networks are on these campuses.''
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Brooks, vice president of marketing for Napster,
called the popularity of the site ``wonderful.'' But she said the
company ``never had an intention of impeding academic traffic or
causing network havoc,'' adding that the company is trying to help
universities deal with the problem.
</P>
<P>
   She said there is a variety of solutions, including prioritizing
traffic on a network, putting academic use above entertainment, or
throttling the bandwidth, which is what UC Berkeley is doing.
</P>
<P>
   But students are angry that college administrators are
restricting their Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   Kapoor, like many of the other students eating in a university
dormitory cafeteria this week, did not know that Napster had caused
problems.
</P>
<P>
   But he did not like the idea of the university deliberately
slowing down the students' connection. He said the slowdown, which
came while he was doing online research for a biology project, was
``irritating.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they should find another way. The Net is for the
students,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Chad Paulson, 19, a sophomore at Indiana University who started
an organization called Students Against University Censorship,
established a Web site to publicize the fight two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   He said that rather than limiting Internet traffic, the campus
administrators should do more to make students aware of the
implications of sucking up so much bandwidth and set use policies.
If students still misuse the system, then they should be cut off.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the students don't realize there are limits to it so
they just go crazy. They don't understand the impact,'' Paulson
said.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem is the way the software works. It sends
users to music files on personal computers that have already
downloaded them. But in order to share music files, users must
leave the software running. Many students do so all night or while
they are in class.
</P>
<P>
   And with the high-speed Internet connections most universities
offer, they think nothing of downloading several songs at once.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first week I came in, both my roommates sat in front of
their computers for weeks downloading songs,'' UC Berkeley freshman
Brian Chung, 18, said.
</P>
<P>
   Paulson has compiled a list of 106 campuses blocking Napster and
has gathered 5,059 signatures for an online petition to pressure
administrators to reinstate access on all campuses _ or at least to
talk with students about it.
</P>
<P>
   He said universities should not unilaterally limit resources for
students who pay thousands of dollars a year in tuition. ``I think
it is our right to see the Internet as the Internet and not the
university version of the Internet,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hawkins, of the university computer workers association,
disputed the students' charges of censorship, saying universities
are not blocking content.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is nothing more than a tool. This is not like saying you
cannot see the Kinsey report or something else that someone finds
offensive,'' he said. ``When this thing is running, it uses so much
of the bandwidth that other people are kept from using e-mail and
the other Internet resources for teaching and learning.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
