<DOCNO> NYT20000303.0035 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-03 01:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5411 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-KINGS-ROCKETS-HNS     03-03 0898
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KINGS-ROCKETS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN 
  c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
Hakeem Olajuwon rushed to find Cuttino Mobley to make sure he
understood what had happened. Coaches had spoken to Mobley. Other
teammates had said a word or two. Mobley's hip was screaming at
him, the pain swimming upstream against the emotions.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But Olajuwon had to be clear. He had to know that Mobley knew
what he had done.
</P>
<P>
   ``He saved the game,'' Olajuwon said. ``That was the game. That
play, that was the game right there.''
</P>
<P>
   Mobley had made running jumpers. He knocked down 3-pointers and
completed breaks with dunks. For the fourth consecutive game, he
led the Rockets in scoring.
</P>
<P>
   But he won the game with a mad, desperate defensive dash that
left him writhing in pain and the Rockets on their way to a 102-99
win over the Sacramento Kings on Thursday night at Compaq Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just telling him that saved the game,'' Olajuwon said.
``To do that without fouling, that was a great play. I love that.''
</P>
<P>
   Mobley had scored 10 of the Rockets' previous 13 points,
bringing them back down the stretch to a two-point lead. But when
he missed a jumper, he saw Jon Barry sneaking up the court and then
flying ahead of the Rockets to what seemed a sure layup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw Barry leaking after I shot it,'' Mobley said. ``I tried
my best to get down there and at least change the shot. He was
leaking the whole game. You get easy buckets like that. So I went
to try to stop him.''
</P>
<P>
   Barry left his layup short with 22 seconds left and the Rockets
leading 96-94. While Mobley crashed to the court with a strained
hip, Steve Francis rebounded. The Rockets made six free throws in
the final 21 seconds to close out the win with Mobley, and his
team-high 22 points, watching from the bench.
</P>
<P>
   Mobley said he planned to play in Saturday's 1:30 p.m. game
against the Nets, though he did not know what his injury is.
</P>
<P>
   But as he labored to dress, Mobley said the Rockets have applied
the lessons learned in their loss to the Lakers on Sunday. After
holding the Clippers to the worst shooting ever by a Rockets
opponent or even by a Clippers team, a defensive play against the
league's most prolific scoring team proved the game-winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach (Rudy Tomjanovich) told us the other day after the
Lakers game, he wants us to play `D' and he wants me to start it,''
Mobley said. ``I try to take it upon myself to make it hard for
people to shoot. I didn't see it that way, but everybody said it
saved the game. I'm all for saving games.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kings did not see it that way either, but for a different
reason. Heading back down the court, Barry called for a foul,
pointing to his right elbow. Forward Chris Webber raised his arms
as if stunned by the no-call.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was a pretty easy call,'' coach Rick Adelman
said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he had been fouled, Barry said: ``I can't say anything.
If you pay my fine, I'll tell you.''
</P>
<P>
   Mobley said Barry said nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's too stupid,'' Mobley said. ``He'd better not say anything
to me.''
</P>
<P>
   But there was more the Kings could blame. On a day the Rockets
brought centers Kelvin Cato and Olajuwon back into the rotation,
the guards dominated and the team rolled to a 19-point first-half
lead. Francis regained much of his shooting touch and swagger. He
had 17 points and nine assists. Though he committed a foolish foul
in the last minute, grabbing Barry's shirt as Shandon Anderson
drove for a breakaway, he made four free throws in the final
seconds to seal it.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson set the early tone and finished with 19 points, his
best scoring game in more than two weeks. And Moochie Norris, who
signed for the rest of the season Monday, had a career game,
scoring 16 points and collecting five assists, four rebounds and
three steals in 25 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Norris nailed a running 40-footer to end the first quarter with
the Rockets surging to a 30-19 lead. He dropped another bomb with
3:12 left, giving the Rockets a 91-88 lead they never would lose.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Moochie was fantastic,'' Tomjanovich said. ``He made
a lot of all-around plays. He was on the boards. He made a big 3
that gave us some breathing room. He's a great addition.''
</P>
<P>
   And between him and Francis, the Rockets forced Kings point
guard and highlight machine Jason Williams into his first scoreless
game of the season. Williams missed his only three attempts. He had
seven assists but also had six turnovers in 20 minutes, spending
all but five minutes of the second half on the bench.
</P>
<P>
   But the Rockets still had to sweat out the last minutes. After
leading by 19 in the first half and 12 at halftime, the Rockets
looked as if the Clippers disease so evident Monday had been
contagious. Within 2{ minutes of the fourth quarter, the Kings took
their first lead since the opening minutes with Scot Pollard
dropping a hook and Barry nailing a 3 to make it 78-77.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets had made one of nine shots in the quarter. Francis
had missed a lauyp, a 3 and a dunk. But Francis pulled up on a
break to nail a trey before Mobley took over. But it was after he
missed that he made the play that had to be made. And in case it
wasn't clear, Olajuwon said it again.
</P>
<P>
   ``He saved the game,'' Olajuwon said. ``I had to tell him. He
seemed to like hearing it. That play saved the game.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
