<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-03 01:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5412 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s BC-BKN-SONICS-SPI &LR;      03-03 0768
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SONICS WILT AGAINST HEAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ The look on Gary Payton's face was perhaps most telling.
</P>
<P>
   Rarely is the point guard's scowl replaced by a puzzling look,
but this was one of those nights.
</P>
<P>
   Again.
</P>
<P>
   Watching opponents make layups as if it were a practice drill
can have a dizzying effect. Especially when the spell reaches three
consecutive games.
</P>
<P>
   So it is safe to say that after a 101-83 loss to the Miami Heat
Thursday night at American Airlines Arena, the Sonics are
officially dazed and confused. However, Payton _ and he is not
alone _ isn't too punch drunk to understand why.
</P>
<P>
   When you allow a team to go from shooting a season-low 29.6
percent in one game to posting a season-high 58-percent, the snag
is clear-cut.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics could not have stopped anyone the way they defended
the Heat. Consequently, the matador defensive effort led to their
second straight road loss on a five-game trip that continues in
Atlanta tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't play defense, we can't beat anybody,'' Payton
said. ``We're not concentrating. We don't trust each other. So
we'll keep winning one and losing one. Lose two and win one. We'll
keep doing that until we realize that we have to play defense.
Until then, we won't be a good team.''
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, the Sonics have been completely fraudulent on this road
trip, beginning with a poor game they somehow stole in Charlotte on
Monday. Thursday was the second straight game in which the Sonics
suffered through below-40-percent shooting. It was also the second
time this week they allowed their opponent to shoot 51 percent or
better, build a big lead and stiff arm any comeback attempts.
</P>
<P>
   Miami built a 23-point lead in the first half as Seattle scored
just 13 points in the opening period and shot 36 percent for the
game.
</P>
<P>
   Curious was that the Sonics settled for outside shots when the
Heat played without starting center Alonzo Mourning. He did not
dress because of a sore ankle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't shoot the ball, and I give their defense a lot of
credit for that,'' Sonics coach Paul Westphal said. ``It's
disappointing. We were slow getting into our offense, and they did
a good job of making us go to our third and fourth option. We were
fighting the shot clock all night.''
</P>
<P>
   Forward Vin Baker dismissed the notion the Sonics thought the
Heat would be easier to handle without Mourning in the middle.
</P>
<P>
   ``They played hard,'' Baker said. ``Coach (Pat) Riley is going
to get them to play hard every night. A lot of times when you don't
have one of your best players in the game, you're going to play
harder. For example, we beat them in Seattle without Horace
Grant.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics actually got within 74-68 with 11:40 to play in the
game, mainly because they attacked the basket more in the second
half. Still, they never posed a serious threat.
</P>
<P>
   Miami answered every Sonics run the same, by forcing its way
around, through and over the Sonics to get to the rim.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first half was an F,'' Grant said of the Sonics' defensive
effort. ``The third quarter was a D-plus. The fourth quarter was an
F-plus. I keep saying we have to just play defense. It's like a
broken record. Until we learn how to play defense, we're going to
keep losing.,,
</P>
<P>
   Because the Sonics rely so much on scoring in transition,
defensive breakdowns disrupt their offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely cause for alarm at this point in the season,''
guard Brent Barry said. ``... There's been no fast-break baskets.
The only fast breaks we're making is to Starbucks before the game
to get coffee.''
</P>
<P>
   Baker and Ruben Patterson were the only ones who played in a
rhythm offensively. Baker had 23 points and nine rebounds.
Patteron's career-high 24 points were wasted.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did a great job on Gary Payton,'' Riley said after the Heat
held Payton to 8-of-23 shooting. ``We were able to prevent him from
making all of the plays.''
</P>
<P>
   The Heat scrambled and trapped the Sonics, forcing poor shots
and miss after miss. Miami then turned those misfires into scores.
Even without Mourning, the Heat were just as effective inside with
his replacement, Clarence Weatherspoon, as they were from outside.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why we need to get slapped in the face for our
team to get it going,'' Barry said. ``We did it in Orlando and
couldn't come back. We did it in Miami and couldn't come back. This
is not good.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Ronald Tillery can be reached at 206-448-8012
</P>
<P>
   or ronaldtillery &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-03-00 0152EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000303.0037 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-03 01:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5413 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      03-03 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
John P.Lopez
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
ORLANDO, Fla., _ Sincerity doesn't come in 400 well-prepared,
double-spaced words.
</P>
<P>
   It comes from the heart, which John Rocker said was where his
apology to the baseball world Thursday came from. But his actions
said otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   No sooner did Rocker sit there stone-faced and staring into the
distance in front of 22 cameras and some 140 reporters reading his
prepared text than he bolted from the room.
</P>
<P>
   Sincerity doesn't come from awkwardly and nervously telling the
public you're sorry, like a rookie weekend anchor reading a
TelePrompTer for the first time. It comes from standing there face
to face _ not in the outfield playing catch with Braves teammate
Rudy Seanez, as Rocker did after his brief one-sided news
conference Thursday. It comes from talking. And listening.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of Rocker's profanity-laced Sports Illustrated
denunciation of minorities, homosexuals, foreigners and everyone
else who doesn't look like Rocker, come from where Rocker comes
from and believe in what he believes in, Rocker said he was sorry.
</P>
<P>
   He came back to baseball, showed remorse in a quick and quiet
five-minute speech, and then went out and acted as if everything
was peachy-keen again, working out in the bullpen and then signing
autographs for 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not like everything is suddenly right again just
because that's what the script said. And it won't be until Rocker
does the very thing he said he would do in his statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``An apology is no more than just words,'' he said, ``unless it
is followed by actions.''
</P>
<P>
   But soon after uttering those words, Rocker announced he
wouldn't address the issue anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of embracing the opportunity to begin stepping back into
the good graces of millions of people who squirmed at Rocker's
words last December, he went jogging into the outfield, leaving his
teammates behind to answer the questions he should have answered.
</P>
<P>
   Ball one.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly ours is a forgiving society and one in which free
speech is among the truths we should hold dear. Rocker had every
right to say what he said, and even those who might believe Rocker
is a weak man, no matter his 96-mph fastball, could eventually
forgive him.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of talking, listening and answering questions
Thursday, Rocker read from a script and blew probably his greatest
opportunity to begin showing the public the John Rocker he says
will be different.
</P>
<P>
   With regard to the seemingly racist views Rocker expressed in
December, we shouldn't forever be appalled by them if he shows
change, or at least an understanding and acceptance of a diverse
society. Everyone deserves a second chance, and, well, all Rocker
did was express his opinion, albeit one that could have severe
consequences for him, the Braves and Major League Baseball.
</P>
<P>
   But what was indeed sad and appalling was the way Rocker made no
effort to answer questions, begin trying to understand other
people's viewpoints, reach out and let actions speak louder than
words.
</P>
<P>
   The strongest, classiest people of all on this tense day at
Braves camp were Rocker's teammates. They were all class. To a man,
they stood there answering questions for as long as they were
asked, hoping to ease the public's pain and explain John Rocker.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker only hid.
</P>
<P>
   Chipper Jones stood in the sun for more than an hour, with
rarely fewer than 30 reporters surrounding him. Jones was asked why
Rocker refused to interact, to back up his words.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe John's scared,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   Of course it's scary. Baseball has been thrown headlong into as
touchy and hot an issue as any in America. But if you are sincere,
and you care and you hope to redefine yourself, you stand up to it
and begin taking those steps. Rocker didn't.
</P>
<P>
   Catcher Javy Lopez sat in the Braves' dugout, trying to let the
public know Rocker was not evil, only different and a man with
problems. But Lopez also wondered why Rocker didn't heed the advice
several teammates gave him in the Braves' closed-door meeting early
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was asked to address this with (the public) straight-on,''
Lopez said. ``He has to show people that he's changed.''
</P>
<P>
   Said shortstop Ozzie Guillen: ``He's maybe immature or stupid or
ignorant or whatever you want to call it. But he has to try to
change that. We'll try to help him, but really it's up to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Rocker had a chance to stand tall and make a sincere pitch to
the world Thursday. But like his first toss into the mitt as his
teammates answered for him, Rocker's effort was well out of the
strike zone.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
