<SLUG> BC-GEN-HOFFARTH-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO NEED TO SHOW GATHERS' DEATH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ (begin ital)``This was the scene about seven
minutes into the first half. Gathers with the stuff and LMU led
25-13. He goes back to play defense. You'll hear a whistle, and you
may want to turn your head. Some of you at home will not like to
see what's coming up. After the whistle, Gathers seemingly fine,
takes a couple of steps and collapses.''(en ital)
</P>
<P>
   -ESPN's Chris Berman on ``SportsCenter,'' March 4, 1990.
</P>
<P>
   There was no reason to show it the first time. There's no reason
to show it again.
</P>
<P>
   But ESPN Classic will do so Saturday at 5 p.m. as part of a
``SportsCenter Flashback'' series, a documentary on the life and
death of former Loyola Marymount basketball star Hank Gathers as it
happened 10 years ago to the date.
</P>
<P>
   The wrenching emotions brought in this less-than-30-second video
clip - watching Gathers go from finishing a dunk to fainting on the
court during a game, sitting up with that horrifying look on his
face, rolling over again and eventually dying from heart failure -
brings back the controversy of what went on behind the scenes at
ESPN with the producers who watched the video shot by a free-lance
cameraman and then had to decide in about an hour before the
``SportsCenter'' show which of it to air.
</P>
<P>
   The clip is a small part of the brilliantly presented hour-long
show on ESPN Classic. Bonded by interviews of some 20 people who
take us through that time, the result is an incredible effort to
cover every aspect of that story.
</P>
<P>
   But the decision then to run that tape is just as difficult -
and wrong - as it is today.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thrust of the show is to revisit the news of the day of
the prism of `SportsCenter,' and that being the case, it seems to
me from a news standpoint that it is appropriate to show again,``
said Vince Doria, ESPN Classic's executive producer who, at the
time of Gathers' death, was managing editor of The National Sports
Daily newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to those involved in the original decision and there
was much more of the video we did not show, such as the family
coming onto the court.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're always weighing whether it's news versus causing pain,
and I know in Los Angeles, this is very painful to watch again. But
it's interesting that no one we interviewed (for this show),
including Gathers' mother and brother, requested we not use it.
That being the case, my feeling is to present it as it was then to
give people the sense of the tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever you do this, there are valid arguments for or
against, but you have to come down one side or another. You go with
your convictions and hope you're doing the right thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox Sports News' Keith Olbermann, working at KCBS Channel 2 the
night of Gathers' death, is one of those whose convictions go the
other way.
</P>
<P>
   Olbermann, who did a beautiful tribute to Gathers during his
``Freestyle'' segment on Fox Sports News on Wednesday, considers
showing the tape of Gathers' last breathing moments ``was, and
remains, barbaric,'' adding he never let them replay that clip in
any ``SportsCenter'' he did at ESPN in the years he was there.
</P>
<P>
   In the ESPN Classic show, most poignant to L.A. viewers are the
comments from former USC basketball coach Stan Morrison and
assistant David Spencer, who brought Gathers and Bo Kimble to
Southern California from Philadelphia and remained very close to
the two after their abrupt firing. Also, former KTLA Channel 5
sportscaster Ed Arnold, who had the two as interns at the station,
breaks down several times remembering Gathers' impact on his life
and the community.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been that close to an athlete before, him and Bo,''
Arnold says in the show. ``Always as a reporter you try to separate
that, you try not to be so personal. This was a natural.''
</P>
<P>
   The show, hosted by ESPN's Karl Ravech, who himself experienced
a heart attack recently, is followed by a replay of the Feb. 3,
1990 game 20th-ranked LMU played at 14th-ranked Louisiana State.
Gathers scored 48 points in a 148-141 overtime loss against LSU
freshman Shaquille O'Neal (20 points, 24 rebounds, 12 blocks) and
another future NBA big man, Stanley Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   Pull up a tape recorder: Like it or not, today's Dodgers-Houston
exhibition opener from Vero Beach, Fla., is the first of weekday
games that will be delayed seven hours on radio, a 5 p.m. start, on
the team's flagship station AM-1150 as well as affiliates KAVL-AM
(610) in Lancaster, KBET-AM (850) in Thousand Oaks and KIIS-AM
(1220) in Santa Clarita.
</P>
<P>
   The games can be heard live on the Internet at the team's Web
site (www.dodgers.com), with most starts at 10 a.m. However, a
30-minute postgame show hosted by Ross Porter won't be taking phone
calls because it's part of the delay.
</P>
<P>
   On weekends, starting with KTLA Channel 5's Saturday (10 a.m.)
and Sunday (11 a.m.) coverage of the Dodgers-New York Mets games,
the experiment of having Vin Scully do a simulcast of the first two
innings for radio and TV starts.
</P>
<P>
   To clarify: The plan is to have Scully do only those two innings
on radio. He'll spend the rest of the time on TV.
</P>
<P>
   During the O'Malley regime, Scully agreed to do the fourth,
fifth and sixth innings of radio. It was cut it back to two middle
innings for the last two seasons. And now, his call won't even be
exclusive for radio.
</P>
<P>
   For the regular season, Scully plans to miss about 45 games.
Aside from taking off road games that aren't televised (about 32),
he'll sit about a dozen home that are on Fox Sports Net. He'll also
miss some time in May when he gives the commencement speech at his
alma mater, Fordham University.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Rick Monday has been mercifully replaced on weekend
``DodgerTalk'' by AM-1150's Jeff Biggs.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT SMOKES
</P>
<P>
   -The effect Los Angeles has on luring athletes into thinking
they have a future in TV and movies is one part of the latest
half-hour ESPN ``Outside the Lines'' (presented by AT&AMP;T, remember)
episode called ``Playing the Part: Athletes as Actors'' (today, 4
p.m., re-airing Saturday at 9 a.m.) The Lakers' Rick Fox and
Shaquille O'Neal are featured, as is former Rams great Fred
``Hunter'' Dryer. This should be a springboard for ESPN's next
``Lines'' special: ``Playing the Fool: `SportsCenter' Anchors Who
Wanna Be On Commercials.''
</P>
<P>
   -Joe McDonnell reports on his Web site (www.la-sports.com) that
he's actively looking to get back into sports-talk radio as well as
keep his afternoon weekday job doing sports updates on KFWB-AM
(980). ``For me to do talk again, it's either going to have to be
earlier in the day, on a weekend or on the Internet. If I was going
to bet on one, I'd say the Internet... And that's what I'm focusing
on right now,'' McDonnell writes.
</P>
<P>
   -ABC will end the season for ``Sports Night'' on April 4 so it
can't do any more ratings damage during May sweeps. According to
Entertainment Weekly, rival networks NBC and HBO are ready to take
the series if ABC dumps it.
</P>
<P>
   -No cracks about 7:15 gametime starts former Dodgers pitcher, TV
analyst and ``DodgerTalk'' host Al Downing has been hired as an
analyst on Fox Sports Net South's 30-game Atlanta Braves' TV
package.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT CHOKES
</P>
<P>
   -It's far from a marketing nightmare, but the Dodgers and some
members of the Jewish community who've shown support of the team
since the signing of !racepay!Shawn Green!off didn't find the first
advertisements about season ticket sales that ran in newspapers
last week very kosher. The ad presents an offer to buy two season
seats and get two more free in selected sections along with the ad
copy that reads: ``Use them with your kids, your clients or the two
schmucks down the street who swear they went to high school with
you.'' The Dodgers offices received calls the next day asking that,
aside from the fact this perpetuates the Jewish stereotype of
trying to get something free, the literal Yiddish translation for
``schmuck'' isn't appropriate. By the way, the marketing company
responsible for the ad, whom the Dodgers recently hired, is named
WongDoody. (begin ital)Oy vay(end ital).
</P>
<P>
   -Because concert dates at the Reunion Arena in the days prior to
the game cut into the prep time ESPN needed for the extra set-up,
the special ``NHL Rules!'' coverage of Sunday's Detroit-Dallas
contest had to be canceled. ESPN will still carry the game (5 p.m.)
with Gary Thorne and Bill Clement, but if it had gone as planned,
it would have been covered by two analysts (Clement and Darren
Pang) and no play-by-play man, and commentary and graphics would
have focused more on offensive and defensive strategies, explaining
rules and taking e-mail from viewers. ESPN's first attempt at this
kind of coverage drew rave reviews last month. A decision on the
next ``Rules!'' telecast will come soon.
</P>
