<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USC CAN'T GRAB A VICTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   STANFORD - USC was so desperate for ways to stop No. 1-ranked
Stanford on Thursday night, injured forward Jarvis Turner lunged
off the bench in street clothes and grabbed Cardinal guard Casey
Jacobsen by the shorts.
</P>
<P>
   Turner's ploy didn't work and he was quickly assessed a
technical foul by the officials.
</P>
<P>
   But nothing else the Trojans tried was remotely successful, as
the Cardinal breezed to a 111-68 victory before 7,391 at Maples
Pavilion.
</P>
<P>
   It was the most points USC has ever allowed in a basketball
game, and the second-worst loss in school history. Only a 92-48
loss to Arizona in 1988 ranks worse than this debacle.
</P>
<P>
   Turner's antics, which looked more like something out of a
cartoon or Marx Brothers movie, at least provided some
entertainment to a lopsided contest. And it was the first play he's
made in nearly five weeks since fracturing his left ankle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just out of frustration. I wanted to win and I got
carried away and caught up in the emotion of the game,'' Turner
said. ``It was real stupid. I shouldn't have done it. I was
frustrated sitting on the bench all season.''
</P>
<P>
   The most surprised person in the arena was Jacobsen, who looked
stunned following the sequence of events.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never heard of that happening before,'' Jacobsen said.
``I was really upset, but he did apologize after the game. It was
very bizarre. I kind of turned around and looked at him and he
wasn't looking at me, like he was hoping nobody saw him. Luckily,
the ref saw it. If the ref hadn't seen it, I would be upset.''
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the evening wasn't quite so funny for the Trojans.
Although forward Sam Clancy made his highly anticipated debut after
being out since Jan. 20 with a broken right foot, the Trojans lost
forward Brian Scalabrine late in the first half when he suffered a
right-hip flexor. He did not play in the second half and finished
with just four points.
</P>
<P>
   USC coach Henry Bibby said the trainers told him Scalabrine
would be OK for Saturday's game at California, but Scalabrine was
limping badly as he left Maples Pavilion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't know until I get back to the hotel for treatment,''
Scalabrine said. ``I stopped and changed directions on the floor
and it just popped. I don't know what's wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Clancy's situation was much more upbeat, or about the only good
news possible, when you've lost by 43 points to the top-ranked team
in the country.
</P>
<P>
   He played 18 minutes and had five rebounds, four points and two
assists and looked decent considering his long layoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt fine. (My foot) didn't bother me at all,'' Clancy
said. ``It's kind of sore now. I felt rusty out there. A lot of
shots I would normally make didn't go for me. I got tired a little
bit.''
</P>
<P>
   The loss probably eliminates USC from NCAA Tournament
consideration. USC hopes to finish the season with three victories
and then pray on Selection Sunday that a 17-13 record would somehow
be good enough to earn an at-large bid.
</P>
<P>
   But a more likely destination is the National Invitation
Tournament, provided the Trojans don't suffer a complete meltdown
and fail to win at least two of their final three games.
</P>
<P>
   USC's fate was about the only distraction from the Cardinal's
complete domination. Stanford (25-1, 14-1) shot 57.6 percent from
the field and did not trail except when Brandon Granville hit a
3-pointer to give the Trojans a 3-2 lead to start the game.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobsen had 23 points and Harvard-Westlake graduates Jarron and
Jason Collins also had big games. Jarron had 19 points and 10
rebounds; Jason added 14 points.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Trojans struggled from the field (37.1 percent),
a trademark during their slump that has seen them lose seven of
their past eight games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just didn't execute,'' Bibby said. ``We've had that problem
lately where we don't run anything, we just have Brandon or Brian
dribbling around. What bothered me tonight was that we didn't even
compete.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
