<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRUGGLING KINGS LOSE TO HURRICANES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A week ago, the Kings were flying, and not just
across Canada on their longest trip of the season.
</P>
<P>
   They were no longer scratching for that final playoff spot, they
were taking it to teams. The question was not if but (begin
ital)who(end ital) they would play in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   But suddenly they have only a tie to show for three games
against lesser opponents, including Thursday's dreary 5-2 loss to
the Carolina Hurricanes in front of a stunned crowd of 15,424 at
the Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   This was a point in the schedule where they expected to solidify
their postseason position, the Kings got just one out of a possible
six. With 18 games left and Nashville in town Saturday, they should
be making a move. Instead, they are standing still.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope we don't think we're in,'' Ian Laperriere said.
``Because if we do, we won't be. This is a very critical point in
the season. We have to realize nothing has been decided.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only are they not scoring, the Kings are taking bad
penalties, including two that led to power-play goals.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings got a power-play goal from Glen Murray with 1:38 left,
but it became even more meaningless when Rod Brind `Amour closed
out the scoring with an empty-netter with 18.8 seconds remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is no way to be playing now,'' said Luc Robitaille, who
scored the Kings' first goal. ``We did not have that desperation
that we need. When we were on the road, we barely practiced and at
the end of the trip we started some bad habits. We still have a
little of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Against the Hurricanes, there was plenty of time for a comeback
when the Kings entered the third period trailing just 2-1. But when
Gary Roberts scored his second goal for Carolina just 25 seconds
into the third period, it was too late for a wakeup call.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings now have two goals in the last two games and four in
the last three. Robitaille, who now has 33 and a league-tying
15-game scoring streak.
</P>
<P>
   Kings coach Andy Murray spent much of Wednesday meeting with
members of the team's sluggish second unit. Center Bryan Smolinski
does not have a goal in eight games and just one in the past 12. He
had one shot Thursday and it came in the first period.
</P>
<P>
   The Hurricanes (27-29-9) had just two victories in their
previous seven games and a 7-5 loss in Phoenix on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   But the Hurricanes, who end their trip Saturday in San Jose,
scored four goals in the third period of that game and appeared
ready to keep it going against the Kings.
</P>
<P>
   After Sami Kapanen scored with 7:32 gone in the first, the Kings
needed almost an entire period to regroup. Carolina goaltender
Arturs Irbe made it nearly impossible with several outstanding
saves in the first period that built the Hurricanes' confidence. He
stopped 30 shots overall.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings finally tied the game at 6:05 of the second period
when Robitaille took a pass from Jozef Stumpel in the slot. But
much of the second period looked like the past two games, a loss to
San Jose and a tie with Vancouver. The Kings often looked out of
sync.
</P>
<P>
   Midway through the period, the Kings went on the power play when
Gelinas was whistled for roughing at 8:50. But only 38 seconds
later, Blake ended the man advantage when he was called for
elbowing.
</P>
<P>
   But the worst came after Smolinski was called for roughing at
12:31. The Kings were 18 seconds from killing the penalty when
Garry Galley was sent off for holding. The momentum was killed. The
Hurricanes quickly took a 2-1 lead on Roberts' goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those penalties were made out of frustration,'' Murray said.
``They came at bad times and they hurt us. We know we're not going
to get into the playoffs with 71 points.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
