<HEADLINE>
KANSAS STATE BACKS OUT OF USC DEAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ USC is searching to fill open dates on its
football schedule in 2001 and 2002 after Kansas State coach Bill
Snyder killed a home-and-home series between the schools.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans and Wildcats had agreed in principle to play at the
Coliseum on Sept. 12, 2001, and Sept. 19, 2002 at Arrowhead Stadium
in Kansas City. But when Kansas State officials presented the deal
to Snyder, it was canceled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach Snyder deliberated and made a decision he didn't want to
formalize an agreement,'' said Jim Epps, Kansas State senior
associate athletic director. ``Coach Snyder has control of
scheduling. It's his call. It has been taken off the board.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was moving forward and had reached a point where we
mutually agreed to play.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision was a blow to USC, which has had trouble filling
those two dates. Last fall, Virginia agreed to play a home-and-home
series before backing out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought the deal was done with Kansas State,'' said Daryl
Gross, USC associate athletic director. ``They gave us every
indication they would play the game.''
</P>
<P>
   USC officials were surprised by Kansas State's reluctance to
play because Snyder has been criticized in recent years for playing
a soft nonconference schedule. Snyder could not be reached for
comment.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, USC has begun talks with Kansas about replacing the
Wildcats on the schedule in 2001 and 2002. There might be a chance
that the 2002 game would be played at Arrowhead Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes it tough to find some in 2001; hopefully, we'll find
someone our fans will like,'' Gross said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, San Jose State has requested that its game with the
Trojans this season, originally scheduled for Sept. 16, be switched
to Sept. 23. This means USC could have two byes in the first four
weeks of the upcoming season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
