<SLUG> BC-BOX-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A COSTLY NIGHT FOR KING?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the epic monuments to American capitalism, Don King, is
on the line from Las Vegas, and I immediately cut to the core with
the notorious fight promoter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any federal indictments against you lately?'' I wondered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, Kirk, I can always count on you being concerned about my
legal welfare,'' responded King theatrically. ``Well, the good news
t that the federal government isn't still trying. Al Capone, Lucky
Luciano and John Gotti didn't get the unrelenting scrutiny that I
have over the years from our government.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that's what makes America such a great country. Yes, I've
been indicted more times than I can count, but each time I've been
as our great legal system has exposed the miscarriage of justice
that has been perpetuated against me. Still, there are times I feel
like Alfred Dreyfus, the French army officer who became a martyr
all around Europe near the turn of the last century because he was
wrongly convicted of treason. I feel as though my great country
doesn't appreciate uniqueness and greatness and too often believes
the scurrilous accusations made against me by my enemies.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, boxing aficionados aren't appreciating King's
Showtime pay-per-view WBA match tonight between two undefeated
fighters, Felix Trinidad (36-0) and David Reid (14-0), that is
being staged in a newly erected outdoor stadium at Caesars Palace.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, King's fierce rival, Bob Arum, who is putting on his
own show Saturday night at Mandalay Bay featuring Paulie Ayala
against Johnny Bredahl for the WBA bantamweight title, is
predicting that King will drop $6 million on this evening's event.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why suddenly is Bob Arum worried about my financial well
being?'' said King. ``First off, I don't go into any fight where my
own money is on the line. Any good businessman always makes sure he
takes out more than he puts in a venture. The site fees from the
casino and the money from the cable network pay the bills on my
show. And, secondly, I could stand to lose six million a year for
the next 100 years, and still not be broke.
</P>
<P>
   ``Isn't America just wonderful? Isn't America the only country
in the world where a Don King can jive and thrive and survive?''
</P>
<P>
   King believes Arum has attempted to sabotage his fight by
spreading rumors in recent weeks that it would be canceled because
of slow gate sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, reports of the demise of our show are slightly
premature, indubitably!,'' said King. ``We're definitely going to
have the fight. Arum wanted me to cancel it so as not to risk
Trinidad getting beat, but it's definitely coming off. They've done
everything to try to ruin my show. I originally made it way back on
November 13, and it was set to be on Saturday, March 4. But then
Dan Goossen (Reid's promoter) backed out of the fight, and the next
thing I knew Arum scheduled a show for March 4. And, when we made
Trinidad and Reid again, we had to put it back a day to March 3.
That's why we're having it on a Friday.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the Trinidad-Reid fight figures to provide far more
thrills and drama than last week's latest Oscar De La Hoya-scripted
farce his preordained, one-sided impalement of the unwilling,
chicken-jawed Darrell Coley at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has all the makings of a classic fight,'' said King.
``You have a great Olympic hero in Reid who's a natural 154 pounder
fighting a great welterweight champion in Trinidad making his first
start at 154. Neither man has lost as a pro, and you can be sure
each will fight to the finish. You won't see one of these guys
kneeling on one knee as Darrell Coley did when he meekly
surrendered against Oscar De La Hoya.''...
</P>
<P>
   Bob Arum insists to me that reports are true that he has made an
Oscar De La Hoya-Sugar Shane Mosley fight in June either at Staples
Center or Mandalay Bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely going to happen,'' said Arum.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first serious mistake you've made with De La
Hoya,'' I told Arum, whose shrewd matchmaking and even shrewder
marketin turned De La Hoya into a fistic superstar even though De
La Hoya has done nothing in his well-choreographed career to
deserve such stature. ``Mosley isn't half as big as De La Hoya,
like Pernell Whitaker was. Mosley hasn't been inactive for two
years, like Ike Quartey was. Mosley won't allow De La Hoya to
dictate the fight, like Trinidad did for eight rounds. Mosley has
the speed and quickness and passion to actually beat De La Hoya.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I know ... I know,'' replied Arum. ``That's what makes this a
great fight, and it should do great at the box office. Oscar just
got tired of Trinidad's father negotiating tactics. He told me on
Monday, `The hell with Trinidad, make the Mosley fight.' And that's
what I've done.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, De La Hoya and Mosley haven't signed a contract yet, and
Arum says that will happen next week, meaning the clever Arum might
just be posturing and waiting for the Trinidad-Reid outcome.
</P>
<P>
   If Trinidad scores a spectacular knockout, you can be sure the
sporting public's yearning for a Trinidad-De La Hoya rematch will
be heightened and so will Arum's.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line is that Trinidad and De La Hoya each will earn
$20 million if they fight each other again, while De La Hoya will
make only $7 million for Mosley and Trinidad will make a lot less
for whoever he fights.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Trinidad loses to Reid, he'll come begging for Oscar,''
says Arum.
</P>
<P>
   Arum might insist that De La Hoya's next fight will be against
Mosley, but I still think financial considerations will result in
it being against Trinidad.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, Bob Arum will make many more millions of dollars if
Trinidad and De La Hoya fight again, a compelling incentive for
Arum to make it...
</P>
<P>
   Arum reveals that Republican presidential candidate Sen. John
McClain, a boxing fanatic who has authored a bill for the federal
regulation of the sport, bought tickets and attended De La Hoya's
fights against Whitaker, Quartey and Trinidad. ...
</P>
<P>
   I find it one of the classic ironies of the insufferable
politically correct climate in which we're now forced to reside
that high-profile murder suspect jocks like Rae Carruth and Raymond
Lewis get treated far gentler in the national media than does an
immature 25-year-old left-handed Atlanta Brave reliever named John
Rocker, who has been drawn and quartered with relentless savagery
for making intemperate remarks to a Sports Illustrated reporter.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, one doesn't condone Rocker's warped views on gays,
foreigners and minorities, but I was under the mistaken impression
that the American Constitution's First Amendment guarantees a
person freedom of speech, no matter how offensive it might happen
to be to some people.
</P>
<P>
   I thought just punishment for Rocker would have been for Bud
Selig to have mandated Rocker to cleanse his mouth out daily with
Borax for 73 days, instead of placating the frenzied mob who wanted
Rocker's scalp with that 73-day suspension and $20,000 fine.
</P>
<P>
   Where is the sense proportion on this issue? Rocker is a
numskull who uttered a bunch of inane statements, granted. But he
didn't rape, shoot, knife, mug, rob, or murder anyone.
</P>
<P>
   The arbitrator, Shyam Das, was right in reducing Rocker's
punishment. Indeed, Rocker has been punished enough in the shrill
court of public opinion and figures to suffer heavily for his crude
remarks for which, incidentally, he has apologized numerous times
for the remainder of his major league career. I find it so typical
of this morally preening era that those who have been most
unforgiving toward Rocker are the same hypocrites who preach
tolerance at the drop of a TV sound bite.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
