<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   These excellent articles are from the current ECONOMIST magazine
(week beginning 4 March 2000); they have all moved to the ``k''
commentary category code.  &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (ATTN. EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist. Nonsubscribers
can use this article only by special arrangement. For purchase
information, call 1-888-269-8796.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MUDDLE IN THE JUNGLE: U.S. NARCS VS. COLOMBIA'S FARC &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It is not Vietnam, nor will it become so. But once again the
United States is preparing to commit lots of cash, military
hardware and advisers to a battle in a foreign jungle. This one is
in southern Colombia, where an embattled president faces daunting
problems, including left-wing guerrillas, right-wing paramilitaries
and the world's largest source of coca, the raw material for
cocaine. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: 2 trims, totaling 150; total uncut is 1,000 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-US-COCA-WAR-450&AMP;add-ECONOMIST-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DEMONIZING HEZBOLLAH WON'T SAVE YOUR SOLDIERS, ISRAEL &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To bomb the Hezbollah guerrillas fighting Israeli occupation or
just to threaten to bomb? That seems to be the only question the
Israeli government asks itself about Lebanon these days. As a
result, Lebanese civilians suffer much more at Israeli hands than
vice versa. True, Hezbollah used to be an alarmingly active
terrorist group. But nowadays, things are not quite so simple.
Indeed, for all the talk of Lebanese terrorism, it is Hezbollah
that has looked the more disciplined force of late, and Israel that
has been making innocents suffer. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (700 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-BACK-OFF-HEZBOLLAH-ECONOMIST-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AMERICA'S RIGHT. STANLEY FISCHER IS BEST BOSS FOR THE IMF &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Doubtless, Caio Koch-Weser is a jolly decent fellow. Germany's
finance state secretary could probably do all sorts of jobs,
perfectly competently or even brilliantly. The trouble is that
running the International Monetary Fund is not one of them. What a
pity that the best man for the job _ Stanley Fischer, the IMF's
deputy managing director and, since Michel Camdessus stepped down a
few weeks ago, it's acting head _ probably won't get it. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (675 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-IMF-HEAD-ACHE-ECONOMIST-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; USA &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE SELF-DESTRUCTION OF BILL BRADLEY &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Willie Whitelaw, a British Tory grandee, once accused Labor
activists of going around the country ``stirring up apathy.'' That
has often seemed to be the essence of Bradley's campaign. He is
such a laconic speaker that one wonders whether the candidate or
the audience will fall asleep first. How did this former basketball
star and Senate veteran turn out to be such a dismal candidate? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Political, Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: Story can stand in 650 words; 850 words uncut) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-BRADLEY-BLOOPERS-ECONOMIST-650&AMP;add-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CALIFORNIA DREAMIN': WHO'LL WIN ELECTORAL GOLD RUSH TUESDAY? &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As goes California, so goes the nation. Or so Californians like
to claim. Only three times in the past century has a candidate won
the presidential election without winning in California. In
November, with Florida and Texas likely to be solidly Republican,
California seems a particularly crucial piece of the electoral
map. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Political, Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (TIMELY for March 7 primary) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: 2 trims, totaling 600 words; 1,325 words uncut) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-CALIF-POLL-VAULT-ECONOMIST-625&AMP;add-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MCCAIN'S GRANDDADDY OF A `SISTER SOULJAH' MOMENT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   John McCain's behavior bears the hallmarks of reckless political
courage. Denouncing the Reverend Pat Robertson, founder of the
Christian Coalition, in his own Virginia hometown, was a remarkable
moment in recent Republican history. Never before has a
presidential candidate nominee castigated the religious right like
that. It was not just a Sister Souljah moment, mimicking Bill
Clinton's 1992 attack on black extremism, it was a brother,
grandmother and indeed entire Souljah family moment. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Political, Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: 2 trims, totaling 225 words; 1,075 words uncut) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-MCCAIN-WRATH-450&AMP;add-ECONOMIST-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PRIMARY COLOR: QUIRKY MOMENTS ON THIS WEEK'S CAMPAIGN TRAIL &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (This week's droll ``Primary Color'' column) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary, Humor, Political Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (475 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-PRIMARYCOLOR-COLUMN-ECONOMIST-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; `POSTER BOY' ELIAN BACKFIRES ON CUBAN-AMERICAN HARD-LINERS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Three months after Elian Gonzalez, a six-year-old Cuban boy, was
rescued from the sea off Miami, his story resembles the fanciful
tele-novelas that Latinos love to watch. Call it ``The Curse of
Elian.'' But there is also a growing sense that the story is not
playing out in the way that Miami's hard-line Cuban-American
leaders had intended. Ironically, they may in fact be helping the
very man they detest: Fidel Castro. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Miami...NOTE March 9 hearing, 7th graf) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: 150-word trim at 375; 900 words uncut) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-ELIAN-CURSE-375&AMP;add-ECONOMIST-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE AMERICAS &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MEXICO'S CERTIFIABLY MAD WAR ON DRUGS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It is known as the ``February surprise.'' Every year, shortly
before the U.S. government announces on March 1 which countries it
``certifies'' as willing allies in the war on illegal drugs, Mexico
unveils a new and bold anti-drugs initiative. This year, though,
the surprise was on Mexico. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (525 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-MEXICO-DRUGS-ECONOMIST-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
