<HEADLINE>
PRIMARY COLOR: QUIRKY MOMENTS ON THIS WEEK'S CAMPAIGN TRAIL  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary, Humor, Political Editors)   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist. Nonsubscribers
can use this article only by special arrangement. For purchase
information, call 1-888-269-8796.)  
  
 From the Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; QUERY OF THE WEEK (1): &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Q: ``If you absolutely had to choose, which of the four
candidates would you most want as your father?''
</P>
<P>
   A: John McCain, 35.9 percent; George W. Bush, 24.2 percent; Al
Gore 18.9 percent; Bill Bradley, 13.7 percent. (Luntz Research
Company for yrock.com, a Web site for young Republicans) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FACTOID OF THE WEEK: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   According to a recent report by the Pew Research Center, 9
percent of Americans learn about the presidential campaign through
late-night talk shows, 6 percent from various comedy programs, and
5 percent from MTV. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; QUERY OF THE WEEK (2): &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Q: ``Which of the four candidates do you think had the most
problems getting a date to their senior prom?''
</P>
<P>
   A: Al Gore, 33.5 percent; Bill Bradley, 23.2 percent; George W.
Bush, 20.3 percent; John McCain, 17.2 percent. (yrock.com) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PORN MERCHANT OF THE WEEK: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   McCain, who, by purchasing space for campaign ads on
theglobe.com, thereby risked placing them on that company's porn
site. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; QUERY OF THE WEEK (3): &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Q: ``Which of the four do you think is most likely to cheat at
golf?''
</P>
<P>
   A: George W. Bush, 36.4 percent; Al Gore, 30.1 percent; John
McCain, 9.8 percent; Bill Bradley, 8.8 percent. (yrock.com) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LYRICAL UTTERANCE OF THE WEEK: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   By Eric Hauser, Bill Bradley's campaign spokesman, as hedenied
rumors that if Bradley lost heavily (as he did) in Washington
state, he would drop out: ``People on the Hill don't know
(expletive) about (expletive). I worked on the Hill for ten years;
their jobs suck, so they spend their time talking about this
(expletive) instead of trying to help the country.'' (Salon.com,
Feb. 29) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPACE METAPHOR OF THE WEEK: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush went to Mars and won as a Martian, and now he wants to
rub the green pigment off his skin. Well, he can't do that.'' (Mike
Murphy, McCain's strategist, on Bush's embrace of the religious
right. Newsweek, March 6) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; QUERY OF THE WEEK (4): &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Q: ``Which of the four do you think is most likely to be an
alien?''
</P>
<P>
   A: Al Gore, 38.9 percent; George W. Bush, 20.8 percent; Bill
Bradley, 17.3 percent; John McCain, 14 percent. (yrock.com) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DELEGATE TOTALS OF THE WEEK: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Bush, 170; McCain, 105. A candidate needs 1,034 delegate votes
to win the Republican nomination. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; QUERY OF THE WEEK (5): &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q: ``Which of the four would you rather kill yourself than be
stuck alone with for a week?''
</P>
<P>
   A: Al Gore, 39.6 percent; George W. Bush, 27.6 percent; Bill
Bradley, 9.5 percent; John McCain, 9.1 percent. (yrock.com) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
