<HEADER>
A5556 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-BORDERS-COLUMN04-COX     03-03 0704
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDERS-COLUMN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    How I created, then ended, the drought
 &HT;    By Gary Borders
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NACOGDOCHES, Texas _ I believe that I am responsible for
creating the drought that has gripped Deep East Texas for a year,
and I hope to take the credit for ending it. I know the drought is
plaguing nearly all of Texas, but I can only bear responsibility
for my neck of the woods. Find another columnist to blame, or
credit, if you live elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   We built our house nearly two years ago. Building a house is
akin to childbirth, or so I'm told _ being genetically incapable of
that act and mighty thankful to boot. Building a house requires a
lot of pain, most of which you forget, which is why people are
willing to go through the process more than once. At the time, East
Texas was blessed with an over-abundance of rain, and since I was
rapidly running out of money I opted not to install a sprinkler
system.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it quit raining on the same day I had the sod laid
down, nearly an acre of it, and I nearly killed myself hauling
hoses around to keep the San Augustine grass alive. My grass went
the first three months without seeing a measurable amount of
unchlorinated water.
</P>
<P>
   But by late fall, we were back to our usual monsoon weather. It
was then I realized that my back yard was a natural swamp, being
about eight feet lower than my backyard neighbor. Funny how you
don't notice these things when the lot is covered with trees. From
the winter solstice on, the back yard had at least six inches of
standing water. By February of last year, I had two choices. Put in
a drainage system or buy a bunch of ducks and declare my back yard
a mitigated wetland area. I was leaning toward the ducks, but my
wife was afraid hunters would start camping out in the back yard,
disturbing her beauty sleep on the weekends with intermittent
blasts from 12-gauges. Once it dried out enough to dig ditches, I
spent, well, too much money putting in a French-drain system that
worked perfectly. Soon the back yard was actually traversable
again.
</P>
<P>
   The drought, a k a ``The Time It Never Rained: The Sequel''
began about 72 hours after the drainage system was installed. In
the last year, it has rained so seldom that my cheap glass rain
gauge cracked. There hasn't been much reason to buy a new one.
</P>
<P>
   Until now. I reached the point of no-return and have poneyd up
the money to put in a sprinkler system. I can't pull hoses around
the yard for another season. My back hurts, and I'm getting cranky.
So I made my banker happy and borrowed the money to put in a
sprinkler system.
</P>
<P>
   The crew started digging on Wednesday. Understand, it hasn't
rained for more than 15 minutes since Thanksgiving. My grass has
been gasping for sustenance for months. My favorite TV show is the
Weather Channel, where smart-looking women promise a chance of rain
but rarely deliver. The weather people blame La Nina for the latest
drought. El Nino got the blame for the last one.
</P>
<P>
   I know the weather means a lot more to folks who actually depend
on it for a living. I'm worried about grass; they're worried about
their livelihood. If it doesn't rain, my lawn dies. Those in the
cattle business have a lot more to worry about. But we're all
praying for rain.
</P>
<P>
   So I decided to put in a sprinkler system. I am feeling hopeful.
It started pouring rain approximately two hours after work
commenced on the sprinkler system. I came home after lunch to find
the crew standing under the eaves on the front porch, smoking
cigarettes and staring at the water. Several days later, work is
progressing slowly, since the ground is wet. There's a 50 percent
chance of more thunderstorms on the day I'm writing this. My yard
now looks like a herd of giant mutant gophers has run amok.
</P>
<P>
   I know better than to complain about rain. I made a vow during
the drought of '98 to never complain about rain again, and I have
kept it. I would just like a little recognition for doing my part
to end the drought. That's all.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Borders is editor and publisher of The Nacogdoches Daily
Sentinel. E-mail: gborders(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
