u k BC-MINTER-COLUMN04-COX     03-03 0870
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINTER-COLUMN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    She wants to see Egypt, but I'm pushing for Alabama
 &HT;    By Jim Minter
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FAYETTE COUNTY, Ga. _ This is the time of the year I begin to
get two questions:
</P>
<P>
   1. ``Is your wife going to let you plant another garden?''
</P>
<P>
   2. ``What trips does she have planned for you?''
</P>
<P>
   The answer to No. 1 is: ``We're currently in negotiations.''
</P>
<P>
   The answer to No. 2 is: ``I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   We spend late winter evenings sitting beside the fire, perusing
our favorite publications. I thumb through seed catalogs while she
studies travel magazines and brochures, which arrive so steadily I
can intercept only a few at the mailbox.
</P>
<P>
   I was engrossed in an item about Burpee's new disease-resistant
English peas when she brought up the subject of travel plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's go somewhere different this year,'' she said. ``I'd like
to know more about how people lived before modern times.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a good idea,'' I agreed. ``We've never done much
traveling in Alabama.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking about something more exotic,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like what?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Like pyramids.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Alabama has Indian burial mounds,'' I answered. ``I doubt
there's a lot of difference. Dead is dead. Besides, the pyramids
are such a long way off in Egypt. We could see Indian mounds in
Alabama and then stop over at one of the lakes for some fishing,
all on maybe two tanks of gas.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're worried about expense, we better go see the pyramids
this year,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why is that?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the election. If a Republican gets in the White
House, the country will have a terrible recession and we won't have
any money.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Where in the world did you get that idea?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I read the newspapers and watch television,'' she replied.
``Don't you know about Bill Clinton giving us the greatest and
longest period of prosperity we've ever known?''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's remarkable,'' I agreed. ``And to think he did that all
by himself while Al Gore was off inventing the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're going to take another long trip, we need to go while
times are good,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were going somewhere far away, I certainly wouldn't go to
Egypt,'' I replied.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why wouldn't you go to Egypt?'' she asked. ``People who have
been there say it's a very interesting place.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That may be,'' I replied. ``But people who go there seem to
have a hard time getting out.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a new excuse,'' she said. ``Where did you dig that one
up?''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's in the Bible. Didn't they teach you about Moses in Sunday
school? I'd hate to get over there and have to go through all the
things he did trying to get back home.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know you were a biblical expert,'' she remarked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't you have to get on a boat and sail up the Nile River to
see the pyramids?'' I asked. ''Didn't you read the story in the
newspaper about Muslim fanatics massacring 22 Christians in one of
those little Nile villages? I don't think Methodists are too
popular over there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I read the story,'' she replied. ''It said Egyptians think
what happened in that village is an extreme case and not likely to
happen again. It's a situation sort of like Buckhead in Atlanta.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's bad enough that the pope is going to Egypt to try to
help,'' I pointed out. ''I think we ought to wait and see how he
comes out before we make plans to go. We can always do the pyramids
after we do Alabama.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not getting any younger,'' she replied. ``We need to
make foreign trips while you can still get around without a cane.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Have you been talking to Claude McBride again?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had some conversations and he sent a brochure.''
</P>
<P>
   Claude is one of my University of Georgia journalism classmates,
a retired Baptist minister who doubles as an alumni tour leader and
chaplain for the football team. He was once a trusted friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly wouldn't go to Egypt with a Baptist preacher when
they're killing Christians,'' I said. ``Being a Methodist or even
an Episcopalian would be dangerous enough.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you think of any other excuses?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other than the need to save money for your Republican
recession and terrorists always hijacking planes in that part of
the world, I can't think of anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   That's how things stand at the moment. Unless I can come up with
an exotic destination in Alabama or Mississippi, I'm afraid I'm in
imminent danger of making a trip to Egypt to see the pyramids. She
has rather firmly ruled out both Panama City and Elvis' place in
Memphis.
</P>
<P>
   The best I can hope for is a larger garden and making sure we're
not away from home when the tomatoes and Silver Queen come in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Go ahead and order your English peas and the other garden seed
you want,'' she said. ``It's nice to have fresh vegetables in the
summer, and we might even put up some for the winter in case the
Republicans win.''
</P>
<P>
   Once again I'm being out-maneuvered, but in spousal
negotiations, you take what you can get.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Minter is a former editor in chief of The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
