A5558 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD04-COX     03-03 0591
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Plane-ly speaking, use jointer to flatten
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The thread of messages on the Internet about whether
one needs a jointer for milling boards, which I wrote about not
long ago, continues.
</P>
<P>
   It's amazing how many folks think the only thing they'd use a
jointer for is jointing.
</P>
<P>
   I suppose that's because it's called a jointer, when in fact it
might more properly be called a flattener or a face leveler.
</P>
<P>
   You do not, in fact, need a jointer to square the edge of boards
for glueing. It's a simple thing to do using nothing but the
standard 22-inch jointer plane. At the risk of boring relatively
experienced readers, here's how it's done:
</P>
<P>
   Take two boards that are to be glued together (laminated) to
make a wider board and set them down in the position in which you
want to glue them, face side up, right and left side ends matched.
Now pick them up and swing them so they are back to back, face
sides out, matching edges down on the workbench. Clamp them
together, being sure to use scrap pads to avoid denting the wood.
</P>
<P>
   Now flip them over and clamp them in the vise. If they're long,
you'll want to clamp the other end to the bench using a pipe clamp
to keep the assembly from slipping.
</P>
<P>
   Once you've got these boards where you want them, all you do is
joint both the edges at once (this assumes you're using 4/4 stock
or thinner. If larger, it's off to the jointer you go). Using a
hand plane is not difficult to learn, although the heavy jointer
plane isn't necessarily the one you want to learn with.
</P>
<P>
   Basically, when starting a pass, you put most of the pressure on
the forward end of the plane until the handle is over the wood;
then you use equal pressure fore and aft until you get to the point
where the forward knob is off the wood. Then you shift nearly all
the pressure to the handle. The object, of course, is to keep from
planing a convex edge into the wood.
</P>
<P>
   The point of doing both edges at once is that if you fail to
keep the plane exactly level, the edges will be mirror images and
will mate anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Make fine cuts until you are taking a shaving off the entire
assembly. At that point, the two boards should be ready to glue.
</P>
<P>
   And speaking of gluing ...
</P>
<P>
   The question came up of preventing slippage while gluing. Anyone
who has glued two edges together knows that the glue makes the
boards want to slide around and, if allowed, slide out of
alignment.
</P>
<P>
   Some woodworkers use biscuits or dowels just to keep the boards
aligned. This is a lot of unnecessary work. One correspondent had a
novel method; he said he sprinkles coarse sand on one of the edges,
and this stops the slippage. I can see that it would, but I'd
rather not get sand anywhere near my edged tools.
</P>
<P>
   If you have trouble with slippage, simply prepare a few scrap
boards with flat, or even slightly convex edges, cut to be an inch
or so longer than the width of the assembly. Run the glue on the
workpieces, put the clamps on and apply enough pressure to get some
squeeze-out. At that point, get some more clamps, make a kind of
sandwich out of pairs of the scrap boards, and clamp them together
edge-down, above and below the workpieces, using wax paper to
prevent them from getting involved in the glue.
</P>
<P>
   Two or three of these ought to keep the boards from shifting,
and then you can finish getting the pressure you need on the
glue-up clamps.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
