   RELIGION
</P>
<P>
   KABBALAH _ DAYTON, Ohio _ What the Beatles did for
transcendental meditation in the 1960s, Madonna, Elizabeth Taylor
and Courtney Love may be doing for the study of the Kabbalah _ the
mystical tradition that lies at the root of Jewish practice.
(Jesse, Dayton Daily News). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   EPISCOPAL-REFLECT _ ATLANTA _ For almost 13 years, Frank Kellog
Allan has been Episcopal bishop of Atlanta, one of the country's
fastest growing Episcopal communities. Beginning Monday, he will be
a shopkeeper. Allan, who has retired from the episcopate ``but not
from life,'' is opening ``By the Work of OUr Hands,'' a store
devoted to folk arts and crafts, to display the work of about 200
North Georgia artisans and to benefit local Episcopal charities.
``You're never closer to God than when you're creating,'' said
Allan, whose woodwork will be sold in the shop. The new role is in
keeping with his belief that people should live simply and give
away much. Several years ago he and his wife sold their large
northwest Atlanta home and moved into a much smaller, and cheaper,
house near Emory. He has given away much of his $100,000 annual
salary as bishop. Recently, Allan sat down to reflect on religion
and life _ especially what he expects in the rest of his own.
(White, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 30.WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
