A5561 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-KABBALAH04-COX     03-03 0629
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KABBALAH04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Kabbalah seeks unity thorugh self-empowerment
 &HT;    By Kathy Whyde Jesse
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ What the Beatles did for transcendental
meditation in the 1960s, Madonna, Elizabeth Taylor and Courtney
Love may be doing for the study of the Kabbalah _ the mystical
tradition that lies at the root of Jewish practice.
</P>
<P>
   Christians, skeptics, even atheists have found benefit from
these Jewish teachings, according to Rabbi Yehuda Shemtov, of
suburban Philadelphia. Shemtov has put together a national Jewish
seminar that offers an introduction to the broad range of mystical
texts that were passed down verbally for thousands of years, and at
one time considered to be a knowledge too powerful for ordinary
people to receive.
</P>
<P>
   Shemtov's program is called Inward Bound. The 4 1/2-hour course
includes group study and discussion, meditation, guided
visualizations and interactive exercises.
</P>
<P>
   More than 1,000 people across the country have gone through the
course since Shemtov started it about four years ago. That's not a
lot of people, but it's important to limit class size in order to
keep it interactive, he says.
</P>
<P>
   No one is asked about their religious background when they sign
up, but he knows that non-Jews participate because they tell him.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are looking for spirituality and not finding it in
organized religion,'' says Shemtov, an Orthodox Jew who
nevertheless believes that such labels are meaningless. ``Religion
has become rote and mechanical. We know that keeping the Sabbath is
one of the commandments, but what is the Sabbath all about? That
has become lost.''
</P>
<P>
   If Judaism is a practice of religion, then the Kabbalah is the
reason behind the practice. And that's what people hunger for,
Shemtov says.
</P>
<P>
   The Kabbalah, like other spiritual explorations that have become
trendy in recent years, is a means toward self-empowerment and
personal growth, Shemtov says. ``It's a key to open up your soul.''
</P>
<P>
   In Kabbalistic literature and practice _ which includes prayer,
fasting, chanting, meditation and breath control _ can be found a
sensitivity to gender equality, environmental protection and
dialogue with other spiritual traditions, says Ron Feldman in his
book, ``Fundamentals of Jewish Mysticism and Kabbalah'' (Crossing,
$12.95). That makes it an attractive option for contemporary
seekers.
</P>
<P>
   David Marcus, 62, a Dayton cardiologist, has been studying the
Kabbalah for about a year. He studies with Rabbi Nochum Mangel,
director of the Chabad Center of Greater Dayton, which is hosting
an Inward Bound presentation in Dayton on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Marcus, who was raised in the Jewish tradition, finds that
Kabbalah study makes his prayer more meaningful and helps ``bring
down godliness into our physical world.'' As a physician, it is
easy to feel that his life's work has purpose. But the Kabbalah
helps him understand that ``it takes many, many talents to make the
world work.''
</P>
<P>
   Mangel says the Kabbalah is the basis for everything he teaches.
His twice-monthly Torah discussions begin with the practical _ the
law, then take a Kabbalistic twist: ``What does this do to our
soul?''
</P>
<P>
   An example: The commandment to love your neighbor as yourself
means go out of your way to help other people. But the mystical
subtext is, ``We're all part of the same creation,'' Mangel says.
That total stranger is another part of yourself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mysticism tries to unite,'' says Rabbi Shmuel Klatzkin, also
of the Chabad Center. ``It teaches that we're not just little egos
walking around in boxes of skin and bones. We're not all so private
and different. We're all here because of God's purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
