<DOCNO> NYT20000303.0073 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-03 10:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5562 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-PALSY04-COX     03-03 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PALSY04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Parents hope high doses of oxygen will heal cerebral palsy child
 &HT;    By Kevin Lamb
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ A girl's upcoming trip for an experimental
cerebral palsy treatment in Toronto has begun kindling some
interest in clinically testing the procedure.
</P>
<P>
   Tiffany Foxx will undergo about 100 hyperbaric oxygen treatments
in June and August. Her parents and doctors hope that breathing
concentrated oxygen will revive brain cells that have been inactive
since she was born five years ago. Few patients have tried the
procedure, but doctors who administer it tell of helping children
walk, sit up, control their arms or eat for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   It's worth investigating, says Dr. John Bishop, medical director
of the Kettering Hyperbaric and Wound Care facility at
Wright-Patterson Air Force Base. Bishop's facility cannot
administer experimental treatments unless they're part of an
approved scientific study, but he says, ``We would be interested in
collaborating with someone who treats cerebral palsy children and
would like to do hyperbaric research.''
</P>
<P>
   It wouldn't be easy, he warned. It probably would take a year of
planning and approval ``to even start it,'' and he hasn't even
looked into where the money would come from.
</P>
<P>
   So Tiffany's mother, Danielle, is trying to round up support
from doctors and patients' advocates at the same time she is trying
to raise $9,800 for Tiffany's trip and treatments. An auction on
Tiffany's behalf is scheduled today.
</P>
<P>
   In researching the therapy, Danielle and her husband, David,
have stumbled over the thin line that separates protecting
patients' families from quackery and discouraging them from hope.
</P>
<P>
   Danielle is angry at the national United Cerebral Palsy
organization's reluctance to support research on hyperbaric
therapy. It calls itself the principal sponsor of nongovernmental
U.S. research and its position paper says there's no evidence
``that the procedure fails to work,'' she points out, so why isn't
UCP doing more to see if it does work?
</P>
<P>
   UCP's position paper has the tone of someone who has had too
many offers to buy the Brooklyn Bridge. ``Unconventional
interventions,'' it says, follow a pattern of enthusiasm giving way
to disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was kind of hesitant at first,'' says David, who is retiring
as an Air Force technical sergeant this month to be a full-time
assistant pastor of the nondenominational Agape Family Worship
Center in Fairborn. ``I thought, `This is just somebody else trying
to sell us another medical treatment.' But the more she researched
it, the more excited she was. She said, 'The doctors are telling me
it doesn't work, but the people are telling me it does.'''
</P>
<P>
   The therapy makes logical sense, at least. Cerebral palsy is a
catch-all term for neurological disabilities resulting from a lack
of oxygen to the brain, short-circuiting its motor signals to the
body's muscles. Hyperbaric therapy delivers 100 percent oxygen at
more than atmospheric pressure, enabling body fluids to absorb
oxygen in higher concentrations.
</P>
<P>
   ``This reactivates dormant (brain) cells that are getting enough
oxygen to exist but not enough to fire electrically,'' says Dr.
Richard Neubauer, a pioneer in hyperbaric CP therapy at the Ocean
Hyperbaric Center in Lauderdale-By-The-Sea, Fla. The high oxygen
doses ``jump-start the brain,'' as he puts it.
</P>
<P>
   Tiffany needs a tracheotomy to breathe safely and a feeding tube
to her stomach to be nourished without choking. Dr. Uday Chada of
the CKC Hyperbaric Centre of Toronto has indicated the treatments
would make both unnecessary, Danielle says, and could enable her to
crawl and restore vision to her left eye.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't expect her to become a miraculous 5-year-old
overnight, but if the extra oxygen jump-starts her brain, she'll be
able to start learning,'' says Danielle, who runs a day care center
and a beauty salon in her home.
</P>
<P>
   Tiffany's mental capabilities now range from 7 months to 2 years
and the tracheotomy keeps her silent. ``But she's boisterous, even
though she can't cry out loud,'' Danielle says. ``She loves
television, she loves music and she loves her brothers (Garrick,
10, and Christopher, 7).''
</P>
<P>
   Danielle learned about the treatment from an ad in a magazine
for parents of handicapped children. On the Internet, she
researched the topic and contacted families who had used it. ``Once
you see it work,'' one mother told her, ``you'll do everything you
can to get your daughter back.''
</P>
<P>
   She met Tina Frederick of Huber Heights, who has taken her son,
Gary, to Canada for 55 treatments. Before that, ``If someone threw
him a ball, he would just sit there and let it hit him,'' Frederick
says. ``Now he bats it away.'' There's been a dramatic decrease in
the number of his seizures.
</P>
<P>
   The limited but promising research has prompted the Canadian
government to commit $1.8 million to further studies. Besides
improvements in motor skills, Neubauer says brain scans typically
show increased blood flow to the damaged areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want every skeptical doctor to evaluate Tiffany before her
treatments, and then see the difference,'' Danielle says.
</P>
<P>
   She understands there are no guarantees. While Bishop says the
therapy should not be rejected out of hand, he adds, ``It's also
not something to sink your life savings into.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Foxxes and Frederick both say they have no choice but to
try everything they can. For Frederick's son, the treatments have
given some hope where there was none. ``Even if it makes his life
just a little bit easier,'' Frederick says, it's all worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
