<HEADER>
A5566 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a k BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-N     03-03 0718
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
  
 
 Here's a tip Hillary  
  &HT;     By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   As if she didn't have enough problems already, what with the
Puerto Rican thing and her husband being named the sleaziest
president in U.S. history, it now turns out that Hillary Clinton is
a lousy tipper.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the first lady was served a $6 lunch by waitress
Trish Trupo at the Village House restaurant in Albion, N.Y. After
finishing her lunch, which the restaurant's owner paid for, Mrs.
Clinton left without leaving a tip.
</P>
<P>
   Needless to say, when this oversight was discovered, Mrs.
Clinton was slammed mercilessly by the local media. The U.S. Senate
candidate wound up sending an apology and a $100 savings bond to
the waitress's son, all of which could have been avoided if she had
just plunked down the customary 15 percent, which in this case
would have amounted to a measly 90 cents.
</P>
<P>
   (Being the high-roller that I am, I would have rounded the tip
off and left the waitress a whole dollar. However, I also would
have pocketed a fistful of mints and at least half a dozen
toothpicks to compensate for my generosity.)
</P>
<P>
   I do not know if there were any extenuating circumstances that
might have given Mrs. Clinton reason to stiff her waitress. Perhaps
her cheeseburger was not cooked medium-well, as she had requested,
or maybe her iced tea came with sugar when she specifically
requested Sweet 'N Low.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe the waitress was one of those annoyingly chirpy types
who came up the table and said, ``Hi! My name is Trish! I'll be
your server today! And perhaps now would be a good time for me to
mention that I'm a good friend of Paula Jones!''
</P>
<P>
   Or, worse yet, maybe someone leaked out that it was Mrs.
Clinton's birthday and Trish and all of her fellow waiters and
waitresses descended, clapping and stomping, on the first lady's
table just as she was taking her first bite of undercooked
cheeseburger and launched into a loud and off-key version of
``Happy Birthday,'' spoiling not only Mrs. Clinton's appetite but
the appetite of everyone else in the restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   This last scenario is not likely given the fact that the lunch
was a planned campaign stop and was therefore attended by dozens of
handlers, media-types and various and sundry gawkers, crowding the
place to the point that a full-blown Happy Birthday! production
would have been impossible. (This is, as far as I'm aware, the
first and only redeeming quality of handlers, media-types and
gawkers. You may want to hire some the next time someone threatens
to take you out for a birthday dinner.)
</P>
<P>
   But the fact remains that things would have to get awfully ugly
_ I'm thinking in terms of a terrible accident involving the
``Happy Birthday'' singers that resulted in Mrs. Clinton's hair
catching on fire _ for someone to deny a waitress a paltry 90-cent
tip.
</P>
<P>
   My guess is that Mrs. Clinton did not fail to leave a tip
because she is cheap or malicious or was dissatisfied with the
service. Being a politician's wife all these years, she's probably
just unfamiliar with the practice.
</P>
<P>
   It just so happens that I am the husband of a restaurant critic
and one of my many jobs (stealing menus and remembering the doggie
bags) is figuring out the tip. This is not as easy as it sounds.
Fifteen percent is a difficult number to manipulate in one's mind,
particularly if you've had a glass of wine two. I tried using a
pocket calculator once, but it was one of those solar-powered jobs
and there wasn't enough light in the restaurant to make it work. I
wound up taking it into the restroom and holding it under the light
above the sink. It worked OK then, but I got a lot of funny looks
from the other guys in the restroom, including one who scolded me
for bringing a cell phone into a restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   So now I just take the coward's route and ask the waiter or
waitress to add 15 percent to the bill. They don't seem to mind
doing it and everyone walks away happy.
</P>
<P>
   It's kind of pathetic, I realize, but it beats getting your name
dragged through the mud by the press and having to send a $100
savings bond to your waitress's kid, who didn't so much as fill
your water glass.
</P>
<P>
   (David Grimes writes for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota, Fla.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
