<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-03 11:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5567 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a l BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-NYTR &LR;      03-03 0693
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
  
 
 &HT;     Ouch, where did that come from?   
 By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 The Press Democrat, Santa Rosa , Calif.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Someone was explaining about malaria and how even when you're
seemingly cured you can suffer sneak return attacks that wallop you
with a feverish replay.
</P>
<P>
   I think Arizona Sen. John McCain's use of the word gook to refer
to his Vietnamese tormenters was like being revisited by a nasty
affliction. Without warning, the old poison came spewing back and
turned on him.
</P>
<P>
   Racism runs deep. You can't just assume that it's been wiped out
in yourself or your community simply because it's known to be bad
for people. Since there's still no cure we need to report every
outbreak like a public health alert. It's the only way we stay
attentive.
</P>
<P>
   A very powerful man who aspires to greater power uses a term
that even backyard bullies know is taboo. When he doesn't apologize
some people are shocked. It's just as shocking when some act like
they could care less.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's remarks hark back to a time when just about every
ethnic group and religion came with a slur word for a nickname. I
learned a few from my father, who was from the ``some of my best
friends are ...'' club. That was the qualifier he used when telling
a joke or making some disparaging remark about Jews, Blacks,
Catholics, Italians or Japanese. Then he'd invoke the ``best
friend'' exemption, thus counting himself as tolerant but still
holding onto his prejudices.
</P>
<P>
   When my sister and I would call him on it he would rationalize
that this was how some people came to feel about certain groups of
other people during his time of history, that being World War II
and the Great Depression. He seemed to believe that if you were
going through a war or tough times someone just naturally ended up
being despised.
</P>
<P>
   John McCain learned to hate a certain group of people during the
Vietnam War just as some of them learned to hate the group that
included John McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Gook is a war word, according to my slang dictionary. Likely of
Filipino origin, it was adopted by U.S. armed forces during the
Filipino Insurrection of 1899 as a contemptuous term for Filipinos
and then spread by American troops to Japanese, Koreans and
Vietnamese.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of ugly words come from war, hate talk being almost as
effective as bullets in targeting an enemy. But the war is over and
the word has been out of favor for a long time now, so it was
unbelievable to hear it slip from the lips of someone like John
McCain. The words smarted, but what was worse was he stuck by them.
And then his defenders stuck by him.
</P>
<P>
   They said that it was just an example of his glib and colorful
speech, as if he were auditioning for a comedy club instead of
leader of the free and fair world.
</P>
<P>
   Someone even suggested that his irreverence might win him some
votes with young people who think it's funny to be anti-PC. If he
follows that line of campaign strategy, he won't want to miss the
party 'til you puke scene.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of media went looking for comments in the Asian-American
community and of course people thought it was shabby, but you
didn't have to be Asian to be offended. A remark directed at Wops
or Krauts would have been equally disturbing. Hate talk embarrasses
all of us.
</P>
<P>
   It's too bad he blew it. While he had our attention he could
have turned his words around and said what he said was stupid, the
word is stupid and so is racism. He could still have made the point
that his torturers were dirty rats and that he would never forgive
those particular sadists, but that he surely didn't want to smear
an entire country, a huge part of the world and all the fine
contributors to the great American melting pot.
</P>
<P>
   He could have said it takes as much strength of character to
admit a failing as it does to survive a war and now he had done
both. School children, the guys at the end of the bar watching
wrestling, Democrats, even _ we all would have cheered.
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Swartz is a columnist for The Press Democrat in Santa
Rosa, Calif. The Press Democrat is a member of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
