<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-03 12:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5600 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r t BC-SKI-UTAH-HNS &LR;      03-03 1214
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKI-UTAH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     MAKING TRACKS IN UTAH'S POWDERY PARADISE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ALAN WECHSLER  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARK CITY, Utah _ The first lesson about skiing in Utah is this:
Never get between a powderhound and his fresh-snow fix.
</P>
<P>
   ``Champagne powder'' is what the locals call the huge,
feather-light snowflakes that often fall in Utah's Wasatch mountain
range. Many say it's the greatest snow on Earth because the
softness and lightness make turning easier. At some resorts, 500
inches fall between November and May, a far greater amount than in
Colorado or California.
</P>
<P>
   For some Utah skiers, the 500 inches is still barely enough.
</P>
<P>
   Witness, for instance, a morning of powder at Park City Mountain
Resort.
</P>
<P>
   Two feet of snow had fallen overnight. All morning long, the
mountains echoed with muffled explosions as workers used mortars to
trigger avalanches and make the steep slopes safe for skiers.
Finally, at 10 a.m., the mountain opened the mile-wide,
1,000-foot-high Jupiter Bowl, a huge cirque of double-black-diamond
slopes.
</P>
<P>
   The ensuing rush to reach the lift was worse than a New York
City subway entrance during rush hour. At one point in the mad
dash, a skier turned to a friend and said, ``If you see anybody who
looks stupid, knock them down so we can get ahead of them.''
</P>
<P>
   I think he was kidding, but it was hard to tell.
</P>
<P>
   Powder does strange things to people, according to Julie Rawl, a
friend of mine in Park City.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ordinarily, nice skiers turn into devils,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Take a few runs in Utah powder and you'll see why.
</P>
<P>
   For the skier or snowboarder who knows how to handle it, there
is no thrill greater than riding through powder. It is an ethereal,
dreamlike experience, a combination of floating and sinking,
jumping and turning that burns fire into your legs and joy into
your heart. On a good day you can't even see your skis, buried as
they are beneath the delicious white stuff. On a good day, you grin
without knowing it. It is so much fun that it's a wonder the
government hasn't made it illegal.
</P>
<P>
   It's also a wonder more people don't come here.
</P>
<P>
   Utah, which for years issued license plates saying ``Ski Utah,''
had about 3.1 million skier-visits last year (the total number of
the skiers on the mountain each day during the season), compared
with about 12 million in Colorado and 8 million in California.
Nevertheless, several Utah resorts are preparing for the 2002
Winter Olympics in Salt Lake City by expanding their terrain and
adding an unprecedented number of new lifts.
</P>
<P>
   Some locals fear the secret powder stashes of Utah may soon be
discovered by the world.
</P>
<P>
   Before that happened, I wanted to see what Utah powder skiing
was all about. So last week, my snowboarding friend Ethan Chase and
I went to the Wasatch Mountains to find some.
</P>
<P>
   It would not be as easy as the ski resorts would have you
believe.
</P>
<P>
   We flew into Salt Lake City, a medium-sized metropolis
surrounded by snow-clad, 10,000-foot peaks. From the airport, 10
world-class ski resorts are less than an hour away.
</P>
<P>
   Our first stop was Brighton, a family-oriented ski resort
located in Big Cottonwood Canyon, a half-hour east of the city.
There was little powder to be seen, but the tiny parking lot still
filled with cars soon after the resort opened. This 10,500-foot
mountain still sports a 1,700-foot vertical drop and a surprising
amount of challenging terrain.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, we headed to Park City, a half-hour away from Salt
Lake City. This former mining town is the closest Utah comes to
glitz, with a main street lined with stores selling southwestern
crafts and framed, 30- by 40-inch wildlife photographs that go for
$995.
</P>
<P>
   I expected to be turned off by Park City Resort, especially as
we made our way through the multitiered resort base filled with
restaurants and ski shops.
</P>
<P>
   But as soon as we took the six-passenger lift from the base, we
discovered a huge mountain with plenty of solitude. The mountain
was built by the United Park City Mining Company in 1960, a few
years after their silver mines closed, and the resort is filled
with mine tailings and rusty metal buildings that add a sense of
history to the skiing.
</P>
<P>
   Two decades ago, skiers were even lifted to the top of one slope
on an old mine rail car and a 1,600-foot elevator ride.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, our rest day, a huge storm was approaching. The
next day, the snow was deep and light. Two days later, we went to
the huge Snowbird Resort in Little Cottonwood Canyon. After traffic
slowed the six-mile approach to 45 minutes, we reached the huge
concrete-and-glass resort base _ only to find that two-thirds of
the mountain _ including its famous 125-person summit tram _ was
closed because of avalanche danger. The powder was two feet deep,
but there was no way to get to it.
</P>
<P>
   Joining thousands of snarling skiers, we waited in half-hour
lines for three unsatisfying runs.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, we discovered a 100-foot-high slope that still
contained untracked powder. I skied, snow flying up my chest, and
stood at the bottom to take a picture of Ethan. As he came down,
another skier _ spying the tiny stretch of untracked snow toward
which Ethan was headed _ cut him off and blasted through.
</P>
<P>
   After this mess, we decided to head to some less-crowded areas
near Ogden, a half-hour north of Salt Lake City. In Ogden, the
mountains are lower, but the snow falls just as hard.
</P>
<P>
   Snowbasin, home to the future Olympic downhill and Super-G race,
is a large mountain with a tiny base area. Workers there recently
added two new gondolas, opening a terrific amount of formerly
backcountry terrain, and are working on a $70 million development
project that will create a new base lodge and a road that will cut
13 miles off the trip from Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   In the future, Snowbasin may become a destination resort on par
with Park City or Snowbird. For now, the undulating terrain hides
plenty of powder ``shots'' that kept us busy all morning.
</P>
<P>
   For our last day, we headed to Powder Mountain, perhaps Utah's
greatest skiing secret (and, at $33, one of the best deals around).
This family-owned mountain has only four chairlifts, but there are
other ways to get to the snow.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, you can hike across a ridge, pay $5 for a snowcat
ride _ you grab a rope trailing behind the tractor-like machine for
a ride to a hidden ridge _ or pay $120 for a helicopter ride to a
nearby peak. Even more backcountry terrain empties onto a road,
where a bus from the mountain brings you back to the base lodge.
</P>
<P>
   The terrain at Powder Mountain is so vast that the mountain
provides a crew of about 150 volunteer hosts whose job is to ski
with first-timers. Our guide, Clint, spent the entire day helping
us search for powder. The snow was somewhat heavy, but two days
after the storm there were still plenty of untracked shots left.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the day, I was at the top of yet another powder
stash that was free of tracks. The next day, we would be flying
back to New York, where the snow was melting and spring seemed on
its way.
</P>
<P>
   But that was the next day. Today, there was still one more run.
And we had a job to do.
</P>
<P>
   I started down the slope, grinning.
</P>
</TEXT>
