<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANCELING `THE DARVA &AMP; RICK SHOW'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Will Rick Rockwell and Darva Conger ever go away? Shouldn't the
clock have run out on their 15 minutes of fame about two weeks ago?
</P>
<P>
   I know what some of you are thinking: Who the heck are Rick
Rockwell and Darva Conger? OK, for those who've been traveling in
outer space _ or who tuned out pop culture and the tabloid media
way back in the O.J. era _ Rick and Darva are the instant
celebrities created by last month's TV game show, ``Who Wants to
Marry a Multi-Millionaire?''
</P>
<P>
   Rockwell was the multimillionaire who wanted to find out who
wanted to marry him. Conger was the aspiring bride who wanted to
marry him _ or thought she did, until she got a look at him.
</P>
<P>
   Darva hasn't come right out and said it, but you don't have to
do much reading between the lines to figure out that the previously
unseen groom's appearance onstage after he chose Conger as his
bride did not produce the magical attack of love at first sight
that the show's producers _ and Rockwell _ had hoped for.
</P>
<P>
   It was more like an attack of nausea. Revulsion at first sight.
Rick wanted to hear Darva say, ``I do'' but it seems that the only
words she could think of were, ``I think I'm gonna be sick.''
</P>
<P>
   Conger later told interviewers that Rockwell wasn't the sort of
person she could ever have a relationship with, which raises the
question: How would she know what kind of person he was when she'd
never even met him?
</P>
<P>
   What she meant, obviously, was that he didn't look like the kind
of person she could have a relationship with. He wasn't handsome
enough.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, Rockwell had some problems that were a lot
more damaging than his failure to be a good-looking son of a gun,
notably allegations of abuse by a former girlfriend who obtained a
restraining order against him.
</P>
<P>
   But Darva didn't know anything about Rick's background when she
instantaneously concluded that she wanted no part of him.
</P>
<P>
   So. At least we know that Conger isn't merely a gold digger. She
is apparently a shallow gold digger who is every bit as interested
in a prospective husband's looks as she is in his money.
</P>
<P>
   I'm proud to say that I didn't watch the program that produced
this lovely couple, but I've been watching the ensuing interviews.
Conger seems like an intelligent person at first glance, but she
must be dumber than a rock if she thought that a man who was
shopping for a bride on a TV game show would look like Brad Pitt or
Kevin Costner.
</P>
<P>
   Rockwell, meanwhile, might as well start wearing a sign around
his neck: ``I'm a moron.''
</P>
<P>
   The disappointed groom _ disappointed because, among other
reasons, he and Darva spent the honeymoon in separate rooms _ has
been telling interviewers that he figured no one would find out
about his problem with the ex-girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   He said he assumed that records of such run-ins with the legal
system ``were purged after seven years or something.''
</P>
<P>
   Conger no doubt wishes that some of her records were purged as
well, particularly those military records that refuted her claim of
being a Persian Gulf War veteran.
</P>
<P>
   Now. Back to the original question: Will these people ever go
away?
</P>
<P>
   The short answer: Not as long as the media remain preoccupied
with the story.
</P>
<P>
   The longer answer: Rick and Darva will eventually go away, but
their saga will soon be replaced by some other freak show that
fascinates the public and obsesses the media. Rockwell and Conger
are just the momentary beneficiaries _ victims? _ of a culture that
seems to glorify the dysfunctional.
</P>
<P>
   If Rockwell and Conger had hit it off, had come back from their
honeymoon pledging eternal devotion to one another, the media and
the public would have dumped them in a heartbeat.
</P>
<P>
   Who cares about happily-ever-after anymore? Here on the edge of
21st-century America, we want heartache. We want lies. We want
humiliation.
</P>
<P>
   Why do you suppose we elected Bill Clinton to two terms as
president?
</P>
<P>
   Rockwell and Conger will go away.
</P>
<P>
   And their successors are waiting in the wings.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can reach him at (817) 390-7787 or
billthompson(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
