<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LABBE-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE QUESTIONABLE HEROISM OF EXPATRIATE PRESTON KING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By J.R. LABBE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Preston King returned to the United States last week for the
first time in 39 years. His arrival, made possible by a pardon
issued by President Clinton, was trumpeted as some kind of a heroic
triumph over a racist wrong done lo, those many years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad the draft dodger didn't stick around long enough to
visit the Korean War memorial in Washington, or walk by The Wall,
where the names of more than 58,000 of this nation's true heroes
are inscribed _ none of them beginning with the word ``Mister.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps memories of American servicemen of all colors coming
home in body bags were fresh in King's mind back in the mid-'50s,
when he asked for and received two educational deferments from
military service so he could study abroad. He didn't have any
problems with the manner in which his local draft board referred to
the African-American when it was granting those requests.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1956, after King returned home to Albany, Ga., from his
studies, he received another notice from the draft board. This
correspondence addressed him as ``Preston,'' not as ``Mr. King.''
</P>
<P>
   This use of the man's given name reportedly held unpleasant
racial implications, particularly for a Southern black. Apparently
the all-white draft board wasn't aware of King's race when it
granted the first two deferments, but now that its members knew he
was black, it used his first name as a way of exhibiting disrespect
for him.
</P>
<P>
   King reacted by notifying the board that he would refuse to
respond to any further correspondence that addressed him as
``Preston.'' In 1958, the 22-year-old went back overseas to
continue his postgraduate studies at the London School of
Economics.
</P>
<P>
   The next trip home, in 1960, was consequence time. He was
arrested and tried before Judge William Bootle. The jury convicted
King of draft dodging, and Bootle sentenced him to 18 months in
jail.
</P>
<P>
   King never served a day _ in the military or in jail. Out on
bail while the case was being appealed, King abruptly fled to
England in 1961, where he lives comfortably to this day.
</P>
<P>
   While King worked to build a life and a career as a political
theorist in England, hundreds of thousands of American men answered
the call to duty when their local draft boards sent out those
``Dear Preston'' letters. They were called by a lot of names other
than the ones their mamas gave them as they grunted and strained
and sweated their way through basic training. On the good days,
they were called ``Soldier.''
</P>
<P>
   Tens of thousands of them died in the jungles of Vietnam while
King was ascending the ladder of success. Their arrivals back home
didn't draw crowds, didn't result in the hero's welcome that King
received last week, although they were so much more deserving of
the honors.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of things were unfair in the United States in the late
'50s and early '60s for people of color. The nation stood at the
cusp of the civil rights upheaval that, without question, needed to
occur.
</P>
<P>
   But contrary to the assertions of King's supporters through the
years, there was nothing unfair about the charge of draft dodging
leveled against him. He willfully refused to respond to his call to
duty. Call it civil disobedience if you like, or _ as King has
asserted _ staying true to his convictions. In this case, the
conviction had nothing to do with abhorrence of war or a religious
prohibition against violence. His conviction required being treated
with respect.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing wrong with that, as long as one accepts the consequences
of one's actions. The consequence of King's refusal to serve was
jail time. The consequence of fleeing justice was not being able to
come home without risking arrest.
</P>
<P>
   The consequence for 58,000 people whose convictions meant
serving their country when called was an early death in a distant
land.
</P>
<P>
   The irony of the situation is that if King hadn't come back in
'56, he probably would have qualified under President Carter's
blanket pardon of all draft dodgers in '76. He could have been home
24 years sooner.
</P>
<P>
   Some may view King as a hero for standing up for what he
believed. In my eyes, the true heroes can be found along a
much-too-long black granite wall in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   (Jill ``J.R.'' Labbe is senior editorial writer and columnist
for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. She can be reached at
jrlabbe(at)star-telegram.com or (817) 390-7599. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
