r l BC-CARS-WILLIAMS-COLUMN-     03-03 1084
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARS-WILLIAMS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLDSMOBILE'S ALERO A WORTHY COMPETITOR TO HONDA ACCORD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Introduced just last year as Oldsmobile's import-busting,
mass-market compact sedan, the Alero already has become the choice
for many consumers who otherwise would have bought a Honda Accord,
Nissan Altima, Mazda 626 or other import in this market segment.
</P>
<P>
   My weeklong test drive of the top-of-the-line Alero GLS
immediately followed a week in the Honda Accord, which gave me a
great perspective. The Accord, of course, has been the top choice
of many compact/midsize buyers for more than a decade, and it has
perennially vied with the Ford Taurus and Toyota Camry for the
honors of top-selling car in the U.S. market, having won that
battle on several occasions.
</P>
<P>
   Moving into the driver's seat of the Alero right from the Accord
made a believer out of me: General Motors really has built a car
that is every bit as good as _ and possibly even better than _ some
of its Japanese competitors.
</P>
<P>
   The Alero had a much more solid feel than the Accord, with
roadhandling that was surprisingly nimble and athletic. I almost
couldn't believe I was driving an American sedan, let alone an
Oldsmobile _ one of those GM brands that was known for decades for
its big, boatlike, wallowing sedans that appealed mostly to
consumers beyond retirement age.
</P>
<P>
   Oldsmobile began re-inventing itself in the mid-90s with the
introduction of the Aurora premium sedan, which I have said before
is one of the best premium sedans that GM or any other automaker
has ever produced.
</P>
<P>
   While the Alero isn't in the same class as the $30,000-plus
Aurora, it is well above the class of some of its competitors in
the compact/midsize segment, including the Nissan Altima,
Mitsubishi Galant, Mazda 626 and Chrysler Cirrus. Although
technically classified by the EPA as a compact because of its
overall interior volume, the Alero offers the roominess and
interior comfort of midsize models such as the Camry, Nissan Maxima
and Volkswagen Passat.
</P>
<P>
   The Alero, which replaced the ho-hum Achieva sedan and is on the
same basic vehicle chassis as the Chevrolet Malibu and Pontiac
Grand Am, comes well-equipped to compete with just about any car in
the compact segment, including the Infiniti G20 and Volvo S40. It's
certainly a cut above the Ford Contour and Mercury Mystique, the
closest competitors in the Ford/Lincoln-Mercury lineups.
</P>
<P>
   You can buy less-well-equipped Alero models that compete
head-to-head with the Contour, Mystique and Accord; the base engine
in the Alero GL and GX models is a 2.4-liter four-cylinder similar
to the base engines in the Contour, Accord and Altima. But the GLS
model ($22,095 including transportation) comes with a
170-horsepower, 3.4-liter V-6 engine and leather interior, moving
it up into the higher echelons to compete with the Maxima, Camry,
G20 and S40.
</P>
<P>
   Oldsmobile says that the Alero and other vehicles in its current
lineup, including the midsize Intrigue sedan, Silhouette minivan
and Bravada sport-utility, have helped lower the average age of
Olds buyers by six years. Alero buyers are primarily women,
although I know of no reason why this car should not appeal to men
as well; and up to 50 percent of Alero buyers have told their
dealers that they would have bought an import if the Alero had not
been available. That's an important statistic for GM, because such
``conquest'' sales over imports is GM's primary marketing goal for
the Alero.
</P>
<P>
   What this car signifies most, perhaps, is that family sedan
buyers don't have to compromise on anything to choose the Alero
over an import. This car is a smart buy for saavy consumers who had
believed imports represent the best long-range value.
</P>
<P>
   There wasn't much to dislike about the Alero. My only two gripes
had to do with the trunk. It's large enough to hold 14.7 cubic feet
of stuff, but the opening is somewhat limited, which restricts the
size of objects you can put back there. This is not unique to the
Alero. This is a problem found in many cars in this class. Also,
the trunk on our Alero had a weird catch that would not allow the
trunk to latch without first pushing a button on the side. Perhaps
this is some new kind of safety feature to prevent small children
from accidentally locking themselves in the trunk, but if so, there
is nothing in the Olds literature that mentions it. It was a bit of
a nuisance; if you try to shut the trunk without first pushing this
button, the lid just bounces back up.
</P>
<P>
   There is plenty of power with the V-6 engine, and the four-speed
automatic transmission shifts smoothly and seamlessly. For 2000,
Olds is offering a five-speed, Getrag manual transmission, but it
is available only with the four-cylinder engine. The GLS model
comes only with the V-6.
</P>
<P>
   Standard GLS equipment includes traction control, manual
air-conditioning, six-way power driver's seat, premium
AM/FM/cassette/compact disc stereo, leather interior, automatic
headlights, four-wheel antilock disc brakes, power
windows/mirrors/door locks, remote keyless entry, cruise control,
front bucket seats with console shifter, illuminated entry system,
and large (and readable) analog gauges.
</P>
<P>
   EPA fuel-economy ratings for the V-6 are 20 miles per gallon in
the city and 32 mpg on the highway. The tank holds 14.3 gallons of
gasoline, and unleaded regular is recommended.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   At A Glance:
</P>
<P>
   2000 Oldsmobile Alero GLS
</P>
<P>
   THE PACKAGE: Compact/midsize, front-wheel-drive, five-passenger,
V-6 powered, four-door sedan.
</P>
<P>
   HIGHLIGHTS: Excellent roadhandling, solid construction, roomy
interior, fun to drive.
</P>
<P>
   NEGATIVES: Weird trunk latch won't close without first pushing a
lever/button on the side of the latch; trunk opening is too small
for bulky objects that otherwise would fit.
</P>
<P>
   MAJOR COMPETITORS: Toyota Camry, Nissan Maxima, Mazda 626,
Mitsubishi Diamante, Honda Accord, Volkswagen Passat, Volvo S40,
Acura CL, Infiniti G20, Saturn LS2.
</P>
<P>
   EPA FUEL ECONOMY: 20 miles per gallon city/32 highway.
</P>
<P>
   BASE PRICE RANGE: $21,545 plus $550 transportation.
</P>
<P>
   PRICE AS TESTED: $22,095 (including transportation).
</P>
<P>
   ON THE ROAD RATING: A-plus.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (G. Chambers Williams III is automotive columnist for the Fort
Worth Star-Telegram. Telephone (817) 685-3810; e-mail
chambers(at)journalist.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
