<HEADER>
A5607 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-FILM-REVIEW-TUMBLEWEE     03-03 0709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-TUMBLEWEEDS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     WAYFARERS IN `TUMBLEWEEDS' CARRY PLENTY OF SOUL 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By AMY BIANCOLLI  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   At the start of ``Tumbleweeds,'' a mother and daughter hit the
highway in a dusty blue jalopy when mother's fourth husband, a
rangy sort of lout, looks like he's prepping to hit someone.
</P>
<P>
   Mom and kid pack up quickly and drive _ first toward Missouri,
then California, searching for a better dream. But ``Tumbleweeds''
is not a road movie. Despite the car, the Thelma-and-Louise-ish
set-up and over-obvious imagery (thar goes a tumbleweed, rollin' in
the wind), Mary Jo (Janet McTeer) and her pubescent daughter, Ava
(Kimberly Brown), are acting out a different Hollywood fantasy.
They don't find epiphany in the metronomic passage of cracked tar
and motels; they find it at the end of the road, in the warm stasis
of everyday life. It is, in fact, a staying-put movie.
</P>
<P>
   Co-written (with Angela Shelton, based on her memoir) and
directed on a very thin shoestring by Gavin O'Connor,
``Tumbleweeds'' is surprisingly sunny for a film about lost souls.
Perhaps that's because they aren't truly lost: Mary Jo, despite her
affinity for loathsome men, manages to skitter out from under them
before any real damage is done. ``I know what comes next,'' she
says, as her newest fella works himself into a violent rage. Mary
Jo isn't a battered woman, and her daughter isn't abused. The
film's too upbeat to rake that kind of muck.
</P>
<P>
   Once Mary Jo and Ava have landed _ in a seaside idyll called
Star Lake Beach _ they start bumping up against other characters.
Ava makes friends at school, tries out for a part in ``Romeo &AMP;
Juliet'' and embarks on her first date. Mary Jo gets a job and sets
about landing a man. Nothing unfolds with any originality or sudden
eurekas (in fact, the whole thing may remind you of ``Alice Doesn't
Live Here Anymore'' and last year's ``Anywhere But Here''), yet the
film's tender optimism slowly prevails. (Less charming is Dan
Stoloff's pitch-and-yaw cinematography, which uses hand-held
cameras for no apparent purpose except to promote disequilibrium.)
</P>
<P>
   McTeer, whose performance earned her an Oscar nod for best
actress, brings both maturity and a blithe gamine quality to her
young mother burned by life. From the start it's clear that Ava,
not Mary Jo, is the grown-up here; Ava yearns to be settled, to
make a home and community, while Mary Jo drags them from state to
state and man to man.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the beauty of ``Tumbleweeds,'' the reason we care at all, is
that Mary Jo is also allowed to be a sensible, loving mother.
There's wisdom in her, whether she's teaching her daughter how to
kiss (with shiny red apples: ``Oh, Adam!'' smack, smack, smack) or
protecting her from Mary Jo's latest lunk of a beau. (``The future
ex-husband,'' Eva calls him.)
</P>
<P>
   What fine moments there are. Ava, clucking loudly at her pet
mouse while mom flirts with a friendly trucker; Mary Jo, stroking
Ava's head after a car thief snatches all their worldly goods; Mary
Jo and Ava, dancing like pagans after Ava gets her period.
</P>
<P>
   McTeer owes much to her young co-star, and it's a shame that
Brown didn't earn an Oscar nomination as well. She deserved one,
not for acting up a storm but the opposite _ for pacing so
naturally along the tightrope between childishness and precocious
wisdom.
</P>
<P>
   The cast's other stand-outs are Jay O. Sanders, who exhales
kindness as a friendly co-worker, and the
always-elfishly-interesting Michael J. Pollard as a ``short,
patronizin', peekin' pervert'' who serves as Mary Jo's boss. The
director himself appears as Mary Jo's California boyfriend, Jack,
to which he brings a cool, heavy-lidded arrogance.
</P>
<P>
   If the plot peters out near the end, the film's air of
hopefulness lingers; it's hard to condemn a movie for narrative
drawbacks when its characters are so well-etched and so damnably
sympathetic. ``Tumbleweeds'' is a small, imperfect and derivative,
but it's got a big fat thumper of a heart.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Amy Biancolli is the film critic for the Albany Times Union,
P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. Her electronic mail address is
abiancolli(at)timesunion.com, or call 518-454-5738.)
</P>
</TEXT>
