<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-03 12:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5612 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-TRAFFIC-TICKET-HNS &LR;      03-03 0629
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAFFIC-TICKET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     AFTER DIALLO CASE, A FRIEND IN BLUE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JOAN STEINAU LESTER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERKELEY, Calif. _ I suddenly noticed the flashing lights
through my rear-view window as the police car came up behind me. I
pulled to the side of the road.
</P>
<P>
   Rolling down my window, I saw a baby-faced young man.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you know how fast you were going?'' he asked me sternly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forty,'' I replied as tears began to well.
</P>
<P>
   They'd been gathering since I'd dropped my son, his wife and
their baby daughter at the San Francisco airport a half hour ago.
Malcolm left my home at age 8 to live with his father. In the
decades since, whenever we part I feel a sudden tug of pain,
reminding me how hard it was to say goodbye each time we ended his
childhood visits.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a 25-mile zone,'' he said. ``License and registration
please.''
</P>
<P>
   My tears began to flow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just a minute,'' I said. And started to sob. He looked at me,
bewildered.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're still a good person. It's not as if you robbed a
bank.''
</P>
<P>
   I cried harder while he continued to reassure me.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, I was able to see through my tears and reach into the
glove compartment for the manila envelope that had held these
documents so many years, awaiting a moment like this.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's OK,'' the young man said kindly. ``You're still a good
person.''
</P>
<P>
   He took my papers and retreated to his car, while I sat and
sobbed. Soon I noticed him behind my car, writing the ticket. I
flashed on an image: What if it were Malcolm being stopped? Would
he be treated as sweetly as I _ a gray-haired white granny speeding
home to the Berkeley hills _ or would his visibly African-American
face bring another response, the kind received so often by my
dark-skinned friends?
</P>
<P>
   I've heard too many stories, firsthand, and worried for years
about Malcolm and the police. Light-skinned though he is, he could
easily be a target. My sobs increased.
</P>
<P>
   When the officer came to give me the ticket, I was still crying.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're a good person,'' he repeated with great concern. ``It
happens to all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   He held up his right hand in a swearing-the-truth gesture.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even me. I've gotten a speeding ticket. We all do. It's OK,''
he smiled at me.
</P>
<P>
   I tried to smile back, sobbing weakly. ``I guess it's good it
happened. I never knew this straight-away on Marin was a 25-mile
zone.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There are children here; we've had complaints,'' he said. ``We
try to keep a presence.''
</P>
<P>
   He explained what would happen: I'd get a ticket in the mail and
have to pay bail.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bail?'' I said, shocked that so many years after my life of
protest demonstrations that word could still apply to me. I might
not need to go to traffic school, he explained, since ``at your
age,'' he smiled indulgently, ``your insurance probably wouldn't
rise. Check with your insurance company.''
</P>
<P>
   Before we parted, as I sniffled a bit, he said once more,
``Remember, you're still a good person.''
</P>
<P>
   In farewell, I heard myself saying words that I never thought my
'60s-hardened heart could ever utter to a cop. Not after what I've
seen, and what I've heard. Melting under his kindness, I said,
``Thanks. I love the Berkeley police.''
</P>
<P>
   And I drove slowly away, praying that my son could say words to
the same effect next time he gets stopped by the police _ here, in
New York City, or anywhere else in these United States. After the
Diallo verdict, I'm increasing my prayers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Joan Steinau Lester is the author, most recently, of ``Taking
Charge: Every Woman's Action Guide,'' and is writing a biography of
Eleanor Holmes Norton, the District of Columbia's congressional
delegate.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
