<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-03 12:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5614 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-LEBANON-AMNESIAQ$ADV0     03-03 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEBANON-AMNESIAQ$ADV05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MILITIA MAN'S APOLOGY JOLTS LEBANON'S AMNESIA
 &HT;    With Photo.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., March 5 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIRUT, Lebanon _ It came in a newspaper advertisement, but it
jolted Lebanon like a flashback from a forgotten nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, a former member of a Christian militia took out ads
apologizing for war crimes during the 15-year civil war that ended
in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to apologize, apologize to all those whose executioner
I was or who were my victims,'' wrote Assaad(CQ) Shaftari. ``I
apologize for the ugliness of the war and what I did during the
civil war in the name of Lebanon, the 'cause' or 'Christianity.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``My hope,'' he wrote, ``is that my call be understood as the
only way out of the Lebanese ordeal. Souls will then be purified of
hatred and rancor, from the pain of the past.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaftari was an officer in the Lebanese Forces, the largest
Christian militia in the bloody sectarian fighting. He was high up,
though not in the top tier of Lebanon's war-makers.
</P>
<P>
   His ads were not the only reminder of a war many want to forget.
</P>
<P>
   In January, the Lebanese government formed a committee to
determine the fate of 17,000 people who ``disappeared'' during the
long-running conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Even as hundreds of Beirut buildings still stand as
artillery-riddled shells, many Lebanese have adopted what they call
an ``amnesia'' about the war.
</P>
<P>
   Lebanon still has no national war memorial for the tens of
thousands who died. Those involved gave themselves a blanket
amnesty for war crimes in 1992, and stayed in influential
government posts.
</P>
<P>
   Many Lebanese here call the war the ``War of the Others,''
implying that responsibility lies with the Israeli, American,
Syrian or other armies that trooped through between 1975 and 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Shaftari disagrees.
</P>
<P>
   Last week in the lobby of a posh Beirut hotel, Shaftari spoke
with three foreign journalists for the first time since the
apology. Dressed in a dark blue suit and tie, with a white sweater
vest, the balding 44-year-old looked like the electrical engineer
is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't say it was the 'War of the Others,''' he said. ``It
was our real war.''
</P>
<P>
   But, there has been little effort to assess blame for the
massacres and destruction that took place. There is no talk of a
truth commission, as was used in South Africa or Guatemala.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders of the war still wield power, sit in parliament or
occupy government ministries.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no power base from which to launch this cleansing,''
said Paul Salem, a political analyst and candidate for the Lebanese
parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the political reluctance to cast blame on the
powerful, many average Lebanese want to focus on rebuilding, rather
than the days of horrifying shellings and kidnappings. At the same
time, they remember who their enemies were and hold grudges.
</P>
<P>
   Salem and others believe it would be helpful to sort out the
ugly past.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, there is a need in terms of social society and
rebuilding trust,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Shaftari said he was not a fighter in the war. He was a
commander whose orders lead to deaths. He would not say how many.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot. You don't want to know,'' he said, raising his
eyebrows. ``There is no difference between one and 10,000.''
</P>
<P>
   At one time, Shaftari was deputy leader of his militia.
</P>
<P>
   History records both sides committing civilian massacres, but
some of the most notorious belong to the Christians.
</P>
<P>
   On ``Black Saturday'' in 1975, Christians seized from the
streets and executed about 350 Muslims.
</P>
<P>
   Shaftari's boss, Elie Hobeika, was blamed for leading the
killing of more than 700 Palestinians in the Sabra and Shatila
refugee camps in 1982. That killing became notorious because
Israeli troops watched from a rooftop and aided with illumination
flares.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last 12 years, Shaftari became involved with a European
peace group his wife, Marie, introduced to him.
</P>
<P>
   He said a tell-all book recently published by one of Hobeika's
bodyguards was too seedy and commercial a way to address the war.
He wanted to set an example for real reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
   ``He scored an immense blow in favor of memory,'' wrote
political commentator Michael Young in Beirut's Daily Star
newspaper. ``Lebanon has been built on a foundation of
state-sponsored amnesia. Yet, in a few hundred words, a former
militiaman exposed this as inane, disclosing how foul the wartime
legacy could be.''
</P>
<P>
   But, not all are as quick to praise Shaftari.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't believe him. He is a liar,'' said Subhiya Faris, 55,
whose husband and three sons have been missing since they were
taken from their car by Christian forces in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   Now, she joins about 35 other relatives of the missing who
demonstrate outside a government building once a week. They want to
know officially what happened to their loved ones, though most
figure they are likely dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``With our constant struggle we have been able to bring about an
official admission that there is an issue of the kidnapped,'' said
Wadad Helwani, leader of the families group.
</P>
<P>
   Her husband, Mustafa, was taken from her home in 1982 by men who
claimed to be with the Lebanese military. He was a teacher, active
with the Lebanese communists. He also organized neighborhood bomb
shelters and neighborhood support programs during the 1982 Israeli
invasion.
</P>
<P>
   She thinks her husband was probably killed, but she and the
other survivors want the government to find out for sure. Until
that happens, apologies from people like Shaftari will not matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not enough for him to apologize,'' she said. ``He has to
ask to be forgiven.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
