<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-03 12:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5620 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-RUSSIA-ADVISORS-$ADV0     03-03 1014
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-ADVISORS-$ADV05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    RUSSIA'S PRESIDENTIAL MEN HOLD KEY TO PUTIN'S POLICIES
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (k) Commentary categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., March 5 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By MARGARET COKER 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Imagine a presidential campaign without television ads
or tour buses, and a platform that arrives only after the election.
</P>
<P>
   Recipe for disaster? Maybe in America. But in Russia this
strategy has kept acting President Vladimir Putin the runaway
favorite in the upcoming March 26 elections, when the world's
second-largest nuclear power is scheduled to elect a new leader.
</P>
<P>
   Like Republican presidential candidate George W. Bush, Putin has
made no bones about drawing policy plans from a tight group of
advisers.
</P>
<P>
   Political observers here say these men _ who to a large extent
are Putin's former college friends or colleagues and currently hold
key posts in his government _ are particularly important to
divining what Putin, a 47-year-old former KGB officer and political
novice, stands for.
</P>
<P>
   It is also these men whom Putin will pick to run the next
government, making them key figures to watch to determine how
Russia will develop policies at home and abroad.
</P>
<P>
   ``Putin is often described as a good manager that knows how to
select people and muster political will to get things done,'' said
Yevgeny Volk, the head of the Heritage Foundation in Moscow.
``First, he needs to get elected. When that happens, he'll have a
proven group of men to run the government.''
</P>
<P>
   The team Putin has drawn around him have a common profile: Most
are men who have studied law, are in their late-30's or early 40's
and hail from the candidate's hometown, St. Petersburg. Among these
are Putin's Chief of Staff Dmitry Kosak, 41; Dmitry Medvedev, 34,
Putin's campaign chief; and the head of the Federal Security
Bureau, 48-year-old Nikolai Patrushev.
</P>
<P>
   However, the one man within Putin's circle who has an entirely
different background from the leader is the person tapped to become
Putin's prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   Mikhail Kasyanov, who has worked in the Ministry of Finance
since 1993, is a Moscow native with a post-graduate degree in
economics. A stocky, blond-haired man who speaks fluent English, he
currently is Russia's first deputy prime minister, and in that
position takes over the reins of government when Putin is out of
town.
</P>
<P>
   Kremlin insiders say Kasyanov, 42, caught Putin's eye after
after the minister successfully negotiated a $10.6 billion debt
relief package for Russia in February. It was a deal extremely
important for the health of the country's struggling economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kasyanov meets all the requirements needed (in a prime
minister). He's experienced in domestic and international politics,
he's a consummate professional, he has no political ambitions and
he has a head on his shoulders,'' said Igor Bunin, the director of
the Center for Political Technologies, a Moscow think tank.
</P>
<P>
   Second in line after Kasyanov is Ilya Klebanov, 49, a close
friend Putin appointed deputy prime minister in charge of defense
last May. An experienced businessman who was chief executive at a
weapons-building company, Klebanov has been cited as one of
Russia's best mangers.
</P>
<P>
   In his current position, Klebanov travels abroad frequently to
negotiate military and trade deals with Russian allies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Russia's economic revival is one of Putin's buzzwords.
(Klebanov) knows what it takes to run a business, and Putin likes
his real world experience,'' a St. Petersburg-based friend of both
men said, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   In December, before becoming acting president, Putin established
an economic think tank charged with creating a 10-year economic
development plan for the country, a plan he made clear he would
adopt if he was elected.
</P>
<P>
   Although the organization has yet to publicize the strategy (and
says it won't until after the elections), the president of the
think tank, German Gref, 36, is expected to become Putin's
Economics Minister.
</P>
<P>
   Gref and Putin have worked together since 1993, when they both
were members of the St. Petersburg city government. Gref, a nappy
dresser who sports a trimmed goatee beard, relocated to Moscow in
1998 when he became the deputy chairman of the State Property
Committee, the government agency in charge of privatization.
</P>
<P>
   He describes his economic views as moderately liberal, favoring
lower taxes and reform in Russia's aging industrial sector. These
ideas, he said would be spelled out in the 10-year plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Government) should be strong so that it can rather quickly
and effectively spell out new rules of the game ... rules of ethics
and taxes ... and ensure all citizens and market participants
followed these rules,'' Gref said in a Feb. 23 speech.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, not all cabinet positions will go to Putin's
entourage. Current Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov is expected to stay
on in his position. The acting president is thought to favor a new
man to head the Defense Ministry, Valentin Bobryshev, the
55-year-old former commander of Russia's Southern Army Group.
</P>
<P>
   This mixture of experienced officials and new bureaucrats is one
strategy Putin's campaign staff is quick to tell reporters that
their candidate likes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's in favor of step-by-step reforms in the economy, while
revolutionizing the inner workings of the Russian government,''
said Mikhail Margelov, a Putin campaign consultant. ``We have a man
who wants to end corruption by making government more vertically
integrated and more user-friendly.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, while Putin's circle gets high marks from Western
business and political circles, the lack of detail they have given
Russian voters has made skeptics of some at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The team's) public pronouncements are pathetic in their lack
of detail. The words could mean one thing, or they could be a
liberal smoke screen,'' said Pavel Flegenhauer, a Moscow-based
political analyst.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
