<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-03 12:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5636 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-FILM-REVIEW-PLANET-HN     03-03 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-PLANET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     `PLANET': HARD-CORE DISAPPOINTMENT  
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By WESLEY MORRIS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In another universe _ though it is difficult to imagine which
one _ Garry Shandling might be sexy.
</P>
<P>
   Here on Earth, he's a mensch who presumably posted high SAT
scores. He has a face women are compelled to slap. His pursed lips
and constant squint double as a lewd come-on, the kind of
expression you'd dread looking up from a drink to see staring at
you from the other end of the bar.
</P>
<P>
   The eventually flat joke in ``What Planet Are You From?'' is not
simply that Shandling appeals to women sexually, but that, with his
metallic, vibrating penis, he's God's extraterrestrial gift to the
fairer sex. Harold, Shandling's hyperadvanced species of man from
outer space, marries Susan (Annette Bening), a lovelorn real estate
agent he spies at an Alcoholics Anonymous meeting. Their unending
honeymoon so wipes her out that she finally tells Harold, ``I had
so many orgasms some of them are stacked up waiting to land.''
</P>
<P>
   Only in an alien-sex farce could Shandling inspire a woman to
deliver a line like that. And Bening plays it for the
mock-breakthrough that it is. Though while it's not saying much,
``What Planet Are You From?'' is light years funnier than its
predecessors _ ``Earth Girls Are Easy,'' ``My Stepmother Is an
Alien'' or ``Starman.''
</P>
<P>
   But the film gives up on Shandling's slut from outer space,
stooping to domestic doldrums that soon drub a misogynistic, if
nebbish, sex machine into a loving husband whose name you'd have no
problem believing is Harold.
</P>
<P>
   The last shot of this movie _ which was directed by Mike
Nichols, written by Shandling and ``War of the Roses'' adapter
Michael Leeson (and revised by two other male writers) _ is a
dispiriting image of married nonbliss. Driving into the sunset
crammed into a new Volkswagen Beetle, Harold and Susan are
bickering like the Jetsons. Harold had bigger things in mind: He
was given a special penis and a mission by Grayden (Ben Kingsley),
his leader, to travel to Earth to impregnate a woman and bring the
kid back to breed more. When he arrives on Earth _ hurtling as a
ball of light into the restroom of an airplane in mid-flight _ he
uses his one-track mind to get close enough to a woman to ask her
if she'd like to have sex.
</P>
<P>
   Back on his home planet, where the men have evolved beyond the
need to procreate, Harold (whose real name is ``H1449-6'') had
reached a personal best of 10 seconds of conversation before asking
a stranger, ``Can I put my penis in you?''
</P>
<P>
   In Phoenix, where the film is set, he does somewhat better,
scoring with a stewardess and topless dancer (not at the same time;
this movie is many things, kinky is not one of them). He takes in
Corporate America and hangs out with the office Lothario, played by
Greg Kinnear as a frat-boyish game-show host with good lines. He
takes Harold to meet women at AA.
</P>
<P>
   That buzzing sound emanating from Harold's crotch is the
cleverest bit of mischief this movie ever gets up to. It's a
brilliant sound gag, but wears out its welcome as soon as you
realize it's all the film has to offer. Before the film bifurcates
into a distracting chase story that has John Goodman as an Federal
Aviation Administration agent trying to sleuth the in-air
disturbances, ``What Planet Are You From'' is relentless as it
wrist-slaps much-lampooned male behavior. It leans heavily on
Harold's vibrator, which goes off whenever he gets aroused, which
is pretty much all the time, and on Shandling's manic discomfort.
</P>
<P>
   Nichols has yet to meet a male in crisis he can't distrust. But
whatever cockeyed, fretful probing he was up to in cynical caveats
like ``The Graduate'' and ``Carnal Knowledge'' gave way to paranoia
and suspicion from a decidedly female perspective in ``Silkwood''
and ``Working Girl.''
</P>
<P>
   Lately, Nichols has fully divested himself of the darker
satirical edges in his chronicles of the difference between what a
girl wants and what a man wants to give her. Now his movies _
``Wolf'' and ``The Birdcage,'' for example _ come in adult pinks
and blues. When ``Planet'' tries to see things from Susan's
perspective, it feels obligatory. She's a doting pleaser, while her
girlfriends _ two of whom are played big and incisively by Camryn
Manheim and Nora Dunn _ are amusing harridans who may as well be
from Venus, or at least Oprah's studio audience.
</P>
<P>
   The opening minutes set on Harold's planet are hysterical
evocations of absurdist mockeries like Woody Allen's ``Sleeper.''
Shandling's minimalist slapstick is as funny as Allen's. But when
Nichols comes to Earth, the film's angle on men gets broad like Mel
Brooks revising Neil Labute's ``Your Friends and Neighbors.''
Putting a goatee on cuddly Kinnear, for example, doesn't make him a
jerk, per se. It just certifies the fact that as insipid sex
comedies go, this one's pretty limp.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Wesley Morris is a film critic for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic mail address
is morris(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
