<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-03 13:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5675 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-FILM-REVIEW-MONA-HNS &LR;      03-03 0523
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-MONA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     HUMOR SINKS TO A NEW LOW IN `DROWNING MONA' 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By WESLEY MORRIS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Drowning Mona'' is a filthy kick in the pants to the people of
Verplanck, N.Y. It's an intermittently funny assault on a place
that's never bothered anybody.
</P>
<P>
   Given the bad haircuts, bad manners and bad vaguely Eastern
accents, it beats taking another billy club to the South. But the
actors crowded around this black comedy are having a grand old time
playing stupid, playing cheap and, in Bette Midler's case, playing
dead.
</P>
<P>
   As the shrew of the movie's title, she drives her Yugo into a
lake during the early minutes and spends the rest of movie in
flashbacks from the perspective of the town's elated,
guilty-looking characters who try to explain her death to the
sheriff (Danny DeVito). Midler, meanwhile, appears to be having a
flashback of her own to her ``Ruthless People'' days. But her Mona
looks so much like a woman whose breath stinks of Newports and Bud,
you believe that when she's standing beneath the summer sun on her
front lawn you can smell her sweat. Then everything around her is
remarkably stinky, including the story by Peter Steinfeld.
</P>
<P>
   As irrelevantly mixed-and-matched as the circumstances
surrounding ``Drowning Mona'' are, there's also some fine
tangential dialogue. In accordance with a flick about trash, the
lines here are practically thrown away in the cadences of normal
conversation as though the actors say such reliably stupid things
every day. Casey Affleck and William Fitchner do this most
adroitly. Affleck plays Bobby, the nice kid who runs a landscaping
business with Mona's dolt son (Marcus Thomas) and is engaged to the
sheriff's little girl (Neve Campbell). Softand understated in a
blond wig, he looks like a prematurely aged Gerber baby with the
baked intonations of a surfer. Fitchner is Mona's husband, who's
been hen-pecked into an affair with an equally shrill waitress
(Jamie Lee Curtis). With his bug-eyes, he's hapless, but
insinuating enough to play the live-action version of ``Simpsons''
barkeep Moe.
</P>
<P>
   Director Nick Gomez applies the same grittiness to these corny
backwoods machinations that he's brought to ``New Jersey Drive''
and episodes of ``The Sopranos.'' He also shows flourishes for
satire _ tattered American flags, a strategically placed
home-version of ``Wheel of Fortune.'' But what is he supposed to do
with them? There's nothing else here to lampoon than more poor,
classless folks.
</P>
<P>
   Someone like Alexander Payne (``Citizen Ruth,'' ``Election'')
may have found something redemptive in ``Mona'' rather than
encourage the cast to play this dumb. And, like most American
actors, the ones here tear into white-trash comedies the way some
Brits do their Shakespeare _ like they're starving. In this case,
blame the hair. There are enough mullets to win this movie a
Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Wesley Morris is a film critic for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic mail address
is morris(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
