<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-03 13:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5678 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-MURRAY-COLUMN04-COX     03-03 0583
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MURRAY-COLUMN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: No allergic reaction to game
warden
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUFKIN, Texas _ A group of us _ a couple of women, a couple of
guys _ were sitting in the waiting room to see the allergy doctor.
</P>
<P>
   In East Texas, if you sit in the waiting room of the allergy
doctor long enough, you're likely to see most everybody you know.
</P>
<P>
   We've got trees, we've got mold, we've got pollen, we've got
grasses, and we've all got allergies.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody was saying much in the waiting room. I was reading a
book. Maybe one or two people were flipping the pages of a
magazine. Others were just sitting there, staring off in space,
wishing they were somewhere else.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in the opening of a door, everything changed.
</P>
<P>
   All of a sudden, it seemed, the women were looking prettier and
the guys were looking friendlier.
</P>
<P>
   The game warden had walked in.
</P>
<P>
   In East Texas, everybody knows the game warden. You either know
him and fear him, or you know him and like him.
</P>
<P>
   You could tell most of our crowd was a law-abiding bunch. You
could tell everybody there liked the game warden.
</P>
<P>
   We were all shaking hands, smiling and nodding. One of the guys
started in right away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you know? I had to call him the other night to arrest my
wife.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, go on, you old thing,'' one of the women said, laughing in
spite of herself.
</P>
<P>
   The game warden just smiled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, yeah,'' the first fellow insisted. ``She was beating me up
so bad I had to call the law on her and have her arrested.''
</P>
<P>
   At this point, the game warden piped in.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I had to bring back up.''
</P>
<P>
   Everybody laughed at that, and me, too.
</P>
<P>
   Game wardens have that effect on folks. For one thing, a game
warden is usually a nice looking fellow, at least he stays trim.
Being on the job amounts to tromping through the outdoors.
</P>
<P>
   Then, too, there's that big gun on his hip. Something about it
gives a man stature, as much with women as with other men. Maybe
it's the air of danger.
</P>
<P>
   You never know when he just may have to shoot it out with
outlaws.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, nowadays most anybody carries a concealed weapon in
Texas, all legal with the proper permit.
</P>
<P>
   Pretty ladies, who you'd never think of as pistol-packing mamas,
won't go anywhere without their chrome-plated, palm-size automatic
in their designer purses. They know how to shoot, too. Part of
getting the permit is going to school to learn gun safety and the
proper use of firearms.
</P>
<P>
   Drill a fellow right between the eyes at 25 paces, these women
can.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why in Texas we always say ``Yes ma'am'' and ``No
ma'am.''
</P>
<P>
   Men tend to keep their pistols in the glove box of their pickup
truck. I say ``glove box.'' A lot of people say ``pistol pocket.''
They're probably closer to the truth.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, I was glad to see the game warden. Never mind I didn't
have much to say.
</P>
<P>
   Someone took notice of even that.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're staying mighty quiet,'' a fellow said to me.
</P>
<P>
   Another spoke up before I could.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's always that way around a man with a gun.''
</P>
<P>
   Everybody laughed at that, and me, too. More and more, nowadays,
I made it a point to stay quiet.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
jmurray(at)Lcc.net; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin,
Texas, 75915.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
