<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000303.0094 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-03 13:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5679 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-JOHN-LENNON-FBI-FILE-     03-03 1281
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOHN-LENNON-FBI-FILE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LENNON'S MI5-FBI FILES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (To publish this ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased
_ the rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 310-798-0970; fax,
310-798-7338.) 
 &HT;    
 By JON WIENER  
 c.2000 The Nation  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; World rights; except NOT AVAILABLE in San Francisco &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   ............................................
</P>
<P>
   The Feb. 20 headline in the Sunday Times of London was
spectacular: ``Lennon funded terrorists and Trotskyists.''
</P>
<P>
   It was also erroneous.
</P>
<P>
   ABC News and other U.S. media presented their own garbled
versions of the story.
</P>
<P>
   But behind the errors lies a fascinating and significant story
about a renegade former intelligence officer for MI5, the
top-secret domestic security service in Britain.
</P>
<P>
   David Shayler, a former officer at the Libya desk of MI5, is one
of those rare establishment whistleblowers. Starting in 1997 he
went public _ in interviews with the British Broadcasting Corp. and
other media outlets _ with his outrage over the abuse of power he
saw while working for MI5.
</P>
<P>
   What he saw included an MI5 file on John Lennon, the former
Beatle, and he told the Sunday Timesand anybody else who'd
listenwhat was in it: reports describing Lennon's financial support
for left-wing groups in Britain in the late '60s, along with a copy
of the lyrics to Lennon's song ``Working Class Hero,'' written in
what appeared to be Lennon's own handwriting.
</P>
<P>
   Shayler made these revelations along with a much more serious
claim: that Britain's foreign intelligence service plotted to
assassinate Col. Muammar el-Qaddafi, the Libyan leader, in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Workers at the security services are prohibited from disclosing
information about their work; under Britain's Official Secrets Act
they can be prosecuted for doing so.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Shayler fled Britain, but soon was detained in a Paris
hotel room by French police at the request of British authorities.
The French government put him in prison while Britain tried to
extradite him. Eventually Shayler was freed, and he now lives in
Paris. But if he sets foot in Britain, he will be jailed as a
traitor.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly enough, after so much time has passed, the Sunday Times
seems not to have considered the possibility that the MI5 files on
Lennon it described perhaps contain erroneous information.
</P>
<P>
   According to Shayler, the files contained reports that Lennon
made large contributions in the late '60s to the Irish Republican
Army and the Workers' Revolutionary Party, whose best-known member
was Vanessa Redgrave _ among the ``terrorists and Trotskyists'' of
the headline.
</P>
<P>
   These reports are almost certainly false. Lennon never had
anything to do with the Workers' Revolutionary Party, widely
regarded as the looniest '60s left-wing group. In the late '60s
Lennon was friendly with the International Marxist Group, which
published the underground Red Mole, edited by Tariq Ali and Robin
Blackburn. But they had a completely different political
orientation from the Workers' Party.
</P>
<P>
   Even a former member of the Workers' executive committee, Roer
Smith, told the London Observer that the MI5 information was wrong:
``There was absolutely no link between Lennon and us.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether Lennon provided financial support to the IRA is a bit
more complicated.
</P>
<P>
   Lennon was an outspoken supporter in the late '60s and early
'70s of what he called ``Irish civil rights.'' He joined protest
marches in London organized by the highly visible ``Troops Out''
movement. Lennon appears in a well-known photograph marching in a
demonstration carrying a sign that said RED MOLE/ FOR the
IRA/AGAINST BRITISH IMPERIALISM.
</P>
<P>
   In 1972, after British troops shot and killed 13 people in
Northern Ireland on Bloody Sunday, Lennon wrote and recorded a
song, ``Luck of the Irish,'' and sang it at a demonstration in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   But Yoko Ono, Lennon's widow, recently denied that the
British-born musician ever contributed money to the IRA. Even if he
had, it would have been a lawful act. It wasn't until the 1974
Prevention of Terrorism Act was passed by the British government
that financial support for the IRA was criminalized.
</P>
<P>
   It's pertinent that in February, 1981, three months after Lennon
was gunned down outside his Dakota apartment in New York City, I
personally made a Freedom of Information request for Lennon's FBI
file. I wanted the dossier for research on a book I was writing
about Lennon, ``Come Together,'' which was later published by the
University of Illinois Press.
</P>
<P>
   In response, the FBI released only about two-thirds of the file
and many of the released documents were heavily censored _ with
large portions of text blotted out. As the plaintiff, represented
by the American Civil Liberties Union of Southern California, I
sued for release of the whole file.
</P>
<P>
   The agency, represented by the Justice Department, fought
against disclosure. In July '91 the Federal Appeals court in San
Francisco directed the FBI to be more specific why the release of
the missing documents would be harmful.
</P>
<P>
   Finally in 1997 the Clinton administration released all but 10
documents from the Lennon file. The FBI has told the courts that
those 10 contain national security information provided by a
``foreign government intelligence agency.'' The FBI refuses even to
release the name of that government.
</P>
<P>
   About three weeks ago (Feb. 18, 2000), at a hearing in U.S.
District Court in Los Angeles, Judge Brian Robbins ordered the FBI
to release two letters it received from the unnamed foreign
government _presumably Britain _requesting that the Lennon
information remain confidential. The FBI has 28 days to comply or
appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Caravallo, a U.S. Justice Department attorney, says an
appeal is likely in order to defend the principle that national
security documents from a foreign government should be kept secret.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Shayler recently provided a declaration for U.S. courts
describing the MI5 documents he has seen. Because of Shayler, we
already know the nature of the information being withheld. We know
that it consists of 30-year-old reports on the political activities
of a dead rock star. We also know that the information is
erroneous, at least in part.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of legitimate national security issues, these pages _
like the pages of the Lennon FBI file that have already been
released _ record an abuse of power by the government, engaged in
illegitimate surveillance of dissidents engaged in lawful political
activities.
</P>
<P>
   Why is Lennon in the headlines after all these years? He
personified the dreams of the '60s. ``Imagine no more countries,''
he sang. And yet the establishment press in Britain still seems
intent on discrediting him. Apparently the battles of the '60s are
not yet over.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c.2000 The Nation
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Jon Wiener is a history professor at the University of
Southern California at Irvine. He is the author of ``Gimme Some
Truth: The John Lennon FBI Files'' (University of California Press,
2000), ``Fighting Words: Essays on Intellectuals, Politics and
Pop'' (1991) and ``Come Together: John Lennon in His Time'' (1984).
This commentary was first published in The Nation.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ----------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
