<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-03 13:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5686 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r l BC-BOOK-TODDLER-LADN-COR     03-03 0478
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-TODDLER-LADN-CORRECTION </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TODDLER TIPS COME IN SHADES OF PINK AND BLUE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: DELETES extraneous material before lede) 
 
 
By NANCY HEWITT 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Being the parent of a toddler is one of the most demanding yet
rewarding jobs you will ever have.
</P>
<P>
   If you check most bookstores, you will find shelves of helpful
books that address different phases of toddlerhood. But until now
there wasn't one comprehensive manual that included the most common
situations parents must deal with.
</P>
<P>
   Authors Laurie Waldstein and Leslie Zinberg have put together a
colorful, informative book called ``The Pink and Blue Toddler and
Preschooler Pages.'' ``We wanted to write a book by parents for
parents,'' says Waldstein. ``When our children were toddlers, we
didn't have the information.''
</P>
<P>
   Over a period of two years, both women did their research,
including soliciting responses from those in fields such as
nutrition, psychology, education and dentistry. Waldstein's husband
is a pediatrician, so she was able to tune in to questions he was
being asked when she worked at his office. ``We took questions we
had as parents,'' Waldstein continues, ``and included them with
questions others had, then put it together as a book.''
</P>
<P>
   The book is not organized in order of importance nor is it
alphabetical. Sections range from caregivers and toilet training to
behavior and safety. Sprinkled through the book are helpful hints
such as: ``Take your child to the store and let him pick out his
new underwear,'' found in the toilet training chapter. Or ``If your
child is not ready to use her manners, do not make it a power
struggle,'' in the chapter on behavior.
</P>
<P>
   The book also presents both sides of an issue as well as the
hints and tips. ``It's a book for busy parents of today,'' Zinberg
emphasizes. ``It is not a cumbersome book. It's comfortable. We
want it to be like you're calling a friend, especially since many
of us are separated from family.''
</P>
<P>
   Waldstein agrees. ``We didn't want people to be intimidated.
Parents need it simple and want it now.''
</P>
<P>
   Both authors encourage parents using the book to use common
sense for most situations because ``you know your own child.'' But
Waldstein adds: ``We give the most comprehensive information
available. But you should always defer to your pediatrician for
other questions you need answered.''
</P>
<P>
   Waldstein and Zinberg will be making local appearances this
week: 11 a.m. Monday at Borders Books and Music, 125 W. Thousand
Oaks Blvd., Thousand Oaks. Information: (805) 497-8159; noon March
11, Borders Books and Music, 14651 Ventura Blvd., Sherman Oaks.
Information: (818) 728-6593.
</P>
<P>
   The book is also available online at barnes&AMP;noble.com,
amazon.com and pinkandbluebooks.com. Suggested retail price is
$14.95. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
