<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-03 13:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5702 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-SAM-HOUSTON-HNS &LR;      03-03 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAM-HOUSTON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SAM HOUSTON: THE REAL POLITICAL OUTSIDER 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By CYNTHIA BASS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DANVILLE, Calif. _ This is a year, the presidential candidates
would have us believe, for outsiders; whichever their party,
whatever their background, they distance themselves from ``politics
as usual.''
</P>
<P>
   Each goes on and on about how he isn't a Washington insider.
Each stresses his willingness to take unpopular stands. And they
push interesting aspects of their biographies to show they're not
cut from common political cloth.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, no one can gainsay John McCain's heroism. Or Bill
Bradley's career in the NBA. Or, for that matter, significant
success in politics by George W. Bush and Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Still, when viewed with a historian's perspective, Bush (a),
Gore (b), McCain (c) and Bradley (d) can hardly be viewed as
outsiders.
</P>
<P>
   No (a) two-term governor, (b) vice president, (c) current
three-term senator or (d) retired three-term senator, who attended
(a) Yale, (b) Harvard, (c) the U.S. Naval Academy or (d) Princeton,
and is the son of an (a) president, (b) senator, (c) admiral or (d)
bank president, can ever be very ``outside.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor have any of the candidates taken particularly unpopular or
courageous stands _ being a pro-choice Democrat or a tax-cutting,
Clinton-bashing Republican is hardly gutsy.
</P>
<P>
   By way of contrast, let's recall Sam Houston (1793-1863), a real
outsider with a truly unusual biography, a man who did take gutsy
(and ultimately costly) political risks.
</P>
<P>
   Alexis de Toqueville, the French author of ``Democracy in
America,'' called Houston ``one of the unpleasant consequences of
popular sovereignty.'' But he was a uniquely American character: a
soldier, frontiersman and hard _ very hard _ drinking (and possibly
opium-smoking) hell raiser.
</P>
<P>
   He was also a brilliant orator who wrote his own speeches. He
was the only man to be governor of two states. He was a man who set
up a republic, then slipped it back into his native land. He was a
visionary who saw just how great a future Texas (now the world's
11th largest economy, as Bush often reminds us) could enjoy with
American statehood.
</P>
<P>
   When Houston was just 14, he left his home to happily live with
a Cherokee tribe _ an unusual move, and undoubtedly at least
partially responsible for his support of Indian treaty rights
throughout his life.
</P>
<P>
   In an era when such support usually meant political suicide,
this was the first of several of Houston's highly unpopular and
extremely resented positions.
</P>
<P>
   Houston had two political lives. A soldier, teacher and lawyer,
he was elected to Congress in 1823; in 1827, at the ripe old age of
34, he became the golden-boy governor of Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   While governor, he married a lovely maiden 15 years his junior.
Three months later, for reasons still unclear, she left him. So
ferocious was the scandal, he quit the governorship. He went back
to live with the Cherokees for the next three years, most of which
he spent drunk.
</P>
<P>
   Like many outsiders, Houston eventually drifted to Texas to
start a new life in what was then a province of Mexico. Soon he
became involved in the rebellion of 1836 and because of his
military experience became commander-in-chief of the ``Texian''
forces.
</P>
<P>
   His ultimate victory made him a hero and the first president of
the Texas Republic. In 1845 he engineered its annexation to the
United States, became one of its first senators (for 14 years) and,
in 1859, was elected governor.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his life in Texas, Houston had the remarkable ability
to take unpopular positions and have time and history prove him
right.
</P>
<P>
   He argued strenuously against defending the Alamo, predicting
exactly the military disaster which eventually happened. After
winning the Battle of San Jacinto and forcing the surrender of
Mexico's forces, he ignored the popular wish to kill Mexican
General-President Santa Anna, arguing this might feel good in the
short term but really would only prolong hostilities.
</P>
<P>
   When Texas, against his advice, chose to join the Confederacy,
he foresaw ``civil Broil'' _ a sadly precise prediction. Although
governor of a state he had helped create when he said this, his
doleful vision so incensed his own war-hungry legislature, it
demanded _ and received _ his resignation.
</P>
<P>
   What does Houston's life say to us during this political season?
Just this: We have four strong presidential candidates, for which
we should all be thankful.
</P>
<P>
   Let's give them all the credit they deserve for their real
accomplishments. But let's not indulge them (or ourselves) by
heaping adjectives such as ``outsider'' or ``maverick'' or
``colorful'' or ``politically courageous'' on any of them. Because
as history _ and Sam Houston's life _ shows us, they're all good
examples of ``none of the above.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
