<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BUSH'S APOLOGY TO BLACKS _ LOST IN THE MAIL? 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ I saw that a plane carrying mail crashed a
couple of weeks ago in Southern California. Maybe George W. Bush's
apology to the NAACP was on it.
</P>
<P>
   After all, surely the Republican presidential hopeful wouldn't
apologize to Catholics for his ill-advised speech at Bob Jones
University and not do the same for African-Americans. He's a
``compassionate conservative'' and ``a uniter not a divider,''
right?
</P>
<P>
   As badly as Bob Jones University has slimed the Catholic Church
(Bob Jr., son of the school's founder, called the pope ``the
anti-Christ'' and the church ``a satanic cult''), the school has
done equally poorly by blacks.
</P>
<P>
   Just a generation ago Bob Jones University flat-out refused to
admit black students, a policy that cost the college its tax-exempt
status. Here, in the Third Millennium, the school still prohibits
interracial marriage and dating.
</P>
<P>
   (This bastion of enlightenment in Greenville, S.C., also
notified its alumni that any gays or lesbians among them would be
arrested everywhere on campus but the religious art museum. Why the
museum? Because it was established as a separate entity from the
university so that it COULD maintain a tax-exempt status.)
</P>
<P>
   As just about everyone knows by now, George W. knew all this
when he chose to salve his New Hampshire primary wounds by
addressing about 5,500 Bob Jonesians on Feb. 2. He answered the
initial flak by basically blowing it off.
</P>
<P>
   The United States is a free-speech country, he said, and just
because a person visits a university doesn't mean he subscribes to
all its beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   Then, of course, Bush lost the Michigan primary amid much Bob
Jones mud-slinging by his GOP rival, John McCain. So Bush decided
to make something ``crystal clear.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I reject bigotry, I reject prejudice, I repudiate
anti-Catholicism and racism,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It was a nice try. But it didn't stop McCain or the media.
</P>
<P>
   So more than three weeks after his address, Bush's campaign
generals apparently accepted the fact that the Bob Jones
controversy was not going away. Last weekend, Bush delivered a
full, bended-knee mea culpa to Cardinal John O'Connor, pastor of
one of the nation's largest Catholic flocks: New York's 2.4
million.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the personal tone of the apology, it was not for
O'Connor's eyes only: The Bush campaign released the letter, very
publicly, on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   In it Bush reminded O'Connor that one of the Bush Brothers is a
Catholic convert with a Catholic wife. He reminded O'Connor that
he, W., and the cardinal had already talked about Catholicism.
</P>
<P>
   He also said that he was in error by not ``disassociating myself
from anti-Catholic sentiments and racial prejudice.'' His inaction,
he said, was ``a missed opportunity causing needless offense, which
I deeply regret.''
</P>
<P>
   Who could ask for more?
</P>
<P>
   If you're Catholic, nobody.
</P>
<P>
   Unless you're Catholic and black. Which brings me back to the
Bush apology that has yet to make it to the NAACP.
</P>
<P>
   The last time I looked, it was legal in all 50 states for
interracial couples to date and marry. How can a prohibition by an
alleged institution of higher learning on either of those choices
not be seen as racist and bigoted?
</P>
<P>
   Why don't blacks rate the sort of big, public ``I'm sorry for
Bob Jones University'' that Catholics got? Is it something about
the NAACP?
</P>
<P>
   In January, during the nasty flap over the South Carolina
statehouse and its waving of the Confederate battle flag,
Republican state Sen. Arthur Ravenel referred to the National
Association for Colored People as the ``National Association of
Retarded People.'' (The NAACP is driving the attempt to rid the
statehouse of the flag.)
</P>
<P>
   Bush's initial assessment of that whopper: It was
``unfortunate.'' Asked several times if he thought Ravenel ought to
apologize, Bush finally allowed as how such statements were ``out
of line, and we should repudiate them.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked several more times if THAT meant Ravenel ought to
apologize to the NAACP, Bush said nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, maybe there was another mail plane crash somewhere
and ...
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. Her electronic mail address
is salter(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
