   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CHECHNYA (Moscow) _ Chechen rebels ambushed a Russian
convoy north of Grozny, killing at least 20 Russians and wounding
scores. The attack, in an area supposedly under tight Russian
control, came two days after Russian generals all but declared
victory. It was the most significant rebel attack in over a month
and indicates that Russia will continue to be confronted with a
dangerous guerrilla insurgency as it heads to March 26 presidential
election, and after it. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-VIGILANTE (Yekaterinburg, Russia) _ Here at the
crossroads of Asia and Europe, the supply lines of opium and heroin
out of Central and South Asia run into big population centers near
the frontier of the drug trade. A group of tough guys who have
organized themselves as a foundation called City Without Drugs, are
leading a brutal civic campaign to take the streets of
Yekaterinburg back from the drug dealers and the corrupt police who
are widely believed to be protecting them. By Patrick Tyler.
</P>
<P>
   PINOCHET (Santiago, Chile) _ Augusto Pincohet, released from
detention in Britain, arrives in Santiago. The former dictator is
greeted by his grandchildren and an army band playing his favorite
marches. By Clifford Krauss.
</P>
<P>
   MOZAMBIQUE-FLOOD (Dateline to kum) _ Flood and rescue
developments. By Rachel Swarns.
</P>
<P>
   BOSNIA-TRIBUNAL (Paris) _ The U.N. war crimes tribunal sentenced
a former Bosnian Croat general to 45 years in prison for
orchestrating ``ethnic cleansing'' of Muslims in Bosnia in 1993. He
is the most senior figure tried so far, and the sentence is the
heaviest yet. By Marlise Simons.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BALLOON (Undated) _ Kevin Uliassi's bid to become the first
solo balloonist to circle the world ended in failure when his
balloon, the J. Renee, touched down in Myanmar Friday, his
headquarters said. By Henry Fountain. (400 words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   ECON-REPORT (Undated) _ The economy generated jobs in February
at the slowest pace in nine months, moderating wage growth and
possibly providing a measure of relief to investors worried about a
series of interest rate increases expected this year. The economy
added 43,000 jobs in February and the unemployment rate edged up
0.1 percent, to 4.1 percent. Average hourly earnings rose 0.3
percent after gaining 0.4 percent in January. By Louis Uchitelle.
</P>
<P>
   NBA-WORLD (Paris) _ After the 1992 Barcelona Olympics, when
millions of non-Americans were hypnotized by the artistry of Magic
Johnson, Michael Jordan and the rest of the Dream Team, the
National Basketball Association started pushing harder to make its
logo, and the superstars that populate its universe, household
images worldwide. By and large, it has succeeded. But if the NBA is
hurting a bit on the home court, many assumptions about global
growth have been cast into doubt, too. Sales of jerseys, balls and
backboards are flat, as is television audience growth, and
magazines about the NBA draw fewer readers than they used to. There
is no crisis, but as in the United States, the figures partly
reflect the impact of the owners' lockout that canceled 464 games
last season, as well as Jordan's departure. But they also
underscore the challenge of keeping fans who are an ocean apart
from spending their sports money elsewhere. By John Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   DEUTSCHE-TELEKOM (London) _ Looking at Deutsche Telekom's
ambitions. The company has been thwarted before in its efforts to
expand beyond its home market and is clearly eager to make a big
acquisition, most likely in the United States. Toward that end,
Deutsche Telekom has talked to 10 companies in the United States
and abroad, including Qwest Communications and Global Crossing. But
the company faces a number of obstacles to a deal in the United
States. By Andrew Ross Sorkin.
</P>
<P>
   COKE-IVESTER (Undated) _ Coca-Cola files its proxy statement,
indicating the package that the retiring CEO, M. Douglas Ivester,
received. Other developments. By Constance L. Hays.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-ATTACK (Washington) _ Folo on the teen-age hacker known
as Coolio, linked to a recent Internet attack. By Matt Richtel.
</P>
<P>
   BORDERS (Undated) _ Borders Group Inc. has hired Merrill Lynch
to help the bookseller explore strategic alternatives, including
recapitalization, a leveraged buyout or business combination with
another company.
</P>
<P>
   THAI-PETROCHEMICAL (Singapore) _ The bankruptcy of Thai
Petrochemical, Thailand's biggest corporate debtor, has generated
considerable uncertainty over the fate of billions of dollars in
unpaid loans and is unnerving investors. By Wayne Arnold.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Stocks were sharply higher in mid-afternoon.
At 2:00 p.m., the Dow Jones industrial average was up 245 points,
the S&AMP;P 500 up 26 points and the Nasdaq composite index up 135
points. Treasury prices were slightly higher. Crude oil was at
$30.96 a barrel. European stock markets were higher: London up 0.69
percent and Frankfurt 0.20 percent. The Nikkei closed down 0.69
percent, while the Hang Seng ended up 2.06 percent.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  (``k'' code)
</P>
