<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-03 14:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5729 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-FENGSHUICARDS-TEX     03-03 0702
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FENGSHUICARDS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WOMAN, HER HOUSE AND A DECK OF FENG-SHUI CARDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GABRIELLE CRIST 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I'm just as interested in peace and harmony as the next person,
so when my sister sent me the Feng Shui Card System, I was eager to
get my home vibes in order.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easy. If you can play Go Fish, you can do the Feng Shui
Card System in your home or office,'' the box for the oversize deck
of cards says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can play Go Fish,'' I said, encouraging myself.
</P>
<P>
   If my home were properly feng-shuied, the cards say, I could
have a better marriage, improved health, increased creativity and
more money.
</P>
<P>
   Who couldn't use a little more money?
</P>
<P>
   As I flipped through the cards, I was happy to discover that I'm
attracting good energy with the curved path to my front door. I was
equally pleased to learn that my wind chimes ward off negative
energy.
</P>
<P>
   The good energy was rushing toward my house, and I just had to
share the news.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, honey, the cards say that since our home faces north, our
careers will benefit,'' I happily announced to my husband, who has
about as much regard for feng-shui as he does for Lifetime:
Television for Women.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, goody,'' he said as he rolled his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, the good energy wasn't flowing to his spot in the
room.
</P>
<P>
   As it turns out, the good energy was having trouble making it
past the front door.
</P>
<P>
   At first glance, I seemed to be a natural feng-shuier. Then I
started analyzing the inside of the house.
</P>
<P>
   My main entry faces my stairs, and the stairs divide two living
areas. That's bad, the cards say, because it splits the energy and
as a result, one room is rarely used.
</P>
<P>
   As I flipped through the cards, things got worse.
</P>
<P>
   I discovered that whoever designed my house didn't consider feng
shui at all when drawing up the plans. Nothing is where it's
supposed to be according to the five elements of earth, water,
fire, metal and wood.
</P>
<P>
   Two of my three bathrooms are in the center of the house, which
is apparently the precise location that causes my financial
resources to be flushed away. That creates stress, the cards told
me, and that can lead to poor health and a possible financial
struggle.
</P>
<P>
   Very, very bad.
</P>
<P>
   But it's nothing a mirror can't solve. Just put one on the
bathroom doors, the cards say.
</P>
<P>
   The laundry room is in the wrong place, too.
</P>
<P>
   It's supposed to be on the north end of the house, where the
water element belongs, but it's in the middle of the house, toward
the east side, posing yet another threat to my financial resources.
</P>
<P>
   Yep, I need a mirror behind the washing machine. This time,
though, it has to be a bac-gua mirror, whatever that is. I put it
on my growing shopping list titled ``needed for better feng-shui.''
</P>
<P>
   Then it turns out that because my bed faces north, I'll have
more struggles of some unspecified variety.
</P>
<P>
   And the bed is aligned with the door, which the cards say ``is
like carting oneself off to death.'' But if I moved the bed over,
it would be too close to a window, which the cards say would make
my health suffer.
</P>
<P>
   I need another mirror, the cards say.
</P>
<P>
   For good feng-shui, I also need a bunch of plants placed in
strategic corners throughout the house. That's cool, except that
the plants have to be healthy.
</P>
<P>
   After going through the house, room by room, learning about my
bad energy with every step, I looked down at my long, long ``needed
for better feng-shui'' list.
</P>
<P>
   It appears, from a cursory review of my situation, that to fix
my feng-shui, I need: approximately 327 mirrors, at least one of
which is a bac-gua mirror; an aquarium that holds eight red fish
and one black fish; a kidney-shaped pond in my front yard; a
crystal in one of my downstairs windows; some bamboo tied with red
ribbon; and a pair of foo-dogs.
</P>
<P>
   And having a bathroom in the middle of the house flushes away my
resources?
</P>
<P>
   Not discouraged? Get your own Feng Shui Card System for the home
or office from pyramidcollection.com for $19.95. They are
manufactured by Mae Chin Williams Inc.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
