<DOCNO> NYT20000303.0104 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-03 14:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5737 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-TV-WALLS-FEATURE-LADN     03-03 1002
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WALLS-FEATURE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOSE BEHIND `WALLS' DO TALK
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: For use Sunday, March 5; tonight is SUNDAY in this story.
Fact box below) 
 
 
By VALERIE KUKLENSKI 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the walls of a certain frame bungalow could talk, they might
whisper, pant and giggle about passionate, sweaty, sometimes
playful sex between women. Or they might tell in straightforward
fashion of three generations of lesbians struggling to live
regular, loving lives outside the scope of what society says is
normal.
</P>
<P>
   ``If These Walls Could Talk 2,'' HBO's follow-up to its very
successful 1996 film on abortion, addresses lesbianism in three
distinct time periods and some of the problems homosexual women
have faced in those eras.
</P>
<P>
   What a lot of what people want to know, however _ as a reason to
tune in or a reason to tune out _ is whether there are graphic
loves scenes between women. The answer is yes, in the latter two
segments of the trilogy. But Sharon Stone, a self-proclaimed
``expert on salacious material,'' said there is so much more to
``Walls'' than naked women between the sheets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if (a sex scene) draws someone to the project, and
they're obviously going to have to watch more than that to get to
that, then we have accomplished something with that, that has
value,'' Stone said.
</P>
<P>
   Stone co-stars with Ellen DeGeneres in the lighthearted third
story, written and directed by Anne Heche. As the current owners of
that bungalow, Stone and DeGeneres play a couple dealing with a
typical ``2000'' dilemma: How to conceive a child outside the
conventional method.
</P>
<P>
   The trilogy begins with ``1961,'' about an elderly woman
(Vanessa Redgrave) living in that house, dealing with the death of
her partner of 50 years, and the grief she suppresses because their
relationship was secret.
</P>
<P>
   In ``1972,'' the bungalow is home to Linda (``Dawson's Creek''
star Michelle Williams) and three other feminist gay college
students. Linda's housemates, angry at men on the whole, turn
against her when she gets involved with a butch lesbian (Chloe
Sevigny of ``Boys Don't Cry'').
</P>
<P>
   The filmmakers and stars of ``If These Walls Could Talk 2,''
speaking to the Television Critics Association, struggled to find
the words to describe the importance of the project.
</P>
<P>
   Stone was asked what she learned by playing a lesbian role.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I learned that I'm exactly like a gay woman except I
don't have sex with women,'' she replied, drawing laughs and a
snappy retort from her comedian co-star.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I learned that I'm exactly like a straight woman, but I
don't have sex with a man. We're kind of the same,'' DeGeneres
said.
</P>
<P>
   Stone explained that she sees lesbians as people subjected to
the same type of discrimination racial and ethnic groups have
experienced.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just, you know, today's prejudice,'' she said. ``I didn't
feel that it was really any different than another prejudice that I
might find in the straight life. I really mean it when I say I'm
just like a gay woman except I don't have sex with women. ...
You're not different. The differences that happen to gay women are
as a result of people oppressing people and trying to make them
hide who they are.''
</P>
<P>
   Martha Coolidge, who directed ``1972,'' took a stab at it:
``Love is love, and couples falling in love is the same, and making
love is the same, but different for each one of us. But it's not
like it's different because of who we love.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I am so delighted that we get to do these pieces,'' added Jane
Anderson, the openly gay writer-director of ``1961,'' ``that some
kid out in the Midwest can watch these films and finally, finally
know that there's normalcy and dignity and acceptance at the end of
this long, dark tunnel that we've had as a minority.''
</P>
<P>
   All right, back to that sweaty, passionate, playful stuff.
Real-life partners Heche and DeGeneres argued about whether a sex
scene was important to the ``2000'' piece, but the writer-director
won the battle.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing DeGeneres well, Heche realized the best way to get her
to relax was with a few drinks. So, she says, she had a
well-stocked bar set up in her star's trailer and suggested
DeGeneres and Stone, who also was uneasy about the scene, knock
back a few before filming it.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, DeGeneres can kid about the ``secret handshake'' she
taught Stone. And she can quip about her short-lived disdain for
the Hollywood establishment after she came out of the closet in
that famous ``Yep, I'm gay'' Time magazine cover and her situation
comedy was canceled. (She said she and Heche changed their minds
about leaving Los Angeles for good after a bunch of reporters
showed up outside their house ``holding hands, singing
`Kumbaya.''')
</P>
<P>
   She is moving on professionally, looking forward to her first
stand-up comedy show in eight years and a CBS pilot for next fall
in which she plays herself hosting a traditional sketch comedy show
in the Carol Burnett vein.
</P>
<P>
   But DeGeneres isn't likely to forget the sting of seeing her old
show's ratings drop, having ABC give up on the series, realizing
that good projects that suit her new public image are going to be
hard to find.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't ever want to visit that place again, because there was
depression, you know,'' she said. ``My show was canceled. I was
sad. I was going through a grieving period and there was a little
bit of bitterness and I made mistakes, publicly. ... There are
things that I acted out publicly that should've just been my
grieving period alone in my corner of my basement rocking naked.''
</P>
<P>
   Amid the laughter, she added, ``Oh my God, I'm revealing too
much!'' &QL; 
_____ &QL; 
The show: ``If These Walls Could Talk 2.'' &QL; 
What: Anthology film in the popular series exploring women's
issues, this one about the lesbian experience. &QL; 
Who: Ellen DeGeneres, Sharon Stone, Vanessa Redgrave, Michelle
Williams, Chloe Sevigny. &QL; 
Where: HBO. &QL; 
When: 9 tonight. Also March 8, 13, 16, 21 and 25. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
