<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-03 14:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5741 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-PANDAS-OAKLAND-HNS &LR;      03-03 0553
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PANDAS-OAKLAND-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     OAKLAND SEEKS A MORE CUDDLY IMAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MATTHEW YI and JIM HERRON ZAMORA  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ City officials trying to enhance Oakland's
image on a global scale say a pair of cuddly pandas from China
could certainly do the job.
</P>
<P>
   Councilman Henry Chang announced Thursday that the city is
zeroing in on a deal to bring two pandas to the Oakland Zoo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very excited about this,'' Chang said. ``If we can get
pandas to come to Oakland, Oakland will be on the map, world-known,
because this is an international thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The councilman got the idea eight years ago while visiting China
on a trade mission as an Oakland port commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're working in China, you have to nurture and you have
to cultivate a relationship first. You can't just go in and say,
``I want a panda,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In November, city officials signed a letter of intent to bring
two pandas, a male and a female, from the town of Pingwu in China's
Sichuan province.
</P>
<P>
   Although that step was important, the deal is far from being set
in stone because Oakland officials still face a slew of obstacles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very excited,'' Allison Lindquist, assistant zoo
director, said Thursday. ``But we're guardedly optimistic because
there are some big hurdles that remain.''
</P>
<P>
   Chang wants to set up a panda research institute at the Oakland
Zoo working with the School of Veterinary Medicine at the
University of California at Davis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our approach is that we are not just trying to get it here for
exhibit purposes,'' Chang said. ``What we have proposed is to bring
the panda here for research. We want to help the species.''
</P>
<P>
   Joel Parrott, executive director of the Oakland Zoo, said ample
space and mild weather are two key advantages offered by this
Northern California city of 370,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   The weather ``makes it very amenable to the outdoor,
naturalistic living that's so beneficial'' to the pandas, he said.
</P>
<P>
   However, money is the biggest problem. The city has not budgeted
a penny for importing the animals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would probably cost us $10 million to build a facility here
and another $1.5 a year to maintain it,'' Chang said. ``We would
have to raise all of that from private sources.''
</P>
<P>
   The councilman said he has lined up several corporate sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we have big corporations that underwrite this, it can be
very fast,'' said Chang, a native of China.
</P>
<P>
   Zoos in other cities are working on deals to import pandas. The
National Zoo in Washington, D.C., is seeking two after its pair
died recently. St. Louis and Memphis, Tenn., also are seeking
pandas.
</P>
<P>
   David Towne, president and founder of the North America Panda
Foundation, sounded a note of caution amid the euphoria. He said it
can take many years and millions of dollars more than anticipated
to bring a panda into this country.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a hellish expense and some zoos are not equipped to take
on the financial burden,'' Towne said from Seattle, where he is
director of the Woodland Park Zoo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not trying to dampen Oakland's party,'' Towne said.
``There are at least 12 other zoos that have similar agreements,
but it's a long haul from there until you get your panda.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
