<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-03 15:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5761 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-CEREBELLUM-HNS &LR;      03-03 0538
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CEREBELLUM-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     RESEARCHERS SAY CEREBELLUM MAY PLAY ACTIVE ROLE IN SENSATION 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By CINDY TUMIEL  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Scientists are rethinking long-held notions about the
cerebellum, a structure at the back of the brain whose function for
years was believed to be limited to coordinating body movement.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past decade, however, research has begun to show this
brain structure plays a vastly more sophisticated role in how the
body perceives sensations.
</P>
<P>
   The latest studies, by scientists at the University of Texas
Health Science Center in San Antonio and the University of
Melbourne in Australia, indicate the cerebellum plays a major role
in the sensation of thirst.
</P>
<P>
   Experiments using positron emission tomography, or PET scans,
showed the cerebellum crackles with activity both during the onset
of thirst and during the satisfaction of that thirst.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence M. Parsons, an assistant professor at the health
science center's Research Imaging Center and one of the lead
authors of a study on the cerebellum, said the new findings offer
additional evidence that the brain section helps direct and
interpret information from the senses.
</P>
<P>
   Drawing an analogy from the world of high tech, Parsons compared
the cerebellum to a computer server that passes information to
other computers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think the cerebellum is involved in that it helps organize
all these thoughts and related sensations that are streaming up
into the highest levels of the brain,'' Parsons said. ``It makes it
easier for the higher level of the brain to do its work.''
</P>
<P>
   The study published this month in the Proceedings of the
National Academy of Sciences backs up other research that has
pointed to cerebellum involvement in the perception of timing, the
ability to group words logically and mentally rotating objects.
</P>
<P>
   In the past two years, studies have suggested defects in the
cerebellum are involved in the learning disorder dyslexia. Other
research suggested the cerebellum tells the brain what to expect
from its own movement. Thus, volunteers who tickled themselves got
no thrill from the sensation.
</P>
<P>
   In Parsons' experiments, brain scans were conducted on 10
volunteers while researchers made people thirsty by injecting salty
fluids into the bloodstream. Volunteers also were scanned after
they drank water to satisfy their thirst.
</P>
<P>
   The scans showed the cerebellum was active during the onset and
satiation of thirst but turned off when thirst was at its peak.
</P>
<P>
   Parsons said that suggests that the cerebellum was active in
passing information to other regions of the brain but was not
responsible for the sensation of thirst itself.
</P>
<P>
   The next step, he said, is research involving other sensory
systems. Parsons said he and colleagues are now looking at patients
with damaged cerebellums to see how well they discriminate between
sounds.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists also want to study cerebellum functions in
alcoholics, since that brain structure is strongly affected by
alcohol abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, the work could provide doctors with a new way of
looking at patients who have body movement problems, Parsons said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
