<SLUG> BC-BOMB-SQUAD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JERUSALEM BOMB SQUAD BATTLES TERROR, TEDIUM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ It is one of the most dangerous jobs in the world.
</P>
<P>
   The Jerusalem Bomb Squad is said to be the busiest of its kind
in the world, rivaled only by Belfast's in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   A few hours with Bomb Squad Team No. 362 Thursday provided a
glimpse into a world that involves hours of tedium, punctuated by
flashes of intensity and brushes with absurdity.
</P>
<P>
   The day began at dawn in the Old City at the Ottoman-era police
station known as ``Kishle'' in the shadow of the Citadel, the Roman
fortress that protected this city for more than 2,000 years. In the
squad room, floor-to-ceiling shelves are crammed with the artifacts
of terror from past missions _ coffee containers, cans of beans,
egg crates, shoes, books _ all hollowed out and intricately rigged
with timing devices and explosives. On the wall are photographs
honoring two from the unit who were killed in the line of duty.
</P>
<P>
   The six teams of bomb technicians get a daily briefing here, and
this particular morning brought bad news.
</P>
<P>
   In Taybeh, an Israeli town bordering the West Bank, a cell
within the militant Islamic organization Hamas had just been
uncovered making a bomb that allegedly was to be detonated
somewhere in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Police and bomb squad units had foiled the plan. At least three
Palestinians were killed during a raid on the house, and the device
they had been building exploded during the shootout.
</P>
<P>
   ``This means we are on a very high alert right now,'' a 23-year
veteran and senior commander of the unit told the morning shift of
his 36-member squad.
</P>
<P>
   The partners of Team No. 362, Sergeants Maoz and Roy _ it is
strict departmental policy not to disclose the last names of squad
members for fear it could endanger their lives _ headed for the
white bomb squad van, a vehicle as familiar to Jerusalem's
residents as a mail truck or a yellow school bus.
</P>
<P>
   All over Jerusalem and other cities of Israel, bomb squads work
around the clock, rummaging through trash and opening parked cars
deemed suspicious in the daily search for bombs. The ritual of
blocking streets to investigate and often blow up suspicious
objects is as common as traffic jams.
</P>
<P>
   The van carries a British-made robot used to investigate
suspicious objects. There is a viewing screen for the robotic
camera and racks of intricate tools and gadgets of the trade. The
remotely operated robot can be used to ``disrupt'' a possible bomb
with a small, controlled explosion, or it can fire a shotgun-like
device to open locked bags and briefcases.
</P>
<P>
   As the van plied the busy streets, squad members eyed
suspiciously everyone wearing a bulky coat or carrying a heavy bag.
Every garbage bag, unattended briefcase, and cardboard box took on
an ominous quality.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the radio dispatcher broke in: ``Suspicious object on
a bus at the central bus station.''
</P>
<P>
   Sergeant Maoz flicked on the siren and began a dash through red
lights, heading the wrong way on one-way streets, and screeching to
a halt at the bus station.
</P>
<P>
   Police were clearing the area already, but Sergeant Maoz barked
into a loudspeaker for people to ``clear the area now.''
</P>
<P>
   Passengers waiting for buses moved along, obediently accepting
the scare as a fact of life in this volatile city. The van pulled
to within 40 yards of the bus where a ``suspicious object,'' a
canvas bag, had been left in storage.
</P>
<P>
   Roy helped Maoz dress in a full-body protective suit and a
helmet with a one-inch thick plexiglass visor. They uncoiled a
climbing rope to attach to the bag.
</P>
<P>
   Up to 60 times a day, the squad receives calls on ``suspicious
objects.'' Israelis are understandably jittery about bombings after
decades of attacks on buses, crowded streets, cafes, and markets. A
campaign by police encourages all citizens to keep their eyes open
for suspicious devices.
</P>
<P>
   Of the roughly 200 daily calls nationwide, only 1 percent turn
up actual explosives, but every one must be approached as if it
were a live bomb.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you have seen the effects of a bomb, once you have walked
through the carnage and the shattered glass and the screaming and
the chaos, you look at life differently,'' said Maoz. He was the
first one on the scene of the 1997 Ben Yehuda Street attack by
three suicide bombers who activated their devices in sequence in
the city's busiest shopping district.
</P>
<P>
   It is with these scenes in mind that Maoz approached the striped
canvas bag, delicately attaching clips to the handle. Slowly, he
backed away, then pulled the ropes to jiggle the bag, in case it
was booby-trapped.
</P>
<P>
   Confident that it wasn't, he slowly tugged it out of the storage
hold. Delicately, he used a pair of pliers to open the zipper.
</P>
<P>
   The tension broke with a smirk and a knowing look toward his
partner. Inside were red peppers, a head of lettuce, carrots, and a
few onions. He pulled the bag toward him, spilling everything to be
sure no bomb was hidden amid the produce.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must look absurd with all this gear and taking part a bag
of vegetables,'' Maoz said later. ``But this is the job. We have to
stay alert on every instance, on every day, on every minute.''
</P>
<P>
   Securing a city like Jerusalem, site of ancient hatreds and
modern enmities, is difficult. It only adds to the squad's tension
that these days most bombs are the work of suicide bombers intent
on destroying the Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope for peace,'' said Maoz at the end of a long day.
``It's strange, you know. We end up hoping that we can be out of a
job someday.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
