<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-PLANET-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEPTH IS ALIEN TO `WHAT PLANET ARE YOU FROM?' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
WHAT PLANET ARE YOU FROM? 
Directed by: Mike Nichols 
Screenplay by: Garry Shandling, Michael Leeson, Ed Solomon, Peter
Tolan 
Starring: Shandling, Annette Bening, Greg Kinnear, Ben Kingsley,
Linda Fiorentino, John Goodman 
Running time: 105 minutes 
Rated: R (sexuality and language) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``What Planet Are You From?'' takes the
men-are-from-Mars-women-are-from-Venus thing to new distances, if
not new heights, then walks away. In this new Mike Nichols comedy,
Garry Shandling's character is from another planet, three solar
systems away. Annette Bening's character isn't from Venus, she's
from Earth. But he's sent to Earth because his cloned species
consisting solely of males can't reproduce. His mission is to
impregnate a woman and bring the baby back to his home planet so
they can keep the species going. The film is almost as shaky as the
science, but Nichols knows how to get the most out of what amounts
to a one-joke comedy, and Bening works virtual miracles, keeping
the scenes with Shandling's admittedly emotionless alien afloat.
``What Planet Are You From?'' isn't the comedy it could and perhaps
should have been. Its ambitions are too timid. But, as Mercutio
said of that blade through his ribs, `` 'twill do, 'twill do.''
</P>
<P>
   The joke, of course, is that male dumbness is intergalactic. The
alien has barely landed and slipped into a false identity as a
banker before he's behaving like his colleague, a philandering
lightweight played by Greg Kinnear. What keeps Shandling alive in
the role is that of the two classic comedians' expressions _
absolute certainty and absolute befuddlement _ he is a prince of
the latter. Shandling's face always looks as if it's about to melt,
even when he and Bening's Susan marry, have the baby, and he turns
into a couch potato, who instead of fondling his wife, fondles a
remote control. And this after a torrid honeymoon in which the film
skips a chance for satire by taking only the most perfunctory
swipes at Las Vegas by linking it to newlywed sex via shots of an
erupting fountain and a faux Eiffel Tower.
</P>
<P>
   The daze in which Shandling's alien stumbles through the film
can be rationalized by the fact that he's supposedly untouched by
anything like human feeling, to the increasing distress of his
wife. Still, it's she who keeps us watching ``What Planet Are You
From?,'' not only because she's simpatico, but because the
precision and sheer juiciness of Bening's line readings are so
gratifyingly savory, even if they constantly remind us that nothing
else in the film comes remotely close to matching them. The
subsidiary characters, who could and should have provided
counterpoint, are insufficiently developed in the screenplay by
Shandling and three others, stranding Kinnear, John Goodman's
government snoop, and especially Linda Fiorentino, who's utterly
wasted in the role of Kinnear's neglected wife.
</P>
<P>
   I may perhaps have made ``What Planet Are you From?'' sound more
glum and less diverting than it actually is. It's not that there
aren't laughs to be had, but the humor too infrequently breaks out
into any really wild or unpredictable territory. It's too lazily
like TV sitcom, with excessive reliance on penis jokes, including a
little glitch involving the reproductive organ with which
Shandling's alien is fitted _ it emits a loud hum when he's
aroused. This means he's forever trying to pass the noise off as
something coming from some appliance or other. Nichols's direction
is clear and shipshape, but the problem is that the Mars-Venus
stuff is scanted once the alien male establishes his urgent need to
have sex and Bening's character voices her need for emotional
context. In view of her flawless performance in ``American
Beauty,'' Bening gets the biggest (perhaps inadvertent) laugh when
she tells the alien upon meeting him that she works as a real
estate agent. Would that this thinly veiled Viagra fantasy had a
fraction of that earlier film's bite.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-03-00 1523EST &QL; 
