<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-BEAUTIFUL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSNIAN EXPATRIOT'S `BEAUTIFUL' CLASH OF CULTURES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
BEAUTIFUL PEOPLE 
Written and directed by: Jasmin Dizdar 
Starring: Edin Dzandzanovic, Charlotte Coleman, Danny Nussbaum,
Gilbert Martin, Siobhan Redmond, Nicholas Farrell, Frauk Pruti,
Dado Jehan, Nicholas McGaughy, Linda Bassett, Charles Kay, Rosalind
Ayres, Roger Sloman, Heather Tobias 
Running time: 107 minutes 
Rated: R (drug use, language and some violent content) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Beautiful People'' is a comedy of cultural collisions in which
a gaggle of Londoners are jolted out of their usual patterns by
Bosnian refugees and become better for it. It's a spirited and
essentially optimistic film, but it's also simplistic, with most of
the characters seeming scarcely more than stereotypes on both sides
of the cultural divide.
</P>
<P>
   Bosnian-born, London-based expatriate filmmaker Jasmin Dizdar
asks audiences to take a few too many Olympics-sized leaps of
faith. We can believe in a romance developing between stranded
Bosnian basketballer Pero (Edin Dzandzanovic) and a free-thinking
medical intern named Portia (Charlotte Coleman) from a stuffy Tory
family. They're fresh and appealing. But the ongoing and
increasingly tedious byplay between two warring Bosnians from the
same village, constantly trying to kill each other from adjoining
beds in a hospital ward, quickly runs out of comic steam. Wouldn't
the busy, overworked staff simply separate them?
</P>
<P>
   There's also a lot of parental disapproval that plays as if it
were transferred intact from a British sitcom. When Portia brings
Pero home to meet her parents, they predictably look down their
noses at him, while he, of course, is miles more sensitive and
proves it by excusing himself from the table, going into the next
room, and playing Chopin on the piano. Lower-middle-class parental
hand-wringing is provided by the despairing dad and mum of a
teenage kid (Danny Nussbaum) who's actually more sensitive than the
pub-crawling, coke-sniffing soccer thug yobbo he works so hard at
being. While Coleman's nurse Portia fights to open up the English
home front, Nussbaum's Griffin becomes separated from his National
Front pals en route to a soccer match in Amsterdam and is airlifted
drunk on a UN plane to Bosnia, where, not surprisingly, exposure to
the suffering he sees makes a big difference in his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beautiful People,'' set in 1993 when the Bosnian conflict was
at its height, sets up a few situations with which it's impossible
not to empathize, most notably when an obstetrician whose marriage
is falling apart shelters one of his patients, a pregnant Bosnian
woman who was raped. Then there's Gilbert Martin's BBC
correspondent who loses a leg in Bosnia and does not experience an
easy return home. Among the film's many plot strands _ too many to
handle adequately _ these provide a welcome gravity as counterpoint
to what often is a welcome light-handedness and avoidance of
sermonizing on Dizdar's part. It would be heartening to believe
that Bosnia's refugees indeed met with such an across-the-board
outpouring of empathy, but more than this film's will to happy
resolutions is required to convince us that this was the case.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-03-00 1524EST &QL; 
