<HEADER>
A5792 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIE-CLOSER-BOS &LR;      03-03 0457
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-CLOSER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE CLOSER YOU GET' DOESN'T GO FAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
THE CLOSER YOU GET 
Directed by: Aileen Ritchie 
Screenplay by: William Ivory 
Starring: Niamh Cusack, Sean McGinley, Ian Hart, Ewan Stewart, Sean
McDonough, Cathleen Bradley, Pat Shortt, Deborah Barnett, Risteard
Cooper, Ruth McCabe 
Running time: 92 minutes 
Rated: PG-13 (brief language and some sexual material) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Closer You Get'' is an overextended little Irish comedy
that relies rather too heavily on local color and an assumption
that the retrograde sex lives of a bunch of bumpkins in a Donegal
backwater is of more than passing interest. It's hardly ``The Full
Monty,'' or the full anything, as we watch a bunch of Irish Peter
Pans with too much testosterone and free time place an ad in the
Miami Herald, hoping to attract the contemporary equivalent of
American mail-order brides. As their heads dance with visions of an
American babe invasion, they ignore even more than usual the local
women, which only increases the already long odds against the lads.
</P>
<P>
   The film essentially consists of them getting it wrong until the
end, when some of them finally get it right. Meanwhile, the film's
views of an unspoiled corner of Ireland and several engaging
performances can carry the slender and often excessively arch and
inescapably dated material so far after the town goes bonkers when
the parish film society _ the village's only source of movies _
projects Bo Derek's ``10'' by mistake, instead of ``The Ten
Commandments.'' In the aftermath of the uproar, the small-town guys
spend a lot of time stewing in the only pub, with most of the
simmering coming from Ian Hart's butcher, blind to the charms and
the spirit of his pretty young shop assistant, Cathleen Bradley's
Siobhan.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Ewan Stewart's ex-footballer, now running the pub,
has grown oblivious to his wife, played by Niamh Cusack in one of
the film's subtlest and most glowingly charming performances. Sean
McGinley's balding sheep farmer hasn't though. Given his penchant
for romantic bumbling, he's hardly the one to be dishing out advice
to his younger brother the butcher, although he's improbably
sympathetic all the same. So are Ruth McCabe's sternly moralistic
and censorial postmistress, who steams open any mail she feels may
be sex-connected, and Deborah Barnett's 11-year-old daughter of the
pub-owning couple, who calls her father an idiot for even thinking
of leaving. Although the film presumably is contemporary, its
attitudes and its characters' behavioral patterns are cluelessly
anachronistic. You won't find even the smallest hint of the new
go-go Ireland here.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-03-00 1526EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
