<HEADER>
A5794 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIE-BROWNE-BOS &LR;      03-03 0566
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-BROWNE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`AGNES BROWNE' TOO SWEET FOR ITS OWN GOOD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
AGNES BROWNE 
Directed by: Anjelica Huston 
Screenplay by: John Goldsmith, Brendan O'Carroll (based on
O'Carroll's novel, ``The Mammy'') 
Starring: Huston, Marion O'Dwyer, Niall O'Shea, Ciaran Owens,
Roxanna Williams, Carl Power, Mark Power, Gareth O'Connor, James
Lappin, Ray Winstone, Arno Chevrier, Tom Jones 
Running time: 93 minutes 
Rated: R (language) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Agnes Browne'' is ``Angela's Ashes'' Lite. Not that Anjelica
Huston's second directorial effort lacks authenticity, at least not
when it comes to local color. As the title character, a suddenly
widowed woman with seven children, Huston's Agnes soaks up the
Dublin locations like deep breaths of air in this story written by
an Irish journalist turned novelist, Brendan O'Carroll. Certainly
there's room for an upbeat take, if not a downright cheerful one,
on a struggling family. But, endearing as Huston's gallant widow
and mom in septuplicate may be, ``Agnes Browne'' is a bit too
candied for credibility. There's more liveliness and mischief
shining forth from the faces of the kids on the cover of the
paperback edition of ``The Chisellers,'' second in the trilogy of
which ``The Mammy,'' source of ``Agnes Browne,'' is the first.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, and there's always something coming at Agnes. Part of her
survival skills involve not fully knowing exactly how bad the
trouble is, like the way one of her kids falls into the clutches of
the neighborhood loan shark that Agnes herself has told off. Ray
Winstone's thuggish money lender thought he had Agnes under his
thumb when she needed money fast to pay for her husband's funeral.
But she paid him back quickly with her late husband's death benefit
before he could squeeze much exorbitant interest out of her. The
funeral, which does not exactly go off with clockwork precision,
provides one of the film's funniest scenes because it's one of the
few unsentimental ones.
</P>
<P>
   Although sentimentality intrudes on it in a big way, the most
rewarding relationship is between Agnes and her pal, who has the
stall alongside the one from which Agnes sells produce in an
open-air market. Marion O'Dwyer is an Irish stage actress who, so
far as I know, has not appeared in films. She'll appear in plenty
from now on. Any actress who can talk out loud to God at regular
intervals, as her character (also named Marion) is asked to do
here, and still compel us to care what happens to her, is a
presence to be reckoned with. Another engaging newcomer is Arno
Chevrier, as the neighborhood's beefy but gentle French baker,
who'd like to be Agnes' boyfriend.
</P>
<P>
   The film's slightly dated quality may be explained by the fact
that it takes place in 1967. The kids, all seven of them, are
filled with rambunctiousness and effortlessly convince us they
reciprocate the love their mother showers upon them. Singer Tom
Jones puts in a good-natured appearance toward the end, becoming a
sort of fairy godfather after he learns that Agnes has been
yearning to attend his concert. There's nothing really wrong with
``Agnes Browne,'' except a tendency to take a few easy, convenient
outs. It's content to deal in melodrama rather than drama or
penetrating characterization. It's as mild in its achievements as
it is in its ambitions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
