<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-NEXT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE NEXT BEST THING' IS NOT MADONNA'S BEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
THE NEXT BEST THING 
Directed by: John Schlesinger 
Screenplay by: Thomas Ropelewski 
Starring: Rupert Everett, Madonna, Malcolm Stumpf, Benjamin Bratt,
Michael Vartan, Josef Sommer, Lynn Redgrave 
Running time: 110 minutes 
Rated: PG-13 (mature thematic elements, sexual content, partial
nudity, language) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Madonna is a better actress than she's been credited with being,
but ``The Next Best Thing'' isn't one of the films that's going to
prove it. As a single woman who hooks up with the gay best friend
who becomes the father of her child after a martini-drenched night
of Fred &AMP; Ginger routines, she never seems comfortable in the skin
of her character Abbie. Then, a little more than halfway through,
Abbie becomes downright unappealing after she meets an almost
unbelievably nice guy and gets into a ``Kramer vs. Kramer''-style
custody fight with Rupert Everett's gay character, Robert, who has
turned out to be a devoted father and family man. The audience's
sympathy flies to him like iron filings to a magnet, especially
after he has been discarded.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from the problematic nature of a subtext suggesting that
heterosexual life brings out the worst in a single mom, the film
has more serious problems, starting with a script that invariably
chooses, with unerringly fatal consistency, the wrong fork in the
road. ``The Next Best Thing'' has a split personality. Never having
decided whether it wants to be comedy or a sentimental
hand-wringer, it tries to be both and winds up being neither.
Certainly Madonna has reason to seem uncomfortable. If her
instincts were telling her that something was missing during the
shoot, they were right, most notably in the scene where the
friendship between Abbie and Robert becomes something more. Instead
of seeming giddy, the cinematic equivalent of bubbles rising to the
top of a flute of champagne, it's flat.
</P>
<P>
   There are other manifestations of flatness. Superficially, the
role has been tailored to accommodate several aspects of Madonna's
offscreen lifestyle, such as Abbie being made a yoga instructor who
exercises a lot. But the actress who seemed so attuned to her own
body in ``Desperately Seeking Susan'' and ``A League of Their Own''
here seems stiff and stilted. Lines fall leadenly from her lips,
conspicuously so in her exchanges with Everett. Whenever Abbie and
Robert engage in a verbal volley, it's painfully obvious which of
them has been trained to speak lines and which of them has not.
</P>
<P>
   Madonna is famous for being disciplined. Her work ethic is one
of the things I like about her. Physically, she's in great shape.
Such great shape that I couldn't help feeling that she'd be better
advised to spend a little less time on the treadmill and a lot more
time in the company of a demanding vocal coach. But the blame for
the absence of chemistry in ``The Next Best Thing'' can hardly be
placed entirely on her doorstep. Madonna's activism on behalf of
gay causes is well-documented, and the film does make an effort to
promote open-mindedness on behalf of nontraditional family
configurations. There's smooth work here as well as tolerance,
especially from the ever-suave Everett as the put-upon partner;
from Benjamin Bratt's Prince Charming; from Lynn Redgrave and Josef
Sommer as his parents; and from Malcolm Stumpf as the 6-year-old
caught in the crossfire. But they can't keep ``The Next Best
Thing'' from deflating, then going sour.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
