<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-SKIP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OF A BOY, A DOG, AND WARTIME IN A SMALL TOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRUCE MCCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
MY DOG SKIP 
Directed by Jay Russell. 
Screenplay by: Gail Gilchriest 
Starring: Frankie Muniz, Diane Lane, Luke Wilson, Kevin Bacon.  
Running time: 95 minutes. 
Rating: Rated PG. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The constituency for My Dog Skip is families, dog-lovers, and
anyone who's a sucker for coming-of-age stories _ but it goes even
beyond them.
</P>
<P>
   In its own quiet, poignant, character-driven way, it's a movie
for almost anyone of any age who's hungry for 95 minutes with a
beguiling story. Youngsters can relate to its authentic depiction
of the agonies and thrills of growing up, or, more accurately, the
struggles and pitfalls of trying to grow up. Adults, particularly
parents, can look upon it from their own perspective, recalling the
agonies and thrills of watching children struggling to grow.
</P>
<P>
   The film is set in the 1940s in the deceptively bucolic, sleepy
community of Yazoo, Miss., the hometown of Willie Morris, a former
editor of Harper's, from whose memoir the film is adapted.
</P>
<P>
   My Dog Skip delineates the relationship between an 8- going on
9-year-old boy and his dog in a way that reflects on his sometimes
shaky and even traumatic relationship with his parents and his
peers. The film also subtly etches the unresolved contradictions
and hypocrisies inherent in a small southern town increasingly
compelled to engage World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Willie, played by Frankie Muniz, is an only child, a ``sissy''
who's bullied and ostracized by schoolmates until he takes matters
into his own hands, stands up for himself, and demonstrates his
fortitude. He's intimidated by his father Jack (Kevin Bacon), an
embittered veteran who lost a leg in the Spanish Civil War of the
1930s. He's watched over by his mother Ellen (Diane Lane), who
defies his father and sets the plot in motion by buying him a puppy
for a birthday present.
</P>
<P>
   Skip, a Jack Russell terrier primarily played by a three-year
old named Enzo, is just too cute for words. Occasionally, he
threatens to upset the equilibrium of the film when encouraged by
the script to show off his winsome tricks.
</P>
<P>
   And it's a simplification to say that Skip, with his eagerness
to please and be loved, emotionally rescues Willie and solves all
of his problems. Still, Skip and Willie's parents work mightily on
each other's behalf to keep Willie on track. Until, that is, in a
fit of tense pique, Willie cuffs Skip, inadvertently driving him
away.
</P>
<P>
   The war's impact on Yazoo and Willie is personified by Willie's
friendly all-American next-door neighbor Dink Jenkins (Luke
Wilson), a high school football hero going off to war. Dink's
departure seems ominous but he returns home, albeit a quite
different guy than the one who left.
</P>
<P>
   The film's vintage setting is as much a character as any other.
Some of the best moments evoke the best parts of easygoing small
town life in a bygone era. The relationship between Jack and Ellen
simmers with occasional tension but never erupts into anything
melodramatic.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
