<HEADER>
A5804 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-ROCK-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      03-03 1114
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROCK-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAITT USES INDUCTION INTO HALL TO PRAISE COLLEAGUES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bonnie Raitt has inducted four artists into the Rock and Roll
Hall of Fame _ Ma Rainey, John Lee Hooker, Ruth Brown, and Charles
Brown. On Monday in Manhattan, Raitt will finally be inducted. It's
hard to believe she has been eligible for five years and just
getting in now, but she's not complaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really surprised to get in, actually,'' she says. ``I
didn't get to be a big deal until just 10 years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Raitt had been a big deal in blues circles for years before that
_ dating to the early '70s, after she learned from blues masters
who passed through Cambridge during her Radcliffe days. But she
didn't become widely known until her ``Nick of Time'' single topped
the charts a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   Still, most people don't think of Raitt as a hit machine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad to be getting in because of who I am, and not because
of how many records I've sold,'' says Raitt, who will be inducted
with Eric Clapton, James Taylor, and others.
</P>
<P>
   A well-known activist as well as singer, Raitt couldn't let the
opportunity pass to suggest other artists who should be inducted.
One is Johnnie Johnson (Chuck Berry's pianist), the other Ritchie
Valens, the ``La Bamba'' singer who died in a plane crash with
Buddy Holly and the Big Bopper. There has been a major movement in
recent years to induct Valens, but so far, to no avail.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it's typical for Raitt to publicize deserving artists _
something she's also done as a longtime trustee of the Rhythm and
Blues Foundation, which gives annual pioneer awards. Says Raitt:
``I'm all for honoring people who have gone before. My fame is all
about shedding light on performers and issues that don't always get
attention.''
</P>
<P>
   For this reason, she's upset that the R&AMP;B Foundation's Pioneer
Awards ceremony, which usually takes place the day after the
Grammys, was postponed this winter because of lack of sponsorship.
She's hoping that sponsors will come forward so the awards can be
held this fall. As a trustee, she's also been a key figure in
lobbying record labels to pay royalties to many pioneers who never
got them in the early days.
</P>
<P>
   As for political activism, Raitt continues to perform many
benefits for causes ranging from Native American rights to
environmental issues. She's also endorses the Green Party, whose
presidential candidates are Ralph Nader and Winona LaDuke.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have no chance to win, but they give us the chance to get
issues discussed,'' says Raitt. ``And I'm pleased that there's a
lot of amazing action going on at the grass-roots level in this
country, versus the dog-and-pony show of the presidential
election.''
</P>
<P>
   Would Raitt ever think of running for a political office?
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' she says. ``I'm in a unique position in the culture to
raise money and I wouldn't want to lose that. It's better for me to
be outside the culture in some ways. Plus, without campaign reform,
the political scene is disheartening. Elections are just bought
these days.''
</P>
<P>
   Raitt has also been enjoying some personal time (she doesn't
plan to release an album this year). She's going through a divorce,
but not moaning about it. ``We just grew apart, and our schedules
made it difficult to see each other,'' she says of her marriage to
actor Michael O'Keefe.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is she remaining static in her music. She just spent three
weeks in Mali to meet Afro-pop musicians, as part of an excursion
organized by World Music Productions in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just a week ago, I was hiking up a mountain to a village in
Mali,'' she says. ``I have a great life and I know it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Toni Lynn set to fly: Susan Tedeschi is in the national
spotlight now, but her label-mate, Toni Lynn Washington, is primed
for national attention herself. Both artists are signed to
Tone-Cool Records, which just released Washington's striking new
CD, ``Good Things.'' It's a keen mix of contemporary blues and soul
_ and the best thing that Washington has done in a career
stretching back three decades to the days when she opened shows for
Jackie Wilson and Sam &AMP; Dave.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very happy with it,'' Washington says. ``It required a
lot of time, but was worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   The effort shows. Washington opens it with the richly soulful
(and aptly titled) ``Good Things Come to Those Who Wait,'' a love
song she cowrote with her bassist, Bruce Bears.
</P>
<P>
   Beautifully produced by local legend Bobby B. Keyes (who has
worked with Jerry Lee Lewis), the CD combines finger-popping
grooves with smoldering ballads that evoke the likes of Irma Thomas
and Etta James. There are songs by Percy Mayfield and Johnnie
Taylor, plus a pair from Washington's guitarist, Tim Gearan, who
formerly worked with Tedeschi and also plays with his own band at
Toad in Cambridge every Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Washington, who has often put her career on hold to raise her
two sons and two daughters, is such a modest person that, when
asked about her own style, she says, ``Style is something I didn't
know I had until I heard it on this CD.''
</P>
<P>
   Trust us, she's got it _ and her humility only makes you love
her more.
</P>
<P>
   Washington, who was born in North Carolina but raised in Boston,
sang with Boston Baked Blues in the '80s, before she and Bears
formed the Toni Lynn Washington Band 10 years ago. She has played
about every local club since then _ and often with Tedeschi in the
audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``She'd come to most of our gigs,'' Washington says. ``She was
such a vibrant young lady. When I'd see her in the audience, I'd
ask her to come up and sing. Sometimes she wouldn't want to, but
she'd always come up in the end because she's so courteous. And
now, I'm blown away that I know somebody who started out like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington is lining up more national gigs herself, and plans to
tour Europe. She is giving up her day job as a telephone
receptionist to tour. ``It's time,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Santana's ``Supernatural'' album, after winning a record
nine Grammy Awards last week, has set another record with the
all-time greatest post-Grammy sales ``spike'' (increase) in
history. This past week over 1.1 million copies were sold
worldwide, including 583,071 in the United States. That's 166
percent increase (nearly 365,000 units) over the previous week's
sales of 219,000 units.
</P>
<P>
   ``Supernatural,'' produced by Clive Davis and Carlos Santana,
has sold a total of more than 9 million copies in the United States
and 13 million worldwide. The album also is the top-selling album
of all time by an artist of Latin heritage.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-03-00 1534EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
