<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-03 15:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5807 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-RAPE-BOS &LR;      03-03 0649
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-RAPE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING DARWIN SPEAK OF MADNESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELLEN CLEGG  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
A Natural History of Rape 
Biological Bases of Sexual Coercion 
Randy Thornhill and Craig T. Palmer 
MIT Press, 251 pp., $28.95 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Science can seem like a reductive world, full of clean lines and
pinpoint inquiry. But, in reality, it can sometimes be as
politicized as any presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Such is the case with this treatise on the dark side of Darwin
by Randy Thornhill and Craig T. Palmer, ``The Natural History of
Rape.''
</P>
<P>
   Thornhill and Palmer hold that the ultimate causes of human rape
are to be found in the evolution of male and female sexuality. Men
often desire numerous sexual partners during a lifetime, they note,
while women are more choosy. True enough, by most accounts. But
neither gender fares well in this explanation:
</P>
<P>
   ``If human females had been selected to be willing to mate with
any male under any circumstances, rape would not occur. On the
other hand, if human males had been selected to be sexually
attracted to only certain females under certain limited
circumstances, rape would be far less frequent. Indeed, if human
males had been selected to desire sexual intercourse only with
females who showed unmistakable willingness to copulate with them,
rape would be an impossibility.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not their use of animal and insect studies that subtracts
from their science _ that kind of field work is a necessity in
anthropology or evolutionary biology. It's their portrait of man as
predator and woman as, well, Betty Rubble.
</P>
<P>
   If our encoded history affects the way we live our lives, so
does the fine moire of civility we've layered over it. Thornhill
and Palmer mention sociologist Emile Durkheim and his work on
religious life, but leave him hanging. And what about our impulse
to art and intellect, language and government _ all sometimes
successful at tamping down the primitive fires inside.
</P>
<P>
   Some of their research simply seems cruel, especially their
attempts to establish a scale of psychic pain for rape victims. ``A
rape victim's degree of psychological pain depends on her age (more
psychological pain if she is of reproductive age), on her mateship
status (more psychological pain if she is married), on the nature
of the sex act (more psychological pain if penile-vaginal
intercourse occurred). . . '' Does an 80-year-old widow really feel
less pain when she is raped because she is infertile?
</P>
<P>
   Thornhill and Palmer come to the thumping conclusion that rape
is about sex, not violence, and excoriate feminist scholars such as
Susan Brownmiller who hold the opposite view. But can't it be about
both? Violence and sex, power and sex, are entwined throughout
popular culture.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Thornhill and Palmer seem too intent on settling
scores. Midway through their book, they interject a chapter that is
bound to puzzle most lay readers, despite whatever urgency it holds
for the academy: ``Why Have Social Scientists Failed to
Darwinize?''
</P>
<P>
   They continue: ``Why have researchers attempting to discover the
evolutionary causes of rape been denied positions at universities?
Why have organizers of scholarly conferences attempted to keep
papers on evolutionary analysis of rape from being presented? Why
have editors of scholarly journals refused to publish papers
treating rape in a Darwinian perspective?''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, a reader hoping to understand humanity's primal
roots and the role of evolution is better served by earlier works,
such as the evocative book ``Demonic Males'' by Dale Peterson and
Harvard scholar Richard Wrangham.
</P>
<P>
   Darwin's march of the species certainly holds keys to
understanding _ of nature, of nurture, of personality, of human
development. Those questions deserve more dispassionate inquiry. In
the end, this is science befogged.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
