<DOCNO> NYT20000303.0131 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-03 15:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5808 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-STAGE-DEARTH-BOS &LR;      03-03 1530
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAGE-DEARTH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE PICK OF THE THEATER CROP IN THE BIG APPLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ED SIEGEL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Much consternation has been expressed this year about
the dearth of new plays on Broadway, and how anyone out for a
``substantive'' theatrical experience has to go off-Broadway. If
one takes four of the hottest tickets in New York and adds in the
about-to-conclude successful run of Arthur Miller's ``The Price,''
it's not clear such an analysis is justified.
</P>
<P>
   If you accept that a top ticket of $75 to $80 is not going to
get any lower _ and it isn't _ then it's reasonable to expect a
theatrical experience that pays some significant intellectual or
emotional return on that investment. The three Broadway shows I saw
last week _ ``The Price,'' ``James Joyce's The Dead,'' and ``Kiss
Me, Kate'' _ are theater-going experiences of such intensity that I
doubt many in the audience of any of them are begrudging their
money on the way out.
</P>
<P>
   The two hot off-Broadway plays _ ``Dinner With Friends'' and
``Fuddy Meers'' _ are well-written, well-produced, recommendable
pieces of theater. But along with ``Fully Committed,'' another hot
off-Broadway show, they don't seem like they belong on Broadway,
not because they take so many risks but because they take so few.
Next to the other three they seem like the theatrical equivalent of
situation comedies.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't to say that there aren't big, bombastic nothings on
Broadway or excellent theater that comes from off-Broadway like
``The Vagina Monologues.'' ``The Dead,'' in fact, began life
off-Broadway, but ``The Dead,'' ``The Price,'' ``Contact'' and
``Copenhagen'' show that there is something of a natural evolution
taking place. (``Contact,'' like ``The Dead,'' just moved from
off-Broadway to Broadway.)
</P>
<P>
   Because there is such a high cost for the failure of new plays
on Broadway it makes sense that producers look for plays to make
their mark somewhere else. The Williamstown Theatre Festival,
whence came ``The Price,'' has been such a conduit. ``One of the
things we have access to,'' said Michael Ritchie, who runs WTF,
``is housing. We can bring up to 500 people here to do shows that
other theaters can't do, like two Shakespeare plays last season
with large-scale casts.''
</P>
<P>
   In the case of ``The Price,'' which had critics swooning,
Ritchie said that the producer David Richenthal, who produced last
season's ``Death of a Salesman,'' came up to see it with Miller.
``Arthur said to David, `I really like this production' and we've
known David for years,' so that fell into place pretty easily with
Arthur and David behind it. That moved to Broadway almost lock,
stock and barrel.''
</P>
<P>
   The swooning, not so incidentally, was entirely justified. This
is a gut-wrenching, emotionally draining production of a play that
explores the dynamics of sacrifice and independence within the
family structure while shaking its fist at the system that forces
people into such unsatisfactory choices. People come to Miller
expecting earnestness and didacticism, but ``The Price'' is funny
and ambiguous. Partly because Harris Yulin gives such a phenomenal
performance as the financially succesful brother who turned his
back on his father, there's no clear-cut right and wrong in this
play. It closes Sunday and if you're going to be in New York this
weekend, this should be a top priority.
</P>
<P>
   Another way for quality plays to get to Broadway is to start at
a smaller theater and prove its worth, which is how ``James Joyce's
The Dead'' moved. One can imagine the skepticism of a producer
hearing about turning Joyce into a musical, but five minutes into
it you wonder why nobody ever thought of it before.
</P>
<P>
   The short story is full of music as it takes place at the Misses
Morkans' annual dance. Richard Nelson and Shaun Davey have done a
fine job embelleshing Joyce's music with a selection of
traditional, operatic, and new seletions of ballads and
toe-tappers. The musical is a bit warmer and cozier than both the
story and John Huston's movie, but it still captures the
magisterial nature of the mystery of ``The Dead.'' At the same time
it more than hints at Joyce's rebellion against the narrowness of
Ireland while acknowledging the comforts within such a world.
</P>
<P>
   Blair Brown, Sally Ann Howes, Marni Nixon, and Stephen Spinella
live up to their accolades but Chrisopher Walken as Gabriel has not
been universally admired for his edgier (isn't that a surprise?)
performance. I thought he made the show with his nervous, or nervy,
command of the stage and his ability to suggest some of the darker
and more complex forces at work in the story. He may not have the
vocal chords of the others, but his delivery of the final song
based on the last paragraph of the story is the most indelible part
of the show. Brown, incidentally, will soon be leaving this show
for Michael Frayn's ``Copenhagen,'' which follows ``The Price''
into the Royale Theatre. ``Copenhagen'' follows another path to
Broadway. It began at the Royal National Theatre in London,
transferred to the West End, and now leaps across the ocean.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing new about Cole Porter's ``Kiss Me, Kate'' or its
path to Broadway. Revivals are reviled by those clamoring for new
musicals but the public is entirely justified in preferring to fork
over 80 bucks for a show with this kind of energy over the
enervating tunelessness of ``Side Show'' and ``Parade'' (and
``Marie Christine'' if the reviews were accurate).
</P>
<P>
   One of the only musicals in the past 10 years that can keep
company with the oldies was ``Ragtime'' and ``Kiss Me, Kate''
reunites two of the stars of that show, Brian Stokes Mitchell and
Marin Mazzie. Mitchell is a rioutous Fred Graham, the producer
staging a musical version of ``The Taming of the Shrew'' with his
ex-wife. There's an infectious energy to his presence and Mazzie's
more operatic voice provides a suitable counterpoint although when
she lets her hair down in and when she lets her hair down in ``I
Hate Men,'' there's nothing not to love.
</P>
<P>
   A score with the likes of ``Another Op'nin' Another Show,'' ``So
In Love,'' ``Too Darn Hot,'' ``Where Is the Life That Late I
Led?'', ``Always True to You (In My Fashion,'' and ``Brush Up Your
Shakespeare'' has enough going on in and of itself. When you add
production values like Michael Berresse scaling the scaffolding in
pursuit of his Bianca you have a musical that gives revivals a good
name.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Off-Broadway
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For all the virtues of ``Dinner With Friends'' and ``Fuddy
Meers'' they simply don't provide that sense of being taken out of
oneself that the three Broadway plays and musicals do. ``Dinner
With Friends'' makes you think about relationships; ``The Price''
shakes you to the core. ``Fuddy Meers'' gets some laughs out of the
dysfunctional family; ``The Dead'' doesn't settle for anything half
as easy.
</P>
<P>
   That isn't to say that ``Dinner With Friends'' and ``Fuddy
Meers'' aren't worth the trip outside of Midtown (check). In
``Dinner With Friends'' Donald Margulies (``Collected Stories'')
pits one divorcing couple against a stable one to explore some of
the issues that Miller explores in ``The Price.'' Is it better to
leave an unhealthy family life behind and set out on one's own or
stay and do the best one can?
</P>
<P>
   Margulies engages the debate with a winning sense of humor and a
smart sense of story-telling. Each of the four characters feels
like a real, flawed human being with whom it's easy to identify and
Neil Patel's sets feel wonderfully lived in, particularly the
kitchens. Relationships come together, relationships fall apart,
but we all need to keep eating. If ``Thirtysomething'' had been
well-written it would have come out like this story of
fortysomethings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fuddy Meers'' has an engaging sense of humor of the more
absurdist variety. Every day Claire (J. Smith-Cameron) wakes up she
has almost completely forgotten what has gone before. And if you
had a family like hers perhaps you would too. One day someone
claiming to be her brother kidnaps her from someone claiming to be
her husband. Bro has a John Candy-ish accomplice who often speaks
through his hand puppet and Claire's mother has had a stroke that
makes her say things like ``fuddy meers'' instead of ``funny
mirrors.''
</P>
<P>
   Harold Pinter used similar memory problems in ``A Kind of
Alaska'' to explore the vagaries of identity. David Lindsay-Abaire
is content to tickle the funny bone, albeit with an off-center
feather. Marijuana jokes abound and ``Fuddy Meers'' has a kind of
potty sensibility about it, for better and worse.
</P>
<P>
   The ``for worse'' is that there seems like there's nothing at
stake in ``Fuddy Meers.'' These five plays may be a flawed snapshot
in time, but these days in New York it seems like you get what you
pay for.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Price'' closes Sunday at the Royale Theatre. Open-ended
runs continue for ``James Joyce's The Dead'' at the Belasco
Theatre, ``Kiss Me, Kate'' at the Martin Beck Theatre; ``Dinner
With Friends'' at the Variety Arts Theatre; and ``Fuddy Meers'' at
the Minetta Lane Theatre.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
