<HEADER>
A5809 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-JAMAICA-BOS &LR;      03-03 0647
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-JAMAICA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POPPIES, PASSION, AND POLITICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CAROL STOCKER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
MY GARDEN (BOOK) 
By Jamaica Kincaid 
Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux, 229 pp., $23 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Is Jamaica Kincaid really writing about gardening? If not, what
is she writing about?
</P>
<P>
   This book is a challenge to her fans, who may wonder why they're
wading through complaints about wisteria _ and also for gardeners
who share her preoccupation with this vine, but who may become
confused by her digressions into the evils of colonialism.
</P>
<P>
   Though this memoir uses gardening as a metaphor for conquest and
slavery, and as a general jumping-off point for random musings, it
is indeed about gardening. But it's about the feelings gardening
evokes, rather than how to do it.
</P>
<P>
   Gardening does tend to attract perfectionists, who are doomed to
be (mostly) dissatisfied with the results of their efforts even as
they create beauty for everyone around them. Like garden writers
Christopher Lloyd and the late Henry Mitchell, Kincaid assumes the
well-worn persona of the curmudgeonly gardener who experiences
continual irritation interrupted by moments of ecstasy.
</P>
<P>
   Kincaid's style requires patience. Her serpentine repetitions
approximate the trance-like altered state that gardeners fall into
when they've lost themselves to planning and planting their
paradises. But her voice becomes something abruptly new and
different when she frames her gardening passion with an angry Third
World political perspective. A native of the former British colony
of Antigua, which was built on slave labor, Kincaid describes
herself as ``of the conquered class and living in a conquered
place,'' and launches salvos against the unspoken assumptions and
conventions of the gardening-writing genre.
</P>
<P>
   The white and the wealthy could play at working the land for
beauty and looked down on the black and the poor who worked it for
food and supposedly lacked aesthetic sensibilities. If you are from
the ``conquered class'' who labored in the fields without choice,
Kincaid writes, to garden for the pure joy of it is a form of
liberation.
</P>
<P>
   Kincaid also shares an outsider's perspective on the four
seasons, and particularly winter. To grow up on a Caribbean island
and then become a gardener in frigid Vermont may seem a misguided
choice, but this is probably seminal to her passion. It is long
winters, not endless summers, that make people obsessive gardeners:
Out of the months of dark and cold is born the longing to grow
things. Kincaid evokes the deprivation of winter, and how gardeners
live in anticipation of an imagined future that is sweeter than the
reality could ever be. This book may be the best ever written about
the gardener in winter, for Kincaid is inspired by that season's
discontent and longing more than by summer's successes.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps inevitably, Kincaid is so front and center in this
memoir that she sometimes blocks our view of the people and
landscapes she visits. This is too bad, because she goes places
most gardeners only dream of, such as the Chelsea Flower Show in
England and a plant-hunting expedition in China in the company of
some world-class horticulturalists.
</P>
<P>
   But her book is also about a struggling beginner on a quest. She
is terrific when writing about the willful plans that sway like
opium poppies in the fever dream of the typical novice gardener.
It's all here: the continual bewilderment, the strong but baseless
opinions, the flipflops of taste, the enthusiasm that goes dancing
off in a dozen directions, unrestrained by knowledge of what is
possible.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Jamaica Kincaid has written a book about gardening!
When you are bitten by the gardening bug, when you have this
obsession through which you see the world, and when it's winter,
why would you write about anything else?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
