<DOCNO> NYT20000303.0134 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-03 15:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5811 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-ECOMMERCE-B2B-ART-BOS     03-03 1212
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECOMMERCE-B2B-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS-TO-BUSINESS WEB SITES FUEL HOT SEGMENT OF E-COMMERCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY ACKERMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Within the forest of tall construction cranes that
tower over Boston's Big Dig highway project, electronic-commerce
entrepreneur Dominic Johnson sees a bright future for himself.
</P>
<P>
   His vision is made up of the backhoes, cranes, and hoists that
now are at work here, but when no longer needed could be sold to
contractors on jobs in other cities _ through AssetLine.com, the
Web auction site that Johnson, 25, a former securities broker, is
launching from offices in Lowell, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   In suburban Burlington, meanwhile, Paul Baier, a veteran of
e-commerce, is overseeing development of another business vision _
an online bazaar of brooms, floor cleaners, fuses, fans, electric
motors, and tools.
</P>
<P>
   Baier's Web site, PurchasingCenter.com, is aimed at factory and
building managers, who regularly buy these goods to keep their
facilities running. The start-up got $26 million in venture capital
last month, and expects to launch its online catalog, with 250,000
product listings, on March 14.
</P>
<P>
   If 1999 was a milestone year for retail e-commerce, 2000 is the
year for business-to-business Web sites _ B2B for short.
</P>
<P>
   The hottest of these are the ``hub'' sites, or Web addresses
that bring together many suppliers in one place that offer a range
of products and services to targeted groups of customers.
</P>
<P>
   For all, the attraction is B2B's potential to cut costs by
reducing time spent by salesmen on the road and writing up paper
orders, and providing a way for buyers to instantly comparison-shop
among a world of suppliers. Sellers say lower overhead costs should
lead to lower prices, while buyers expect such a wealth of
information will give them better bargaining leverage.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most impressive illustration of business-to-business
e-commerce's promise is the announcement last week by Detroit's Big
Three automakers for an online purchasing exchange for the $200
million worth of parts and materials that the auto industry
collectively buys each year. Two global retail giants, Sears,
Roebuck &AMP; Co. and Paris-based Carrefour SA, followed this week with
a plan to match retailers and their suppliers online.
</P>
<P>
   Online ordering of parts and supplies is, in fact, an idea with
some history, pioneered by defense industries in the 1980s. James
A. Manzi, after leaving Lotus Development Corp. following that
company's takeover by IBM Corp. in 1995, tried popularizing the
concept with an early B2B site, Industry.Net. But the company went
bankrupt in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The introduction of software that automated online buying and
selling changed the picture. After Amazon.com and others put these
tools to work at the consumer level, other entrepreneurs quickly
figured that trading carload lots of industrial goods could roll up
profits faster than selling books one at a time.
</P>
<P>
   By the beginning of this year, more than 1,000
business-to-business hubs were online, according to Erica
Rugullies, an analyst with Giga Information Group in Norwood.
</P>
<P>
   Some B2B companies, such as Ariba.com, FreeMarkets.com, and
CommerceOne.com, are hits on Wall Street and focus on large
companies' needs for industrial parts and commodities.
</P>
<P>
   Others, such as SupplierMarket.com of Burlington and
PurchasingCenter.com, aim to fill a similar role for smaller
companies. Baier has drawn an even smaller target market for
PurchasingCenter.com _ plant maintenance engineers and shift
foremen _ people who, he says, ``stand on cement floors eight hours
a day and wear safety goggles, and need halogen lamps and floor
waxes to keep things running smoothly.''
</P>
<P>
   Alongside these are hundreds of even more tightly focused sites
serving single industries or single product categories. This list
includes PaperExchange.com of Boston, serving the paper industry;
GoFish.com of Portland, Maine, an online exchange for seafood;
Bulbs.com of Worcester for lighting supplies; and MRO.com of
Bedford for business software.
</P>
<P>
   By next January, Rugullies thinks 10,000 B2B hub sites could be
operating in the United States. ``Everyone and their brother is
building hub sites,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   And many are attracting big investors. PricewaterhouseCoopers
found 268 business-to-business start-ups nationwide shared $2.6
billion in investment from venture funds last year _ six times more
companies than in 1998, and 10 times the money.
</P>
<P>
   Forrester Research Inc. of Cambridge forecasts
business-to-business online deals in the United States alone will
reach $2.7 trillion a year in 2004, about 15 percent of all online
sales.
</P>
<P>
   David Delande, an electrical supplies distributor in Peabody,
who has signed to sell products through PurchasingCenter.com,
explains: ``The conventional route would be to write a requisition,
send it to purchasing, which would send it to my salespeople, who
would do more paperwork, and we would do the billing.'' Delande
says eliminating such steps will let him discount the prices he
posts online.
</P>
<P>
   Changing buying habits could take time. ``A lot of purchasing
directors fear their jobs are on the line,'' says Christiane Loup
of the Purchasing Managers Association of Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Lohse, e-commerce research director at the Wharton School
at the University of Pennsylvania, says this fear is overblown, but
is based on a kernel of truth. ``People who don't add much value to
a transaction will be displaced and replaced by new intermediaries
that are more efficient,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Smaller companies that don't now have Internet connections will
have to get them and train employees how to use the Web. At
E-wood.com, a start-up auction site for the lumber and wood
products industry, founders Lincoln Alden and Arnold Kraft have set
up classes to teach loggers, sawmill operators, and wood products
manufacturers about computers and electronic commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Purchasing agents, while cost-conscious, also worry about
breaking relations with trusted vendors and salespeople. Lisa
Bankowski-Call, purchasing director at Zoom Telephonics Inc. in
Boston, says the Internet has proved very useful in finding
hard-to-get items like flash-memory chips, applauds the chance to
save money. ``But I think for most purchases in companies like ours
you will always need a person . . . who understands your
business,'' she said. ``It comes down to loyalty.''
</P>
<P>
   Some industries lend themselves better to electronic commerce
than others. Lohse, at the Wharton School, cites Goldman Sachs &AMP;
Co. research predicting aerospace, electronics, and the computer
industry itself will be big online buyers and sellers. Paper,
steel, health care and the coal industry scored lower. But, Lohse
said, ``When you look at the efficiencies that even these
industries can gain in terms of dollar value, you still are talking
about a lot of money.''
</P>
<P>
   Manzi, while bruised by his Industry.Net experience, had it
right. Only his timing was wrong. After the bankruptcy, the Web
site name ended up with Information Handling Services Group, a
privately held Denver company that publishes online databases for
25 industrial sectors _ and makes a profit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
