u f BC-PAPER-EXCHANGE-BOS &LR;      03-03 1459
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAPER-EXCHANGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAPER FIRM TARGETS A NET NICHE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MEG VAILLANCOURT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The New England Patriots and their new privately funded
$275 million stadium is how owner Robert Kraft and his family spend
money. A hot Internet start-up is one way the Krafts hope to make
money.
</P>
<P>
   The company is called PaperExchange.com.
</P>
<P>
   Backed by some of the biggest names on the Web, it's the
brainchild of Kraft and his son Jonathan, president and chief
operating officer of the family's paper and packaging business.
According to industry experts, it's poised to dramatically alter
the way paper is bought and sold across the globe.
</P>
<P>
   ``In their industry, PaperExchange could be the next AOL,'' Chip
Dillon, an analyst with Salomon Smith Barney. ``They're ahead of
the competition and backed by the right people. . . . I'd say these
guys could become the largest player in the Internet paper
market.''
</P>
<P>
   Headquartered in the Back Bay, PaperExchange is an online
marketplace for the paper industry. Instead of an eBay-like
auction, the site allows large-scale buyers, sellers, brokers, and
shippers of paper and papermaking equipment to negotiate their own
terms.
</P>
<P>
   Like many of the hottest Internet start-ups, the company is
targeting the white-hot business-to-business, or B2B, market. The
goal is to build a Web-based ``vertical market'' that can become a
one-stop shopping center for paper businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The company is courting clients with the claim they can cut
costs by wringing out the inefficiencies that traditionally plague
the paper industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the inefficient B2B markets that stand to gain the most
from a Web-based exchange,'' said Bernie Jaworksi, an e-commerce
expert at the Cambridge-based Monitor Group. ``Especially with
commodity-like products like paper that don't need to be viewed or
touched.''
</P>
<P>
   Key industry leaders are already convinced. Two days ago, Asia
Pulp &AMP; Paper, the world's second-largest paper company, announced
it will sell its products on PaperExchange.com. Last week,
International Paper, the world's largest paper producer, announced
it will use the site and invest in the company.
</P>
<P>
   PaperExchange went online two years ago and today more than
3,000 members in 75 countries use the site to trade all grades of
paper. The company hopes to make money by charging a small
commission on each sale and by acting as bank for the capital
intensive industry.
</P>
<P>
   Officials won't discuss revenue, but given the paper industry's
$300-billion-a-year global sales, PaperExchange needs to capture
only a portion of the market to become profitable.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Kraft, 35, conceived of the company back in early 1990s
when he was pushing the Patriots to become the first team in
professional sports with a Web site. Charged with directing the
Kraft Group's investment strategy, he and other family members
backed about 30 Internet start-ups, including Andover-based CMGI
and the New York-based Internet Capital Group before it went
public.
</P>
<P>
   PaperExchange was spun off from International Forest Products,
the Krafts' paper-trading company and one of the nation's largest
exporters of paper. PaperExchange's directors are among the biggest
players in the paper and Internet industries.
</P>
<P>
   It's the only board that includes both ICG cofounder Walter
Buckley and his frequent rival, David Wetherell of CMGI. Robert
Kraft is chairman, and Roger Stone, former CEO of Stone Container,
sits on the board. Michael Dell of Dell Computers is a lead
investor.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a marquee board that certainly would be hard to
beat,'' Dillon said. ``The names involved on both the paper and
Internet side may well discourage some players from trying to mount
a competitive exchange.''
</P>
<P>
   Depite the prominence of their backers, the Krafts and other
company officials declined requests for more information about
PaperExchange, fueling speculation that the company is preparing to
go public.
</P>
<P>
   If the company is successful in executing its business plan,
analysts estimate the value of PaperExchange could range from $2
billion to $4 billion. Indeed, a special report on the e-commerce
market issued by Hambrecht and Quist last month specifically cited
PaperExchange as an example of a B2B exchange likely to be among
``2000's best investments in the overall Internet sector.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, a key reason investors are bullish on the idea is
the paper industry's historically low profit margins.
</P>
<P>
   Creating a new paper mill can cost upwards of $1 billion, with
millions more needed for annual maintenance. It's also
prohibitively expensive to start and stop mill operations, meaning
that tons of surplus inventory is produced. And since the equipment
severely limits the width of paper that can be produced, more goes
to waste as rolls are trimmed to fit orders. Most mills are
concentrated in North America, Indonesia, and Scandinavia, but
demand for paper is worldwide. Filling the geographic gap is an
army of brokers who pair sellers with buyers and take on the
complicated task of arranging to ship tons of product across the
globe.
</P>
<P>
   PaperExchange claims it can increase sales by finding a market
for surplus inventory and at the same time cut costs by eliminating
the middle men. The company is marketing its Web site as an
effective ``spot market'' where buyers can easily compare prices
and coordinate production and shipping schedules. Internet analysts
argue the paper market is tailor-made for the kind of improvements
a Web-based exchange can engender. They point to a recent Fortune
magazine survey rating 37 industries for return on equity, return
on assets, and return on revenue over the past decade.
</P>
<P>
   In every category, the paper industry ranked dead last. ``There
is a huge opportunity for e-marketplaces in the paper industry
because there are so many different steps in the distribution
chain,'' said B2B expert Bruce Tempkin of Forrester Research. ``All
those guys who have the word `broker' in their names are in trouble
as information becomes more easily accessible.''
</P>
<P>
   The crucial question is whether PaperExchange can deliver on
that promise faster and better than anyone else.
</P>
<P>
   In the see-it-now world of the Internet, good ideas are quickly
cloned. At the moment, however, rivals are either focused on narrow
niche markets or aren't online yet.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, PaperExchange eliminated its closest competitor the
old-fashioned way: It bought it. Officials then moved
Portland-based MPX to Boston and merged with PaperExchange.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft and company also have bulked up by seeking out strategic
partners. PaperExchange recently increased the value of its Web
site by allying itself with VerticalNet, a Pennsylvania company
that provides editorial content and online portals in more than 50
industries.
</P>
<P>
   The new alliance also telegraphed the growing market power of
PaperExchange. Just last month, Microsoft announced it was
providing $100 million to help VerticalNet build new industry
specific exchanges. But even with Microsoft's might behind them,
VerticalNet chose to partner with PaperExchange rather than compete
_ a move analysts say underscores the Boston-based company's head
start.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the company hopes to make money by lending it.
</P>
<P>
   Given the large transactions common in the paper industry,
PaperExchange is setting itself up to act as a bank _ lending money
to buyers and checking credit for sellers who want to certify
potential bidders can pay on demand.
</P>
<P>
   There are, of course, plenty of possible pitfalls ahead. Like
other B2B start-ups, PaperExchange must first persuade industry
leaders to make the leap to Internet buying and selling.
</P>
<P>
   One hurdle is reassuring members that a site backed by huge
paper producers can remain neutral and confidential. Cyber experts
from Ernst &AMP; Young recently certified the security and neutrality
of the site, but concerns about possible conflicts of interest
remain a stumbling block for some companies.
</P>
<P>
   A Web-based exchange also represents a major shift in how the
paper industry operates. Persuading industry leaders to abandon
their traditional practices _ and cast off the hundreds of
thousands of salespeople and brokers currently employed buying and
selling in the offline world _ will require a massive marketing
effort.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, institutional investors and bankers who heard
Jonathan Kraft pitch PaperExchange at an exclusive Goldman Sachs
seminar in California late last year said they were impressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still early in the game, but PaperExchange is the clear
leader,'' said Dillon. ``With their expertise, contacts and
front-runner status, it's their game to lose right now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-03-00 1542EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
