u w BC-DEPOTS04-COX     03-03 0478
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEPOTS04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CONGRESS WORRIES THAT AIR FORCE HAS OVER-PRIVATIZED ITSELF
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The U.S. Air Force is turning over so much of its
aircraft maintenance to private contractors that the military's own
repair depots are endangered, a U.S. senator charged Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. James M. Inhofe, R-Okla., chairman of a Senate Armed
Services subcommittee on readiness, said that an increasing trend
of relying on private companies to maintain new weapons systems
could mean ``the eventual collapse of the public depots.''
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force has three major depots, or ``air logistics
centers,'' at Ogden, Utah; Oklahoma City, and Warner Robins, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   However, depots at Sacramento, Calif., and San Antonio are being
closed amid the post-Cold War shrinking of the military. At the
same time, the Air Force has increased the private share of
maintenance work from 36 percent in 1991 to 50 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
   At the hearing Friday, Gen. George Babbitt Jr., commander of the
Air Force Materiel Command, attempted to reassure Inhofe that the
Pentagon wants to retain public depots even as it hires private
contractors for new weapons systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goal of our program is to have that industrial base''
capable of providing parts and maintenance, he said. Contractors
can do some of the work, he said, but he added that they ``won't
hold the reserve capacity'' that the Air Force depots can provide.
</P>
<P>
   The concerns arose last month when Air Force Secretary F.
Whitten Peters told Congress he was waiving a requirement that at
least 50 percent of all maintenance work be performed by the public
depots.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to get aircraft back in the air,'' Peters told the
Senate panel. He said the Air Force needed the backup partly
because of the wear and tear on equipment from the Kosovo conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were dramatic increases of aircraft on the ground,'' he
said, adding that ``our mission-capable rates were going down very
quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Max Cleland, D-Ga., said he was concerned about whether key
aircraft would still be maintained by the Air Force at Warner
Robbins. ``Is the depot system broken?'' he asked Peters.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force secretary responded one part of the system was
``broken,'' an effort to recalibrate crucial fighter plane parts at
the Ogden depot.
</P>
<P>
   Peters also told the panel that Air Force maintenance operations
have persistent problems, including ``dismal'' shortages of
experienced personnel and continuing challenges in retaining those
who become skilled. However, he said that a serious spare parts
shortage is now abating, after Congress granted $500 million in
supplemental funds last year.
</P>
<P>
   Julia Malone's e-mail address is juliam(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
