<HEADLINE>
FOR SOME, SYCAMORE STOCK'S TOO HOT TO HOLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In its brief life as a public company, Sycamore Networks Inc.
has blessed investors as few, if any, other Massachusetts stocks
have ever done.
</P>
<P>
   Sycamore, which launched its initial public offering in October,
is scheduled to sell millions of new shares later this month, and
you can easily imagine investors lining up for a piece of the
action. The Chelmsford, Mass. company, its well-regarded managers,
and the white-hot interest in optical telecommunications networks
have proven to be a powerhouse stock story so far.
</P>
<P>
   A few words to the wise: Pay attention to the other Sycamore
stock line, the long queue being formed by early investors who plan
to sell a piece of their holdings. Dozens of early birds _ from
institutions such as Harvard and MIT, which are planning to move
hundreds of thousands of shares, to individuals who expect to sell
much more modest positions _ have publicly registered their
intentions.
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing extraordinary about early investors selling a
portion of their stock after legal ``lock-up'' periods expire, but
these are no ordinary times.
</P>
<P>
   A surreal daily market for Sycamore stock has driven the shares
up a stunning 68 percent in the last week alone, apparently fueled
in part by investors who wanted to buy in front of an important
industry conference next week in Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   Sycamore shares weren't cheap to start with. Adjust the numbers
for a February stock split, and the shares Sycamore sold to the
public for $38 each four months ago were worth just under $570
Thursday (the actual closing price was 189 15/16). A company with
lots of promise and revered managers but few actual products is now
valued at $44.8 billion. This week, it passed Gillette Co. to
become the state's second-most-valuable public company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever it's worth, it's getting ahead of itself,'' said
Boston investment manager Fred Kobrick. ``If this stock doesn't
correct, that means the gravitational pull of the earth isn't
working anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Kobrick, who bought shares in the IPO, was upbeat about the
company's prospects, but reluctant to buy at current prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a stressful dilemma when you really like a company and
want to buy it at a price you think is appropriate, but people are
driving it to the moon. We're in a market that doesn't know what
anything is worth and doesn't care,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Huge amounts of money are being invested in optical networking
companies in the belief they will become the key suppliers in the
rewiring of America in a fiber-optic telecommunications age.
</P>
<P>
   The problem: Few companies in Sycamore's category have real
products yet, and no one knows who is going to win.
</P>
<P>
   Investors love Sycamore in particular because it's run by Desh
Deshpande and Daniel Smith, who built Cascade Communications Corp.
and sold it for $3.6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Deshpande and Smith each hold stakes in Sycamore worth more than
twice the entire sale price of Cascade three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Deshpande owns just under 49 million Sycamore shares, worth
about $9.3 billion; Smith's 44.1 million shares are valued at about
$8.4 billion. Their investment in a two-year-old company places
them at a level of wealth, at the moment, that may be eclipsed only
by Abigail Johnson's, of Fidelity Investments.
</P>
<P>
   Deshpande and Smith plan to sell a sliver of their holdings,
240,000 shares each, in the upcoming company stock offering.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Sycamore's potential, the company also faces real risks.
</P>
<P>
   There are competitors with deep pockets and long relationships
with big customers, such as Nortel Networks Corp. and Lucent
Technologies Inc. Cisco Systems, likely to become the world's most
valuable company any day now, is lurking. And Ciena Corp. is
another legitimate contender.
</P>
<P>
   How many winners can there be?
</P>
<P>
   Maribel Lopez, a senior analyst at Forrester Research in
Cambridge, predicts the top three will emerge with most of the
business, a fourth company will win a little market share, and
everyone else will fight for table scraps.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had to make a call, in the foreseeable future Sycamore
will be one of the top three,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Sycamore has made impressive progress since it went public. The
company signed up Enron as an important new customer, signed
contracts with two European telecommunciations providers, pushed
new products out to field trials, and earned a modest profit.
</P>
<P>
   Now, it is preparing for a public sale of 15 million shares
(including 2.6 million offered by insiders) that will generate
hundreds of millions in new cash.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, more institutions and others who invested very
early through venture capital funds are planning to take some money
off the table.
</P>
<P>
   The people in charge of that money would tell you their
investments were always earmarked for venture capital and, besides,
endowments demand diversification.
</P>
<P>
   Probably they wouldn't tell you that Sycamore stock has gotten
much too expensive for now. That's our job.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
</P>
<P>
   boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-03-00 1543EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
