<DOCNO> NYT20000303.0139 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-03 15:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5816 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BKN-CELTICS-PITINO-BO     03-03 1031
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CELTICS-PITINO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PITINO'S CELTICS SHOW LITTLE PROGRESS AFTER THREE YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Shot was just the beginning. No sooner had Vince
Carter's improbable game-winner Wednesday night settled through the
net than the Toronto Raptor was surrounded and congratulated _ by
FleetCenter fans.
</P>
<P>
   Across the floor, Celtics coach Rick Pitino was in a crouch,
unwilling to move, staring at the recently replaced parquet floor,
the one that was around for the franchise's 16 NBA championship
banners. The optimism for a 17th is now long gone. Making the
playoffs is the lofty goal now, and Pitino Thursday acknowledged
that the chances of ending the team's five-year, non-playoff run
are ``slim.''
</P>
<P>
   When Pitino finally did stand and make his way to the locker
room, he was jeered by some of those fans. Shortly into his
postgame news conference, Pitino vented. He defended his sagging
team, which has lost four straight at home and 14 of 18 overall. He
blasted the fans and the city of Boston for its history of
``negativity.'' He reminded fans that the Big Three _ Larry Bird,
Kevin McHale, and Robert Parish _ the most recent links to the
Celtics' storied era, were ``gray and old.'' That was then; this is
now. Get used to it.
</P>
<P>
   That is both the truth and the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly three years into his precedent-setting 10-year,
$50-million deal, Pitino presides over a team that has made scant,
if any, progress. In his first year, he had a young team that by
all accounts worked hard and overachieved by winning 36 games. In
1997-98, that Celtics team filled the FleetCenter 28 times. This
year, Pitino still has a young team that works hard, but is on a
pace to win 33 games. The FleetCenter has been sold out only six
times in 27 games.
</P>
<P>
   What happened?
</P>
<P>
   In May 1997, Pitino left a championship-caliber program at the
University of Kentucky and took over the Celtics' basketball
operations in what only could be described as a coronation at the
FleetCenter. He was given money, power, titles, and all the help he
wanted. Wednesday night, 34 months later, a coach who rarely saw
his college team lose anywhere watched the Celtics fall at home to
Toronto and get booed in their own building. He then launched into
a rambling, bitter monologue that instantly became talk-radio
fodder.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no problem with anything I said,'' he insisted
Thursday, having slept on the remarks. ``Everything I said was the
gospel truth, according to me.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the Gospel According to Rick. The gospel according to the
NBA is that the Celtics will, in all likelihood, not make the
playoffs this season. Once Pitino promised results, now he preaches
patience.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can't change overnight,'' he said Thursday. ``There are no
overnight solutions. You start from the bottom and inch yourself
up.''
</P>
<P>
   The last two games in Boston crystallized Pitino's frustration
and sent him into his Wednesday night rant. On Monday, the Celtics
led by 20 points with less than 19 minutes to play and lost by 8 to
the Dallas Mavericks, a team they had bowed to only once in Boston
in the previous 18 years. The Mavericks have been synonymous with
failure in the 1990s. But in two years, they'll have a new arena
and as much as $20 million to spend on players. They already have a
young, enthusiastic new owner who's willing to spend money.
</P>
<P>
   But if the loss to Dallas was disheartening, and it was, then
Carter's basket was the metaphorical dagger in Pitino's chest. In
Pitino's first year, the Celtics went 3-0 against Toronto. The
Raptors were an NBA joke, winning only 16 games. Now, thanks to
sage moves by management, the Raptors are on pace to make the
playoffs with one of the game's young, dynamic players in Carter.
They have hope. They have a future.
</P>
<P>
   Does Boston?
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics have a young, hard-working team, but as Kevin McHale
_ that ``gray and old'' Boston veteran _ is fond of saying, ``Hard
work will only get you so far. If all I wanted was hard workers,
I'd hire 12 plumbers. You need talent.''
</P>
<P>
   This year's Celtics are a team Pitino flatly predicted would
make the playoffs, a team he has said he loves to coach, even if
that love often appears unrequited. It is a team that, he said this
week, needs patience and understanding, two words never associated
with Pitino and his coaching history. He was always the one who
quickly turned teams around.
</P>
<P>
   It also is a team loaded with too many mediocre players pulling
down big salaries, most of them signed by Pitino and many of them
untradeable. He frequently complains about being unable to compete
with big-spending teams in the league while neglecting to note that
several teams with better records _ Toronto, Charlotte, San Antonio
_ are spending much less than Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Because of Pitino's own free spending, he put the Celtics in a
position where he could not afford to re-sign one of his best
players, Ron Mercer. He traded Mercer for Danny Fortson last
August. He then traded Fortson, complaining that he, too, was too
expensive to keep. (Fortson came back after the player he was
traded for flunked his physical; it remains to be seen whether he
even wants to re-sign with the Celtics.)
</P>
<P>
   It was Pitino who promised this team would make the playoffs. It
wasn't a hedge. It was a flat-out guarantee. He made the promise
last year. He made the promise while he still had Mercer and while
Adrian Griffin, this year's surprising newcomer, was playing in the
Continental Basketball Association.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Pitino dragged out ancient history. The Celtics
troubles, he said, are not just the fault of the salary cap, of all
those big spenders, of the ``negative'' Boston fans. What about the
1997 NBA Draft Lottery? Wasn't that lottery supposed to deliver Tim
Duncan and return the Celtics to prominence?
</P>
<P>
   Pitino accepted the Celtics coaching job 10 days before that
lottery. He could have waited to see if the Celtics got the first
pick. He didn't wait; he jumped at the $50 million.
</P>
<P>
   It's all moot now. He has what he has and, right now, what he
has just isn't nearly good enough.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
