<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-03 15:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5821 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BOX-WEIGHT-2TAKES-BOS     03-03 1439
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-WEIGHT-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEIGHT SWINGS AMONG BOXERS CAUSING CONCERN 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ There was $40 million sitting on a table waiting for
Felix Trinidad and Oscar De La Hoya. All that was standing between
them picking it up was a few pounds of suet.
</P>
<P>
   Everything necessary for them to sign for a June rematch at
Caesars Palace was in place with the exception of one weighty
problem. De La Hoya insisted he's a 147-pound welterweight.
Trinidad said he's a 154-pound junior middleweight, even though he
presently holds two of the three welterweight titles. Friday (March
3) Trinidad will try to prove his point by fighting World Boxing
Association champion David Reid at Caesars Palace. If he wins, he
claims that title and would have fought De La Hoya at what is
called a catch weight.
</P>
<P>
   And that was the catch.
</P>
<P>
   Both fighters had agreed to fight at 151 pounds originally but
De La Hoya insisted that the two make weight the day of the fight,
not 24 hours earlier as has become the norm for weigh-ins at
big-time fights in recent years. Trinidad's promoter, Don King,
wanted his fighter to weigh in 24 to 36 hours earlier and then use
that time to go up from 151, but when representatives of the two
sides sat down, Trinidad's father actually kept insisting the
weight be 154, which to De La Hoya's counselors meant he could
weigh as much as 170 pounds by fight night, 18 pounds more than De
La Hoya's normal 150-152.
</P>
<P>
   It was a weighty problem and one that had come into the
forefront of people's minds this week in part because of the way
Maine's Joey Gamache was destroyed last Saturday night by Arturo
Gatti, who who came into the ring at Madison Square Garden weighing
19 pounds more than Gamache. It was originally reported the
difference on fight night was 16 pounds, but it turned out to be an
even wider disparity, 160 to 141, and the result was that Gamache
was flattened three times in two rounds and rocked by nearly every
punch that landed before he suffered a serious concussion and was
hospitalized for several days.
</P>
<P>
   After De La Hoya's promoter, Bob Arum, saw that fight and read
of the huge weight disparity by fight time, he decided what he
would advise De La Hoya to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I read the articles about that fight I was stunned,''
Arum said. ``I can't have Oscar go into the ring at 151, 152, and
fight a guy who's 170 pounds or more. Oscar's a hell of a lot
better fighter than Trinidad, but I don't want to spot him that
kind of weight. We agreed he'd make 150 the day of the fight and
King is saying 151 plus or minus, which means 152, but the father
keeps saying 154 day before, which could mean 170. You saw the
Gamache debacle. Where not going to let that happen to Oscar.''
</P>
<P>
   And so Monday, De La Hoya agreed to fight Shane Mosley, the
former lightweight champion, at 147 June 10 or 17 at 147 pounds
give or take nothing. De La Hoya will earn the same $20 million he
was likely to get fighting Trinidad while Mosley agreed to $5
million, with promoter Cedrick Kushern getting 15 percent. So, at
least in their case, weight was an issue. To the guy known
throughout boxing as ``The Fight Doctor,'' it always should be.
</P>
<P>
   ``The greatest crime that we've done in boxing in the last 10
years is to allow a guy to gain 19 pounds and get into the ring
with a 141-pound opponent,'' Dr. Ferdie Pacheco, Ali's old doctor,
said. ``It makes it the most futile thing in the world (to fight
such a weight disadvantage). Why do you weigh guys in? To keep
160-pound guys from fighting 140-pound guys. You couldn't make that
match legally if you tried but they let a guy weigh in 36 hours
early and get him down to 141 and then let him weight whatever he
wants on fight night?
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at the result. They almost killed (Gamache). It was like
adding a piece of iron in the glove like (Jack) Dempsey did with
Jess Willard. It wasn't negligible. It was criminal and the people
in charge of overseeing the sport allowed it. How many times do
they have to see this?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What they saw with Arturo Gatti's weight is what De La Hoya will
not allow himself to face with Trinidad, yet it has become a
growing trend in the sport that fighters scramble to make weight,
knowing they have 36 hours or so to revitialize themselves. So
beyond mere hard training they take an assortment of laxatives,
even the veterinary medicine Lasix, to purge their bodies of all
fluids at the last minute. They sweat out every drop of water in
their bodies in saunas, by working out in rubber suits, by taking
appetite suppressants, by eating and drinking little or nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Then they step on a scale for as short a time as possible, leap
off and drink a gallon of water to begin a process called
rehydrating. For some it takes too much of a toll and they enter
the ring with nothing left inside. Others end up like Gatti,
looking like a giant in the Land of Lilliputians. In fact, Gatti's
trainer, Hector Rocha, said Gatti gained back much of his weight on
a pasta and water diet. It seemed to work.
</P>
<P>
   For James Toney, on the night he faced Roy Jones Jr. several
years ago, it did not. At that weigh-in, Toney looked like a man
ready to pass out, but he made 168 pounds. By the next night, he
weighed 15 pounds more but was an empty shell, his body used up,
dried out, weak.
</P>
<P>
   It can happen that way just as it can happen the other way as it
did in Gatti's case. Gatti came into the ring looking twice as big
as Gamache and after he landed one straight right hand that put
Gamache down and through the ropes, everyone knew it was over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I was too strong for him in the first round,'' Gatti
would say later.
</P>
<P>
   That's not always what happens to a fighter who puts himself
through this, but the process of rehydration is always the same.
The results will vary from fighter to fighter, but the rest of it
is unchanging.
</P>
<P>
   ``You pay a price when you do that to your body,'' Pacheco said.
``You deplete your body of all water and the fat goes with it. It's
cruelty to the body but it gets your weight down. Then you step on
a scale, get off and all your cells are like dry sponges. Any drop
of water they suck up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything goes in for the next 36 hours and nothing goes out.
It's almost like a kidney shut down. The body is thirsty so it
retains every bit of fluid and your weight just increases rapidly
to get back to where you should be. To what you really are.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Nevada Athletic Commission was the first to begin reweighing
its fighters in the locker room on fight night. It has been
recording the varying weights of thousands of fighters and the
results from those fights. Statisticians at the University of
Nevada-Las Vegas are studying the results.
</P>
<P>
   After Marc Ratner and the Commission get the results, they plan
to alter how much weight they will allow a fighter to gain the day
before a fight. Although they will continue to have weigh-ins 24-36
hours before a match, Ratner said they see a need to reduce the
amount of weight fighters are allowed to put back on to avoid what
happened in New York with Gatti and Gamache.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big problem,'' Ratner said. ``We need to limit what
they can gain the next day (after a weigh-in). Maybe we'll have a
second weigh-in the day of the fight and tell the fighters they
can't regain more than a certain percentage of what they first came
in at, say 7 or 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I recall, moving to the day before weigh-in started with us
after a fight in which Steve Cruz struggled to make weight on the
day of one of his title fights. He made it but was so dehydrated he
could barely move and he was badly beaten. The fact is, severe
weight loss on the day of a fight just to make weight is also
dangerous, and could cause serious injury to a fighter because
there's no fluids in his body.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our doctors discussed this and we went to the day before
weigh-in because medically it's better and safer for the fighter to
have more time to rehydrate. The theory was the guy still had
punished himself to make the weight.
</P>
<P>
   ``About 12 years ago, I remember, there was a fight between
Nigel Benn and Iran Barkley. Barkley weighed 160 at the weight in
and nearly 180 for the fight. It was the greatest weight gain I'd
ever seen. We acknowledge these things are happening and it's
become a problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``We acknowledge that gaining 20 pounds like that is taking
advantage of the weigh-in rules and it has to stop. Gatti-Gamache
made that obvious.''
</P>
<P>
   Not to everyone in boxing it didn't.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
