<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-03 15:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5823 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BOX-WEIGHT-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE-     03-03 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-WEIGHT-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 LAS VEGAS: ... it didn't.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Veteran trainer Teddy Atlas watched that fight, heard of the
huge weight disparity and the fact that at the weigh-in there had
been questions about the scales and whether Gatti ever balanced
them.
</P>
<P>
   Gamache's handlers now claim they argued with the New York State
Athletic Commission officials in charge of the scales but were
rebuffed and the fight went on to its inevitable conclusion.
Knowing that, Atlas doesn't see weight as the real issue here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did he really weigh that weight or was he heavier to begin
with?'' Atlas said. ``He got on and off fast and they say the scale
never balanced. If that's true, then somebody should have said,
`Get back on the scale or you can go get another fight for HBO.'
They didn't, so why say it now?
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes to weight, all things are relative. If you can
fight well enough it doesn't matter. You might not win but you
don't have a result like you had with Gamache. When Toney went up
so much in weight in the Jones fight, nobody made anything of it
because all he did was lose every round. He didn't get blown out so
nobody made anything of the weight gain he had.
</P>
<P>
   ``No offense to Gamache, but if he was a better opponent, the
weight wouldn't have made a difference. Look at his line by line
(record). He's only got four losses but they were all blowouts
against top guys. I don't care if Gatti weighed 400 pounds or 120
pounds, the weight difference didn't make Gamache easy to hit. He
got hit clean because of the fighter he is now. If you want to add
the weight in after that, go ahead, but Toney added more weight
against Jones and it didn't help.
</P>
<P>
   ``So before we throw the book at this weigh-ins the day before,
look at the situation first. The fact is, it's safer for the
fighters to weigh in the day before the fight. It allows you to
regenerate the guy right, using electrolights.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now you can make the argument that if you can't make the
weight on the day of the fight, you go to another class and the
fight is off but the fact is that would cause havoc with
postponements. How could anyone be in reasonable control? What does
a TV network or a promoters do? Advertise four fights? These are
the two we hope to show and these are the two over the weight
fights just in case? You can't do that. You can't put television in
that position.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of all this talk about the weight gain, look at
whether the guy should have been in there with the other guy. When
there's a blowout like that, I always look at the opponent, not the
weight, because if both guys can fight, it's not usually an issue.
It's an issue if it's a bad match to start off with.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Many have charged that the move to early weigh-ins was a move
not to protect the fighters, but the cable networks that pay
millions to broadcast major bouts and the promoters who stage them.
As with most things in boxing, the truth lies in the middle.
</P>
<P>
   Medically, it is safer for a fighter battling to reach a certain
weight to have the most time possible to reactivate his body. That
was a large part of the reason the sport went away from day-of-the
fight weigh-ins. But, so too was it a move to ensure that the
people paying for major events got what was advertised.
</P>
<P>
   So to Al Mitchell, the responsibility of protecting the fighter
from an overweight opponent no longer goes to the commissions
because they have a vested interest, as do the television networks,
in finding ways to make the fights.
</P>
<P>
   Thus it falls on ``the coach,'' as Reid's trainer likes to call
himself, to be responsible for the scales as well as the weights.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the coach has got to protect the fighter,'' Mitchell
said. ``Gatti awlays has been big (on fight night). They knew he'd
been coming in that way. I'm surprised Gamache's people didn't know
that.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as the first punch was thrown, it was a mismatch.
Nineteen pounds is a lot of pounds. I don't fault anybody else but
the coach. They know an 18-pound difference is a mismatch. Gatti
had a history of that. I know that I don't take the fight. Not when
my kid is going to be 141. This ain't the first time Arturo did
this, so if I've got a 140-pound fighter, he ain't gonna fight with
Gatti. Don't blame the commissions or TV. Who's supposed to be
accountable for the fighter? His corner.''
</P>
<P>
   Pacheco wouldn't dispute Mitchell's belief in the cornermen's
responsibilities, but he also has as good an understanding of the
two sides of the question as anyone because he has long served in
the corners of great fighters and more than a few times had to
bring their weight down in a desperate, last-minute fashion.
Sometimes it worked, other times it didn't.
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, he has long been a television boxing analyst, too,
and is well aware of whose interests often come first in the sport
and whose come last.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate to blame television, but they got to have the guy fight
they say is fighting,'' Pacheco said. ``In the old days, you always
had day-of-the-fight weigh-ins. You didn't make weight the fight
was off, and you replaced it with someone else, or you fought over
the weight for less money and no title.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't have that now with the big money that's being paid.
I can see no reason, no real justification to have the weigh-in 36
hours early except for the convenience of the promoter and the TV
executives to ensure on the day of the fight, they have a fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Last Saturday night they had one. In June, they won't, in part
because of what happened to Gamache. The one thing you can be
assured of is that in the latter case, there won't ever be a
19-pound difference between Oscar De La Hoya and Felix Trinidad.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to know why, go watch tape of Joey Gamache's last
fight.
</P>
</TEXT>
