<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING SENSE OF THE MADNESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now that it is officially March, we can get past the business of
the regular season _ and deal with the madness known as the NCAA
basketball tournament.
</P>
<P>
   It's still a week early to be getting into projections and
serious tournament seeding, but it is not too early to take a look
at the conferences and which teams should feel comfortable about
playing past the Ides of March.
</P>
<P>
   --America East (1) _ Hofstra won the regular season and the
Flying Dutchmen should prevail in the America East tournament,
which starts Friday in Newark, Del. Hofstra will have the
home-court edge in the championship game next Saturday if it takes
care of business this weekend. If Hofstra gets upset, it is the
only America East team with a chance to play in the NIT.
</P>
<P>
   --Big Sky (1) _ Eastern Washington is the front-runner, but
watch out for red-hot Northern Arizona, which knocked off Eastern
Washington last week. First-place team hosts the postseason
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   --Big South (1) _ Regular-season champ Radford is the favorite.
Winthrop, one of the two teams to beat Radford during the
conference season, is a possibility.
</P>
<P>
   --Big West (1) _ Utah State is the team to beat.
</P>
<P>
   --Colonial (1) _ George Mason is the front-runner, but James
Madison also could be a factor. Dark horse? UNC-Wilmington.
</P>
<P>
   --Ivy (1) _ Penn continues to roll along.
</P>
<P>
   --Atlantic Coast Conference (3) _ Duke, Maryland, North
Carolina. Virginia needs help. ACC coaches will say this is
blasphemy, but everyone else is well under .500 in the league,
which isn't that great.
</P>
<P>
   --Atlantic 10 (3) _ Temple, Dayton. St. Bonaventure. That's all
the conference deserves, barring an upset, which puts another team
in the tournament champion's role. And St. Bonaventure is iffy.
</P>
<P>
   --Big East (6) _ Miami, Syracuse, St. John's, Seton Hall, UConn,
Villanova. Notre Dame's losses to Providence and Pittsburgh sealed
the fate of the Irish. Villanova has an outside shot, but will have
to win at least one game in the Big East tournament.
</P>
<P>
   --Big Ten (5) _ Michigan State, Ohio State, Purdue, Indiana,
Illinois. Wisconsin has wins over Temple and Texas, but five of the
Badgers' seven wins have come against the bottom half of the
league. It will take a significant run in the NCAA tournament to
get the Badgers out of the NIT field and into the NCAA tournament.
</P>
<P>
   --Big 12 (5) _ Oklahoma, Oklahoma State, Kansas, Iowa State,
Texas. Missouri is very close with 10 league wins, but a
first-round tournament loss could doom the Tigers.
</P>
<P>
   --Conference USA (3) _ Cincinnati, Louisville, DePaul.
Cincinnati and Louisville are givens, but after that, where do you
go? Tulane has a shot if it can make the championship game. DePaul
has some quality nonconference wins over Florida and St. John's,
giving it an edge.
</P>
<P>
   --Metro-Atlantic Athletic Conference (1) _ Sienna is again the
runaway favorite.
</P>
<P>
   --Mid-American Conference (2) _ Kent, Bowling Green. The MAC has
become a decent league in recent years and deserves two spots. Both
Kent and Bowling Green have more than 20 wins and decent RPIs
(ratings percentage index). Kent is 28, Bowling Green 46.
</P>
<P>
   --Mid-Continent (1) _ Oakland won the regular season, but is
ineligible for the tournament since it hasn't been in Division 1
long enough. Second-place Valparaiso looms as the heavy favorite.
</P>
<P>
   --Mid-Eastern Athletic Conference (1) _ South Carolina State and
Coppin State are running neck and neck. One of them should get the
bid.
</P>
<P>
   --Midwestern Collegiate Conference (1) _ Butler is the heavy
favorite.
</P>
<P>
   --Missouri Valley Conference (2) _ It's a tossup between Indiana
State and Southwest Missouri. Creighton could sneak in as a team
with a strong tournament run.
</P>
<P>
   --Mountain West (2) _ Utah, UNLV. Utah is a lock and Nevada-Las
Vegas should get in, although it has a shaky RPI (52). The
tournament is played in Vegas, though, which should help.
</P>
<P>
   --Northeast (1) _ Central Connecticut has had a fabulous season
and should win the tournament and get a 15 seed in the East, which
will probably earn it a first-round game against Temple.
</P>
<P>
   --Pac 10 (4) _ Stanford, Arizona, Oregon, UCLA. Stanford,
Arizona, and Oregon are locks. UCLA is going to have to make a
strong run in the next week, but has a superior RPI (27), which
could be the difference.
</P>
<P>
   --Ohio Valley (1) _ Southeast Missouri State and Murray State
tied for the regular-season title. The winner will get the bid. If
either falters, they'll have to settle for an NIT bid.
</P>
<P>
   --Southeastern Conference (6) _ Kentucky, Auburn, Florida,
Tennessee, LSU, Vanderbilt. The best conference this season will
get the most teams. Vanderbilt has slipped some, but should still
make it.
</P>
<P>
   --Patriot League (1) _ Lafayette or Navy. Take your pick. The
winner gets the bid. If it's someone else, both will be hoping the
phone rings with an NIT bid, but don't count on it.
</P>
<P>
   --Southern (1) _ College of Charleston remains the team to beat
because of its past history, but it is not as invincible as in past
years.
</P>
<P>
   --Southland (1) _ Sam Houston State won the regular season, but
Louisiana Monroe could emerge.
</P>
<P>
   --Southwestern Athletic Conference (1) _ Alcorn State is the
pick here.
</P>
<P>
   --Sun Belt Conference (1) _ South Alabama tied with Louisiana
Lafayette for the regular-season title, but swept the season series
between the two teams.
</P>
<P>
   --Trans-America Athletic Conference (1) _ Either Troy State or
Georgia State should emerge.
</P>
<P>
   --West Coast Conference (2) _ Pepperdine and Gonzaga are the
front-runners, but the Zags are fading.
</P>
<P>
   --Western Athletic Conference (3) _ This league is doing better
than expected. Tulsa is a genuine threat to reach the Final Four;
Fresno has 20 wins; and SMU is coming on strong.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Irish ire not smiling
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fan behavior has been a problem all season. Notre Dame's 73-71
loss to Syracuse in South Bend Wednesday night is a case in point.
With Notre Dame trailing by 2, 70-68, with 8.8 seconds left,
Syracuse's Ryan Blackwell was fouled. It was a close call that drew
the ire of the Notre Dame fans, who had been warned twice about
throwing things on the court. When a water bottle hit the court,
official Jody Silvester hit the Irish with a technical foul.
Blackwell made one of his two free throws to make it 71-68. The
Irish should have had the ball. But the technical foul voided that.
``They could have won the game,'' said Syracuse guard Jason Hart.
``You don't know what would have happened. They gave us two free
throws and the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Stop the silliness
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The business with the NCAA and players who received financial
support to attend prep schools is getting silly. You can go down
the list of most major Division 1 rosters and find some connection
between a player and a benefactor who gave him financial aid before
he arrived in college. The NCAA has to find a way to implement a
workable policy regarding AAU programs and players. The NCAA also
made a major mistake when executive director Cedric Dempsey made a
public statement criticizing St. John's for statements made in the
Erick Barkley case. ``I don't believe it's in anyone's best
interest that there be public disagreement about issues taking
place between the NCAA and a member school,'' Dempsey said. ``The
university's accusation of an NCAA guilt before stance is
inaccurate.'' It's also not in the NCAA's best interest for its
head to make a statement criticizing a member school during an
investigation . . . Barring a run through the Big East tournament,
the Irish are almost certainly headed for the NIT now instead of
the NCAA tournament . . . Word has it that Tulsa coach Bill Self is
high on the list as Bobby Cremmins's replacement at Georgia Tech.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-03-00 1551EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
