<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NCAA TOURNEY BAFFLING EXPERTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Clark Kellogg is normally cool and conservative as CBS's college
basketball analyst. But even he is excited about the upcoming NCAA
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be wild and wacky,'' said Kellogg, who added
that has not seen a dominant team emerge this season. Stanford is
big and deep and Cincinnati has added perimeter shooting and depth,
but neither of those teams has struck fear throughout the land.
</P>
<P>
   Kellogg cited a handful of teams that with a little luck could
end up in the Final Four in Indianapolis. According to Kellogg,
Tennessee, for one, has as much talent as anyone in the country but
has a tendency to get selfish with the ball. Florida has a great
pressure defense and 3-point shooters. Michigan State has
experience and poise, and, according to Kellogg, is the hottest of
the Big Ten teams. That's not to say that Kellogg's alma mater,
Ohio State, doesn't have a shot. Or even Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   The University of Connecticut has not played as well as
expected, but Syracuse, and possibly St. John's, has a chance, too.
</P>
<P>
   Kellogg said the Southeastern Conference could have six or seven
teams in the tournament. He also mentioned Auburn (depending on the
Chris Porter situation), Tulsa, Iowa State, and Oklahoma State as
potential Cinderella teams.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Let Madness begin
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There will be plenty of college basketball action this
league-championship weekend.
</P>
<P>
   CBS tops the ticket with tripleheaders Saturday and Sunday. Tim
Brando and James Worthy will call Saturday's noon game between
Florida and Kentucky; Ian Eagle and Jimmy Spanarkel have
Syracuse-UConn at 2 p.m.; and Jim Nantz and Billy Packer will
handle UCLA-Stanford at 4. Kellogg and Greg Gumbel will work the
CBS studio throughout the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ABC has North Carolina-Duke at 3 p.m., with Brent Musburger,
Dick Vitale, and Brad Dougherty calling the game from Cameron
Indoor Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   CBS's Sunday coverage starts at noon with Verne Lundquist and
Bill Raftery calling the St. John's-Miami game. Kevin Harlan and
Jon Sundvold will call the 2 p.m. Missouri-Kansas game, while Dick
Enberg and Al McGuire will handle Indiana-Wisconsin at 4.
</P>
<P>
   Starting 2 p.m. Saturday with the TransAmerica Athletic
Conference Championship, ESPN and ESPN2 will be carrying a total of
58 men's and women's games over nine days.
</P>
<P>
   Vitale will be calling four ACC tournament games, including the
championship game on March 12 at 1 p.m., and will be studio analyst
on March 8, 9, and 12. Len Elmore also will be very visable, as
analyst for the Southeastern Conference Championship and seven Big
East Championship games.
</P>
<P>
   CBS airs its ``Road to the Final Four'' on March 12 at noon,
followed by the SEC final at 1 and the Big Ten final at 3:30. The
NCAA tournament pairings will be announced at 6:30.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Atencion!
</P>
<P>
   Univision and Galavision, the Spanish-language networks, will
carry four Major League Baseball games this spring, starting March
11 with the 3 p.m. Red Sox-Houston Astros game on Univision. The
next day, Galavision has Red Sox-Astros at 1. The remaining two
games will be on Galavision and feature the March 18 contest
between the Atlanta Braves and Tampa Bay Devil Rays at 6 p.m. and
the March 19 Arizona Diamondbacks-Anaheim Angels game at 1 . . .
ESPN has an interesting ``Outside the Lines'' special on athletes
in movies. ``Playing the Part: Athletes as Actors,'' airs Friday
night at 7 . . . ``Nasty'' Nestor Aparicio, Boston's All Sports
1510 radio host, broadcasts live from Caesar's Palace in Las Vegas
6-10 Friday night. Aparicio is there to cover the Felix
Trinidad-David Reid middleweight fight. Patriots.com, the Patriots'
official Web site, has a new feature that will allow users to watch
construction of the team's new stadium, which is scheduled to open
in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Howard Manly covers the sports media for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
