<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-03 15:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5833 &Cx1f; tad-z
r p BC-DEMS-$ADV0305-COX     03-03 0834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMS-$ADV0305-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: EMBARGOED UNTIL SUNDAY, MARCH 5
 &HT;    Super Tuesday the crucial for Bradley
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Democrat Bill Bradley calls it ``take off day.'' The
political establishment dubs it Super Tuesday. Whatever the label,
Tuesday's primary balloting in 15 states and American Samoa is
undeniably do or die day for the former U.S. senator from New
Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Having lost four primary contests to Vice President Gore since
the Iowa caucuses just six weeks ago, Bradley must, as he says,
post some wins Tuesday to breath viability into his insurgent
campaign for president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've said all along that March 7 is the take off time,''
Bradley told reporters last week in California, where he trails
Gore five to one in the most recent poll. ``That's when we have to
win some primaries and that's when we are going to surprise some
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley has spoken of surprises before. He promised a surprise
in Iowa, where instead he was defeated by Gore two-to-one in the
Democratic caucus. He promised a surprise in New Hampshire, but the
promise came up empty by fewer than 6,000 votes, the margin of his
defeat to Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley invested six days of precious campaign time in
Washington state, which held a non-binding primary last Tuesday,
hoping for a lift. Once more he came up empty.
</P>
<P>
   Should Bradley again come up empty Tuesday he will be under
enormous pressure to drop out the race. And the end of the
nomination battle has important implications for Gore, who will
then be free to focus on the fall campaign against the Republicans
while the GOP candidates themselves may continue their own, bitter
fight.
</P>
<P>
   After months of sustained attacks on Bradley's health care
proposals and comittment to preserving Social Security, Gore over
the past week has turned away from Bradley and instead directed
more of his digs at Sen. John McCain (R-Ariz.) and Gov. George W.
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Gore attacked Bush Friday for not offering a forceful
endorsement of mandatory trigger locks for guns, a proposal that
both he and Bradley support. ``Is that what passes for courage on
the Republican side of this contest?'' Gore snipped.
</P>
<P>
   Recent polls show that Bradley trails Gore in all the March 7
states, including New York, the second largest prize of the day
with 243 delegates at stake. New York and the northeast was to have
been Bradley's firewall. Bradley played ten years with the New York
Knicks and served 18 years as a U.S. senator from neighboring New
Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Georgia, California and most of the South and West,
Bradley was well known in the East and began his campaign with a
regional base of support. But Bradley's early losses hurt him here.
</P>
<P>
   To date only 68 delegates have been determined, 41 for Gore and
27 for Bradley. But those numbers will change dramatically on
Tuesday. Some 1,315 delegates _ about 37 percent of those at stake
_ will be allocated on Super Tuesday, based on primary returns.
</P>
<P>
   In the seven days that follow, the delegate count will jump to
two-thirds of the total at stake for the Democrats. Some of those
states holding primaries that week are in the South and Southwest,
where Gore holds a regional regional, as well as institutional,
advantage over Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   In the days leading up to Tuesday's voting, Bradley campaigned
with the dogged determination of man fighting against the odds,
while Gore exuded the confidence of a candidate that is already
looking toward the Fall.
</P>
<P>
   Gore added yet another endorsement to his long list of
established, Democratic supporters when Sen. Bob Graham of Florida
endorsed him Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Also on Friday, Gore campaign manager Donna Brazile said that it
is possible that Gore could collect the 2,169 delegates needed to
secure the nomination by March 14.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, meanwhile, skipped across the Eastern seaboard, making
brief stops in New York, Connecticut, Maine and Rhode Island. He
flew to his native Missouri Saturday before returning to the East
Coast todaySUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   Rarely mentioning Gore, Bradley sought to portray himself as a
bold leader who was the only true reformer in the race. He
delivered a foreign policy speech at Brown University in
Providence, R.I., Friday, and stirred a large crowd in Portland,
Maine, with a passionate plea for a new politics based on
conviction and belief.
</P>
<P>
   But more often than not, Bradley faced questions from local
media about his chances of winning, not his credentials to be the
next president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in those places before, when nobody thought you can
do it and I did it. So it doesn't bother me,'' he said in interview
with a CBS affiliate in New York. ``After a moment's pause, he
added, ``I'd be less than truthful if I didn't tell you I wish I
was 30 up.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
