<DOCNO> NYT20000303.0150 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-03 15:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5835 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-ELECTION-$ADV05-COX     03-03 1020
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELECTION-$ADV05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CAMPAIGN TOOK A TWISTING ROUTE TO ITS EXPECTED DESTINATION
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories for release
Sunday, March 5.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ What a long, strange trip it's been for Al Gore and
George Bush.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, both were widely expected to stroll to their
parties' presidential nominations. And indeed, ``Super Tuesday''
primary victories this week could mark the fulfillment of their
political quests.
</P>
<P>
   But in between, this campaign has been like a political game of
Chutes and Ladders. Unexpected reversals of fortune raised doubts
at times whether either Bush or Gore would make it to the finish
line.
</P>
<P>
   Even if they do, both will be different _ some say vastly
improved _ candidates, fighting on a different battleground than
the one envisioned when the race began.
</P>
<P>
   ``The destination was predictable, but the route was not,'' said
former GOP strategist Jack Pitney, now a college professor in
California. ``For Bush, it was like traveling from Savannah to
Atlanta _ via the Bermuda Triangle.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Gore was shocked by polls showing Bill Bradley
running stronger than expected last fall, and even leading in the
first primary state of New Hampshire. ``Bad poll numbers are like
smoke detectors _ the sooner you get the signal, the better,'' said
Pitney.
</P>
<P>
   In the Republican race, the Bermuda Triangle has been John
McCain, the Arizona senator, political maverick and Vietnam War
hero whose surge in the GOP contest has confounded Bush strategists
and political analysts.
</P>
<P>
   They are still trying to sort out the reasons for McCain's
victories last month in New Hampshire and Michigan. The
reawakening, stronger than ever, of Ross Perot's reform-minded
constituency? Resistance among rank-and-file Republicans to the GOP
hierarchy's anointment of Bush? Simple hero-worship?
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody's figured this all out yet,'' said Republican pollster
Robert Teeter, who worked for Bush's father in the 1988 and 1992
presidential campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's missteps have also aided McCain's success: his
unimpressive performances in early debates, his lack of knowledge
of foreign policy and his appearance at anti-Catholic Bob Jones
University during the hard-fought battle for hard-line Republicans
in South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   But it's generally agreed that the primary battle, in which Bush
repackaged himself as ``a reformer with results,'' has left him
better prepared for a general election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's much crisper and much better schooled on all the issues
he's asked about. This primary scuffle is good for him,'' Rep.
Jennifer Dunn of Washington, a Bush backer, told The New York
Times.
</P>
<P>
   Still, if Bush prevails, political historians will likely point
to a different reason: the unprecedented $69 million he has raised,
and mostly spent.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's fund-raising prowess drove five candidates from the field
long before the actual voting: former Vice President Dan Quayle,
former Red Cross chairman Elizabeth Dole, former Tennessee Gov.
Lamar Alexander, Sen. Bob Smith of New Hampshire and Rep. John
Kasich of Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Conservative commentator Pat Buchanan cited the power of Bush's
money when he left the GOP to seek the nomination of the
Perot-founded Reform Party.
</P>
<P>
   Most of those who stayed were easily dispatched. Sen. Orrin
Hatch of Utah dropped out after Iowa, former Reagan administration
aide Gary Bauer after New Hampshire and wealthy magazine publisher
Steve Forbes after Delaware.
</P>
<P>
   Now Bush is opposed only by McCain and former ambassador Alan
Keyes, who refuses to end his campaign despite single-digit
support.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, like Bush, launched his campaign with clear advantages: he
was well-known, well-organized, well-financed and the overwhelming
favorite of the party establishments. In fact, Gore had the
unprecedented endorsement of the incumbent president he served.
</P>
<P>
   But like Bush, Gore found himself up against a candidate in
Bradley who seized the popular issue of campaign finance reform and
practiced ``the politics of authenticity'' _ disdain for
poll-tested campaign themes and a willingness to talk straight with
the voters.
</P>
<P>
   And like Bush, Gore found a way to respond to Bradley's strong
challenge and become ``a much better candidate,'' said Darrell
West, a presidential campaign expert at Brown University.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign headquarters was moved from Washington's
lobbyist-haunted K Street to Nashville, and the candidate traded
his blue suit and speeches from a lectern for earth tones, a
wireless microphone and open meetings with voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``His message became tighter and he positioned himself as a
fighter for the average person,'' West said.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, meanwhile, fell back into the ``old politics'' mode by
attacking Gore's truthfulness in the final debate before the New
Hampshire primary.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Bradley also fell victim to McCain's success. The
independent voters Bradley saw as his way to challenge the
``entrenched power'' of the Democratic Party chose the scrappy
McCain over the professorial Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with their party nominations within reach, Bush and Gore
may soon be free to concentrate on each other, and on the
transformed political terrain for the general election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The reform issue has energized a huge bloc of swing voters,
presenting a challenge to candidates strongly identified with the
status quo. Besides the expected battlegrounds of gun control and
taxes, other unforeseen issues have risen to prominence: health
care reform, abortion, and even religious tolerance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm comfortable asking the questions,'' said Larry Sabato, a
nationally known author and political scientist at the University
of Virginia, ``but not in giving definitive answers about this
election.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Shepard's e-mail address is scotts(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   (For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
