<HEADER>
A5840 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-RELIGION-JONES-COLUMN     03-03 0719
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-JONES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FARRAKHAN'S PEACE OVERTURES SCRUTINIZED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM JONES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When minister Louis Farrakhan first declared publicly that he
had a change of heart, he gave us hope that we would see an end to
his diatribes against whites, Jews and others.
</P>
<P>
   But we may be expecting too much too soon.
</P>
<P>
   Following an experience with cancer last year, the Nation of
Islam leader pledged to uplift ``lost and fallen humanity
regardless of their color, their race or their creed,'' Religion
News Service reported. Also, the powerfully magnetic leader who
drew multitudes to his Million Man March five years ago says his
movement is shifting toward traditional Islam.
</P>
<P>
   Many of us hope his peace moves are the real thing.
</P>
<P>
   Farrakhan commands much influence and is a masterful speaker. He
could do much to bring reconciliation among all religious and
racial groups in American society.
</P>
<P>
   But the peace signals were mixed at Farrakhan's annual Saviors
Day Conference in Chicago on Sunday, attended by 20,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   Farrakhan did speak words of peace during the event.
</P>
<P>
   Several times, he embraced W. Deen Mohammed, leader of the rival
Muslim American Society, a much larger predominantly
African-American Muslim group that has moved away from earlier
teachings of white hatred and toward orthodox Islam.
</P>
<P>
   Farrakhan asserts that his own Nation of Islam is moving toward
traditional Islam, too, and that he seeks closer ties with all
groups ``not for evil but for love, not for hatred but in good,''
The Associated Press reported.
</P>
<P>
   The Nation of Islam now observes traditional Friday prayers and
fasts during the month of Ramadan. Also, the Nation now
acknowledges that the prophet Mohammed is the final prophet, not
Elijah Muhammad, the leader of the original separatist black Muslim
movement.
</P>
<P>
   But there were some snags in Sunday's peace effort.
</P>
<P>
   Farrakhan, who once called Judaism a ``gutter religion,'' said
nothing dastardly about Jews. But he allowed Rabbi Dovid Weiss, the
leader of a small fringe Orthodox Jewish group that opposes the
state of Israel, to speak.
</P>
<P>
   Weiss' group, known as Neturei Karta International, has the
extremely radical notion that the Holocaust was punishment for Jews
who created the state of Israel by secular means, rather than by
allowing it to be created by the hand of God through the promised
Messiah.
</P>
<P>
   And during a news conference the next day in which a Nation of
Islam leader was present, Weiss repeated his unpopular view that
most Jews today are not authentic Jews.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's Zionism, not Judaism,'' The Associated Press quoted Weiss
as saying. ``They are something which is an abomination of God. It
is a heresy of God.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Briskman, director of the Southwest Region of the
Anti-Defamation League of B'nai B'rith, said Farrakhan is just
changing tactics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of attacking Jews personally, he used a radical
element of the Hasidic movement to do his dirty work for him,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Briskman said his organization has taken a wait-and-see attitude
on Farrakhan's professed change of heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very suspicious when somebody claims they are changing
and then allows someone to attack Jews from his own podium,''
Briskman said.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi Ira Youdovin, executive director of the Chicago Board of
Rabbis, told reporters he was stunned by Farrakhan's decision to
allow the anti-Israel leader to speak.
</P>
<P>
   But Youdovin is willing to work with Farrakhan if the Nation of
Islam leader apologizes for past insults against the Jewish people.
</P>
<P>
   ``I might lose my job for saying so,'' Youdovin told the AP.
``But the Nation of Islam does a lot of good work in the black
community, too. It's a frustration not being able to participate
with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Farrakhan likely won't apologize for the appearance of the
anti-Israel leader. But many people of good will are praying that
Farrakhan's change of heart is sincere. What an impact he will make
for religious unity if his words of peace lead to action.
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Jones is religion editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7707, or e-mail:
jimjones(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
