<HEADER>
A5841 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-HOCKEY-COMMMENTARY-10     03-03 0708
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOCKEY-COMMMENTARY-1000(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SANCTIONED VIOLENCE IN HOCKEY RUINS A ONCE-CHERISHED RITE OF
BOYHOOD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIM MADIGAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One Sunday a few weeks ago, my 8-year-old son, Patrick, played
ice hockey (or a loose variation thereof) for the first time. He
proudly donned his new helmet, his new shoulder pads, shin and
elbow guards, his new skates, and took to the ice, stick in hand,
to chase after a puck with a couple of other kids his age. The
first time he shot the puck into the net, Patrick thrust his arms
toward the ice rink's ceiling, which is the way real hockey players
celebrate goals.
</P>
<P>
   It was an exhilarating day for him, as I was pretty sure it
would be, because it had been an exhilarating day for me 35 years
ago when I played hockey for the first time on a frozen pond in
Minnesota. For the balance of my childhood, that was how I spent my
winters, gathered with my buddies in subzero temperatures on
outdoor rinks, chasing pucks for hours, oblivious to frozen feet,
and earlobes, and noses, and fingers. Such was the force of the
game's hold on us. Each spring, when the ice melted, was a
sorrowful time.
</P>
<P>
   Then on that recent Sunday in Texas, the game was passed from
generation to generation, and in truth, my wife, Catherine,
deserves the credit. To me, hockey was the cherished ritual of
fishing hockey pucks out of snow banks on winter nights. To her,
hockey was the bloodthirsty thuggery of the professional game as it
was often portrayed on television.
</P>
<P>
   I think I was gradually able to convince her that hockey,
particularly as it was played by kids, was not that way, that
professional hooliganism was an aberration, that hockey was really
about speed and skill and camaraderie, and fierce competition
without the ugliness. So Catherine finally gave her blessing to
Patrick's participation, and on that recent Sunday, she was happy,
too, because her son was getting a chance to do something that he
loved, and that his father had loved before him.
</P>
<P>
   But her good feeling lasted only a few days, until Feb. 22, when
the National Hockey League and a player for the Boston Bruins named
Marty McSorley ruined everything. That night, my wife and I watched
a videotaped replay as McSorley nearly decapitated Vancouver's
Donald Brashear with a vicious two-handed swipe of the stick across
Brashear's head. Brashear tumbled to the ice beneath the blow,
unconscious. The image left us both nauseated and speechless. Tears
came to my wife's eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell you how much I don't want my son to play
hockey,'' she said a short time later.
</P>
<P>
   I wish I could dismiss her feelings as those of an
overprotective mother. But I can't. After seeing what we saw, on
top of all the other NHL nastiness over the years, I can't blame
her a bit. I do resent the National Hockey League, which condones
and perpetuates a culture of violence that ultimately led to
McSorley's grotesque attack. The NHL doesn't seem to realize that
kids emulate the pros, ``in all things.'' The NHL doesn't seem to
realize that the ugliness of the pro game, with McSorley now as its
poster child, threatens to deprive kids like my son of their chance
to play a wonderful sport. Yes. That I resent.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Since the McSorley incident, the National Hockey League has been
gagging on its own hypocrisy.
</P>
<P>
   The league quickly suspended McSorley for the rest of the
season, and decried the act as something that the NHL would not
tolerate. Missing from the statements of contrition, however, was
the fact that both McSorley, the perpetrator, and Brashear, the
victim, are hockey goons who make their living _ not with an
ability to skate, shoot and score _ but with their fists. In fact,
earlier in the same game, McSorley and Brashear had dropped their
gloves and bludgeoned each other. For this, there were no
suspensions or statements of contrition. Instead, the two were
allowed to dust themselves off, spend a few minutes in the penalty
box, and emerge to battle again. After the ill-fated game, McSorley
said that his intent was not to decapitate Brashear, merely to pick
a fight with him again. That, where the NHL is concerned, would
have been quite OK.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   Such is the code of justice in pro hockey. The NHL is the only
major sport (pro football, baseball and basketball being the
others) that tolerates such behavior. It seems that hockey fighting
is the rough legacy of the Canadian frontier, where the game began.
It survives in a more civil time, some NHL players, coaches and
officials maintain, as a sort of safety valve, allowing combatants
in the high-speed, volatile sport, to blow off steam.
</P>
<P>
   Without such an outlet, the laughably disingenuous argument
goes, there would actually be an increase in the type of atrocities
like the one perpetrated by McSorley.
</P>
<P>
   Yet fighting is not tolerated in American high school hockey, or
college hockey, or in the Olympics, or in Europe. As best we know,
decapitations at those levels are at a minimum.
</P>
<P>
   On the contrary, the real reason fighting is allowed, even
encouraged in professional hockey, is something else altogether: It
has to do with marketing. The NHL knows fighting appeals to our
darker natures, and darker natures sell tickets.
</P>
<P>
   OK. I'll admit to the perverse thrill of watching two NHL
heavyweights ``chucking knuckles,'' the same way I'll watch a
bullrider being gored, or a NASCAR driver smashed against a
retaining wall. The NHL knows the voyeur exists in us all, and the
league has not been able to resist perversities that have made
Jerry Springer and professional wrestling cultural phenomenons. So
the Marty McSorleys pair up with the Donald Brashears on a regular
basis in the NHL, and try to beat each other senseless. The crowd
roars, and officials wink, then profess shock and outrage when one
or the other gets carried away and commits aggravated assault, or
worse.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that my son has not shown any desire to ride
bulls, or drive race cars, or wrestle professionally. He does love
hockey. I would love for him to play, to have the same experiences
that I had. But now, where his mother is concerned, I find myself
in the position of defending the indefensible.
</P>
<P>
   For help I went to Ken Hitchcock, head coach of the Dallas
Stars. Hitchcock is a thoughtful, articulate man, who demands
fiercely competitive play from his players, but has little stomach
for the staged muggings that remain part of the game. On the
morning before a Stars contest against Chicago, I asked him to help
me convince my wife that it was a good idea for our son to become a
hockey player.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure,'' Hitchcock said, leaning back on a bench in the Stars'
locker room, obviously warming to the task. He spoke of the value
of belonging to a team, the exhilaration, the speed, the unique
energy of the game. But he seemed to understand my quandary and my
wife's concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if the game turns violent _ it's always going to be a
physical game _ but if it turns disrespectful, then there's no
place to play hockey,'' Hitchcock said. ``You can't play this game
if it turns the other way. It's a very emotional game. It's a
wonderful game, but it doesn't have a place for that. But if that's
the way the game's going, then I don't think a lot of people want
to be a part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Our tickets for the game between the Stars and the Chicago
Blackhawks were Christmas presents from Catherine to Patrick and
me. Our seats were just a few rows from the ice, and after watching
the McSorley attack, I could tell my wife had regretted her choice
of gifts. In her mind, we would be sitting close enough to be
splattered by blood if the game turned ugly. I promised her that
Patrick and I would leave Reunion Arena if that happened.
</P>
<P>
   But it didn't. Instead, the game was an advertisement for
everything that the NHL is, or at least could be, if they would
excise the game's criminal element. Sitting so close, the speed of
the game was breathtaking, the body contact often fierce, but
within the rules. The visiting team won in overtime, but everyone
in the disappointed crowd had been wildly entertained. My son left
the arena hoarse from yelling, and dreaming of the day when he
would dash down the ice like his hero, Stars superstar Mike Modano,
his sweater flapping in the breeze.
</P>
<P>
   And he will get his chance, at least for now. We will continue
to make our weekly trips to the ice rink after all. The joy of the
game as it is played by kids will continue to outweigh the
lawlessness of professional hockey that borders on the immoral. At
least that's my hope. My wife might feel differently.
</P>
<P>
   (Tim Madigan is a staff writer for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7544, or e-mail:
tmadigan(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
