<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SONG-SOPRANOS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOB HIT?: RADIO STATIONS WAKE UP TO SOPRANOS' THEME SONG
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   By now, it's possible that you've heard A3's ``Woke Up This
Morning,'' the theme song to the HBO series ``The Sopranos,'' even
if you don't have HBO. Not only is it on a terrific soundtrack
album that also includes cuts from Bob Dylan, Frank Sinatra and
Elvis Costello, it's starting to get airplay on radio stations.
</P>
<P>
   We like the song so much that we became curious about it,
wondering how it came to be ``The Sopranos'' theme song. Despite
this being a simple question, it took several phone calls before a
Columbia Records spokeswoman gave us the answer: ``Sopranos''
creator David Chase heard it one morning on KCRW, the public radio
station in Santa Monica, Calif. He hadn't even planned on using a
theme song for the series, but when he heard the A3 cut, he fell in
love with it, and it became the counterpoint to the opening titles
featuring Tony Soprano's long drive home.
</P>
<P>
   That's right, it's not a new song. It's been around longer than
``The Sopranos,'' even though it sounds as it were written just for
the series. We found out some other interesting things:
</P>
<P>
   A3 is a British group, whose full name is Alabama 3. It's a
large, odd, roots-rock-worshipping congregation led by the Rev. Dr.
D. Wayne Love. That could explain ``Woke Up This Morning's''
gospel-style chorus.
</P>
<P>
   The group was a buzz band at Austin's South by Southwest
festival in spring 1998 _ months before ``The Sopranos'' premiered.
A3 was supposed to be a big deal, but went nowhere. For a while,
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Woke Up This Morning'' first appeared on a 1998 album called
``Exile on Coldharbour Lane,'' released around the time of South by
Southwest. ``In six months, they'll either be big or gone,'' the
Fort Worth Star-Telegram's Malcolm Mayhew wrote about the group in
a review of the album. He praised the songs ``Ain't Goin' to Goa''
and ``U Don't Dans 2 Tekno Anymore'' but said nothing about ``Woke
Up This Morning.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only is ``Woke Up This Morning'' not new, it's not even a
new single. ``They worked it to radio before, and it got some
airplay _ but very little airplay,'' said Scott Strong, program
director of The Merge.
</P>
<P>
   The song has yet to show up on the Billboard Hot 100, even
though virtually everyone who hears it says it's really cool. It's
at No. 16 and rising on Radio &AMP; Records' adult-alternative chart.
``It's still comparatively early to judge how it's doing,'' Strong
says. ``The great thing is the reaction that it has from listeners
who are so into the show.''
</P>
<P>
   One fan is Jay Leno, who brought A3 across the Atlantic two
weeks ago just to sing ``Woke Up this Morning'' on ``The Tonight
Show.''
</P>
<P>
   A3 has quite a Web site (www.elemental.music.co.uk
/alabama3/index.htm), on which the group shows a distaste for
corporate rock. Funny, since the album ``Exile on Coldharbour
Lane'' was released by Geffen and the ``Sopranos'' soundtrack was
released by Sony _ and the TV series runs on Time-Warner's HBO.
Guess you can be corporate when it suits you.
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is pop culture critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7872, or e-mail:
robp(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-03-00 1612EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
