<DOCNO> NYT20000303.0157 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-03 16:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5846 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FILM-MADONNA-TEX     03-03 1118
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-MADONNA-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MADONNA'S GOT GUTS, STYLE, MUSICAL MOXIE ... BUT, GIRLFRIEND CAN'T
ACT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARK LOWRY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's not difficult to write an appreciation of Madonna the pop
star, Madonna the shrewd businessperson or Madonna the woman. No
matter how much you love or hate her, there's no denying that she's
a cultural force, a woman who continues to be a ray of light in
music, videos and all things fashionable.
</P>
<P>
   She has an inimitable ability to reinvent herself and to grow in
her artistic endeavors _ except acting.
</P>
<P>
   An appreciation of Madonna the actress is not so easy. And her
look-at-me-I'm-acting turn in ``The Next Best Thing'' doesn't help
her case. The movie is just more proof that acting is not even the
next, next, next best thing Madonna does.
</P>
<P>
   I had honestly hoped that I wouldn't have to say that. My love
affair with Madonna has been a roller-coaster ride. It always
seemed that just when she had created something worthwhile, she
followed it with something utterly mediocre, musically speaking.
But I always stuck with her.
</P>
<P>
   When she first burst onto the scene during the '80s, I was
cautiously fascinated. Fast-forward a little bit. I disliked the
``True Blue'' phase and the white, short 'do. I loved everything
about ``Like a Prayer'' _ the videos, the look, the
autobiographical songs and, ooh, the Pepsi controversy. I didn't
care for the ``I'm Breathless'' and ``Dick Tracy''/Warren Beatty
period, and hated the Vogue craze that soon smothered the gay
dance-club scene. I enjoyed ``Justify My Love'' and the very cool
remix of that song in which she quoted from the Book of Revelation.
Then, I passionately hated ``Erotica'' and the ``Sex'' book, and
later kind of dug ``Bedtime Stories,'' although I didn't buy the
album because I had stopped caring.
</P>
<P>
   Until the ``Human Nature'' video. The declarative last line of
that song, ``absolutely no regrets,'' was cause for more ``You go,
girl'' snaps than anything she had done before.
</P>
<P>
   Then came ``Evita,'' and the event that seemed to make the most
noticeable change in her yet: little Lourdes. Becoming a mother was
probably the best thing for her. Next she produced her most mature
and personal album to date, ``Ray of Light.'' Whereas ``Like a
Prayer'' _ which is still my favorite Madonna album because of the
time in my life it represented _ was deeply personal in that she
tried to exorcise the ghosts that had driven her to rule the world,
with ``Ray of Light'' she made peace with them and, ultimately,
with herself. Motherhood and an introspective exploration of her
spiritual side through yoga, Hinduism and the Cabala (Jewish
mysticism), played no small role in this.
</P>
<P>
   With ``Ray of Light,'' the girl was not material anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Drowned World/Substitute for Love,'' the first song on ``Ray
of Light'' begins ``I traded fame for love/Without a second
thought/It all became a silly game/Some things cannot be bought/Got
exactly what I asked for ... And now I find/I've changed my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Other songs on the album are equally representative of her
change, and the atmospheric techno touches by producer William
Orbit perfectly backdrop her words and new life outlook. In
``Shanti/Ashtangi'' she adapts text from the Yoga Taravali.
``Little Star'' is a loving ode to her child: ``God gave a present
to me/Made of flesh and bones ... You make my spirit whole/Never
forget who you are/Little Star.''
</P>
<P>
   With all this positive energy suddenly directed down an
enlightened path that made her seem more self-assured than ever, I
just knew her acting would improve. It had no where to go but up.
</P>
<P>
   And that brings us to the other side of her celebrity: her film
``career.''
</P>
<P>
   Hands down, the best movie she has starred in was ``Truth or
Dare,'' the expertly done documentary that followed her on her 1989
Blond Ambition tour. She, of course, was herself. No acting
involved. She wasn't bad in ``Desperately Seeking Susan,'' because
the title character ``was'' Madonna. In ``A League of Their Own''
and ``Dick Tracy'' she was decent, but those characters called for
overacting. There's no need to mention most the other films. I've
forgotten them, and you should, too.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was ``Evita.'' It was heralded as the highlight of
her acting career, and maybe it was, but that's not saying much.
She earned a Best Actress in a Comedy or Musical Golden Globe for
playing Eva Peron in Alan Parker's film version of the Andrew Lloyd
Webber musical. I think the movie was overrated, as was her
performance. She never really grasped the character. It was more
like a megastar had been asked to play an equally strong
personality, but couldn't give any humanity to the role because the
megastar had long stopped trying to be a real person.
</P>
<P>
   Still, ``Evita'' was a step forward. It was the closest she had
come to being a serious actress.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Next Best Thing'' could have been an opportunity to move
toward that goal. The film has some nice performances by a few
truly talented actors: Rupert Everett as the gay best friend, ``Law
&AMP; Order's'' Benjamin Bratt as the man who falls in love with
Madonna's character, and a brief appearance by Illeana Douglas as a
lawyer. It would be easy to say that playing next to such talent
highlighted her shortcomings. But an even bigger indicator of her
lack of acting finesse is that the movie is as exciting as a
backgammon match on television. Being surrounded by fine actors
does not a quality movie make, as Madonna should have learned in
``Body of Evidence,'' which co-starred Willem Dafoe.
</P>
<P>
   The character, Abbie, is even a little like Madonna. She's a
yoga instructor who loves gay men, and gay men love to love her
back.
</P>
<P>
   But every line she utters and every move she makes in ``The Next
Best Thing'' is so calculated it feels as if she's working on a big
chess board. She's convincing neither at physical comedy nor at
finding her pathos. This movie is proof that some people simply
don't have what it takes to be an actor.
</P>
<P>
   Let me just break character for a moment. Madonna: I love you. I
love your gumption. I love your success as a pop star, a mother and
trend-setter. I love the way you constantly challenge yourself. I
love ``Ray of Light,'' and I'm happy that you have finally found
yourself.
</P>
<P>
   But please, if you're going to star in another movie, make it a
documentary. The only character you excel at playing is yourself.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Lowry is a staff writer for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7747, or e-mail:
markl(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
