<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-03 16:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5851 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-PARIS-FASHION-ART-NYT     03-03 1316
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARIS-FASHION-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR THE COQUETTE WITH ASPIRATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By GINIA BELLAFANTE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Early in ``The Arcades Project,'' Walter Benjamin's
recently published 1,073-page study of mid-19th-century Parisian
habits, there is the following observation: ``Making money becomes
the object of an almost sensual fervor, and love becomes a
financial concern. In the age of French Romanticism, the erotic
ideal was the working girl who gives herself; now it is the tart
who sells herself.''
</P>
<P>
   The words are not Benjamin's but are quoted from a German
writer, Egon Friedell, who goes on to conclude that the paragon of
fashion during the Second Empire ``was the grande dame who becomes
the coquette.''
</P>
<P>
   If all this were unfamiliar to you, and you happened to find
yourself a contestant on some very rarefied version of ``Who Wants
to Be a Millionaire,''you might make an educated guess that the
quotations originated in the program notes of any of a dozen fall
2000 runway collections. That is, assuming that the program notes
were written by people who decided to abandon the usual drivel (``I
am. I am dawn. I am transparency.'') and to opt for musings meant
to telegraph what has, in fact, really driven the spirit of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   The fall 2000 shows come to a close in Paris on Friday. By now
journalists and buyers have looked at women in heels and tight,
needle-wide skirts, or swaddled in fur, or draped with streams of
gold chains across bare breasts in four cities on two continents
over 27 days. In and out of taxis, from one show to another,
there's been a lot of chatter about the season's celebration of
money, but less about the tribute being paid to one kind of woman
who pursues it. The coquette, as Friedell would put it, who wants
to be a grande dame.
</P>
<P>
   This particular message blared the loudest at the Celine show
here on Tuesday night, where the theme music to ``Dallas,''
``Dynasty'' and ``Lifestyles of the Rich and Famous'' played. The
problematic notes handed out before the show indicated that the
muses here were ``stylish gamines from Leslie Caron to Chloe
Sevigny.'' One could no sooner imagine Sevigny _ who was recently
nominated for an Oscar and whose cool first came to the attention
of fashion editors when she was a downtown fixture wearing socks
with flip-flops like a Sicilian grandfather _ strutting about in
Celine's denim trousers with a built-in gold-chain belt, or in a
leopard jersey dress, than one could picture Patti Smith knocking
on the door of Nancy Reagan's closet.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Kors, who designs the Celine line, took the signifiers
of wealth that are so trendy again _ herringbone, chevrons, blanket
plaids _ and cheapened them on purpose, one guesses, to appeal to
his own sense of camp fun. But nothing about the show felt like
fun. All that jumbling of sex and social ambition called to mind
Annette Bening in ``American Beauty,'' literally trying to vacuum
away her middle-class life in her slip and pumps.
</P>
<P>
   Those who ventured to Veronique Branquinho's show immediately
afterward experienced relief. A Belgian, Branquinho generally holds
her Paris shows in gloomy places so far from the city center that
they might as well be in Brussels, and she has generally paid
little heed to what other designers might be doing. This time,
however, she showed at the Ecole des Beaux-Arts on the Left Bank, a
spot with all the romance its name implies. She worked with many of
the same signifiers of the good life that Kors and others have
appropriated: houndstooth, used on thick wool sweaters, and glen
plaid, cut into trousers in a perfectly fitting hourglass shape.
But she stripped them of their banality.
</P>
<P>
   Branquinho turned out trench coats with rich, contrasting lapels
and cut them long and narrow. Gone was the swishy ``I'm running to
Le Cirque and then to my collagen injection'' effect. She showed
chevron-pattern skirts, but cut on an A-line and worn over skinny
pants.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was probably thinking, This is how my mother dressed in
the '70s and this is how I'm going to do it,'' said Michel Botbol,
creative director of Harper's Bazaar, who was raving about
Branquinho's show as he awaited the start of the Chloe show on
Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Botbol was also one of the first to notice that seated in the
front row was that rare celebrity one doesn't expect to see at a
fashion show, Jerry Seinfeld. Seinfeld was with his new wife,
Jessica Sklar. Asked what he was doing at a Paris fashion show, he
responded, ``I couldn't stay away any longer,'' in a kind of
fatigued monotone.
</P>
<P>
   Seinfeld got to witness much of what Stella McCartney, Chloe's
designer, does best. She had exquisite tops with 1920s-inspired
beadwork splaying from the collar. She ventured beyond her
signature girlishness too, with military-inspired coats thrown over
short silk Jacquard print dresses. Skinny jeans paired with high
heels are another of McCartney's trademark looks. It never looks
trashy in her hands, perhaps because it is a look plucked from her
own world of well-bred young Londoners. Still, she could have
benefited from showing fewer jeans this time around.
</P>
<P>
   At the Emanuel Ungaro show a few hours later, McCartney's
influence was hard to miss. He included a top made only of gold
chains, as McCartney did last season and so many other designers
have done since. And there were plenty of jeans and heels, and
models in aviator glasses.
</P>
<P>
   At his young age, Alexander McQueen, who scooted out at the end
of his show for Givenchy in a baggy denim jumpsuit, has a greater
claim to bad 1980s rock references than Ungaro does. Still, there
was little excuse for what he produced on Wednesday: blazers worn
as dresses over skinny ties, patent leather miniskirts that fitted
like swaths of tinfoil, an endless array of leather leg warmers
worn on just one leg, which reminded one of a controversial shoot
Helmut Newton did for Vogue in which he fixed braces to his model's
limbs. McQueen's show didn't come off as subversive, however; it
came off like the stuff 10th graders shop for on Eighth Street in
Greenwich Village. The clothes were poorly styled as well. Dark
hose and white shoes, the worst of all glamour don'ts, did not
achieve any sense of purposeful hip.
</P>
<P>
   If uptown shopkeepers, or any shopkeepers for that matter, found
little to meet their needs at Givenchy, they were to find little,
either, at Christian Lacroix, who despite all his gifts seemed to
be designing for a country of one: Bette Davis, in ``What Ever
Happened to Baby Jane?'' There were clownishly cut pants and models
with painted apple-red cheeks and oversize plastic bows in their
hair.
</P>
<P>
   Retailers are grateful for designers like Dries van Noten, who
turned out an inspired collection of full funneled skirts in mohair
and printed silk, tweed coats over sequined dresses and other coats
with playful ballooned lapels.
</P>
<P>
   Another Belgian, Olivier Theyskens, had some mishaps at his show
on Monday, which began inauspiciously 90 minutes after it was
supposed to. Theyskens is experimenting passionately, if not
altogether spectacularly, at the moment. He turned out some
questionable to-the-knee black leather parkas gathered at the
sides, which seemed to be designed for those with a need to scratch
their thighs. His high point, though, came in the form of
crinolined hoop skirts, which were striking for their vastness,
though he cut some of them too long, and as a result made the
models stumble.
</P>
<P>
   Theyskens said he worked on one of them, a green velvet version,
with the help of 10 friends. ``It's really like a tent,'' he said
of his creation. Despite his mistakes, it's hard not to give him a
break. ``I should go camping in it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-03-00 1617EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
