<P>
   MOZAMBIQUE-FLOOD (Dateline to kum, Mozambique) _ Developments on
the continuing rescue of thousands of people trapped in trees and
on rooftops by floodwaters. By Rachel Swarns.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   BOSNIA-TRIBUNAL (Paris) _ The international tribunal for the
former Yugoslavia in The Hague on Friday sentenced the highest
ranking military commander brought to trial to date for war crimes
during the Balkan conflict. The court sentenced the Croatian
commander, Gen. Tihomir Blaskic, to 45 years in prison for ordering
brutal attacks on Muslim villagers in Bosnia between 1992 and 1994
while his forces were trying to secure the area for Croatia. It was
the harshest sentence handed down by the tribunal since its
creation by the United Nations in 1993. By Marlise Simons.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   REPUBS-NY (New York) _ John McCain and George W. Bush brought
their intense fight for the Republican nomination to New York on
Friday with Bush accusing McCain of shortchanging breast cancer
research and McCain charging his presidential rival was seeking to
``hijack the campaign'' with big money. Bush turned to the pillars
of Republican power in New York in an effort to snuff McCain's
insurgent campaign, but there was controversy even there. Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani was resisting the McCain-bashing efforts of Gov.
George Pataki and other GOP state leaders. By Adam Nagourney and
Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   With photos of McCain, NYT6, and BUSH.
</P>
<P>
   INDEPENDENT-ADS (Washington) _ Developing. A Texas businessman
who is one of Gov. George W. Bush's biggest campaign contributors
said Friday that he had paid for $2 million in television
commercials airing in New York and other primary states that
criticized Sen. John McCain and promoted Bush's record on clean
air. The businessman, Sam Wyly, who recently sold a software
company he co-owned for $3.9 billion and has close ties to many
other Bush supporters, said he and his family had paid for the
advertising to draw attention to environmental issues. But McCain's
aides flatly accused the Bush campaign of being behind the
advertising, and labeled the commercials a scurrilous attempt to
evade campaign finance laws and steal the election. By Richard W.
Stevenson and Clifford J. Levy.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-PROPOSITIONS (Los Angeles) _ On television and radio, the
pitch is made relentlessly. Every commercial break brings another
political come-on. But most of the time, it isn't the governor of
Texas or the senator from Arizona, the vice president of the United
States or the former New Jersey senator that they are asking you to
vote for. It's Yes or No. The 30-second spot clock never seems to
stop, whether it is for Indian gambling or against insurance
reform, in favor of clean water or opposed to gay marriage. So many
groups, in fact, are elbowing for television time to broadcast
their positions on one of the 20 initiatives and referendums on the
California ballot, that they are all but drowning out the political
advertising by the presidential candidates. By Peter Marks.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   ECON-REPORT (Undated) _ Job growth suddenly weakened in
February, the Labor Department reported Friday, but there were few
indications that the unexpected slowdown in job creation pointed to
a serious softening of the economic boom. ``I don't think there is
anything in this report that shows the economy is weakening,'' said
Alexis Herman, the labor secretary. Like various private
economists, she pointed to unusually warm weather in early January,
which caused a surge in jobs in construction and a few other
sectors _ and these jobs disappeared in the colder February
weather. But stock market investors took the report as a sign that
the Federal Reserve may not have to raise interest rates quite as
much in order to brake an economy that appears to slowing on its
own. The Dow Jones industrial average rose 188 points, or 1.8
percent. By Louis Uchitelle.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``s'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   WATCHING-TIGER (Undated) _ When Tiger Woods plays golf,
television executives swoon. With his rare power to move ratings,
he is the sports version of ``E.R.'' or ``Who Wants To Be a
Millionaire,'' a singular, 24-year-old programming entity capable
of clubbing rival networks in their Nielsens in his pursuit of
tournament victories. Woods doesn't have to win. He simply needs a
chance at victory to stir viewers to watch. When he's out of
contention, or not playing, ratings for PGA Tour events are strong,
but not as formidable; players like Jeff Maggert, David Duval, Phil
Mickelson or Vijay Singh just don't carry the same weight. Woods
has become what Michael Jordan's appearances with the Chicago Bulls
once meant to NBC's National Basketball Association broadcasts: a
guarantee of higher ratings than any other team and a surefire
reason to ooh and ahh. By Richard Sandomir.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CRIME-RATES (New York) _ With the city's stunning drop in crime
in the 1990s, many New Yorkers have come to assume that aggressive
police tactics and crime reductions are inextricably linked. But a
look at other cities around the nation suggests that large
reductions in crime can be achieved with less reliance on the kinds
of confrontational law enforcement measures New York has used. In
fact, some cities, notably San Diego and Boston, have recorded as
big or even larger drops in violence through strategies that rely
on close cooperation between the police and the community and have
ended up improving race relations. By Fox Butterfield.
</P>
