<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-03 16:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5867 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-NY-SPORTS-CLUB-$ADV05     03-03 1050
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SPORTS-CLUB-$ADV05-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE JADED MUSCLES EXERCISE THEIR OPTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, March 5)  
(lh) 
 By ALEX WITCHEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After spending seven hours at the new Sports Club/LA
at Rockefeller Center, I think I burned all of 50 calories, most of
them saying ``thank you.'' Despite its jock-like name, this place
comes closer to matching its publicity agents' billing as ``an
urban country club'' than a gym. But it certainly surpasses any
country club I ever visited, growing up in Scarsdale, where there
were two kinds: the Protestant ones with overstocked bars and
crummy food, and the Jewish ones with understocked bars and yummy
food. Both had the type of help whose manner hovered between
diffident and resentful.
</P>
<P>
   The Sports Club/LA, all 90,000 square feet of it, cost $20
million to build and has turned the gym into a mini-resort where
fitness doesn't have to be the top priority. Members can shop on
the stationary bikes and get highlights at the salon or Botox shots
from the on-site dermatologist, or sip martinis with a prime view
of the ice skaters. Convenience and service rule here: A concierge
will get you into Daniel for dinner, and a massage therapist will
apply your self-tanning lotion. To call this place a gym is like
calling the Four Seasons a hostel.
</P>
<P>
   Owned by the same company that owns the Reebok Sports Club/NY on
the Upper West Side, and the Sports Club/LA that is to open next
summer on the Upper East Side at the old Vertical Club, this branch
is teeming with crisp, professional help, each employee more
cheerful than the next.
</P>
<P>
   Good cheer doesn't come cheap, of course, especially in New
York. An executive membership, the top of the line plan, means a
$2,400 initiation fee and monthly charge of $330 (privileges
include personalized laundry service and membership at all New York
branches, the Sports Club/LA in Los Angeles and the others
scheduled to open soon in Washington, Houston, San Francisco,
Boston and Miami). The less deluxe membership entails a $1,200
initiation fee and a $180 monthly charge. Spa and salon services
are extra _ but who's counting?
</P>
<P>
   What's remarkable about millennial New York of course, is the
number of people who seem to have no shortage of time or money and
are so starved for activities they are clamoring to fill these
luxury monoliths. Rande Coleman, an executive at Douglas Elliman &AMP;
Associates, signed up for the East Side branch six months ago.
``It's an urban situation where you can literally spend a day with
unlimited options,'' she said excitedly. ``It's like day camp.''
</P>
<P>
   The East Side branch promises to be even more imposing, with a
rooftop terrace encompassing a driving range and tennis courts,
five squash courts, meditation gardens and a 15,000-square-foot
weight training gym, which the company says will probably be the
largest weight room in the country.
</P>
<P>
   I have to say, I haven't belonged to a gym in years. I got sick
of waiting in line for the treadmill, sick of changing my schedule
to go at off-peak hours, only to have a workman spray the mirror in
front of me with Windex, as if I weren't there, sick of musclehead
guys in the weight room taking up all the space and drenching every
bench with sweat they barely bothered to towel off.
</P>
<P>
   So I thought I would play at being one of the not-so-idle rich
and instead of just working out, ``spend the day at the club.''
Though the afternoon I chose was on a deserted holiday weekend, I
could tell that no workmen were brandishing Windex and no member
needed to hog anything. There seemed to be miles of machines, many
hooked up to Netpulse, which means you can check your e-mail or
shop on eBay while working out; my favorite part though, is that
once you have your password, every minute you spend on the machine
accrues to a Netpulse account that rewards you with frequent flier
miles. Talk about incentive!
</P>
<P>
   I discovered quickly that the drawback of Netpulse is that it
won't work unless you, the exerciser, are in movement. I valiantly
tried to shop for dresses at Bloomingdale's while pumping away on
the Precor, an elliptical Stairmaster, but gasping for air made it
hard to concentrate.
</P>
<P>
   Charleene O'Connor, who trains the trainers here and showed me
around, graciously offered to pedal for me so I could shop, which I
did for about a minute before I was overcome by guilt.
</P>
<P>
   We moved on to another form of virtual exercise, the interactive
class video. This means you push a button and watch a clip of an
exercise class so you can decide if you would like it. I shunned
Extreme Games, described as ``military style'' calisthenics,
preferring Candlelight Stretch, in which people gather in a
darkened room with candles and a guitarist. (Kumbaya, my Lord?)
</P>
<P>
   Thoroughly exhausted from watching other people exercise, I made
my way past the Pilates studio and a boxing class to the office of
Vicki Poth, the director of spa operations. The Splash spa is open
to the public, as is the Splash salon, and it is possible to
schedule a full day's activities for any event, including, say, a
bachelor party complete with barber shaves for the boys.
</P>
<P>
   Poth introduced me to Dr. Steven Victor, a cosmetic
dermatologist affiliated with Lenox Hill Hospital, who is on the
club's staff.
</P>
<P>
   He suggested I get a laser facial to ``rejuvenate the skin,'' a
process he described as ``vaporizing the outer layer of skin.''
This would cost $200, and most of his patients, he said, get one
every six to eight weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``You like to squint,'' he continued. ``I would recommend
Botox.''
</P>
<P>
   When I objected to the idea of injecting botulism near my brain,
he scoffed, and went on to recommend electrostimulation for my
facial muscles once a week for 10 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   I shook my head firmly. ``You do your hair, right?'' he asked.
``Why wouldn't you do your face?''
</P>
<P>
   Well, I told him, lately, I've actually been looking at my face
as a sort of science experiment as it shifts into unforeseen
formations of lines, bags, puffs and creases. It fascinates me
enough to wait and see what happens next. Maybe one day it'll
sprout rings, like Saturn.
</P>
<P>
   His face stayed blank, but that could be because of his own
Botox shots, which he had readily admitted.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   I took my squinty eyes down to the spa and got ready for an
endermologie treatment. This is a machine equivalent of cellulite
massage, and Diana, my therapist, gave me a pair of nylon Dr.
Dentons to protect my skin. She applied what looked like a vacuum
cleaner attachment to my hips and behind, which actually felt
relaxing, and I drifted off once or twice. (P.S. Afterward, the
skin looked exactly the same, though it supposedly takes weeks
before you see a change).
</P>
<P>
   Another therapist, Danielle, appeared soon after to administer
the silliest procedure of the day, the ``self-tan.'' She applied
some freezing exfoliating lotion to my arms and legs, and though
she wiped most of it off before applying Sothys Self-Tanning Lotion
(the brand they use on ``Baywatch,'' she said), I still felt some
sandy granules mixed in with the tan. Then she massaged my head and
feet, hard, and left, by my watch at least, five minutes before the
appointed time.
</P>
<P>
   Before going to the hair salon for my blow-out, I stopped by the
concierge to have her phone in a take-out order from a nearby
Chinese restaurant, so I could pick it up on my way home.
</P>
<P>
   Hanan, the stylist, who was wearing a tie with the Mona Lisa on
it, proclaimed, ``I see a smooth, polished look for you.'' When he
was done I had stick-straight hair that ended in a flip with some
long bangs in front. I looked like Sissy Spacek in ``Coal Miner's
Daughter.''
</P>
<P>
   I went to the Martini Bar to meet my sister for a drink, and she
tried not to laugh. As we nibbled on steak tartare in the Pulse Bar
&AMP; Grill, run by Drew Nieporent of Nobu, the concierge came in and
said I could pick up my food in half an hour.
</P>
<P>
   I left the building feeling thoroughly cosseted and comforted.
After dinner, I took off my clothes and started to laugh. The
self-tan, which takes four hours to set, was in full bloom, but its
application left something to be desired. Long white triangles
stood out on my thighs where apparently Danielle had missed, and
one heel was bright orange. So much for ``Baywatch.'' I looked like
a Picasso.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, if I had still been at the club, all I would have had
to do was snap my fingers and someone would run to fix it. But I
was home now. I would just have to wait for it to self-fade, all on
its own.
</P>
<P>
   Pity.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
