 Attn: Style and Leisure Editors:  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service plans the following articles
from the Style section for use Sunday, March 5, and thereafter. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GALLERY-ART-QUEEN (New York) _ The sleek crowd grew restive at
the opening late last month at Mary Boone's Fifth Avenue gallery,
but Boone was nowhere in sight. At exactly 6 p.m., Boone emerged
from her office. She was dressed expressly to complement one of the
paintings _ a Valentine-themed work full of swirly frosting and
candy hearts printed with messages like ``Hug Me'' _ in a
rose-print Todd Oldham frock and red python stilettos. It was easy
to see in the outfit not only a vote of confidence for Will Cotton,
the latest in a wave of young painters Boone is once again
championing. It was a vote, too, for Boone herself, for whom life
has started to seem oh-so-sweet again. The flamboyant dealer once
known as the Queen of SoHo, who moved uptown in the mid-1990s after
the scene she helped ignite had flared out, is working hard to
reinvent herself. By Nancy Hass. WITH PHOTO. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NY-SPORTS-CLUB (New York) _ The Sports Club/LA, all 90,000
square feet of it, cost $20 million to build and has turned the gym
into a mini-resort where fitness doesn't have to be the top
priority. Members can shop on the stationary bikes and get
highlights at the salon or Botox shots from the on-site
dermatologist, or sip martinis with a prime view of the ice
skaters. Convenience and service rule here: a concierge will get
you into Daniel for dinner and a massage therapist will apply your
self-tanning lotion. To call this place a gym is like calling the
Four Seasons a hostel. By Alex Witchel. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SABBAH-FASHION (New York) _ Da House of Sabbah, a clothing store
in Manhattan, owned by Claude Sabbah, 47, is a favorite with
underground fashion editors, ghetto-fabulous rappers and art-world
style icons wanting to preen. While he calls himself a couturier,
his clothes, at $500 to $2,000, cost a fraction of the real
couture. Customers pick out clothing samples hanging on racks that
Sabbah, who was born in Morocco, fabricates on a made-to-order
basis. By Elizabeth Hayt. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NY-CATS-MUSICAL (New York) _ Residents of Manhattan have scorned
Andrew Lloyd Webber's most famous musical ``Cats'' for years, but
how many of them have actually seen it? The news that after 18
years, the show will close on June 24 presents a unusual problem
for the jaded among us. On the one hand, there's the impulse to
ridicule or ignore the very tourist traps of which ``Cats'' is the
apogee. On the other, there's a nagging need to have seen and done
it all. In my case, the second instinct won out. And so, last
Sunday afternoon, four of us found ourselves behind the big
billboard eyes of the Wintergarden Theater doing the unthinkable. I
think it was an experience none of us will soon forget. By Rick
Marin. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NITEOUT-WOODLAWN (New York) _ Born Harold Danhakl, 1946.
Transformed into Holly Woodlawn in 1969, when Andy Warhol asked for
a last name. ``We were watching this episode of `I Love Lucy,'''
she said, ``and behind her was this sign on the No. 4 train,
`Woodlawn,' and we said: `That's it. Holly ... Wood. Holly
Woodlawn.'' She became the scene-stealing transvestite in Paul
Morrissey's ``Trash.'' Now, the movie, and Holly, are being rolled
out for a 30th-anniversary appearance. (``Trash'' opens March 17 in
Manhattan and in Los Angeles.) Thursday found her at
Bloomingdale's, all man, in a camel's hair jacket, khakis, yellow
sweater and fedora for an early lunch at Le Train Bleu with Karin
Lefler, in from San Francisco, who runs the Web site
hollywoodlawn.com. By Linda Lee. WITH PHOTO. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-COLUMN (Undated) _ Kumquat is among the hardiest citrus _
it can take temperatures to 15 degrees Fahrenheit _ and part of
that hardiness is because of the long winter's rest into which it
settles. Like other citrus, kumquat is a pretty sight all year
round, with glossy, evergreen leaves that provide a perfect
backdrop for the waxy white, sweet-smelling flowers. The fruit is
what makes kumquat stand out from the citrus crowd. You can eat
only the pulp of oranges and grapefruit, and for the most part, use
only the juice of a lemon or a lime. Kumquats can be eaten skin and
all. By Lee Reich. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
