<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BUSH TESTS HISPANIC VOTER APPEAL IN CALIFORNIA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (For release Sunday, March 5.)   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By Dan Freedman  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHULA VISTA, Calif. _ For George W. Bush, Tuesday's California
primary is a crucial test not only in his battle against John
McCain for the Republican nomination but also in his effort to show
he can attract the traditionally Democratic Latino vote.
</P>
<P>
   One day last week Bush demonstrated his techniques in trying to
appeal to the group by going to a largely Hispanic gathering at the
Clear View Charter School here just north of San Diego. He answered
questions asked in Spanish and called himself ``Jorge Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   In addressing about 75 parents, he spoke in English although he
often uses Spanish before such groups. He boasted about his
education initiatives in Texas that he said had raised the test
scores of minorities. He also said he won nearly half of the
Hispanic vote in his 1998 re-election as Texas governor, not
mentioning some estimates pegging his share at 39 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like him because I think he looks out for minorities,
Latinos, and I really look for people like that,'' said one of he
parents, Lorna Mena.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign is spending around $3 million on television
and radio in California, which will send a whopping 162 delegates
to the Republican National Convention in Philadelphia this summer.
About a quarter of the $3 million is going to Hispanic TV and radio
outlets in the state, ``more than any other Republican Presidential
effort has spent,'' said one senior Bush adviser, who asked not to
be identified.
</P>
<P>
   McCain is not conceding the state's Hispanic vote. But so far
the senator has not advertised on any Spanish-language outlet in
California, and the Spanish-language branch of his Web site _
``Vamos con McCain'' went operational only in the last few days.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's matter of resources,'' said McCain spokeswoman Heather
Mirjahangir.
</P>
<P>
   McCain won 55 percent of the Hispanic vote in Arizona in his
last re-election bid in 1998, and he has been endorsed by the
Washington-based Hispanic Business Roundtable and by the Latino Los
Angeles County sheriff, Lee Baca.
</P>
<P>
   Among voters generally, Bush has run as much as 21 points ahead
of McCain in California polls. So his reaching out to Hispanics now
is less about winning the California primary than winning
California in November if he gets the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush effort ``is one that says the Latino vote is critical,
and we're not going to wait until the fall,'' said Lionel Sosa,
whose San Antonio-based advertising and marketing firm is producing
Bush's Spanish-language California radio and TV ads.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Bush has not locked up the Hispanic vote.
</P>
<P>
   Registration among Latinos skyrocketed in the past decade from 4
percent of California's electorate in 1990 to 14 percent in 1998,
according to Mark Baldassare, survey director of the Public Policy
Institute of California, a San Francisco-based nonpartisan research
group. Of those, 63 percent are Democratic and 23 percent are
Republican.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers are a direct result of ballot initiatives backed by
former Republican Gov. Pete Wilson. Proposition 187 in 1994 barred
undocumented immigrants from using taxpayer-funded services such as
hospitals and schools. It was challenged in court and found
unconstitutional. Proposition 209 in 1996 ended affirmative action
hiring, contracting and admissions programs in state institutions.
And Proposition 227 in 1998 severely restricted bilingual education
in public schools.
</P>
<P>
   Bitterness over these measures lingers. ``There was a sense of
immigrant bashing, and it would be a problem if Bush basically
followed the same pattern as Pete Wilson,'' said Bertha Wilson, a
Chula Vista School Board member.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question that there are some open wounds here
between leaders of the Republican Party and the Hispanic
population,'' said Alixe Mattingly, Bush's California spokeswoman.
However, Mattingly insisted Bush can overcome the legacy of
bitterness.
</P>
<P>
   The governor often mentions the good relations his family has
had with Hispanics and notes that his brother, Gov. Jeb Bush of
Florida, is married to a Mexican American, Columba Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, George W. Bush took part in a town meeting televised
by the Spanish-language television network, Univision, that was
</P>
<P>
   staged in Los Angeles and wired into four other locations around
the state. Bush answered questions in Spanish, and, Mattingly said,
his performance ``was a home run.''
</P>
<P>
   But the response of Hispanic voters remains in doubt. A poll by
Baldassare's Public Policy Institute of California showed that 40
percent of Hispanics said they might vote for Bush vote in
November. That would be a stunning contrast to 1996 when GOP
candidate Bob Dole got 28 percent of the Latino vote to President
Bill Clinton's 65 percent.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, a Los Angeles Times poll that showed Bush
ahead of McCain 47 percent to 26 percent overall also found that 52
percent of Hispanic voters have an unfavorable impression of Bush
while 56 percent have a favorable impression of McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Prominent Hispanic Democrats in California are not ceding an
inch of turf to Bush. ``He may speak some Spanish, but I don't
think that's going to be enough in Calfornia,'' said California
Assembly Speaker Antonio Villaragosa. ``He is out of sync (with
Latinos) on health care, out of sync on gun control, and his
tax-cut plan would jeopardize Social Security and Medicare. The
vast majority of California's electorate would oppose any plan that
did that, especially Latino voters.''
</P>
<P>
   Villaragosa added that Bush has moved ``farther and farther to
right, associating himself with elements of the (Republican) Party
who have been immigrant scapegoaters.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush has said he opposes the ``spirit'' of Proposition 187
barring undocumented immigrants from most social services. But
regarding Proposition 209, he has said, ``I support the spirit of
no quotas and no preferences.'' He has been unenthusiastic about
bilingual education. At the Chula Vista meeting, he said children
should master English first and focus on other languages if
possible. Some parents disagreed, saying bilingual education would
prepare their youngsters for the new free-trade economy where
mastery of both English and Spanish is a resume enhancer.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, many of the parents said they would keep an open
mind about Bush. ``We're not all thinking about only voting for a
Democrat,'' said Ana Talavera, a Democrat whose question prompted
Bush's discussion of bilingual education. ``We're not in a box. We
don't want to be a one-size-fits-all.''
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Freedman can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address dan(at)earstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-03-00 1652EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
