A5889 &Cx1f; ttg-z
u w BC-SOUTHERN-EXPOSURE-COL     03-03 0856
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTHERN-EXPOSURE-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 (Eds: Southern Exposure is the weekly political notebook from the
Washington Bureau of the New York Times Regional Newspapers) &HT;    
 &HT;     GEARING UP FOR ELECTION, LAWMAKERS HIT BRAKES ON HILL ACTION 
 &HT;    
 By CARL HULSE and SEAN LOUGHLIN  
NYT Regional Newspapers  
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With their eyes on the elections less than eight
months away, congressional leaders have apparently decided less is
more when it comes to legislating.
</P>
<P>
   Since the new year began, House and Senate members have spent
less than half their time on Capitol Hill in active session.
Republicans, who hold the majority in both chambers, have set a
light schedule for the remainder of the year. They want to adjourn
by early October to allow lawmakers opportunity to campaign, and
they're working in plenty of breaks before then.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats are griping that Congress isn't doing its job.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very frustrating to me that we're not getting our work
done,'' said Sen. John Edwards, D-N.C., citing the paucity of votes
in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Pushing for Congress to take up the issue of expanding Medicare
to include a prescription drug benefit for senior citizens,
Democratic leaders have taken to mocking Republicans for the
schedule. Citing the numerous proclamations and resolutions that
Congress considers each week, Sen. Tom Daschle, the minority
leader, cited some recent honors.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're celebrating national ``On Hold Month'' and national
``Procrastinators Week'' by doing what they do best - nothing,''
Daschle said.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans say it's not unusual for Congress to adopt a lighter
schedule during a presidential election year. And they say they're
being judged by President Clinton's agenda, which they have no
interest in tackling.
</P>
<P>
   GOP leaders are pushing for such items as relief from a marriage
tax penalty and repealing the Social Security earnings limit, which
the House recently passed.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, meanwhile, are pushing their own agenda, citing the
need for stronger gun control, a raise in the minimum wage and
advocating a patients' bill of rights.
</P>
<P>
   To some extent, both sides see an advantage in highlighting
these issues and letting the voters decide in November which party
should take the lead in resolving these disputes.
</P>
<P>
   CARPAL TUNNEL VISION
</P>
<P>
   Southern Republicans are feeling ignored by the Occupational
Safety &AMP; Health Administration.
</P>
<P>
   A group of top GOP House members wrote the head of OSHA, asking
that he schedule a public hearing on controversial new workplace
ergonomics rules somewhere in the Sunbelt. Sessions are now planned
only for Washington, Portland and Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   The letter from GOP Whip Tom DeLay of Texas and Rep. Dan Miller
of Florida among others asked that OSHA ``consider adding a hearing
in the Southern region of the U.S. to give all Americans a chance
to express their views on the proposal.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans contend that OSHA's voluminous 1,200-page regulation
would put employers in a bind if they had to comply with all the
provisions to ease repetitive motion disorder. They say OSHA is
deliberately avoiding the South to concentrate on more welcoming
locations with a strong labor presence.
</P>
<P>
   DRILLING FOR VOTES
</P>
<P>
   Conflicts on offshore oil and gas exploration apparently won't
determine this presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   Despite rising energy prices, all the chief presidential
candidates have signaled they won't try to boost drilling in waters
off states where the public resistance to such activity runs deep.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., was the latest to weigh in, saying
during an ABC interview that ``I think that we should allow these
decisions ... to be made by the people who are directly affected by
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Texans want offshore oil drilling,'' he said. ``That's fine
with me. Off Florida, they don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush has already sided with his brother,
Florida Gov. Jeb Bush, in resisting drilling there and Vice
President Al Gore has said that not only does he oppose new
drilling, but that he would move to block activity on existing
leases off Florida and North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   DUBIOUS ACHIEVEMENT
</P>
<P>
   Four Southern water projects have made a Top 10 list, but it is
a list of civil works jobs deemed wasteful by a taxpayers group.
</P>
<P>
   As prime examples of pouring money down the drain, Taxpayers for
Common Sense cited a $200 million Mississippi Delta flood
prevention effort, jetties costing $108 on the Oregon Inlet in
North Carolina, the annual $20 million dredging of the Apalachicola
River for limited barge traffic in Florida, Georgia and Alabama,
and the deepening of the Savannah, Ga., harbor at a cost of $230
million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Taxpayers should be outraged by this flagrant misuse of their
money,'' said Ralph DeGennaro, head of the taxpayers group, which
issued the report in cooperation with the National Wildlife
Federation.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the cited projects, of course, believe they are
all worthy and justifiable.
</P>
<P>
   (Carl Hulse and Sean Loughlin write from the Washington Bureau
of the New York Times Regionals.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
