<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Saturday, March 4, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(jt) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL FORECAST &LR;
</P>
<P>
   An area of cool rain will slide east across parts of the
Carolinas in concert with a surface low pressure system and a
pocket of high-altitude cold air trailing just to the west. The
cold pocket will sag south over portions of south Georgia and
northern Florida Saturday afternoon, setting the stage for widely
separated showers and thunderstorms, a few with brief, moderately
heavy rain. Low clouds will linger west of the system over parts of
the southern Appalachians, with clouds breaking later Saturday over
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Isolated showers and thunderstorms will affect spots in the
Southwest States as a cold low pressure in the upper atmosphere
spirals sluggishly east from the offshore waters of Baja
California. Farther north, generally light to occasionally moderate
rains will dampen the Pacific Northwest, with rains spreading east
of the Cascades in Washington and Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   A warming trend will continue across the Middle West as a warm
region of high pressure ridges northward from Texas. Warmth will
build eastward Sunday, embracing much of the Mississippi,
Tennessee, and Ohio River Valleys. Warmth will also build into the
Southeast States Sunday in the wake of Saturday's low pressure
system.
</P>
<P>
   Generally light snow will fall in parts of northern Maine early
Saturday in the unsettled wake of a low pressure system over the
Canadian Maritimes. The strong winds that buffeted parts of New
England Friday will ease Saturday as the low pulls farther away to
the northeast. Saturday night will not be as chilly as Friday night
across the region.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: Gentle Winter
</P>
<P>
   Winters can be bitter in the northern Plains where northerly
winds direct arctic cold from the Canadian tundra. But, the most
recent winter has been exceptionally gentle. In Sioux Falls, S.D.,
the period from December through February was the eighth warmest
since records began in 1892. The coldest day in Sioux Falls was
December 20 when the mercury reached 11 degrees. On average, in
seven out of ten winters the temperature stays below zero on at
least one day. This past winter was dominated by winds from the
west which brought mild air masses from the Pacific Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
