<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-03 17:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5891 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-SABBAH-FASHION-2TAKES     03-03 0709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SABBAH-FASHION-2TAKES-$ADV05-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FASHION 911'S? DIAL DA HOUSE OF SABBAH  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 5) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ELIZABETH HAYT 
  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Like all divas, the rap performer Eve likes to make a
grand entrance. On a Tuesday afternoon, after keeping a dozen
people waiting two hours, she sashayed into Da House of Sabbah, a
clothing store on Mulberry Street, wearing a chubby gold fur
jacket, dripping in pave diamond jewelry, with her normally
platinum hair newly dyed cinnamon red.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's dope,'' she said, spying a black fish-net gown with a
leopard lining on a rack. ``It's wild. It's different. No one else
would wear it.''
</P>
<P>
   She pulled the dress off the hanger and disappeared into a
dressing room.
</P>
<P>
   At 11 the previous night, a stylist working with Eve had made an
emergency call to Claude Sabbah, the store owner and designer,
whose sexy camouflage suit is worn by Eve in her latest video,
``Love Is Blind.'' The rapper wanted a new ensemble for the closing
number of a six-week tour she was about to begin. Sabbah had only a
day and a half to create a show-stopping look.
</P>
<P>
   The short notice might throw another designer into a tizzy, but
Sabbah, 47, quickly pulled out his fabric shears. As a creator of
custom clothes in his NoLIta studio, a former welding shop
identified by a graffiti sign, he is a favorite with underground
fashion editors, ghetto-fabulous rappers and art-world style icons
wanting to preen.
</P>
<P>
   A few trendsetters who appear in the party pages, like Ahn Duong
and Anne McNally, have also been spotted in his clothes.
</P>
<P>
   Although Da House of Sabbah opened only in November, Sabbah, who
was born in Morocco and has worked as a stylist, D.J. and designer
for a French department store, has gained a following in New York
through word of mouth.
</P>
<P>
   While he calls himself a couturier, his clothes, at $500 to
$2,000, cost a fraction of the real couture. Customers pick out
clothing samples hanging on racks that Sabbah fabricates on a
made-to-order basis. In contrast to the luxe fabrics and ``Belle de
Jour'' styles that prevailed on the New York runways last month,
Sabbah's designs are urban, ethnic and theatrical.
</P>
<P>
   He is inspired by hip-hop, Middle Eastern caftans and clerical
robes, as well as military and martial arts uniforms, with a little
disco cheesiness thrown in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a camouflage jacket lined in red velvet, and I get
stopped in the street by hip-hop kids who love it and the elitist,
socially acceptable New York crowd who react to it in the same
way,'' said Carmen Zita, a freelance art curator.
</P>
<P>
   Yvonne Force, an art consultant, who wore a camel-colored
cashmere sheath dress with a hood by Sabbah for New Year's Eve,
said that the designer's penchant for camouflage fabric recalls
Andy Warhol's paintings in the same pattern. ``Sabbah takes these
materials seen in a different context, like tacky gold lame and
Desert Storm fatigues, and transforms them,'' Force said. ``Just
when you thought camouflage got to be so trendy, Sabbah brought
another life to it by layering it with fish-net or creating a big
Chanel flower out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The clothes are really avant-garde,'' said Claude Grunitzky,
editor of Trace, an urban style magazine that featured Lauryn Hill
on the January 1999 cover in a Sabbah dress. ``There's an element
of flash in his clothes, and the hip-hop community is really into
being loud and flashy. People find them spiritual, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Claiming the do-rag _ or head scarf that African-American men
have long worn _ as a signature accessory, Sabbah has turned this
particular street look into high fashion. Eve, who wears a lace
do-rag with a train created by the designer in her recent video,
said she was the first female rapper to sport the look. It makes
her feel ``tomboyish,'' she said, adding that women now wear
do-rags to her concerts.
</P>
<P>
   ``My main piece for men and women is the do-rag,'' Sabbah said.
``It's all about black elegance. When I arrived in New York from
Paris and saw the messenger boys wearing do-rags, it reminded me of
Rudolph Valentino, the Son of the Sheik. It struck me that wearing
the do-rag, you could be princes and princesses in the street.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Sabbah affects an outlandish look, typically dressing in
oversize pants, gold medallions and knuckle rings. With a
gold-capped tooth and brown eyes rimmed with dark blue pencil, he
makes Puffy Combs look understated.
</P>
<P>
   In his steel-floored studio , amid burning candles and
camouflage pillows strewn around harem-style, he plays the role of
designer-artiste, pontificating about everything from palmistry to
style. ``In ancient Greece, the word `stylos' means pen,'' he said
as his assistant, a seamstress and a young intern listened raptly.
``A nose has style. A mouth has style. An eyebrow has style. You
understand?''
</P>
<P>
   Sabbah, who was born in Casablanca and whose father was a
butcher, personifies multiculturalism. He is Jewish but was raised
by a Muslim nanny. In 1965, the family immigrated to the south of
France, and by his early 20s, Sabbah was living in Paris. Without
any formal training, he briefly worked at the couture house of
Jacques Esterel, a futuristic designer prominent in the late '60s
and early '70s.
</P>
<P>
   In the '80s, Sabbah went to London, working as a fashion
stylist, DJ and singer. By 1990, he had returned to Paris and
within a couple of years was collaborating with the designer Gilles
Rosier (now the creative director for Kenzo), who started the label
GR 816, a hip clothing line.
</P>
<P>
   The two men also designed for Tati, a French discount department
store. During that time, Sabbah traveled to India to create
clothing for a sari company.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Sabbah said, he arrived in New York with only
$100 to spare for fabric. He bought a bolt of camouflage, one of
the cheapest materials available, on Canal Street. He had a few
high-profile friends, like Duong, whom he knew from her days
modeling in Paris, and he began to outfit them.
</P>
<P>
   Because he was on a tight budget, he made things to order,
rather than mass-producing them. Little by little, he saved enough
to open his store, and in February 1999 he held his first fashion
show at the Soldiers', Sailors', Marines' and Airmen's Club on
Lexington Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw his work last year, and his whole sensibility mixes a
real urban thing with Bedouin,'' said Kim Hastreiter, a co-editor
and co-publisher of Paper magazine, which features Sabbah's designs
in its March issue. ``But it's smart and sophisticated. It has a
`streety' twist, but he knows how to make couture.''
</P>
<P>
   Sabbah was one of 16 low-profile designers Hastreiter chose to
show together in the tents of Bryant Park over two days during the
recent Fashion Week. The audience at his show lacked a Manolo
Blahnik-shod front row, but it was filled with camcorder-toting
downtown types and fashion students.
</P>
<P>
   At Da House of Sabbah, Eve parted a red velvet curtain and
emerged from the dressing room. The train of her fish-net gown
swept her feet.
</P>
<P>
   Grabbing the excess fabric at her midriff, Sabbah insisted that
the dress be skintight.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hot,'' Eve told her stylist, Kithe Brewster. ``Don't we
have any awards coming up?'' Brewster mulled the question. The
rapper cocked her head, admired her image in the mirror and
pirouetted to study the back of the dress, which she decided to
buy. ``This is for walking down the red carpet,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
