<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-03 17:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5894 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-$ADV05-     03-03 0990
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-$ADV05-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRETTY IN ORANGE, AND DELICIOUS, TOO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, March 5)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(lh) 
 By LEE REICH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I love cold and snowy winters. Still, my mouth waters and my
hands itch to pluck ripe citrus from a home-grown tree in winter.
It can be done, as attested to by all the potted calamondin orange
trees now basking in sunny windows. But as pretty as calamondin
trees are, their fruit is barely edible, if that. I'd rather have a
plant that also bears edible fruit.
</P>
<P>
   Oranges and grapefruit are possibilities, but I think a
4-foot-high citrus tree festooned with a few large, colorful fruit
lacks grace. Lemons and limes are better proportioned to an indoor
plant and have the advantage that a single fruit of either goes far
in the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   The citrus that offers the most mileage as a potted plant is
kumquat. (Kumquat actually is a close relative of citrus, moved
from that genus in 1915 to the closely related genus Fortunella.)
</P>
<P>
   Like other citrus, kumquat is a pretty sight all year round,
with glossy, evergreen leaves that provide a perfect backdrop for
the waxy white, sweet-smelling flowers.
</P>
<P>
   The fruit is what makes kumquat stand out from the citrus crowd.
You can eat only the pulp of oranges and grapefruit, and for the
most part, use only the juice of a lemon or a lime. Kumquats can be
eaten skin and all. The skin has a sweet, spicy flavor that mixes
well with that of the pulp, which, depending on variety, varies
from sweet to tart. The orange fruit are about the size of a
quarter, perfectly proportioned to a potted plant, and can be
popped whole into your mouth.
</P>
<P>
   With just a few wrinkles, the kumquat should be grown like any
other house plant. Fruiting takes energy, which comes from
sunlight, so my kumquat trees spend summers outdoors in almost full
sun and winters at a south-facing window. A cool room is best in
winter, with cool temperatures compensating to some degree for
reduced light. I pot them in the same mix I use for other potted
plants, consisting of equal parts compost, garden soil, perlite and
peat moss.
</P>
<P>
   Although this mix offers nutrients, I supplement them with more
or less regular applications of some soluble fertilizer, except in
midwinter, when the plant is resting.
</P>
<P>
   Kumquat is among the hardiest citrus _ it can take temperatures
to 15 degrees Fahrenheit _ and part of that hardiness is because of
the long winter's rest into which it settles.
</P>
<P>
   Color change of the ripening fruit is my plants' only sign of
life right now. But the fruit are almost too pretty to eat.
Fortunately, ripe kumquats hang in good condition on the plant for
many weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The kumquat sold in stores is the oval-fruited Nagami, whose
thick skin encloses a tart pulp. Besides Nagami, I grow the variety
Meiwa, which has fruit larger than the Nagami and round, with a
thin skin enclosing a sweet-tart pulp. Less well known are Marumi
and Changshou (Fukushu in Japan), both with round fruit and
sweetish pulp.
</P>
<P>
   Citrus breeders have incorporated the cold-hardy genes of the
kumquat into a number of hybrids whose names are fun to speak.
Limequats are hardy lime substitutes, and they include such
varieties as Eustis and Tavares. Orangequats are larger and sweeter
than kumquats, and quite cold hardy. Hardiest of all are
citrangequats, hybrids of kumquat and citrange. The citrange is
itself a hybrid of orange and poncirus, an inedible citrus relative
that grows as far north as New York City. But they have those large
fruit, and I want to be able to eat the whole fruit.
</P>
<P>
   Just as soon as I harvest the last of my Meiwa and Nagami
kumquats, I prepare the plants for next year's crop. Because both
plants are as large as I want them to be, I root-prune them to make
way for fresh soil so that they can go right back into their
present 10-inch-diameter pots. To do this, I slide each plant out
of its pot and then, with a knife, slice an inch of roots and soil
from the sides and bottom of the root ball. Teasing the remaining
outermost roots with a fork or stick encourages them to grow into
new potting soil. After setting the root ball in the pot on a new
bed of soil, I pack the new soil into the space between the root
ball and the edge of the pot.
</P>
<P>
   After root pruning, the stems need pruning to encourage fresh
growth, avoid congestion, and keep the plants a manageable size. My
technique is the same for my Meiwa, with a trunk like a small tree,
as for my Nagami, which looks more like a bush. My first cuts
remove some stems right to their origin. Next, I shorten remaining
stems wherever increased branching is needed. Finally, I remove
twiggy or crowded stems. As I prune, I step back and look at the
plant with an artist's eye, clipping stems here and there to put
them visually in balance with each other and with the size of the
pot.
</P>
<P>
   You could start a kumquat tree from the seeds of a store-bought
fruit. Unlike most fruit, whose seed-grown progeny can be very
different from the parent tree (for the same reason that human
children differ from their parents), citrus seedlings commonly are
identical to their parents. Still, a seed-grown kumquat could take
10 years to bear fruit.
</P>
<P>
   The easiest thing is to get kumquats from nurseries, which
propagate them by grafting onto kumquat or poncirus seedlings.
Grafted plants usually cost $20 to $40 and will bear within a year
or two.
</P>
<P>
   These nurseries offer kumquats:
</P>
<P>
   Four Winds Growers, P.O. Box 3538, Fremont, CA 94539; for a
catalog, send a stamped, self-addressed business-size envelope.
</P>
<P>
   Just Fruits and Exotics, 30 St. Francis St., Crawfordville, FL
32327; (850) 926-5644; catalog, $3.
</P>
<P>
   Pacific Tree Farms, 4301 Lynwood Dr., Chula Vista, CA 91910;
(619) 422-2400; free catalog.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
