<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-03 17:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5899 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-ABANDONED-RAILROAD-$A     03-03 1230
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABANDONED-RAILROAD-$ADV05-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     TRAIL OF DISAPPOINTMENT LEADS TO THE RIO GRANDE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (For release Sunday, March 5)   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By RUSSELL GOLD  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRESIDIO, Texas _ For nearly a century, the South Orient
railroad has carried the promise of trade between the United States
and Mexico, and has delivered decades of disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   Now Texas officials say they are in a race against time to save
the little-known railroad that crosses the Rio Grande on a wooden
trestle. While the North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA) has
turned the six other rail lines that connect the two countries into
busy routes, this line has grown weeds.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no question that some time in the future, we will be
very, very sorry that we lost that line if we let it go,'' said
David Laney, the state transportation commissioner. ``There is no
question that the volume of NAFTA traffic is growing very
quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, the operators sought to abandon the line, citing
mounting financial losses. The federal Surface Transportation Board
denied their petition, but kept the door open to reconsider the
decision.
</P>
<P>
   Now a final effort to resuscitate the railroad that runs as far
as San Angelo, Texas, is under way, aided by $6 million in the last
state budget to sweeten the deal for a prospective buyer.
</P>
<P>
   GrupoMexico, the majority owner of Ferrocarril Mexicano, or
FerroMex, the newly privatized Mexican company that owns the tracks
connected to Presidio, is negotiating to buy the railroad, Laney
said. The announcement of a deal is ``imminent,'' according to
various people familiar with the talks.
</P>
<P>
   Phone calls to FerroMex officials in Mexico City were not
returned.
</P>
<P>
   If this latest deal sours, officials said, the federal
government might have no option but to let the rail line be
abandoned.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it is ever pulled up and scrapped, you can't ever build it
again,'' said state Rep. Rob Junell, a Democrat from San Angelo who
is the railroad's staunchest ally in the Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are only seven crossings in the whole of the U.S. into
Mexico by rail,'' Junell said. ``Preserving every entry and every
mile of rail that has strategic value is very important.''
</P>
<P>
   Residents of this isolated West Texas border town, population
3,500, would like to hear the rattle of the railroad again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish anybody would take it over. Don't abandon it. Don't
close it,'' said Adam Covos, who lost his railroad job when the
South Orient stopped running trains in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   He now drives the town's only garbage truck.
</P>
<P>
   The South Orient was created in 1900 by Arthur Stilwell, a
visionary who had dreams of international commerce a century before
Mexico, the United States and Canada became partners in NAFTA.
</P>
<P>
   His goal was to connect Kansas City to the Pacific Ocean by the
shortest route _ across West Texas and through Mexico. He planned
to ship goods to Asia, a failed scheme that nonetheless left the
railroad with the ``Orient'' in its name.
</P>
<P>
   He soon ran afoul of financiers, denouncing them as the
``cannibals of Wall Street.'' The project went into receivership,
and it wasn't until 1930 that the new owners, the Santa Fe Railway,
completed the line to Presidio.
</P>
<P>
   In Mexico, the track connected through to Chihuahua City and on
to Topolobampo, a deepwater Pacific Ocean port.
</P>
<P>
   Traffic over the line never developed, and, over the years, so
little basic track maintenance has been done that the line's
condition has deteriorated.
</P>
<P>
   Unwilling to watch the track torn up, West Texas officials
turned to the Texas Legislature. During a special session,
lawmakers appropriated $3 million to buy the right of way.
</P>
<P>
   The line was leased to the South Orient Railroad Co., a
partnership of three businessmen, two in Dallas and one in Mexico
City.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the advent of substantially increasing levels of trade
between the United States and Mexico, (we) saw an opportunity,''
South Orient President Joel Williams III said in a 1998 affidavit.
</P>
<P>
   He declined to comment for this article because of the ongoing
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   His business plan was to team up with the Burlington Northern,
the only major U.S. railroad that didn't have a route into Mexico.
But soon after the purchase, the Burlington Northern merged with
the Santa Fe Railway, which already operated a bridge in El Paso.
</P>
<P>
   From Dallas to the northern Mexican city of Chihuahua, the South
Orient route is 425 miles shorter than the merged Burlington
Northern Santa Fe and 175 miles shorter than Union Pacific's route,
according to Williams.
</P>
<P>
   But while the underdog had the shortest route, the major
railroads had all the freight traffic. The South Orient suffered.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not an unneeded piece of railroad, it's just that given
the current railroad industry organization, the megamergers, it has
been left out by itself,'' said George Werner, a railroad historian
who lives in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the promise of border trade has passed Presidio without
stopping.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even in the truck industry, we are not picking up on any of
that NAFTA traffic,'' said Presidio Mayor Alcee Tavarez, a social
studies teacher at the high school. ``The maquiladora program has
not caught on along the border in this area. I don't know why; I
can't put my finger on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Maquiladoras are foreign-owned companies set up in Mexico,
usually close to the U.S. border, to take advantage of more
favorable taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The South Orient tried to develop traffic, but had little
success. Few shippers in Presidio or Brewster counties need the
railroad, although the development of large deposits of humate, a
fertilizer, has stirred interest in rail traffic.
</P>
<P>
   The long-term survival of the rail line, almost everyone
involved agreed, depends on international trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it weren't for NAFTA and it weren't for the potential
tremendous explosion of traffic, I don't know that anyone would be
talking about it,'' said Jerry Martin, head of the rail division at
the Texas Railroad Commission.
</P>
<P>
   The South Orient discovered that potential trade is not a good
alternative for paying customers. Other possible suitors agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were approached three different times about our interest in
operating that line, and we turned it down on three occasions,''
said Bruce Flohr, founder and former chairman of RailTex Inc., a
San Antonio-based company that was sold to RailAmerica Inc. last
year. ``There is just no business on it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The trains stopped on June 23, 1998, when a fire damaged a
bridge about 30 miles north of the border near the ghost town of
Casa Piedra. The bridge was repaired, but in October 1998, the
federal government approved a request to discontinue service.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, trains have become a rare sight along the desolate
track.
</P>
<P>
   Unless a buyer willing to invest in upgrading the track can be
found, the future looks bleak.
</P>
<P>
   A few months after the order to discontinue train service, in
what Mayor Tavarez said was cruel timing, the state transportation
department finally complied with a long-standing request to install
crossing gates where the tracks cross Highway 170 near the high
school.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are we going to see coming through here now?'' he said
with a laugh.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-03-00 1730EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000303.0175 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-03 17:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5903 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-ROCK-PUMPINS-BOS &LR;      03-03 1273
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROCK-PUMPINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SMASHING PUMPKINS LIGHTEN UP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating for all needed)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The supposedly difficult Billy Corgan of the Smashing Pumpkins
is reminded of an interview he did with this newspaper two years
ago. ``Was I contentious that day?'' he asks. No, comes the reply.
``You got me on a good day, then.''
</P>
<P>
   Corgan is having more good days lately.
</P>
<P>
   He is steering the Pumpkins into a new, more optimistic era with
the release of ``MACHINA: the Machines of God,'' which comes out
Tuesday. It also restores the hard-driving, rocking side of the
band, versus the indulgent, downtempo style of the last CD,
``Adore,'' which raised questions of whether the band might be
headed toward a breakup.
</P>
<P>
   The new songs address love, survival, and humanity with far more
hope than the days when Corgan sang his generational rant:
``Despite all my rage, I'm still just a rat in a cage.''
</P>
<P>
   The cage has opened - and some bright light is pouring in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to project a more positive energy,'' Corgan says on a
cell phone from Chicago, where the band began. ``What's funny is
that when we were inherently more of a narcissistic, negative kind
of band, back when we were just trying to basically blow people's
minds, we got a lot of negative energy back. And now that we've
turned the corner, I think it's generating a lot of
</P>
<P>
   positivity. You reap what you sow.''
</P>
<P>
   Corgan can still be cantankerous (``I'm a terrorist, but instead
of using bombs, I use ideas''), yet he's definitely turned the
corner with new tracks like ``This Time'' (``Only love can win''),
``Raindrops and Sunshine'' (``I'm just
</P>
<P>
   trying to walk with you between the raindrops''), and the
spiritual ``With Every Light'' (``Look ma, the sun is shining on me
. . . In every light that's shining down on me/ I'm never alone'').
</P>
<P>
   Corgan wrote most of the songs very early in the morning (at 7
and 8 a.m.) in ``almost a dream state'' when he got out of bed.
``It's a blurring of dream and reality and metaphysical impressions
and junk culture and drugs and whatever else gets thrown in the
blender,'' he says, though he adds later: ``I don't drink and I
don't really take any drugs. I'm a pretty clean liver. I'm allergic
to about half of what's in the world anyway, so it's pretty much
just me and water. . . . When I was younger, I felt I needed to
push myself, as a lot of young people do, into some sort of
psychotic state to reach that part of myself, but I don't feel that
way anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   There's still plenty of edginess on the new CD, however, so old
fans shouldn't feel left behind. The nearly 10-minute ``Glass and
the Ghost Children'' has eerily psychedelic echoes of the Doors'
``The End,'' while ``Heavy Metal Machine'' has a dense, Nine Inch
Nails-like electronic rush, capped by the macabre line, ``If I were
dead, would my rec ords sell?''
</P>
<P>
   But the overall effect is of a damaged band trying to be whole
(drummer Jimmy Chamberlin, once kicked out for drugs, is now back
in); and of a damaged soul (Corgan) trying to find a fresh balance
in life.
</P>
<P>
   So what's with the new spirituality? Has Corgan been meditating
on any mountaintops?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, God hit me over the head with a two-by-four,'' he says
with a laugh. ``Really, I think that it's hard . . . to travel the
world, meet so many people, and go to places where people could
care less about Mariah Carey and our world of pop and rock, without
finding some sort of humility. And I don't
</P>
<P>
   mean humility in a kind of I'm-not-worthy way, but humility in a
deeper respect for life and what goes on.''
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't subscribe to any single religion, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``How about this: I just believe. I don't prejudice myself
against anybody else's (religion). I just believe. I think one look
at the ocean is all you need. You don't need to find it in somebody
else's version. It's right there in front of you.''
</P>
<P>
   Either way, Corgan is much less self-consumed than before.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think when you're younger, it's easy to think that (life) is
all about you, but as you get older, you realize it's not all about
you,'' says Corgan, now 32. ``There's a line in a song that's not
on the album but reflected the way I felt, which is: `I'm just one
of many more to come.' It's about the folk
</P>
<P>
   troubadour tradition and how I'm just another guy with a guitar
and there will be a lot after me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Realizing that, you respect what you have and you feel that
you can effect change in a positive way. It doesn't have to be
pretty. It doesn't have to be perfect. It can be messy. If you want
any insight into how we work, we're not afraid to be cracked or
broken, because we feel in some ways it is a truer
</P>
<P>
   reflection than something that is airbrushed and perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, Corgan says, he finds it hard to be included in
any Grammy nominations with other bands, ``because you find
yourself in the same categories as airbrushed, plastic-surgeried,
pimped-up, blown-up stars.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead - and this is where some industry types get upset with
the Pumpkins (including Sharon Osbourne, who just quit as their
manager) - the Pumpkins ``demand to be treated like real artists.
If people don't like that, then that's OK. But rock 'n' roll is not
supposed to be safe and comfortable. Not
</P>
<P>
   everyone is supposed to like you, and if everyone does, you're
definitely doing something wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Corgan has taken some shots lately - notably from, of all
places, The Washington Post, whose writer said he looked like
``Uncle Fester'' and was presiding over a band with ``soap opera
histrionics.'' Says Corgan: ``I expect that from Spin magazine, but
not from The Washington Post. I was stunned.''
</P>
<P>
   The soap-opera types started buzzing when bassist D'Arcy Wretzky
left the band after the new CD was made, claiming she wanted to go
into acting. Corgan says of Wretzky (who was just arrested for
possession of crack cocaine): ``We've decided on taking a graceful
pass on talking about why she left the band. It's a complex
situation. There's no one single factor.''
</P>
<P>
   But he's pleased with new bassist Melissa Auf Der Maur (formerly
of Courtney Love's band, Hole), who is now an official member. And
he's pleased that the Pumpkins are back to a four-piece unit,
rather than the bloated seven-piece that toured last time. The
Pumpkins have been doing autograph signings at various record
stores and playing occasional surprise gigs in cities they visit
(look for one in Boston later next week), which have been well
received. And though they could headline arenas again, Corgan wants
the group to play in smaller venues later this year, maybe doing
multiple gigs in each city.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a street band again,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   As for continued rumors that the Pumpkins might throw in the
towel and break up, Corgan says with another laugh, ``I've
considered throwing it in every day of my life! But, really, the
speculation around the band is just too funny. We simply live in a
rumored world. I mean, I would say of every three questions I'm
asked, one is based on rumors or Internet information, so that
seems to be the world I'm living in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Also, we wouldn't have made this record unless we were looking
at a future,'' he says. ``Many people seem to be really excited
about the record, and excited about the prog ress the band has
made. A lot of people thought the band was a dead entity, but we're
living in a really good kind of sunny day
</P>
<P>
   right now. All that other stuff just seems to feed a monster
that's not even of our own making anymore.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
