<HEADER>
A5919 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-EDUCATION-TAX04-COX     03-03 0690
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDUCATION-TAX04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GOP SENATORS CELEBRATE WIN ON EDUCATION TAX BREAKS
 &HT;    310&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Senate Republicans celebrated a victory over
President Clinton on Friday, saying they hope to convince him to
sign their bill creating tax breaks for parents of children in
public and private schools.
</P>
<P>
   During a week-long Senate debate, Republicans fought off five
attempts by Clinton's supporters to eliminate its central
provision, which resembles legislation that Clinton vetoed in 1998
and 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Crafted by Sen. Paul Coverdell, R-Ga., that provision would let
parents and others put up to $2,000 per child per year into
educational savings accounts that would earn tax-free interest. The
savings could be withdrawn not just for college, but also for
educational expenses at home or in a public, private or parochial
school.
</P>
<P>
   Under current law, the annual limit is $500 and the money can
only be used for college.
</P>
<P>
   ``We passed this bill last night with a bipartisan majority of
61 to 37,'' said Sen. Don Nickles, R-Okla., at a news conference
packed with students wearing red T-shirts with pro-education
slogans. ``It's time the president quit playing politics with our
children's future.''
</P>
<P>
   Most Republicans and nine Democrats voted for the bill, while
most Democrats and two Republicans followed Clinton's request to
vote against it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It reminds me of the welfare debate,'' Coverdell said. ``In
the end, it becomes indefensible to argue that things should stay
the way they are _ to defend the status quo.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the administration will continue to oppose the measure
when it reaches the House, said David Frank, communications
director for the Education Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``This bill is bad education policy and bad tax policy,'' said
Frank. ``The president vetoed this approach in the past and
retained enough votes in the Senate to uphold another veto.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Bipartisan congressional analysts said that letting education
savings accounts earn tax-free interest would save the average
family with a child schooled at home or in a private school $37 a
year. The average public-school family would save $4 a year.
</P>
<P>
   But many others also had a stake in the fight. Besides the
savings accounts, which would cost the treasury $2.4 billion in
revenue over 10 years, the bill contains more than $6 billion in
other tax breaks with widespread bipartisan support.
</P>
<P>
   Among the beneficiaries of those other provisions:
</P>
<P>
   _ Computer sellers and other businesses that donate used
computer equipment to schools or senior citizen centers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Employers who pay for their workers' undergraduate or graduate
studies.
</P>
<P>
   _ Teachers who buy classrooms supplies out of their own pockets.
</P>
<P>
   _ Professionals who switch to teaching careers in mid-life.
</P>
<P>
   _ School districts that earn interest on unspent bond proceeds.
</P>
<P>
   _ Families that use prepaid college tuition plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he were to veto this, he would be turning away from them
all,'' Coverdell said.
</P>
<P>
   Not necessarily, said Sheldon Steinbach, general counsel of the
American Council on Education, a higher education association that
took no stand on pre-college savings accounts.
</P>
<P>
   ``In light of their popularity, those items are likely to be
re-attached in some form to another bill later, if the president
vetoes this bill,'' Steinbach said. ``Or possibly the offensive
provision may be dropped in (a House-Senate) conference; that would
be the easiest way.''
</P>
<P>
   Such a quiet compromise is unlikely, said political scientist
Joseph Cooper at Johns Hopkins University.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Republican strategy is to put the president behind
the 8 ball,'' Cooper said. ``They want him to veto a bunch of bills
in the next eight months so that they can tell the voters, 'We
Republicans passed those good things and the Democrats are the guys
who killed them.' ``
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Mollison's e-mail address is AndyM(at)Coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
