<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-COLUMN-ART-$ADV05-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW `THE BIG MO' TOOK THE TOP PRIZE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888 603-1036
or 888 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 5)  
 (af)  
 By MARK HULBERT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's Oscar month, so let me suggest a new award category _
lifetime achievement in investment. My nominees for the inaugural
prize are the often-criticized strategies of momentum-based
stock-pickers.
</P>
<P>
   The reasoning is simple. Each of the newsletters atop the
performance rankings of The Hulbert Financial Digest for the 5, 10
and 15 years through 1999 uses a momentum-based strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Momentum means different things to different people, but these
newsletters consider a stock to have momentum if it has
outperformed the market over the previous 6 to 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   Often, strategies that emerge from historical research stop
working almost the moment they are discovered. But these momentum
strategies, which have been widely known for decades and have
gained in popularity, have shown staying power.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, momentum strategies look more effective than ever.
Consider OTC Insight, a a momentum-oriented newsletter edited by
James Collins, which is the top-performing letter among those
tracked by the digest over the last 10 years. Last year was its
best, with its average model portfolio _ which included stocks like
JDS Uniphase and Cisco Systems _ gaining 153 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, investors should be cautious about any strategy,
including momentum investing, until they receive a good explanation
of how it works. Only then can they weed out those managers or
newsletters whose records result from luck alone.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers have found two factors that may account for
momentum's success. I call the first the bandwagon effect. As a
stock keeps outperforming the market, more and more investors
``discover'' it and jump on board _ propelling it even further
ahead of the market and seducing still more buyers. (Eventually
that can cause the stock to become overvalued and subject to
correction, but that's another matter.)
</P>
<P>
   For stocks that have recently underperformed the market, a
reverse bandwagon is often at work as more and more investors
succumb to selling pressure.
</P>
<P>
   The second factor has to do with the behavior of Wall Street
analysts. Because of certain incentives and disincentives, they
often respond sluggishly to new information.
</P>
<P>
   Say the consensus earnings estimate for a company is $1.20 a
share, but one analyst finds new information that justifies an
estimate of $2. There is little incentive for the analyst to go out
on a limb with the new estimate, because he will receive almost as
much attention for being the first to predict, say, $1.50 a share.
That way, he will be poised to garner still more attention if and
when he becomes the first to predict $1.75, and then $2. And each
higher projection helps keep the stock's momentum going.
</P>
<P>
   This, too, works in reverse. Analysts are reluctant to announce
earnings estimates that are far below the consensus for fear of
alienating the company and endangering their relationship with its
management. So their estimates usually fall gradually.
</P>
<P>
   The key question becomes this: Over what period should momentum
be measured in order to get the best results? Six months appears to
be ideal, according to a study conducted by two finance professors,
Narasimhan Jegadeesh of the University of Illinois at
Urbana-Champaign and Sheridan Titman of the University of Texas at
Austin. They created a hypothetical portfolio that on Jan. 1, 1965,
bought the 10 percent of stocks with the best returns over the
previous six months. Every six months, through June 30, 1998, they
reconstituted the portfolio so it held the 10 percent of stocks
with the best returns over the previous six months.
</P>
<P>
   Over the 34 years through 1998, the portfolio gained 21.7
percent, annualized. That is 16.5 percentage points better than one
that held the 10 percent of stocks with the worst returns over the
previous six months and 7.8 points better than the broader market.
</P>
<P>
   Now that's an Oscar-winning performance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
