<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   DEPOTS _ WASHINGTON _ The Senate military readiness subcommittee
holds a hearing on Air Force depot maintenance. (Malone, Cox News
Service). 20.
</P>
<P>
   EDUCATION-TAX _ WASHINGTON _ Sen. Paul Coverdell, R-Ga., on
Friday celebrates Senate approval of an amended version of his bill
to give tax breaks to families that save up to $2,000 per child per
year to meet the expenses of going to a public, private, parochial
or home school. It would also give education-related tax breaks to
teachers, would-be teachers and businesses. But the bill passed by
too narrow a margin to guarantee an over-ride of the veto expected
from President Clinton, who has vetoed similar bills twice, and
wants Congress to pass his own package of education tax breaks
instead. Political scientist Joseph Cooper of Johns Hopkins
University explains why senators from both parties cheerfully spent
more than a week of floor time debating an education bill that
won't become a law. (Mollison, Cox News Service). 15.
</P>
