   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   NIGERIA-STRIFE _ LAGO, Nigeria _ We take a look at the
increasing religious strife between Christians and Muslims, that
has brought this country _ struggling with a fragile new democracy
_ once again to the brink of civil war. Developing. (Roughton, Cox
News Service). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving SPOT on Fri., March 3.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-NAMES _ LONDON _ Look in any newspaper in the Czech
Republic and you'll see Julia Robertsova and Meryl Streepova, not
Julia Roberts and Meryl Streep. That's because the suffix ``ova''
is added to all women's names to indicate the woman belongs to her
husband or father. But times are changing. Legislation proposed by
the Czech Ministry of Interior _ and expected to pass _ would
finally allow a woman to delete the ``ova'' suffix. This change is
a surprising one in Europe, where countries have long resisted
American-style ``political correctness,'' a term derided as
describing a ridiculously tortured sensitivity that has resulted in
absurd changes to the language. In Britain, for example, letter
carriers (American-style P.C.) are still called ``postmen,'' even
</P>
<P>
   if they are women. (Emling, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Wed., March 1, in (i) International and (l) Lifestyle
categories.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-POLLUTION MEXICO CITY _ Mexican environmental officials
proudly announced in January that this crowded ? and usually
smog-filled ? had enjoyed the cleanest air in a decade in 1999.
Within a few weeks those officials were all but eating their words.
Just after they unveiled data showing that one of the world's most
polluted cities had made gains, the city was shrouded once again in
eye-stinging, throat-burning smog. Kids, who are at special risk
here, were ordered indoors in the southern end of the city. Brown
clouds hung on the horizon like frozen dust storms. Coughs and
respiratory ailments soared. From the World Trade Center, one of
the city's tallest buildings, the view was apocalyptic. A blanket
of smog rolled over the city 46 stories below, growing thicker by
the minute. Yes, the air is cleaner thanks to reforms. But problems
with industry emissions, traffic and even soil erosion are still
serious. (Ferriss, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Wed., March 1.
</P>
<P>
   BOLIVIA-LIFESAVERS _ The village where Bautista Cruz was dying
is so high his journey to heaven would be very short. At more than
13,000 feet in the Bolivian Andes, there isn't a lot of air to
start with. But Bautista's lungs were being squeezed by a bowel
obstruction the size of a basketball. The obstruction would either
rupture and kill him or squeeze the last breath out of his lungs
and kill him. A group of Franciscan nuns were determined that
wouldn't happen. (Reid, Palm Beach Post). 50. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   MARDIGRAS-PANTIES _ NEW ORLEANS _ New Orleans cops have placed
signs up all over saying public nudity is forbidden for this year's
Mardi Gras. The crackdown on festival bawdiness seems extra-serious
this year. A suburban city has banned obscene throws, like dildos,
from its parades, but voted that panties were OK. A city councilman
worried about the appearance of that: ''So,'' he said, ``we are on
the record as pro-panties?'' (Konigsmark, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
