<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-03 17:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5926 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-NY-CATS-MUSICAL-$ADV0     03-03 1114
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CATS-MUSICAL-$ADV05-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOUR CITY MICE WHO HAD TO SEE `CATS' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, March 5)  
(lh) 
 By RICK MARIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``We've got 4 tickets! Do we need more?''
</P>
<P>
   An improbable e-mail for one New Yorker to receive from another,
considering the show the tickets in question were for.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cats.''
</P>
<P>
   Residents of Manhattan have scorned Andrew Lloyd Webber's most
famous musical for years, but how many of them have actually seen
it? The news that after 18 years, the show will close on June 24
presents a unusual problem for the jaded among us. On the one hand,
there's the impulse to ridicule or ignore the very tourist traps of
which ``Cats'' is the apogee. On the other, there's a nagging need
to have seen and done it all.
</P>
<P>
   In my case, the second instinct won out. So, last Sunday
afternoon, four of us found ourselves behind the big billboard eyes
of the Wintergarden Theater doing the unthinkable. I think it was
an experience none of us will soon forget.
</P>
<P>
   To give our excursion the patina of irony, we had lunch first at
Katz's Delicatessen, on Houston Street. Then we could tell people,
``We went to Katz's, then `Cats.' Get it?''
</P>
<P>
   Our seats were within hissing range of the stage, whose outsize
junkyard props _ convincingly decayed-looking after 18 years _ are
meant to convey a cat's-eye view. Around us were Japanese tourists
and the sensibly fanny-packed elderly. There was no mistaking the
scene for the Brooklyn Academy of Music. The patron of the arts
next to me spent most of the show on his nanny's lap sucking his
thumb. (Much of the audience was in the under-5 demographic.)
</P>
<P>
   The house lights dimmed. A 25-piece orchestra, offstage left,
played its first rock-operatic notes. Men and women in Halloween
makeup, skin-tight body stockings (all right, cat suits) and leg
warmer ``fur'' entered, miming feline poses. As the company burst
into the first number, ``Jellicle Songs for Jellicle Cats,'' one of
my party leaned over to ask, ``What's a Jellico cat?'' It would not
be the last time one of us would fail to grasp what was going on.
</P>
<P>
   I know I didn't. And I even own ``Old Possum's Book of Practical
Cats,'' the slender volume of T.S. Eliot poems published in 1940,
which supplied most of the lyrics for ``Cats.'' My copy, an old
Faber &AMP; Faber edition, came from my grandmother's library. As a
youth, I pulled it off the shelf, confused by the seeming
incongruity between its heavyweight author and nonsense verse. I
liked the way the cover said ``Nicholas Bentley Drew the
Pictures,'' but could never quite bring myself to read it.
</P>
<P>
   Which may be why the dogfight in ``Cats'' between the Pekes and
Pollicles went over my head. The cats put on masks made from trash,
see, and pretend to be dogs. I thought they really were dogs, which
was embarrassing. This is, after all, a musical that owes its
cross-cultural longevity to the fact that you can understand it
without knowing English.
</P>
<P>
   Act One consists largely of introductions. The Old Gumbie Cat.
Bustopher Jones, who looked like the grotesquely fat man who
explodes in Monty Python's ``Meaning of Life.'' Mungojerrie and
Rumpleteazer, whose smug, vaudevillian slapstick was our first
walkout challenge.
</P>
<P>
   The tallest of us had the aisle seat, trading leg room for the
constant, terrifying threat of audience participation. The
performers frequently gambol into the crowd, but the feeling is not
always mutual. In 1997, a spectator who refused to dance with Rum
Tum Tugger sued the Shubert Organization for $6 million, accusing
it of assault, battery, invasion of privacy, violation of civil
rights, negligence, intentional infliction of emotional distress
and false imprisonment. (The case never went to trial.) Our friend
on the aisle slouched deeper and deeper into his seat.
</P>
<P>
   The tedium of the ancient (also fat) Old Deuteronomy was matched
only by the gothic weirdness of Grizabella, the Glamour Cat. A
Norma Desmond figure, Grizabella closes Act One with the only
``Cats'' song anybody knows, ``Memory,'' which is not an Eliot poem
and sounds like an ``Evita'' leftover. It was the second walkout
challenge and, this time we accepted. We repaired to Gallagher's
bar around the corner to grapple with the phenomenon we had just
experienced.
</P>
<P>
   Seeing ``Cats'' today, you can't quite believe that a) this
thing was ever a hot ticket among consenting adults, and b) it
didn't close on opening night. Theater people will argue that when
it opened in London in 1981, there had never been anything like it.
This could also be regarded as a blessing.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Rich's review in The New York Times was no rave, but he
predicted the show's trans-Atlantic success, writing, ``It's not
that this collection of anthropomorphic variety turns is a
brilliant musical or that it powerfully stirs the emotions or that
it has an idea in its head.'' No, the reason it would be a hit,
Rich explained, was that ``it believes purely in theatrical magic,
and on that faith it unquestionably delivers.''
</P>
<P>
   Now but no longer forever, ``Cats'' will be missed. Television
commercials for new Broadway shows will no longer be able to quote
theatergoers gushing, ``Better than `Cats!''' David Letterman, who
broadcasts from the Ed Sullivan Theater up Broadway, will be
deprived of a punchline.
</P>
<P>
   The news that ``Cats'' was closing broke on a Sunday. Ticket
sales on the following Tuesday were $285,000, up from the normal
$60,000 range, said Jonathan Schwartz, a spokesman for the show.
``And the demand for house seats is back,'' he added, indicating
that show business insiders are calling in their connections again.
The 11th hour revival of interest may give ``Cats'' another nine
(or 18) lives. Like ``The Fantasticks,'' it could go on in some
Village basement until the end of time.
</P>
<P>
   None of us enjoyed ``Cats,'' on any level. But not enjoying it
did not make me feel superior, as camp is supposed to. I e-mailed
Hugh Kenner, the Eliot scholar now professor emeritus of English at
the University of Georgia, and asked him what T.S. _ the Old Possum
himself _ would have thought of ``Cats.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Eliot would have been gratified by the success of
`Cats,''' Kenner replied. ``Why not? His text's behind the costumes
and music. And it made a secure income for Valerie (his widow), to
whom he was devoted. Drop all stereotypes of Eliot the touchy
aesthete.''
</P>
<P>
   If perhaps the greatest poet of the 20th century wouldn't have
had a problem with ``Cats,'' where do we get off? Besides, a week
after leaving halfway through, I'm still reciting that dumb
Jellicle cat song. The scary thing is I'm starting to like it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-03-00 1757EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
