<HEADER>
A5927 &Cx1f; tad-z
r p BC-POL-TICKER04-COX     03-03 1285
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Decision day arrives in 3 states
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BREAST CANCER RESEARCH AS CAMPAIGN ISSUE
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush went to a breast cancer research center in New
York today to emphasize his criticism of John McCain for listing
some breast cancer projects as pork-barrel spending. Bush's ads in
New York feature a breast cancer survivor calling McCain's
opposition to research funding ``shocking'' and saying America
deserves ``a candidate with a record on women's issues we can
trust.'' McCain said he has repeatedly voted to increase spending
on breast cancer research. Speaking on ``Imus in the Morning'' in
New York, McCain said he could get his message to voters despite
such ads, but, ``If they don't figure it out, we will have run an
honorable campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   BREAST CANCER RESEARCH AS PERSONAL ISSUE
</P>
<P>
   Another reason John McCain was offended by the George W. Bush
radio ad accusing him of being indifferent to breast cancer
research funding is that McCain's sister is a breast cancer
survivor in remission. McCain refused to answer questions about her
condition, but Sandy McCain Morgan was reached by phone by online
magazine Salon: ``All I can say is that I'm very grateful for my
brother's support for breast cancer research, and I'm very grateful
to Johns Hopkins Hospital,'' where her illness was treated.
</P>
<P>
   MYSTERY DONATIONS AIR CLEARED
</P>
<P>
   The mysterious group airing ads in the presidential race
promoting George W. Bush's environmental record is headed by Sam
Wyly, a Texas entrepreneur. Wyly and his brother Charles, have
donated thousands of dollars to Bush political campaigns. Wyly's
newly formed group, Republicans for Clean Air, is airing $2 million
in TV ads that go after John McCain on the environment and tout
Bush's record. It would be an illegal donation if the Bush campaign
were involved with planning the ads, but the Bush camp says it has
nothing to do with them. McCain said that's what's wrong with the
campaign finance system.
</P>
<P>
   LONG-ODDS BRADLEY PLUGS AWAY
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore, looking to knock Bill Bradley out of the race Tuesday
night, confidently road-tested a general election fight with
Republicans today, while Bradley urged supporters to ignore the
pollsters and vote their convictions. Bradley, in Portland, Maine,
called the race ``a choice between the politics of division, of
exaggerated and unfulfilled promises, and a politics based upon
belief, conviction and straight talk,'' but never mentioned Gore by
name. With Bradley no longer seen as a serious threat, Gore already
has begun looking past his only Democratic rival, railing instead
against the two Republicans. And in Jacksonville, Fla., today, Gore
added Sen. Bob Graham to his lopsided pile of Democratic Party
endorsements.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT MAY HAVE A VERY GOOD FRIEND
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush suggested that if he is elected president, he
might order the Justice Department to drop its antitrust case
against Microsoft, Britain's Financial Times reported. ``I think it
is very important for our society, when there is innovation taking
place, to understand the consequences of litigation,''the paper
quoted Bush as saying during an interview in Seattle, where the
company is based. ``I am not sympathetic to lawsuits. Write that
down. I worry about the effect of lawsuits on job creation. If you
are looking for the kind of president I will be, I will be slow to
litigate.'' The monopoly case is pending in federal court.
</P>
<P>
   BOB JONES III FIGHTING BACK
</P>
<P>
   Bob Jones University is using full-page newspaper ads to answer
national criticism of its interracial dating ban and other issues
that cropped up after George W. Bush made a campaign stop at the
fundamentalist Christian school last month. In the ``Letter to the
Nation,'' University President Bob Jones III says the Greenville,
S.C., schoo has been wrongly painted as racist and anti-Catholic.
The issue is religious freedom, he wrote. The ad appears in USA
Today and the three largest South Carolina papers, in Columbia,
Charleston and Greenville. Jones is to be interviewed tonight by
Larry King on CNN (9 p.m. EST).
</P>
<P>
   JERRY FORD WOULD HAVE AVOIDED THE WHOLE MESS
</P>
<P>
   Criticizing both Republican presidential candidates, former
President Gerald Ford says he would not have spoken at Bob Jones
University and wouldn't have criticized Pat Robertson and Jerry
Falwell. ``It would be better for candidates to stay away from any
group that is so dedicated to a single religious conviction,'' Ford
said of George W. Bush's visit to the university. Ford also called
some of John McCain's comments about Robertson and Falwell ``poor
judgment _ any candidate should not call someone evil ... I would
not use that language myself.''
</P>
<P>
   FOUR DAYS TO SUPER TUESDAY, AND MCCAIN NEEDS HELP
</P>
<P>
   Four days before Republicans vote in 13 states, there were no
signs that John McCain is closing George W. Bush's wide leads in
California, Ohio, Missouri and Georgia polls. New York is
competitive and most of New England is leaning McCain's way, but
some advisers warned privately that McCain's 's candidacy was in
jeopardy unless he could generate fresh support this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   DESTROY THE VILLAGE TO SAVE IT
</P>
<P>
   John McCain said today the Republican Party is headed for
another defeat, and that's what sparked him to challenge the party
establishment's ties to some conservative religious leaders and
campaign donors. ``If you want business as usual, the Republican
Party has lost the last two presidential elections, the last two
congressional elections, and we're headed down the same path,''
McCain said. ``I had to take on the Republican establishment and
status quo.''
</P>
<P>
   THE MESSAGE, REMEMBER THE MESSAGE
</P>
<P>
   John McCain is railing against George W. Bush's campaign tactics
and the evangelical leaders who ``unfairly attacked'' one of his
advisers. Suddenly an aide jumps up from a hotel sofa, leans over a
tray of coffee cups and slips him a note. ``Social Security,'' is
scrawled on the paper, a reminder that _ once again _ the boss is
off message. Getting the hint, McCain abruptly changes the subject
in an interview with a group of newspaper editors and launches into
his plans to bolster Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY'S WIFE COMES OFF THE BENCH
</P>
<P>
   In a sign of spousal and female unity, Bill Bradley's wife,
Ernestine, made plans to tour upstate New York with the wives of
New York Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan and Los Angeles Lakers
basketball coach Phil Jackson: Elizabeth Moynihan and June Jackson.
They're slated to go to Rochester, Buffalo and Albany.
</P>
<P>
   FUND-RAISER IN THE FAMILY
</P>
<P>
   Karenna Gore Schiff, the oldest daughter of Al Gore, raised
$40,000 for her father's presidential campaign at Cities, a
Washington restaurant, packing in 150 young professional Gen-Xers
like herself. Gore Schiff, 26, said her generation tried to
``cultivate an ironic detachment'' but she urged her listeners to
overcome their cynicism and support her father.
</P>
<P>
   SOUND OF A DIFFERENT DRUMMER
</P>
<P>
   Rat-tat-tat, rat-tat-tat. That's the sound of a new addition to
John McCain's campaign rallies. Backers who applauded during one of
his speeches Thursday were joined by the pounding sound of a drum.
``Now we have an Al Gore drum,'' McCain chuckled. The reference was
to one of his stock phrases _ that he'll ``beat Al Gore like a
drum.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
