<HEADER>
A5931 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-DJEBAR-LANGUAGES-900(     03-03 0947
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DJEBAR-LANGUAGES-900(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN ALGERIAN WRITER FINDS HER LOST PAST THROUGH LANGUAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By LESLIE CAMHI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``So Vast the Prison,'' the new novel by Assia
Djebar, begins inside the protected walls of a women's hammam, or
public bath, in a small Algerian city in the 1960s. The narrator's
mother-in-law, speaking Arabic, begs a friend to stay a bit longer.
The friend replies:
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot possibly stay later today. The enemy is at home!''
</P>
<P>
   She left.
</P>
<P>
   ```The enemy?' I asked, slowly turning to my mother-in-law.''
</P>
<P>
   Her mother-in-law explains that the Arabic word for enemy is
also the word local women use to refer to their husbands when
speaking among themselves.
</P>
<P>
   That moment, which reveals language's multiple meanings as well
as the bitter traces of women's experience, is typical of Djebar's
work. Like other writers who have had to adopt different languages
and homes, she is something of a cultural nomad. Djebar, 63, was
born in Algeria, lives in the United States and Paris and writes in
the language of her homeland's French colonizers. It is a
magisterial French that is both a legacy of 130 years of colonial
occupation and an instrument of liberation from the constraints of
tradition and Islam.
</P>
<P>
   French plays a new role in today's Algeria, where for the last
eight years a savage civil war between Islamic militants and an
army-backed government has cost over 100,000 lives. Francophone
writers and intellectuals have been frequent targets of
assassination by both Islamic militants and shadowy
counterinsurgency forces.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a man who has lost his homeland, writing becomes a place
to live,'' the German philosopher Theodor Adorno observed, while
living in exile in Los Angeles during World War II. Djebar has made
the French language her domain, which she has won back slowly, over
the course of years, from the language of the colonizers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Think of German Jews, writing after the Shoah,'' Djebar said
in French during a recent visit to New York. ``German is their
language, and yet they suffer in it. Well, little by little, I
began to question my own relation to French and the memories it
carried for me.''
</P>
<P>
   The result is a complex, passionate and highly literary oeuvre:
nine novels and several books of essays, short fiction and poetry,
many of which have won international awards. (Seven of her novels,
``So Vast the Prison'' among them, and a collection of short
stories have been translated into English or are forthcoming.) In
her work, which also includes two films, she explores the roots of
Algeria's current crisis in language and history.
</P>
<P>
   Djebar was born in 1936 in Cherchel, a coastal town about an
hour west of Algiers. Her father was the only native teacher of
French in a colonial school. Her mother was descended from a family
with deep roots in Berber and Andalusian culture.
</P>
<P>
   She spoke Arabic with her mother and listened to her
grandmother's ramblings in Berber. But she was educated in French,
since teaching Arabic was forbidden by the colonial authorities. At
the age of 10, when her female cousins left school and assumed the
veil required by Islam, her father insisted that she continue her
education. So for her, French became identified as an ambivalent
source of liberty. ``Fantasia: An Algerian Cavalcade'' (1985), her
first mature novel, explored this fractured linguistic identity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fantasia started from my simple perception, at the age of 40,
that I was incapable of saying words of love in French,'' Djebar
said. ``The book tells the double story of how the French language
arrived in Algeria with violence and the military conquests of the
19th century, and the way I learned French as a child _ my first
words and how strange the culture seemed to me. First it was the
language of the enemy, then it became a kind of stepmother, in
relation to the maternal tongue of Arabic.''
</P>
<P>
   At 19, Djebar was the first Algerian woman to attend the Ecole
Normale Superieure, the elite, state-run French training school for
teachers, where she studied history. She soon dropped out, however,
to join the FLN, the Algerian movement for national liberation, in
Tunisia.
</P>
<P>
   Returning to a newly independent Algeria in 1962, she became the
first woman to teach at Algiers University. She had already written
three novels under the nom de plume she has used ever since. (The
pseudonym, adopted as a veil of discretion for a woman publishing
in a Muslim society, now shields her family in Algeria from
reprisals.)
</P>
<P>
   The new state increasingly sought to impose a single language
(classical Arabic) on a nation that was 90 percent illiterate, with
a cultural elite largely trained in French and a broader population
that used a mix of popular Arabic dialects, French and several
Berber languages.
</P>
<P>
   In 1965, Djebar, chafing under the constraints of the new
government, went to live in Paris, but in 1974, longing for home,
she returned. (Two years later, the government adopted Islam as the
state religion, and the Arabization process intensified.)
</P>
<P>
   For the next two decades (and over the course of two marriages)
_ before the current conflict made travel in Algeria more difficult
_ she shuttled continually between the two countries, as if between
two halves of a long historical equation.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a woman between two worlds,'' says Clarissa Zimra, a
professor of comparative literature at the University of Southern
Illinois at Carbondale. ``She says: `This is where history has
landed me. And therefore, I will make it my territory.'''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Voices Which Besiege Me,'' a recent collection of
essays that has not yet been translated into English, Djebar
reflects on the fertile multilingualism of her native land. There,
centuries of successive invaders have imposed Punic, Latin,
classical and dialectical Arabic, Turkish and French over several
native Berber languages. Djebar is one of the Algerian writers,
including the novelist Kateb Yacine (whose funeral in 1989 was the
occasion for Berber demonstrations) and Tahar Djaout (a poet,
novelist and journalist murdered in 1993), who have invoked this
pre-Islamic, pre-Arabic past as a challenge to both fundamentalist
and government orthodoxy.
</P>
<P>
   Internationally, Djebar's approach to language and history has
been compared to that of the Caribbean writer Wilson Harris. Born
in 1921 in Guyana (then a British colony) and educated in English,
Harris (who is descended from a mix of English, Hindu, Indian,
Afro- Caribbean and Amerindian ancestors) has written more than 20
novels, which slide between an ancient or imaginary and a more
recent past.
</P>
<P>
   On the telephone from England, where he has lived since the
1960s, Harris talked about Guyana's ancient Amerindian peoples, the
Arawakf and the Macusis. ``I do not speak their languages,'' the
writer said. ``But the landscape of Guyana is saturated with their
names. And this has affected my writing. I have the sensation of
languages that come into English and change the tone of English. So
that you get crosscultural significance.''
</P>
<P>
   In Algeria the stakes of such exchanges can be deadly. Djebar
began writing ``Algerian White'' (coming next year from Seven
Stories Press) after three close friends _ a psychiatrist, a
sociologist and her brother-in-law, a playwright _ were
assassinated. The book reconstructs the last moments of 19 Algerian
writers: from Albert Camus, who died in a car crash in 1960, to an
unidentified Muslim woman, a teacher gunned down in 1994. A hymn to
friendship and the enduring power of language, it is also a requiem
for a nation's unfinished literature.
</P>
<P>
   ``So Vast the Prison'' seems remote from these harrowing
memories. In three sections, it recounts a modern Algerian woman's
observation of her disintegrating marriage; the history of
archaeological searches for the lost alphabet of the Berber tribes;
and the carefully reconstructed life stories of the writer's mother
and grandmother. For Djebar, the middle section, in which the
ancient Greek historian Polybe appears as a character, holds
particular significance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Polybe had seen his own country destroyed, and then was
brought as a Roman captive to Carthage to describe its
destruction,'' she explained. ``And when that was over, the Romans
told him, you're free, you can go home. But when he finally arrived
at his native city he witnessed the famous sack of Corinth. He was
over 70 years old.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``So Vast the Prison,'' Djebar writes: ``Polybe the historian
... Polybe the deported writer, returning in the twilight of his
life to his native land, sees that he no longer has a land or even
a country (the latter enslaved and in chains). All that he has is a
language whose beauty warms him and that he uses to enlighten the
enemies of yesterday who are now his allies. He writes. And his
language, his hand, his memory and all his powers just before they
fade, contribute to this untimely, yet necessary transmission.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When I think about Polybe,'' Djebar later reflected, ``I ask
myself, what are the conflicts of Algeria today in relation to
these past centuries of destruction? And somehow I feel calmer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
