<HEADER>
A5935 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-JAPAN-CLEANLINESS-NYT     03-03 1046
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-CLEANLINESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPANIES HOPE TO CASH IN ON JAPANESE OBSESSION WITH PERSONAL
HYGIENE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CALVIN SIMS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ In a country with cramped living quarters, crammed
subways and overcrowded streets, it stands to reason that the
Japanese often go to great lengths to avoid germs.
</P>
<P>
   Shoes are not worn in the home, people with colds wear surgical
masks in public and waiters spray their hands with disinfectant
before serving customers. At the cash register, money is placed on
a small tray and not in the hand. Body odor is simply not
tolerated.
</P>
<P>
   But lately the obsession with cleanliness has reached new
heights with the introduction of a variety of products ranging from
deodorized underwear to breath-freshening lipstick, all intended to
keep the body free of odor.
</P>
<P>
   The main targets of the sales campaign are older people,
especially middle-aged men. According to cosmetics companies and
public surveys, they smell worse than the rest of Japanese society.
</P>
<P>
   Shiseido Co., Japan's largest cosmetic maker, said it has
discovered the source of body odor in people over 40 _ a substance
called noneal, which researchers said is more pronounced among
middle-aged men.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our data shows that older women and men produce the same
amount of noneal but that we smell more odor coming from men
because they tend to be less hygienic than women,'' said Shoji
Nakamura, a Shiseido perfumer, who is credited with discovering the
offending agent.
</P>
<P>
   In September, Shiseido introduced a line of shampoos, lotions
and deodorants that it says reduce body odor in older people by
inhibiting the breakdown of fatty acid in skin that creates noneal.
</P>
<P>
   Noneal, which has a ``greasy, grassy odor,'' is rarely found in
the body odor of people in their 20s and 30s but increases in
volume and strength with aging, the researchers said.
</P>
<P>
   Shiseido said it expects sales of the new product line, called
Care Garden, to reach $30 million by March, more than five times
its initial target.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's mainly salarymen in their 50s who are buying it,'' said
Kyoko Asakura, manager for Matsumoto Kiyoshi, a discount drug store
in the Ginza shopping district. ``Many of them come into the store
and shyly ask for `the product that takes away old man's smell.'''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to unpleasant body odor, Shiseido said that its
market research showed that Japanese people were most concerned
about bad breath and bad smells produced by the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   Many young women like Miki Ishimoto, a 21-year-old student, say
they are afraid to touch a subway strap after an older man, or
ojisan as they are known in Japan, has handled it. And if an ojisan
should accidentally brush up against her: ``I feel so contaminated
that I immediately go to wash myself,'' Ms. Ishimoto said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Shiseido is not the only company trying to capitalize on the
germ phobia. Etiquette Water, a health drink made of fruit enzymes
and minerals, promises to eliminate bad breath and underarm odor.
Elizabeth Arden, Japan, is marketing the Lip Lip Hooray line of
lipsticks that contains citric acid that the company says
neutralizes the compounds that can cause bad breath.
</P>
<P>
   SSK Corp. has a line of T-shirts that contain deodorant fibers
that it says eliminate foul odors when exposed to the sun's
ultraviolet rays. The deodorizing agent remains in the shirt when
it is washed, SSK said.
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone thinks the preoccupation with cleanliness is
healthy. Koichiro Fujita, a professor of immunology at Tokyo
Medical and Dental University, said that while the Japanese have
long been attentive to personal hygiene, they have become ``slaves
to smell,'' succumbing to the recent barrage of advertising by
deodorant producers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The marketers have brainwashed people to be afraid of their
own smell, which is supposed to be something natural, something
that as a living creature is a way of asserting I am here,'' Fujita
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our country is suffering from super cleanliness syndrome and
it's so extreme that even elementary school children are afraid to
make a bad smell in the bathroom for fear that they will be teased
or bullied,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Fujita, citing a recent rise in asthma, allergies and dermatitis
in Japan, said that too much cleanliness is actually detrimental to
one's health because it reduces the body's ability to fight off
infections and diseases. His book ``Cleanliness is a Sickness'' has
sold 30,000 copies.
</P>
<P>
   But some people have a simpler explanation why the Japanese have
so readily embraced products that eliminate any distinctive
personal smell.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before these products were created, the norm for Japanese men
was to wear that awful smelling hair tonic, and they really didn't
care how they smelled,'' said Harueko Kato, a sociologist at Tokyo
Women's Christian University. ``Today, whether it's in the office,
subways trains, or at home, Japanese men want to be liked, so they
are trying to improve their image, and I think it's great,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   While the Japanese eschew bad odors, they also avoid strong
fragrances and generally like their cosmetic products, soaps, and
incense to have subtle scents. Indeed, cosmetic industry figures
show that the Japanese buy more deodorant products intended to
prevent bad smells than perfumes that create a strong individual
fragrance.
</P>
<P>
   Shiseido said that its new line of cosmetics was not
specifically targeted at middle-aged men but rather for all people
over 40. The company said its market research showed that people of
all ages and both men and women were buying the products.
</P>
<P>
   With Japan's population aging faster than those of most other
industrialized countries, Shiseido said it hopes the product will
become a part of daily grooming for the elderly. People in their
70s secrete almost 10 times more of the fatty acid that turns into
noneal, the smelly substance, than do people in their 40s, the
company said.
</P>
<P>
   In a consumer survey conducted by Shiseido, a grandmother told
the company that after using Care Garden she was no longer
concerned that her strong body odor might offend her young
grandson, who sometimes sleeps with her in the same bed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
