<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-03 18:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5937 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-ART-PAPERS05-COX     03-03 1982
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-PAPERS05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Art Papers Magazine is an Atlanta-based review, nationally
respected for contemporary coverage, but the publication may be
turning a final page
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, March 5.
 &HT;    By Tom Sabulis
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Art Papers is a small magazine. If you didn't know
from its circulation _ about 1,500 subscribers, a press run of
5,000 _ you might guess from visiting its office, a Fonzie-era
classroom in a retired elementary school, which also houses a
community radio station and the Atlanta Jugglers Association.
</P>
<P>
   Or you might get a clue from meeting the board president, a
self-effacing sculptor with no business experience, whose
large-scale artwork has utilized junked cars, telephone poles and
an old school bus.
</P>
<P>
   Scan some of the magazine's headlines. Witness ``Tensions
Confronting Today's Turkish Artists'' and ``Unnecessary Duplicates:
Identity and Technology in the Performances of Laurie Anderson.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, it's not a must-read for everybody.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the size and specialized subject of Art Papers belies its
influence and history and the national cachet it gives its
hometown, which has suffered a recent spate of arts-event crises
and leadership losses.
</P>
<P>
   This esoteric, nonprofit art journal, with its Southern focus
and international reach, may be the city's least-known arts
institution. And suddenly, much like the Arts Festival of Atlanta,
which folded in 1998, it embodies a rich tradition that's on the
verge of dying after building heavy debt during one really bad
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're on the verge of extinction,'' says Evan Levy, the
40-year-old board president and sculptor.
</P>
<P>
   But, as it turns out, hanging tough. It's merely on life
support.
</P>
<P>
   Born in the late '70s heyday of public funding for the arts, Art
Papers began life as the Atlanta Art Workers Coalition Newsletter,
an awkward, leftist-sounding title for the mouthpiece of an
artists' rights group.
</P>
<P>
   After absorbing another magazine, Contemporary Art Southeast, it
became Atlanta Art Papers with the March 1980 issue, evolving into
just plain Art Papers in January 1981. (It added ``magazine'' to
the title more recently, in part to help cut down on phone calls
inquiring about paper products.)
</P>
<P>
   Since its earliest days, the magazine has helped establish the
South as fertile turf for contemporary art. Fans appreciate it for
recognizing artists early in their careers _ such as Atlanta's own
Radcliffe Bailey _ without filtering its views through the
exclusive prism of the New York gallery world.
</P>
<P>
   ``It offers a fresh view,'' says Robin Bernat, a local video and
book artist whose work will be included in the upcoming Whitney
Biennial in New York. ``Art Papers reviewed my work very early in
my career, when I first graduated from art school and opened my own
studio. It was important, because it was prior to my having gallery
representation.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the key Atlanta arts figures leaving the city, Harriet
Sanford, director of the Fulton County Arts Council, says, ``It's a
critical journal that not only helps us get a sense of where we
stand artistically, it helps keep us on the map.''
</P>
<P>
   Art Papers maintains its edge by avoiding ``mainstream and
blue-chip galleries,'' says New York free-lancer Susan Canning, one
of the magazine's dozen or so contributing editors.
</P>
<P>
   It spotlights newer galleries and alternative spaces, such as
the Lump Gallery in Raleigh and Exit Art in New York _ places the
glossier, more established magazines such as Artforum and Art in
America are less likely to feature. The January/February issue
includes reviews from Miami, New Orleans, Washington, Richmond, New
York, Philadelphia, Chicago, Minneapolis/St. Paul, Denver, Kansas
City, Los Angeles, Portland, San Francisco, Berkeley, Istanbul and
Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Editor Michael Pittari coordinates it all from Art Papers'
office _ blackboard still intact on the wall _ in the old Moreland
Elementary School. The building operates as the Little Five Points
Community Center, a sort of boardinghouse for nonprofit
organizations: Along with the jugglers association and radio
station WRFG-FM (89.3), the Horizon Theatre is another full-time
tenant.
</P>
<P>
   Pittari, 32, and his contributing editors supervise more than 50
free-lance writers and critics around the country. The magazine
covers the Southeast more than other areas, but it also
concentrates on the West Coast and the Northeast. ``It's very
difficult to ignore what's happening in those places,'' Pittari
says.
</P>
<P>
   For nearly a quarter-century, the magazine has made its
grass-roots mark with long, essay-format reviews, often presented
in a dense, gray format. Art Papers was an early champion of folk
art, publishing its first major reviews in 1982 _ before
Washington's Corcoran Gallery of Art introduced self-taught
African-American artists to a wider audience. Some of the bigger
names lauded in their pre-celebrity mode _ performance artist
Laurie Anderson and MacArthur Foundation ``genius'' grant recipient
Kara Walker.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its boutique size, the magazine remains a warehouse of a
resource for its supporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It keeps us afloat in information and ideas,'' says Louise
Shaw, a local consultant and former director of the recently
renamed Atlanta Contemporary Art Center. ``Art Papers has
legitimized Atlanta and the Southeast. It's the only serious art
journal being distributed out of the region.''
</P>
<P>
   Laura C. Lieberman, a co-founder who served as editor from 1979
to 1984, stresses the archival importance of reviews by more than
1,000 writers. ``It is the only history of artists in the South
that exists,'' says Lieberman, now development coordinator with the
American Museum of Papermaking in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The bimonthly lands on newstands ($7 cover price) all over the
country. In Manhattan, you can find it at Tower Books on Lafayette
Street and at Printed Matter in SoHo. In Seattle, it goes to the
Henry Art Gallery at the University of Washington; in Chicago, the
Museum of Contemporary Art.
</P>
<P>
   Locally, Borders Books &AMP; Music carries a few copies, as do some
independent bookstores and the High Museum of Art and Emory
University's Michael C. Carlos Museum.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, however, the magazine could be out of circulation for
good. It is enduring what Levy calls ``the biggest crisis in the
history of the publication,'' referring to some recent
mismanagement that left it with a debt of about $70,000.
</P>
<P>
   The financial abyss, discovered suddenly last fall, stunned
board members, who won't discuss specifics because of an ongoing
investigation and audit of last year's records. Staff members had
to be let go. The executive director and business manager resigned.
The magazine's developing Web site (artpapers.org) was put on hold.
All this at a time when the magazine's National Endowment for the
Arts grant had been cut roughly in half; Art Papers historically
gets 30 percent of its funding from grants, Levy says. Its normal
annual operating budget is $210,000 to $230,000.
</P>
<P>
   As some were fearing the next issue would not make it to press,
the local arts community fashioned a rescue. Photographer Lucinda
Bunnen, an Art Papers board member, called friends and raised
$25,000 in three days.
</P>
<P>
   An auction fund-raiser last month at Lowe Gallery was jammed by
600 arts enthusiasts who cleared the walls of more than 150 works
of art donated by local galleries and artists. The benefit raised
about $40,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``That will help get us off the hook,'' says Pittari, one of
only two remaining full-time staffers. ``But it's important from a
business standpoint to show our supporters that we're going to make
changes to make sure it doesn't happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   A more accessible approach is key for survival, and to serve a
changing audience. Senior editor Jerry Cullum, a part-time staffer
who has been with Art Papers since 1984, says the magazine
typically dealt in ``a fairly academic manner'' with the
contemporary art scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we're trying to be intelligent but much more informal,''
explains Cullum, a painter and poet who also reviews visual arts
for The Atlanta Journal-Constitution. ``We've always been strong as
a magazine read by artists themselves. But we've made a great
effort to branch out'' to other segments of the arts audience.
</P>
<P>
   One sign of the times: more stories relating art to film and
music.
</P>
<P>
   Arts insiders say it's crucial that Art Papers succeed in
remodeling itself.
</P>
<P>
   If the magazine folded, ``there would be a real drastic
reduction in opportunity for artists from the area,'' says Kathryn
Hixson, editor of New Art Examiner in Chicago, a competing
publication and one of the few surviving regional art journals in
America. (Some recent publishing casualties in the field: Reflex in
Seattle and Artpaper in Minneapolis.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though we've become more globalized and Internetted,''
Hixson says, ``it's more important that these kinds of regional
magazines stay afloat to serve those communities. Because they're
not gonna get coverage from (magazines based in) New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Steven Vroom, who teaches art criticism at Cornish College of
the Arts in Seattle, uses Art Papers in his classroom and is trying
to get the school library to subscribe. ``As far as content,
usually every issue has something thoughtful, unique,
problematic.''
</P>
<P>
   At the recent benefit auction, the Fulton County Arts Council
showed its support by buying $5,000 worth of art for its art loan
program. It also plans to give the magazine another $5,000 for
technical support, Sanford says.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from making its editorial product more reader-friendly,
the magazine has hired a new director of operations and is
attempting proactive business solutions. Brainstorming with local
museums about ways to increase circulation. Thinking about
databasing its archives. Persuading the phone company not to cut
off service.
</P>
<P>
   Another concern: strengthening its board of directors _
dominated by artists _ with business people who know how to raise
money and monitor the bottom line. ``We don't have a big corporate
presence on the board,'' Bunnen says. ``But we're going to address
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Cullum says the debt reduction has raised spirits in the office.
But the magazine's long-term health is still a critical concern for
arts supporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we need it more than ever,'' Lieberman says. ``It's
harder and harder for artists to see a reason to stay here. Art
Papers makes it easier for collectors to justify buying a Southern
artist. Everyone in the arts in Atlanta needs to have Art Papers
working.''
</P>
<P>
   AHEAD OF THE CURVE
</P>
<P>
   Over the years Atlanta's Art Papers Magazine, a small but savvy
journal, has reviewed blossoming artists and published incisive
critics before they attained national celebrity. Some examples:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Performance artist Laurie Anderson was featured on the
March/April 1979 issue, when she was interviewed by an unknown
artist named John Turturro, before he went on to a successful
acting career in such movies as ``Barton Fink'' and ``Quiz Show.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  In the mid-1980s, the magazine published essays by Henry Louis
Gates and Cornel West before they established themselves as
intellectual stars and prolific authors.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  A 1995 review singled out artist Kara Walker, who attended the
Atlanta College of Art, before she was featured on the cover of
major art magazines in New York and London. In 1997, at the age of
27, Walker was awarded a MacArthur Foundation ``genius'' grant.
</P>
<P>
   How to Subscribe
</P>
<P>
   _ Send a check for $35 for a one-year subscription (six issues)
to:
</P>
<P>
   Art Papers
</P>
<P>
   P.O. Box 5748
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta, Ga. 31107
</P>
<P>
   _ For an online purchase, go to info(at)artpapers.org
</P>
<P>
   _ Or call 404-588-1837
</P>
<P>
   Tom Sabulis writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
