<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-03 18:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5938 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-DELTA-SEWAGE03-COX     03-03 2141
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELTA-SEWAGE03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Millions of dollars in federal money bypass a Mississippi
community made up of the poorest of the poor
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, March 5.
 &HT;    By Anne Rochell Konigsmark
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME, Miss. _ Emmanuel Jackson remembers a time, not long ago,
when most people in this tiny village had outdoor toilets.
</P>
<P>
   Things weren't so bad then.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's worse now,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Time and ``progress'' have made this Mississippi Delta community
more miserable, not less. At least with outhouses, the waste went
into a hole in the ground. Today, with no sewage system and broken
or inadequate septic tanks, much of what drains from sinks and
flushes out of indoor toilets winds up in ditches beside people's
homes and along the dusty gravel streets. In the summer, the smell
is unbearable. When it rains, raw sewerage washes over yards and
into the road. Toilets back up. Snakes are a daily problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like the Third World here,'' says resident Willie
Knighten.
</P>
<P>
   It's been 15 years since the Rev. Jesse Jackson stood in Sugar
Ditch, a destitute section of Tunica, and dubbed the Delta
``America's Ethiopia.'' The open sewage streams of Sugar Ditch are
gone, and in many larger Delta towns like Tunica, there have been
improvements in the standard of living. Millions of dollars' worth
of federal grants and the development of casinos have brought some
changes to a region struggling to diversify after more than a
century of growing cotton.
</P>
<P>
   But in the shadows are Rome and places like it _ poor, mostly
black communities where even the most basic needs are not met. As
the nation enjoys its most prosperous era, the people of Rome stand
by and watch, painfully aware of being left behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have much here besides water and lights,'' Emmanuel
Jackson says, standing behind his frame house, looking down at a
ditch murky with dirty dishwater and raw sewage. He is unemployed
right now, and can't travel far: His car broke down. ``The county
will come through and mow the grass by the road in the summer, but
that's about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson won't believe it until he sees it, but a sewerage system
is in the works, thanks to years of effort by a small and
determined group of Rome citizens. It took battling the
indifference from the powers that be, who were reluctant even to
accept the $1 million grant applied for and obtained by the
citizens. It is only the first step on a long road to a better
life. And Rome is only one of perhaps dozens of communities in need
in the Delta.
</P>
<P>
   Delta native Hodding Carter III, former editor and associate
publisher of the Delta Democrat Times, says he didn't know anyone
still lived in Rome, which is at the north end of Sunflower County.
But he knows such communities exist.
</P>
<P>
   ``With almost all federal programs, there are going to be some
communities falling through the cracks,'' says Carter, who is
president and CEO of the John S. and James L. Knight Foundation.
``Now, you have even more sharply etched isolation, pockets of
implosion and economic deflation.''
</P>
<P>
   TWO COMMUNITIES,
</P>
<P>
   WORLDS APART
</P>
<P>
   Rome used to be a community of field hands, but machines do most
of the farm jobs these days. Many people have moved away, and the
ones who remain seem stymied by a lifelong hunch that no one cares
_ particularly the white people who run most things. They are
trapped by their own lack of education and resources. And so they
watch their situation deteriorate, year by year, decade by decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the people here, they just don't know how to get what
they want,'' says Hime ``Skinner'' Weekly, who owns one of the two
nightclubs in town. ``They are so used to people telling them what
to do, they don't know how or they don't even want to try to
upgrade this town.''
</P>
<P>
   Racial tension is almost palpable here, so there is little
cooperation or even communication between blacks and whites. Weekly
and other black residents accuse whites of clinging to old
plantation notions of superiority. The white residents accuse
blacks of being unable to take care of themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Sunflower County Supervisor Barry Bryant, a white Rome resident,
says he tries not to judge people by the color of their skin, but
he also believes segregation is ``human nature.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in Martin Luther King's speech `I have a dream,'''
he says. ``But we don't go to church together, we don't eat
together or live together.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he would like to see that change, Bryant says, ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   AND THE WALLS COME
</P>
<P>
   TUMBLING DOWN
</P>
<P>
   About 250 people, 95 percent of them black, live along the dusty
gravel roads of Rome. Their homes are fragile wood frame houses or
house trailers guarded by dogs with threatening snarls. The ravaged
downtown looks like Main Street Sarajevo: The facades on some of
the abandoned brick buildings are dangerously close to collapsing.
Inside an old grocery, the shelves and freezer cases and even boxes
of Italian dressing and hot sauce lie in shambles on the floor.
People have thrown bottles and cans inside for what must be years,
judging from the mountainous piles. Another store is practically
carpeted in broken glass. Residents say the owners of the stores
packed up and left many years ago. There is only one open store, a
service station out on U.S. 49.
</P>
<P>
   If ever a community was in need of a leg up, it would seem to be
this one. Yet none of the $40 million provided by the Mid-Delta
Empowerment Zone, the latest in a string of federal programs
designed for the troubled region, will ever reach Rome. The
boundary of the zone, which contains parts of six counties, is
about 15 miles south, in the middle of Sunflower County.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how they cut us out,'' says community activist
Betty Smith, who lives in nearby Drew, a town also not in the zone.
``The empowerment zone is like a cover, so people will say, `Oh,
they're doing something now.'''
</P>
<P>
   INFRASTRUCTURE
</P>
<P>
   DRAWS THE MONEY
</P>
<P>
   Being left out of the empowerment zone created a fresh sense of
bitterness in Rome, even among the whites, who are generally better
off than the black residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``For goodness' sake, the empowerment zone includes Indianola,
and they are the only town in Sunflower County that already had a
Wal-Mart,'' says Bryant, owner of the one store in Rome. Indianola,
thanks to the empowerment zone, has a $4 million work force
training center and a Dollar General distribution facility that
employs more than 400 people.
</P>
<P>
   Knighten, who is black, says, ``You want to see poverty, come
here. The empowerment zone is not doing what it was supposed to do.
That money was supposed to be for poor communities.''
</P>
<P>
   Harry Bowie, co-chairman of the empowerment zone, says there
were geographical reasons why the north end of Sunflower was not
included. The land mass had to be contiguous, and it had to be
built on census tracts, not counties. Moreover, the grant is
designed to attract industry by providing matching funds.
Businesses are drawn to areas that have infrastructures in place.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Indianola, there was an opportunity to create
opportunity,'' he says. ``You can't use the resources of the
empowerment zone to rebuild small communities like Rome.''
</P>
<P>
   The empowerment zone, created in 1994, got off to a slow start.
It was so mismanaged at first that the state Department of Economic
and Community Development threatened to send the money back to
Washington. With a new director, a more streamlined application
process and a slightly smaller board, things are moving forward,
Bowie says. About half the money has been granted, and about a
dozen businesses have moved into the Delta. In Sunflower County,
the unemployment rate has dropped 7 percent. It used to hover near
20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happens in the empowerment zone is good for the entire
Delta,'' Bowie says.
</P>
<P>
   AT THE BOTTOM
</P>
<P>
   OF THE ECONOMIC HEAP
</P>
<P>
   The statistics for the 18 northwest Mississippi counties that
make up the Delta can be numbing. Its counties are at the bottom of
most rankings in a state that ranks worst or close to it on most
national lists. Of the 16 Mississippi counties with poverty rates
above 30 percent, 12 are in the Delta. Sunflower County and Holmes
County are two of the poorest counties in the nation, according to
the U.S. Census.
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. Robert Clark, the speaker pro-tem and the first black
person elected to the Legislature, is frustrated that most of his
native Holmes County was left out of the empowerment zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``So far I have not seen any changes because of the zone,'' he
says. In fact, unemployment in Holmes County has gone up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whoever drew up the empowerment zone did not have a grasp of
what was needed in the Delta,'' he says. ``I quit going to the
board meetings because it was a waste of my time. It is nothing but
feel-good talk.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowie says there is no comprehensive program set up to deal with
communities like Rome.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was an agrarian community, but once that pool of labor is
gone, the grocery stores and such go, and the town goes to the
pits,'' he says. ``I don't know of a program that looks at that.
But there are individuals who do. I have seen towns that have
gotten inspired and thought about what they can do for
themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   That's just what Rome is doing. Through the efforts of a small
group of citizens, there is a happy chapter in the story of Rome.
The village should have a sewerage system in about a year.
</P>
<P>
   TOWNSPEOPLE MOTIVATED
</P>
<P>
   TO HELP THEMSELVES
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, a black church in the town formed the Rome
Community Development Organization. The members asked the governing
board of the Rome Water Association, a seven-person body that was
and always had been all white, to apply for grant money for a sewer
system. The board is the only official body in the village, since
there is no mayor or police or fire department. They were
reluctant, citing residents' poverty and inability to pay bills. So
the organization raised money to send Willie and Irie Knighten to a
nearby community college to learn how to write grants.
</P>
<P>
   The Knightens then went to the county supervisors and persuaded
them to let the Rome residents apply for $1 million in federal
money. The money was awarded in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Next, the residents had to persuade the Rome water board to
accept the money and take n the project.
</P>
<P>
   That was more difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a problem,'' says Billy Patterson, a water
board member. ``We have water customers who can't pay a $25 water
bill. You put a $25 sewer bill on top of that, and what's going to
happen? Probably half this community is way below the poverty line.
They're welfare people, food stamp people, three, four generations
back.''
</P>
<P>
   The water system is a cooperative, which means everyone in Rome
owns it. So the Knightens asked the water board to have a meeting
last fall. They got several dozen residents to attend the meeting.
They took a vote on accepting the money to build a sewer system,
and more than 30 people were in favor of it. Several residents, all
whites _ some of them on the water board _ voted against it.
</P>
<P>
   At that same meeting, two board seats were up for re-election.
The residents voted Irie Knighten and a black woman to be the first
black members of the Rome water board.
</P>
<P>
   SEEKING SOLUTIONS
</P>
<P>
   FOR THE FUTURE
</P>
<P>
   Willie Knighten, a medical technologist who is studying for a
master's degree, says she has great hopes for Rome.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to get residents involved,'' she says. ``I think this
community is going to be an example. We're going to see some
progress.''
</P>
<P>
   Patterson is not so sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people need a way to make a living,'' he says. ``Rome
isn't going to make it. There is no economic base.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter wonders as well about the viability of tiny Delta towns
whose roots are in an agrarian culture that is fast disappearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no longer a need for these little towns,'' he says.
``There is no place for unskilled labor communities. Exactly how
much money should any society spend to prop up circumstances that
have no economic fundamentals?''
</P>
<P>
   Bowie would like to see communities like Rome link up with
nearby larger towns.
</P>
<P>
   ``They could be sort of like the suburbs, but in a rural area,''
he suggests. ``They could share a tax base with a larger town.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knightens and other Rome residents remain optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once we get this sewerage system, we've got something,'' says
Irie Knighten, who says he wants to run for county supervisor when
Bryant's term is up in four years. ``Then people might give us
grants to build businesses. We've got the ammunition now.''
</P>
<P>
   Anne Rochell Konigsmark writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
