<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000303.0196 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-03 18:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5939 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-EPISCOPAL-REFLECT04-C     03-03 1410
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EPISCOPAL-REFLECT04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Retiring Bishop Frank Allan is getting in touch with his
artistic side, setting up a shop for artisans to benefit Episcopal
ministriesBy Gayle White
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For almost 13 years, Bishop Frank Allan has been a
shepherd of the Episcopal Diocese of Atlanta. Now, he's becoming a
shopkeeper.
</P>
<P>
   Allan is trading in one kind of miter for another _ his bishop's
pointed hat for wood joints.
</P>
<P>
   Among the products he will be selling at the Work of Our Hands,
a store for arts and crafts, are his own handmade wooden toys and
bowls.
</P>
<P>
   The shop, featuring the work of more than 100 Southern artisans
in weaving, pottery, basketry, quilting, caning and painting, will
open soon in Atlanta. The nonprofit corporation, which will benefit
some Atlanta Episcopal ministries, takes its name from Psalm 90:17,
which asks God to ``prosper the work of our hands.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My belief is we're closest to being in the image of God when
we're involved in creating,'' said Allan, who first took up
woodworking many years ago when his father passed down to him an
old Sears and Roebuck scroll saw.
</P>
<P>
   He began turning bowls last year after his staff gave him a
lathe _ ``I sort of hinted,'' he admits. In his almost-empty office
sit three smooth bowls of different sizes and different woods _
maple, magnolia and red mahogany _ and a communion chalice he has
made.
</P>
<P>
   Although he will always be an Episcopal bishop, Allan's last day
as head of the Atlanta diocese is March 12. He had planned to step
down a week earlier when his elected successor, the Rev. Robert
Trache of Richmond, was to be consecrated. But late last week the
diocese called off Trache's consecration, saying the bishop-elect
had failed to disclose significant matters in his personal and
financial life.
</P>
<P>
   Allan wrote in a statement to North Georgia Episcopalians that
he was ``grieved'' by the decision but agreed with it. ``It had
been my hope to end my tenure as your bishop on a note of
celebration instead of grief and disappointment,'' he wrote.
``There is no doubt in my mind that it is appropriate for me to
move on.''
</P>
<P>
   Parish priest at heart
</P>
<P>
   Allan, who will turn 65 in May, grew up ``a pretty inactive''
Presbyterian in Atlanta, graduated from Druid Hills High School and
attended Emory University, majoring in English literature and
graduating in 1956. As a college student, he first visited Holy
Trinity Episcopal Church in Decatur and said he was taken by the
beauty of the liturgy and the openness of the clergy he met.
</P>
<P>
   By the time he met Agnes Scott history major Elizabeth Ansley in
a Russian history summer school class at Emory, he had decided to
become an Episcopal priest _ but she didn't realize that when the
two started dating.
</P>
<P>
   She was a member of First Presbyterian Church of Decatur who had
conscientiously avoided serious relationships with students at
nearby Columbia Theological Seminary because she didn't want to be
a preacher's wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was snuck up on from behind'' by Allan's career plans, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   The two married in 1957 when she graduated from Agnes Scott and
he was going into his second year of theology school at the
University of the South in Sewanee, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   The oldest of their four children turns 40 this year.
</P>
<P>
   Allan went on for a master's degree at Sewanee and a doctorate
at Emory. He was rector at St. Mark's in Dalton; St. Peter's in
Columbia, Tenn.; St. Paul's in Macon; and St. Anne's in Atlanta
before being consecrated bishop coadjutor in 1987, to serve with
and then succeed Bishop Judson Child. Child retired in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Allan said he remains a parish priest at heart. ``It took me
about five years to feel like a bishop,'' he said. During the
election process when he realized he might be chosen, he was
tempted to stand up and shout, ``Wait a minute! I was just
kidding,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As bishop he has gained a reputation as an intellectual, a good
preacher, a fair boss and a person of solid integrity. He's also a
``computer nerd,'' said his longtime secretary Glenna Smith. ``He
fixes all the computers for the entire staff now,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Allan uses his computer to extend his working time into the wee
hours of the morning. Priests in the diocese are not surprised to
click on their computers and find that the bishop has sent them
e-mail at 2:30 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always worried about the amount of time he puts into
it,'' said the Rev. Richard Callaway, president of the diocese's
six-member Standing Committee, or bishop's advisory board. ``But he
has a very steady hand on the helm. He listens well. He's not
afraid to say he made a mistake, but he makes them rarely.''
</P>
<P>
   Under Allan's leadership, the Atlanta diocese has grown by 16
congregations and now has 91 churches with about 53,000 members.
</P>
<P>
   But during that time, a few churches have left the diocese,
saying the national denomination had become too liberal by
ordaining women priests and consecrating female bishops. Two local
Episcopal priests became Catholic clergy, one taking a congregation
with him.
</P>
<P>
   Allan from the beginning supported women's ordination and
accepted the first female deacon in the diocese as his associate in
Macon.
</P>
<P>
   If the question of female clergy seemed to dominate the church
during the first part of his tenure, the questions of whether to
ordain sexually active gays and lesbians and bless same-sex unions
have divided Episcopalians _ and other mainline Christians _ during
latter years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every bishop has one or two big issues,'' Allan said. ``My
issue was homosexuality. That's what the church was absorbed
with.''
</P>
<P>
   Running the store
</P>
<P>
   Allan has made it clear that he would like to be able to open
ordination to gays and lesbians in committed relationships _ but he
will not because it is against the doctrine of the Episcopal
Church.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are part of a communion,'' he said. ``I believe we cannot
act unilaterally.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a diverse diocese,'' said Callaway, rector of St.
Julian's in Douglasville. ``We've got lots of folks on the ends of
the theological spectrum, the economic spectrum and the issues of
the church. He manages to hold all that in tension, and he loves
those he disagrees with as much as those he agrees with. We've been
managed well.''
</P>
<P>
   The bishop's greatest strength, Callaway said, has been his
wife, Elizabeth. ``She's a partner in ministry but she has her own
personality, her own life,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Allan is a teacher who retired last year from the
Fulton County system. ``I didn't go back in case when he retired he
wanted to take one of those trips you hear about,'' she said. ``I
soon found out different.'' She is also a poet who has kept a diary
of her life since 1968.
</P>
<P>
   About 10 years ago, the Allans sold their large northwest
Atlanta house to move into a more modest one on Briarcliff Road,
cutting their mortgage in half and committing themselves to give
away much of the difference mostly to Episcopal outreach ministries
and to their alma maters. Elizabeth Allan mows their lawn, the
bishop said, and they consciously consider how they use their
resources.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do try not to be cumbered about with too much,'' he said.
``I think John Wesley said, 'I don't want to be cumbered about with
too much lest it get into my heart.'''
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Allan, who recently spent time doing relief work in
Honduras, says she plans to look after her grandchildren _ four of
six live in metro Atlanta _ help out with the shop, and ``travel,
whether he does or not.''
</P>
<P>
   The bishop will run the store with his two partners and longtime
friends, Smith, his secretary since his St. Anne's days, and Martha
McClatchey, a jewelry designer, painter and St. Anne's parishioner
who was in a sixth-grade Sunday school class he taught while he was
an Emory student.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a grand time together,'' McClatchey said.
</P>
<P>
   Allan is already spending every unscheduled evening at the shop
installing display shelving. He will also teach at Emory, write,
sail, bicycle and continue to use his computer.
</P>
<P>
   ``He likes to keep busy,'' said his wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not retiring because I'm tired and burned out. I'm
retiring because it's time to do other things,'' the bishop said.
``I'm retiring as bishop but not from life.''
</P>
<P>
   Gayle White writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
