<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-03 18:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5945 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f BC-COMPUTER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      03-03 0909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIMS GAME'S ALLURE IS THAT IT'S LIKE LIFE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Will Wright created the original SimCity game 11 years ago, and
looking at the concept on paper, nothing could seem more boring.
Players build a city from scratch, manage its resources and keep
the citizenry happy.
</P>
<P>
   Who but a municipal bureaucrat or a policy wonk would think
that's fun?
</P>
<P>
   But the SimCity franchise _ the latest version is SimCity 3000 _
has sold more than 7 million copies, according to game developer
Maxis' Web site. It spawned an entire genre of computer games that
simulate real-life systems, but it remains the best of the best.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, every city has citizens, and in the SimCity line the
inhabitants are called Sims. Most players of the game come to hate
the Sims because they complain all the time _ taxes are too high,
housing or jobs are scarce, traffic is too congested, pollution is
nasty. You just wanna slap their little pixilated faces ... which
is why the game also lets you unleash tornados, earthquakes, movie
monsters or space aliens on your simulated town.
</P>
<P>
   Now you can get to know these annoying creatures better.
Wright's latest game, The Sims, drills down to examine life inside
the walls of SimCity's homes. It's described as a ``people
simulator.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sims is easily the most addictively enjoyable game Wright
has done since the first SimCity. It's complex enough that longtime
fans of simulators will not be bored, but not so hard that novices
will be frustrated.
</P>
<P>
   But most of all, it's compelling fun. Essentially, players
control simulated human lives, down to the smallest detail, and
there's something primally appealing about that. You can even tell
the Sims when to use the bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
IT STARTS WITH MAN, BARE HOUSE &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Sims, which currently is available only for Windows 95/98
systems (it will also run on Windows 2000), begins with a simple
tutorial. Players start with a sparsely furnished house and a male
character with a fairly balanced personality. The tutorial shows
you how to work with the clever interface _ a series of simple
icons that lead to more complex menus _ and how to manage your
Sims.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually a second character, a female, is added to the home,
and now you get to see how your Sims interact. She also has a
fairly balanced personality, so she's likely to get along with her
new mate.
</P>
<P>
   Just as in real life, don't expect fireworks right away. As they
get to know each other, they get to like each other better _ and if
they really hit it off, one will propose marriage. If they get
along in marriage, they may have a child ... or not.
</P>
<P>
   The Sims go off to work each day, climb the career ladder, and
bring home money _ or Simoleans, the coin of the Sim-realm. With
that money you can buy them things, upgrading that cheap
black-and-white TV for a snazzy plasma-screen model, but only if
you can afford it. The more gadgetry and luxury you provide for
your Sims, the happier they are.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
YOU CAN CREATE PERSONALITIES &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You can let the game create Sims for you, or you can craft your
own. The Sims' personalities are controlled by variations in five
settings: Neat, Outgoing, Active, Playful and Nice.
</P>
<P>
   Ratchet up the Outgoing, Active and Playful settings and you'll
make a Sim who's gregarious and a bit childish. Back off on Nice,
crank up the Active and reduce the Outgoing setting and create one
who's mean, keeps to herself but fidgets and likes to dance.
</P>
<P>
   As you progress through the game, your Sims will meet other Sims
and you can watch how different personality types get along. These
may be Sims you've set up in other houses, or random Sims that drop
by.
</P>
<P>
   For example, early in the game a woman in a tight red dress
dropped by to visit one of my male Sims while his wife was away at
work. I expected hanky panky, but instead they didn't get along.
The two began arguing, and he told her to leave.
</P>
<P>
   The game is full of little touches that make it fascinating. For
example, early in their lives, the Sims aren't good cooks. They are
liable to cut themselves as they prepare meals on a chopping board.
And don't buy them a gas stove too early, or they will likely burn
the house down.
</P>
<P>
   The Sims like to have music and television around, and you can
change stations to suit their moods. Play classical music, and
they'll sit and relax. Play rock 'n' roll, and they'll boogie in
the kitchen. Some Sims seem to have a fondness for horror flicks,
while others prefer Westerns.
</P>
<P>
   The Sims have all the emotional and biological needs of real
people. They must work, play, eat, practice good hygiene and even
use the toilet. When they take a shower or visit the restroom,
their images pixilate, using the same effect TV does when trying to
hide someone's identity.
</P>
<P>
   One of the fun, low-effort aspects of all the Sim games is to
just let them run and watch what happens. You can do that with The
Sims, and they will live their lives on auto-pilot. But it's a lot
more fun to intervene, and sometimes you have to. One of my Sims
liked to sleep in and was constantly late for work, which
eventually cost him his job.
</P>
<P>
   The Sims even has an online aspect of sorts. You can upload the
Sims you've created to www.thesims.com to share with other players.
This lets you diversify the Sim-gene pool.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
