<HEADLINE>
INTERNET ACCESS OPTION ISDL A HYBRID OF ISDN AND DSL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Q: In investigating high-speed Internet service, I
find limited options for my home. My cable provider does not offer
cable-modem service, and I am too far from the Southwestern Bell
central office to get ADSL service. However, I have been told I can
get IDSL at 144,000-bit-per-second speeds. The only thing I know
about ISDL is that it is related to ISDN. Is it a worthwhile option
until I have better options available?
</P>
<P>
   A: IDSL stands for ISDN Digital Subscriber Line. It's a kind of
hybrid blend of two technologies: ISDN, one of the earliest ways to
get faster Internet access, and the more modern DSL.
</P>
<P>
   DSL has severe distance limitations, though. The farther you are
from the phone company's central office, the weaker the DSL signal.
At more than 17,000 feet, the signal is virtually unusable, and
most providers won't sell you the service.
</P>
<P>
   ISDN has fewer limitations but is costlier to set up and use.
</P>
<P>
   The hybrid, originally developed by Ascend Communications, a
communications hardware manufacturer, uses the ISDN-style signal,
but gets it to you in a fashion similar to other forms of DSL.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, with ISDN, you actually have to dial up a connection,
similar to a regular phone call. ISDN goes through the phone
company's switching equipment. DSL does not _ it plugs into
different equipment at the central office. IDSL takes ISDN and
pumps it through equipment similar to that used by DSL.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, you can get IDSL service in places where you
normally cannot get DSL. If it's cheaper than standard ISDN, it
could be an excellent choice until something better is available in
your neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Q: In your review of the Epson Stylus Color 860 printer and the
Hewlett-Packard 5300C scanner (see
www.chron.com/cs/CDA/story.hts/tech/457394), you said that older
printers and scanners that use parallel port connections would be
``useless'' with new legacy-free computers that only use USB ports.
But what about the adapters that are available that let you connect
parallel port devices to a USB port?
</P>
<P>
   A: You're right, adapters are available. But they have
drawbacks.
</P>
<P>
   You don't see the speed gains you'd get from moving to a pure
USB printer or scanner. Although some manufacturers claim speed
improvements over a standard parallel port, that hasn't been my
experience.
</P>
<P>
   You also lose the two-way communications ability that lets your
computer and device talk to each other. This is used by printers,
for example, to report ink cartridge levels, or by scanners to scan
only certain areas of an image or document. In some cases, your
device's drivers may not work properly if two-way communication
isnot available.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have a 1-gigabyte SyQuest SparQ drive, and I love it.
However, I've filled up my last disk and need to buy more. SyQuest
went out of business and now I can't find the disks. Know where I
can get 'em?
</P>
<P>
   A: Although SyQuest went bankrupt and sold most of its assets to
rival Iomega, it still operates a Web site at www.syquest.com.
There's an online store where it appears you can buy disks for your
SparQ and other SyQuest drive. In fact, the online order form even
indicates you can buy SparQ drives. The site also has support
information and drivers to download.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
