<SLUG> BC-WORKING-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDICARE SHIFT HITS HOSPITAL IN THE WALLET 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By L.M. SIXEL 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The 15 employees in the legal and risk management
department of Memorial Hermann Healthcare System recently got the
word they were being replaced by an independent firm that promised
to do the work for 30 to 40 percent less.
</P>
<P>
   The employees, who were told to pack up their personal
belongings, turn in their pagers and leave, are victims of the
Balanced Budget Act of 1997. The legislation, which went into
effect last year, has substantially reduced Medicare reimbursements
to health care providers. Consequently, some hospital systems are
finding themselves in financial trouble.
</P>
<P>
   In the first seven months of its fiscal year, Memorial Hermann's
12 hospitals have suffered an operating loss, and the system has
had to sell its financially troubled health maintenance
organization.
</P>
<P>
   To turn its fortunes around, Memorial Hermann hired Ernst &AMP;
Young to find ways to cut $50 million out of its budget next year,
said Patty Riddlebarger, spokeswoman for Memorial Hermann
Healthcare System. The consulting firm is also searching for $30
million in new revenues _ such as collecting more of the hospitals'
overdue medical bills.
</P>
<P>
   Memorial Hermann hopes ``Project 2000'' will turn the fourth
quarter into a profitable one. One of its hospitals has already
reduced the number of days it takes to send a bill from four days
to two, Riddlebarger said.
</P>
<P>
   And there have been other terminations. A week before the legal
and risk management department was let go, 19 people in information
systems were terminated.
</P>
<P>
   Riddlebarger said she doesn't know if more dismissals are in the
offing.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
RURAL HOSPITALS REALLY SUFFERING &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Other hospitals are also suffering, said Amanda Engler,
communications manager for the Texas Hospital Association.
</P>
<P>
   An association analysis indicates that the effects of the
Balanced Budget Act of 1997 will cost Texas hospitals $3 billion
over the next five years. Memorial Hermann lost $29 million in
Medicare reimbursements last year.
</P>
<P>
   Rural hospitals are being hit especially hard because some have
90 percent of their business in Medicare, Engler said. Some rural
hospitals have closed while others have shuttered their home health
care operations and dropped their skilled nursing facilities, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   It's a sharp turnaround for the health care industry. After
being a good jobs creator _ health care providers added 3,400
positions in 1998 _ the industry cut 1,800 jobs in Houston last
year, according to the Texas Workforce Commission.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
JOB HELP TO BE OFFERED &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even though the financial troubles are real, some of the
Memorial Hermann employees who got the boot are grumbling about the
way the hospital system did it.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't exactly generous, for example, one employee said. It
offered only two weeks of severance pay for every year of service
up to a maximum of 15 weeks for those below the director level.
</P>
<P>
   Another grumbled that the hospital system offered no help in
finding another job.
</P>
<P>
   Riddlebarger said the severance plan is comparable to those of
other health providers. And Memorial Hermann is putting in an
outplacement center next week to provide classes on writing a
resume as well as teaching interviewing skills and job search
strategies.
</P>
<P>
   All the employees who have been terminated can use the
outplacement center, Riddlebarger said.
</P>
<P>
   The hardest thing for the employees to get over is that the
terminations hit them like a ton of bricks because it affected the
whole department.
</P>
<P>
   There were meetings on how to reduce costs, said a former
employee. But no one expected the whole department to get the ax.
</P>
<P>
   Berating herself, the employee said she should have seen the
signs and started looking for a new job. The department was moving
to another location, and there was just a small space allocated to
it, for example.
</P>
<P>
   ``We figured a mistake was made,'' the ex-employee said.
</P>
<P>
   Riddlebarger said it would have been difficult to give prior
notice of the terminations because the outsourcing contract was
signed just two days before the employees were let go.
</P>
<P>
   Memorial Hermann is betting the outsourcing arrangement will
save money. And if the contract company can't do it with half the
employees? That's not Memorial Hermann's responsibility any more.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
