u f BC-INTEL-GIGAHERTZ-HNS &LR;      03-03 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTEL-GIGAHERTZ-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTEL SET TO WIN RACE TO PRODUCE 1-GIGAHERTZ CHIP 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The race to see who can be first to market with a 1-gigahertz
personal computer chip could be won much earlier than expected _ as
in, next week.
</P>
<P>
   Industry sources said Intel Corp. on Wednesday will announce
1-GHz versions of its Pentium III chips. Personal computers with
the processors will be available later this month.
</P>
<P>
   In doing so, Intel may beat rival Advanced Micro Devices to the
milestone.
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard will be among the first to offer the systems. A
company spokeswoman confirmed that Pavilion consumer computers with
the fast Intel chips will be on store shelves by the end of March.
Commercial H-P systems aimed at businesses will be available in
June.
</P>
<P>
   Other companies that make personal computers using Intel
processors are also likely to announce 1-GHz systems next week,
including Compaq Computer Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq spokeswoman Hedy Baker would not specify when the
Houston-based PC manufacturer would offer machines with the chips,
other than to say ``we are going to launch a 1-GHz class product in
the not-too-distant future.''
</P>
<P>
   Dell Computer Corp. and IBM are also both expected to ship 1-GHz
PCs this month. Both companies, along with H-P, demonstrated
computers with 1-GHz Pentium III chips during a developer's
conference in February sponsored by Intel.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq and H-P use processors from both AMD and Intel. Compaq's
Presario line uses more AMD chips, while H-P's Pavilion relies more
on Intel.
</P>
<P>
   Intel and AMD have been battling to see who could be the first
to offer chips that break the gigahertz barrier, which is the
equivalent of 1,000 megahertz. Currently, the fastest PC processor
available is an 850-megahertz Athlon chip from AMD, but both
companies have demonstrated versions running at 1 GHz or more.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers refer to the clock speed of a processor, which is
the main chip in a personal computer. The clock speed indicates how
fast the processor manipulates data.
</P>
<P>
   The speed of processors has been roughly doubling every year.
Intel last February introduced Pentium III chips that ran at 500
MHz.
</P>
<P>
   The 1-GHz goal was not expected to be reached until later this
year, in the late second or early third quarter. Analysts said the
acceleration of development can be directly attributed to the
competition between Intel and AMD, and the introduction last year
of AMD's powerful Athlon chip.
</P>
<P>
   ``Intel has some real competition in the market now,'' said Van
Baker, director of consumer market research for Dataquest in San
Jose, Calif. ``It's a matter of bragging rights _ who's first on
the block with the fastest processor.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though Intel has scheduled an announcement for next week,
AMD may not be far behind. Drew Prairie, a spokesman at AMD's
Austin facility, said Thursday that ``our plans are to remain
competitive throughout the year.''
</P>
<P>
   But he added that AMD is sticking by its earlier statements that
1-GHz Athlons will likely come at mid-year.
</P>
<P>
   Intel spokesman Howard High would not confirm the release date,
but said that once 1-GHz chips were launched, it would be a while
before they would be widely available.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would guesstimate that the stage when we hit general
availability will be in the third quarter of the year,'' High said.
</P>
<P>
   And early on, the gigahertz chips will probably cost buyers
gigabucks.
</P>
<P>
   Baker, of Dataquest, estimated that PCs using the chips will run
in the $2,500 to $3,500 range.
</P>
<P>
   He added that, other than avid computer gamers and others who
demand the fastest processors available, few users actually need
the power found in a 1-GHz chip.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're living in an era when the software just hasn't caught up
with hardware,'' Baker said. ``You can go out and buy a PC that
performs adequately for most people for $800 or $900. That was
unheard of a couple of years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
