<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-03 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5949 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i BC-BOLIVIA-LIFESAVERS-CO     03-03 0939
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOLIVIA-LIFESAVERS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The boy who came down from the mountain
 &HT;    By Paul Reid
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The village where Bautista Cruz was dying is so high his journey
to heaven would be very short.
</P>
<P>
   At more than 13,000 feet in the Bolivian Andes, there isn't a
lot of air to start with.
</P>
<P>
   But Bautista's lungs were being squeezed by a bowel obstruction
the size of a basketball. The obstruction would either rupture and
kill him or squeeze the last breath out of his lungs and kill him.
</P>
<P>
   Life is hard and short above the tree line, above the clouds. It
was 1996; Bautista was 6 and not likely to see 7.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am Inca,'' Bautista said Thursday. ``My language is Quechua,
the language of the Inca.''
</P>
<P>
   He pauses. ``Do you like Pokemon? I do.''
</P>
<P>
   Bautista Cruz has come down from the mountain.
</P>
<P>
   The trek began when a Franciscan nun visited his mountain
village. It ended in Jupiter, in the home of his adoptive mother, a
nurse anesthetist named Mary Kay Thomas. Until she met Bautista in
1996, she was a career single woman _ no kids, no husband, lots of
travel, free time, quiet evenings at home in Jupiter.
</P>
<P>
   Then their paths crossed. Merged. They trek together from here
on out.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Kay Thomas has spent part of each of the last 15 years in
Bolivia. She and about 40 other doctors, nurses and medical
technicians with the MIMA foundation of Jupiter travel to the
mountains to perform surgery, treat smashed bones, infections, all
the maladies that kill people in poor countries. MIMA comes from
the Spanish word meaning to care for. Since 1995 they have focused
their attention on the high Andes of Bolivia.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1996 visit, Franciscan nuns brought Bautista to the
MIMA clinic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw this little boy, his stomach swollen beyond belief,''
says Thomas. ``It was obviously the end. Hirschprung's disease. The
nerves in the bowel don't work. The tissue isn't dead, but it
doesn't do its job. He had already undergone a few surgeries in
Bolivia, but it kept returning. He had to be treated in the States,
or die.''
</P>
<P>
   MIMA has performed more than 1,000 surgeries over the years.
Thomas had attended thousands more. A patient is a patient. She had
never brought one home.
</P>
<P>
   But she spoke Spanish. Bautista's doctors thought if the boy
came to the States for surgery he'd recuperate best if he lived
with someone who spoke Spanish. So after consulting with Bautista's
parents, who knew his choices were surgery or death, the MIMA
doctors took Bautista to Jupiter. St. Mary's and Good Samaritan
medical centers donated services. Two local surgeons, Gabriel
Zambrano and Ahmad Toufanian, donated their skills. Nurses,
doctors, hospitals. Everyone gave.
</P>
<P>
   They saved Bautista. And he went home with Thomas. Then
everybody realized they had missed an obvious consideration: There
was no way Bautista could lead a normal life back in his village.
The disease might return, his dietary needs could not be met. In
the United States he could live with his condition. In Bolivia he
would die.
</P>
<P>
   ``His parents knew this,'' says Thomas. ``They knew their son
couldn't live in their village. His doctors knew it. I didn't see
where it was going. He started calling me mama. I started looking
at toys and boys clothes when I walked through the mall. My mother
said, `What have you gotten yourself into?' At the end of the
winter she said, `What are we going to do about Bautista?' She
didn't want to say goodbye.''
</P>
<P>
   Bautista's mother, Basilia, had already lost three of her six
children to one ailment or another.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked about adoption, all of us. Bautista's parents. Me.
Him,'' says Thomas. ``He's not an orphan, so everyone had to agree
on this. This was a new life for all concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   Bautista has taken to his new life. He's about as average as any
American 10-year old. Except for his mastery of four languages, a
good grasp of surgical procedures and a natural talent for telling
tales of the Inca and the Andes. He takes Irish step dancing
lessons. Likes soccer. Not sure about baseball. Doesn't watch much
TV. Has a big fat cat named K'acha, which means cute in his native
tongue.
</P>
<P>
   The adoption is moving along in spite of a few diplomatic snafus
here and there. Lost signatures. A visa and passport problem that's
keeping Bautista from accompanying Mary Kay to Bolivia on another
MIMA trip today. She and her MIMA colleagues are going for two
weeks. Bautista has visited his family on Mary Kay's previous
trips, but not this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will always go back to my village,'' he says. ``I have two
families. My brothers write letters. My sister is growing. My
father farms potatoes. I help him.''
</P>
<P>
   Hard enough for parents to watch a child go into surgery.
Bautista's parents watched him go in, and come out as a future
citizen of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so hard for them,'' says Thomas. ``His mother had taken
care of him for years, with an illness that should have killed him.
She did what nobody thought was possible. She kept him alive. And
then said goodbye.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas is packing for the trip. She'll bring photos of Bautista,
his schoolwork and letters to his parents. She'll climb to where
the soil is rock and the wind never stops and Inca children die
young. She'll tell Bautista's mother and father their son is safe
and happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``They entrusted their son to me. But it's going to work for
everyone. I love being a mother. I love my son.''
</P>
<P>
   To contribute to the MIMA Foundation, write to P.O. Box 7133,
Jupiter, FL 33468-7133.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
