<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILITARY-PAY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOW PAY THE REAL ENEMY FOR MANY IN THE ARMED FORCES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KIM COBB 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KILLEEN, Texas _ Quotesha Austin is tired of being poor. It is
not what she expected as an Army wife.
</P>
<P>
   Her husband, Pfc. Gary Austin, spends his days training to
defend his country at sprawling Fort Hood, where he drives a
lumbering, tanklike vehicle called a Bradley. He is paid $1,171 a
month before taxes, a couple of hundred dollars in subsistence pay
and a housing subsidy that does not cover the rent for his family.
</P>
<P>
   ``That spells broke,'' Quotesha Austin says dryly. They can't
afford a car, and she can't find a job that pays enough to cover
day care for her two children.
</P>
<P>
   In November, she began collecting food stamps, and the Austins
joined the list of an estimated 12,000 military families who do the
same.
</P>
<P>
   More than $13 million in food stamps was redeemed last year in
military commissaries. There is no way to measure how many were
redeemed by military families in civilian supermarkets.
</P>
<P>
   Although food stamp recipients are less than 1 percent of the
nation's 1.4 million service members, the issue has embarrassed
some officials who claim to be supporters of the military and has
erupted as an emotional campaign topic for GOP presidential
hopefuls George W. Bush and John McCain.
</P>
<P>
   They argue that it is an outrage that men and women who put
their lives on the line for their country must seek help to feed
their families.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, the Department of Defense has studied the food
stamp issue and dismissed it as too costly to fix in light of the
relatively small number of military families eligible for food
stamps.
</P>
<P>
   But the military has another problem _ how to recruit and retain
good people during an era of plentiful jobs and a strong economy.
The Senate Armed Services Committee met recently to discuss the
subject.
</P>
<P>
   Many advocates for better military pay point to a 13 percent gap
between overall military pay and that for comparable civilian jobs.
The defense-oriented Center for Strategic and Budgetary Assessments
believes the gap is exaggerated, but concludes that increasing pay
and benefits to some degree is a reasonable response to recruitment
problems.
</P>
<P>
   The Defense Department has ordered another study on its food
stamp families, the third since 1991. Defense spokeswoman Susan
Hansen said incremental pay raises scheduled through 2005 and a
proposed major boost in the housing allowance should help alleviate
cost-of-living problems for everyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I think we've seen in the past that the food stamp issue
is more a function of larger families for junior personnel than
other demographic groups,'' Hansen said.
</P>
<P>
   Food stamp recipient Shauntrel Linton says her husband joined
the Army specifically because she was pregnant with their first
child. Her father was in the military, and they assumed joining the
Army would cover their young family's costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I thought he'd be making the same amount as my dad,''
Linton said.
</P>
<P>
   The military doesn't want to encourage people who are young and
at low levels in the military to have a lot of children, said
Steven Kosiak of the defense-oriented Center for Strategic and
Budgetary Assessments. Although raising all military salaries costs
more than just taking care of the food stamp population, targeting
special financial consideration to potential food stamp recipients
creates the problem of different pay for the same work.
</P>
<P>
   ``But having said that, nobody wants to think there are military
people who are so underpaid they are resorting to food stamps,''
Kosiak said. ``This is not an unsolvable problem, but it is
complicated.''
</P>
<P>
   The last Defense Department study, conducted in 1995, found that
59 percent of military food stamp recipients were living on the
base. Most of that group would not be eligible for food stamps, the
study speculated, if the agencies that administer them were able to
fully measure ``hidden compensation,'' such as on-post housing.
</P>
<P>
   Those conducting the study found that another 41 percent of
recipients were collecting food stamps even though they lived off
base and their housing allowances were calculated as part of their
gross pay. The study determined that of 4,900 food stamp families
living off base, only 1,100 should qualify for food stamps, based
on income and family size.
</P>
<P>
   ``Adjusting the military compensation system to account for the
4,900 members receiving food stamps and living off base with
above-average-size families would be complex, expensive, and we
believe, unwarranted,'' the study concluded.
</P>
<P>
   At the lowest end of the scale, an enlisted man or woman at the
pay grade of E-1 earns $1,005.49 per month in base pay. The largest
percentage of servicemen and women drawing food stamps are at the
slightly higher E-4 pay grade, which starts at $1,242.90 per month
for those with less than two years of service.
</P>
<P>
   The military got a 4.8 percent raise in January for every person
in uniform. Seventy-five percent of all service members will
receive another pay increase in July, although it's targeted to
midgrade and noncommissioned officers.
</P>
<P>
   The defense budget President Clinton has submitted for 2001
calls for another across-the-board pay raise of 3.7 percent, plus a
boost in the Basic Allowance for Housing allotted to families who
don't live on post. Incremental raises are planned through 2005.
</P>
<P>
   But many military families barely noticed the raise in January,
in spite of claims from the Clinton administration that it was
``the largest military pay raise in a generation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty much gone,'' said Kim Garman, 31. Her husband,
Staff Sgt. Dale Garman, has been in the Army for nearly a decade
and soldiers like him at a pay grade of E-6 earn a monthly basic
pay of $1,932.60 before taxes.
</P>
<P>
   They live on post, which means they have no housing costs. Other
military families who live off the post (there's a waiting list for
base housing) receive a housing subsidy that varies by location in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Th% verage military family pays 19 percent of its rent out of
pocket, because the housing allowance frequently doesn't cover fair
market rent. But the housing allowance is worth hundreds of dollars
a month, depending on regional costs and the size of housing
required, and is not taxed. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Money is pretty tight, Garman says, but she does think her
husband is compensated adequately _ with this caveat: ``Most
civilians who aren't familiar with the military think we get a lot
of things free. That's not the case. We don't get as much as they
think we do.''
</P>
<P>
   Their family income is low enough to qualify Garman and her
children for the Special Supplemental Nutrition Program for Women,
Infants and Children known as WIC. Military families redeemed more
than $21 million in WIC vouchers in U.S. commissaries last year for
dietary supplements such as milk, cheese and infant formula.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent month, 14,245 clients received WIC vouchers in the
region surrounding Killeen, and slightly more than half of those
were Fort Hood military dependents. The county workers
administering the WIC program there joke that Fort Hood keeps them
in business.
</P>
<P>
   Though WIC vouchers are available to families that earn much
more than food stamp families (as much as $2,575 a month for a
family of four like the Garmans) it is designed to provide
supplements such as milk, cheese and infant formula for children
considered vulnerable to nutrition problems. That free formula
makes a big difference in the Garman household.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a hundred dollars a month,'' Garman said. ``There's no
way we could pull that out of our paycheck. And diapers. It frees
us up to buy meat and vegetables _ the other things you need.''
</P>
<P>
   Fort Hood provides financial counselors to help young servicemen
and women make the adjustment to military life and budgeting. At a
basic level, they advise families how much money they can afford to
spend for off-post housing. For those who arrive from out-of-state,
they include a lesson on the reality of utility costs during the
hot Texas summers.
</P>
<P>
   Sgt. Kelly Barcal says most of the financially strapped families
he counsels do not appear angry, only frustrated. ``We really
haven't dealt with a whole lot of people on food stamps,'' he said,
then was surprised to learn that about $250,000 in food stamps was
redeemed at Fort Hood commissaries last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the families we deal with, they're making it, but
they're barely making it,'' Barcal said.
</P>
<P>
   His own raise in January, he concedes, was only $38.50 a month
after taxes. ``The 4.8 percent looked like a real good deal,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every soldier has to make up their own mind if they stay in or
not, or if they feel like they can make a better financial life for
themselves,'' Barcal said. ``That's totally up to that soldier and
his family.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the highest levels of food stamp redemptions show up in
states with higher costs of living. The Defense Commissary Agency
reports Schofield Barracks in Hawaii leads the list with $1.4
million in food stamp redemptions last year and another $800,000 in
WIC vouchers.
</P>
<P>
   Commissaries in Texas redeemed slightly more than $1 million in
food stamps last year, with Fort Bliss in El Paso heading the list
at $475,782 in redemptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a true picture because many are too proud to
accept food stamps, even though they are eligible,'' said Defense
Commissary Agency spokesperson Flo Dunn. ``Others don't want their
peers to see them use food stamps in the commissary, so they go off
post to shop.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't bother me to come and ask for help, no,'' said
Austin, the Fort Hood mother. ``As long as my children can eat.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
