<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-03 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5951 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-MACHINES-HUMANS-ART-2     03-03 1155
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MACHINES-HUMANS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING COMPUTERS RELATE TO THEIR HUMAN PARTNERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT2 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(lh) 
 By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the 97 years since the Wright brothers made their first
flight, aviation has progressed to the point where an airline pilot
can now take off, push a button and sit back while the plane flies
to its destination and even lands by itself.
</P>
<P>
   Engineers have done such a good job of designing flight
computers, navigational equipment and autopilots that flying is by
far the safest form of travel. But the advances over the last 15
years have also energized a debate among designers and industrial
psychologists about how machines should relate to their human
operators. It is a concern that is expanding to other fields, like
medicine, where equipment is becoming increasingly complex.
</P>
<P>
   ``These technologies are not really purely reactive tools
anymore that you use to perform certain tasks,'' said Nadine P.
Sarter, a specialist in cognitive engineering at Ohio State
University. ``They are far more autonomous.'' She calls them
``independent machine agents'' because they can act on their own
based on programmed assumptions about the operator's desires in a
given circumstance.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge of the best way to mate man and machine led Airbus
Industrie and Boeing Co., the only two makers of large passenger
jetliners, to adopt different philosophies when they designed the
cockpits of their latest airplanes.
</P>
<P>
   The contrasting approaches in some ways reflect each
manufacturer's cultural origins. Airbus, which is a consortium of
European companies based in France, takes a paternalistic approach.
It places so-called hard limits on its pilots to protect them from
themselves. The airplane's computers do not allow the pilot to
pitch the plane too high or too low, to fly it too fast or to bank
it beyond a 67-degree angle.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing, perhaps reflecting an American cowboy spirit,
deliberately gives pilots the ability to risk destroying the plane
in order to save it. Computers tell pilots when they are
approaching the airplane's limits but it is left up to the captain
to decide whether to exceed them.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies are quick to say that both approaches are safe.
But as fierce international rivals fighting each other for every
sale from the world's airlines, they are each equally quick to make
the case for the superiority of their own design.
</P>
<P>
   Edwin Hutchins, a professor of cognitive science at the
University of California at San Diego, who has studied cockpit
safety issues for 10 years, says, ``The reality is more complex and
a lot more subtle than the way it has been discussed by the
manufacturers.''
</P>
<P>
   He explained that accidents are so rare compared with the number
of miles jets fly and are caused by so many factors that it is
impossible to measure accurately which design is better. ``The
debate for me proceeds in the absence of empirical evidence,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But the two different approaches illustrate the knotty issues
facing researchers and designers in many fields. Highly automated
machines now administer drugs to hospital patients, produce
complicated semiconductors and operate power plants, transforming
technicians from machine operators into supervisory controllers.
How the human masters are kept ``in the loop'' so they know what
the machines are doing will ultimately affect hundreds of millions
of people's lives.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the airline industry's safety record, several recent
crashes have shown that fatal mistakes still occur. Experts have
become increasingly concerned because the growth in air travel is
soaring while accidents rates have declined slowly in recent years.
If that trend continues, the number of accidents will rise.
</P>
<P>
   The low-hanging fruit in terms of aviation safety has now been
picked. Jet engines are highly reliable. Advanced navigational
tools means that planes rarely get lost.
</P>
<P>
   Automation has undoubtedly improved safety, but it has also
created new problems. Today most commercial airplane accidents
occur not because of mechanical problems but because pilots become
confused.
</P>
<P>
   A 1996 report by the Federal Aviation Administration expressed
concern that pilots were losing their basic flying skills because
they were depending so much on automation. ``It's a mixed
blessing,'' said Earl Wiener, professor emeritus at the University
of Miami, who was one of the first to sound a warning about the
perils of aviation automation. ``We see things we haven't seen
before.''
</P>
<P>
   Until recently the cockpits of all passenger jets were pretty
much the same. Pilots controlled the plane with a steering wheel
and column that was connected to a series of cables and pulleys
that moved the flaps on the wings and the elevators on the tail.
</P>
<P>
   Then in 1988 Airbus introduced its A320 twin-engine jet, which
replaced the cables with electronic signals routed through
computers, a system known as fly-by-wire that had been used on
fighter jets and the supersonic Concorde.
</P>
<P>
   Having eliminated the cables, the pilot no longer needed the
leverage afforded by a wheel-and-column yoke to control the
airplane. Instead Airbus introduced a joystick on the side much
like the one used to play video games. Airbus pilots make the jets
climb, descend and bank with slight movements of the joystick,
while the jet's computers automatically adjust the elevators and
other control surfaces so that the plane flies smoothly on its
course.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Boeing introduced the 777, its first fly-by-wire jet.
But instead of using a joystick controller, Boeing decided to keep
the wheel-and-column design. Indeed, Boeing went to great lengths
to mimic the feel of the traditional mechanically controlled jets.
When the 777 slows, the yoke gets heavier, as if the pilot is
feeling the resistance on the plane's wings increase.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Airbus, Boeing also designed the cockpit so that the
mechanical levers, like the throttle, move even if the plane's
computers, not the pilots, are controlling them. After changing
course, pilots must also manually make adjustments, or trim, a
feature that is automatic in the Airbus.
</P>
<P>
   One reason for this is to give pilots a system that they were
used to so they could draw on their experience and act intuitively
in an emergency. Another reason is to provide a variety of visual
and tactile cues so that pilots are aware of what the jet is doing.
</P>
<P>
   Airbus says such feedback is unnecessary. Larry Rockliff, the
vice president for training at Airbus, likened it to having a
carriage return on a word processor. He also said that it created
the possibility that a mechanical error might give the pilot a
false cue, indicating that the plane was, say, accelerating when in
fact it was not.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   And he said the Airbus system was more consistent. For example,
if a pilot suddenly must avoid a collision, pulling back on the
joystick immediately instructs the Airbus to climb at the maximum
angle of 30 degrees. The pilot knows the jet will give that same
performance every time but will not allow the plane to pull up too
far, at an angle that would make it lose lift and stall or fall to
the ground.
</P>
<P>
   He said Airbus thought the emphasis should be on adapting to a
new system that is superior, rather than relying on what he called
mechanical crutches.
</P>
<P>
   But John E. Cashman, Boeing's chief pilot, argues that the
Airbus system gives the machines too much control. The Boeing
cockpit always enables the pilot to override the airplane's
computers, taking advantage of a human being's unique ability to
sum up a new situation quickly and improvise, something computers
are not good at.
</P>
<P>
   In the Boeing cockpit, for instance, the controls begin to
vibrate to warn the pilot that the plane is about to stall. It is
up to the pilot to operate the plane at the ``outer edge of the
envelope'' but to take care not to cross it. This gives the pilot
the ability to use all of the plane's capability.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's there and they need it, we think the pilot should have
it,'' Cashman said.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the Airbus design might have saved an American
Airlines Boeing 757 that crashed into a mountain ridge while trying
to land at Cali, Colombia, in 1995, killing 159 people. After the
airplane's warning system alerted the pilots that they were about
to hit terrain, they tried to climb as quickly as possible but but
were forced to ease back each time the control column began to
vibrate warning of a stall. In their haste, they forgot to retract
the airplane's speed brakes, which are flaps on the wings that made
climbing more difficult. The plane missed clearing the ridge by
about 250 feet.
</P>
<P>
   When a pilot pulls back on the joystick in the Airbus, the
plane's computers assume the pilot wants maximum aerodynamic
performance and automatically retract the speed brakes. A study by
American found that if the Cali-bound 757 had had its speed brakes
retracted and was flown at a constant angle just beneath the stall
point it would have gained about 300 more feet in elevation and
cleared the ridge.
</P>
<P>
   Both the American pilots' union and Boeing dispute that
conclusion. In any case, there have also been crashes of Airbus
jets in which the Boeing cockpit design might have made the
difference.
</P>
<P>
   For example, in 1994 an Airbus A300 crashed in Japan, killing
264, after the pilot accidentally triggered the autopilot while the
plane was approaching for landing. The mistake sent the plane into
an emergency climb. Unaware of what was happening, the pilot tried
to compensate by pushing the plane's nose down. But the autopilot
countered by pitching the plane further up. The jet eventually
stalled and crashed. Japanese investigators noted that the
autopilot in Boeing cockpits automatically disengages if the pilot
exerts enough force on the control column.
</P>
<P>
   Automation researchers are loath to compare specific accidents
because each has so many distinct causes. (One study found that 25
major errors contributed to the Cali accident.) Instead, they are
focusing on the best ways for pilots to interact with computers so
that there are fewer breakdowns in communication like the one that
sent the Cali-bound jet off course toward the mountains without the
pilots realizing it.
</P>
<P>
   The principal challenge is how to alert the pilots to their
situation without overloading them with information, especially in
a crisis when they become highly focused. One approach is to try to
rely on as many human senses as possible to feed information to the
pilots in parallel channels _ like the moving levers in the Boeing
cockpit, which can be picked up easily in a pilot's peripheral
vision instead of requiring the focused attention of reading a
gauge.
</P>
<P>
   But a premium is also placed on simplicity. A recent study by
the Air Line Pilots Association, the largest pilot union, found
that they could get ``more consistent and repeatable performance''
with the Airbus design. But the authors preferred the ``soft
limits'' of the Boeing design. They recommended that the two
manufacturers incorporate the best of both designs in their future
cockpits.
</P>
<P>
   Sarter says industry and safety agencies are asking more
questions of social scientists than there are answers. She contends
that researchers need to focus more on generic issues facing all
machines rather than on specific systems like a single model of
airplane. ``We are chasing technology,'' she said. ``It is
developing so quickly that by the time we get around to studying
one thing, the next thing is on the horizon.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
