<SLUG> BC-ECON-COLUMN-$ADV05-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE RISKS IN THE FED'S ASSAULT ON STOCKS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 5) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Alan Greenspan can be clear as a bell when he wants
to be. Testifying before Congress last month, he left no doubt that
he intends to keep raising interest rates for as long as the wealth
being created by the stock market generates more demand than the
economy can satisfy.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even as he put investors on notice that monetary policy will
get tighter, he was unwilling or unable to address head-on the
quandary he faces: how to put a speed bump in front of Wall Street
without sending the entire economy into a skid, hurting workers who
own little if any stock while he hunts an enemy, inflation, that is
nowhere in sight.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan, who has been all but deified over the last few years,
rarely finds himself on the defensive. But his approach is puzzling
even some of his biggest fans, and if he miscalculates in raising
rates this year, his reputation, not to mention the nation's
prosperity, could take a beating.
</P>
<P>
   It is one thing for the Fed chairman to lay the blame for
inflationary pressures on Wall Street. Whatever the economic merits
of his position, making the stock market his bogeyman is less
politically incendiary in an election year than the traditional
central banker's warning that too many people are working and
earning good money.
</P>
<P>
   But having made the stock market the villain, he could have
trouble justifying interest rate increases that also skewer the
innocent. Is there any practical difference between raising rates
to curb the wealth effect and raising them to push up the
unemployment rate and subdue wage increases?
</P>
<P>
   When Greenspan appeared before the Senate Banking Committee,
Sen. Jim Bunning, R-Ky., told Greenspan not to lose sight of the
fact that wage and price increases have remained remarkably
restrained, given the robust pace of growth. ``Don't become so
frightened by success that you throw wet blankets on a fire that
isn't burning,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Charles E. Schumer, the New York Democrat, suggested that
Greenspan consider raising margin requirements on investors who buy
stocks with borrowed money, as a way of reining in the stock market
without putting jobs and improved standards of living at risk.
``Isn't raising interest rates too blunt an instrument, a meat
cleaver rather than a scalpel?'' Schumer asked.
</P>
<P>
   Implicit in these pleas is that ownership of equities, although
far more common than in the past, remains relatively concentrated
among the wealthy. The Fed's most recent Survey of Consumer
Finances found that in 1998, 48.8 percent of households owned
stocks, either directly or through mutual funds and retirement
accounts _ a remarkable jump from 31.6 percent in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Among households earning $25,000 to $50,000 in 1998, those stock
holdings had a median value of $11,500. Among households earning
$100,000 or more, the median value of stock holdings was $150,000.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Paul Sarbanes, D-M., cited the example of a high school
dropout he met recently who had finished a training program and
found work for the first time. ``This young fellow is far removed
from the wealth effect,'' Sarbanes said. ``If the activity and the
volatility is in the stock market, we may need to think of some way
to address that without slowing down the whole economy and
affecting the opportunities for these young people.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan is far more attuned to the benefits of strong growth
than his critics acknowledge. He makes a solid case that the best
thing for Sarbanes' young dropout and others like him is to ensure
that the long expansion is not poisoned by an outbreak of
inflation. And there is no question that the economy's 6.9 percent
annual growth rate in the fourth quarter is far above anyone's
speed limit.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Greenspan is candid in saying that there are many
things about the fast-changing economy that even he does not fully
understand.
</P>
<P>
   The charitable view is that Greenspan is still puzzling over how
to deal with the ways that lofty stock prices ripple through the
economy. The more skeptical view is that Greenspan, for all his
protestations that he is not aiming directly at stock prices, is
really doing just that.
</P>
<P>
   Newly released transcripts of policy meetings of the Fed during
1994, when it was raising rates repeatedly, show that Greenspan was
concerned even then that the equity market was in dangerously
speculative territory _ and that he quite consciously used rate
increases to send a chill through investors.
</P>
<P>
   He is no doubt equally eager now to take the froth out of the
markets. His challenge is to do it without draining the life out of
the best economy most of us will ever see.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-03-00 1822EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
