<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-03 18:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5954 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-REDS-GRIFFEYS-NYT     03-03 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-REDS-GRIFFEYS-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CINCINNATI DOUBLES UP ON GRIFFEYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.) 
 By DOUG FERNANDES    
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARASOTA, Fla. _ The scene could be a clubhouse anywhere.
Pittsburgh or Montreal or St. Louis. But this is the spring
training clubhouse at Ed Smith Stadium, and the two Griffeys are
discussing family.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Griffey Jr., standing by one of his two lockers, is talking
to dad about his 6-year-old son, Trey. Ken Griffey Sr., pouring
salad dressing over a mound of lettuce, listens for a moment, then
responds.
</P>
<P>
   The conversation is unremarkable, lasting just seconds. But what
transcends the words is the demeanor of the two men. They are
father and son, yes, but more than that, they are best friends.
</P>
<P>
   The Cincinnati Reds are counting on this bond, a son's love for
his dad, to pave over any unforeseen potholes. It's no secret
Griffey Jr. wasn't happy last year in Seattle. He hit .255 in
September, his focus was reaching 400 home runs, not the woebegone
Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Junior finished with 48 homers, 134 RBI. What could he do
this season, relaxed and back home?
</P>
<P>
   Dad ponders the question, then smiles. ``Could be some strange
things happen,'' he said. ``But we'll wait and see.''
</P>
<P>
   And Ken Griffey Sr., the Reds' hitting coach, will be there for
every swing. He missed the media frenzy of Junior's arrival in
Sarasota. Dad was in the hospital having knee surgery.
</P>
<P>
   The anesthesia has long since worn off.
</P>
<P>
   The thrill of having his son aboard hasn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nah, it's still good,'' said dad. ``I'm still having fun with
it. As long as I can help teach, it doesn't make any difference who
it is. I know him a little better than most.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffey Sr. told the story of awaking at 2 a.m. one morning and
heading to the refrigerator to get a drink. There in front of the
door was somebody, unrecognizable to the Cincinnati outfielder.
</P>
<P>
   It was Junior. While dad had been away at spring training, son
had become a man.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just blew up,'' said Griffey Sr. ``One summer, he grew like
six inches and gained 25 pounds.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's why mom, Alberta, always made sure to carry
Junior's birth certificate. No one believed a 12-year-old boy could
be that big. Maybe that's why Junior was intentionally walked
several times in high school with the bases loaded.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were scared of him,'' said dad.
</P>
<P>
   Dad's interest in his son didn't lessen, even after Griffey Jr.
made the Mariners. He would call Seattle's clubhouse attendant
during the middle of a game. ``Tell Junior he's pulling off the
ball,'' dad would say into the phone. The attendant then would
relay the information to Junior.
</P>
<P>
   For no one knows Griffey Jr.'s swing better than Griffey Sr.
It's not hard to understand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the one who invented the swing,'' said dad. ``His swing
started to develop when he was about 7 or 8. Then we worked more on
thinking about what he's doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffey's stroke is honey sweet. He swings down on the ball,
from top to bottom _ ``It's like I'm chopping down a tree,'' said
dad. Because he hits down on it, backspin is created. Junior's
essentially a line-drive hitter, aided by this intense movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``So if you hit the ball 310 feet, and you got the backspin,
it's going to go 340,'' said dad. ``That's how his line drives are,
and they get a carry on them. He gets down through it and stays
above the ball and the ball carries.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Junior unleashes, his mental approach to hitting remains
uncomplicated. He doesn't guess pitch or location. He merely sees
the ball, then hits it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't get fooled much,'' said dad. ``He just looks for
the ball, in or out. He knows if it's away from him, he can hit it
out that way, and he knows if it's inside, he can pull it. That's
basically what I taught him as he came along.''
</P>
<P>
   One approach, two different players. That dad was a table-setter
for the Reds, a guy who got on base for Johnny Bench, Joe Morgan
and Tony Perez to knock in, while son is the table-clearer, means
nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey Sr. had to teach himself how to hit. His father left
when he was 2. His swing wasn't honed by roving hitting
instructors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like him having a short cut,'' Griffey Sr. about his son.
``And I knew what to develop because I had to be mentally strong
about everything. So I knew if he was happy and he was mentally
strong about certain parts of his game, he could be untouchable.''
</P>
<P>
   Exactly what the Reds are hoping.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-03-00 1822EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
