<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-03 18:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5955 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-THAI-PETROCHEMICAL-NY     03-03 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THAI-PETROCHEMICAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MULTI-BILLION-DOLLAR BANKRUPTCY BATTLE IN THAILAND HAS INVESTORS
WORRIED 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By WAYNE ARNOLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SINGAPORE _ A bitter bankruptcy court struggle between
Thailand's largest corporate borrower and its creditors has
generated considerable uncertainty over the fate of billions of
dollars in unpaid loans in the country where the Asia financial
crisis began.
</P>
<P>
   For the past two years, Thai Petrochemical Industry has been
talking with creditors over how to begin repaying $3.5 billion in
debts it defaulted on when the crisis struck. In late February, the
company balked at a deal that would leave its family owners in
charge but declare it insolvent. It was not insolvent, Thai
Petrochemical protested. Exasperated lenders, which include not
only Thailand's largest bank but the World Bank's International
Finance Corp. and the U.S. Export-Import Bank, petitioned
Thailand's fledgling bankruptcy court to let them take over the
company.
</P>
<P>
   The court said Thursday it would decide March 15, but more than
the company's fate appears to hang on the outcome. As the dispute
escalated in February, foreign investors headed for the exits,
sending Thailand's benchmark stock index tumbling almost 20 percent
in February to four-month lows.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big issue here is debt restructuring,'' said Therapong
Vachirapong, a strategist at Merrill Lynch in Bangkok. ``People now
realize it's a bit more difficult than they thought.''
</P>
<P>
   The strength of investors' reaction is giving some economists a
sense of deja vu: only weeks ago, the International Monetary Fund
declared Thailand's financial crisis over and said that the
country's economy could expand by 5 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
   Thailand's banks have already restructured about 1 trillion
baht, or $26.4 billion, in loans, according to the central bank's
corporate debt restructuring advisory committee.
</P>
<P>
   But so far, the restructuring agreements have been largely
consensual. Now comes the hard part, analysts say. The problems at
Thai Petrochemical trouble investors not only because the company
is Thailand's largest corporate debtor, but because of what it may
mean for attempts to recover some of the 2 trillion baht in
nonperforming loans that remain and the more than 400 lawsuits to
recover them filed by creditors in Thailand's new bankruptcy court.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are worried about whether the court is going to work,''
said Donaldson Hartman, an analyst at Salomon Smith Barney in
Bangkok.
</P>
<P>
   Thai Petrochemical was established in 1978 by an ethnic Chinese
family of rice traders, the Leophairatanas. To this day, Prachai
Leophairatana remains the company's chief executive, overseeing a
plastics and gasoline business that turned the family members into
billionaires in the mid-1990s.
</P>
<P>
   The devaluation of the baht in July 1997, however, nearly
doubled Thai Petrochemical's debt as measured in local currency.
Talks with creditors quickly degenerated into what has become a
bitter soap opera, as Prachai and the company's nearly 150 lenders
feud over how much ownership the family must surrender.
</P>
<P>
   About a year ago, the two sides reached a tentative agreement
that, in exchange for $300 million to $400 million in accrued
interest, the company would give creditors a 30 percent stake and
reduce the family's stake to 40 percent from roughly 60 percent.
Prachai would retain control but if the company failed to meet
interest payments, lenders could raise their stake to 75 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In December, Prachai sought to change the terms. Creditors
refused and issued a January deadline for Prachai to agree to a
court-supervised restructuring deal or be taken to court
involuntarily. The company objected and a court hearing began
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Legal experts say the case highlights remaining weaknesses in
Thailand's bankruptcy and foreclosure laws. Though both laws were
strengthened after the financial crisis struck, the bankruptcy law
still contains problems inherent in the original version Thailand
adopted decades ago from Britain, according to Sutee Supanit, a law
professor at Bangkok's Thammasat University. Foremost among its
shortcomings, experts say, is that the creditor must prove a
company is insolvent.
</P>
<P>
   Thai Petrochemical's defense is that it is not insolvent: assets
exceed liabilities. Creditors dispute that interpretation, saying
the company has not paid debts in two years and is therefore
insolvent.
</P>
<P>
   In English, both conditions fit the definition of insolvent. The
problem is that in the Thai legal lexicon, Sutee said, the word for
insolvent means liabilities that exceed a debtor's assets. An
inability to pay debts on time, on the other hand, is described by
a different Thai word that translates roughly into
``overindebtedness'' and is not provided for under the law.
</P>
<P>
   To decide in favor of Thai Petrochemical's lenders, Sutee said,
the judge hearing the case will have to expand the interpretation
of insolvency.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute has helped accelerate an exodus of foreign money
from Thailand's stock market. According to the Stock Exchange of
Thailand, foreigners pulled at least 9.7 billion baht out of the
market in February, more than in the previous three months
combined. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
