<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-03 18:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5967 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-GENOCIDE-MINISTER-HNS     03-03 0504
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GENOCIDE-MINISTER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     U.S. TO EXTRADITE MINISTER WANTED FOR GENOCIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By BONNIE PFISTER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAREDO, Texas _ An elderly Rwandan clergyman accused of genocide
and other international war crimes will be extradited within a few
weeks, a federal official said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Elizaphan Ntakirutimana, a former pastor with the Seventh-day
Adventist Church in Rwanda, will soon be deported to the
Tanzanian-based international tribunal for Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be a matter of days or weeks, not months,'' said Robin
Croft, a State Department official who deals with war crimes
issues.
</P>
<P>
   Such a move would make Ntakirutimana, who is in his 70s, the
first person arrested on U.S. soil to face an international war
crimes trial.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Ntakirutimana's lawyer nor his son, a medical doctor in
Laredo, could be reached for comment Friday. But in the past four
years of legal appeals, the senior Ntakirutimana has maintained his
innocence.
</P>
<P>
   The pastor was first arrested here in September 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. International Criminal Tribunal for Rwanda charged that
in April 1994, the minister herded hundreds of refugees into his
church. Ntakirutimana then led a mob armed with machetes, grenades
and guns to massacre the refugees, according to charges filed by
the tribunal.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Rwanda was in the throes of a bloody feud between
the country's dominant ethnic groups, the Hutus and Tutsis, strife
that killed an estimated 500,000 and sent 2 million refugees
fleeing to neighboring nations. Most of those killed, including
those in Ntakirutimana's church, were Tutsis. Ntakirutimana, a
Hutu, also is charged with being a fugitive of a foreign
government.
</P>
<P>
   Ntakirutimana was released from jail here in late 1997 by a
judge citing the lack of a U.S. extradition treaty with Tanzania,
where he would face trial.
</P>
<P>
   But two months later, federal agents arrested him again, saying
they had found more evidence against him.
</P>
<P>
   Ntakirutimana's lawyer, former U.S. Attorney General Ramsey
Clark, could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   However, Clark has said his client could not receive a fair
trial in Tanzania, because anyone testifying on Ntakirutimana's
behalf would suffer reprisals in Rwanda. His client's final avenue
of appeal was closed in January, when the U.S. Supreme Court
declined to hear the case.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright signed a
surrender warrant authorizing the extradition of the Rwandan man.
Croft said U.S. Marshals and a physician would transport the
prisoner from the Laredo jail.
</P>
<P>
   Ntakirutimana has been ill during much of his confinement in the
Webb County Detention Center. A condition affecting his esophagus
and throat often sent him to the jail infirmary.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, jail administrator George Gonzalez said Ntakirutimana
appeared to be healthy on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was visiting with his family this morning. He seemed
fine,'' Gonzalez said.
</P>
</TEXT>
