<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GENOCIDE-MINISTER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     U.S. TO EXTRADITE MINISTER WANTED FOR GENOCIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By BONNIE PFISTER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAREDO, Texas _ An elderly Rwandan clergyman accused of genocide
and other international war crimes will be extradited within a few
weeks, a federal official said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Elizaphan Ntakirutimana, a former pastor with the Seventh-day
Adventist Church in Rwanda, will soon be deported to the
Tanzanian-based international tribunal for Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be a matter of days or weeks, not months,'' said Robin
Croft, a State Department official who deals with war crimes
issues.
</P>
<P>
   Such a move would make Ntakirutimana, who is in his 70s, the
first person arrested on U.S. soil to face an international war
crimes trial.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Ntakirutimana's lawyer nor his son, a medical doctor in
Laredo, could be reached for comment Friday. But in the past four
years of legal appeals, the senior Ntakirutimana has maintained his
innocence.
</P>
<P>
   The pastor was first arrested here in September 1996.
</P>
