<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-03 18:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5975 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-NY-WOMEN'S-VOTE-HNS &LR;      03-03 1065
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-WOMEN'S-VOTE </SLUG>
 -HNS  
 &HT;     BUSH AND McCAIN BATTLE FOR WOMEN'S VOTE IN NEW YORK  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 &HT;     By STEWART M. POWELL and DAN FREEDMAN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush and Sen. John McCain,
R-Ariz., battled Friday for the influential women's vote in the New
York presidential primar9, a contest McCain has said he must win.
</P>
<P>
   Bush put McCain on the defensive with radio commercials accusing
him of voting to cut federal funds for two New York-based breast
cancer research programs. The two programs _ at New York University
Program in Women's Cancer and the North Shore-Long Island Jewish
Health System's breast cancer program _ were among a list of $13
billion in projects that McCain's web site characterized as
``garden variety pork.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush highlighted the breast cancer issue by visiting a breast
cancer awareness program at Stony Brook Health Sciences Center on
Long Island. Long Island has one of the nation's highest rates of
breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Bush told reporters, ``I don't think the senator should be
squealing about pork and then squealing when somebody disagrees
with one of the cuts he wants to make.''
</P>
<P>
   There are 13 primaries on Super Tuesday when 56 percent of the
GOP convention delegates will be selected. New York will provide
101 of those delegates and McCain has said he must win the state in
order to offset his expected losses in California and other states.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, women are an influential swing constituency, with
recent elections showing that a successful candidate in New York
must garner the support of women.
</P>
<P>
   New York Gov. George Pataki joined Bush at the Stony Brook
campus and complained that ``time and again, Sen. McCain has voted
against our interests.'' The governor said that what McCain called
``garden variety pork'' is instead ``important research funds to
help us beat cancer.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain responded to Bush's criticism by citing his 18-year
congressional record of voting for breast cancer research. He also
touted his unsuccessful effort to levy taxeson the tobacco
industry that would have generated $50 billion in federal revenue _
some of it for cancer research.
</P>
<P>
   Anti-cancer research projects sometimes are buried in
controversial appropriations measures approved by Congress that
also include treasured pet projects back home that critics dub
``pork barrel spending.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain, in an interview on the Don ``Imus in the Morning'' radio
talk show, said the Bush campaign ad distorted his voting record on
breast cancer research.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've voted for it many times,'' McCain said, adding: ``It's
really an unfortunate part of American political campaigns when the
Bush people would pay for such an outrageous statement.''
</P>
<P>
   Guy Molinari, the Staten Island borough president and former
congressman leading McCain's campaign here in New York, said the
Bush campaign had unfairly isolated two cancer programs among
nearly 800 so-called ``pork barrel'' spending projects that McCain
had criticized for inclusion in multi-billion dollar appropriations
measures.
</P>
<P>
   Molinari said McCain had opposed the measures not on merit but
because lawmakers had sneaked the spending into the final
legislation without scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   McCain campaign manager Rick Davis said the Bush campaign
attacks on McCain's record were using a ``cheap trick'' of
isolating McCain's votes on legislative maneuvering to portray him
as an opponent of the spending.
</P>
<P>
   McCain made no reference to the fact that his sister, Sandy
McCain Morgan, has been treated for breast cancer at Johns Hopkins
University. Morgan told Salon Magazine in a telephone interview
that her cancer was in remission and that she was ``very grateful
for my brother's support for breast cancer research.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain tried to steer the campaign debate back to his own
insurgency message of ending the influence of special interests in
the nation's capital.
</P>
<P>
   In a fiery address in the Wall Street financial district, McCain
decried a mysterious, $2 million advertising blitz launched in New
York by a mysterious group calling itself ``Republicans for Clean
Air.'' The ad attacks his record on clean air environmental
regulation.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said the ad, paid for by an unknown organization with a
post office box in Virginia, underscores the impact that special
interests can have in election campaigns using undisclosed,
unregulated soft money contributions to launch message ads without
formal ties to a candidate.
</P>
<P>
   McCain railed against ``big money _ from God knows where _ that
distorts the election'' and urged New Yorkers to ``send a message
back to the special interests that we're sick of your influence in
New York and in America and we want our government back.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, Texas investor Sam Wyly, a prominent Bush supporter, was
identified as the sponsor of the ad. Bush denied there was a
connection between his campaign and the ad.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's successful effort to put McCain on the defensive over his
record on breast cancer research could bolster the edge that Bush
already enjoys among women voters.
</P>
<P>
   Bush rolled up a 16 percentage point edge among women voters in
Virginia's Feb. 29 primary and a 14 percentage point advantage in
South Carolina's Feb. 19 contest, contributing to decisive
victories that rescued his then-faltering campaign for the GOP
presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Even in Michigan's Feb. 22 presidential primary where Bush lost
to McCain, Bush held down the margin of McCain's victory with the
help of women voters; Bush trailed McCain among women in Michigan
by 4 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic Rep. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., ousted Sen. Alfonse
D'Amato, R-N.Y., in 1998, thanks in part to a 19-percentage point
edge among women. Republican Gov. George Pataki quelled a
Democratic challenge for a second term in 1998, with a 19
percentage point edge among women. Pataki was able to defeat
Democratic New York Gov. Mario Cuomo in 1994 when Cuomo's support
among women wavered.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton captured the state in 1992 and 1996 with a
substantial edge among women, holding a 35 percent edge among women
voters over Republican challenger Bob Dole in 1996 and a 24 point
edge among women voters in 1992 when he defeated President George
W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell and Dan Freedman can be reached at
202-298-6920.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
