</P>
<P>
   POLICE-CRIME-RATES (New York) _ With the city's stunning drop in
crime in the 1990s, many New Yorkers have come to assume that
aggressive police tactics and crime reductions are inextricably
linked. But a look at other cities around the nation suggests that
large reductions in crime can be achieved with less reliance on the
kinds of confrontational law enforcement measures New York has
used. Some cities, notably San Diego and Boston, have recorded as
big or even larger drops in violence through strategies that rely
on close cooperation between the police and the community. By Fox
Butterfield.
</P>
<P>
   WATCHING-TIGER (Undated) _ When Tiger Woods plays golf,
television executives swoon. With his rare power to move ratings,
he is the sports version of ``E.R.'' or ``Who Wants To Be a
Millionaire,'' a singular, 24-year-old programming entity capable
of clubbing rival networks in their Nielsens in his pursuit of
tournament victories. Woods doesn't have to win. He simply needs a
chance at victory to stir viewers to watch. By Richard Sandomir.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   ECON-REPORT (Undated) _ Job growth suddenly weakened in
February, the Labor Department reported Friday, but there were few
indications that the unexpected slowdown in job creation pointed to
a serious softening of the economic boom. By Louis Uchitelle.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
