u f BC-BORDERS-NYT &LR;      03-03 0496
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERRILL LYNCH TO HELP BORDERS SEEK WAYS TO BOOST ITS LAGGING
STOCK 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CLAUDIA H. DEUTSCH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Borders Group Inc., one of the nation's leading booksellers,
said Friday that it had hired Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. to explore steps
it might take to bolster its faltering stock price.
</P>
<P>
   Gregory P. Josefowicz, the chief executive of the book chain,
said in a statement that the alternatives ``could include a
recapitalization, a leveraged buyout or a business combination with
another company.'' Analysts said they expected that stock buybacks
and perhaps a sale of part of the company's money-losing Internet
operation, Borders.com, would be high on the list.
</P>
<P>
   The company's stock has been trading in the low to mid teens,
down from more than $40 a share in mid-1998, despite several years
of matching or even beating analysts' earnings estimates. The
company is scheduled to announce fourth-quarter results Monday,
``and there's no reason to expect a downside surprise this time,
either,'' said Charles L. Hill, director of research at First
Call/Thomson Financial.
</P>
<P>
   Borders has some Wall Street fans. ``This is a misunderstood,
undervalued stock,'' said Donald I. Trott, an analyst with Brown
Brothers Harriman who recently upgraded his recommendation on the
stock to ``buy'' from ``neutral.'' Although there are many lukewarm
``buy'' recommendations, ``no one's pounding the table saying you
must buy this stock,'' Hill said.
</P>
<P>
   Borders' stock woes, most analysts say, reflect investor
uncertainty over how well the chain can fare in an increasingly
dot-com world. The company's same-store sales, a prime barometer of
retail health, have been steadily increasing. In fact, several
analysts note that people who browse through book titles on the Web
are often driven into bookstores to learn more about interesting
titles. Still, Borders.com is losing enough money to pull the
company's overall profits down substantially.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes &AMP; Noble, the country's largest book chain, sold half of
its dot.com operation to Bertelsmann _ for a sum that analysts said
was twice what it had invested _ and the two owners in turn sold 20
percent of the company to the public last spring. Thus, Barnes &AMP;
Noble has already reaped cash from its Internet foray and has
reduced the effect of online losses on the parent company's bottom
line.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes &AMP; Noble's stock, however, has not done well, either _ it
closed at $9.9375 a share Friday, well below the $40 it traded at
last spring. ``There's a general lack of interest in retail stocks,
and particularly in specialized retail categories,'' said Amy E.
Ryan, who follows Borders for Prudential Securities.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Borders' announcement seems to have cheered investors
somewhat. Borders shares rose $2.0625, to $14.9375, on the New York
Stock Exchange. ``Sometimes, just hiring an investment banker turns
into a self-fulfilling situation,'' Trott said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-03-00 1858EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
