<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-INTERNET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON ORDERS SECURITY EVALUATION OF GOVERNMENT COMPUTERS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CRAGG HINES 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. _ President Clinton, reacting to public and
corporate alarm at massive, intentional Internet disruptions, on
Friday ordered a governmentwide study of federal computer system
security.
</P>
<P>
   In an executive memorandum, Clinton directed each federal
department and agency to review its computers against ``denial of
service attacks'' such as those directed at some of the busiest
Internet sites earlier this year. He named White House chief of
staff John Podesta to coordinate the review.
</P>
<P>
   ``These Internet disruptions highlight how important computer
networks have become to our daily lives and how vulnerabilities can
create risks for all _ including the federal government,'' Clinton
said in the order.
</P>
<P>
   The memo was issued as Clinton traveled to Silicon Valley to
speak to an Aspen Institute Forum on Communications and Society,
where his audience included executives from some targets of the
disruption, such as Yahoo. Such sites were bombarded with so many
hits that they crashed.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton promised to order the government review after a White
House meeting last month with communication company executives,
academics and privacy experts. That followed his release in January
of the first National Plan for Information Systems Protection and
his call for $2 billion in federal spending on computer security.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know we have to keep cyberspace open and free because it
sparks innovation,'' Clinton told the conference. He said his memo
was a government attempt to ``lead by example.''
</P>
<P>
   One point of the review, he said, would be to ensure that
government computer systems are not used as conduits by outsiders
to attack systems in the private sector.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also argued against overreaction: ``We must not
undermine freedom in the name of freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   He said, however, some data is ``so sensitive'' that it must be
protected from unauthorized dissemination. He mentioned medical
records, financial records and Internet communications between
parents and children.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are worried about this,'' Clinton said. ``This is a big
deal to people. ... They are really concerned. They are afraid they
will have no place to hide.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton urged high-tech communications firms to heighten their
self-policing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you have privacy policies you'd be glad to have reported in
the media?'' Clinton asked.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also touted his administration's effort to reduce the
``digital divide'' that he contends keeps some poor people and
minorities from sharing in the benefits of high-tech advances. The
president also pledged continued support for nanotechnology, the
work that allows information storage at an atomic or molecular
level.
</P>
<P>
   He said that if successful, the entire holdings of the Library
of Congress could be stored in the space of a sugar cube and cancer
could be detected when only a few cells had been affected.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's 30-minute speech at the headquarters of Novell, a
computer networking company, was a ``cover'' event to ensure that
the government will pay at least part of the expense of the
California leg of the president's weekend trip.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spent much of the remainder of the day at three
Democratic fund-raising events expected to raise $1 million for the
party, much of it unregulated contributions known as ``soft
money,'' which has draw criticism from campaign-finance reformers.
</P>
<P>
   At his final event Friday night, Clinton was scheduled at a
private residence where 16 people, for a minimum contribution of
$50,000 a couple, were to nibble a fruit meringue dessert with the
president _ for an estimated total take of $400,000.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will visit with daughter Chelsea, who is attending
Stanford University, before flying Saturday afternoon to Los
Angeles for two more Democratic fund-raising events.
</P>
<P>
   Before returning to Washington on Sunday, he will fly to Alabama
to participate in events marking the 35th anniversary of the
Selma-Montgomery civil rights march and the bloody confrontation of
demonstrators and local white law enforcement personnel.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
