<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-03 19:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5986 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-DALI-EXHIBIT-ART-NYT &LR;      03-03 1224
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DALI-EXHIBIT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPACKAGING DALI FOR A NEW GENERATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By GRACE GLUECK    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. _ One known as the clown prince of Surrealism,
Salvador Dali (1905-1989) saw his muse as ``Paranoia,'' and he
painted her in 1935-36, a kitschy bust with a bosom deep in
Hollywood decolletage. Her fugitive face is composed of a
Leonardo-esque battle scene, with eyes formed by the rumps of
warriors' horses and the nose and mouth a twisted figure. The
setting is pure de Chirico (an artist from whom Dali freely
appropriated), a stagy floor of boards reaching back in long
perspective to the rocky seascape of Cadaques, Dali's home in
northern Spain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paranoia'' is among some 60 Dali visions on view in ``Salvador
Dali's Optical Illusions'' at the Wadsworth Atheneum here. The show
is said to be the first Dali retrospective in this country in
nearly 60 years and the first devoted to his preoccupation with
optics and visual perception. But Dali goes way back with the
Wadsworth; in 1932, under its innovative director, Chick Austin, it
was the first museum in the world to purchase one of Dali's
paintings.
</P>
<P>
   This show, a clever repackaging of his work for a new
generation, was organized by the Wadsworth with an outside curator,
Dawn Ades, a Dali scholar who is professor of art history and
theory at the University of Essex in England. It has been
attracting large crowds, the biggest since the museum's exhibition
of Robert Mapplethorpe's homoerotic photographs in 1989. Viewers
seem intrigued by the images _ some haunting, some downright silly
_ and the optical challenges in the paintings, which were dismissed
as ``crossword puzzles'' by the Surrealist theorist Andre Breton
when Dali fell out of favor with the movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paranoia'' is one of the simpler paintings done in what Dali
called his ``paranoiac-critical'' method, by which he meant the
replacement of so-called reality with an obsessional or delusional
reading of it. A madman's version, in his view, was as deserving of
attention as a more rational perception. Not that he himself was a
madman; he simply felt, he said, that the world of the inner self _
its dreams, reveries, fears and delusions _ should be rendered ``as
objectively evident as the exterior world of phenomenal reality.''
</P>
<P>
   The chief tool of the paranoiac-critical method was the double
or multiple image. Like those old childhood puzzles that challenge
you to find the gamboling lamb in the little girl's hair, its aim
was to make one image function simultaneously as another. In
``Paranoia'' the battle scene, viewed at a short distance from the
painting, reassembles itself into the muse's face.
</P>
<P>
   An earlier work, ``The Invisible Man'' (1929-32), contains the
first of the paranoiac double images, a gigantic seated hominid
constructed from landscape elements. His hair is a flow of golden
clouds, his head a pile of ruins; his hands and legs are formed by
the negative shapes around an Art Nouveau fountain that is closest
to the viewer. Other Dali-esque elements in the painting include a
woman's head that is also a jug, a gruesome ``family'' group and
two sexy women standing on the ledge of a classical building. They
represent Gala, Dali's adored, omnipresent wife and astute business
manager.
</P>
<P>
   Besides double imagery Dali was interested in more complicated
illusory strategies, like anamorphosis, an elongated distortion
that looks normal only when viewed from a certain perspective. The
best-known example of it is the crude apparition resembling a
whale's jaw that lies mysteriously on the floor in Hans Holbein's
elegant painting ``The Ambassadors'' (1533). When viewed from the
right of the painting at the level of its two subjects' heads, it
is decipherable as a skull.
</P>
<P>
   Dali's use of anamorphosis is seen at its eeriest in the 1933
painting ``Myself at the Age of 10 When I Was the Grasshopper's
Child (Castration Complex).'' Dressed in the sailor suit Dali used
as a symbol of himself when young, a boy sits before a table, his
enormously elongated, fishlike head stretched out on it. The table,
too, is grotesquely elongated, reaching toward a distant horizon to
end in a phallic cone.
</P>
<P>
   Although no grasshoppers are visible, the painting, as described
in its catalog entry, relates to Dali's phobia of these insects,
which in turn refers to a castration complex engendered by his
relationship with his father, which goes beyond that to the
repulsion caused by the insect's sudden movements from stillness to
action and its sliminess when crushed, which ultimately refers to
the pull between existence and annihilation _ well, you get the
picture.
</P>
<P>
   Many negative things can be said about Dali. He was a terminal
publicity hound who courted public attention with outrageous
behavior and pronunciamentos. He was an aesthetic reactionary who
looked to the past while the 20th century soldiered on with
modernism. And he was an anti-democrat who expressed racist views,
made light of Hitler and _ though an early supporter of the
Loyalist side in the Spanish Civil War _ accepted the Franco
regime, returning to Spain after the dictator's victory.
</P>
<P>
   Yet he was a virtuoso painter, with a keen interest in art
history and the sciences (particularly psychoanalysis). His
paintings of the 1920s and early '30s, before he turned to religion
as a subject, are sometimes dazzling. Among the best in the show
are smaller canvases, like ``The Phantom Cart'' (1933), a quiet
evocation of his childhood in the Pyrenees. It's a simple theme: a
cart, seen from the back, travels across a stretch of sugar-colored
sand toward a distant town, its two inhabitants blending with the
buildings as they remain individuals. A sparkling amphora fragment
lies in the foreground, a relic of the area's ancient
civilizations.
</P>
<P>
   A far bolder and more powerful work is ``Soft Construction With
Boiled Beans: Premonition of Civil War'' (1936), in which a
Goya-inspired human monster rends its own body limb from limb. Its
positioning forms a grotesque rhombus through which appear an
incongruously bright sky and clouds. The ``boiled beans'' scattered
around the death-wracked monster refer to another Dali theme in
which a cannibalistic father bent on killing his son is distracted
by an offering of different food.
</P>
<P>
   But Dali's later works, often religious in imagery, tend to be
stiff and bombastic. Some seem painted merely in the interest of
visual games, like ``Gala's Christ'' (1978). It consists of two
canvases, similar but for slight changes in viewpoint and subject
matter; each presents a highly foreshortened view of a female body
lying on a cross that floats horizontally in midair. An angled
mirror placed between them gives a ``stereoscopic'' or
three-dimensional effect. Yet the painting itself is empty,
emotionally dead.
</P>
<P>
   Does this show reveal Dali as an artist of cosmic consequence?
No. But it does provide an intriguing new look the former
Surrealist poster boy whom the art world has long been used to
dissing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Salvador Dali's Optical Illusions'' is at the Wadsworth
Atheneum, 600 Main St., Hartford, (860) 278-2670, through March 26.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
