<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-03 19:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5991 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CAR-NASCAR-AERODYNAMI     03-03 0481
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-AERODYNAMICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASCAR IS CALM ... FOR NOW  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.C., Nev., Fla., Ala.)   By PATRICK ZIER   
 The Ledger, Lakeland, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After watching General Motors' cars rebound at Rockingham, N.C.,
NASCAR plans no rule changes for Sunday's Winston Cup at Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Chevy teams in particular were vocal after Daytona, where Ford
dominated and appeared to have an advantage aerodynamically.
</P>
<P>
   After the Daytona 500, NASCAR took Dale Jarrett's Ford, Ward
Burton's Pontiac and Mike Skinner's Chevy to the wind tunnel for
tests. After the Dura Lube/K mart 400 in Rockingham, it ran tests
on Bobby Labonte's Pontiac, Dale Earnhardt's Chevy and Jarrett's
Ford to try and determine if any make has a built-in advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Labonte won at Rockingham and Earnhardt finished second,
followed by Ward Burton and Tony Stewart, both in Pontiacs. Jarrett
finished fifth.
</P>
<P>
   ``The competition was much more balanced at Rockingham,'' said
Kevin Triplett, NASCAR's director of operations. ``It was what we
hoped to see at Daytona, but everybody knows Daytona and Talladega
are different.''
</P>
<P>
   The tracks in Daytona, Fla., and Talladega, Ala., are the only
one where restrictor plates are used on engines. The plates limit
the air-fuel mixture reaching the engine, cutting horsepower.
Aerodynamics are also important at Daytona and Talladega because
the tracks are steeply banked.
</P>
<P>
   For those reasons and others, Daytona and Talladega cannot be
used as a gauge for what will happen elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   While Fords swept the first five spots in the Daytona 500, a
Pontiac won Rockingham and three Pontiacs and a Chevy took the
first four spots.
</P>
<P>
   Triplett said he felt Chevy, Ford and Pontiac cares qualified
well and raced well at Daytona. He said Mark Martin and Rusty
Wallace were strong in their Fords and Bobby Labonte and Tony
Stewart ran well in Pontiacs. Overall, we were pleased with the
results.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin and Wallace drive Fords; Labonte and Stewart Pontiacs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It should be very interesting in Las Vegas,'' Triplett said.
``That's a place where, if somebody hits the setup, they can check
out on everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Triplett pointed out that Daytona presents special problems for
NASCAR, especially when new cars are being introduced.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not an ideal situation for us to go into our biggest race
of the year with so many unknowns,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the alternative isn't much better. You don't want to
approve a new body style late in the year and give somebody an
advantage in the last few races when there's a close race.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something we constantly have to look at,'' Triplett
added.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's Carsdirect.com 400 in Las Vegas begins at 2:30 p.m.
Eastern
</P>
<P>
   (Patrick Zier writes for The Ledger in Lakeland, Fla. The Ledger
is part of the New York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-03-00 1902EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
