<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-03 19:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5999 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-GUENNOL-EXHIBIT-ART-N     03-03 1126
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUENNOL-EXHIBIT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WORLD OF OBJECTS UNITED BY THE PASSION OF 2 COLLECTORS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By KEN JOHNSON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Can art collecting itself be an art? If you doubt it,
see ``The Guennol Collection: Cabinet of Wonders'' at the Brooklyn
Museum of Art.
</P>
<P>
   Alastair Bradley and Edith Park Martin, who began collecting in
the late 1940s, were not artists in the strict sense of the word,
nor is their collection, strictly speaking, a work of art. But they
pursued their aesthetic interests like artists, with a refreshing
disregard for the usual categories of art history and an absolute
insistence on the primacy of personal response. A result is an
extremely diverse collection unified by a singular sensibility, a
kind of psychological double self-portrait.
</P>
<P>
   In naming the collection, the Martins used the Welsh word
gwennol (meaning martin, the bird in memory of their honeymoon in
Wales. Mr. Martin, a New York investor who has been a Brooklyn
Museum trustee since 1948, and Mrs. Martin, who died in 1986,
provided many works to the museum as gifts or as long-term loans.
This exhibition brings together for the first time their loans,
more than 40 gifts and works from the family's collection.
</P>
<P>
   That the 100-plus objects on display do seem to belong together
is amazing, for they represent almost all the earth's continents
and date from more than 5,000 years. To view the exhibition is to
leap freely through time and space _ from ancient Egypt to New York
modernism; from pre-Columbian to American folk art; from Africa to
Japan _ yet to feel one is always still in the same magical place.
</P>
<P>
   With its many carefully placed, mostly small, mostly
three-dimensional curiosities, the exhibition is like a walk-in box
by Joseph Cornell, one of whose dreamy yet rigorously formal
assemblages greets the visitor at the beginning of the show.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the extraordinary diversity, you don't have to look at
many pieces before you begin to understand the rules. You can see
that the Martins favored things formally compact (often small
enough to hold in your hand) and exquisitely refined, like a
graceful four-inch marble bowl encircled by the smoothly carved
heads and wings of ducks (from Egypt, circa 1938-1759 B.C.). They
also liked things imbued with a kind of primitive animation, like
the sweetly pensive head of a giraffe from a 19th-century American
carousel. And as in Albert Pinkham Ryder's painting ``The Lovers'
Boat,'' they were drawn to things fantastic or visionary.
</P>
<P>
   A top contender to best embody the spirit of the Guennol
collection is ``Leonine Goddess,'' a small sculpture thought to
have been made in southwestern Iran around 3000 B.C. Just over
three inches tall, this smooth carving in white limestone depicts a
lion with the body of a human weight lifter. With its finely
modeled head turned to one side, its beefy arms drawn close and its
fingers interlocked it radiates the relaxed potential strength of a
powerful athlete. It is at once a materially beautiful object and a
haunting mythic image. (Children might enjoy its resemblance to
certain contemporary superhero toys.)
</P>
<P>
   It is interesting to learn that when the Martins lent ``Leonine
Goddess'' to the Brooklyn Museum in 1948, no one knew what it was.
Its exact identity still remains uncertain and yet it has been one
of the most widely reproduced works in the museum's collection, an
eloquent testimony to intuitions untainted by professional
training.
</P>
<P>
   The Brooklyn Museum curators who organized the exhibition, Diana
Fane and Amy G. Poster, have responded admirably to the
idiosyncratic variety of the collection. Conceiving the exhibition
as a ``Cabinet of Wonders'' _ a reference to the European
Wunderkammer of the 16th and 17th centuries, in which awe-inspiring
natural and artistic wonders were displayed _ they have not tried
to impose the usual art historical categories. Objects are grouped
thematically, but each group contains works of very different
origins.
</P>
<P>
   In a section called ``Collaborations Between Art and Nature,''
there is a miniature faux tree from 17th-century Germany made of
bright orange coral planted in a tiny gold pot and mounted on a bed
of purple amethyst. Sharing the case is a 19th-century American
folk artwork, a plaque in which a map of a town intricately inlaid
in wood embraces a found stone, which represents a pond while
suggesting a woman's ghostly profile. Such juxtapositions bring out
the unique qualities of each piece.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bestiary'' offers more similarity among objects, all
representations of animals. This section will appeal to the
viewer's inner child: there is a fat, blue, six-inch hippopotamus
from ancient Egypt; a playfully crouched celadon lion from Japan
with swirling mane and tail and a big grinning mouth; and a painted
wood sculpture of `` Frog and Toad Out for a Ride'' in a wooden
boat, by Oscar Peterson, an American folk artist.
</P>
<P>
   Where works resonate together most strikingly is in ``Between
Worlds.'' A ferocious, toothy woman by Willem de Kooning; a
maniacally grinning, pop-eyed bronze ``Head of a Guardian'' from
Japan; a Mexican folk sculpture of the skeletal figure of death
riding in a rough cart; and a rugged, simply carved gravestone by
the American folk artist William Edmondson together create a richly
uncanny, macabre atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   The show's other categories are ``Object and Text,'' ``Royal and
Elite Patronage'' and ``Exotic Materials, Technical Virtuosity.''
</P>
<P>
   One can imagine some politically minded critics objecting that
the Guennol Collection is ethnocentric: instead of explaining
artworks in terms of what they meant to their cultures, it
privileges the taste of acquisitive Westerners. It is true that the
Martins absorbed cultural expressions of all sorts into their own
world and put them to the service of their own self-expression. Yet
there is nothing self-aggrandizing about their enterprise and it
would be absurd to say that they erased the identity of any object.
</P>
<P>
   It is surely  &UR; because &LR;  they were so ruthlessly true to their own
instinctive susceptibility to the unique and the beautiful and
shrugged off the imperatives of any institutional agenda _
academic, political, moral _ that each object in the collection
retains its own distinctive character and radiates so arrestingly
its own sacred essence. It would be hard to imagine a more deeply
respectful approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Guennol Collection: Cabinet of Wonders'' is at the
Brooklyn Museum of Art, 200 Eastern Parkway, at Prospect Park,
(718) 638-5000, through May 7.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
