<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JUDICIAL-NOMINATIONS-$ADV05-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     LONGEST WAIT IN JUDICIAL NOMINATIONS HISTORY TO END 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (For release Sunday, March 5.)   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARK HELM  
 &HT;     c. 2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After a record-breaking four-year wait, Richard
Paez, one of California's most controversial federal judges, is
expected to be approved this week for a seat on the U.S. 9th
Circuit Court of Appeals.
</P>
<P>
   But the resolution of his fate has not come easily. Last
November Sen. Barbara Boxer, D-Calif., held up a Senate vote on the
judicial nomination of a friend of Senate Majority Leader Trent
Lott, R-Miss., in order to force a vote on Paez, whose nomination
had blocked by conservative Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sen. Boxer has always been very interested in making sure Paez
got his chance,'' Boxer spokesman David Sandretti said Friday. He
said Paez has waited longer for a confirmation vote than any other
judicial appointee.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after Boxer's action, Lott relented and promised to
allow a vote on Paez by March 15, but only on the condition that
Boxer stop holding up the nomination of his friend Glenn
McCullough, the mayor of Tupelo, Miss., to the governing board of
the Tennessee Valley Authority.
</P>
<P>
   The deal also cleared the way for a Senate floor vote on another
California nominee, Marsha L. Berzon, to the 9th Circuit Court of
Appeals, which covers California and eight other Western states.
Berzon's nomination has been pending for nearly two years.The
conservative Republican senators objected to Paez, a U.S. District
Court judge in Los Angeles, and Berzon, a San Francisco lawyer
specializing in federal appeals cases, saying that they are too
liberal. Berzon is also a member of the board of the American Civil
Liberties Union.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's plenty out there to cause me great concern,'' Sen. Don
Nickles, R-Okla., said last week, adding that opposition to the
nominations was growing among GOP senators. However, backers of the
pair say they have the votes to win.
</P>
<P>
   Paez's nomination also has drawn fire from a conservative
judicial watchdog organization. ``There's more opposition to Paez
than any judicial nomination outside the Supreme Court,'' said
Thomas J. Jipping, director of the Judicial Selection Monitoring
Project of the Free Congress Foundation, a Washington-based
conservative group.Jipping contended that Paez engages in
``judicial activism,'' refusing to fully enforce laws that he
disagrees with. In a letter to Senate Judiciary Committee Chairman
Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, Jipping pointed to statements Paez made in a
1995 speech criticizing a 1994 ballot measure approved by the
voters that would have cut off nearly all social service benefits
to undocumented immigrants. That measure was later ruled
unconstitutional. He also criticized a measure that was about to go
on the 1996 ballot that ended affirmative action hiring, admissions
and contracting in state programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``In that speech, (Paez) also demonstrated his preference for
politics over judicial independence by actually calling for
lawsuits to force diversity in judicial appointments,'' Jipping
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   However, Democrats point out that both Berzon and Paez have
gained the support of several prominent Republicans, including
Hatch, who called Berzon one of the most qualified nominees he has
ever seen.``These are two extremely qualified candidates, and they
deserve a vote,'' Sandretti said.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past year, Democrats had showcased the stalled
nominations of Paez, a Latino, and Berzon, arguing that Senate
Republicans were slow in dealing with judicial nominees who were
female or members of minority groups. The Republicans denied the
accusation.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic campaign led to Boxer's move last November to
take a political hostage of her own, blocking a Senate vote on
McCullough, who had been nominated by Clinton as a favor to Lott.
</P>
<P>
   Boxer invoked a Senate rule allowing an individual senator to
put a ``hold'' on a measure, blocking floor action on it.
</P>
<P>
   In their agreement Lott agreed to allow an eventual vote on the
two Californians, and Boxer agreed to let the Senate vote on
McCullough on Nov. 12. Later that evening, the Senate confirmed
McCullough's nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Latino leaders applauded the agreement to push the nominations
to a floor vote and praised Boxer for her efforts on the
Californians' behalf. ``We're very excited these two qualified
individuals finally will get te chance they deserve,'' said Marisa
Demeo, regional counsel for the Mexican American Legal Defense and
Education Fund, a Washington-based advocacy group.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too bad that it's taken this long, but better late than
never,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
