<HEADER>
A6028 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-NOISE-MUSIC-REVIEW-NY     03-03 0947
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOISE-MUSIC-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`NOISE OF TIME': TO THE LAST SIGH: A DARK, DRAMATIC PORTRAIT OF
SHOSTAKOVICH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Britain, Russia) (See also NOISE-THEATER-REVIEW) 
(DW) 
 By ANTHONY TOMMASINI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a sense, every committed performance of a
Shostakovich string quartet is already a dramatic presentation.
This Russian master's 15 quartets are haunting and confounding
works, at once craftily composed scores and deeply personal
chapters of a musical memoir. So the idea of creating a multimedia
theatrical work to depict the life and times of Dmitri Shostakovich
that had as its core a performance of his searing final string
quartet from 1974 would seem to be fraught with potential pitfalls.
</P>
<P>
   The most memorable aspect of ``The Noise of Time,'' the
ambitious, amorphous theater piece receiving its world premiere
though Sunday at the John Jay College Theater, a collaboration
between the director Simon McBurney, who conceived it, the Theatre
de Complicite (the London-based company McBurney directs) and the
Emerson String Quartet, is the way the work succeeds in providing a
boldly theatrical frame for a performance of String Quartet No. 15
in E flat minor. ``The Noise of Time'' shatters the normal
protocols of concertgoing and compels the audience to experience
this discomforting music without intellectual defenses to protect
yourself.
</P>
<P>
   The actual theater piece that provides a context for the
performance of the quartet, which uses taped readings of poetry,
letters and autobiographical materials as well as projected
photographs, film clips and four silent actors, is by turns
fascinating and exasperating. Presenting a clear, chronological
narrative is not the point here.
</P>
<P>
   If, for example, you do not know that the cellist Mstislav
Rostropovich was one of Dmitri Shostakovich's most devoted younger
colleagues, it will take you time to realize that the comments of a
man identified as Slava are from Rostropovich.
</P>
<P>
   As its title implies, the work seeks to evoke not just the
composer but also the entire era he lived through. For example, a
powerful image is used to convey the effect of the 1942 radio
broadcast of Shostakovich's Seventh Symphony, the ``Leningrad.''
After its premiere in the Soviet Union, a microfilm of the score
was sent to the United States. Toscanini conducted the work in a
live broadcast with the NBC Symphony Orchestra. This bombastic
flawed symphony became a symbol of resistance to the Nazis. Here,
the image of lonely men bent over their home radios, lighted only
by the glow from the dials, poignantly captures the effect this
music must have had on the millions who heard it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Noise of Time'' is so intentionally a mash of sounds and
imagery that when the piece turns in its last segment to the
performance of the quartet, you feel that finally something
concrete is happening. But the very chaos of the theatrical
experience makes us want, even need, to hear that music by that
point.
</P>
<P>
   Last month the players of the Emerson String Quartet
demonstrated their intense connection to Shostakovich's quartets
when they performed all 15 works in order in a remarkable series of
five concerts at Alice Tully Hall. Typically, fine ensemble work is
a benchmark of great string quartet playing: can the four musicians
play and think and breathe as one? But here, the violinists Philip
Setzer and Eugene Drucker, the violist Lawrence Dutton and the
cellist David Finckel emerge from separate corners of the stage,
playing in light barely bright enough to see.
</P>
<P>
   The slowly inexorable, quietly anguished modal music of the
opening Elegy employs the four instruments with daring independence
and in this theatrical context, as the players walk slowly about
the stage, we hear the music as four individual voices. Even to
someone who knows this score well, it was a revelatory listening
experience. The players perform whole stretches of the work from
memory and without benefit of eye cues.
</P>
<P>
   As the first movement proceeds, each of the four actors pairs up
with a musician. One of them sits opposite the cellist, Finckel,
staring intently, vanquished by the music. Another, engrossed in
the violist's printed score, sits on a chair reading it, entranced
as Dutton meekly looks over the actor's shoulder and plays the
music with mournful beauty.
</P>
<P>
   Gradually, as the Elegy segues into the deceptively titled
Serenade, a fractured, slow dance of the soul, and then the
skittish figurations of the Intermezzo movement burst out of the
languidly lyrical lines, the four players come together and take
seats on a small platform. But they face not each other, as is
normal, but the audience. So we still experience them as four
individuals struggling to find common ground, and hear the music
that way.
</P>
<P>
   The fifth movement is an oddly tranquil funeral march run
through only sporadically with the dotted-rhythm characteristic of
the genre. It leads to the weirdly shimmering harmonies and
tremulous sustained trills of the Epilogue. The Emerson played with
a bleak emotional honesty that was bearable only because their
mastery of the music assured us that someone was in control here
and we were safe.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM. REVIEW CAN END HERE.)
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the performance, when the stage darkened, the
audience remained utterly silent for a long while, until the house
lights came on and the ovation started. Whatever the strengths and
shortcomings of ``The Noise of Time'' as a multimedia theatrical
piece, it offers a chance to lose yourself in a musical work that
McBurney has aptly called ``a kind of prayer about the 20th
century.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-03-00 1918EST &QL; 
