<SLUG> BC-NEW-AMERICA-DIALLO-CASE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE DIALLO CASE: A QUESTION OF RACE  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE clients.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchse information, see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 By VERNON JARRETT  
 &HT;    My more than 40 years as a journalist cushioned me from the
shock of learning that four black jurors joined eight white jurors
in a not-guilty verdict for the four New York City police officers
who, on Feb. 4, 1999, fired 41 rounds at Amadou Diallo, an unarmed
22-year-old black man from West Africa, striking him 19 times.
 &HT;    Diallo's only crime was standing in the vestibule of his Bronx
home.
 &HT;    Unlike many of my younger friends, I did not predict a hung jury
simply because there were four black women on the panel. I was
prepared for anything, because I've grown to understand a lot about
contradictory ``black responses'' that might confound the best of
America's social critics.
 &HT;    However, I was indeed stunned when, on Feb. 22, I heard two of
the black jurors say in a television interview that race never came
up during the 21 hours of jury deliberations.
 &HT;    How could race have been so consciously ignored? Surely the
frequently debated issue of ``racial profiling'' might have been
introduced at some point.
 &HT;    The verdict makes me question many things:
 &HT;    Would Diallo have been shot down so quickly and mercilessly in
his doorway if he had presented the typical ``boy next door'' image
_ like that of the blond, young, white gentleman who was convicted
of blowing up the federal building in Oklahoma City? Would Diallo
have fared better if he resembled the Columbine High School killers
_ also white _ instead of exposing a dark round face, a broad nose
and a fuzzy mustache over thick lips?
 &HT;    Doesn't Diallo's face resemble the countenance of thousands of
innocent young black men across America who are suspect in the
minds of cops? Henceforth, must they quiver in their doorways every
time a car loaded with plainclothes cops drives by at night with
the power to harass them, possibly kill them and go unpunished?
 &HT;    Since all sides agreed that Diallo was not being sought for any
crime, why didn't the jury find some of his slayers guilty of at
least one of the six charges against them, such as criminally
negligent homicide?
 &HT;    Over the years, I've observed a noteworthy thought pattern among
some African-Americans that may apply here: Some will bend over
backward to prove they are not biased. Others will voluntarily
ignore a sound judgment derived from their own remarkable social
histories. Instead, they elect to view the world through lenses
fashioned by whites.
 &HT;    Initially the defense team tried to remove three of the four
black women from jury consideration because of their race. The four
black jurors successfully proved the defense wrong.
 &HT;    Then there was the Bronx District Attorney, Robert T. Johnson, a
black man who appeared so eager to be fair-minded that he didn't
appoint a single black lawyer to the prosecution team in a case
which arose in a borough that is 77 percent black.
 &HT;    Yet race mattered from the trial's outset: The proceedings were
moved from the Bronx, a largely black neighborhood, to upstate
Albany, which is mostly white. The cautious prosecution team even
declined to refer to racial prejudice as a serious factor in police
conduct.
 &HT;    Finally, Justice Joseph C. Teresi told the jury to walk in the
shoes of the four white cops on the night of the Diallo slaying.
Consequently the question of race became a non sequitur, even
though according to Eliot Spitzer, the state attorney general,
blacks constitute 62.7 percent of people stopped by the NYPD Street
Crime Unit to which the defendants belonged _ a unit that stopped
blacks 23 percent more times than whites.
 &HT;    Oddly enough, the judge did not ask the jurors to place
themselves in Diallo's shoes in those moments before his quick,
unexpected execution.
 &HT;    Let's not forget that Amadou Diallo was the only fatality on
that February night in the Bronx when four cops acted out their
unit's slogan: ``We own the night.''
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    (Vernon Jarrett is an active member of the national advisory
board of the Rosa and Raymond Parks Pathways to Freedom Program for
Youths. In 1991 he received a Lifetime Achievement Award from the
National Association of Black Journalists.)
 &HT;    -----
 c.2000 Vernon Jarrett 
