<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-AMERICA-COMPARATIVE-TRADING-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONEY MANAGEMENT: COMPARATIVE TRADING  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE clients.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 By MARK DAVIS  
 &HT;    A recent federal tally counted 157 online brokers competing for
your business. In this crowded marketplace, don't be too surprised
or impressed if a brokerage claims to be the No. 1 firm. The
Internet is flush with online broker rankings and hardly any two
agree.
 &HT;    According to Gomez Advisors Inc., the best-known judge of online
services, Charles Schwab earns the best overall ranking. But even
Gomez (at www.Gomez.com) hedges its bet. It also issues four other
top rankings that emphasize features such as cost and planning
tools.
 &HT;    When choosing a broker, look for a ranking that emphasizes the
features that matter to you. For example, Gomez Advisors calls
Schwab the best site for a ``One-Stop Shopper.'' But the same site
ranked 10th on the list for a ``Hyper-Active Trader.''
 &HT;    Other sites rank trading sites with different systems, but let's
start with the one factor they all share _ price. Even the most
expensive online brokers charge commissions that are a fraction of
what full-service brokers charge. And if you want any brokerage
firm's lowest commission, including a discount broker's cheapest
turn, you will have to open an account online.
 &HT;    After prices dropped dramatically in the early years of online
brokering, the commissions among the 10 largest online brokers now
hover at just under $16 a trade, according to averages calculated
by Credit Suisse First Boston Corp.
 &HT;    However, that average masks a considerable range. A trade at
Brown &AMP; Co. can cost as little as $5. A similar transaction would
cost $8, $9.99, $12, $14.95, $20, or $29.95 at other sites,
according to a comparison by Fortune magazine.
 &HT;    The real-market cost of a trade gets more complicated than just
a flat price. For starters, the price varies depending on what type
of order you use. That $5 Brown trade, for example, is for a market
order, the simplest type of transaction. Limit orders and other
strategic techniques often cost more.
 &HT;    The most popular sites go beyond handling transactions. They
offer online big payment services, financial planning, market
research, securities analyses and personal-finance software. In
fact, Schwab is currently the biggest online broker in terms of
market share, but at $29.95 per trade, it's also one of the
costliest.
 &HT;    A cheaper choice would be Firstrade Securities Inc., which will
execute the same order as Schwab for only $6.95.
 &HT;    Firstrade scored a perfect 10 in the most recent ``overall
cost'' comparisons by Gomez Advisors.
 &HT;    But focusing so much on price sacrifices the features and
convenience that drive people to trade online in the first place. A
look at the eight most popular online brokers _ Schwab, E*Trade,
 &HT;    Waterhouse Securities, Datek Online, Fidelity Investments,
Ameritrade, DLJ Direct and Discover Brokerage Direct _ shows no
correlation to prices, which start at Ameritrade with $8 per trade.
 &HT;    As a rule, expect no hand-holding at the less-expensive firms.
 &HT;    ``They're extremely nonservice-oriented,'' says Mark Lynch, a
Firstrade customer in Kansas who switched from Schwab over the
price issue. ``You just buy and sell stocks through them.''
 &HT;    The downside of trading online includes system crashes, software
glitches and trying to climb the learning curve while making
big-money trades.
 &HT;    In general, the pricier sites earn credit for being dependable
and having all those brokers to take calls when things break down.
 &HT;    The Securities and Exchange Commission reports that customers
complain most often about not being able to access their accounts.
Also prominent have been complaints that orders were delayed or
were not processed, or that errors occurred in processing them.
 &HT;    Depending on the financial context of your investments, one
botched trade by your brokerage firm could jeopardize any
cost-savings you achieved in low transaction fees.
 &HT;    Regulators found that one of the problems with delays is a
misconception by online customers that they're directly connected
to the stock market. Because most orders are confirmed almost
immediately, they assume it really works that way.
 &HT;    But trading online is fundamentally the same as visiting your
broker's office or calling to place an order on the telephone. The
customer still makes the order, and a licensed broker must execute
it. The distinction is that online brokers let you deliver the
order over the Internet which usually means your order reaches the
floor faster and more efficiently.
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    (Mark Davis is a financial writer for the Kansas City Star.)
 &HT;    -----
 c.2000 Hispanic Business magazine 
<TEXT>
 &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on NEW
AMERICA NEWS SERVICE and other features. &QL;
