<HEADER>
A6068 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-CHECHNYA-REFUGEES-BOS     03-03 0983
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHECHNYA-REFUGEES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHECHEN FAMILIES RETURN UNDER PERIL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SLEPTSOVSKAYA, Russia _ The Russians told them they would be
safe. But then Khabikha Astamirova and her family awoke to find a
large group of separatist fighters occupying her village of
Katyr-Yurt, about 15 miles southwest of Chechnya's capital of
Grozny.
</P>
<P>
   It was Feb. 5. Within a few hours, before Astamirova and other
civilians could leave, Russian planes and tanks began a three-day
bombardment of Katyr-Yurt. When it was over, the Chechen fighters
were gone, most having escaped to the mountains in the south. All
that was left of Katyr-Yurt was a wasteland of smoking ruins and
dead bodies.
</P>
<P>
   Astamirova took her two young children and fled Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, as they sat in a bus headed home, Astamirova
confronted the questions faced by more than 200,000 Chechen
refugees. Is the fighting really over, as the Russian generals say?
And is it safe to return?
</P>
<P>
   The people on Astamirova's bus had little reason to think so.
The death of as many as 37 Russian paramilitary troops in a rebel
ambush in Grozny Thursday has put the lie to the generals'
assurances that the separatists have been swept out of Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   When Russia seized Grozny several weeks ago, the government said
the rebels controlled only a small area in the mountains to the
south. But a rebel commander said Friday that the ambush signals
the beginning of a protracted guerrilla war.
</P>
<P>
   If that is true, Chechen civilians say, they could become the
targets of reprisal by Russian forces, who have vowed to intensify
security sweeps to hunt down rebel fighters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rebels come and go, but it is the peaceful population that
faces reprisals during the sweeps,'' Astamirova said.
</P>
<P>
   Chechnya's ruined villages provide little shelter, no food, no
work, and no amenities. But the refugees are going back because
they have nowhere else to go. Every day, columns of buses head back
from the Russian region of Ingushetia, which took in most of those
who fled the fighting.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no peace in Chechnya, but people in Ingushetia are
tired of refugees,'' Astamirova said. ``They are charging rent, and
we have no money to pay. So we'll go back. One room in our house
was not that badly damaged. We can stay there.''
</P>
<P>
   But many refugees said they were convinced that violence will
return. During the security sweeps over the past two months,
refugees and human rights workers say, Russian troops have
repeatedly gone on looting and killing sprees, leaving dozens,
perhaps hundreds, of civilians dead.
</P>
<P>
   The last time Bela Guchigova was at her wrecked home in
northwest Grozny's Staropromyslovsky District, she says, she saw
the site of a massacre in which her brother, her grandparents, and
dozens of her neighbors were killed.
</P>
<P>
   According to survivors interviewed by human rights groups, about
100 soldiers systematically robbed and shot civilians in the
two-day rampage that began Feb. 5. The troops also raped several
women and hurled grenades into basements where residents were
trying to hide, survivors said.
</P>
<P>
   Guchigova said survivors told her that soldiers had ordered
people into their yards and then rampaged through the ruined
houses, looking for things to take. Anyone who protested was shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their only crime was that they were at home. Some of the
bodies were still lying where they fell,'' Guchigova said. ``The
soldiers wouldn't let the survivors bury them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Russians tell us to go back, but once you are in Chechnya,
you become an enemy,'' said Sultan Dakhayev, the Guchigovas'
neighbor in a tent camp on the Chechen-Ingush border.
</P>
<P>
   None of the Chechens want to go back to Grozny, especially after
Thursday's attack.
</P>
<P>
   The Staropromyslovsky District, where Bela Guchigova lives, is
also where rebels launched their assault on a column of 98 Russian
paramilitary officers who had just arrived to relieve troops that
had captured the city in early February.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels fired rockets at the first and last vehicles in a
convoy of nine heavy trucks, then sprayed the rest with machine-gun
fire and rocket-launched grenades, the survivors told Russian
television. The Interior Ministry at first reported 20 dead, but
later a military spokesman put the death toll at 37.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the beginning of a guerrilla war,'' Baultdin Bakuyev,
a Chechen field commander, told The Associated Press. He said that
his fighters had pulled off the deadly ambush, then escaped into
the mountains.
</P>
<P>
   The attack evoked memories of Russia's failed 1994-1996 campaign
to defeat the separatists. In early 1996, Russian forces had chased
the rebels into the mountains and the generals were declaring
victory. But in August, the rebels mounted a surprise attack and
regained control of Grozny.
</P>
<P>
   Moscow has vowed not to let that happen again.
</P>
<P>
   In response to Thursday's attack, a police spokesman said,
Russian troops rounded up 80 suspects in Grozny. Such actions are
something else the refugees fear.
</P>
<P>
   Roza Dikayeva, who was on a bus bound for Urus-Martan, 12 miles
south of Grozny, said most Chechen women are afraid to take their
husbands and sons back with them. Fighting-age men are routinely
detained during the Russian sweeps. So is anyone with scars, or a
last name similar to that of a rebel leader. Some are taken to
Chernokozovo, a detention camp in northern Chechnya where human
rights groups say inmates are beaten and tortured.
</P>
<P>
   Moscow denies the accusations and accuses Western media of
having an anti-Russian bias; it has begun organizing media trips to
Chernokozovo. But there are other ``filtration camps'' where
suspected rebels are held, and, Chechens say, beaten and tortured.
</P>
<P>
   One of them, Dikayeva said, is in the basement of an orphanage
in Urus-Martan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
