<HEADER>
A6074 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-L.A.-POLICE-PARKS-NYT     03-03 0950
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-L.A.-POLICE-PARKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOUGH BUSINESS AS USUAL FOR CHIEF OF A FORCE IN TURMOIL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ko) 
 By JAMES STERNGOLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ By most accounts, Bernard Parks managed his long
rise as a black officer on the once racially divided Los Angeles
Police Department largely by knowing the minutiae of how the force
worked better than anyone else and by developing a reputation as
intolerant of infractions of the rules. He was a consummate
insider, a man known less for finesse than for overwhelming
problems with mountains of details.
</P>
<P>
   Now that his department is caught in the uncomfortable glare of
a corruption scandal, the vexing question that this intelligent,
ramrod-straight police chief faces is whether those skills as an
inside policy technician, rather than a bridge to the community,
will be his undoing.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he felt like his term had suddenly veered off course,
Parks, who wears a crisply ironed blue uniform on duty, insisted
not. ``Anybody that takes the job of chief of police and doesn't
understand that they may be confronted with challenges like this is
naive,'' Parks said.
</P>
<P>
   Parks, 57, was born in Beaumont, Texas, but when he was still
young his family moved here, and his father became an officer with
the harbor police. Parks drifted into police work in 1965, after
working briefly at a General Motors plant. He quickly made the
force his home and became known for his dedication.
</P>
<P>
   When he became chief in mid-1997, he was the second black to
hold the job, and he inherited a force that had become demoralized
under Chief Willie Williams, a former head of the Philadelphia
police who was often criticized for his relaxed and vague style.
Parks' style was anything but.
</P>
<P>
   He may have irritated some officers with his toughness _ he has
dismissed on average 50 officers a year, compared with fewer than
14 a year in the preceding decade _ and he could be smug in
dismissing outside interference in his department, but his lack of
a congenial public persona was just the thing many people here
seemed to want. He won plaudits for the plummeting crime rates and
a comforting sense that everything was under control.
</P>
<P>
   And then six months ago everything changed _ except, it seems,
Chief Parks.
</P>
<P>
   A rogue officer caught stealing cocaine from an evidence lock-up
disclosed that his inner-city anti-gang unit had for years, and
seemingly with impunity, beaten, framed and, in two instances, shot
innocent people.
</P>
<P>
   Parks has been aggressive in response. He has said at least 99
people were wrongly imprisoned and should be freed, a number
certain to rise. Some 20 officers have faced sanctions, and he
initiated what most agree is the most scorching self-examination in
the department's history. The 362-page report, released Wednesday,
detailed a shocking array of management lapses across a department
that Parks always maintained he knew, and controlled, better than
anybody else.
</P>
<P>
   The largely Hispanic communities that had been brutalized felt
vindicated, after years of having had their complaints ignored. The
mayor has offered unwavering support, but many civic leaders have
demanded more outside scrutiny and less insularity on the part of
the chief.
</P>
<P>
   Parks has responded with energy, insisting that only he knew
enough to get the department back into shape. He has heatedly
rejected the need for an outside investigation. In an often
contentious interview in his utilitarian office, Parks laid most of
the blame at the feet of his predecessor, saying, ``These are the
issues that are coming out from the five years of history when an
outsider was in charge of the department.''
</P>
<P>
   When he released the 362-page internal investigation at a news
conference last week, he said how proud he was of the officers who
prepared the report, but he did not once mention the scores of
victims of the police brutality, none of whom he has met with.
Indeed, he has not visited the neighborhood where the anti-drug
unit worked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to hear your point,'' Parks boomed when a
reporter pressed the question of whether he might show concern for
the victims individually. ``Your point has been covered.'' And he
responded with derision to the suggestion that he should make any
special effort to reach out to the communities that had suffered
from the corruption.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're trying to correct things in the public, you can get
a public relations firm to do that,'' he said. ``If you're trying
to clean up and deal with the operational issues within the
department, you have to have someone who knows what those
operations issues are.''
</P>
<P>
   Parks grew even more pugnacious when he was asked whether he
should resign to take responsibility for the management lapses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue is this, I'm not going to answer that because I have
not been asked to resign,'' he said. ``I am the one who has been in
the forefront of investigating this issue, so I think that's
totally inappropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, the civilian police commission is evaluating Parks'
report, with some of its members having privately expressed concern
about Parks' seeming insularity. The City Council has not mustered
the votes to launch a separate investigation, and the mayor has
expressed pride in his police chief.
</P>
<P>
   Parks, who is married and has four grown children, said his life
had not changed. He never sees movies, he has said, and spends many
evenings reading reports. He said he occasionally went to the
theater and vacationed in Mexico with his wife every 10 weeks or
so. He is operating as he always has.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the way you respond to something like this is the way
you were trained to respond,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
