<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-03 19:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6083 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-GOP-THUMBS0304-1STLED     03-03 1365
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-THUMBS0304-1STLEDE-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Eds: added state's delegate count
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans' Super Tuesday at a Glance
</P>
<P>
   c, 2000 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   California , with it's 162 delegates, and New York, which brings
with it 101 delegates are the two grand prizes on Tuesday, but
there are still 11 other states, worth a total of 350 additional
delegates, at play.
</P>
<P>
   CONNECTICUT
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush was born and went to college in Connecticut (Yale
University is in New Haven), and this state elected his grandfather
to the Senate, but his prospects here didn't look too bright until
recently. A February poll showed him trailing McCain by 13 points,
but a Zogby/Reuters/MSNBC tracking poll released Friday showed the
two in a statistical dead heat.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, Connecticut elected former Sen. Lowell Weicker governor
as an independent, and McCain's maverick campaign appears to be
resonating. Gov. John Rowland, a Republican, has endorsed Bush,
however.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut, the nation's wealthiest state per capita, went for
Bill Clinton over Bob Dole in 1996 by a large margin, 53-35
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The winner of the primary takes all of the state's 25 delegates.
</P>
<P>
   GEORGIA
</P>
<P>
   Bush hasn't yet lost a Southern state primary and he isn't
likely to lose this one: In a survey conducted Feb. 28 and 29, he
held a commanding lead, 62-23 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Many voters here are social conservatives, giving Bush a big
advantage. But the primary is open and, as in South Carolina, the
delegates are allocated by congressional district, so McCain can
win some delegates in more moderate urban districts.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia hasn't elected a Republican governor since
Reconstruction (it's the only state that hasn't elected a GOP
governor this century), but the Democrats' strength has been ebbing
over the past 20 years. Georgia voters chose Dole over Clinton in
1996, 47-46 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Some 54 delegates are at stake.
</P>
<P>
   MAINE
</P>
<P>
   The Bush family has a summer home in Kennebunkport, but Maine,
like the rest of New England, may be McCain country.
</P>
<P>
   There hasn't been a poll taken recently, but there are few
social conservatives in the state and voters here have shown an
independent streak: Ross Perot beat Bush's father here in 1992, and
the state elected an independent as governor in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Maine's primary is closed, although independents can register as
Republicans at the polls so long as they don't change their
affiliation again for three months.
</P>
<P>
   A total of 14 delegates will be awarded proportionally, but if
the victor gets a majority, it's winner take all.
</P>
<P>
   MARYLAND
</P>
<P>
   Maryland might seem to be a winnable state for McCain because
most of its Republicans are moderate and independents can vote in
its open primary. Furthermore, the Naval Academy, McCain's alma
mater, is here and Maryland has plenty of residents with Navy ties.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the most recent polls show Bush in the lead. Two
surveys released on Wednesday showed Bush leading McCain 47-40
percent and 47-37 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Maryland is politically diverse: Its eight House seats are
divided equally between the parties. The state gave Clinton his
third-highest percentage in 1992 and fifth-best in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The state's 31 delegates will be allocated by congressional
district.
</P>
<P>
   MASSACHUSETTS
</P>
<P>
   This New England state may deal Bush a New Hampshire-like
primary blow. A University of Massachusetts tracking poll shows
McCain leading Bush 66-21 percent. A Zogby/Reuters/MSNBC tracking
poll shows McCain with a 30-point lead.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts is a heavily Catholic, predominantly white
Democratic stronghold. Both senators and, since 1996, all its
representatives, are Democrats. Political life in the Bay State
remains dominated by the Kennedy family legacy. Sen. Edward Kennedy
has represented the state since 1962.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts voters went for Clinton in 1996 and in 1992. That
year, Clinton beat Bush's father here, 47-29 percent. In 1988, the
elder Bush lost to former Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis, but
by a much slimmer margin, 53-45 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The state offers up 37 delegates, winner take all, in GOP
primaries that are closed to Democrats but open to independents.
</P>
<P>
   MINNESOTA
</P>
<P>
   Talk about an independent streak: Minnesotans shocked the nation
in 1998 when they elected ex-pro wrestler and Reform Party
candidate Jesse Ventura governor.
</P>
<P>
   While surprising, the state's wasn't exactly out of character:
Minnesota Republicans renamed themselves ``Independent
Republicans'' after Watergate, while Minnesota Democrats call
themselves the ``Democrat Farmer Labor'' party.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota produced the nation's first anti-smoking bill, one of
the first public campaign financing plans and the nation's first
statewide educational choice plan.
</P>
<P>
   There haven't been any recent polls here, where 34 delegates
will be in play at nonbinding straw votes.
</P>
<P>
   MISSOURI
</P>
<P>
   Missouri is a presidential bellwether state, having voted for
the winning president in every election in the past except in 1900
and 1956.
</P>
<P>
   The primary here will be open, but McCain could lose a few votes
to Bill Bradley, who was born and raised here. Many of the state's
swing voters are Catholic Democrats, however, so Bush's Bob Jones
University speech could be problematic for him.
</P>
<P>
   A poll released Wednesday showed Bush with a commanding 12-point
lead over McCain. Two-thirds of Republicans support Bush, while
McCain beats the Texas governor among independents, 57-26 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The winner will take all 35 delegates.
</P>
<P>
   OHIO
</P>
<P>
   No Republican has ever been elected president without winning
Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   The Buckeye State looks a lot like America: close to the
national average in income, urban-rura split and racial and ethnic
composition.
</P>
<P>
   In this open primary, Reagan Democrats in Cleveland may help
McCain, while Bush may get a boost from social conservatives near
Cincinnati. With the exception of Sen. Mike DeWine, the state's
elected Republicans are backing Bush.
</P>
<P>
   A poll taken Feb. 23-27 showed Bush leading 53-36 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton won Ohio in 1996 and 1992, but by narrow margins. Only
twice in the past 100 years _ in 1944 and 1960 _ has Ohio not
picked the winning presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Some 69 delegates will be awarded, winner take all by
congressional district.
</P>
<P>
   RHODE ISLAND
</P>
<P>
   Rhode Island has a Republican governor, a Republican senator and
a Democratic senator. The most heavily Catholic state in the nation
is overwhelmingly Democratic when it comes to presidential
politics.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's father lost there to Clinton in 1992, 47-29 percent, and
to Dukakis in 1988, 56-44 percent. The state went for Ronald Reagan
over Walter Mondale in 1984, 52-48 percent.
</P>
<P>
   This GOP primary, worth 14 delegates winner take all, is closed
to Democrats, but independents may cast ballots.
</P>
<P>
   VERMONT
</P>
<P>
   Tiny Vermont is just shy of 100 percent white, but it is a mixed
bag politically.
</P>
<P>
   The state voted Democratic for president in 1992 for the first
time since 1964. The state also is represented in the House by
Bernard Sanders, Congress' first socialist representative since
1928.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton won here in 1996 and in 1992. Bush's dad won here in
1988 and Reagan in 1984 and 1980.
</P>
<P>
   Vermont is the only New England state with open primaries, which
means Democrats can vote in Tuesday's GOP contest. The winner will
get 12 delegates.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   In a surprise primary result last week, Bush won in this
historically Democratic state by a whopping 58-38 percent. Bush
later said his victory here would prove to be a turning point in
the GOP nomination race this year.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not over yet. In a complicated system of doling out its
37 GOP delegates, Washington held a primary last week worth 12
delegates _ Bush got 7, McCain 4 and Alan Keyes 1. The remaining 25
delegates will be awarded in caucuses on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Based on his overwhelming victory last week, Bush should be a
shoe-in.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
