<HEADER>
A6116 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-SCI-BALLOON-NYT &LR;      03-03 0470
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-BALLOON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN BALLOONIST'S SOLO ATTEMPT TO CIRCLE THE WORLD ENDS IN
ASIA  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ill., Switzerland, England, Myanmar)   By HENRY FOUNTAIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   An American balloonist's solo attempt to circle the world ended
well short of that goal Friday when he landed safely in Southeast
Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Uliassi, who had lifted off from a quarry in Rockford,
Ill., 10 days before, brought the balloon down in central Myanmar,
formerly Burma, about 300 miles north of the capital, Yangon,
formerly Rangoon. He had traveled 13,325 miles, more than halfway
around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Uliassi's wife, Renee, said in a telephone interview from the
mission's command center in Homewood, Ill., that data transmissions
from the balloon indicated her husband had made a controlled
descent from about 30,000 feet. He suffered some bruises during the
landing and had been taken to a hospital, where he was expected to
spend the night.
</P>
<P>
   Uliassi left a message on a family answering machine to report
that he was safe, but his support team had not heard directly from
him. ``We have no idea why he came down,'' she said. Mrs. Uliassi
said they last talked to him at about 3:30 p.m. Central time on
Thursday, about 13 hours before the landing. At that time he
reported no problems and said he was going to sleep.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Uliassi said that by coincidence a British balloonist and
his team were in Myanmar and had offered to help her husband pack
up the balloon for shipment home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not disappointed whatsoever,'' Mrs. Uliassi said. ``For
Kevin and I it was a success just to put a balloon together.''
</P>
<P>
   After a relatively slow start across the Atlantic, the
160-foot-high balloon, named the J. Renee in honor of Mrs. Uliassi,
had caught favorable winds in the middle of the week and had
traveled at more than 100 miles an hour as it crossed India on
Thursday. Uliassi had been due to have a discussion with his
support team on Friday about whether he had enough fuel and oxygen
to proceed over the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   Uliassi, 36, was attempting to become the third person to fly a
balloon nonstop around the world, and the first to do it alone. Two
Europeans accomplished the feat in a similar balloon last year.
Uliassi's trip did not even set a record for solo balloon travel;
that mark, of more than 14,000 miles, was established by Steve
Fossett, a wealthy Chicago businessman, in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   This was Uliassi's second attempt at an around-the-world trip,
and was far more successful than the first, which ended shortly
after launching when the balloon ruptured. Like that mission, this
one was run on a shoestring, with an all-volunteer support crew and
no deep-pocket backers. ``He's basically flying all his assets,'' a
spokesman, Scott Lorenz, had said on Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-03-00 1950EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
