<DOCNO> NYT20000303.0253 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-03 19:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6126 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-BIZ-PROFILE-SYRON-$AD     03-03 0976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-PROFILE-SYRON-$ADV05-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MR. FIX-IT REWIRES A COMPANY  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 5) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mass.)   (af)  
 By CLAUDIA H. DEUTSCH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ever since he was a child, Dick Syron has been a tinkerer. As a
teenager, he fixed TV sets and cars for spare cash. As an adult, he
rewired a 134-year-old house. And he loves working on his 28-foot
Bertram motorboat almost as much as he loves powering it through
the waves.
</P>
<P>
   And now, at 56, Richard F. Syron is facing what may be his
biggest tinkering job yet. As the chief executive of the Thermo
Electron Corp. _ a post he has held for just nine months _ he is
revamping the diverse manufacturing company top to bottom.
</P>
<P>
   Once he is done, Thermo Electron will no longer be a
multitentacled company with dozens of publicly traded subsidiaries.
It will be a mainstream manufacturer with one set of shares.
</P>
<P>
   ``People's willingness to buy small, thin-float stocks that
don't have dot-com on them is pretty low,'' Syron said. ``We're
better off as a conventional company.''
</P>
<P>
   The revamping is well under way. The company, based in Waltham,
Mass., announced on Jan. 31 that it would sell businesses that had
provided one-third of its $4.2 billion in revenues. It is spinning
off to shareholders two other businesses: biomedical devices and
paper manufacturing equipment. And it plans to buy back the public
shares of those companies that will form a business making
analytical instruments.
</P>
<P>
   Such a transformation is a tall task for someone who had never
before run a public company. Sure, Syron had been on Thermo
Electron's board for nearly two years, and yes, he had known George
Hatsopoulos, the company's founder and former chairman, for
decades.
</P>
<P>
   He has done some big-time quasicorporate tinkering, as well: as
president of the Boston Federal Reserve in the early 1990s, he
helped keep many New England banks solvent as others across the
country went under. In his most recent job, as president of the
American Stock Exchange, he was an architect of its merger with
Nasdaq's parent, the National Association of Securities Dealers.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts wondered about Syron's qualifications to run Thermo
Electron. ``When he was first named, I did have to scratch my head
a bit,'' said Deane Dray of Goldman Sachs, who nonetheless has high
hopes for Syron's reign.
</P>
<P>
   Syron acknowledges Wall Street's doubts, but says they are
misplaced. ``Organizational restructuring is not rocket science,''
he said. ``It's common sense.''
</P>
<P>
   To hear Syron's friends and former colleagues tell it, he has
that in abundance. ``Dick is extremely bright, pragmatic and
energetic _ emphasis on that middle word,'' said E. Gerald
Corrigan, a Goldman Sachs partner who worked with Syron at the
Federal Reserve. ``He isn't caught up in theology; he's a doer.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas F. Ryan, Syron's predecessor at the stock exchange, cited
a case in point. ``He knew enough not to involve the members in the
merger decision until it was time to vote,'' Ryan said, ``and then
he knew how to persuade everyone that this merger was right.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, why would Dick Syron take on Thermo Electron? He took a
50 percent pay cut when he left the Amex, he says. And for now, his
million stock options, priced at $19.10, do not represent any
bonanza. Thermo's stock closed at $21.9375 on Friday _ well above
its low of $12.50 on April 9, 1999, but nowhere near its high of
$44.50 on Dec. 31, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stock has to go up substantially for this to be a good
financial move,'' Syron said. ``Anyone who says it is cheaper to
live in Boston than New York hasn't lived in Boston lately.''
</P>
<P>
   So again, why? ``I like to fix things,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Syron grew up in Watertown, Mass., the child of Irish immigrants
_ his father was a blacksmith, his mother a domestic worker. They
lived in a three-family house, with relatives in the other
apartments and other relatives a few blocks away.
</P>
<P>
   Many of them loved to work with their hands, and Syron picked up
the knack. ``In our environment you didn't call a plumber; you
borrowed your uncle's wrench,'' he said. Uncles and cousins taught
him how to fix automobiles, and he learned to repair televisions at
an after-school job.
</P>
<P>
   He seemed destined to be an electrical engineer. But in college
in the late '60s, he discovered he had a learning disability that
made mechanical drawing impossible. He also met his future wife,
Peggy. They have been married for 28 years, and have a daughter,
Erin, 20, and a son, Brendan, 15.
</P>
<P>
   As an economics major at Boston College (he has advanced degrees
in economics from Tufts), Syron worked summers painting houses in
poor sections of Boston. At the Boston Fed, he tried to ensure that
people in poor neighborhoods were not unfairly denied mortgages.
</P>
<P>
   Donald L. Isaacs, a retired banker and his best friend, recalls
that Syron, an avid boater, has eschewed fancy sailing clubs,
instead joining the more blue-collar South Boston Yacht Club.
``Dick judges people by characteristics and qualities, not
titles,'' Isaacs said.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, that is how Thermo Electron's board chose him, too.
Investors had soured on the company's strategy of constantly
spinning out public companies. In September, Hatsopoulos' brother
John, his intended successor, announced that he would resign. The
board, wanting someone familiar with the company, chose Syron.
George Hatsopoulos resigned as chairman in January, giving Syron
that title as well.
</P>
<P>
   Syron expects that it will be more than a year before the sales
are completed, the spinoffs done and the company operating as a
manufacturer. When everything is fixed, will he leave?
</P>
<P>
   Probably _ but then again, maybe not. ``There are many other
things I want to do,'' he said. ``But you can't make decisions
about what you'll do three years down the road.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
