<HEADLINE>
CLINTON CALLS FOR GREATER PRIVACY AND SECURITY IN CYBERSPACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MARC LACEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. _ President Clinton said Friday that he
considers cyberspace too insecure for him to correspond privately
by e-mail with his daughter, Chelsea, who is away at college. In a
speech to high-tech executives here in the heart of the Silicon
Valley, Clinton called on the industry to enhance computer privacy
to reassure many people like himself who are still wary of the new
technology.
</P>
<P>
   And the president issued a memorandum Friday to the heads of
federal departments, urging them to increase the safeguards of
federal computers against intrusions like the recent spate of
attacks that overloaded and shut down major Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Privacy rights in cyberspace received renewed attention this
week with the decision by DoubleClick Inc., the nation's largest
online advertising company, to back off from a plan to compile
personal profiles of people who surf the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   During a technology forum at the offices of Novell Inc., a
software company, Clinton said he believed the federal government
ought to get involved in protecting the privacy of financial
information and medical records on the Internet. But the president
called on the industry to police itself in other areas. Already,
Clinton said, 66 percent of the commercial Web sites have privacy
standards, up from 15 percent just a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know we have to keep cyberspace open and free because it
sparks creativity and innovation, because its infinite networks can
do so much to bring us together,'' Clinton said. ``But we also know
that cyberspace must be a community of shared responsibilities and
common values.''
</P>
<P>
   At the forum, organized by the Aspen Institute, Clinton told the
high-tech executives that computer users deserved notice about what
personal information was being collected and how it would be used,
and should be be able to choose whether the data would be shared
with third parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, ordinary folks, even people who aren't online yet,
are very excited about the prospects of this age so many of you
have done so much to create,'' Clinton told the executives,
including the heads of such Silicon Valley powerhouses as Yahoo,
Cisco Systems and Siebel Systems. ``But they are really concerned
about this. They are afraid they will have no place to hide.''
</P>
<P>
   After his speech, Clinton said in a brief interview that he was
one of those people wary about sending information through
cyberspace. ``I won't send e-mail to Chelsea because I don't think
it's secure,'' Clinton said. The president added that once he
leaves office next year and becomes a ``Joe Sixpack'' he will
probably not be as concerned about his electronic communications.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Clinton admits that he is a newcomer when it comes to the
Internet. Just last week, during a fund-raising visit to Florida,
he marveled at something as mundane as a screen saver.
</P>
<P>
   Before Christmas last year, Clinton ordered some gifts over the
Internet, an experience he still talks about in speech after
speech. ``Yesterday, we got a new benchmark for the new economy
when the Department of Commerce released its first ever quarterly
report on e-commerce,'' Clinton said Friday, ``telling us the
Internet sales from the fourth quarter of last year, the holiday
season, were $5.3 billion _ about $65 of those attributable to the
president.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's anxiety over e-mail clearly will not stop him from
communicating with his daughter. He said they spoke on the phone,
and in between a string of fund-raisers in San Francisco and Los
Angeles on Friday night and Saturday that will raise $1.6 million
for the Democrats, Clinton plans to spend time, face-to-face, with
Chelsea in Palo Alto.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
