<HEADLINE>
ORGANIZATION EFFORT FAILS AT DELTA AIR LINES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Management at Delta Air Lines, the least unionized major
carrier, won a key victory Friday with the overwhelming rejection
of organizing efforts of its ramp workers and baggage handlers.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta-based airline has a labor cost advantage over its
top competitors because only its pilots, dispatchers, and flight
instructors are unionized.
</P>
<P>
   The organizing effort by the Transport Workers Union was soundly
defeated by the airline's 10,800 ramp workers who had to return a
ballot to vote for unionization. Only 1,868 ballots, or 17 percent
of those eligible, were returned. At least 50 percent of the
ballots needed to be returned for the election to pass.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street reacted favorably, with the stock jumping 3 1/8 to
close at 46 15/16.
</P>
<P>
   The vote also is an endorsement of Maynard-native Leo Mullin,
Delta's first chief executive from outside the company. The former
banking executive was brought in to reestablish customer service
and improve employee morale.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, the airline had very good relations with its
employees and in the early 1980s the workers bought the airline a
Boeing 767 with voluntary pay deductions. But morale was shattered
by an aggressive cost-cutting program instituted in the early 1990s
by the previous management team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a strong endorsement of Leo Mullin and the new
management team,'' said Candace Browning, an airline analyst with
Merrill Lynch Global Securities. ``Many people thought the covenant
was broken. Leo has worked very hard to reestablish that covenant,
and this vote is a sign that he has done that. I think this is
great for management.''
</P>
<P>
   Browning said that many people expected the union organizing
effort to work.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the Transport Workers Union were shocked by the
result.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't understand what went wrong,'' organizer Steve Roberts
told Reuters.
</P>
<P>
   The poll was the first major union vote at the airline in many
years, although other organizing efforts are under way with
mechanics and flight attendants.
</P>
<P>
   Mullin has made defeating those a priority and earlier this year
gave 3 percent raises to every domestic nonunion worker at the
company, which employs about 72,000 worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   The raises were the most recent in recent months and last month
the company said it would give every worker a personal computer at
reduced cost.
</P>
<P>
   Delta officials would not predict what the ramp workers vote
might mean for ongoing orgnization efforts of mechanics and flight
attendants.
</P>
<P>
   ``Delta employees made a signifigant positve choice for their
future and Delta's future,'' said spokeswoman Cindi Kurczewski.
``We plan to work hard to keep the trust they placed in the company
with this vote.''
</P>
<P>
   She said the vote ``removes a bit of a distraction'' and permits
the airline to refocus on customer service.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-03-00 2003EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
