<HEADER>
A6150 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-R-NOISE-THEATER-REVIE     03-03 0927
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-NOISE-THEATER-REVIEW-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`NOISE OF TIME': FEAR IN THE COSMIC NIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (REPEATING to add photo note)  (ART ADV:  Photo  is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(Eds: Production notes appear at end of review.) 
(See also NOISE-MUSIC-REVIEW) 
(DW) 
 By BEN BRANTLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The music seems plucked from the darkness, as if strings had
been turned into shadows. There are eight men onstage at that
point, the four members of the Emerson String Quartet and another
foursome, long-limbed figures in suits, as anonymous as the neatly
dressed men in Magritte paintings.
</P>
<P>
   The light is such that you can't always distinguish between the
performers and the onstage listeners, who have come to seem like
nonthreatening dopplegangers of the musicians, and it's as if that
collaboration _ which by extension embraces the audience _ were
necessary to produce the exquisitely sad sounds of Shostakovich's
String Quartet No. 15 in E flat minor.
</P>
<P>
   The pools and glints of light, reflected off faces and the
burnished surfaces of violins and cellos, are sustained, you have
the feeling, by the notes themselves. Yet when the stage again goes
as dark as a starless night and the music has stopped the melody
has by no means ended in your mind.
</P>
<P>
   Darkness is the earth and oxygen of ``The Noise of Time,'' the
exquisitely realized elegy of a performance piece created by the
Theatre de Complicite.
</P>
<P>
   As directed by Simon McBurney, this remarkable contemplation of
the life of the great, famously troubled Russian composer Dmitri
Shostakovich (1906-75) presents darkness as an element that while
all-consuming is by no means sterile.
</P>
<P>
   Extraordinary things emerge from the cosmic night that has been
so expertly conjured by McBurney and his technical team for this
production, which was commissioned by the Lincoln Center Great
Performers series. The evening is divided into halves: an abstract
multimedia preface, which limns the life and times of Shostakovich
in strewn mosaic fragments, and the performance of the final
quartet, thought to be the composer's personal requiem.
</P>
<P>
   Projected images compose themselves slowly, as if brought into
focus by memory itself, onto screens that are pieces of clothing,
the disembodied front of a cello, the entire back wall of the
stage. The images, which sometimes dissolve into nothingness and
sometimes into other things, include a strangely heartbreaking
silhouette of a lanky grown man and a small child, an immense X-ray
of 10 fingers and, again and again, photographs of Shostakovich at
different ages, often with his hand partly blocking his face.
</P>
<P>
   Forging a connection between the tellingly camera-shy composer
and the haunting string quartet _ composed in the year before he
died _ that reads as his own epitaph is what ``The Noise of Time''
seeks to achieve. Well, among other things. The ambition of this
piece, which lasts a mere 90 minutes but seems infinitely longer
and shorter than that, is hubristic.
</P>
<P>
   As conceived by Simon McBurney, with the collaboration of his
brother, the composer Gerard McBurney, ``Noise'' aspires to create
not just a biographical frame for a piece of music. There is also
the implicit goal of setting that life in the context, both moral
and technological, of the century in which that life occurred.
Beyond that, ``Noise'' boldly considers the essential nature of
music and the ways in which we experience it.
</P>
<P>
   It all sounds a bit schoolteacherish in the description, a sort
of adult equivalent to Young People's Concerts, with their
visualization exercises and careful explanatory metaphors. But
anyone who saw the Theatre de Complicite's brilliant production of
``Street of Crocodiles,'' adapted from the densely poetic stories
of Bruno Schulz, knows with what seamlessness this troupe can find
theatrical equivalents for seemingly nontheatrical material.
</P>
<P>
   ``Noise'' builds a beautiful and enlightening bridge into one
artist's sensibility. But it never mistakes the bridge for what it
is leading us to. The production respectfully and wisely lets the
music itself, so magnificently performed by the Emerson group, have
the last word. Its ultimate and most valuable achievement is that
it has successfully asked us to hear that music with newly attuned
ears.
</P>
<P>
   The evening begins with a single old-fashioned radio spotlighted
on a chair, an image that segues into a parade of illuminated
radios, floating through the darkness. There's an aural background
of static and shards of speech and music. (The highly sophisticated
sound design is by Christopher Shutt and Gareth Fry.) The sounds
coalesce into a variety of more comprehensible patterns.
</P>
<P>
   One hears a snatch of music for dancing the Charleston; a
newscast from World War II; technical explanations of how sound is
transmitted by radio. A BBC-style voice emerges to say
didactically, ``Tonight we pose the question: what happens when we
listen to music?''
</P>
<P>
   There are bits of accounts of Yuri Gagarin's pioneer flight into
space and of the legendary premiere of Shostakovich's Symphony No.
7 during the siege of Leningrad, performed by a skeletal,
starvation-devastated orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   There are also reminiscences of Shostakovich, often spoken in
English against blurs of monologues in Russian, ranging from tales
of his precocious boyhood to a wry and somber description of the
composer waiting on the telephone to be connected to Josef Stalin.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Shostakovich's relationship with the Stalin regime is famously
complicated, still a subject of debate as to the degree of the
composer's artistic and moral compromises. The sound of taped
applause that erupts again and again throughout the evening's first
half accordingly seems as sour as it is sweet.
</P>
<P>
   Visually, too, the production unfolds in snippets, giving off a
sense of a whole decomposing into pieces and then recomposing
again. The show's four nonmusical performers (Antonio Gil Martinez,
Richard Katz, Tim McMullan and Toby Sedgwick) manipulate bodiless
shoes and items of clothing into the semblance of walking phantoms,
waiting to be given corporeal form.
</P>
<P>
   Accounts of Shostakovich skiing with his young son (the composer
was terrified of the sport and wanted his son to know no fear) are
echoed by the actors being blown together and apart, as if by angry
winds. A cello falls apart and then reconstitutes itself.
</P>
<P>
   This sense of fragmentation and recomposition _ given artfully
immaterial-seeming physical life by Joanna Parker (design), Paul
Anderson (lighting) and Jan Hartley (projections) as well as the
actors _ is the shaping rhythm of the evening. It prepares us for
the consummate act of self-dissection and reconfiguration that is
the liturgical 15th quartet.
</P>
<P>
   As haunting as McBurney's preface to this piece of music is it
is the staging of the performance of the quartet that is the
production's real epiphany. The movements of the remarkable
musicians _ Philip Setzer, Eugene Drucker, Lawrence Dutton, David
Finckel _ and their shadows, the four actors, have been
choreographed with stately precision in ways that seem both
surprising and inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   The manner in which the quartet members seem to toss, quite
literally, individual notes among themselves is astonishing. And
you never, ever feel that the music is being imposed upon with
metaphorical conceits. Its own images are not polluted by
extraneous ones, in the ways that everything from Mozart's 21st
piano concerto (remember ``Elvira Madigan''?) to Tchaikovsky's
``1812'' Overture (that appalling puffed rice commercial) have
been.
</P>
<P>
   The entire evening takes place before a wall of sheets of music,
which at moments are perilously stirred by currents of air. Against
this wall, a series of increasingly less identifiable images are
projected, morphing without your even being aware of it. By the
evening end's that wall has turned to dull silver: it suggests both
the face of a memorial monument and an uncontainable space,
glistening with possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `THE NOISE OF TIME' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Conceived and directed by Simon McBurney; creative collaborator,
Gerard McBurney. Dmitri Shostakovich's Quartet No. 15 in E flat
minor performed by the Emerson String Quartet. Created by Theatre
de Complicite with Charlotte Medcalf and Jan Knightley. Sets by
Joanna Parker; lighting by Paul Anderson; projections, Jan Hartley;
sound by Christopher Shutt with Gareth Fry; costumes by Christina
Cunningham; production coordinator, Anita Ashwick; production
manager, Nick Schwarz-Hall; research, Hannah Whitley; assistant
director, Steven Canny; technical stage manager, Martin Riley.
Lincoln Center presents Great Performers New Visions. A Theatre de
Complicite production, in association with the Emerson String
Quartet. At the John Jay College Theater in Manhattan.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With: Antonio Gil Martinez, Richard Katz, Tim McMullan and Toby
Sedgwich. Emerson String Quartet: Philip Setzer, violinist; Eugene
Drucker, violinist; Lawrence Dutton, violist; and David Finckel,
cellist.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
