<HEADLINE>
ECONOMISTS CITE WEATHER IN SLOWER FEBRUARY JOB GROWTH 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By LOUIS UCHITELLE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Job growth suddenly weakened in February, the Labor Department
reported Friday, but almost nothing in the unexpectedly sharp
decline suggested a softening of the economy itself.
</P>
<P>
   Employment grew by 43,000 jobs, way off the recent pace of
250,000 or more a month, and the unemployment rate edged up to 4.1
percent from 4 percent. But the February performance was mostly a
result of abnormal weather, economists said. An unusually warm
January caused a surge in outdoor jobs, especially in construction,
and those jobs disappeared in the colder February weather.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of the more remarkably irrelevant job reports that
we have seen for some time,'' said William Dudley, chief U.S.
economist for Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co. ``There are plenty of indicators
that show the economy is still really quite strong.''
</P>
<P>
   Stock market investors, however, took a different tack. They
seemed to see in the weak employment report a sign that the Federal
Reserve will not have to raise interest rates that much after all
because the economy is beginning to slow on its own. So they bought
stocks with abandon, driving up the Dow Jones industrial average by
202.28 points, or 1.99 percent, to 10,367.2. The Nasdaq, where most
Internet stocks are traded, jumped even more, to another record.
</P>
<P>
   That bullishness may turn out to be self-destructive. The
Federal Reserve seeks to slow the booming economy to avert
inflationary shortages of goods and services. But the Fed also
seeks to slow the stock market, on the ground that the growing
market wealth encourages people to spend freely, and thus
contributes to the inflationary shortages.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Greenspan, the chairman of the Fed, made these points in
congressional testimony last week. He warned, in effect, that the
Fed will raise interest rates in coming months partly to cool the
stock market. Stock prices plunged in the aftermath of his remarks,
but they have been recovering all this week and the February
employment report only fed the bounceback _ almost in defiance of
Greenspan's warnings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market could compel the Fed to raise interest rates even
more than it had planned,'' said Richard D. Rippe, chief economist
at Prudential Securities.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration stressed the economy's strength.
Alexis Herman, the labor secretary, noted that while February's job
growth was the lowest number since last May, when only 28,000 new
jobs were created, the performance is much better when viewed over
a longer period. The surge in January created 384,000 new jobs, so
the monthly average for January and February was 214,000, she
noted, and that was not much below the 1999 average of 226,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there is anything in this report that shows the
economy is weakening,'' Herman said.
</P>
<P>
   The wage measure included in the employment report also showed
no sign of rising. Average hourly earnings for production workers _
one measure of whether a tight labor market is forcing employers to
raise wages _ went up only 6 cents, or 0.3 of a percent, leaving
this measure of wage growth hovering, as it has for months, at a
mild annual rate of 3.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   What stood out in this report were construction workers. In the
mild January weather, this industry added 116,000, jobs but in
February employment fell by 26,000 _ a huge downward shift.
</P>
<P>
   A fall in service sector jobs, however, was harder for
economists to explain. The overall rise was only 62,000 jobs _ way
below the monthly norm of 200,000 or so, and the lowest increase
since August 1997. The biggest falloff was in the service category
that includes office work, computer processing, ski resorts,
amusement and recreation, health care and temporary help agencies.
Here the job growth was only 6,000, the smallest increase since
April 1991, at the end of the last recession.
</P>
<P>
   ``This may suggest that we have had some softening in consumer
spending on services in February relative to the very strong
showing in January,'' said Kenneth J. Matheny, senior economist at
Macroeconomic Advisers, a forecasting and data gathering firm in
St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the falloff was also weather related: Outdoor work in
restaurants, and amusement centers fell, for example. But so did
jobs in transportation, particularly trucking, where rising fuel
prices appear to be taking a toll. And rising mortgage rates appear
to have reduced employment in that industry, said Thomas Nardone,
chief of the division that prepares the employment reports at the
Bureau of Labor Statistics.
</P>
<P>
   Manufacturing jobs, on the other hand, are beginning to revive,
rising by 5,000 last month and by 31,000 since October after having
fallen by 527,000 over the previous 18 months. Overtime in
manufacturing also edged up. And with energy prices rising, a more
profitable oil and gas industry added 9,000 jobs last month.
</P>
<P>
   The small February gain, while pushing the nation's total
employment to 131.33 million, produced very little change in the
unemployment rate for men, women, blacks and Hispanics. Tee-nage
unemployment rose to 14.1 percent from 12.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   For the labor force as a whole, however, the pool of people who
might be drawn into seeking and taking jobs seemed smaller than
ever.
</P>
<P>
   The work force as a percentage of the total population is now a
record 64.8 percent, the level reached in January from 64.4 percent
in December. The labor force participation rate _ all those
employed plus the unemployed actively seeking jobs _ rose to a
record 67.6 percent of the population from 67.5 percent in January.
</P>
<P>
   The average time that unemployed workers go without landing a
job has fallen to 12.5 weeks from 13.8 over the last year, the
lowest level since the last recession. And the unemployment rate
among people with less than a high school education is now only 6
percent, the lowest level since the Bureau of Labor Statistics
began tracking this group in 1992.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
