<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-645&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHECHEN REBELS AMBUSH CONVOY OF ELITE RUSSIAN TROOPS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ In a daring assault deep inside territory that the
Russians thought they controlled, Chechen rebels ambushed a Russian
convoy near Grozny on Thursday, killing 20 police officers and
wounding 29.
</P>
<P>
   According to reports reaching here Friday, the rebels blasted
the first and last truck of the nine-truck convoy and engaged the
stranded soldiers in a four-hour firefight before melting into the
mist.
</P>
<P>
   The daylight attack was also a challenge to Acting President
Vladimir Putin, whose popularity stems in part from his decision to
mount a military campaign to subdue the breakaway republic.
</P>
<P>
   With the presidential election scheduled for March 26, Putin
still appears to be unbeatable. But the extensive coverage of the
bloody ambush on television news, which first reported the extent
of Russian losses, was highly likely to sharpen the debate over the
five-month-old war.
</P>
<P>
   On a visit to Siberia, Putin described the ambush as a tragedy
but insisted that laxity on the part of Russian commanders, and not
Kremlin policies, was to blame.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no room for carelessness,'' Putin said. ``Here we
have to talk about the competence of those people who organized the
movements of servicemen in Chechnya.''
</P>
<P>
   But Grigory Yavlinsky, the leader of the liberal Yabloko party
and a presidential candidate, argued that the Kremlin had led the
nation into a military quagmire and called for a negotiated
settlement. ``The main danger today is a guerrilla war and a wave
of terrorism that could flow out of the North Caucasus to engulf
the whole country,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The incident began when a detachment of 98 policemen from the
OMON elite militia units set off in nine military trucks from the
Russian military town of Mozdok and headed along a fog-bound road
for Grozny, the devastated Chechen capital that was taken by
Russian forces last month.
</P>
<P>
   The OMON, a Russian version of SWAT teams, are generally used
for riot control and major law enforcement operations. The Chechnya
detachment was assembled from units in the Moscow region.
</P>
<P>
   The militia's mission was to relieve a police unit in the
Staropromyslovsky district of the Chechen capital. The convoy was
not accompanied by armored personnel carriers, which had been
standard practice during most of the war.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, rebels opened fire with grenades on the first and last
trucks in the convoy. Twelve policemen were killed by the initial
volley, which froze the convoy in place.
</P>
<P>
   Mines placed prevented Russian troops from advancing toward the
rebels' firing positions. By the time Russian reinforcements
arrived 20 minutes into the battle, the convoy had been badly
mauled.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most serious losses occurred during the first two to four
minutes minutes when the servicemen were in the trucks and
unprepared for combat,'' said Gen. Ivan Golubev, the deputy Russian
interior minister who is leading a government investigation into
the incident.
</P>
<P>
   After a four-hour firefight the rebels fled. Russian officials
said that up to 50 rebels were involved in the attack and that they
may have come from nearby villages or been hiding among the
civilian population.
</P>
<P>
   ``This action was well prepared and skillfully designed,'' said
Golubev. ``We don't exclude the possibility that the rebels knew
about the movement of this convoy.''
</P>
<P>
   Igor Luchikhin, the deputy commander of the OMON unit from
Sergiyev Posad, a town near Moscow, said that negligence on the
part of Russian forces, not espionage, was to blame.
</P>
<P>
   ``I doubt it was betrayal,'' he said. ``I think it was our
carelessness and lack of order.''
</P>
<P>
   The assault pushed the already considerable Russian toll even
higher. Russians officials said Friday that 1,420 Russian troops
and militia have been killed and 3,869 wounded since Oct. 1, the
official start of the military campaign in Chechnya.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   It was hardly the first time the rebels had caught the Russians
by surprise. In early January, the militants launched a
counteroffensive, briefly seizing the towns of Argun and Shali and
ambushing a Russian column on the road near Gudermes.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians took advantage of their superior fire and larger
forces to regain control. The militants' attacks, however, showed
their ability to elude Russian roadblocks and sneak around the
countryside.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Thursday's ambush was a rude shock to many Russians
as it occurred just days after Russia's generals all but declared
victory.
</P>
<P>
   The commanders said on Monday that they had delivered a
knock-out blow to the militants after Russian forces seized the
town of Shatoi, the rebels' last major stronghold in the southern
highlands. Russian officials were even talking about starting troop
withdrawals from Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   ``The military phase of the anti-terrorist operation in Chechnya
is drawing to a close,'' Vladimir Rushailo, Russia's interior
minister, said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   A day later disaster struck. After learning of the ambush,
Rushailo, who oversees the nation's militia, cut short a trip to
Belarus to race back to the North Caucasus.
</P>
<P>
   He described the attack as a ``black page in the history of the
Russian militia.'' Some of his aides suggested that Russian
officers may face criminal prosecution for failing to take
precautions against a Chechen attack.
</P>
<P>
   The ambush dominated the television news Friday night. Instead
of the presidential campaign, viewers saw grim images of wounded
soldiers and heard analyses of a one-sided fight in which the
Chechens bested some of Russia's elite milita.
</P>
<P>
   Frustrated Russian Interior Ministry troops did not welcome the
news coverage. After the ambush, a television crew from the
state-owned ORT network went to the mortuary in Mozdok where the
OMON dead had been brought. The Interior Ministry troops took out
their frustrations on the ORT correspondent and roughed him up.
</P>
</TEXT>
