<SLUG> BC-COKE-DRESS0304-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coke adopts casual dress policy
 &HT;    By Henry Unger
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Coke execs are taking off their suits and ties.
</P>
<P>
   The company told all its U.S. employees Friday that they could
start dressing casually for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on associates' questions and interest, and consistent
with our desire for more flexibility and agility in our culture,
the time has come for more flexible business attire,'' company
President Jack Stahl told employees in Coke's internal newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   The move to casual business attire, from dress attire, comes at
a time when the company is trying to improve employee morale in the
wake of massive jobs cuts.
</P>
<P>
   The dress change is effective immediately and applies every day
_ not just on Fridays or special occasions.
</P>
<P>
   The company did point out, however, that suits and ties still
may be appropriate on certain occasions, including when employees
are interacting with customers, partners, visitors and other
``stakeholders.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Associates should use their judgment to determine how to dress
in a way that is flexible, but still exemplifies a professional
image for our company,'' the newsletter said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
