A6162 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-COKE-PLAINTIFF0304-CO     03-03 0378
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-PLAINTIFF0304-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Plaintiffs ask judge to punish Coke
 &HT;    By Christopher Seward
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Plaintiffs in the racial discrimination suit against
Coca-Cola want the federal judge in the case to punish the company
for continuing to withhold ``damaging documents.''
</P>
<P>
   In a motion filed Friday, plaintiffs' attorneys say the material
includes a study of pay equity among African-American and white
employees, and ``an adverse impact study analyzing promotions by
race.''
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola also is accused of not supplying documents created
after June 9, 1999, and data created after April 22, 1999, even
though it is under orders to turn over material produced after Jan.
1, 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coca-Cola's entire discovery strategy is designed to prevent
plaintiffs and the Court from obtaining a true picture of the
company's treatment of African-Americans,'' plaintiffs say in their
motion.
</P>
<P>
   In their suit filed in U.S. District Court in Atlanta, eight
current and former employees allege Coca-Cola has discriminated
against African-Americans in pay, promotions and performance
evaluations.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola, which denies the suit's allegations, declined to
comment Friday on the latest motion.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides are now in the pretrial ``discovery'' phase of the
case, in which documents are exchanged.
</P>
<P>
   Plaintiffs' attorney Steven Rosenwasser said the plaintiffs know
the documents and data on pay equity and promotions exist because
they have been provided to the U.S. Labor Department's Office of
Federal Contract Compliance Programs.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs have asked U.S. District Judge Richard Story to
impose ``a severe monetary penalty'' on the company and order it to
pass along employee data that were created after April 22, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   In their motion Friday, plaintiffs' attorneys reminded Story of
a telephone conference call he held with both sides last June in
which he said to Coke's attorneys, ``as more material comes
available to you, it will be an ongoing request, an obligation to
provide those materials to the plaintiffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Story ordered both sides to try to settle the case
through non-binding mediation.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
