<SLUG> BC-PINOCHET-RETURN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER DICTATOR STEPS FIRMLY ON NATIVE SOIL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTIAGO, Chile _ Declared unfit to stand trial in Europe for
human rights violations, former dictator General Augusto Pinochet
projected strength in a triumphant homecoming Friday, lifting
himself out of a wheelchair and walking steadily across an airport
tarmac to the cheers of adoring supporters.
</P>
<P>
   But as military officers saluted him and throngs serenated him,
Chileans victimized or exiled by Pinochet's military dictatorship
angrily questioned whether he escaped justice by fooling British
doctors into believing he was too mentally and physically enfeebled
to stand trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wasn't in a wheelchair despite all that they said about him
being ill and unable to move and that he was a broken man,'' said
Carlos Reyes, director of a London-based group of Chilean exiles
who lobbied to try Pinochet.
</P>
<P>
   Stepping on his native soil Friday for the first time since his
arrest in Britain 16 months ago, Pinochet smiled, hugging senior
military officials and family and waving to 200 applauding friends,
associates and decorated soldiers at the airport. He cast aside a
wheelchair to walk purposefully with a metal cane to a helicopter
that ferried him to a military hospital in the capital.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, the 84-year-old Pinochet _ wearing a dark blue
suit, white shirt and lavender tie _ paused and raised his cane to
the cheering crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just have lots of inner peace that this is finally over and
he's back home,'' said Lucia Pinochet, the general's daughter.
</P>
<P>
   His arrival ended an international legal saga that put dictators
worldwide on notice. He still must wait for a Chilean judge to
decide if he must begin another legal odyssey in his own country
for crimes committed during his 17 years of iron-fisted rule.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the constant legal and political pressure to free
Pinochet applied by Chile's conservative president, Eduardo Frei,
no government officials showed up at the airport to formally
welcome Pinochet, now a senator-for-life.
</P>
<P>
   About 8,000 flag-waving supporters crammed the streets around
the military hospital where Pinochet was taken, waiting for a
glimpse of the general from the balcony of his suite.
</P>
<P>
   Pinochet opponents, meanwhile, held their own smaller marches
downtown, calling for the former dictator to be tried for
atrocities, such as the 3,197 people who, by official government
count, died or disappeared at the hands of his secret police.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the day, small groups of anti-Pinochet demonstrators
scuffled with supporters outside the hospital before dozens of
police officers stepped in.
</P>
<P>
   Interior Minister Raul Troncoso criticized Friday's
demonstrations by both sides because of the unresolved legal
questions. ``It appears improper to organize this as if it were a
party, in spite of the circumstances under which Pinochet was
allowed to leave London,'' Troncoso said.
</P>
<P>
   Pinochet critics have asked a Santiago appeals court to strip
Pinochet of his legislative immunity so that he can face 60
lawsuits that have been filed against him in Chile, all of them by
relatives of victims of repression.
</P>
<P>
   As a compromise, the Frei administration, which is scheduled to
leave office in eight days, is reportedly trying to push Pinochet
to retire completely from pulbic life while allowing him to keep
his parliamentary immunity.
</P>
<P>
   If an agreement cannot be reached, the Pinochet dilemma will
fall to socialist President-elect Ricardo Lagos, who has said his
government will not pursue a deal but rather let the courts decide.
</P>
<P>
   While at the military hospital, Pinochet is scheduled to undergo
another series of tests to check his physical and mental health.
</P>
<P>
   British doctors who examined Pinochet last month found damage to
the frontal lobes of his brain, which had been caused by a series
of strokes linked to cardiovascular illness and diabetes. They also
concluded that he was unable to stand trial because of memory loss
and a limited ability to understand complex sentences.
</P>
<P>
   It was that diagnosis that led British Home Secretary Jack Straw
to drop extradition proceedings brought by Spain, which wanted to
put Pinochet on trial for crimes committed against Spanish citizens
during his dictatorship.
</P>
<P>
   Upon hearing Straw's decision, Pinochet and his wife immediately
boarded the Chilean military Boeing 707, which had been waiting in
England. About 24 hours later, after a refueling stop at an
undisclosed site, the jetliner landed in Chile.
</P>
<P>
   But Pinochet's appearance upon landing raised new doubts about
the British teams' conclusions, said Andrew Hogg, spokesman for the
Medical Foundation for the Care of Victims of Torture.
</P>
<P>
   ``The medical foundation has suspected from the outset that
General Pinochet has sought to present himself in as poor a state
of health as possible in order to avoid extradition,'' Hogg said.
</P>
<P>
   Even with Pinochet's return, it remains unclear how Chile will
repair its damaged political and diplomatic relations with several
countries. It has recalled its ambassador to Britain and runs the
risk of hurting an important economic partnership with Spain. Even
Argentina, its neighbor, refused to allow Pinochet's pilots to
cross its airspace.
</P>
<P>
   The global tension played out on Santiago's streets, where
Spanish and Argentine reporters covering the developments were
frequently heckled and pushed by angry Pinochet supporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's our liberator and he freed us from communists and from
becoming a second Cuba,'' said Sandra Torre Alva, a 31-year-old
housewife who joined the thousands of jubilant Pinochet supporters
outside the hospital. ``It doesn't matter what the rest of the
world thinks. We're grateful to Pinochet.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
