<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-PINOCHET-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PURSUING PINOCHET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Because British doctors found him mentally unfit to stand trial
in Spain for crimes against humanity, Chile's former dictator,
General Augusto Pinochet, was able to elude prosecution abroad and
return home Friday. For survivors of the tyrant's killers and
torturers, and for relatives of the murdered and the disappeared,
Pinochet's homecoming betokened a thwarting of justice.
</P>
<P>
   On the night before his return, 500 Chileans conducted a
candlelight vigil in front of La Moneda, the presidential palace
that Pinochet's mutinous troops bombed and strafed during his
military putsch of Sept. 11, 1973. The demonstrators chanted, ``No
to the amnesty, no to immunity, the blood of the dead is not
negotiable.''
</P>
<P>
   Their chant was a way of saying that political niceties must not
stifle the requirements of justice. Terrible crimes were committed
under Pinochet's regime; he ordered them, and he has not been
punished. Another unmistakable message of the vigil in Santiago was
that the pursuit of justice did not come to an end in London.
</P>
<P>
   It is now up to the political leaders of a democratic Chile to
decide on lifting the immunity that Pinochet enjoys as a senator
for life, thanks to the constitution created when he was in power.
</P>
<P>
   It will not be easy to bring to justice the 84-year-old
patriarch of Latin American fascism. Although a judge of the
Santiago Appeals Court is currently investigating 60 criminal
complaints against Pinochet and there is no shortage of witnesses
to testify against him, he cannot be tried for the crimes committed
during his reign without a constitutional change. And he still has
fierce partisans in the military and among Chile's traditional
elites.
</P>
<P>
   Difficult as it may be to judge and punish Pinochet in Chile, it
must not be forgotten that his case before the Law Lords in
Britain's House of Lords has established a legal precedent of great
significance for the cause of human rights. The Law Lords found
that there is no sovereign immunity for Pinochet or others like
him; their exercise of state power cannot protect them when they
travel abroad. This Pinochet precedent will outlive its namesake,
and may save many lives.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-03-00 2014EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
