<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-03 20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6175 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-NBA-WORLD-ART-2TAKES(     03-03 1188
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NBA-WORLD-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNATIONAL HOOP DREAMS AND FISCAL REALITIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(lh) 
 By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Watching from overseas in the 1990s, it was often hard
to tell just what the NBA was. Was it a sports league; a global
merchandiser; a public relations company building a global brand?
Or was it a bit of all three?
</P>
<P>
   After the 1992 Barcelona Olympics, when millions of
non-Americans were hypnotized by the artistry of Magic Johnson,
Michael Jordan and the rest of the Dream Team, the National
Basketball Association started pushing harder to make its logo, and
the superstars who populate its universe, household images
worldwide. By and large, it has succeeded.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are problems. The NBA is hurting a bit on the home
court, where average attendance at games is depressed, television
ratings have sunk to their lowest level in a decade, and
merchandise revenue has plummeted. And many assumptions about
global growth have been cast into doubt, too.
</P>
<P>
   In Europe, sales of jerseys, balls and backboards are flat, as
is television audience growth. Magazines about the NBA draw fewer
readers than they used to. There is no crisis, but as in the United
States, the figures partly reflect the impact of the owners'
lockout that canceled 464 games last season, as well as Jordan's
departure.
</P>
<P>
   But they also underscore the challenge of keeping fans who are
an ocean apart from actual sweating, dunking teams from spending
their sports money elsewhere. In 1998, the soccer World Cup in
France captured audiences outside the United States; last year, the
rugby World Cup began a wave of rugby-inspired fashion.
</P>
<P>
   David Stern, the 57-year-old NBA commissioner, is not fazed. The
league is expanding its network of offices abroad, and the league's
Web site, a vehicle for sales, is popular outside the United
States. Recent deals to bring pro basketball more actively onto the
Web by making its games and its products available to fans
worldwide via computers, televisions and phones are expected to
revive revenue growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're pushing ahead unabatedly,'' Stern said in a recent
interview.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, the league opened an international headquarters in
Geneva after hiring Paul Zilk, a former Nestle executive, to run
global operations. In 1997, Zilk moved the headquarters to Paris,
then opened smaller offices in Tokyo, Hong Kong, Mexico City, and
most recently Milan, Italy, and Munich, Germany.
</P>
<P>
   The investment paid off, as kids from Melbourne, Australia, to
Marseille, France, donned Chicago Bulls jerseys, sending
merchandise sales soaring. They also took part in league-sponsored
clinics or swapped NBA trading cards. A tournament started in 1988
and sponsored by McDonald's was polished up after the Barcelona
Olympics. Held every two years in different cities, it drew large
numbers of fans to watch league champions play international teams.
</P>
<P>
   Added revenue flowed in through the sale of television rights,
as cable and digital networks proliferated. By the time of this
year's All Star Game, the NBA was broadcasting to more than 240
countries in 44 languages. By the mid-1990s, league executives were
predicting overseas revenue growth of 15 to 20 percent annually _
but after 1997 growth actually stagnated or fell.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Not that the NBA was alone. Major League Baseball spread its
wings, particularly in Latin America and Japan; the National
Football League played exhibition games abroad and in the early
1990s started a league in Europe. And National Hockey League games
are broadcast to about 180 countries.
</P>
<P>
   But the NBA has had the most success, partly because basketball,
like soccer, requires little equipment. Moreover, basketball is
already played by amateurs and professionals alike in many
countries, notably in Europe, and the league gets most of the
credit.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Dietrich Woestehoff, spokesman for Premiere World, a German
digital channel controlled by the Kirch Group, said the channel
broadcasts about 1,000 hours of American sports a year, including
baseball, hockey, football, and track and field, but nearly half is
the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   Michel Denisot, director of sports programming at Canal Plus in
Paris, said fans of American sports want just two things: pro
basketball and the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   The image of American sports in the European imagination is what
makes them attractive to broadcasters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We literally started with the NBA,'' Denisot said. ``It's part
of our history and our identity. It's modern, it's young, it's
creative, and those are our ideals.'' Canal Plus broadcasts about
50 league games a year, including the All Star Game and the
playoffs. It also owns the broadcast rights for Spain and Italy,
the biggest NBA markets in Europe, after Germany and France.
</P>
<P>
   As basketball thrived, so did the culture it created. In
sporting goods stores, like the Decathlon chain in France, or the
Footlocker unit of Venator, which opened hundreds of stores in
Europe in the 1990s, NBA jerseys and other products were hot items.
</P>
<P>
   To feed interest in basketball superstars, magazines sprouted
widely. In both France and Germany, a half-dozen dedicated to the
NBA popped up. ``The explosion came after the Dream Team, in '93
and '94,'' said Frederic Lesmayoux, editor of Mondial Basket, the
No. 1 basketball magazine in France.
</P>
<P>
   What also drew young Europeans was the growing presence of
European players. From Germany, Detlef Schrempf went to the Indiana
Pacers, but now plays for Portland; more recently from France,
Tariq Abdul-Wahad joined the Orlando Magic, but is now at Denver.
</P>
<P>
   But the magic of the NBA has faded. In Europe, as in the United
States, the league was hurt by the lockout and Jordan's retirement.
It also fell victim to changing fashion tastes. With the NBA off
the TV screen and Jordan gone, sales of merchandise fell.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Though the league will not say how much of a decline has
occurred, a measure of it came in 1997 when the league approached
Adidas, now known as Adidas-Salomon, about selling NBA apparel
outside the United States. Adidas, after a year of talks, declined.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just felt there wasn't value in it,'' said Tom Harrington,
the executive who negotiated for Adidas. ``A kid in Germany buys a
Bulls shirt, although he's never seen a Bulls game, and maybe never
will.''
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, Zilk left, and his job is being filled in New York
by Stern.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Television executives insist they have clung to a hard core of
loyalists, but there, too, interest is down. In Germany, DSF, a
sports channel owned by the Kirch Group, recently moved its NBA
broadcasts to 11 p.m. from late afternoon, despite protests from
fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``After Jordan's withdrawal, growth came to a halt,'' Woestehoff
of Premiere said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the league continues to push the game, via
television, into the world's untapped nooks and crannies. After
signing up four new stations this fall _ in Malta, Kazakhstan,
Serbia and Montenegro _ the NBA boasted that it could reach 650
million households abroad, more than six times the American figure.
But how many are actually watching from abroad is impossible to
determine.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the league runs into bureaucratic hurdles. Two years
ago, British broadcast authorities forced the private broadcaster
Channel Four to drop its NBA and NFL coverage because it had too
much American material on the air. Pro basketball immediately found
an alternative in the Independent Television Network.
</P>
<P>
   But other evidence suggests that in major markets interest in
the NBA is flagging. In 1992, after the Dream Team's triumphant
march, a publisher in Cologne, Germany, started Basket, one of four
or five new German magazines about the NBA. In five years,
circulation climbed to 50,000. After the lockout, it plummeted to
25,000, though it has since clawed its way back to about 40,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last 12 months, interest has been low,'' said the
editor, Robin Barberan. Of five German monthlies, only two survive.
</P>
<P>
   A similar lack of interest is apparent in France. Circulation at
Mondial Basket, one of five French magazines dedicated to the
league, has dropped to about 50,000, half what it was in the years
immediately after Barcelona.
</P>
<P>
   ``It corresponds to a trend in fashion,'' Lesmayoux, the editor,
said. ``In France, rap and street were popular; now, that's
passe.'' The market for sports apparel, he estimated, is down about
a third.
</P>
<P>
   Little of this appears to upset Stern. Indeed, if anything, it
serves to steel his resolve to thrust changes already under way
within the NBA out into the global business.
</P>
<P>
   To increase the league's reach, officials are considering
opening offices in Warsaw, Poland; and Shanghai, China, to go with
those just added in Munich and Milan. For 2000, he said, the league
is projecting revenue outside the United States of about $500
million, unchanged from recent years, thanks to increased sales of
videocassettes and electronic games to offset the decline in
apparel. The league has been approached to support regional ``super
leagues'' in Asia and Europe. But he said putting NBA teams abroad
was not part of the plan.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States and overseas Stern puts much hope in the
Internet. Five years ago, the league began NBA.com, which now draws
some 4 million visitors a week, about a third from overseas. In
November, Stern began NBA.com TV, making the league the first to
manage its own network via satellite and digital cable. The screen
carries images in one corner and streams of statistics and news
scrolling across the bottom.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Stern announced a deal with Barry Diller of
USA Networks to sell league merchandise on the Internet and on
Diller's Home Shopping Network. The league is already talking to
overseas broadcasters, including ITV2 in Britain, to provide a
24-hour NBA channel.
</P>
<P>
   But can the league successfully hawk merchandise via the
Internet if it cannot do so in stores?
</P>
<P>
   David M. Carter, principal of the Sports Business Group, a Los
Angeles sports consultancy, called the Internet push a ``very
positive trend.'' He said Stern was being encouraged in this
direction by team owners like Ted Leonsis, president of America
Online Interactive Properties, who owns part of the Washington
Wizards, and Mark Cuban of Broadcast.com, who paid $280 million
last month for the Dallas Mavericks.
</P>
<P>
   But Carter added: ``It will not be easy to pursue what he's
doing overseas.'' For one thing, Internet use abroad significantly
lags that of the United States. Moreover, can interest in the NBA
be sustained without actually having teams nearby?
</P>
<P>
   Stern said it could. Planting a franchise flag outside North
America, he said, is ``less remote than five years ago, but it
doesn't seem close in the short to medium term; I don't see that as
the model.''
</P>
<P>
   The model, he says, is the rock concert. ``Sell lots of
records,'' he said. ``Tour occasionally.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
