<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-PATRICK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KENNEDY'S UPLIFTING CANDOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Representative Patrick Kennedy performed an important service
when he told a Rhode Island political gathering that he has been
treating depression with medications. In doing so, he demonstrated
that it is possible to lead a successful career while coping with a
mental condition requiring medical treatment _ an example to
counter the stigma still applied to those who suffer with mental
illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy, a Democrat in his third term, was taking part in a
campaign appearance Tuesday with Tipper Gore, the vice president's
wife. She too has told the public about her own bouts of depression
and about treatments she has undergone.
</P>
<P>
   Depression is an insidious condition that can undermine
self-esteem and disrupt normal life. But it can be overcome enough
for remarkable accomplishments. Abraham Lincoln is thought to have
had periods of serious depression, yet he is regarded as perhaps
America's greatest president. Ludwig von Beethoven, the great
German composer, was similarly afflicted. Winston Churchill
referred to periods of depression in World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Depression strikes about one in 10 Americans at some time in
their lives, with varying durations. In extreme cases it can lead
to suicide, but it diminishes the lives of all sufferers, as well
as their families and associates. Mental illness costs nearly $100
billion annually in lost productivity and is ranked by the World
Bank as the fourth leading cause of disability in developed
nations.
</P>
<P>
   Along with other even more disabling mental illnesses,
depression remains a stigmatizing condition that unnecessarily
deprives society of the full contribution its sufferers can make.
That stigma probably accounts for the fact that Kennedy is only the
third member of Congress to say publicly that it has been a
problem, although raw statistics suggest several others have
similar difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, great strides have been made in the clinical
treatment of depression through the use of drugs. Kennedy's
comments advance the day when such conditions are no longer
debilitating.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
