<HEADLINE>
A HEATING OIL RESERVE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Monday, March 6, 2000)  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   President Clinton's suggestion that America's strategic
petroleum reserve might be used to help stabilize world oil prices
was obviously an attempt to influence markets, but it had little
effect as oil prices _ at least briefly _ set nine-year highs.
Clinton could, however, stave off a repeat of last month's price
spike by establishing a fuel reserve of heating oil that could help
reduce wild price swings.
</P>
<P>
   The strategic reserve of crude oil was established after the
1979 Iranian revolution to cushion Americans from political
disruptions of oil production and sales. By itself the reserve
could not do much to stem price increases resulting from either
genuine shortages or arbitrary production cuts by the oil cartel
OPEC.
</P>
<P>
   After years of being no more than marginally effective in
controlling prices, OPEC recently pulled itself together long
enough to create tight markets in crude oil, driving up prices,
improving its members' revenues, and making its production quotas
easier to live with for countries (Venezuela, Nigeria, Iran among
others) that used to produce more than OPEC permitted.
</P>
<P>
   Some OPEC leaders say that their ultimate objective is to
stabilize oil prices at about $25 a barrel, compared with $31 a
barrel at the end of February and with less than $10 a barrel in
late 1998. This price may be the level at which OPEC can get
maximum revenue without provoking increased exploration and
development of oil by non-OPEC competitors and still be a price
that does not disrupt customer economies.
</P>
<P>
   Heating oil, a refined product of crude, is a different matter.
Last month's price spike was caused by failure of American oil
companies to build adequate inventories to cope with surges in
demand brought on by severe cold spells or interruptions in
refining and shipments of heating oil. That failure was the result
of fear that oil prices were going to drop rather than rise _
reasonable, perhaps, but wrong. A publicly held reserve would have
at least dampened the price hike. Such a reserve should be
established to help avoid a repeat performance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
