u p BC-BRADLEY-NYT &LR;      03-03 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY TAKES UP UNEXPECTED SUBJECT: FOREIGN POLICY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT7 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(ko) 
 By DAVID W. CHEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PROVIDENCE, R.I. _ With only four days left before crucial
primaries that are likely to seal his fate as a presidential
candidate, former Senator Bill Bradley defied conventional
political wisdom on Friday and spoke about foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
   Even though that has not been a major concern of voters this
year, Bradley offered his most detailed remarks to date on
America's foreign policy, criticizing the Clinton-Gore
administration's handling of Russia and China and promising to
pursue a broadly internationalist policy.
</P>
<P>
   Saying the next president should be able to juggle rapid changes
in globalization and technology, Bradley said it was essential to
reduce barriers to trade, capital, immigration and ideas. But he
also said it was crucial for America to have a consistent foreign
policy and military infrastructure, _ something he excoriated the
current administration for failing to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the past decade we have sometimes been the world's
volunteer fire department, a role that we have executed with
considerable success,'' Bradley said before a boisterously
supportive crowd at Brown University. ``But we have been
inconsistent about when we would act and when we should stand
aside.''
</P>
<P>
   There were no major surprises in his 50-minute speech, as
Bradley elaborated on the foreign policy framework he sketched in
November, in a short speech and question-and-answer session at
Tufts University. But the timing certainly raised some eyebrows.
</P>
<P>
   When Bradley talked about his foreign policy agenda in November,
his aides indicated that a fuller accounting would come in weeks.
But weeks turned into months. So now, with Mr. Bradley trailing
badly in most polls, and Super Tuesday just four days away, the
idea a weighty policy speech with the gravitas of a master's thesis
did not exactly seem like a strategy from Political Campaigning
101.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the speech almost sounded like the reading of an
important, thoughtful statement into the Congressional Record, with
an eye as much on posterity as on constituents.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about the timing, Eric Hauser, Bradley's campaign
spokesman, said Bradley wanted to demonstrate leadership and
showcase a command of complex international issues, gained in part
from serving on the Senate Intelligence Committee for 8 of his 18
years in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going into a national political primary, and foreign
policy is something that people ought to know where the leaders
stand,'' he said. ``This just proved to be the right time.''
</P>
<P>
   In his address, which capped a day of campaigning before
student-dominated crowds in here and in Portland, Maine, Bradley
first talked about the importance of electing a president with the
ability to make the world a smoother place.
</P>
<P>
   ``My vision of this new world is one of increasing
interconnectedness,'' he said, using a turn of phrase that might
seem more apropos for an Internet speech. ``Our challenge is to
keep lowering barriers between countries so that goods, capital,
people and ideas can move even more freely and help people of
different nationalities, races and religions to co-exist and
cooperate.''
</P>
<P>
   He then criticized the Clinton-Gore administration as being
inconsistent, he said, on what he described as the world's four
other major powers: Russia, China, Japan and Europe.
</P>
<P>
   He blamed the administration for failing to articulate a clear
policy on China and Taiwan, saying: ``Unfortunately, the
Administration's inconsistent signals have confused both Beijing
and Taiwan, and thereby increased the risk of miscalculation,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   And he was particularly critical of the administration's policy
on Russia, calling it ``perilously counterproductive'' and saying
it had ``resulted in a situation in which the world's only other
nuclear superpower is coming apart at the seams, a situation that
makes the world a far more dangerous place than it needs to be.''
</P>
<P>
   In response, Douglas Hattaway, a spokesman for Vice President Al
Gore, dismissed Bradley's foreign policy record in the Senate,
noting that Bradley voted in 1984 against sending aid to Nicaraguan
rebels fighting the Sandinista government, only to reverse field
and vote for it in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't have much standing to criticize the Clinton-Gore
foreign policy records, when his own record is a series of waffles,
flip-flops and bad votes,'' Hattaway said.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the biggest surprise of the day, though, was that
Bradley veered from his prepared text after the policy address and
launched into a version of his stump speech. He sounded almost
wistful about his days as a student at Princeton and tried to tout
the virtues of politics to the standing-room-only crowd of 350
students.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a way you move ahead as a country; it's a way we shape
our common future,'' he said. ``Your generation of Americans can be
a great generation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
