<SLUG> BC-NYSE-NASDAQ-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NYSE AND NASDAQ DISCUSSED MERGER _ BUT THE IDEA DID NOT ADVANCE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Nasdaq Stock Market and the New York Stock
Exchange have held informal discussions regarding a possible
merger, but nothing came of them, people briefed on the talks said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   That the two markets _ historically bitter competitors that have
regularly claimed superiority over each other _ had even discussed
the idea was another indication of just how much the structure of
stock market trading is now in flux, with the introduction of new
electronic networks and with both the Securities and Exchange
Commission and Congress pondering what changes need to be made.
</P>
<P>
   The conversations were reported in The Wall Street Journal.
</P>
<P>
   One person briefed on the talks said that Richard Grasso, the
chairman of the New York Stock Exchange, had made an informal
overture to Frank Zarb, the chairman of the National Association of
Securities Dealers, Nasdaq's parent organization, but that nothing
had come of the idea.
</P>
<P>
   In a private placement memorandum, a part of which was provided
to a reporter, Nasdaq disclosed the talks but gave no details. That
memorandum was issued in connection with efforts by the exchange to
sell stock in itself.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from the two organizations would not discuss the talks
in any detail, but Robert Zito, a Big Board spokesman, said that
``everyone in the industry has been talking to everyone else in the
industry for 18 months.'' Andrew MacMillan, a NASD spokesman, said
there were ``no current negotiations'' with the New York Stock
Exchange.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
