u f BC-JUPITER0304-COX     03-03 0708
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JUPITER0304-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wireless is music to Internet convention
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Internet: It's not just for desktops anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anywhere, anyplace, anyhow'' was the slogan of nearly every
speaker and analyst to take the stage at the annual Jupiter
Consumer Online Forum downtown at the Sheraton Hotel and Towers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nevermind broadband,'' said Richard Bressler, CEO of Time
Warner Digital Media. ``It's wireless. You can do it, and you can
do it now.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have cable,'' he said referring to Time Warner's cable
franchise, one of the largest in the country. He pointed out that,
despite its size, it only reaches about 20 percent of U.S. homes.
``So if we don't think about wireless, we'll get our lunch eaten.''
</P>
<P>
   America Online, which plans to merge with Time Warner by the end
of this year, made key deals last month with several wireless
providers, including BellSouth and Sprint PCS. AOL will provide
wireless-tailored content to those providers for use by AOL and
wireless subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   While Bressler talked about the cable and wireless combination,
Universal Music President Edgar Bronfman Jr. outlined his own
vision of bringing digital downloads from both famous and unknown
artists to the Web in a way that will benefit consumers, artists
and ultimately Universal. Bronfman, who parlayed his family's
wholesale liquor business into a multimedia empire including
Universal Pictures, Universal Music and the USA Network, spoke with
optimism about the Web as the next and possibly most profitable
vehicle for selling music.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to stop thinking about selling people round things,''
Bronfman said in his keynote address Friday to the more than 1,600
attendees gathered here from as far away as Japan.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us, the Internet is about the opportunity to get more
music to more people in more places,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His statements echo the strategies of other Internet and
traditional executives who hope to give users a positive Internet
experience on any electronic device, from a desktop PC to a
wireless phone or personal digital assistant.
</P>
<P>
   Bronfman even predicted a day when a button on a car radio would
let users instantly order or download songs they might happen to
hear while driving.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, we ask music buyers to do a lot of work,'' he said.
``They have to listen to the radio, try to remember who the artist
is and then go somewhere else to make a purchase.'' He went on to
outline a strategy for a collection of secure sites where users
could sample, download and purchase music from Universal.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, though, it's still all about money, and Bronfman
knows that many music purchases are impulse buys. He plans to use
the Web to make music buying easier than ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``The student may have time to wade through thousands of MP3
links, but the average consumer doesn't. They want something that's
quick and convenient.
</P>
<P>
   ``It facilitates impulse buying,'' he said. ``For example, when
you hear a song you like, you aren't always near a music store. But
if you're online, you are one, maybe two clicks away from making a
purchase. Music and the Internet is truly a match made in heaven.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said that, particularly when it came to music, he wasn't
worried about the new format replacing any existing formats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Experience shows that if you build it and it's better, they
will come,'' he said, noting the development of recorded music from
old 78 rpm records to mini-disc technology and now digital
downloads.
</P>
<P>
   Bronfman painted a rosy picture of happy music lovers buying
music literally around the clock, but the same old question came up
of whether users will pay for online content. However, unlike years
past, the answer for the first time seems to be a qualified
``maybe.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If the creators want to get paid, content won't be free,''
said MTV Interactive President and CEO Nicholas Butterworth.
</P>
<P>
   MarthaStewart.com emissary, COO Sharon Patrick summed up thus:
``When you have to make that Halloween costume for your child and
you've only got two hours to do it, you'll pay.'' She got a
standing ovation.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
