<P>
   NY-WOMEN'S-VOTE (New York) _ Sen. John McCain and Texas Gov.
George W. Bush battle for the women's vote in Tuesday's Republican
presidential primary in New York. McCain defends his record on
federal spending for breast cancer research and touts his plan for
tobacco regulation that would have financed more such research.
Bush visits a cancer research center on Long Island, where breast
cancer rates are among the highest in the nation. By STEWART M.
POWELL and DAN FREEDMAN. (1stld-writethru filed.)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   RIGHTS-MARCH (Selma, Ala.) _ Bloody Sunday, the racial violence
that broke out on a bridge near here when marchers tried to vote in
1965, was a turning point in the battle for civil rights. It has
since become an annual festival of reaffirmation. On Sunday, as the
35th anniversary of the march is observed, President Clinton and 50
members of Congress are expected to join a commemorative march and
jubilee. By LORI RODRIGUEZ.
</P>
<P>
   GENOCIDE-MINISTER (Laredo, Texas) _ The State Department says
that an elderly Rwandan clergyman accused of genocide and other
international war crimes will be extradited within a few weeks.
Elizaphan Ntakirutimana, a former pastor with the Seventh-day
Adventist Church in Rwanda, is accused of taking part in the
massacre of Tutsi refugees during an ethnic bloodbath in his native
country in 1994. By BONNIE PFISTER. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-INTERNET (San Jose, Calif.) _ President Clinton,
reacting to public and corporate alarm at massive, intentional
Internet disruptions, orders a study of federal computer system
security. By CRAGG HINES. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   MILITARY-PAY (Killeen, Texas) _ Some 12,000 military families
use food stamps at military commissaries. And that doesn't take
into account how many more food stamps were redeemed by military
families in civilian supermarkets. Pay for service members has
embarrassed some officials who claim to be supporters of the
military and has erupted as an emotional campaign topic for GOP
presidential hopefuls George W. Bush and John McCain. By KIM COBB.
(Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   SERIAL-KILLER (Undated) _ A drifter jailed in South Texas for
his attacks on two girls has confessed to the bizarre slaying of a
family of four in a small town in southern Illinois in 1987. The
former carnival worker has now been tied to nine slayings in five
states, including Alabama, Arkansas and North Carolina, according
to Texas investigators. By JAMES PINKERTON.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-COLUMN (Houston) _ Will Wright created the original
SimCity game 11 years ago, and looking at the concept on paper,
nothing could seem more boring. Players build a city from scratch,
manage its resources and keep the citizenry happy. But the SimCity
franchise _ the latest version is SimCity 3000 _ has sold more than
7 million copies. It spawned an entire genre of computer games that
simulate real-life systems, but it remains the best of the best. A
look at the latest version. By DWIGHT SILVERMAN. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-HELPLINE (Houston) _ A reader asks, `` In investigating
high-speed Internet service, I find limited options for my home. My
cable provider does not offer cable-modem service, and I am too far
from the Southwestern Bell central office to get ADSL service.
However, I have been told I can get IDSL at 144,000-bit-per-second
speeds. The only thing I know about ISDL is that it is related to
ISDN. Is it a worthwhile option until I have better options
available?'' Assorted Q&AMP;As. By DWIGHT SILVERMAN. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   WORKING-COLUMN (Houston) _ The Balanced Budget Act of 1997 has
hit Texas hospitals hard. A look at its effects, and how hospital
employees are being fired. By L.M. SIXEL. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   INTEL-GIGAHERTZ (Undated) _ The race to see who can be first to
market with a 1-gigahertz personal computer chip could be won much
earlier than expected _ as in, next week. Industry sources said
Intel Corp. will announce 1-GHz versions of its Pentium III chips.
Personal computers with the processors will be available later this
month. By DWIGHT SILVERMAN. (Already filed.)
</P>
