<SLUG> BC-BOSNIA-TRIBUNAL-390&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAR CRIMES TRIBUNAL SENTENCES CROATIAN FOR ATROCITIES IN BOSNIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By MARLISE SIMONS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ An international tribunal in The Hague sentenced a
Croatian general, the highest-ranking military commander yet
brought to trial, to 45 years in prison Friday for war crimes
committed during the Balkan conflict.
</P>
<P>
   The International Criminal Tribunal for the Former Yugoslavia
sentenced Gen. Tihomir Blaskic for ordering a series of attacks on
Muslim villagers in Bosnia between 1992 and 1994 while his forces
were trying to secure the area for Croatia. It was the harshest
sentence handed down by the tribunal since the United Nations
created it in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Unexpectedly, the court also indirectly indicted the government
of former President Franjo Tudjman of Croatia, openly stating that
Zagreb had overall control of the Bosnian Croat authorities and
Blaskic's militia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republic of Croatia did not content itself with merely
remaining a spectator on the sidelines or even seek simply to
protect its borders,'' the ruling read. ``It intervened in the
conflict, pitting Muslims and Croats of central Bosnia against each
other.''
</P>
<P>
   Blaskic, 39, was convicted for crimes against humanity, war
crimes and grave breaches of the Geneva Convention, which deals
with the protection of civilians during war. Although he was not
charged with ``killing a Muslim by his own hand,'' the judges said
that as commander of the militia, the so-called Croatian Defense
Council, he was responsible for personally ordering attacks and for
failing to prevent or punish crimes committed by his subordinates.
</P>
<P>
   In Zagreb, officials of the new government immediately
criticized the verdict, saying that Blaskic had been far more
moderate than many Croatian nationalists. ``There is no doubt that
the sentence is very harsh and I believe it will have to be
re-examined in the appeals process,'' Prime Minister Ivica Racan
said on Croatian radio.
</P>
<P>
   Announcing the ruling of the three-judge panel, Judge Claude
Jorda cited a long list of atrocities by the Croatian militia
against terror-stricken Muslims in the villages of Bosnia's Lasva
Valley, where hundreds were killed and many were beaten, raped or
burned alive in their homes. One of the worst examples was the
rampage in the village of Ahmici, which led to the death of more
than 100 men, women and children.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``The crimes you committed, General Blaskic, are extremely
serious,'' Jorda said. ``The acts of war carried out with disregard
for international humanitarian law and in hatred of another people,
the villages reduced to rubble, the houses and stables set on fire
and destroyed, the people forced to abandon their homes, the lost
and broken lives, are unacceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses said that as the sentence was read out in the
courtroom, Ratka Blaskic, the defendant's wife, broke down and
sobbed while he remained calm.
</P>
<P>
   During the trial, Croatian nationalist extremists threatened
Ante Nobilo, one of Blaskic's lawyers, who then moved his family
temporarily to The Netherlands from Croatia.
</P>
<P>
   The general's defense lawyers had argued that the commander was
powerless to stop the Croatian militiamen because they were
``poorly trained recruits'' in a new and ill-organized command. But
the judges ruled that the court had more ``evidence than it needs
to note that the chain of command was operating satisfactorily.''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors expressed satisfaction with the verdict and said the
sentence had helped achieve their goal of judging the most senior
commanders of the war in the former Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today is a turning point,'' said Paul Risley, spokesman for
the prosecutor's office. ``In previous sentences, we've been forced
to deal with the foot soldiers and camp guards and the like who
carried out crimes. Now we are moving to the more senior
commanders.''
</P>
<P>
   Three senior Bosnian Serb commanders are now in custody in The
Hague, and their trials are expected to start soon.
</P>
<P>
   Blaskic's trial took 25 months and involved testimony from 158
witnesses and some 30,000 pages of evidence. It has been held up,
both inside and outside the tribunal, as an example of how the
court should not function, paving the way for reforms meant to
speed up the proceedings.
</P>
</TEXT>
