<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-ETHICS-$ADV05-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE REAL BOTTOM LINE FOR ALL THIS FREE STUFF  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 5) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By DANIEL AKST   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The best things in life may not be free, but lately a lot of
pretty good things can be had for practically nothing.
</P>
<P>
   The Village Voice, for instance, is one of many newspapers that
are now distributed gratis. There are also no-fee credit cards,
free income tax software and even free computers. In the investing
world, of course, there are no-load mutual funds, not to mention
stock-trading commissions that seem to be fast approaching zero.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet, of course, is truly the land of the free _ from
free e-mail, voice mail and fax services to access to Encyclopedia
Britannica and major newspapers and magazines of every stripe.
Linux, the upstart operating system that some people see as a
challenge to the hegemony of Microsoft, is free, too. And until
Microsoft scotched the idea recently, there was even talk of making
Windows free.
</P>
<P>
   With news of $30-a-barrel oil and $2.85 million for a
one-bedroom apartment in Manhattan, Alan Greenspan is hardly the
only one worried about inflation. In such a climate, it is
deceptively easy to overlook the opposite trend: all the cheap
stuff bubbling up to the surface of our economy. And the cheapest
of these goods and services _ the ones that cost nothing _ are
notable as harbingers of long-term social and economic changes.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, this free stuff is aimed at affluent people, who
in effect are trading on their status as sales leads. That suggests
that the trend offers yet another way, besides marrying each other
and investing in Internet stocks, that the rich will keep getting
richer.
</P>
<P>
   A further implication is that the recipients will be obliged to
surrender more of their already depleted store of privacy. But
despite considerable hand-wringing, they probably won't mind very
much, because even though their lives have become a more open book
to strangers, they already enjoy unprecedented physical privacy
from the people they really care about _ their neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   These days, the affluent do not perambulate in watchful
villages. They cruise sprawling suburbs behind tinted windshields.
For most people, this supposedly horrifying arrangement has proven
remarkably congenial, and it doesn't appear likely to change.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, nothing in life is really free. Providers of free
information may hope that the recipients will pay by listening to
advertisers' messages; providers of free computers make the
recipients sign long-term Internet access agreements. Yet many of
us find that the costs of our new free services are borne mainly by
other consumers, suggesting that we are at the threshold of a
golden age of free riders.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not referring here to turnstile jumping, but to arrangements
like no-fee credit cards with grace periods. People who pay in
full, and on time, get free use of a bank's money for a month,
underwritten by customers who maintain outstanding balances.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, investors in index funds get to ride free on the
coattails of the costly research and investment decisions made by
others, decisions in the absence of which the stocks in the index
would cease to rise. If you read this column on a Web site instead
of buying the paper, you would be free-riding, too.
</P>
<P>
   Can all this continue? Some of it surely can, because the rising
tide of free services reflects two long-term trends that show no
sign of abating. The first is global competition, which has a way
of making even things that aren't free amazingly cheap. Consider
the labor, materials and capital investment that went into what you
are picking up for a song at Wal-Mart or Costco.
</P>
<P>
   The second trend is a technology-inspired acceleration in the
commodification of goods. Is there really any material difference
between brands of vodka or cola or comparably equipped personal
computers? Stock-trading systems, mutual funds, Internet access and
other goods and services are becoming ever more alike. Even cars,
within a given model class, are more difficult than ever to tell
apart.
</P>
<P>
   Given a decently managed money supply, how do you raise prices
in this environment, or stand out in the crowd? I predict
ever-higher premiums attached to marketing, which already occupies
a hallowed place in American business culture.
</P>
<P>
   There will also be innovation, naturally. Building a better
mousetrap always holds out the possibility that people will be
willing to pay more for rodent control. That won't be inflationary,
if the mousetrap really is better.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the possibility reminds us that the best mousetrap
is always likely to cost something, and that even in Freebie
Nation, you get what you pay for, one way or another. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Akst's column tilts at conventional business wisdom and
appears the first Sunday of each month. E-mail:
culmoney(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
