<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-03 20:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6228 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-CAR-SMART-AUDI-ART-$A     03-03 1025
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-SMART-AUDI-ART-$ADV05-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FAST SEDAN THAT SHINES IN BAD WEATHER  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 5) 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888 603-1036 or 888
346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By JAMES G. COBB   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the secular philosopher Mae West once posited, too much of a
good thing can be wonderful. Though she wasn't thinking of
horsepower, low-end torque and high g's on a skid pad, the racy
lady would no doubt have admired enthusiasts' primal urge to drive
faster, stop quicker and hang tighter in corners.
</P>
<P>
   Such desires are being particularly well sated by European
carmakers. Starting with something sensible _ capable sport sedans
with room for several adults _ they add sensuality in the form of
lusty engines, beefy suspensions, sexy wheels and grippy tires.
These are Clark Kent automobiles with a bit of Superman's cape
peeking through.
</P>
<P>
   BMW has mastered the art with cars from its M works. Mercedes is
turning out a whole line of rockets from its AMG tuning shop. Volvo
has worked with Tom Walkinshaw Racing, and Saab has transformed its
9-3, as sensible as shredded wheat, into the Viggen, the very model
of turbocharged anarchy.
</P>
<P>
   Audi, too, has been playing the game in Europe, but only now is
it bringing one of its ``S'' cars to this country. The S4 is based
on the compact A4 sedan, still one of my favorite cars at any
price. But while the A4 has a turbocharged four-cylinder or a
normal-breathing V-6, the S4 gets a twin-turbo 2.7-liter V-6 that
makes 250 horsepower.
</P>
<P>
   More impressive, it produces 258 foot-pounds of torque at just
1,850 rpm. The S4 zooms from zero to 60 in about 5.5 seconds; it
launches from stoplights like a mission to Mars.
</P>
<P>
   Every A4 is a delight to drive, with a suspension that stays
buttoned down, excellent steering and brakes that mean business.
The S4 has some added attractions. Crucial components of the
suspension (four-link front, double wishbone rear) are made of
aluminum, the suspension is lowered a bit and the handling benefits
from 17-inch alloy wheels, borrowed from Audi's Avus concept car,
plus wide 225 tires. The ventilated disc brakes are beefed up.
</P>
<P>
   More significant, all S4s have quattro all-wheel drive, an
option on A4s. Quattro varies the power to all four wheels, all the
time, providing as much bad-weather prowess as most sport utility
owners are likely to need _ in a much more comfortable, sensible
package, if you ask me.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth generation of quattro detects the spin of a wheel and
redirects power from side to side to take advantage of any wheel
that does have traction. Audi boasts that while some
traction-control systems cut power when a wheel spins _ what it
calls a ``disabling technology'' _ quattro is ``enabling,'' since
it prevents the wheels from spinning, in theory, to begin with.
</P>
<P>
   With this much power trying to spin the wheels, it is good to
have some help. The S4 engine started as the 2.8-liter, 30-valve
V-6 of the A4, but Audi reduced the displacement to get stronger
cylinder walls. The two small turbos, one for each bank of
cylinders and each with an intercooler that lowers the temperature
of air forced into the engine, provide quicker response than a
single large turbo.
</P>
<P>
   Driven with a light foot, the V-6 gives few clues to its
potential, feeling nearly as demure as the plain-vanilla engine on
which it is based. But when driven aggressively it responds in
kind. Stomp the accelerator in second gear, with the tachometer
needle at 2,500 rpm, and the power doesn't just build; it surges,
tugging you back in a tightly bolstered sport seat.
</P>
<P>
   On a steep mountain road I drive regularly, the S4 zoomed up in
fourth gear on a stretch where I'd usually downshift to second or
third; its third gear handled climbs where I usually shift to
second, or even first.
</P>
<P>
   But there is an unfortunate trade-off. The six-speed manual
shifter is rubbery and out of character. Throws between gears are
too long, and a vagueness forces the driver to hunt for a gear or
risk missing it. One cannot help but make an unfavorable comparison
to the crisp Getrag shifters of BMW's M cars.
</P>
<P>
   Worth considering is the S4's five-speed Tiptronic, a
``manumatic'' that changes gears with a tap of the shift lever,
without a clutch. The six-speed actually detracts, rather than
enhances, the S4 experience.
</P>
<P>
   Nor does this Audi have the jittery, sporty edge of the M3, a
rear-drive car that feels best near its limits. The Audi handles
nearly as well, perhaps better in some maneuvers, gripping the road
like a baby primate clinging to its vine-hopping mom.
</P>
<P>
   It would certainly be my choice in rain, sleet or snow. Yet
while its proficiency is never in doubt, it is a little less fun to
toss around than the M3.
</P>
<P>
   The S4's subtlety carries through to its trim. The only clues to
its special status are small badges on the grille, deck lid and
steering wheel, plus the larger wheels and a front bumper with
gaping air intakes.
</P>
<P>
   The car can be ordered with special colors, like Imola yellow
and Nogaro blue, either of which could catch the eye of a state
trooper in the next county. If you order the sport interior, you
get suede seat and door inserts _ eye-catching but bordello-gaudy _
in the same colors.
</P>
<P>
   The instruments are as good as the A4's have always been, with
red-lighted gauges and controls right at hand. The optional sunroof
is controlled by a nifty dial with detents that let you instantly
open it just so.
</P>
<P>
   Audi's timing is impeccable, since it now has the compact
supersedan market pretty much to itself. Mercedes has stopped
making its C43 and there will be no M3 until that car returns this
year in the new 3-Series body. The Viggen is far less polished and
far harder to control.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from its shifter, the S4 is hard to fault. At $37,900, it
is $9,110 more than the A4 2.8, but that may be a small price to
pay for the envy of those in the know. As West also said, ``It's
better to be looked over than to be overlooked.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE TRACK: Six gears short of perfection.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
