<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-03 20:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6230 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-ABOUT-CARS-MERCEDES-A     03-03 0995
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABOUT-CARS-MERCEDES-ART-$ADV05-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SPORT UTILITY ITCHING TO BE A SPORTS CAR  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 5) 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888 603-1036 or 888
346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By SERGE SCHMEMANN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When a people falls in love as deeply as Americans have with the
sport utility vehicle, there is money to be made. So auto
manufacturers have scrambled to produce an SUV to meet every
conceivable niche, and even some inconceivable ones.
</P>
<P>
   In the process, the breed has grown from the pioneering
International Scouts, Jeep Cherokees and Ford Broncos to embrace an
ever-expanding universe.
</P>
<P>
   These have ranged from Lilliputian two-seaters like the Suzuki
X-90 to mastodons like the Ford Excursion, from snarling war
machines like the Hummer to leathered luxocruisers like the Lexus
LX 470, from car-SUV blends like the Subaru Outback to sci-fi
creations like the Isuzu VehiCross. More are on the way.
</P>
<P>
   In this feeding frenzy, the definition of sport utility has
hopelessly moved beyond the original notion of a truck with a
covered bed and four-wheel-drive to manage the hunting trail. It
now covers virtually anything that has big, knobby tires and a
hefty dose of attitude.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there must be limits somewhere. And in my subjective
view, the Mercedes-Benz ML55 AMG is somewhere just beyond them.
Yes, this is the M-Class sport utility built in Alabama, which
normally comes as an ML320 (with a 3.2-liter V-6) or an ML430 (with
a 4.3-liter V-8).
</P>
<P>
   These trucks have been praised for their design and their
competence on and off the road, but criticized, at least at the
beginning, for less-than-Mercedes levels of quality.
</P>
<P>
   But once the power-loving makeover artists at AMG, the in-house
performance tuners of Mercedes-Benz, pump the power up to 342
horses, bolt on 18-inch, 50-series sport tires and paint the brake
calipers bright red, are you not taking things just a notch too
far? I mean, niche marketing is the name of this game, but does
anyone really need an off-road vehicle capable of going 141 miles
an hour?
</P>
<P>
   Mercedes says that people who buy the ML55 will be those who
want a Porsche 911, but need utility. I have no doubt there are
people like that. Me, for example, and probably you.
</P>
<P>
   But a vehicle that has its center of gravity somewhere near a
Porsche's roof line, weighs almost two and a half tons and pushes
the aerodynamic equivalent of a sheet of plywood down the road is,
sorry, a truck. Conversely, a van with racing tires and a
supersophisticated 5.4-liter V-8 capable of sprinting from a stop
to 60 mph in 6.8 seconds _ a time recorded by Car and Driver
magazine _ is not the sort of truck you'd use to tow the fishing
boat.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, you may say, but how does that differ from the LX 470 or
the Cadillac Escalade, or the new BMW X5, vehicles that also show
little sign of longing for the great outdoors? True, the effect is
similar. But the difference is that AMG deliberately set off to
turn a competent sport utility into a hot rod, with all the
sacrifices in off-road prowess that implies.
</P>
<P>
   The ML55 sits eight-tenths of an inch lower than its humbler
M-Class siblings, and though that still leaves it with a
respectable 7.6 inches of ground clearance, the sport tires, the
nervous power and the stiff suspension beg to be left on a straight
and level road. I drove the ML55 onto a wet lawn and had trouble
modulating the power enough to get off the grass without scorching
some worms.
</P>
<P>
   Enough complaining. Let's accept that this is a very powerful
and sophisticated truck, big enough to move a college student to
campus, fast enough to run with the best and different enough to
make whatever statement you may be wanting to make.
</P>
<P>
   The latter might require some guidance, since the Germans are
not into yawning hood scoops, huge lettering and heavy chrome. But
once spotted, the two big bulges on the hood (nonfunctional!), the
red calipers peeping through the five-spoke wheels and the two big
chrome exhausts do give off an aura of excessive muscle. And
inside, the dark burled walnut, twinkling dash and nice leather
whisper ``class.''
</P>
<P>
   The power is very, very nice, especially when delivered through
all-wheel drive. AMG started with the 5-liter V-8 from the big
S-Class sedans and stretched it to more than 5.4 liters, to make
342 horsepower at 5,500 rpm.
</P>
<P>
   Bucking the general trend of softening the ride on upscale
models, AMG stiffened the shocks, planting the huge tires firmly on
the road. It all made for some fun accelerator-stomping around
town, some brisk cruising on the Interstate and some pretty
impressive handling in the twisties, though there's something about
sitting high above the pavement that argues against roaring
headlong into a hairpin.
</P>
<P>
   The price is about $65,000, not so bad in the rarefied realm of
luxury SUVs, but high enough to pose a serious question: Is this
souped-up van really worth 20 grand more than an ML430, which is
not that much slower, and really can go off-road?
</P>
<P>
   Another nit: the centerpiece of the ML55's dash is a fancy
control center intended to handle the stereo, phone and navigation
system, the on-board computer and probably some other functions.
But despite considerable poking and arguing we never really
mastered it, and even if we had, the driver should not even try.
</P>
<P>
   We did get the navigation system working, but as we approached
New York City on Interstate 80, pointed directly at the George
Washington Bridge and headed for the Upper West Side, the computer
stubbornly insisted that we use the Tappan Zee Bridge, some 20
miles to the north, or the Lincoln Tunnel, 15 minutes south. Only
after the last exit was behind us did the navigational whiz
reluctantly accept our decision to take the most direct route into
Manhattan. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE TRACK: It's fast. It's fun. But it ain't a Porsche.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
