<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-WAIVER0304-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coke changes waiver stance
 &HT;    By Henry Unger
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In a sudden and rare about-face, Coca-Cola said Friday
it will allow laid-off black employees to participate in the racial
discrimination lawsuit against the company while still qualifying
for enhanced severance benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Coke's move, described by observers as a wise public relations
decision, came just 24 hours before African-American employees were
scheduled to meet at St. Philip A.M.E. Church to talk about actions
they might take to try to change the company's mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am simply overjoyed,'' said Larry Jones, a laid-off manager
and chief organizer of today's meeting. ``I think this is a
tremendous victory for all employees _ not just black employees _
and, in the end, it's a victory for the company. ... We will
absolutely have a monumental celebration. It will sound like Sunday
morning in the sanctuary.''
</P>
<P>
   The company changed its mind, despite the fact that it has
prevailed on the issue in court so far.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end, this decision was guided by our desire to treat
all of our employees with dignity, respect and fairness,'' said
company President Jack Stahl.
</P>
<P>
   It is the fairness issue that Jones and other black employees
called into question when the company had required laid-off
employees to sign a release form giving up the right to sue Coke in
the future to get enhanced severance benefits. Those benefits
amount to about double the regular severance benefits.
</P>
<P>
   For African-American employees, the old policy meant that they
could not get the more lucrative benefits while participating in
the discrimination suit as a plaintiff or as a member of a class,
if the judge certifies the case as a class-action in the future.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview prior to the company's change of heart, Jones
described the gut-wrenching decision hoisted on black employees as
a ``diabolical scheme.'' Take the enhanced benefits now, or take
your chances that the class will be certified down the road and
you'll share in some settlement or award.
</P>
<P>
   The company had maintained that it was just following its
standard operating procedure for reducing its litigation exposure
from departing employees. Employment experts also said it is common
for companies to offer enhanced severance benefits to eliminate
future legal problems.
</P>
<P>
   Many of these companies, however, are not in the middle of a
discrimination suit in which the class certification issue is still
up in the air while layoffs are under way.
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks ago, about 150 employees attended a meeting at St.
Philip to discuss what to do, and Jones expects hundreds more
current and former employees at today's meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Essentially, the release form, or waiver, issue started to
mobilize black employees for the first time since the
discrimination suit was filed nearly a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   The original release form, Stahl acknowledged in a memo Friday
to all employees, ``has contributed to confusion at a sensitive
time. ... For that reason, and to ease the challenges facing our
departing employees, we are modifying this waiver requirement, so
as not to apply to any claims against the company filed and still
pending in any court as of Jan. 12, 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   That is the date eight current and former employees filed their
amended suit, claiming the company discriminated against
African-Americans in pay, promotions and performance evaluations.
They are seeking class-action status to represent about 2,000 black
salaried employees in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Coke has denied the allegations in the suit and has opposed
plaintiffs' efforts to make it a class action.
</P>
<P>
   Stahl also said the company will cancel the release forms that
laid-off African-American employees already have signed. Instead,
they will receive new forms.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are delighted by the company's change of position,'' said
plaintiffs' attorney Cyrus Mehri. ``As we've always maintained,
this is the right thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Management experts also praised the company's action.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't think of another situation where that's been done
across the board for a population,'' said Rick Cobb, vice president
and national director at Challenger Gray &AMP; Christmas. Often, when
companies take a stand on a sensitive issue such as severance
agreements, he said, they tend to ``dig in their heels.''
</P>
<P>
   By extending this olive branch to workers, Coke is sending two
signals, said Daniel Rodriguez, an assistant professor at Emory
University who has studied downsizings.
</P>
<P>
   ``One, the incoming leadership is showing flexibility and that
it is attuned to employees' needs,'' Rodriguez said. ``And two,
they're saying, `Hey, we need to go ahead and eliminate some of the
distractions on our plate so we can focus on what Coke's all about:
maximizing market share, revenue growth and profitability.'''
</P>
<P>
   Before the company's turnaround, Jones, the organizer, said
employees would be discussing a ``national strategy.'' He would not
elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   But after Coke's announcement Friday, Jones said, ``We will now
reassess the initiative we were anticipating.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
