<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-03 20:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6237 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-NOISE-MCBURNEY-ART-NY     03-03 1093
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOISE-MCBURNEY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LISTENING TO SHOSTAKOVICH A NEW WAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(See also NOISE-THEATER-REVIEW (listed on early skeds as
NOISE-THEATER) and NOISE-MUSIC-REVIEW (listed on early skeds as
NOISE-REVIEW)) 
(DW) 
 By SARAH BOXER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``I had one idea,'' Simon McBurney, the director of
``The Noise of Time,'' said Friday. That idea was to listen to the
15th Quartet of Shostakovich ``in another way.'' He added quickly:
``I'm not suggesting that there was one way. The way the mind
decodes music is an individual mystery. But the physical
circumstances can change the way you listen.''
</P>
<P>
   McBurney changed the physical circumstances radically. As Philip
Setzer, one of the violinists of the Emerson String Quartet, put
it: ``We move around; we play on a raked stage; we play standing;
we play in the dark; we play by memory; we play separated from one
another. We are not used to doing any of this.''
</P>
<P>
   Each musician has a silent someone following him around _ four
actors, one for each quartet member, carrying chairs, clapping
noiselessly, just sitting. ``Like Shostakovich's music,'' Setzer
said, ``they function on many levels. They are a Greek chorus. They
are the people. They are the part of us that listens.''
</P>
<P>
   But long before the Emerson had come out onstage, the audience
had been primed to listen differently. It had just been through a
theatrical evocation of Shostakovich's life performed by the
Theatre de Complicite, which McBurney heads. During the drama a
disembodied voice had floated the haunting question, ``Can music
lie?'' An answer was offered but it was just as enigmatic as the
question: Music can lie, but ``only if it is used like a language,
like a code.''
</P>
<P>
   Did Shostakovich use music like language? His rhythms did
occasionally contain a kind of Morse code. For example, he used the
rhythm dot-dash-dash in his 10th Symphony, which was not only a
coded reference to the name of a woman with whom he was in love,
but was also, McBurney said, the code for ``I am on fire and have
dangerous cargo on board.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 15th Quartet, you keep hearing the rhythm, dash-dot-dot.
It turns out this is not only Morse code for the letter D (the
first letter of Shostakovich's first name), but it also means
``Keep away, maneuvering with great difficulty.'' These are odd
collisions of meaning that McBurney relishes.
</P>
<P>
   As Setzer put it: ``Music can function on different levels.
Shostakovich had to write music that would pass the eyes of the
horrible people judging him. Thus, until recently Shostakovich was
discarded as simplistic enough to pass the eyes of the Soviet
regime. His music was viewed as a compromise. There were
constraints on what he could say. But what he was saying was
powerful'' and more complicated than anyone suspected.
</P>
<P>
   How does this relate to the actual events in Shostakovich's
life? In one sense all the events presented onstage are parts of
his life: it is true that Shostakovich played music in a movie
theater that burned down while he was playing. It is true that
Stalin personally called him up on the phone. It is true that he
had to denounce himself as a Formalist. It is true that he composed
a piece that Yuri Gagarin sang from outer space. It is true that
everyone came to know his music by listening to the radio.
</P>
<P>
   But it is not the biographical content that McBurney is
concerned with: ``Everything in the drama that leads up to the
musical performance of the quartet relates to the numinous side of
the events in Shostakovich's life,'' he said. ``Shostakovich's
final pieces, his quartets, are scratching the surface of another
world.'' The radio, the fear of skiing, the images of flight, the
association with Gagarin, the fire in the movie theater, even the
Morse code relate to this numinous world.
</P>
<P>
   Take Shostakovich's relationship to Gagarin. Shostakovich not
only composed a piece that Gagarin sang in space. He was also, like
Gagarin, a Soviet icon, a puppet, or as Shostakovich called
himself, ``a cut-out paper doll on a string.'' The song that
Gagarin sang in space was called ``The Motherland Is Listening.''
</P>
<P>
   On one level, McBurney said: ``It is a great piece of Social
Realism. But it's also ironic.'' Here you have a picture of the
motherland eavesdropping. ``The irony,'' he says, ``is already in
the language itself.'' In the Soviet Union, McBurney suggested:
``No one knew what was true and what was false. Photographs were
retouched.''
</P>
<P>
   When a work was not up to Communist Party standards, McBurney
said, people would say, ``It does not conform to the idea of Soviet
reality.'' So even the idea of what is real and what is false was
slippery.
</P>
<P>
   The very first moment in McBurney's drama brings the
slipperiness of truth to the fore. A man comes out onstage and
announces that the BBC is recording the performance. He directs the
audience to be silent for a moment and then to applaud when he
signals. There is grumbling in the audience: ``I don't know if I
want to applaud.''
</P>
<P>
   As some people guessed, the BBC recording was bogus. But,
McBurney said, the experience did contain a grain of truth. It
showed ``the terrible tyranny of applause.'' The audience resented
being bullied into clapping. This kind of order made the audience
``want to be silent,'' McBurney said. And that had a special
meaning for Shostakovich.
</P>
<P>
   Mstislav Rostropovich, the cellist, used to visit Shostakovich,
so that they could sit together in total silence for an hour.
Shostakovich used to say, ``Come quickly,'' and then they would
just sit silently together. ``He had an urgent need to be silent,''
McBurney said. Then he would say, ``Thank you, goodbye.'' Those, by
the way, are the last words that are uttered in the play before the
musicians come onstage to perform the quartet.
</P>
<P>
   When McBurney first began listening to the Shostakovich 15th
Quartet, he said he thought each movement was ``a meditation upon
death,'' but after a while, he said, ``I began to think it was more
about leave-taking.'' All the movements are a different kind of
leave-taking.
</P>
<P>
   This is a certain kind of musical truth. And a certain kind of
historical truth. ``It is extraordinary,'' McBurney said, ``There
are things in his music which tell us about our time,'' and which
you can only hear in retrospect. Then McBurney quoted Aleksandr
Blok, the Russian Symbolist poet: ``History is the noise of time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
