<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-03 20:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6243 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-INVEST-WITH-HOOVER-AR     03-03 1087
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-WITH-HOOVER-ART-$ADV05-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTING WITH MICHAEL E. HOOVER: EXCELSIOR ENERGY AND NATURAL
RESOURCES FUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic of Excelsior Energy &AMP; Natural Resources Fund is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888 603-1036 or 888 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 5)  
 (af)  
 By CAROLE GOULD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   These days, OPEC might as well stand for Oil Prices are
Exorbitant, Chump.
</P>
<P>
   The price of West Texas intermediate crude oil was $31.51 a
barrel on Friday, up from $12.91 just 12 months ago, as the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries and its allies have
continued to confound the pundits by more or less sticking to the
production cutbacks they imposed in 1998. The world's hunger for
oil, meanwhile, has grown.
</P>
<P>
   But little of this squeeze is evident in the prices of energy
stocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see the most significant value opportunities in energy,''
said Michael E. Hoover, 46, who runs the $57.5 million Excelsior
Energy and Natural Resources fund.
</P>
<P>
   Investors in his fund aren't likely to be complaining about high
prices at the gas pump. Excelsior Energy returned 34 percent in the
12 months through Feb. 25 while the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock
index has returned just 8.4 percent, according to Morningstar Inc.,
the Chicago financial publisher.
</P>
<P>
   When energy prices were low, Excelsior Energy, which has often
invested in a variety of commodity and cyclical stocks, took a more
defensive stance. It assumed heavy stakes in utilities, gas
pipeline and integrated oil companies, whose chemical and retail
businesses make them less sensitive to the price of oil.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy helped it outperform its peer group of energy
funds. For the three years through Feb. 25, Excelsior Energy
returned 8.7 percent a year, on average, compared with a 3.1
percent loss for its category.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Hoover is an oil bull, having increased the fund's energy
stake to 92 percent of invested holdings, a record, from 85 percent
three months ago.
</P>
<P>
   From his office in Midtown Manhattan, Hoover said he believes
that oil prices will ease, but not by as much as many experts
think. Part of the decline will result from seasonal factors this
spring: demand for heating oil will drop while gasoline demand
won't peak until summer.
</P>
<P>
   As for OPEC, which meets again on March 27, Hoover sees a desire
``to engineer prices down to the $22- to $23-a-barrel level.''
</P>
<P>
   But he thinks oil companies will keep passing along today's
higher prices for crude at the gas pump _ raising prices an
additional 5 to 8 cents a gallon by summer. And the higher gasoline
prices, he said, will further drive up the prices of oil stocks.
``That will remind investors that oil company profits are on the
rise,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Many investors think oil will soon fall back to under $20 a
barrel. Hoover, while noting that ``it's impossible to forecast oil
prices,'' sees an average of $23 a barrel over the next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``For that reason,'' he said, ``we are very bullish on energy
stocks, which are trading at valuations that reflect oil prices of
$16 to $17.''
</P>
<P>
   The fund focuses on four sectors of the energy market. Oil
services companies account for 28 percent of the fund's invested
holdings; major integrated oil companies, 20 percent; independent
exploration and production companies, 20 percent; and natural gas
companies, 16 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The majors, including Royal Dutch/Shell, BP Amoco and Texaco,
are long-term holdings. Hoover buys more shares after their prices
take sudden dips of 20 percent or more. His favorite is Exxon
Mobil, because of opportunities he sees in the newly merged
company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Exxon will apply its strict financial discipline to Mobil
assets,'' he said, ``and the combined company will have
opportunities for cost reduction by reducing head count and
drilling only the best wells.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoover says he is bullish on Exxon Mobil's offshore drilling
properties in Angola and West Africa. And he expects the company to
resume its share buybacks during the second half of the year; the
buybacks were suspended last December.
</P>
<P>
   The fund initially bought Exxon shares in 1994, at $31 a share;
Exxon Mobil now trades at $75.6875, or 18 times his earnings
estimate of $4.15 a share for 2002. He forecasts a long-term
earnings growth rate of 9 percent a year.
</P>
<P>
   Among the independents, Hoover prefers companies that are
drilling in the same fields as the majors. ``A discovery will have
a bigger impact because they start from a smaller revenue base,''
he said. Such companies are purer plays on the path of oil prices,
in part because they seldom own chemical or retail businesses.
</P>
<P>
   He likes Triton Energy, which is based in Dallas and has
operations in Colombia, Thailand and West Africa. Because of its
small revenue base, Triton will reap outsized benefits from its oil
fields along the West African coast, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The fund bought the stock last October at $17.25; it now trades
at $27.375, or 5 times his cash flow estimate of $5.50 a share for
2002. Hoover said the stock could climb to $35 over the next 18
months.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, the fortunes of oil services companies, too, are highly
sensitive to oil prices. As their cash flow rises, the majors
invest more cash in exploration, drilling and production, creating
business for the oil service companies.
</P>
<P>
   He likes Nabors Industries of Houston, a driller that has 30
percent of the market for land-based deep drilling rigs. He bought
shares in October 1995 at $9; the stock closed on Friday at
$37.4375, or 7.5 times his earnings estimate of $5 a share for
2002.
</P>
<P>
   A favorite in natural gas is El Paso Energy of Houston, which
has announced a merger with the Coastal Corp. The combined entity
will have the largest natural-gas pipeline network in the United
States and 30 percent of the country's natural-gas market, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would term this an integrated natural gas company, with a
variety of revenue streams,'' Hoover said. The company makes money
from oil and gas exploration and production, transporting natural
gas and marketing gas and electric power.
</P>
<P>
   It also has an opportunity to lay fiber optic cable along its
rights of way, he added, or to sell those rights to
telecommunications companies.
</P>
<P>
   He predicted that El Paso Energy's earnings would grow 15
percent to 18 percent, annualized, over three years. The stock now
trades at $38.0625, or 13 times his earnings estimate of $3 a share
for 2001.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
