<HEADER>
A6247 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-INVEST-INSIGHT-Q&AMP;A-$A     03-03 0847
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-INSIGHT-Q&AMP;A-$ADV05-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SEASON TO CONSIDER VERY REAL EARNINGS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 5) 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Questions may be italicized)  
(af) 
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Believe it or not, spring is just around the corner. And while
most stocks slogged through January and February, the companies
behind the ticker symbols have been out there in the real world,
doing real business, many of them making real money.
</P>
<P>
   In about a month, when first-quarter profit numbers start to
roll in, people who have been worried sick about rising interest
rates may start to remember that there is a lot of life out there.
Of course, there is a very real chance that outside of technology,
those investors may spend the intervening period merrily selling
shares of very good companies that are making very good money.
</P>
<P>
   Leah Modigliani, a United States equity strategist at Morgan
Stanley Dean Witter, took some time last week to talk about
profits, interest rates and the stock market. Following are
excerpts from the conversation: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. The economy barreled ahead at nearly a 7 percent annual clip
in the fourth quarter, and so far this quarter hasn't shown many
signs of slowing. Does that bode well for corporate profits?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Earnings were very strong in the fourth quarter and we think
that trend is continuing.
</P>
<P>
   For the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 companies, we think earnings will
rise about 15.7 percent on a year-over-year basis in the first
quarter, and 12 percent for the year.
</P>
<P>
   There will be some aberrations within the group, particularly in
the energy sector, where in some cases earnings will go from
negative to very positive. And we will continue to see good
earnings growth out of technology, even though some of these stocks
are ahead of themselves on fundamentals. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Are there other sectors that will do particularly well?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. We should see very strong earnings growth in basic materials
companies, the paper, chemical and aluminum stocks.
</P>
<P>
   According to our calculations, the consensus projected earnings
growth rates for energy companies will go from negative in 1999 to
45 percent this year. The projected growth rate for basic materials
is 36 percent, which is a little higher than the 33 percent
earnings growth projected for technology companies. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. For the most part, investors seem to have ignored these
signs, especially in the groups you just mentioned. Why? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Even though we are seeing very strong earnings growth in
energy and basic materials, the market doesn't seem to care.
</P>
<P>
   We have liked energy stocks for some time, and still do. But
people seem to be concerned that oil prices will come down from
these peaks. That may happen, but they will still be way up from
where they were a year ago. And that will be reflected in earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the so-called Old Economy stocks are undervalued. Even
some of the companies that are migrating to the New Economy are not
getting much credit for it right now, like the auto stocks. They
have good sales and are really jumping on more efficient
Internet-based purchasing methods. But for the most part, the
stocks are in the dumps. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Isn't there also some concern that if rising interest rates
choke off growth, these kinds of cyclical stocks will get badly
hurt?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. If the economy gets into trouble, that would be the case. But
because of healthy growth overseas, energy companies would be a
little bit of an exception to that. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. What about interest rates? The worry seems to be that the Fed
will tip the economy into recession. Is that likely? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. If the economy goes from 7 percent growth to 4 percent, it is
a slowing that on the margin is a negative. But 4 percent growth is
still very strong. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Technology stocks seem impervious to the prospect of higher
interest rates. Are they really that bulletproof? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. The cost of capital for these companies is extremely low, so
higher rates will not impact that. You would think stocks with a
high price-to-earnings multiple would be impacted. But people are
looking at the wonderful opportunity for technology in the future
and are not worrying about a one-year rise in interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   That said, valuations are ahead of themselves. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. With the Nasdaq composite index being the notable exception,
most major measures are down so far this year. Are you expecting
more selling? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. In the beginning of the year, we were calling for a 20
percent to 25 percent correction for the Dow Jones industrial
average and the S&AMP;P 500. We are probably part of the way through
that, but there may be more to go. I am not talking about the
Nasdaq, which is an index I don't have a focus on. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. What stocks do you like right now? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. In a general sense, we like the oil service stocks.
Schlumberger and Halliburton are two that I like. And I like
integrated oil company stocks like Conoco, and some of the bigger
companies, like Exxon Mobil.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
