<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-03 20:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6251 &Cx1f; tta-z
u s BC-WATCHING-TIGER-ART-2T     03-03 1021
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WATCHING-TIGER-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN TIGER WOODS IS IN CONTENTION, GOLF RATINGS JUMP 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT16 is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic
is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(lh) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Tiger Woods plays golf, television executives swoon. With
his rare power to move ratings, he is the sports version of ``ER''
or ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'': a singular programming entity
capable of clubbing rival networks in their Nielsens in his pursuit
of tournament victories.
</P>
<P>
   Woods doesn't have to win. He needs only a chance at victory to
stir viewers to watch. When he's out of contention, or not playing,
ratings for PGA Tour events remain good, but not as formidable.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's drawing fans who might watch a college basketball game,
the NBA or auto racing,'' said Sean McManus, president of CBS
Sports. ``But he's also drawing fans who might not watch sports on
Saturday or Sunday afternoons.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods' entry in a tournament has come to mean what Michael
Jordan's appearances with the Chicago Bulls once meant to NBC's
National Basketball Association broadcasts: a near guarantee of
higher viewership than usual and a sure-fire reason to ooh and ahh.
</P>
<P>
   How important is Woods? Last year, CBS averaged a 4.1 rating in
the 11 tournaments it showed that Woods played in, 71 percent
higher than its seven events that he missed. The Woods differential
for CBS stood at 68 percent the year before.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the Tiger Factor has led to golf's recent run of
primacy over the NBA. On the last four Sundays, final-round golf
telecasts have all drawn better than the NBA. Last Sunday, when
Woods finished second to Darren Clarke in match play at the 36-hole
World Golf Championships, ABC's 5.0 rating defeated a tripleheader
of NBA games, including the NBC debut of the league's hottest star,
Toronto's Vince Carter. It was a 39 percent increase in ABC's
rating for the same event last year and was no doubt tied more to
whom Clarke defeated than the skill he displayed in winning.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 13, when Woods finished in a tie for second in the Buick
Invitational, the 8.0 Sunday afternoon rating exceeded the NBA
All-Star Game's prime-time telecast by 16 percent.
</P>
<P>
   An 8.0 for a non-major golf tournament is extraordinary, nosing
toward the territory of Sunday National Football League ratings,
which averaged an 11.0 on Fox and a 10.5 on CBS last season. No
major golf tournament, except the Masters, with a 10.1 rating,
posted a higher Sunday rating in 1999. (One rating point is equal
to about 1 million television households.)
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no bigger star,'' said Mike Tirico, the golf
tournament host at ABC Sports. ``A certain percentage of the
audience will watch every Sunday. A more attractive leaderboard
brings some more. Tiger on the leaderboard brings the general
sports fan in.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ABC doesn't alter its coverage to accommodate Woods, but Tirico
said, ``If he's two strokes behind the leader, producers and
directors will show his shot going to commercial to plant the seed
of coming back to see more of him.''
</P>
<P>
   Gregg Winik, the executive producer of NBA Entertainment, said
the league does not fear Woods' encroachment on its turf, which
comes at a vulnerable time. Woods is at the peak of his appeal
while the NBA, in a transition period after Jordan's retirement, is
averaging a 3.7 rating, down 14 percent from the 4.3 for last
year's lockout-shortened season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, Tiger is growing the sports audience,'' Winik said.
``Sometimes, he'll be competitive with us, sometimes the lead-in.
He's `The It Guy,' he's got buzz, which is something we're familiar
with.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, as the PGA Tour heads to Florida, starting with this
week's Doral-Ryder Open, Woods will be on NBC at the Bay Hill
Invitational in two weeks and at The Players Championship a week
later.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all evens out,'' said Dick Ebersol, chairman of NBC Sports.
</P>
<P>
   Woods chooses his own schedule and opts not to play some
tournaments, so the networks carrying golf must hope that Woods
will enter the events they show. Woods will probably play about 15
to 20 tournaments out of more than 40 this season.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The surge in golf ratings is not a tale totally about Woods,
just mostly about him.
</P>
<P>
   Woods' emergence as the central personality of professional golf
has helped other golfers reap the benefits of higher ratings and
greater prize money. His sudden renown and success in 1997 _
including his transcendent Masters victory _propelled the PGA Tour
to dramatically higher network rights fees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our ratings are better than ever, even when Tiger's not
there,'' said Donna Orender, the PGA Tour's senior vice president
of television. ``People like to see Tiger, but they like to see the
rest of our players. Tiger being the biggest factor is not wrong;
but there are positives all around.''
</P>
<P>
   True, but the stories are less riveting and spread among several
golfers. When David Duval won the TPC last year, the final round
rating rose 5 percent from the year before. At the Houston Open,
Stuart Appleby's victory pushed the rating up 9 percent. When Olin
Browne took The Colonial on CBS, the rating jumped 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But consider that during Woods' six-tournament winning streak,
which started last August at the World Series of Golf and ended at
the Buick Invitational last month, ratings for the Sunday rounds
increased at an accelerated pace.
</P>
<P>
   Pebble Beach's rain-delayed third round saw a 50 percent ratings
leap, even though it was not a deciding round; Woods would need a
ferocious charge the next day to win. (In 1999, he finished 53rd.)
At the Mercedes Championship in January, his victory yielded a 3.5
rating for ESPN, 75 percent above a year ago, when he finished tied
for fifth.
</P>
<P>
   And at the Tour Championship, Woods' victory generated a 3.2
rating on ABC, up 68 percent from 1998 when he finished 20th in the
pack.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Well before Woods turned pro, golf's upscale demographics made
buying time on tournaments worthwhile to advertisers of golf
equipment and broader-based products like insurance, cars and
computeres. Bob Igiel, president of the broadcast division of The
Media Edge, a unit of Young &AMP; Rubicam, said Woods has ``reawakened
younger viewers toward golf and people who never watched golf.''
</P>
<P>
   For companies like AT&AMP;T, United Airlines and Metropolitan Life,
for whom Igiel purchases time on golf telecasts, Woods'
pre-eminence has helped make prudent buys smarter. Said Igiel:
``There are certain premier attractions in golf that are even more
attractive because of Tiger, bigger purses, and better golfers,
which translate into higher prices paid for golf advertising.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``There's still value in tournaments where he doesn't
appear, but it's better to have him there, in contention.''
</P>
<P>
   But an advertiser would certainly prefer buying into the
Woods-driven Buick Invitational's 8.0 rating on Feb. 13, than the
2.9 for the Phoenix Open on Jan. 30, when Woods did not compete and
when golf had to compete with ABC's Super Bowl pre-game show.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The benefits of being planets in Woods' orbit prevents CBS, NBC
and ABC from moaning that his presence on a competitor beats their
programming. Since all three networks telecast golf, they know
they'll get their crack at exploiting his frequent visits on
tournament leaderboards. CBS, with the most events, receives the
most Tiger nourishment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that he's doing so much to improve the stature of
golf outweighs the fact that he might be hurting our individual
ratings,'' McManus said. ``So you're not totally disheartened when
he beats us while playing on another network. If he plays
remarkably well at the TPC on NBC, a lot of commentary will focus
on how he'll do two weeks later at the Masters, which we have.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Said Ebersol: ``If you love sports, you love it even if it
causes you some discomfort. What's great about sports is that it's
an unscripted drama. What Tiger does is make the unscripted drama
especially delicious.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-03-00 2039EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000303.0300 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-03 20:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6254 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GORE-ART-NYT &LR;      03-03 0776
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JESSE JACKSON HOPES TO UNITE GORE AND BRADLEY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Ga.)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT1 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Rev. Jesse Jackson, who has mediated several
international incidents and won the release of hostages, says he
wants to build a ``bridge'' between the Gore and Bradley campaigns,
although he added that it would be ``presumptuous and premature''
to offer to do so now.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, the civil rights leader who endorsed Vice President Al
Gore on Wednesday, said in an interview that he understood what it
was like to lose, having lost two presidential campaigns himself.
And he said he wanted to be sensitive to the ``withdrawal process''
that former Sen. Bill Bradley might have to undergo if he fares
poorly in the many presidential primaries on March 7.
</P>
<P>
   But, Jackson said, ``I do have a lot of friends on both sides,''
adding that he would like to serve as the ``bridge'' when it comes
time to bring the Democratic Party together.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Hauser, Bradley's spokesman, said he was unaware of any
outreach so far from Jackson or the Gore campaign, but he did not
scoff at Jackson's comments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our focus is March 7 and beyond, and we are competing very
hard to do well on March 7 and take off and go from there,'' Hauser
said. Jackson's desire to mediate a rapprochement between the two
candidates, he said, ``is not relevant right today, although Bill
Bradley has a lot of respect for Jesse Jackson.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson himself offered effusive praise for Bradley, adding:
``He got people involved who have never been involved before, and
we must maintain his involvement.''
</P>
<P>
   Democratic officials said that Jackson's desire to help bring
Bradley into the Gore fold partly explained why Jackson's
endorsement of Gore came at a time when it seemed designed not to
get maximum media exposure _ five minutes before the start of the
candidate's debate Wednesday night in Los Angeles. They said that
the endorsement had long seemed inevitable, but that Jackson did
not want to do it in a high-profile way that would alienate
Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson also noted that Gore himself had lost a presidential
campaign _ in 1988, losing primaries to Jackson _ and that Gore too
was sensitive to the process that Bradley might have to go through.
``He has been there himself,'' Jackson said of Gore. ``He couldn't
get traction, and he had to go through a withdrawal process.''
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, Jackson said, it would be too early for him to
approach Bradley now. But the March 7 primary states, including New
York and California, all seem poised to go overwhelmingly for Gore
and could prove decisive for Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   The concern in the Gore camp at the moment is making sure that
even with his nomination seeming like a foregone conclusion, his
supporters still get to the polls.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Gore and his campaign have swung into high gear to
get out the vote. For the Democrats, that means paying special
attention to blacks, labor, gays and various ethnic groups.
</P>
<P>
   Gore is courting them all in these last days before March 7, and
aiming television and radio commercials at each group.
</P>
<P>
   March 7 is not only primary day in several states but the 35th
anniversary of the historic civil rights march in Alabama from
Selma to Montgomery. Gore will mark the occasion by appearing by
satellite from Washington at a church service in Alabama on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   As he moves through each media market, Gore counts on local
endorsements, like that Friday of Rep. Corrine Brown, a Democrat
from Jacksonville, Fla., which came when Gore spoke at a black high
school there.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vice president not only talks the talk but also walks the
walk on our issues,'' Brown told the students.
</P>
<P>
   Later, in Atlanta, as he visited Chanterelle's restaurant, Gore
posed with numerous black patrons, including some students, about
whom he enthused: ``These students are from Morehouse and Spelman,
the greatest colleges in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   A 60-second radio commercial in New York touts Gore's record on
civil rights and his support for affirmative action. It features
prominent blacks like Rep. Charles Rangel, a Democrat from Harlem,
and the state comptroller, Carl McCall.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps somewhat surprisingly, Jackson, who is planning to make
radio commercials for Gore, will concentrate on the labor vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't need him to get the black vote,'' said one campaign
official. ``Gore can do that. He'll do liberals, progressives and
labor.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
