<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-03 20:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6260 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV05-B     03-03 1273
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV05-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BICOASTAL GOOD DEED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, March 05, 2000)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For all their seeming simplicity _ dorms, classrooms, playing
fields, and Old Main _ universities have long been very complicated
places, fiercely proud of their role as producers and conservators
and arbiters of knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   So the ruckus was no surprise in 1982 when scientific instrument
entrepreneur Jack (Edwin C.) Whitehead tried to give away a fortune
to establish a research institute that would be in the university
but not completely of it, more focussed on basic research than on
teaching. Duke turned him down, several others took a pass. At the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology, a reliable minority kicked
up a fuss.
</P>
<P>
   Legend has it that Nobel laureate David Baltimore indicated he
would leave the biology department if MIT didn't seize the day.
(Thirty years earlier, MIT had taken a pass on the semiconducting
properties of silicon, and Robert Noyce had moved to California.)
The faculty overwhelmingly embraced the deal. And so the Whitehead
was established in 1982 with a grant of $132 million.
</P>
<P>
   Within a few years, lightning struck. A rapid series of
breakthroughs became a revolution; the new field of molecular
genetics was born. Some of its most important tools were devised by
a man who was at MIT only because of the peculiar strength of
Whitehead Institute.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Lander was a mathematician who had learned molecular
biology evenings while teaching entrepreneurial finance at Harvard
Business School. Baltimore hired him _ no biology department would
have seated him without a degree _ and before long Lander and
molecular biologist David Botstein were devising new ways of
mapping fragments of genes that in due course led to the project to
map the human genome.
</P>
<P>
   So it is not without significance that last week computer
publishing moguls Patrick and Lore Harp McGovern committed $350
million over the next 20 years to establish a McGovern Institute
for Brain Research at MIT, modelled on the lines of the Whitehead.
</P>
<P>
   McGovern is founder and chairman of the privately-held
International Data Group, the world's leading computing publisher,
market research and exposition firm. His wife is a successful
venture capitalist wife in her own right. An annual Forbes magazine
survey places them among the 200 wealthies families in America.
</P>
<P>
   This time there was no fuss. The man tapped to head the McGovern
Institute was Phillip Sharp, a biologist who had been a firm
(though not romantic) supporter of the Whitehead. ``You have to
realize that the idea is to set up an institute with a big
endowment and taking three of our best and most notable biologists
to start it,'' Sharp told science journalist Philip Hilts at the
time. ``They will be adding 20 more people on the faculty. So, for
the 43 of us left behind, your power and influence is going to be
diluted.''
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Sharp has become a Most-Notable himself; he shared
the the Nobel Prize in 1993 for his discovery of surplus DNA and
gene splicing. Presumably no one would argue today that the
Whitehead had done the university or the biology more harm than
good.
</P>
<P>
   A twenty-year boom, scientific as well as economic, has changed
the climate of opinion nearly completely. Thus the McGoverns,
advised by a panel of scientists headed by David Baltimore,
interviewed seven schools over a period of three years. All of them
responded enthusiastically.
</P>
<P>
   Brain science is widely believed to be on the brink of explosive
growth, thanks to dramatic advances in imaging technology,
computational power and molecular genetics. Proposals were
solicited for MIT and Columbia University in the East, and Stanford
University, California Institute of Technology, and University of
California campuses in San Francisco, Berkeley, and San Diego in
the West.
</P>
<P>
   McGovern's roots are in the East. (Lore McGovern was raised in
Germany) He grew up in Philadelphia, graduated from MIT with the
class of 1959, and founded his company in Boston. IDG employs some
12,000 in Massachusetts, publishing everything from the ``Computers
for Dummies'' series to ``Computerworld,'' ``PC World'' and ``The
Industry Standard'' among its 290 magazines and newspapers, not to
mention reams of market research.
</P>
<P>
   But the couple lives in San Francisco. (``Pat himself lives on a
plane'' says a friend.)
</P>
<P>
   California apparently mounted a very strong bid _ especially San
Francisco, where UCSF chancellor and Nobel laureate Michael Bishop
presides over a new 43-acre campus being built on old railyards on
the city's southeast side along Mission Bay.
</P>
<P>
   The man who apparently made the difference was Abraham Siegel,
long-time dean of MIT's Sloan School. It was Siegel who smoothed
the negotiations with the Whitehead family in 1981, making the case
to MIT that the Whitehead children should remain involved, making
the case to Whitehead that MIT should have seats on the Institute's
board. He filled one himself for many years. And it was Siegel who
got the McGoverns involved with the Whitehead several years ago,
before they had any idea of attempting to clone it.
</P>
<P>
   What was wanted was an organization with the same strengths as
the Whitehead. ``We have the luxury of investing in young
scientists, and we take a lot of chances that might be considered
too far out for government funding,'' says Whitehead director
Gerald Fink. ``We only supply seed money, enough to get a lab
started. After that, investigators have to attract their own
grants, from government or industry. You can eat up a lot of money
if you fund the whole thing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a combination of things,'' says Susan Whitehead, an
attorney who is the Whitehead's chairperson. ``Strong leadership. A
lot of community-building. We have a lot of stars, and stars can
get temperamental if they don't know each other, each others'
families very well. And of course the science has been moving at an
incredible pace.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitehead members are all obligated to teach; many do so in
MIT's mandatory freshman year course. ``You can't tell them apart''
from members of the bioloogy department,'' said Paul Joskow, a
member of the Institute's board.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the McGovern Institue will not enjoy quite the same
arrangement. This time MIT drove a harder bargain. The university
will own the land, supply the building, pay the staff. But the
basic architecture of the McGovern Institute is the same: a core of
15 or 20 principal investigators with faculty appointments at MIT,
and more than 300 postdoctoral fellows, graduate students and
undergraduates from around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most creative of all, the Brain Institute sticks it
pretty good to Harvard University, a couple miles down the street
from MIT. After years of relative neglect, Harvard recently had
begun scrambling to catch up in the neurosciences, behind the
leadership of Arts and Sciences dean Jeremy Knowles. Large sums
were budgeted. Some 166 scientists from all over the immense
university have been loosely yoked together in a ``Mind, Brain
Behavior Interfaculty Initiative.''
</P>
<P>
   If the McGovern Institute succeeds to anywhere near the degree
of the Whitehead, Harvard will find itself even farther behind. But
then this cheek-by-jowl competition between not-so-friendly rivals
is precisely the mechanism that has kept Boston at the forefront of
modern biology and medicine for fifty years.
</P>
<P>
   (David Warsh writes about economics for The Boston Globe. His
e-mail address is warsh(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
