<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON PEOPLE AND PERSONALITIES  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 5) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Never Mind the Watch. Stock Options Are Golden. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What do you give the retiring chief executive who has
everything? A gold watch? A Caribbean cruise? How about a bundle of
stock options worth more than $30 million?
</P>
<P>
   The American Express Co. gave Harvey Golub, its chairman and
chief executive, options on 750,000 shares of stock last March,
according to a proxy statement filed last week that valued the
``special award'' at $30.9 million.
</P>
<P>
   The options raised Golub's total pay to about $52 million. He
got an additional $38 million from exercising other options the
company had granted.
</P>
<P>
   A company spokesman said the options rewarded Golub for a job
well done and gave him ``an incentive to stay during the
transition.'' Golub, 60, will give up his job as chief executive to
Kenneth I. Chenault, the president, in April 2001, and his
chairman's post a year later. Chenault, 48, received options worth
$16.5 million plus stock worth $4.9 million, raising his 1999 pay
to about $32 million.
</P>
<P>
   Until not that long ago, companies stopped granting options to
executives about five years before they retired, said Graef
Crystal, a compensation consultant. Now, more boards hand them out
as going-away presents, or, as in Chenault's case, coming-in
presents. These days, Crystal says, ``there's always a cause for
celebration in the world of executive compensation.''
</P>
<P>
   _Patrick McGeehan &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   From Highways to Runways &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After building cars for more than 40 years, Harold A. Poling,
the former chairman of Ford, is taking on a new job. Poling, once
an avid pilot, will announce Monday that he is becoming chairman of
the Eclipse Aviation Corp., a fledgling company in Scottsdale,
Ariz., that will build small jets, primarily for executives.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was involved in business, the use of airplanes was
essential,'' Poling said. ``But I became a little concerned at Ford
that we were spending so much on the company jet and not have very
many people on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite Poling's new job, part of his attention remains with
Ford. Of particular concern is Ford's stock, which fell to
$41.0625, a 52-week low, on Wednesday, before recovering to
$42.6875 on Friday. ``Aside from the stock, Ford is doing great,''
Poling said. ``But investors are not interested now in auto stocks.
They're caught up in the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   _David J. Morrow &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Millionaires on Board &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Forget the annual bake sale. Elite private schools, stocking
their boards with wizards of finance and technology, are now
gathering the sort of million-dollar-plus donations long enjoyed by
universities.
</P>
<P>
   The Crossroads School for Arts and Sciences in Los Angeles,
having received $2 million from its board chairman, Peter Norton
(as in Norton Utilities), named a separate campus, with a new
elementary school and sports center, as the Norton Campus last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Fiona Biggs Druckenmiller, once a star fund manager at Dreyfus,
and her husband, Stanley Druckenmiller, chief investment strategist
for George Soros, have made donations to the Spence School in
Manhattan that total about $10 million. Druckenmiller is a Spence
alumna and board member. Leon Black, the financier, joined the
Spence board last year. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _Victoria Goldman &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Same Tory, New Chapter &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Having held almost every job that matters in British government,
except one, Michael Heseltine, the former deputy prime minister,
now has a publishing empire to run. Still a member of parliament,
Heseltine became chairman of his family's Haymarket Publishing
Group after the Conservative Party lost in the 1997 elections. Now,
he has his own foreign policy, concentrating on Hong Kong and the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   In New York recently to be host of an awards dinner for 1,000
public relations people, he described how Haymarket had gone from
selling its medical reference books in the United States, beginning
about 10 years ago, to publishing an American edition of PRWeek in
late 1998, to starting an American edition of Revolution, a
magazine about online marketing, this week.
</P>
<P>
   Isn't e-anything a crowded field? He dismisses the investing
craze as ``a gold rush.'' But he says that public relations
executives like Richard Edelman asked him to bring PRWeek to the
United States, and that Revolution answers similar demands.
</P>
<P>
   At 66, with the tall stature and shaggy mane that brought him
the nickname ``Tarzan,'' Heseltine has other United States ventures
in store. ``I can't see the point of retiring,'' he said. ``What
would I do?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
