<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-03 20:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6266 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-CANCER-MARROW-BOS &LR;      03-03 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANCER-MARROW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY QUESTIONS BREAST CANCER TREATMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   An aggressive and controversial form of treatment for advanced
breast cancer has been shown to be ineffective, researchers Friday
said in a report that will probably end the practice of combining
high-dose chemotherapy with bone-marrow transplantation.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts law currently requires insurers to cover the
procedure, which was once considered a last hope for women dying of
the disease.
</P>
<P>
   But doctors said they could find no evidence that the procedure
works. In an editorial accompanying a medical journal report that
was rushed into publication Friday, Dr. Marc Lippman, a noted
breast cancer specialist at the Lombardi Cancer Center in
Washington said: ``This form of treatment for women with metastatic
breast cancer. . .has been proved to be ineffective and should be
abandoned'' in favor of other new experimental therapies.
</P>
<P>
   The report was hurriedly posted on the Web site of the New
England Journal of Medicine, which will publish the study in its
April 13 issue.
</P>
<P>
   Survival three years after high-dose chemotherapy and
bone-marrow transplanation was about the same for women who
received four to six cycles of chemotherapy alone at standard
doses.
</P>
<P>
   Studies reported last year had come to much the same conclusion.
But that verdict was clouded with uncertainty because one of the
studies, from South Africa, showed a benefit from high-dose therapy
and transplantation; that study was recently found to contain
fraudulent data.
</P>
<P>
   The New England Journal posted the report urgently because of
confusion created by the falsified study, said Dr. Marcia Angell,
its editor-in-chief.
</P>
<P>
   That study, she said, ``left a lot of concern and confusion
among women and insurers who weren't sure whether to cover it.
</P>
<P>
   The new report, she added, ``is is the best of the studies'' on
the issue ``and it was negative, and we felt that we owed it to the
public'' to air it immediately, said Angell.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Edward A. Stadtmauer, director of bone marrow
transplantation at the University of Pennsylvania Cancer Center,
headed the research group that published the new study, begun in
1990.
</P>
<P>
   All of the volunteers were women with breast cancer that had
metastasized to other parts of the body, but whose disease had been
in check temporarily by standard chemotherapy. The theory behind
the combination treatment is that it might be possible to eradicate
all traces of disease with chemotherapy so potent it would be
lethal if the woman wasn't subsequently given a transplant to
restore her blood-forming tissues.
</P>
<P>
   A total of 110 patients were randomly assigned to the aggressive
treatment while 89 received standard chemo. After three years,
there was no significant difference in survival between the groups
(32 percent in the transplanted patients and 38 percent in the
standard group) or in how long the treatment kept the cancer from
recurring (9.6 months in the aggressive treatment group and 9.0
months in the others.)
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes in large studies, researchers will identify a subset
of women who benefited from a treatment even when the overall group
did not. Dr. John K. Erban, a New England Medical Center cancer
specialist who participated in the study, said in an interview
Friday that there was no subgroup that clearly benefited, but that
the study might ``not be the final word'' because some very small
set of patients might still be found to do better with the
transplants.
</P>
<P>
   Erban also said that a transplant might be a reasonable option
for women with metastatic disease that can only be held in check by
indefinite standard chemotherapy. ``There might be quality of
life'' advantages to the transplant, he said.
</P>
<P>
   However, Erban said that the study ``is going to very much, and
appropriately, limit the number of times when it should be
recommended.''
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of the report's conclusions, Massachusetts insurers
still have to cover bone marrow transplants if the doctor and
patient request it.
</P>
<P>
   But those requests may well decline. ``I think we're going to
see, hopefully, no physicians recommending this treatment,'' said
Dr. Kurt Sligar, chief medical officer for Blue Cross/Blue Shield
of Massachusetts. He said that numbers of the procedures, which
cost $50,000 to $100,000, have declined in recent months.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
