<SLUG> BC-DEMS-LEDE0304-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bradley rips Gore on China, arms pacts
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PROVIDENCE, R.I. _ In a lengthy foreign policy speech Friday,
Democrat Bill Bradley said rogue nuclear powers and a destabilized
Russian nation pose the greatest threats to national security.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley criticized the Clinton-Gore administration for failing
to ensure the safekeeping of Soviet nuclear weapons material and
for being the ``first four-year government since the 1960s not to
conclude even one nuclear arms treaty.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have squandered an opportunity of historic proportions,''
Bradley told students and faculty at Brown University here.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley also criticized Gore individually for telling labor
leaders recently that the agreement bringing China into the World
Trade Organization needed to be strengthened to safeguard workers.
Gore acted ``for short-term political gain,'' Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley suggested Gore's statements to labor could torpedo the
deal, a stated priority of the Clinton administration and of many
major business groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``Apart from stoking Chinese antipathy, it probably capsized one
of the most significant agreements this country has ever signed,''
Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to the accusation, Gore spokesman Doug Hattaway said
the vice president ``made it clear that he supports this agreement
and wants Congress to act on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hattaway also criticized Bradley's own foreign policy record,
noting he supported aid to the Nicaraguan Contras in the 1980s and
opposed the congressional resolution authorizing U.S. intervention
in Kuwait in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley opened his speech by lamenting the fact that foreign
policy no longer is a central part of running for president. ``It
almost makes you nostalgic for what campaigns used to be about,''
Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
   Turning to the substance of his remarks, Bradley said U.S.
foreign policy around the world must be clear, consistent and
founded on a trust between the president and the American people.
</P>
<P>
   He said the United States should use diplomatic muscle
aggressively, but military force sparingly. Quoting the late
President Kennedy when he was a Massachusetts senator, Bradley said
the United States could not be the world's ``firefighter.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley called for military force when U.S. interests are
threatened and, in some cases, when humanitarian tragedies occur
around the world. He said the use of force for humanitarian reasons
is justified only when there are no other options and U.S. victory
is assured.
</P>
<P>
   The United States also must work to preserve strong relations
with Russia, China, Mexico, Japan and the countries of the European
Union, he said.
</P>
<P>
   With respect to China, Bradley said the world's most populous
nation should be given permanent, normal trading relations with the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
