r l BC-HEALTH-DRIVING-STRESS     03-03 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-DRIVING-STRESS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAS, BRAKE, BREATHE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By EVAN HENERSON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Keys? Check. Snack? Check. Foreign language tape? Cheque.
Aromatherapy air freshener? Uh, OK, why not? If it works for you,
go for it.
</P>
<P>
   Throw in general peace of mind and a non-aggressive temperament,
and now, say the experts, you're ready for the daily traffic grind.
You're road-worthy.
</P>
<P>
   So many of us in Southern California have a
longer-than-civilized daily commute to and from work. And on Los
Angeles freeways, one of our lovely traffic snarls can instantly
double what is normally a 45-minute ride.
</P>
<P>
   The rules for a daily commute don't differ substantially whether
your commute is five minutes or 90 minutes. Most of the rules
involve the use of common sense, and your neighborhood Department
of Motor Vehicles office _ or, if you're unlucky, CHP officer _
will be more than happy to remind you what they are: Watch the
road, don't drive when angry or sleepy, obey the speed limit, no
using cell phones while driving ... yada, yada, yada.
</P>
<P>
   Most of us can't significantly change the amount of time we
spend on the road, but here are a few ways psychiatrists and
traffic experts say you can make that time a little less painful.
</P>
<P>
   Happy driving. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR;  &QL; 
PRE-ROAD PREPARATION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   It's a luxury most of us don't possess, but psychiatrists say
the better prepared you are mentally before you get behind the
wheel, the more comfortable and relaxed you'll be on the drive.
That could mean a series of stretches, meditation or even a prayer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking about people's mental health,'' says Dr. Lourdes
Villegas, a psychotherapist at Kaiser Permanente's Imperial Medical
Offices in Bellflower. ``If you're already stressed, whatever
happens on the road is going to make you twice as stressed. Put it
into perspective: `This is only 45 minutes. This is not my whole
life.'''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, get calm, get centered _ and then get going. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR;  &QL; 
AT HOME IN YOUR CAR &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Keep your vehicle at your comfort level. Know your ideal
temperature and seat settings. Use a pillow or other means of
support if it helps your comfort. Or an air freshener if a certain
scent makes you feel better.
</P>
<P>
   Just don't make things so relaxing that you'll doze off at the
wheel. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR;  &QL; 
THE ROUTE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Find an alternate way (or ways) to get to and from work. Do this
not to save time _ although that could happen _ but to vary your
routine and mix in a change of scenery. An ugly drive is an ugly
drive, which can get depressing. Study new neighborhoods that you
might pass through. Know the territory between your home and your
office in case you're ever forced to make a stop.
</P>
<P>
   You can make the journey even more challenging by trying to
memorize street names and other landmarks. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR;  &QL; 
THE ROAD/TAPE OR CD PLAYERS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Our cars now come with VCRs, and navigation systems and vehicle
Internet access aren't far behind, but any traffic expert will tell
you that your stereo system is the ONLY part of your car that
should be allowed to distract you while you're driving. Granted,
talking on a cell phone, shaving or eating might help break up the
time, but those activities can also cause accidents. The radio is
safe, provided you're not fumbling for CDs when you should be
changing lanes.
</P>
<P>
   Choose your listening carefully. Since the name of the game is
comfort and relaxation, watch out for the type of music that gets
your heart pounding or your blood rushing. Aggressive music can,
experts say, put you in an aggressive mood, which is not what you
want when you're behind the wheel.
</P>
<P>
   Many people recommend books on tape. Travel and foreign language
tapes can aid those who need to feel they're actually accomplishing
something while being stuck in the quicksand that is the 405
freeway.
</P>
<P>
   If the radio is your entertainment of choice, make sure you know
a place to find reliable traffic reports. ``I would try to find a
station that doesn't make you feel more tense and stressed out than
you might ordinarily be,'' says Sandra Ball-Rokeach, professor of
communications and sociology at USC and an expert in traffic-injury
prevention. ``Too many people I find are stuck on the freeway. Very
few people just get off and take a surface route.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR;  &QL; 
YOUR ROADMATES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   No matter how slowly you think they're driving, or how close
they came when they nearly cut you off, people in the other cars on
the road are not out to get you and have no real interest in
ruining your commute. Once you understand this principle,
psychologists say, you will have beaten road rage. Then nothing
that happens on the road can touch you.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to want a peaceful drive,'' says Dr. Arnold
Nerenberg, a clinical psychologist and authority on road rage.
``You've never seen these people before, and you'll probably never
see them again. Do you want to turn control of your emotions over
to them? To those people who you call `idiots'? Most people
don't.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-03-00 2052EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000303.0308 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-03 20:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6275 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-MCCAIN-SENATE-2TAKES-     03-03 1064
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-SENATE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
  
 McCAIN'S SENATE RECORD: CONSERVATIVE, BUT NOT IDEOLOGICAL  
 (bl)  
 By ADAM CLYMER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ At one level, John McCain has been a model of
conservative Republican orthodoxy in his 13 years in the Senate,
with a voting record close to that of Jesse Helms, who sets the
standard for Senate conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's career gets an 85 from the American Conservative Union,
a 9 from the liberal Americans for Democratic Action and an 89 from
the National Right to Life Committee. Helms, the dean of Senate
conservatives, gets 99 from the ACU, 3 from the ADA and 99 from
Right to Life.
</P>
<P>
   But a Senate career is more than just showing up to vote. And a
review of McCain's record shows that, by subtler measures, his
interests, even passions, are hardly ideological. His biggest
continuing concern has been the armed forces _ not necessarily in
giving them what they want, but what he thinks they need.
</P>
<P>
   His most striking achievement came when he joined with another
Vietnam veteran, Sen. John Kerry, D-Mass., to puncture the myth
that Vietnam continued holding U.S. prisoners. The pair then worked
to get Senate approval of an end to the trade embargo against
Vietnam. That led to the start of diplomatic relations in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The McCain passion which on its face seems most conservative,
and is certainly unorthodox Senate behavior, is his insistent
opposition to pork barrel spending. He is especially hostile to the
variety of pork in which an influential senator quietly gets some
money ``earmarked'' for a particular local interest, like a
university or a hospital, without going through the peer review
that governs most federal grants.
</P>
<P>
   For years that opposition drew attention but usually lost in the
Senate. But this week, Gov. George W. Bush's campaign seized on
earmarked grants that McCain opposed, in the form of $104 million
for a breast cancer program at New York University, and another $1
million for the program at the North Shore-Long Island Jewish
Health system, to contend that he opposed breast cancer research in
general.
</P>
<P>
   Legislatively, McCain's highly visible losses on campaign
finance and the tobacco settlement overshadow not only the Vietnam
effort but also his substantive but less than striking
accomplishments as chairman of the Commerce Committee since 1995,
his work for Indian tribes and his success in getting a line item
veto law passed in 1996. The Supreme Court has found the law, which
allowed presidents to veto specific pieces of spending measures,
unconstitutional, and McCain blames himself for losing control of
its language. He still calls it his proudest achievement: ``If we
could have kept it, it would have had the most profound effect on
the legislative process.''
</P>
<P>
   Passing campaign finance or the tobacco measure, though, involve
a degree of difficulty so high that if McCain had succeeded, he
would have been seen as a legislative magician, an achiever on the
level of Sen. Edward M. Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   Those huge issues aside, it seems clear that McCain's success in
the Senate has been limited by his temperament in two ways. There
is no question that he sometimes loses potential allies by his
penchant for telling off other senators. One friend, Sen. Thad
Cochran, R-Miss., said, ``He's not afraid to embarrass people and
go after people.'' The Senate, after all, remains an institution
where the bitterest enemies call each other ``my distinguished
friend.''
</P>
<P>
   In a larger sense, McCain is an impatient man _ perhaps because
he lost five years of his life as a prisoner of war _ in an
institution that worships delay and rewards endurance.
</P>
<P>
   After 13 years in the Senate, today McCain is involved in a
presidential race in which he somehow appeals not only to moderate
Republicans but even to liberal Democrats, and in which Republican
enemies have labeled him a ``moderate'' with liberal tendencies.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the basis of those labels, it's not McCain's voting
record, which also include a career 15 percent rating from the
AFL-CIO and a 28 from the League of Conservation Voters (for whom
his dedication to the Grand Canyon is outweighed by his commitment
to environmental deregulation generally).
</P>
<P>
   The phenomenon is clearest on abortion. Intensity matters.
Douglas Johnson, legislative director of the National Right to Life
Committee, supplied the 89 percent rating. But he said that while
votes mattered, they were not everything, and the group feared that
``if elected president, Mr. McCain would be unlikely to use the
office's powers to advance the pro-life cause.'' He cited
statements made by McCain which, he said, acknowledged that
abortion was a ``necessary evil.'' Whether or not that view is
fair, it is clear that neither in the Senate nor in his
presidential campaign has McCain sought to lead the anti-abortion
movement.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's heroic military career and ex-POW status made him an
obvious choice to serve with Kerry, a Silver Star veteran who
turned against the war, on the special committee that examined the
POW-MIA issue. On Jan. 13, 1993, he concluded ``I have seen no
evidence that convinces me that there are Americans alive, or that
there are likely Americans alive'' in captivity.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's concern over prisoners carries over to current members
of the armed services. On the Armed Services Committee, he has
worked to improve pay and benefits for active duty personnel and
veterans. But he has also challenged major weapons spending, such
as the Seawolf submarine, C-130 transports and B-2 bombers. In
committee, said Cochran, ``he was rather hard on the military. He
made them talk about what they really needed.''
</P>
<P>
   That posture led to his frequent criticism of pork-barrel
spending _ a McCain target not confined to military budgets but one
where the Pentagon figured large. He tangled with House Speaker
Newt Gingrich, Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott and even
Appropriations Committee chairman Ted Stevens, R-Alaska, over money
matters they slipped into bills.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has not won any big floor fights over pork barrel
spending. But even Stevens says his opposition has been useful,
since it can be used to scare off some greedy members. ``We've sort
of used him as the bogey-man,'' said Stevens, with warnings that:
``If you do that, McCain will be after you.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But it is not an issue which wins McCain friends. His web site,
www.itsyourcountry.com, lists spending that he considers
outrageous, not by sponsoring senator, but by state, which is close
enough. Items like ``$750,000 for grasshopper research in Alaska''
or ``$1 million for rehabilitation of a U-505 submarine at the
Museum of Science and Industry in Chicago, Illinois'' have easily
discernible parentage.
</P>
<P>
   Some of McCain's colleagues call him a hypocrite for attacking
their projects while pushing for goodies for Arizona. He has argued
that the difference is that he seeks his projects openly, through
hearings, while others add theirs in the dead of night.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, he has merged his attacks on campaign finance
with attacks on pork. ``Pork barrel spending is a direct result of
unlimited contributions from special interests,'' his web site
maintains. When combined with the list of projects, that charge
implies that senators who get listed projects for their state has
been bought.
</P>
<P>
   Republican senators who don't like McCain's campaign bill don't
like that implication either, and they harangued him over it the
last time the campaign finance bill came up, in October 1999. One
who took particular offense was Sen. Robert F. Bennett, R-Utah, who
got $2.2 million earmarked to help build sewers for the 2002 Winter
Olympics in Salt Lake City. He demanded that McCain tell him what
``soft money'' influenced him. McCain did not answer directly but
just complained that the money had been sneaked into a bill.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's own party revolted against his tobacco settlement bill,
which would have increased the price of a pack of cigarettes by
$1.10 a pack, and filibustered it to death in 1998. It had gone
through the Commerce Committee easily, but the tobacco industry ran
millions o dollars of ads attacking it before it died.
</P>
<P>
   McCain became an advocate of campaign spending law changes after
what he has called his worst mistake in the Senate _ attending a
meeting with regulators in which Charles Keating, a constituent and
contributor, sought leniency from savings and loan regulators. The
Ethics Committee eventually found he did no more than exhibit bad
judgment, but its partisan proceedings were an ordeal he has called
worse than captivity in hanoi.
</P>
<P>
   For four years, McCain and Sen. Russell Feingold, D-Wis., have
together sought to ban ``soft money,'' the unlimited contributions
from rich people, corporations and unions which dominate
presidential and congressional elections, and to curb the use of
``issue ads'' which interest groups buy to influence elections
(anti-abortion and tobacco groups ran ads against him in South
Carolina.)
</P>
<P>
   Norman J. Ornstein, a congressional scholar at the American
Enterprise Institute and a supporter of the campaign legislation,
said ``I've worked with him pretty closely on campaign reform. He
has been ``a mix of principle and pragmatism, what you hope for''
in managing the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he has never won the support of more than eight
Republicans, and in a Senate with 45 Democrats, that is seven short
of the number needed to break a filibuster.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-03-00 2055EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
