</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRIDIUM-BANKRUPTCY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLANS TO RESCUE SATELLITE PHONE COMPANY ARE DROPPED 
</HEADLINE>
  (ko) 
 By DAVID BARBOZA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Cellular telephone pioneer Craig McCaw said Friday
that he was dropping plans to acquire Iridium, the troubled global
satellite telephone company that filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy
protection last August.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, McCaw's private investment group, Eagle River
Investments, said the company had decided to focus its investing on
satellite services that had high-speed data capabilities.
</P>
<P>
   The decision comes as a serious blow to Iridium, which was
counting on McCaw's money and reputation in the wireless
communications world to save an ambitious $5 billion satellite
telephone service that had once promised to communicate ``with
anyone, anytime, anywhere in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street analysts say the move leaves Iridium on the brink of
collapse. On Monday, the company is scheduled to lose access to $5
million in emergency financing under a bankruptcy court agreement.
Motorola said Friday that its agreement to operate the service
would also expire on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the death blow,'' said Armand Musey, an analyst at
Banc of America Securities. ``It looks like even at a ridiculously
low cost structure McCaw doesn't think it's worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   Iridium, which is based in Washington, issued a statement Friday
saying it was still committed to a sale of its assets, which McCaw
was expected to bid on to form a separate company.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have received expression of interest from other potential
buyers,'' said Randall Brouckman, the company's chief operating
officer. The company did not disclose the names of other interested
parties.
</P>
<P>
   Industry experts said they were surprised by McCaw's decision
because it came less than a month after he had agreed to provide
$74.6 million in emergency financing to Iridium. Eagle River and
Motorola, which helped develop the Iridium system, have already
made $5 million in emergency financing available.
</P>
<P>
   McCaw said his aim in rescuing Iridium was to restore confidence
in the satellite industry and to create a network of satellite
systems that included Iridium, ICO Global Communications _ which he
is also trying to rescue from bankruptcy _ and Teledesic, the
``Internet in the sky'' satellite system that is expected to be
ready by 2004.
</P>
<P>
   But on Friday, McCaw said he had revised his strategy to focus
primarily on delivering data capabilities through ICO and
Teledesic. Iridium is a narrow-band service primarily intended for
voice and paging services.
</P>
<P>
   Several analysts said McCaw's change of heart was unusual and
could be a negotiating ploy or a sign that his due diligence turned
up troubling details at Iridium.
</P>
<P>
   But Eagle River officials said the decision was primarily
strategic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We explored Iridium, and we did a very thorough review of the
assets, and we decided it was just best to stick with Teledesic and
ICO,'' said Roger Nyhus, a spokesman at Eagle River in Bellevue,
Wash. ``This is a final decision.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman at Motorola, which developed the Iridium system and
took huge charges against earnings in the last two years because of
Iridium's difficulties, said the company regretted the
announcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are disappointed to hear that Eagle River decided not to
bid on Iridium's assets,'' said Scott Wyman, a spokesman at
Motorola, which is based in Schaumburg, Ill. ``From our perspective
the future of Iridium now rests with the bankruptcy court.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say Motorola is unlikely to rescue the company, which
it helped found. Iridium has not paid Motorola to operate the
system since November 1998, and the company recently told reporters
that it would not bid on the assets.
</P>
<P>
   Motorola has also taken a hard line on the company, saying it
would not provide additional aid unless the company reorganized its
operations and attracted substantial financing.
</P>
<P>
   The problem for Iridium, which began offering service in early
1999, has been a dearth of subscribers. Many also complained of
bulky telephones, operational glitches and expensive service.
Iridium recently said it had about 50,000 subscribers. At one
point, there were estimates of 42 million subscribers by 2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``This McCaw deal never made sense to me,'' said Andrew Cole, a
vice president at Renaissance Worldwide, a consulting firm that has
worked with Iridium. He said that Iridium was incompatible with ICO
and Teledesic and that it had no data capabilities. ``To do what
McCaw would like to do, he'd have to rip the thing apart and then
start over.''
</P>
</TEXT>
