<HEADER>
A6279 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-INDEPENDENT-ADS-ART-N     03-03 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDEPENDENT-ADS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH CONTRIBUTOR CLAIMS RESPONSIBILITY FOR `MYSTERY' COMMERCIALS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, N.Y., Calif., Ohio)  (Eds: 2nd take is scheduled to move by 9:30 p.m. ET) 
(ART ADV: Photos NYT6, N0 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON with RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A wealthy Texas businessman who is one of Gov.
George W. Bush's biggest campaign contributors said Friday that he
had paid $2.5 million for political commercials that sharply
criticized Sen. John McCain and promoted Bush's environmental
record.
</P>
<P>
   The businessman, Sam Wyly, who recently sold two software
companies he co-owned for $7.9 billion, said that he and his family
had paid for the advertising, whose source had been a mystery in
recent days, to highlight environmental issues at a time when the
public is paying attention to the presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain's aides accused the Bush campaign of being behind the
advertising and called the ads a scurrilous attempt to evade
campaign finance laws. They said the Bush campaign was trying to
steal the election by placing a huge amount of anti-McCain
advertising on the air in New York, California and Ohio just days
before primaries in those states that could decide the outcome of
the Republican presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   The law is somewhat fuzzy when it comes to advertising about
political issues paid for by people or groups outside of a
campaign, with money that is not disclosed as a contribution. But
it generally bars a candidate from coordinating such an effort with
outside supporters, and it prohibits the commercials from making
direct appeals to vote for or against a particular candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no question in our campaign's mind that the ads are
being sponsored, coordinated and managed by the George Bush for
President campaign,'' Rick Davis, McCain's campaign manager, told
reporters in New York. ``I think it's incumbent on the Bush
campaign to prove somehow that they are not involved in this
incredible act.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis offered no direct evidence to support his assertion, but
cited a tangle of personal, business and political relationships
between Wyly and his family and the Bush campaign to suggest that
their interests were so close as to be indistinguishable.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at a news conference on Long Island, N.Y., Bush denied
any link between Wyly's commercials and his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had no knowledge whatsoever that Sam Wyly was going to run
this ad,'' Bush said. ``There is no coordination. I can't put it
any more plainly to you: I had no idea the ad was going to run.''
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview from Dallas, Wyly had the same message.
Asked if he had had any contact with the Bush campaign, even
indirectly, over the commercials, Wyly said, ``Absolutely not.''
</P>
<P>
   Wyly said that ``of course'' he hoped the commercials would
benefit Bush, but added that he had laughed as the commercials were
being prepared at how surprised Bush and his team would be when
they learned about what he was doing.
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, the episode gave McCain an opportunity to turn
public attention back to the centerpiece of his agenda, an overhaul
of the campaign finance laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think maybe the Bush campaign is out of money and somebody's
putting in $2 million to try to hijack the campaign here in New
York,'' McCain said on the NBC News ``Today'' program before Wyly
revealed his role.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody knows where it came from,'' McCain said. ``We'll
probably find out, but probably too late. This is why campaign
finance reform is so important.''
</P>
<P>
   The commercials open with a picture of McCain superimposed over
smokestacks belching dirty air. The voiceover says that McCain
voted against solar- and renewable-energy programs, leading to
``more use of coal-burning plants that pollute our air.''
</P>
<P>
   The narrator goes on to say that Bush ``led one of the first
states in America to clamp down on old coal-burning electric power
plants,'' and that the Texas governor was ``leading so each day
dawns brighter.''
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists said that the claim that Bush had cut down on
coal-burning plants was exaggerated, and that while McCain had
voted against spending programs to promote solar power and
renewable-energy sources in the case cited, he had also supported
them in other votes.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
