<SLUG> BC-GLF-DORAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BIRDIE BARRAGE ON THE BLUE MONSTER IS LED BY AMES WITH 61  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ For the second consecutive day, players feasted on the
fabled Blue Monster golf course like hungry teen-agers at an
all-you-can-eat buffet.
</P>
<P>
   When the Blue Monster course at Doral Golf Resort and Spa was
remodeled last year and 25 bunkers were removed, it was expected to
play easier than before. But nobody expected Friday's birdie
barrage during the second round of the Doral-Ryder Open.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Ames set the course record with an 11-under-par 61.
Edward Fryatt shot 62, including a string of eight consecutive
birdies, which tied the PGA Tour record. Instead of the usual
strong winds that put teeth in the Blue Monster, conditions
remained calm, and the course looked defenseless. How low can they
go this weekend? If the wind stays away, Greg Norman's 72-hole
record of 23 under par (265) set in 1993 will be in serious
jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   Shooting a nine-under-par 63 to pace a hard-charging field,
Franklin Langham held a three-stroke lead at 15 under par (129)
after Friday's second round. Ames, Vijay Singh, Jim Furyk and
Shigeki Maruyama were tied for second place at 12 under par.
</P>
<P>
   The atmosphere was much different from the past few years at
this tournament, when many players complained after Raymond Floyd
remodeled the course in 1996. Floyd added bunkers and made an
already challenging course more difficult, causing some players to
balk. But the course was remodeled again last year by Jim McLean,
and the new version is far more player-friendly. After Friday, some
may argue that the course is too easy. But most players who were
asked seemed happy with the changes, and attributed the low scores
to the lack of wind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the only reason it lacks the feel of a challenge is
because the wind is not up,'' said Ames, who broke the previous
course record of 62 held by Norman and Furyk. ``If the winds aren't
blowing, it's going to be easy. If it's blowing, it's going to be
tough. You have to accept that one year you're going to have 24
under winning, and the other year, eight under might win.''
</P>
<P>
   Fryatt, a tour rookie, may never have another round like this
one. Starting on No. 4, Fryatt made eight consecutive birdies,
tying the mark established by Bob Goalby in 1961, and equaled by
Fuzzy Zoeller in 1976 and by Dewey Arnette in 1987. Fryatt had a
legitimate chance to make nine consecutive birdies, but his 12-foot
attempt for birdie at No. 12 slid past the hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pretty incredible,'' said Fryatt, who shot 29 on the
front nine. ``I felt like a guy tossing a no-hitter out there.
Nobody was talking to me. When I looked up, every putt was pouring
into the center of the hole. It was eerie.''
</P>
<P>
   After a birdie at No. 14, Fryatt was 10 under par through 14
holes. He could have become only the fourth player in tour history
to shoot 59 if he had finished with three birdies and a par, but
Fryatt bogeyed No. 15 and birdied No. 18 to settle for his 62.
Fryatt gave credit to David Frost, one of his peers on tour, who
gave him a putting lesson on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He changed my grip and it really worked,'' Fryatt said. ``I
have to send a bottle of wine his way. I admit, I was thinking
about 59, but I forgot about it after the bogey at 15. But I have
no complaints with a 62.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-03-00 2102EST &QL; 
