<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-03 21:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6282 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-RIGHTS-MARCH-HNS &LR;      03-03 1455
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RIGHTS-MARCH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATIONAL SPOTLIGHT TO FOCUS ON 35TH ANNIVERSARY OF `BLOODY SUNDAY' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LORI RODRIGUEZ 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SELMA, Ala._ For more than three decades, U.S. congressman John
Lewis has returned every March to this sleepy town on the banks of
the Alabama River to stand on the bridge where state troopers
cracked his skull in an infamous civil rights clash.
</P>
<P>
   Aptly known as ``Bloody Sunday,'' the March 7, 1965, attack on
600 freedom marchers by troopers armed with tear gas, bull whips
and billy clubs riveted the nation. Three weeks later, the Rev.
Martin Luther King Jr. led another voting rights march to
Montgomery, this time 25,000-strong and under the protection of the
Alabama National Guard.
</P>
<P>
   In August, Congress passed the 1965 Voting Rights Act that
banned the poll tax as a requirement to vote and imposed strict
federal oversight of Southern voting laws.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, D-Ga., has returned every year but one, to re-enact the
march across the hulking Edmund Pettus Bridge and most of all ``to
never, ever forget.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, at the 35th commemoration marking that galvanizing
event, he will not come alone. In a media event that precedes the
Georgia primary election on the actual anniversary, Lewis will be
joined by President Clinton, several Cabinet secretaries, 50
members of Congress, the cream of the civil rights community and,
again, attract the national spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   Some believe the city's lingering racial woes and inequities
will be exposed; and some of the country's as well. But this time,
Lewis hopes the major focus will be on how much closer Americans
are to reconciling their differences.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was beaten. I was hit by a night stick. I had a concussion
right there on the bridge. To this day, I don't know how I made it
back to the church where we started,'' recalls Lewis, then a
21-year-old freedom fighter armed with only a backpack.
</P>
<P>
   ``To come from that to where the president of the United States
is going to join us; it is unreal. It is unthinkable.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis' trek to Selma's annual ``Bridge Crossing Jubilee''
intensified three year ago when he and Rep. Amory Houghton, R-N.Y.,
reached across the aisles separating races and political parties to
begin ``conversations on race.'' Working with Washington's Faith
and Politics Institute, Lewis and Houghton now lead other
congressmembers on pilgrimages to what some consider the holy
trinity of the civil rights movement: Birmingham, Montgomery and
Selma.
</P>
<P>
   Before descending on Selma, the group Saturday will tour the
haunting images in the Birmingham Civil Rights Institute and take
the ``Freedom Walk'' around Kelly Ingram Park, where police dogs
and fire hoses were turned on marchers.
</P>
<P>
   In Montgomery, they will contemplate the Civil Rights Memorial,
a black granite tribute to 40 people slain in the struggle, and
visit King's somber Dexter Avenue Baptist Church. Before proceeding
to Selma, they are to attend services at the 16th Street Baptist
Church, Birmingham's first black church and the site of a Sept. 15,
1963, racist bombing that killed four young girls and appalled
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   From the late-1940s until the mid-1960s, nearly 50 unsolved
bombings earned the city the nickname ``Bombingham.'' The 16th
Street pastor, the Rev. Chris Hamlin, says he will tell the
congressmembers that a another kind of tenacious violence still
tears at the black community.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of inequities still exist; a lot of suffering
continues,'' says Hamlin. ``They don't have to look further than
that whole black belt of rural counties around Selma where there
are so few jobs and such deep poverty.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis says congressional members who have joined the pilgrimages
have been profoundly affected. ``Some have compared their visit to
going to the Holy Land. Some have called it a spiritual renewal.
Some have gone and literally cried. Some have just found it
unbelievable,'' says Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis reminds them that measurable strides have been made,
albeit at great human cost. In 1963, says Lewis, blacks and whites
couldn't sit together at lunch counters, drink at the same
fountains, go to the same schools, live in the same neighborhoods
and only 2.5 percent of voting age blacks were registered to vote.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1965, the struggle to vote moved to Selma after the
murder of a young black activist named Jimmy Lee Jackson. The
slaying sparked plans for the 50-mile march to Montgomery that was
turned back by troopers in riot gear, Dallas County Sheriff's
deputies and white vigilantes. On March 9, troopers turned back a
second march led by King after the fatal beating of the activist
Rev. James J. Reeb drew national outrage.
</P>
<P>
   On March 21, under federal protection, King, flanked by Lewis
and other civil rights stalwarts, finally reached Montgomery where
they were joined by 25,000 marchers from across the country.
</P>
<P>
   Five months later, the new legislation allowed blacks to vote
who had never been to the polls and dramatically increased the
number of black elected officials.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the Selma City Council and Dallas County Commissioners
Court are biracial and the police chief and fire chief are black.
</P>
<P>
   Selma still has the same white mayor, Joe Smitherman, who stood
with the troopers as they assaulted the marchers. ``But I went back
to a book signing last year and the mayor presented me to this
biracial audience,'' says Lewis. ``Back then he called me a
trouble-maker and a dangerous man. Today, he calls me a close
friend and a brave man.
</P>
<P>
   ``And it's not just Selma. It's Alabama, it's the South, it's
the country. We're a better nation, we're a better people and at
least in the American South, we're in the process of laying down
the burden of race.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis and Houghton, a white Republican, believe they can bridge
America's racial distances one congressional member at a time. But
until last year, an emblem of the Confederate flag adorned the
pillars and arches that read, ``Welcome to Selma,'' at the foot of
the bridge. Just down Water Street, not far from where Clinton will
address a rally and near the site of a slave trading post and
Confederate munitions plant, blacks live in grinding poverty amid
overgrown lots and rusted vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   More than half of Selma's black children are living in poverty,
says Rose Sanders, founder of the Voting Rights Museum and guiding
spirit behind the 3-day annual jubilee. A carefully planned
interfaith church service Sunday deliberately draws whites and
blacks but few of those whites ever return for the re-enactment.
</P>
<P>
   Whites mainly live alongside whites and the same for blacks.
There is a surface and symbolic sharing of power, says Sanders,
whose husband is state Sen. Hugh Sanders.
</P>
<P>
   ``But whites still hold all the real economic and political
power, and there's a lot of lingering racial hatred.''
</P>
<P>
   Alabama Gov. Don Siegelman postponed a trip abroad to join
Clinton. But even as members of Congress tour the state's civil
rights landmarks Saturday, Southern preservation groups are
scheduled to hold a counter-rally at the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   Led by the League of the South, a group that wants Alabama to
secede and return the Confederate flag to the Capitol dome, the
Southern preservationists include the Alabama Heritage Coalition,
Alabama Proud and the Sons of Confederate veterans. The group has
announced it will unveil a ``Declaration of Southern
Independence.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There are still problems,'' concedes Sandra Holley, a white
Chamber of Commerce volunteer who leads hundreds of tourists each
year through Selma's historic swath of blocks along the river.
</P>
<P>
   She takes them past the old cotton warehouses, the slave trading
post, the arsenal; she tells them Selma, far below the Mason-Dixon
line and a destination for Birmingham's steel and iron ore, was the
Confederacy's second largest source of cannons, horseshoes, uniform
buttons and other articles needed in the Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   She tells them that, today, a bi-racial, civic-minded group
called One Selma regularly meets, discusses problems, plans events
and maps out a path to better race relations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly we can always make improvements,'' said Holley.
``But our town is pulling together and working together like never
before. This is a wonderful time for the eyes of the nation to be
on Selma.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, pointing to the record migration of blacks to the
prosperous cities of the New South and even the small towns of the
old, agrees. ``To bring the dirt and the filth out from under the
rug of the country, we almost had to have Selma,'' says Lewis. ``It
had a cleansing effect on the very psyche of America.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
