<SLUG> BC-DOMINICAN-EXTRADITE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOMINICAN AID HALTED OVER WESTCHESTER FUGITIVE 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The head of the House Committee on International
Relations has invoked a rarely used power to block $6 million in
aid to the Dominican Republic unless it hands over a man charged
with a 1991 murder in the legislator's district in Westchester
(N.Y.) County.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Benjamin A. Gilman, a Republican, announced the move last
month after sending two letters about the case to President Leonel
Fernandez Reyna of the Dominican Republic without receiving a
response.
</P>
<P>
   Lester Munson, a spokesman for Gilman, said that the attempt to
force an extradition by withholding aid was very unusual. ``It's
the first that I know of,'' he said. ``It's definitely not an
everyday occurrence.''
</P>
<P>
   The action already appears to have had some effect on the
Dominican government, which has responded with promises of a search
and has convicted the suspect in absentia. The suspect, Carlos
Grullon, has been a fugitive since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Grullon, who lived in Westchester County at the time, was
indicted by a grand jury there in December 1991, charged with
murdering his wife, Yolina Arcenia Camacho. The police said the
killing took place in Tarrytown, N.Y., in front of five witnesses,
among them the two children of Grullon and Camacho. The children,
Richard, 10, and Dahiana, 14, now live with their maternal
grandmother in Sleepy Hollow, north of Tarrytown.
</P>
<P>
   Ater the killing, Grullon fled to the Dominican Republic, where
he was arrested. He spent several months in a Dominican jail before
being released on bail in 1992. He has been on the run ever since.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Gilman's office last week, a high-level Dominican
official said the government would ``deploy all necessary efforts''
to catch Grullon. Dominican officials have also met with Gilman's
staff, offering further assurances.
</P>
<P>
   And last Tuesday, a Dominican court tried and sentenced Grullon
in absentia for the murder and his bail violation, according to
U.S. and Dominican officials.
</P>
<P>
   The frozen aid money is earmarked for programs to promote
democracy, the rule of law and human rights. Gilman allowed more
than $1.5 million for AIDS prevention and for the coming
presidential election to go through at the request of the Dominican
Republic.
</P>
<P>
   Once Grullon is caught, Dominican officials said, the Dominican
attorney general will consider the case for extradition.
</P>
<P>
   Gilman said in a statement: ``The government of the Dominican
Republic has informed me that it will do all it can to arrest
Carlos Grullon. This is a significant first step toward securing
his extradition. While I am pleased by this positive response, we
await further concrete action.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Munson, three other legislators besides Gilman have
the power to freeze aid money: the head of the Senate Foreign
Relations Committee and the chairmen of the House and Senate
subcommittees on foreign aid appropriations.
</P>
<P>
   Gilman stressed that the money would not be restored until
Grullon was in the custody of U.S. officials. ``I am not prepared
to relinquish my holds on assistance funds for the Dominican
Republic until we see real progress in achieving the arrest and
extradition of Carlos Grullon,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The United States had an extradition treaty with the Dominican
Republic from 1910 until the country passed a law in 1969
precluding Dominican citizens from being extradited. But three
years ago, after lobbying from U.S. officials, the Dominican
Republic passed a law allowing extradition.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-03-00 2107EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
