<DOCNO> NYT20000303.0318 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-03 21:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6285 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-MARDIGRAS-PANTIES0304     03-03 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARDIGRAS-PANTIES0304-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New Orleans initiates anti-ludeness campaign
 &HT;    By Anne Rochell Konigsmark
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ Anyone who has ever been to Mardi Gras has a
favorite lewd story.
</P>
<P>
   Remember that time the girl on Bourbon Street contorted her body
like a crab and the guy... Or the time the two women on the balcony
took their shirts off and... How about the beads that woman got for
showing her...
</P>
<P>
   If the New Orleans police could be all places at all times,
there would be no such stories at this year's Mardi Gras
festivities, which kick into high gear this weekend. The police are
cracking down on the Mardi Gras ``tradition'' of flashing breasts
or even private parts in exchange for strands of brightly colored
plastic beads. The beads usually are thrown from parade floats, but
they can also be bought all over the French Quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The police last week taped 1,000 posters around the French
Quarter_epicenter of the bustling breasts for beads trade_warning
revelers that ``flashing'' is a crime and could cost $1,000 and
some jail time.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't the first year New Orleans has enforced laws barring
public nudity. Last year, police arrested 360 flashers during Mardi
Gras. But it is the first time there have been posted warnings and
public announcements about the campaign against lewdness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never known them to make a big deal about it,'' said Ken
Kneipp, who was in town this week from Minnesota but lived in New
Orleans for 30 years. ``I think it's kind of crazy. No one gets
hurt or injured or even offended.''
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Sandy, agreed, but with a caveat: ``It's fine down
here on Bourbon Street, but if it is in the neighborhoods, with the
children, it would matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus is the divided nature of Mardi Gras.
</P>
<P>
   To most residents, Mardi Gras is about the parades that begin
several weeks before Fat Tuesday, March 7 this year. The parades
weave through Uptown New Orleans, the Garden District and Mid-City
and usually end downtown on Canal Street. They never enter the
French Quarter. The Quarter, especially Bourbon Street, is for
tourists who want to attend one of the world's largest, and
lewdest, street parties.
</P>
<P>
   But there is breast-baring along the parade route, and there is
no question the act prompts generous bead tossing from the float
riders. Robert Johnston, a New Orleans native who is in the
parading krewe of Bacchus, which rolls down St. Charles Avenue
Sunday night, said things begin to get raunchy around Lee Circle,
at the edge of the warehouse district downtown.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a wall-to-wall extravaganza down there,'' he said. ``To
harass people for that is the stupidest thing I have heard in my
life. If you don't want to see it, don't go past Lee Circle. And
you enter the French Quarter at your own peril.''
</P>
<P>
   While some residents could care less what goes on downtown,
others say the police are right to crack down on public nudity.
More than 3,000 people flooded the New Orleans Times-Picayune with
calls, e-mails and faxes when the newspaper asked what readers
thought of the crackdown. Two-thirds sided with police.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are ruining Mardi Gras,'' one reader wrote of the
flashers. ``It's become trash, strictly trash.''
</P>
<P>
   Even in the suburbs, where Mardi Gras is decidedly tamer, the
issue of obscenity arose this year. The Gretna City Council voted
to ban ``sexually explicit throws'' from their carnival floats.
</P>
<P>
   However, the governing body decided to allow the tossing of
women's panties from floats.
</P>
<P>
   ``So we're pro- panties _it's on the record,'' Councilman
Vincent Cox said.
</P>
<P>
   On Bourbon Street, the police warnings carry some weight, but
they aren't exactly scaring the, ahem, pants off any partyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are asking me if they'll go to jail if they flash,''
said Jimmy Burgin, a bartender at Tropical Isle, home of such
famous drinks as the Hand Grenade and the Horny Gator. The warning
sign that was up at the bar keeps getting torn down. ``If I see
someone out on the balcony dropping pants or whatever, I tell them
to stop.''
</P>
<P>
   Nick Atchue, a tourist from Boston, didn't seem too worried.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get awesome beads when I flash,'' he said. ``I showed some
lady mine, she showed me hers_she even took her shorts off.''
</P>
<P>
   Ask a tourist on Bourbon Street what Mardi Gras is all about and
you usually get the same answer:
</P>
<P>
   ``I think beads, and I think flashing,'' said Matt McCue of
Wooster, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Playboy Magazine, which has a nine-page spread of flashing from
last year's Mardi Gras in its current issue, has incensed some city
officials, who are determined to remind the world that Mardi Gras
is about more than beads and breasts.
</P>
<P>
   Good luck: Playboy.Com even has instructions on what women will
do for beads.
</P>
<P>
   ``Present an ordinary strand of those worthless, little plastic
pearl necklaces to the right woman, and she might give you a peek
at her muffalettas,'' says the site, referring to women's breasts
as a traditional New Orleans sandwich.
</P>
<P>
   So far, police say they have arrested more than 50 people for
public nudity and lewd acts.
</P>
<P>
   It's going to be a long weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
