<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   ITALY: NORTH KOREAN VISIT
</P>
<P>
   Foreign Minister Lamberto Dini is to visit North Korea at the
end of March, the most senior official of a major industrial nation
to go there. The trip, announced during a state visit to Italy by
the South Korean president, Kim Dae-jung, follows Italy's move last
January to open diplomatic relations with the North. Dini, who has
brokered openings to Iran and Libya, seeks to position Italy as a
diplomatic icebreaker.
</P>
<P>
   ITALY: PILGRIMS DEPORTED
</P>
<P>
   A group of 32 young African men on a Holy Year pilgrimage were
stopped at the Rome airport last month and sent home to the Congo
Republic, Fides, the news agency of the Vatican's missionary
branch, reported. The men were turned away because officials
suspected they were seeking to immigrate illegally, Fides said.
</P>
<P>
   POLAND: PORNOGRAPHY BAN
</P>
<P>
   Parliament narrowly passed a tough antipornography bill, but the
president may veto it. Opponents say it fails to define pornography
and limits freedom of expression. Since the fall of communism,
pornography has been widely available and the Roman Catholic church
has campaigned against it strongly.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   INDIA: BIHAR SWEARS IN NATIONALIST
</P>
<P>
   Nitish Kumar, a Hindu nationalist, was sworn in as chief
minister of Bihar state, and he has 10 days to muster a majority in
the assembly. The move outraged his opponent, the political
maverick Laloo Prasad Yadav, whose party won the most seats in
recent elections.
</P>
<P>
   PAKISTAN: SHARIF'S LAWYERS RETURN
</P>
<P>
   All but one of the lawyers defending Nawaz Sharif, the deposed
prime minister, have rejoined the case, saying he pleaded with them
not to abandon him during his trial on charges of hijacking,
treason and attempted murder in connection with his attempt to
remove his military commander.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   RWANDA: U.S. TO DEPORT MASSACRE SUSPECT
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright has cleared the way for
the deportation of the only suspect wanted by the Rwanda war crimes
tribunal in American custody. Elizaphan Ntakirutimana, a
Seventh-day Adventist pastor charged with offering ethnic Tutsi
shelter at his church compound and then turning a Hutu mob on them
during the 1994 genocide, was first arrested in Texas in 1996. He
fought the case until he lost his appeal to the Supreme Court on
Jan. 24.
</P>
</TEXT>
