<HEADLINE>
TESTIMONY OF PETE ROSE'S GAMBLING HABIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dying for a little sports ``action'' because the Bruins and
Celtics aren't giving it to you? Then get on-line, set aside a
couple of hours, read the 225-page Dowd Report, and understand why
baseball commissioner Bud Selig is so adamant about not reinstating
Pete Rose.
</P>
<P>
   This report was presented to the public May 9, 1989. John M.
Dowd, a Washington lawyer, was hired as chairman of the special
committee set up by then-commissioner Peter Ueberroth, to look into
Rose's alleged gambling. The full report can be found at
www.dowdreport.com, and it's fascinating reading.
</P>
<P>
   When finished, you will not have one doubt in your mind that
Rose bet on hundreds of baseball games, and many of them were games
involving the Cincinnati Reds, the team he was managing. No matter
how much Rose denies it, this report has him every which way but
loose. It has testimony from his ``friends,'' who placed bets for
him and from bookies who took the bets. It also includes betting
slips and telephone records to support the evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Pages 119-190 are riveting. It is a daily journal of every bet
Rose made from Opening Day, April 8, 1987, to July 5, 1987, which
was the All-Star break. Here is Rose's action on Opening Day: he
won $2,000 on the Reds; lost $2,200 on our heroes, the Red Sox; won
$2,000 on Minnesota; and another $2,000 on California.
</P>
<P>
   On April 11, he bet eight games: he won $2,000 each on the Reds,
St. Louis, Los Angeles, Milwaukee, Detroit, Seattle, and Houston,
and lost $3,200 on Philadelphia. Obviously motivated by his
winnings, Rose bet heavily the next day, and won $2,000 each on the
Phillies, Dodgers, Royals, and Twins. However, he lost $3,400 on
the Reds, $4,800 on the Mets, $2,800 on the Indians, and another
$2,600 on the Angels. So on April 11, he made $10,800, and gave
back $5,600 the next.
</P>
<P>
   The report shows that Rose's life in that period (1986-1988),
was consumed by sports gambling. It has him locked into betting
with three bookies _ one in Ohio; one in Tampa where the Reds
trained; and one in Staten Island, N.Y., where he would go when he
owed money to the other two. Rose used a friend as a ``straw'' to
make the bets, and it is the sworn testimony of one of these
straws, and the bookie in Ohio, that negates any alibi Rose tried
to use.
</P>
<P>
   Rose's typical bet was $2,000. When he was short on cash, he
would often go to card/memorabilia shows, and leave with a satchel
of cash, carried by one of his buddies. There are a couple of
humorous asides in the report. Early in one of these seasons, the
scoreboard in Cincinnati was not working for a couple of weeks, so
Rose could not keep up with the out-of-town games he bet on. So his
straw at the time, a friend named Paul Janzen, sat in the stands,
and by hand signals, told Rose whether he was winning or losing on
the day.
</P>
<P>
   Janzen had a cell phone and would call the national sportsline
to get inning-by-inning scores. Often Rose would come to the top
dugout step, look at Janzen, give him a signal asking ``what's
going on?'' and Janzen would respond with a thumbs up or thumbs
down. In another episode, Janzen's girlfriend placed a bet on
behalf of Rose and Janzen, and realizing that she bet more than
they wanted, tried to cancel the bet. The bookie refused because
the team they bet on was losing, 6-0, after the first inning.
However, she got off the hook when the team rallied in the ninth to
win, 10-9.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation of Rose and his friends was masterful, and
until Rose admits he not only bet on baseball, but lied about it to
the investigators, then no commissioner is going to lift the ban
and give him a chance to get into the Hall of Fame. There is no
evidence that he ever bet against his own team, and although there
is no final accounting of if he won or lost money, he clearly comes
across as a loser.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   John Wooten should be given the ``Most Courageous'' award in the
NFL for 2000, even though he's retiring and hasn't played in 25
years. Wooten was one of the best offensive linemen in the league
for the Cleveland Browns when Jim Brown was posting record-breaking
performances.
</P>
<P>
   After his retirement as a player, Wooten worked all across the
league from scout, to personnel director, through the league
office, winding up in the front office of the Baltimore Ravens,
where he got to know Ray Lewis, who has been charged with murder.
</P>
<P>
   In a Chicago Tribune interview, here is what Wooten had to say
about Lewis, and the current state of affairs in the NFL: ``I
personally feel almost fooled because born-again Christians (which
Lewis purports to be) don't go to places like that _ too many drug
dealers and strippers. We're hearing that he didn't do the
stabbing, but you wonder how a young man who makes so much money
($26 million contract) and who is so popular in our community could
risk it all by running with the people he was with.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I know is that players used to go out with players and
protected each other from situations like that. But today's players
have to surround themselves with these ego people who are only
interested in the player's name and money. Now I go into the locker
room and hear our players calling each other (racial slur) and it
hurts my soul. We've had people killed for saying that word, and
now they are using it like nothing. People didn't want to listen to
(former Steelers coach) Chuck Noll a few years ago when he said
there's a thug element in our game and if we weren't careful,
they'll take it over. He was right.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jamie Fox of Northeastern University, one of the foremost
authorities on criminal behavior, was asked to talk about the
increasing frequency of professional athletes being involved in
crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of these athletes have roots in poor neighborhoods and
gangs. Just because you can take the player out of the
neighborhood, that doesn't mean you can take the neighborhood out
of the player,'' Fox said. ``A lot of these players have developed
a sense of entitlement because other people have taken care of
things for them; done their thinking for them; not given them a
sense of responsibility, and sometimes they take things too far.
You can't say (in the cases of Lewis and Rae Carruth) that their
background is responsible (for being implicated in murders) because
there is a direct correlation between poverty and murder, and these
players are not poor. They had money. But money doesn't bring you
good sense, or the ability to understand certain situations. When
people in other businesses are a success, and gain wealth, they've
done it with their brains. With a ballplayer, it's brawn not brain.
</P>
<P>
   In the NFL they are conditioned to use their brawn, to be
aggressive. When they get into a situation where they have to made
a decision, brawn or brain, brawn is going to win most of the time.
That's when they get into trouble. But when they do, people start
making excuses for them.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo's Doug Flutie and St. Louis's Kurt Warner (this year's
regular-season and Super Bowl Most Valuable Player), might have a
lot in common next season. Word out of St. Louis is that the Rams
still feel Trent Green, who was the starter before he was injured
in the final preseason game, is the better quarterback. New coach
Mike Martz is going to have a lot of explaining to do if Green
starts after what Warner did last season. In Buffalo, Rob Johnson
will go into training camp as the starter. Your humble reporter
asked a top Cleveland Browns executive last week why the team
passed on Warner when St. Louis placed him on the expansion list,
making him available to them for nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We checked out his background,'' the executive said. ``We were
told that the only reason he was with the Rams is that they were
doing a favor for some coach. The coach who had this guy (Warner)
in Arena Football was going to work in our (NFL) European League,
and wanted to keep Warner with him. To play in Europe, a player has
to be on an NFL roster, and that team has to assign him to the
European League.
</P>
<P>
   ``The coach knew someone in St. Louis and asked them to do a
favor. They did it, because it didn't cost them anything. When you
assign a player to Europe, he doesn't count against your own
roster. You can have an exemption, but you still have the rights to
him. So the Rams didn't know how good he was, and our people
didn't, either. Then he shows up as the MVP. What does that tell
you?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The FleetCenter is going to take a financial beating this spring
with the Bruins and Celtics both blowing the playoffs. The teams
receive about $1 million at the gate for every playoff game, and
the FleetCenter's take is close to $200,000 per contest, as it's
end of the business ranges from suites, preferred seats, and
concessions. The Red Sox won't have any money problems. In spite of
increased ticket prices, they have had a record-breaking 99 percent
season-ticket renewal after their big 1999 season. Less than 50
accounts, out of more than 7,000, didn't renew. Generally, the rate
of renewal is less than 95 percent.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Football Hall of Fame inductee Howie Long, on some people who
helped him along the way when he was growing up in Charlestown, and
later playing football at Milford High School: ``Ron Burton gave me
the first uniform I ever had when I was a kid in Charlestown trying
out for Pop Warner. He was a very nice, gentle kind of man. I'll
always respect what he tried to do for us over there. And then Ray
Hamilton gave me a nice call after I was voted into the Hall. Ray
was my camp counselor on Cape Cod one year in a football camp my
high school coach, Dick Corbin, sent me to, and he was very
helpful.''
</P>
<P>
   Burton was the original Patriot draft choice, a black man who
started Pop Warner football in, at the time, almost all-white
Charlestown as a favor to a friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really didn't know anyone over there,'' says Burton, an
executive with John Hancock who is known across the state for his
wonderful charitable work. ``But a friend asked me to start it up.
I was over there for four or five years, almost every night in the
fall. I had to borrow the money to buy the uniforms from Bucky
Warren (Sporting Goods Co. at the time) and old Bucky thought I was
crazy. But I paid it all back eventually, and the program helped a
lot of kids. I was thrilled when Howie got picked for the Hall
because I felt like I had a small, very small, part of it, but
still, I had a part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Did you know that Fred Haas Jr., the golfer who stopped Byron
Nelson's record-winning streak at 11 tournaments, was an amateur?
Haas beat Nelson by four strokes in August 1945, and later turned
pro . . . Paul Boudreau, offensive line coach for the Miami
Dolphins, after Bruce Smith left Buffalo and joined the Redskins:
``As soon as every left tackle in the AFC East heard that Bruce
signed in Washington, they had their own party. None of them ever
looked forward to playing against him twice a year, and even though
he's near the end, he can still crank it up on Sundays when he
feels like it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Harry Sinden remembers where he was 40 years ago last Monday. He
was the captain of the Canadian Olympic hockey team that had just
lost the gold medal to the United States in a tremendous upset at
Squaw Valley: ``A bunch of us decided we were going to go to Reno
and cry in our beer. The nearest town to Squaw Valley was Truckee,
Calif. You got the train there to go to Reno. We were early for the
train and decided to stop in a bar right across from the station.
The bartender found out who we were, and made some smart remark.
Next thing I know, one of our guys jumps over the bar and starts
throwing punches. Then the wildest brawl you ever saw broke out. It
was like an old wild west movie, and a lot of us got to Reno with
lumps on our head.''
</P>
<P>
   Jack Riley, who coached the winning US team, had a different
experience. ``I was coaching at West Point, and when I arrived back
there, I couldn't wait to see the superintendent. When I asked him
for a leave of absence to coach the team, he told me yes, but
(kiddingly) said don't come back unless you win. Three jeeps with
military police met me. The search lights were turned on as we
drove up. All 2,400 cadets came to the superintendent's house. They
had the Zamboni in front of his house. And they had a seven-gun
salute with the West Point cannons, one for each win. Then we all
went back to the hockey rink and had a party.''
</P>
<P>
   (Will McDonough is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
