<HEADLINE>
CLINTON STEPPING UP EFFORTS TO NORMALIZE TRADE WITH CHINA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Mich., Mont., Nev.)  (js 
 By JOSEPH KAHN and ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton, amid signs that support for an
important China trade accord is slipping away, will send a bill to
Congress as early as Wednesday that permanently normalizes trade
relations with Beijing, administration officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The accelerated timetable answers calls from pro-trade members
of Congress, who have urged the Clinton administration to push for
an early vote because of mounting evidence that the measure will be
an even tougher sell as election-year politics intensify. Organized
labor has made defeating the China trade measure a top priority,
and a senior House Democrat has warned that as many as two-thirds
of his rank-and-file are ready to vote against the accord.
</P>
<P>
   Even pro-trade Republican leaders say they are having trouble
rallying support among their members. China's renewed threats to
use force against Taiwan and the administration's own report that
the human rights situation in China has deteriorated have given
fresh ammunition to right-wing opponents of the trade measure as
well as to those on the left.
</P>
<P>
   The administration calls the vote its most important remaining
foreign policy goal. The president has said a loss would be
``devastating.''
</P>
<P>
   Congress is being asked to surrender its annual review of
China's trade status and to grant the country permanent normal
trade relations, a privilege enjoyed by most other nations. Last
year, the administration pledged to Beijing that it would work to
grant it normal trading rights as part of a broader package that
paves the way for China to join the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   A `no' vote would not necessarily derail China's drive to join
the trade body. But China could then revoke normal trading rights
for the United States, denying U.S. businesses some trade benefits
it grants other nations. Failure to pass the measure might also
lead to a serious rift with Beijing, which has long pushed to
eliminate the annual trade review.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it's really in everyone's interest to see this vote
happen soon,'' said Commerce Secretary Bill Daley, who is leading
Clinton's campaign to drive the measure through Congress. ``There
is a sense that the chances get marginally worse the longer we
wait.''
</P>
<P>
   In a shift in strategy, the administration will seek a Senate
vote before a House vote, reversing the usual order for such
legislation, administration officials said. Supporters hope that a
favorable vote in the generally pro-trade Senate will give them
momentum for the looming battle in the House, where both Republican
and Democratic leaders say scores of undecided lawmakers make the
outcome too close to call.
</P>
<P>
   As part of a carefully calculated campaign to step up pressure
on Congress, Clinton has also decided to devote an unusually large
amount of time to lobbying lawmakers, coordinating strategy with
business executives and giving public speeches extolling the
benefits of increased trade with China.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the president plans to deliver a broad address
here focused on the future of U.S. relations with the world's most
populous country, and administration officials are considering
sending the bill to Capitol Hill that day as well.
</P>
<P>
   The administration and its congressional allies say they have
found a way around one tall hurdle that pro-trade legislators had
feared could delay a vote for months. They plan to include a
provision that makes China's permanent trade status conditional on
China joining the World Trade Organization on terms equal or better
for the United States than those negotiated last year.
</P>
<P>
   That should put to rest any talk in Congress that a vote cannot
be held until the European Union, Mexico and a handful of other
countries complete their own talks with China about joining the
Geneva-based trade regulatory body, administration officials said.
Europe's talks are dragging on far longer than anticipated _ some
observers say that Europe is using China's eagerness to get
permanent trade status here as leverage in its negotiations _ and
the administration says it can no longer hold off until Europe
seals a deal.
</P>
<P>
   Prospects for the bill's passage are good in the Senate, which
traditionally is more supportive of trade agreements than the
House. ``It's a done deal,'' said Sen. Max S. Baucus, a Montana
Democrat who favors permanent trading status.
</P>
<P>
   Other pro-trade lawmakers agree that the Senate will approve the
measure, but only after a bumpy ride. Some Senate Republicans have
grown increasingly alarmed over Beijing's recent bellicose warnings
to Taiwan. Many Democrats are under pressure from organized labor
to reject the pact on the ground that it does not ensure adequate
worker and environmental standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are potholes in the Senate as well,'' said Sen. Pat
Roberts, a Kansas Republican and strong supporter of permanent
trading status with China. Roberts said his fears were reinforced
Friday after a conversation with Agriculture Secretary Dan
Glickman. ``Privately, he's worried that this is coming apart,''
Roberts said.
</P>
<P>
   In another troubling sign for supporters, Sen. Harry Reid of
Nevada, the second-ranking Democrat, said in an interview Monday
that he was leaning in favor of passage. But after meeting with
labor leaders this week, Reid is now having second thoughts, top
Democratic aides said. Reid is concerned, aides said, that passage
of the bill could so alienate labor unions that they would depress
Democratic voter turnout in battleground states like Michigan,
where Democrats hope to pick up a Senate seat.
</P>
<P>
   Most people believe the toughest fight will be in the House.
Labor has made the vote a litmus test for Democrats, with the
Teamsters and United Auto Workers lobbying legislators especially
hard. Even Vice President Al Gore, who has been courting labor's
vote, has sent mixed signals about his support for the China
accord, which gives wavering Democrats political cover to vote
against the measure.
</P>
<P>
   In the opposite camp, the Business Roundtable, a lobbying group
for some of America's largest corporations, will kick off a $1.5
million television advertising campaign this weekend in support of
China trade.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. David Bonior of Michigan, the second-ranking Democrat, said
this week that 128 of 211 House Democrats now oppose the measure.
``The administration is in trouble in the House, and they know
it,'' Bonior told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   But a key pro-trade Democrat, Rep. Robert Matsui of California,
dismissed Bonior's vote-counting. He said the trade vote this year
is higher-profile than previous annual votes of whether to renew
China's trade status and that most members, in the end, will favor
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once we get this bill to the floor, we'll win it,'' Matsui
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
