<HEADLINE>
SOX REACH TERMS WITH FIVE MORE PLAYERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT MYERS, Fla. _ Then there were two: The Red Sox came to
terms with five more players Friday: outfielder Jermaine
Allensworth, pitcher Tomo Ohka, second baseman Donnie Sadler, and
pitchers Brian Rose and Jin Ho Cho. The Red Sox have cleared the
decks of all players except for closer Derek Lowe and catcher Jason
Varitek, both of whom they would like to sign to multiyear
contracts and be spared future arbitration cases.
</P>
<P>
   Rose, who was renewed for the minimum salary of $200,000 last
season, which left a bad taste, will be paid $250,000. Brian
Daubach, who was at $215,000 in 1999, will be paid $295,000, with
Trot Nixon believed to be at $275,000, and Sadler at $230,000.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, Red Sox policy is to pay players with fewer than 45
days' service time the $200,000 minimum.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Coming/going attraction
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota Twins ace Brad Radke will soon grow accustomed to the
scene he encountered in the Twins' clubhouse Thursday night after
his two innings of work _ a cluster of visiting writers wondering
if he'll soon be pitching in (fill in the team of your choice)
because of his uncertain contract status. The Twins want to sign
Radke, who is eligible for free agency after the season, to a
contract extension, but Radke is insisting on the right to demand a
trade after two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think about it,'' Radke said when asked if he will be
changing zip codes any time soon. ``That's the way I am. Things
happen for a reason. If something gets done here, great. If not, we
move on.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No writer's block
</P>
<P>
   The Twins and Red Sox play back-to-back games this weekend,
which could raise the question of how Pedro Martinez will react
when he encounters La Velle E. Neal III, the Minneapolis writer who
left the Sox ace off his MVP ballot last winter. Neal said Thursday
night that he received more than 400 e-mails when his vote became
public.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of 'em were pretty descriptive,'' he said. ``One guy said
he was going to e-mail me every day to remind me of what a big
idiot I was.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez said he won't turn from anyone who wants to talk to
him. ``I don't see any reason to approach him,'' said Neal, who
added that he still wouldn't vote for a pitcher. ``Based on what
I've read, he's not upset.''
</P>
<P>
   But Twins manager Tom Kelly had a little fun with the writer.
When Neal noted that the Twins were missing Martinez Friday night,
Kelly said: ``You may be trying to avoid him, but we're not. No, we
like facing Pedro. It gives us something to go by with our young
guys. Let's see how we can do.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Vintage Nomar?
</P>
<P>
   No wine before its time: The April edition of Wine Enthusiasts
magazine has a story about Nomar Garciaparra joining fellow
shortstops Alex Rodriguez and Derek Jeter in purchasing a new
winery in Napa Valley, which they plan to call Position Six. The
name, of course, corresponds to the number used for the shortstop
when keeping score. The story said the three had enlisted the aid
of wine consultant Heidi Barrett, who is as big in the wine biz as
the players are in their game.
</P>
<P>
   So, what's next, a wine rack next to the bat rack in the Sox
dugout?
</P>
<P>
   Not to worry. The piece was all in jest, part of the magazine's
April Fools edition. Mike Schachner, senior editor of the magazine,
is a Yankees fan. ``All in fun,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But here's the surprise. Garciaparra said Friday he has become
quite the avid wine collector. ``Strictly reds,'' said Garciaparra,
who noted that several teammates are ahead of him in their
expertise. ``Sabes (Bret Saberhagen) knows his wines, Val (John
Valentin), Mike Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the idea (of the winery). I'll have to talk to Derek
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Saberhagen all cleared up
</P>
<P>
   Saberhagen worked out after missing three days with a sinus
infection, similar to what laid up Lowe last weekend . . . The Sox
have 57 players in camp, compared with 58 a year ago. The
breakdown: 27 pitchers, 7 catchers, 14 infielders, 9 outfielders.
Forty-two of the players in camp have played in the big leagues . .
. CEO John Harrington arrived in town earlier this week.
</P>
</TEXT>
