<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-GORE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY CRITICIZES CLINTON ADMINISTRATION IN FOREIGN POLICY SPEECH 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ALAN BERNSTEIN 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PROVIDENCE, R.I. _ Four days from the elections that could
derail his presidential campaign, Bill Bradley switched gears
Friday from his campaign rallies and delivered a major speech on
foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
   In the speech, Bradley criticized the Clinton administration's
approach to Russia and China while singling out campaign foe Al
Gore on related issues.
</P>
<P>
   But Bradley's foreign policy message was a topic most voters
don't name in surveys about their top concerns.
</P>
<P>
   As for the timing of the speech, Bradley said shallow treatment
of foreign policy in this year's campaign makes him nostalgic for a
time when such a contest turned on whether a candidate was
qualified to help protect the world.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesman Eric Hauser said Bradley had always promised to lay
out his vision for global peace and prosperity, and that Friday was
as good a time as any.
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen states conduct primaries or caucuses on Super Tuesday,
and Bradley, who trails Gore in the polls in every one of those
states, has said he must win some to stay in the race.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has criticized what he views as Bradley's ivory-tower
approach to several issues, saying that the presidency is not an
academic exercise. Bradley shared his foreign policy thoughts in a
50-minute address to about 600 students Friday in a cathedral-style
lecture hall at Brown University.
</P>
<P>
   The former senator from New Jersey said that as president he
would be prepared to use military force _ in certain situations _
to resolve human rights crises in other countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``The commitment of U.S. troops should be considered only to
stop egregious human rights violations; only when no other
solutions are available and only when our military leaders are
confident that their strategy will be successful,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He also called for a stronger U.S. role in the United Nations
and further use of its humanitarian projects.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, who served on the Senate Intelligence Committee, said
the government has botched its relationship with post-Communist
Russia. It has produced a situation ``in which the world's only
other nuclear superpower is coming apart at the seams,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The United States should not ignore Russian corruption or human
rights violations against Chechnya and should consider cutting off
financial aid to Russia unless there are assurances that the money
won't go to the military or the elites, Bradley said. But at the
same time, he continued, the United States needlessly antagonized
Russia by swiftly adding more European countries to NATO.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has also sent confusing signals on its role in
supporting Taiwan's relationship with China, Bradley said. At the
same time, China should be granted permanent normal trade status
with the United States as a way to expand not only trade but also
democracy, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In his most specific reference to Gore, Bradley said the vice
president hurt the chances for a trade agreement with China last
month when labor leaders claimed he pledged to them that he would
negotiate tougher requirements on China. The White House insisted
that Gore meant he would seek tougher labor standards in future
trade agreements, not the one pending with China.
</P>
<P>
   While criticizing Gore in the foreign policy speech, Bradley's
statements about the vice president were generally muted.
</P>
<P>
   No longer is Bradley questioning Gore's truthfulness or the
consistency of his voting record on abortion and gun control.
</P>
<P>
   In Jacksonville and looking beyond Florida's March 14 primary,
Gore assailed Gov. George W. Bush's stances on gun control and
federal aid for public education.
</P>
<P>
   Gore told the nearly 2,000 students at Raines High, where the
student body is almost entirely African-American, that he
vigorously opposes the anti-affirmative action campaign called
``One Florida'' that is led by Gov. Jeb Bush, the brother of the
Texas governor, whom Gore may be opposing in the November
presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   Gore chided George W. Bush, as well as GOP presidential
candidate Sen. John McCain of Arizona, for not calling for
mandatory trigger locks on guns to avert tragedies like this week's
fatal shooting of a Michigan first-grader.
</P>
<P>
   In his plea to preserve affirmative action programs, Gore said
those who want to abolish the concept ``have blinders on'' and
refuse to acknowledge racial inequities that have persisted for
generations.
</P>
<P>
   Regarding the conviction of Maria Hsia, a political fund-raiser
and longtime associate of the vice president, Gore said ``... the
jury has spoken, and I'm not going to comment further on a matter
that is still working its way through the courts.''
</P>
<P>
   Hsia was convicted Thursday of channeling more than $100,000 in
illegal contributions to Democratic candidates in 1996, including
$65,000 in tainted money she brought in the day after Gore's
controversial appearance at a Buddhist temple.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Houston Chronicle reporter John W. Gonzalez contributed to this
story. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
