<HEADER>
A6294 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-BIZ-BTOB-E-COMMERCE-A     03-03 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-BTOB-E-COMMERCE-ART-$ADV05-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE HIGHER STAKES OF BUSINESS-TO-BUSINESS TRADE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., Calif.)   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888 603-1036
or 888 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 5)  
 (af)  
 By RICHARD A. OPPEL Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ No one doubts that there is tremendous money to be made
helping companies do business with one another over the Internet.
And judging by the enormous multiples that investors are paying,
they seem pretty sure which kinds of companies are going to make
that money. But are they right?
</P>
<P>
   Business-to-business electronic commerce, known as B2B, covers a
lot of ground. For some years, companies have been developing
digital links with customers, distributors and suppliers to improve
supply-chain management and demand forecasting and to squeeze out
inventory costs.
</P>
<P>
   But lately the concept has taken a quantum leap in scale, to
encompass whole industries buying, selling and trading with one
another online.
</P>
<P>
   Now growing numbers of software companies and dot-com start-ups
are pouring in, enticed by the prospect of billions of dollars of
transactions in, say, auto parts, freight-hauling services or
specialty chemicals passing through a Web-based ``exchange'' or
``marketplace,'' akin to an eBay for big business, that they could
build and control.
</P>
<P>
   And investors have followed, sending stock prices soaring for
B2B companies like i2 Technologies, based here in Dallas, whose
market capitalization of around $26 billion is about 1,000 times
last year's earnings; i2 began life 12 years ago as an enterprise
software concern.
</P>
<P>
   Ariba and Commerce One, two of i2's competitors, have also seen
their stocks shoot up 20- and 30-fold from their offering prices,
standing out even in the highflying technology sector.
</P>
<P>
   But the announcement by General Motors, Ford and DaimlerChrysler
that they would combine forces to create a single Internet
marketplace through which to do their buying has called into
question whether the keys to the gold mine will ultimately be
claimed by the B2B players or the Old Economy companies they want
to serve.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the automakers' announcement froze out the technology
companies: Oracle, the Redwood City, Calif., database and
e-commerce concern, was chosen to be a key technology provider to
the new venture along with Commerce One, and both stocks have
jumped since the announcement. But it is not certain that playing
the limited role of technology supplier will ever yield enough
revenue to justify today's sky-high stock valuations.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say most B2B exchange revenue will come three ways:
from recurring subscription and maintenance fees from participants,
from a small commission on each transaction and from equity stakes
in the new exchanges. Together, the amounts should be huge.
</P>
<P>
   Consider a few hypotheticals. Total B2B transactions are
expected to rise from $145 billion last year to $7.3 trillion in
2004, according to the Gartner Group, a consulting firm. A cut of,
say, 0.25 percent of that in transaction fees would yield nearly
$20 billion in annual revenue, with much more growth to come.
</P>
<P>
   As for equity, some Wall Street analysts are already estimating
that the Big Three's exchange could, as a publicly traded company,
have a market capitalization of more than $30 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is probably at least a trillion dollars in market cap up
for grabs in the B2B industry,'' said Andrew Roskill, an analyst at
Warburg Dillon Read. ``At the end of the day, there are probably
only going to be a very few winners in each vertical industry
sector, but those guys are going to command a very high premium.''
</P>
<P>
   For some others, it won't be pretty, as the aftermath of the
carmakers' Feb. 25 announcement suggested. As it became clear
during the day that i2, which had been helping GM with its own
Internet site, had been left out of the new venture, its stock fell
by more than one-quarter from its high that day.
</P>
<P>
   The stock recovered some of the lost ground last week, thanks to
happier news about new Internet exchanges in the apparel and ground
transportation industries and a successful meeting here with
analysts; i2's shares closed Friday at $170.75.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the episode shows that for all the talk of the New
Economy triumphing over the old, some e-business highfliers cannot
count on being masters of their own fate. Many traditional
companies are rapidly deciphering the B2B world and demanding
better terms for their participation, sometimes leaving smaller
slivers of equity and lower fees for the technology companies than
they had hoped.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts expect Oracle's cut of the new auto venture to be
smaller relative to Ford's than the two had initially discussed for
Ford's own Web site project, although terms have not been
announced.
</P>
<P>
   With so much at stake, competitive tensions run high. The chief
executive of i2, Sanjiv Sidhu, said in an interview last week that
his staff was still negotiating for a role in the automakers'
exchange. Sidhu argues that Oracle is not in his company's league
technologically. ``It's tough to really understand what they have
to offer if you measure it based on what they have up and
running,'' Sidhu said.
</P>
<P>
   In response, an Oracle spokesman said new products due in the
next few months would make the company ``the best of the breed for
supply-chain software'' and that i2's exclusion, so far, from the
Big Three's venture meant that ``i2 is now irrelevant in the auto
industry.''
</P>
<P>
   George Gilbert, an analyst at Credit Suisse First Boston, agreed
with Sidhu that Oracle lagged behind i2 in some crucial areas of
technology. He said i2, struggling to cope with a huge flow of new
proposals, was searching for a more standardized and efficient way
to strike deals.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, Gilbert said, i2's ``biggest challenge has been
marketing, because they've seen farther down the road than most,
and they've had to bring people along.'' But lately, he said, ``the
market has caught up with them. It's like everything is coming
together.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking about B2B in general, Sidhu said fears that fees and
equity stakes for companies like his would be squeezed were
overblown. Demand for new Internet exchanges and associated
software is so great, he said, that everyone is focused simply on
getting sites up and running, not on the financial fine points.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are many patients needing attention,'' Sidhu said, ``and
there's a shortage of doctors.''
</P>
<P>
   Technology companies may have an easier time in fields where
both buyers and sellers are fragmented, like agriculture, than in
concentrated industries where a handful of companies hold all the
cards. Leah Knight, a principal analyst at the Gartner Group, said
the automakers must have realized that they could dictate terms,
and ``if they want to take a larger percentage of the transaction,
that comes with the turf.''
</P>
<P>
   Roskill said the same dynamic was developing elsewhere. ``The
last six months or so, we've seen a bit of a wake-up call from
traditional industry players trying to shift the balance of power
away from the technology providers to the actual people who provide
the order flow,'' he said. But, he added, there is a limit to how
far the pendulum should swing: ``It makes sense to give the
technology provider a stake that's meaningful, so their interests
are tied together'' with the users'.
</P>
<P>
   In such an environment, Knight sees a shakeout ahead. While some
B2B players ``have the potential to become companies in the upper
end'' of the Fortune 500, she said, ``maybe not even half'' of
those now in the field will be winners. The current stock market
valuations of the remainder leave them a lot of room to fall.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
