<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-03 21:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6296 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-GORE-CLINTON-LEWINSKY     03-03 1033
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-CLINTON-LEWINSKY-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW THE LEWINSKY SCANDAL STRAINED GORE'S TIES TO CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It was not until the night of Aug. 10, 1998, after
seven months of public denials, that President Clinton told Al Gore
the truth about his affair with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Although the president and his vice president lunched alone
together each week, before that night, in the back of a darkened
limousine in Chicago, Gore had never asked and the president had
never told whether he had had a sexual liaison with the White House
intern, according to close associates of both men.
</P>
<P>
   Gore learned the truth just a week before Clinton grudgingly
admitted to a federal grand jury, and then to the public, that he
had had an ``inappropriate'' physical relationship with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Neither man has ever publicly discussed their conversations
about the affair, which ultimately led to the president's
impeachment, but their actions offer some clues about the strains
that Clinton's disastrous dalliance brought to their partnership.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton appeared buoyed by his belated confession to the vice
president, leading aides to speculate afterward that Gore had given
him a vow of unconditional support that he later made good on. That
night, aboard Air Force One on the way to Los Angeles, he bantered
with reporters about disaster movies and seemed relaxed to senior
members of his staff.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, by contrast, emerged from the car stunned and sobered.
Friends and associates say he was angered by Clinton's deceit,
repulsed by his behavior and appalled at his recklessness. Gore
brooded then and afterward about what the episode might mean for
his own presidential ambitions. His sense of loyalty struggled
against an offended morality, a conflict that, his friends say, has
not yet been resolved.
</P>
<P>
   Gore left that night for a long-planned vacation in Hawaii,
where he went into virtual hibernation with his family in a
borrowed beach house. On the day of Clinton's grand jury testimony,
Aug. 17, the vice president did not appear in public to defend him.
Gore's Washington office issued a brief statement saying in part,
``I am proud of him, not only because he is a friend, but because
he is a person who has had the courage to acknowledge mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   The statement was an effort to reconcile two competing impulses
that often tugged at Gore over the course of the Lewinsky
controversy: his desire to remain loyal to Clinton while distancing
himself from the president's behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning in January 1998, when accusations that the president
had had an affair with a White House intern were first published,
the vice president's words and actions concerning the Lewinsky
matter followed an intricate trajectory. One question that Gore has
left unanswered, over the course of the controversy and its
aftermath, is whether he soon began to doubt the president's denial
of an affair _ a denial Clinton maintained even as more evidence of
his entanglement with Lewinsky emerged _ and, if so, when.
</P>
<P>
   In the first few days after the January reports, Gore issued a
vigorous defense of the president. But he then retreated into
months of nervous silence. After Clinton confessed the truth seven
months later, Gore defended the president's performance in office
while conspicuously saying little about his personal conduct.
</P>
<P>
   On the day that Kenneth W. Starr, the Whitewater independent
counsel, released his incendiary report on the Lewinsky episode,
Gore, first at a White House prayer breakfast and then at an
evening event honoring Irish-Americans, praised Clinton's character
and courage. But within days he again fell silent, letting others
defend the president and attack Starr.
</P>
<P>
   That December, when the impeachment debate became a matter of
partisan combat, Gore again spoke out forcefully on the president's
behalf, most memorably on the day of the House impeachment vote.
</P>
<P>
   During his campaign for the presidency, Gore has tried to avoid
the subject, issuing rote answers about the president's ``mistake''
and asserting repeatedly that the public cares about the future,
not the past. He and his wife, Tipper, have put substantial
physical and symbolic distance between themselves and the White
House, appearing there infrequently and shunning campaign
appearances by Clinton or Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The tactical separation has been only partly successful. Half
the public believes that Gore has been tainted by his association
with Clinton, according to an ABC News/Washington Post poll
released this week. Responding to the statement ``Al Gore is too
close to Bill Clinton to provide the fresh start the country
needs,'' 49 percent of respondents agreed and 49 percent disagreed.
The numbers are unchanged since September.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton-Gore relationship has always been complicated and is
already drawing scrutiny in this year's campaign. At its core is a
mystery: How has Gore reconciled his essentially conservative,
family-centered personal values with the looser morality of his
mentor and partner?
</P>
<P>
   Gore will not say. He declined requests for an interview for
this article, and in responding to written questions a spokeswoman
said the Lewinsky matter had been studied exhaustively for two
years by an independent counsel, Congress and the press. She added
that the vice president did not discuss his private conversations
with the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has made clear a number of times that the president is his
friend, but he was as disappointed as all Americans were by the
president's personal mistake,'' said the spokeswoman, Laura Quinn.
``The vice president shares the view of all Americans that it is
time to turn the page and focus on the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore frequently refers to Clinton's ``mistake,'' without ever
specifying what he means. Was the mistake getting involved with
Lewinsky? Lying about it under oath? Deceiving the public, his
family, his staff and his vice president?
</P>
<P>
   ``Res ipsa loquitur,'' replied Gore's chief campaign spokesman,
Chris Lehane, using a legal term from Latin that means ``the thing
speaks for itself.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Did Clinton ever apologize directly to Gore for the affair or
the deception? If so, neither man is saying, and Gore would be one
of the few to have received an apology. Spokesmen for Clinton and
Gore say any such conversations were private and will remain so.
But two White House advisers say they suspect that Clinton offered
some sort of apology to Gore that August night in the limousine.
</P>
<P>
   When pressed in interviews to say how he views the president's
conduct, Gore has always tried to escape the subject as quickly as
possible. His most extensive comments were made to Diane Sawyer of
ABC News as he was beginning his presidential campaign last spring.
He evaded one question that dealt with his learning the truth of
the Lewinsky affair, saying, ``You can imagine how I felt.''
Pressed further, he said, ``What he did was inexcusable, and
particularly as a father I felt that it was terribly wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   When Sawyer asked directly if the president had lied to him, he
replied, ``Certainly the impression that he gave me and the others
that he worked with was not the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   More recently, Gore has ducked the issue entirely. When Jay Leno
asked him on ``The Tonight Show'' how he could remain a friend of
the president while distancing himself from the Lewinsky affair,
the vice president's body tensed, and his face became a rigid mask.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you ever have a friend who made a mistake?'' he answered.
``I'm running for president on my own, with my own vision.''
</P>
<P>
   Out of the public eye, Gore has struggled with his feelings
about Clinton and the Lewinsky scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Roy Neel, a longtime aide to Gore and one of his best friends,
said that the matter had left the vice president alienated from
Clinton but that the two remained ``mutually supportive,'' at least
on a political level.
</P>
<P>
   And on a personal level?
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't even venture to guess what's in his heart of hearts,''
Neel said of the vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Gore, two moderate Southern baby boomers, seemed a
perfect fit when they first came together in 1992, campaigning by
bus across the country to the sound of Fleetwood Mac and cheering
crowds.
</P>
<P>
   But their public camaraderie masked an intense rivalry and
mutual wariness. Clinton, who had assiduously avoided the draft as
a young man and was now already suspected of extramarital
dalliances, was disappointed that Gore did not defend him more
forcefully that fall in a debate with Vice President Dan Quayle,
who said Clinton lacked the character and integrity to be
president. Despite their apparent close relationship during the
campaign, it soon became clear that contrary to Clinton's early
assertions that they would have an unusually close governing
partnership, he would not be operating any kind of co-presidency,
at least not with Gore.
</P>
<P>
   The Lewinsky scandal only added to an unbridgeable distance
between them.
</P>
<P>
   Yet throughout the investigation and the impeachment battle,
Gore was stalwart in his public defense of the president, while
keeping his private doubts entirely private, even from his closest
friends and advisers.
</P>
<P>
   When the scandal first broke, Gore said, ``The president has
denied the charges, and I believe him.'' He added then, as he has
so many times since, ``He is not only the president of our country,
but he is my friend.''
</P>
<P>
   A week later, the vice president introduced Clinton at a raucous
rally in Champaign, Ill. His hands slashing the air and his voice
rising to a shout, Gore said, ``I want to ask you now, every single
one of you, to join me in supporting him and standing by his
side!''
</P>
<P>
   Those statements stood as Gore's public testament for seven long
months, until Clinton finally confessed his version of the truth to
the vice president, Hillary Rodham Clinton, the White House staff
and ultimately the grand jury and the public.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's wife, Tipper, was outraged at both the president's
actions and his breach of trust, friends say. Her unforgiving view
of the affair affected Gore's attitude then and now, according to
these associates. She has appeared at few White House functions in
the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, between denial and confession, what did Gore
believe? Most Americans _ even most White House officials and
Clinton loyalists _ suspected that something unseemly had occurred.
Was Gore the last person in Washington who thought Clinton wholly
innocent?
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a difference between believing something and wanting
to believe something,'' said the political consultant James
Carville, a friend of both Clinton and Gore. ``I'm sure he hoped it
wasn't true.''
</P>
<P>
   A senior adviser to the vice president said Gore's duties had
never included spiritual counsel to the president and that he could
thus plausibly claim ignorance of the truth of the Lewinsky affair.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Clinton may have been trying to protect Gore from
the matter by not involving him in scandal strategy sessions.
</P>
<P>
   But after the grand jury testimony _ and particularly after the
release of Starr's damning report _ Gore rose again to the
president's defense.
</P>
<P>
   On the day the House voted four articles of impeachment against
the president, Gore watched part of the proceedings with Clinton in
the private study off the Oval Office where Clinton sometimes met
with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not fair, what they've done to you,'' Gore told the
president just after the vote, according to an aide who was
present.
</P>
<P>
   Later that day, Gore introduced the president to an odd pep
rally of Democrats on the White House South Lawn.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the saddest day I have seen in our nation's capital,''
Gore told the die-hard throng. He chastised Republican leaders for
engineering the impeachment vote and said, in words that will most
likely provide fodder for Republican television advertisements this
fall, ``What happened as a result does a great disservice to a man
I believe will be regarded in the history books as one of our
greatest presidents.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
