<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-03 21:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6298 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-YANKS-JAYS-NYT &LR;      03-03 1138
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-JAYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIRARDI, SOJO AND DAVIS WILL BE MISSED 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. _ Players come and go every year, but a few leave a
small part of themselves behind, some trait that will be woven into
the fabric of the team for a year or two, or a generation of
players.
</P>
<P>
   It would be hard for anyone on the New York Yankees to gripe
about a lack of playing time without remembering Joe Girardi's
unselfishness, the way he tutored his successor at catcher without
any complaint.
</P>
<P>
   It would be hard for anyone to be unprepared for a game without
thinking of Luis Sojo, who might play twice a month at second base
and still be effective, and have fun doing it.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees will talk about an opposing pitcher in the dugout
between at-bats and think of designated hitter Chili Davis and how
much he liked to discuss hitting.
</P>
<P>
   But Girardi, Sojo and Davis are gone. So, too, is designated
hitter Darryl Strawberry, whose corner locker was cleaned out
before Friday's game, his equipment packed away, his nameplate
removed a few days after he was suspended from baseball for failing
a drug test.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees are beginning the process of adjusting to their
absence. They lost to Toronto, 7-2, Friday, their second defeat in
two days to the Blue Jays at the outset of this exhibition season.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan Bradley, among the most talented of the Yankees' pitching
prospects, continued to struggle with his mechanics. He allowed
five hits, four runs, a wild pitch and a hit batsman in two
innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a tough kid, but he's a little lost out there,'' Yankees
Manager Joe Torre said.
</P>
<P>
   If the regular season began Friday, the Yankees would be
scrambling for healthy pitchers. Orlando Hernandez was scratched
from his scheduled start in Saturday's exhibition against the
Pittsburgh Pirates because of a muscle strain in his back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel good,'' Hernandez repeated Friday in response to
virtually every question that related to his health.
</P>
<P>
   Ramiro Mendoza continues to suffer from what the Yankees believe
is bronchitis, but his treatment has been adjusted and he may be
told to stay at his apartment for a few days. Ed Yarnall, too, has
had a sore back. He hopes to throw in the bullpen in the next few
days.
</P>
<P>
   Girardi and Sojo were seen by their Yankees teammates as future
managers, smart men who had a knack for leadership and for adapting
to other personalities, and now Girardi is with the Chicago Cubs
and Sojo is with the Pirates. Davis would make a great hitting
coach, others say, now that he has retired. The three were
important to the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were a big part of the team, on and off the field,'' said
Paul O'Neill, who will one day leave his own keepsake of
personality.
</P>
<P>
   Willie Randolph, the third-base coach, said, ``We lost three
real good teammates, three good people, and those guys are going to
be missed.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees players lamented the departure of Tim Raines last
spring, feeling that his sense of humor, his easygoing nature and
his high-pitched laugh would be missed because he managed to keep
others from taking defeat and success too seriously.
</P>
<P>
   Sojo had filled some of that void. He, too, has an acute sense
of humor, has enjoyed a long career and has a deep knowledge of the
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He might be the most respected teammate I've ever been
around,'' David Cone said.
</P>
<P>
   Sojo speaks English, but his pronunciation of the language is
imperfect, and for the amusement of teammates, he would sometimes
accentuate the imperfections. Sojo would play intermittently,
sometimes after weeks of sitting on the bench, and he always
managed to do something significant with his awkward, flailing
swing, and then he would laugh about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Luis had a lot of fun playing, and you do need that throughout
the course of the season,'' O'Neill said. ``You need to laugh once
in awhile.''
</P>
<P>
   Sojo was very close to Derek Jeter, counseling him on his
defense. And Sojo devoted a lot of time to younger players,
particularly the younger Spanish-speaking players.
</P>
<P>
   Left fielder Ricky Ledee said if he had a bad day, Sojo would
make a point of asking him if he was all right. Randolph would go
to a restaurant late at night and he would see Sojo eating with the
younger players, like D'Angelo Jimenez or Alfonso Soriano.
</P>
<P>
   Girardi was the field leader when he played, Cone said. You knew
he was in control; you knew he would set a tone sprinting to and
from his position. Even as Girardi's playing time decreased and
Jorge Posada gradually developed into the Yankees' front-line
catcher, Girardi maintained his status as a clubhouse leader.
</P>
<P>
   Girardi sometimes spoke in team meetings, and it seemed to
others that his words were carefully chosen. And there was no doubt
everything he said was heartfelt.
</P>
<P>
   He called a meeting last May and told his teammates that he did
not like the way they were going about their business. His words
were sharp and direct, and others listened closely.
</P>
<P>
   Randolph spoke to Girardi in the winter and told him how much he
would be missed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's probably one of my top 10 all-time teammates,'' Randolph
said.
</P>
<P>
   Davis was with the Yankees for only two seasons, missing a
substantial period because of injury. In that time, teammates came
to appreciate his devotion to the craft of hitting. Some of the
Yankees were more comfortable waging their hitting wars privately,
but Davis would sit on the bench between each of his at-bats and
talk about what the opposing pitcher was trying to do, how he was
trying to get hitters out. He was a sounding board for others,
someone to compare notes with.
</P>
<P>
   He lingered in front of his locker after games, talking about
baseball. After Ed Yarnall's first spring training appearance with
the Yankees last year, Davis _ who had faced Yarnall in the game _
told the left-hander that his fastball was good enough to win with
in the majors, to keep pitching to his own strengths. The words
still resonate with Yarnall.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see a lot of guys are showered and walking out the door
quickly after games,'' Cone said. ``Chili was very old school in
that regard. We're going to miss that. It's hard to say who's going
to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have other leaders. Tino Martinez and O'Neill
continue to establish a high level of intensity, and each year,
Jeter takes on more responsibility. Cone often speaks for the team
en masse, something the others appreciate. Roger Clemens seemed to
make an overt attempt to blend in, but now he is in his second
season and might inject himself into a leadership role.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ideally, you'd like to have the exact same team,'' O'Neill
said. ``For me, Joe was probably my best friend I had on the team.
When you see people leave like that, you're going to miss them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
