<SLUG> BC-HKN-BOURQUE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS MUM ON BOURQUE   SPECULATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY MARRAPESE-BURRELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILMINGTON _ Ray Bourque and president/general manager Harry
Sinden declined to comment Friday on the increasing speculation
that the Bruins captain will be dealt to a Stanley Cup-contending
team before the March 14 trade deadline.
</P>
<P>
   The two men met Friday, but both said they elected not to talk
because there was nothing new.
</P>
<P>
   However, as unthinkable as it may seem that Bourque would ever
play in a different uniform, recent events could prompt him to
change teams _ perhaps as early as today. A source close to both
sides said Bourque will change clubs _ it's just a matter of when _
and other sources indicated Friday that the team getting Bourque's
services will be Philadelphia, Detroit, Dallas, St. Louis, or
Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   A look at the key reasons it will happen:
</P>
<P>
   --Injuries: A few days ago, Bourque believed the Bruins were
still a contender for a playoff berth. However, the team's abysmal
performance against Montreal Thursday indicates that even if it was
to claw its way into the top eight, there is no hope of going far,
given the losses of Jason Allison, Anson Carter, and Byron Dafoe.
Carter announced Friday he will have wrist surgery soon and that
his season is over. It's unlikely No. 1 goalie Dafoe will be back,
either, after undergoing an arthroscopy on his right knee Friday.
The talent level of this team is so thin, the consistency so
lacking, that a playoff miss is all but guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
   --Coaching: Bourque has been a big booster of coach Pat Burns,
especially in the worst of times. He has never been a controversial
figure in his 21-year career and has always been loyal to the
organization. But Bourque's vocal support of Burns after the coach
came under fire from team ownership was eye-opening. Bourque is
rumored to have been very upset with management about the way Burns
was being hung out to dry, but Bourque steadfastly maintained that
rumor is false. Bourque felt there was plenty of blame to go
around.
</P>
<P>
   --No Stanley Cups: Five Norris trophies and perennial trips to
the All-Star Game aside, Bourque's most cherished moments as a
professional were the two years _ 1988 and '90 _ he went to the
Stanley Cup finals. He enjoyed going through what he called ``the
wars'' of each round as the stakes went higher and higher. Since
it's clear the Bruins aren't going near the finals this year, it
makes sense that Bourque have one more shot _ especially since this
may be his last year.
</P>
<P>
   --His stance: Bourque has consistently said that if he won a
Cup, he wanted to do it in Boston. Bourque briefly considered
changing teams during the horrid 1996-97 season when it was clear
the Bruins were going to finish dead last. Beyond that, he always
said he would finish his career in the Black and Gold. He planned
to win a Cup in Boston, or not at all. But in the last few days,
Bourque hasn't nixed the idea. He hasn't confirmed he wanted to
change teams, especially because he believed the Bruins still had a
chance. Now that it appears they are headed for an early offseason,
it seems obvious Bourque is considering it.
</P>
<P>
   --Family: Bourque's family has always meant everything to him.
He has three children who are old enough to lead busy lives. If
Bourque were to play for another team for a couple of months, he
wouldn't have to uproot his wife and kids.
</P>
<P>
   If Bourque were traded, the question is: What would the Bruins
receive in return? No team that believes it has a real shot at the
Cup is going to give up a player of importance. Given that Bourque
would likely not have the same dominant role with a loaded team
would decrease his value. Add that to his age and it's likely
Bourque would net a draft pick, which would help Boston's
rebuilding status.
</P>
<P>
   If the Flyers were to get Bourque, he would be met there with
open arms.
</P>
<P>
   ``From what I've heard it's something that, you know, I think
it's not a bad thing for hockey or for him,'' said defenseman Eric
Desjardins, who practiced with his teammates at Northeastern
Friday. ``He's played 21 years here and he feels his chances to win
with the Bruins are not good . . . why not? I think he deserves it.
He's played so hard for the Bruins.''
</P>
<P>
   Desjardins said he likes the Flyers' chances to go deep into the
playoffs, but the addition of Bourque would be a big plus.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, when you have a player like him on your team, you
improve by a lot,'' he said. ``We have what it takes to go all the
way; it's what I believe. If you have a guy like Ray on the team,
it gives you a lot more chance to go all the way.''
</P>
<P>
   Flyers captain Eric Lindros said it would be strange to see
Bourque in a different uniform given that he's so closely
associated with the Black and Gold.
</P>
<P>
   ``To gain a player like Ray Bourque, a player of his character,
stature, and demeanor, just the way he handles himself on and off
the ice, you're picking up a fine hockey player.''
</P>
<P>
   The buzz is definitely in the air despite both sides staying
mum. Local sports radio station WEEI is saying a deal for Bourque
is already done, although the Bruins deny that vehemently.
Management said there is no indication any deal will be made to add
to the struggling squad or to accommodate Bourque's wishes to end
his career with a Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have so many players out that it's difficult to do right
now,'' said O'Connell when asked, in general, about making a trade.
``We haven't ruled anything out but people who are looking to do
something in the playoffs don't necessarily want your injured
players. There's nothing going as of yet but there's still some
time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-03-00 2118EST &QL; 
