<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE'S NO BEATING BIG LEAGUE EXPERIENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT MYERS, FLA. _ If it's a regular Red Sox spring training
game, the entire visiting team isn't standing on the top of the
dugout watching the home team take batting practice.
</P>
<P>
   And if it's a regular college game, the school's athletic
director isn't watching his own team take B.P.
</P>
<P>
   For the big league team, it's a peculiar irritation, a spring
training game that really isn't a spring training game, a game that
has only two conceivable outcomes: validation or humiliation.
</P>
<P>
   For the college team, it is a fantasy game, a chance to tell the
grandchildren about the day grandpa either batted against
fill-in-the-blank or whiffed Mr. X, the noted big leaguer.
</P>
<P>
   For Friday night at City of Palms Park the Red Sox played their
annual spring training game against Boston College. Call it the
photo album game. This is the night when the mothers, fathers,
aunts, uncles, grandparents, brothers, and sisters snap away,
proving to whoever will later need to know that, yes, our
Billy/Mike/Andy/Jarett/Whomever really did get to play a game
against the Boston Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   ``For our kids, this is the experience of a lifetime,'' says
Boston College coach Peter Hughes, a Brockton native. ``For me,
it's also the experience of a lifetime, since I grew up rooting for
the Red Sox. This game is everything for us in terms of recruiting.
We can say to kids that if they come to B.C. they will play against
the Red Sox in spring training and they will play in Fenway Park
during the Beanpot.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is big for us,'' confirms athletic director Gene
DeFilippo. ``Our kids get to play here and dress here. The Red Sox
are just wonderful to us. They put on a nice buffet before the game
for the alumni. I can't say enough about them.''
</P>
<P>
   It is, of course, lose-lose for the Red Sox and win-win for the
B.C. Eagles. So what if a Red Sox pitcher goes six-up, six down? So
what if a regular hits one halfway to Sarasota? Against Boston
College you're supposed to do these things, no?
</P>
<P>
   Ah, but for B.C. there is no real down side. True, the B.C.
officials were a bit worried four years ago when they came off a
19-0 loss in 1995 with an even more gruesome 22-0 loss that
featured a first inning in which the Red Sox scored 13 runs before
the Eagles retired a man. In fact, from 1994-1998, the combined
score was 76-2. But Red Sox CEO John Harrington, (B.C. '57 with a
Masters in '66) assured the folks at The Heights that the series
would continue.
</P>
<P>
   He might have been reconsidering that position last year, when,
with two outs in the seventh and final inning and his alma mater
trailing his ball club by a 4-3 score, there were men on first and
second and 6-foot-7 inch Sean McGowan, arguably the nation's
leading collegiate power hitter, striding to the plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know what to do,'' says Hughes. ``I didn't know what
I was supposed to feel. I knew that it definitely wasn't going to
be a good idea to beat them. I mean, after all that flap during the
offseason with Mo, now we're at the start of spring training, the
first game, and they might lose to us?''
</P>
<P>
   So here was McGowan, who would wind up with gaudy .430-25-70
Triple Crown stats, who slugged a stratospheric .916 and who is now
a valued prospect (third round) with the San Francisco Giants, at
the plate. What if he put one over the palm trees?
</P>
<P>
   ``Sean was a great fastball hitter,'' Hughes recalls, ``and when
he was up there we verbalized to him, `Inside fastball.' And he got
an inside fastball! But he didn't get the head of the bat out there
fast enough, and he grounded out. So it worked out real well. They
beat us by one, and we outhit them.''
</P>
<P>
   Keep your eye on the Boston College baseball program. DeFilippo
is committed to making B.C. a force in the Big East, and when Mo
Moloney left the post following the 1998 season, he sifted through
an astounding number of applications before deciding on Hughes, who
had been the head coach at Trinity College in San Antonio for two
seasons. Hughes presided over a team of bashers who hit a
you've-gotta-be-kidding-me .354 while establishing a season high in
victories. The 26-21 Eagles averaged 7.5 runs. The only problem was
that they gave up an average of 8.2.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a guy who always believed in hitting and scoring a lot
of runs,'' Hughes says. ``Last year made a believer out of me. We
can hit with anybody. But we've got to find some kids who can throw
strikes.''
</P>
<P>
   These games ordinarily bear little resemblance to a real affair
_ for either team. Red Sox manager Jimy Williams starts a veteran
lineup, but one at-bat for the regulars is the norm. After that
you're looking at the players they'll be seeing in Trenton and
Pawtucket. But they're still professionals, and they are wearing
the timeless white uniform with the red lettering.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes, meanwhile, has a solemn obligation. ``We put in more
time preparing for this game than any other on our schedule,'' he
says. ``We have to make sure we get nine pitchers and 19 position
players into the game.''
</P>
<P>
   But this doesn't mean coach Hughes ignores his competitive
juices. In the midst of all his substitutions last year, isn't it
interesting that when Sonny Nictakis and Scott Foley reached base
in the ninth, Mr. McGowan just happened to be the next man up with
the game hanging in the balance?
</P>
<P>
   There were some nice B.C. moments last night. Starter Andy
Sullivan fanned Jose Offerman and Mike Stanley in a scoreless
first. Brian Durkin ripped a low outside Jason Sekany pitch down
the right-field line to score Neal McCarthy and give B.C. a 1-0
lead in the second. Shortstop Mike Hubbard made a sensational stop
of an Israel Alcantara smash for a great forceout at second to end
the third. Scott Foley made a leaping four-star robbery grab of an
Andy Sheets liner. Chris Rosado hawked a Gary Rath pitch over the
left-field fence in the seventh. B.C. looked like a ball club, all
right.
</P>
<P>
   But by the seventh-inninmg stretch, it was 6-3, pros. In other
words, both managers were happy men.
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-03-00 2121EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000303.0331 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-03 21:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6303 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-INDEPENDENT-ADS-ART-2     03-03 0710
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDEPENDENT-ADS-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: other votes.   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The commercials are part of a rapid expansion in the use of
so-called issue advertising. Issue ads can be paid for by the
political parties _ a technique President Clinton used to his
advantage in 1996 _ or by outside interest groups. As long as they
do not contain overt appeals to vote for or against specific
candidates and are not directly coordinated with a candidate, they
are as a rule not subject to regulation under campaign finance
laws, meaning that the sources and amounts of money behind them do
not have to be disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   While some of the groups behind issue advertising are vague
about their membership, Wyly's effort was a rare instance in which
commercials were aired without any hint of their origin.
</P>
<P>
   ``The secrecy aspects of this are taking campaign finance
problems to yet another new and dangerous level,'' said Fred
Wertheimer, president of Democracy 21, a group advocating tighter
campaign finance laws. ``What we're seeing here is the use of
unlimited, undisclosed money to influence a federal election, and
that's totally at odds with the whole notion of campaign finance
disclosure.''
</P>
<P>
   The campaign finance laws are fuzzy about what it takes for
issue advertising to step over the line into run-of-the-mill
political appeals. The McCain campaign's argument Friday was that
Wyly, his family and his advisers, in putting the commercials on
the air, did not need formal consultations with the Bush camp to
know that their effort would amount to a direct boost for their
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Wyly and his brother, Charles, gave more than $200,000 to Bush's
two gubernatorial campaigns in Texas. Charles Wyly is a
``Pioneer,'' the designation given to the top fund-raisers for
Bush's presidential campaign, those who have brought in at least
$100,000. An investment fund run by the Wylys has received business
from the University of Texas, whose board was appointed by Bush.
</P>
<P>
   A Republican political consultant from Texas who helped to put
the commercials on the air, Jeb Hensarling, was once a business
associate of the chairman of the Pioneers, James B. Francis Jr.,
one of Bush's closest friends and advisers. The advertising firm
that bought time on television stations for the commercials in New
York has a long record of working with Gov. George E. Pataki, who
is helping to run the Bush campaign in New York.
</P>
<P>
   People in the Bush camp said they knew of no communication
between Wyly and his team and the Bush campaign concerning the
advertising. Francis, for example, said in an interview that he had
not even spoken to Hensarling in about six months.
</P>
<P>
   Wyly said he had been thinking for some time about creating an
organization, Republicans for Clean Air, to promote his message
that the party should do more to clean up air pollution. Wyly owns
a stake in a power company, GreenMountain.com, that bills itself as
producing and selling electric power generated with a minimum of
environmental damage _ a claim disputed by environmentalists.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain's campaign said that Wyly had frequently donated
money to Republicans judged by environmental groups to have less
than sterling reputations on working for clean air and water. And
they said that it could not be a coincidence that Wyly chose the
days leading up to the most critical round of primaries in the
campaign to begin airing the commercials in New York, California
and Ohio, the three states with the most delegates at stake.
</P>
<P>
   Wyly went public Friday after the McCain campaign on Thursday
raised questions with the Federal Communications Commission _ which
McCain oversees in his role as chairman of the Senate Commerce
Committee _ about whether the commercials adequately disclosed who
was paying for them.
</P>
<P>
   The McCain campaign did not raise the issue of campaign finance
laws, but rather whether the commercials met a requirement of the
Communications Act of 1934, which holds that television stations
must say who has paid for commercials other than product
advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Rob Allyn, a media consultant to Wyly, said that Wyly was now
providing stations and networks with additional documentation, and
that the commercials would run as scheduled through Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
