<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HACKER-SUSPECT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALLEGED HACKER UNDER STATE, FEDERAL SCRUTINY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAMAL E. WATSON AND RAFAEL LEWIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WOLFSBORO, N.H. _ Dennis Moran's life had been fairly
unremarkable until FBI agents showed up at his door. They wanted to
talk to him and then they took the 17-year-old's most prized
possessions: three computers Moran says he used to hack into three
secure Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been pretty boring without the computers,'' said Moran,
who describes himself as a loner with few friends in this small
town on the shores of Lake Winnipesaukee.
</P>
<P>
   For the past two weeks, Moran has been under investigation by
federal and state authorities after they said he used his screen
name ``Coolio'' to penetrate secured Web sites operated by a
leading computer security company, and DARE.com, a national
anti-drug Web site managed by the Los Angeles Police Department.
Phillip McLaughlin, the New Hampshire attorney general, said
charges of computer related crimes may be filed soon against Moran.
</P>
<P>
   Moran could face up to 15 years in prison and as much as a
$4,000 fine, McLaughlin said.
</P>
<P>
   But Moran seems unfazed by the possibility of jail. For the
moment, his biggest concern appears to be his confiscated
computers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I just read books and watch the news,'' he said
standing in a cluttered three-bedroom apartment that he shares with
his father and two younger sisters. ``It would be nice to have
those computers back, and the FBI agents said that they plan to
return them to me sometime. When? I actually don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   McLaughlin said investigators are combing through computer
records to gather evidence that could be used against Moran.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our job at this point is very mechanical. We're trying to
collect sufficient evidence through mountains of data, and that is
taking us longer than we had hoped,'' McLaughlin said. ``Our
investigation has been going on about three weeks. It's based on
having technicians carefully scrutinize the evidence. It's computer
forensics, basically.''
</P>
<P>
   Authorities are also investigating whether Moran was responsible
for the attacks last month on YAHOO! and Amazon.com, two major
electronic-commerce companies. The sites were shut down for hours
after they were bombarded with simultaneous messages, authorities
said.
</P>
<P>
   But Moran denied hacking into those two sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``I jokingly told a few friends in a chat room that I did it,
but I really did not,'' he said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The teenager said he regrets hacking into two of the Web sites _
a US Commerce Department site that sets rules for exporting
chemicals that could be used to produce weapons, and Rsa.com, a
leading Internet security firm _ but said he had no second thoughts
about infiltrating DARE's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't regret hacking into the DARE site at all,'' Moran
said. ``The organization puts out misleading propaganda, and I
think that drugs should be legalized.''
</P>
<P>
   Moran said he dropped out of Kingwood Regional High School last
year because he became ``bored.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I generally keep to myself and stay inside the house,'' he
said, adding that most of his friends are people he met online.
</P>
<P>
   Camera crews and reporters swarmed around Moran's apartment
Friday, leaving this small, quaint town of 5,000 people overwhelmed
by the national attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the biggest thing to happen in Wolfsboro in a long
time,'' said Johanna Kent, 16, who attended school with Moran last
year. ``He was the kind of person who always wanted to get
attention, but I never thought he had the ability to do something
like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Grace Napoli, 73, a longtime resident of the town said she was
outraged by Moran's actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``These young children have too much time on their hands,'' she
said. ``Where were his parents? Why weren't they supervising their
child's behavior on the Internet? I don't understand.''
</P>
<P>
   Moran's father, Dennis F. Moran Sr., who works as a computer
consultant for a small company in Londonderry, N.H., could not be
reached for comment. The younger Moran said that the two have not
spoken about the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, an increase in computer hacking incidents has
forced the US Justice Department to crack down after several high
profile cases. Two weeks ago, a Northeastern University student was
charged with hacking into the computer systems of several federal
agencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Attorney General (Janet) Reno had a meeting in Palo Alto
(Calif.) a few weeks ago to talk about coordinating expertis to
combat hacking,'' McLaughlin said. ``She made one point abundantly
clear: this kind of situation is not going to go away any time
soon, so we have to be much better prepared.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan Kazanciyan, 18, a computer science and economics major at
Duke University calls himself a former hacker.
</P>
<P>
   He has designed and maintains a former underground Web site
called hideaway.net that focuses on computer security.
</P>
<P>
   ``Honestly, everyone tries to make themselves well-known. It's
hard to know who's genuine and who isn't,'' he said. ``A lot of
people brag about amazing hacks, and it's true. A lot of people
brag, and it isn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Kazanciyan said he believes that hacking is far more pervasive
than authorities are willing to admit. ``I guarantee that at least
half to three-quarters of all teenagers on the Internet have at
least dabbled with these programs. It's no longer like you're a
geek if you can work your way around a computer. Now it's getting
to the point where you're the cool one. You have power. That's an
amusing turn of affairs.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, McLaughlin said, the fact is hacking is against the law.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who live in the year 2000, even if they're young, have
the same obligations we've always had: You don't hurt your
neighbor, you don't hurt your friends, you don't hurt your
government,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Moran said he doesn't know what all the fuss is about. He claims
he inflicted very little damage and acknowledges that he is only
``semi-concerned with going to prison.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I did something that a lot of people can't do,'' Moran said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
