A6305 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-COKE-PROXY0304-COX     03-03 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-PROXY0304-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Severance deal worth millions to ex-Coke chairman
 &HT;    By David McNaughton
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If Coca-Cola cut a check today to cover all future
benefits former Chairman M. Douglas Ivester could receive as part
of his severance, it would be about $14million.
</P>
<P>
   The severance deal also gives him immediate access to 335,000
shares of formerly restricted Coca-Cola stock, worth about $16.8
million as of Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The $14 million figure is the estimated present value of what
Ivester, and his wife, Kay, will get over their lifetimes because
of the separation agreement he signed with the company.
</P>
<P>
   Ivester, who will be 53 on March 26, stunned the business
community in December by announcing he would retire this spring,
saying Coca-Cola would ``be best served by fresh leadership.'' He
wound up leaving in mid-February.
</P>
<P>
   Last year was the first ``in recent history'' in which no top
executive at Atlanta-based Coca-Cola was paid a bonus, according to
spokesman Chuck Reece. It was a year marked by declining profits,
dismal stock performance, troubled acquisitions and a massive
recall of the company's soft drinks in parts of Europe after a
health scare.
</P>
<P>
   As part of his separation package, Ivester receives:
</P>
<P>
   _ Payments of $1.5 million in February of this year and in
February of 2001 and 2002. The payments are in lieu of bonuses
Ivester might have gotten in the future, had he stayed at
Coca-Cola.
</P>
<P>
   _ Monthly payments of about $66,300 from now until March 2002,
when Ivester will be 55.
</P>
<P>
   _ Monthly payments of about $56,300, starting in April 2002, and
continuing as long as Ivester and his wife live. That's apart from
his monthly retirement benefit, which will run about $58,700 a
month.
</P>
<P>
   _ Consulting fees of $675,000 a year from 2002 through 2007.
</P>
<P>
   _ Title to his company car _ a 1996 Mercury Grand Marquis _ plus
``suitable office space and secretarial services, maintenance of
home security systems and club dues for existing clubs'' until May
1, 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Ivester had no employment contract, according to Reece. The
separation package was approved _ after his retirement decision _
to fulfill four goals of the board of directors, Reece said.
</P>
<P>
   One was to ``help ensure a smooth and orderly transition,'' he
said. ``Another was to recognize Mr. Ivester for his many
contributions during his 20 years with the company.''
</P>
<P>
   The board also wanted to retain Ivester as a consultant, as well
as keep him from competing against Coca-Cola in the non-alcoholic
beverage industry, Reece added.
</P>
<P>
   Under Coca-Cola's agreement with Ivester, he cannot compete
against the company for seven years, according to Reece.
</P>
<P>
   Has Ivester indicated an interest in competing against
Coca-Cola?
</P>
<P>
   ``Not to my knowledge,'' Reece said. The non-compete clause was
included to protect the interests of Coca-Cola, he added.
</P>
<P>
   The proxy statement that outlines Ivester's benefits includes
the fact he received a salary boost in mid-1999, to an annual rate
of $1.5 million, from $1.25 million. It was his first salary boost
in 23 months, the proxy statement notes.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his severance, Ivester got immediate access to an
additional 1,615,000 shares of restricted stock. That came under
conditions of an early retirement program Coca-Cola offered as part
of its plan to cut 6,000 jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Ivester also received a $3 million benefit in immediate access
to outstanding stock options.
</P>
<P>
   All told, Ivester owns or has the rights to 4.4 million shares
of Coca-Cola, worth $221 million.
</P>
<P>
   The proxy statement does not disclose how much Ivester's
successor, Doug Daft, or President Jack Stahl will make in their
new jobs. Information on that will be disclosed in next year's
proxy.
</P>
<P>
   Daft, formerly head of Coca-Cola's Asia, Mideast and Africa
operations, was paid $459,833 in salary last year and was awarded
options for 125,000 shares of stock. His annual base pay was
boosted to $750,000 in December when he was named president and
chief operating officer.
</P>
<P>
   Stahl, formerly head of Coca-Cola's U.S and Latin America
operations, was paid a salary of $485,000 in 1999, and also got
options on 125,000 shares of Coca-Cola.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which has thousands of stockholders in Georgia,
will hold its annual meeting April 19 in Wilmington, Del. Among the
issues to be voted on is a proposal to end bonuses and stock option
programs.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
