<SLUG> BC-BKC-CREMINS0304-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cremins wants win for seniors, to avoid Duke
 &HT;    By J.C. Clemons
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Georgia Tech basketball fans wish nothing other than
the best for Bobby Cremins, who today coaches his last home game as
Yellow Jackets boss.
</P>
<P>
   However, one Cremins desire won't be acknowledged this afternoon
at Alexander Memorial Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game is going to be for the seniors,'' Cremins said
Friday about Tech's regular-season finale against Clemson.
``Everybody has been great to me, and the accolades have been
incredible. But I don't want the focus to be on me.''
</P>
<P>
   But with Cremins announcing two weeks ago that he would not
return for a 20th season as the Jackets' coach, the crowd will
express lots of sentiment for the 52-year-old native New Yorker who
made Tech basketball magical.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've asked Georgia Tech not to do anything,'' Cremins said.
``I'll come back in a few years, hopefully, and watch a great
Georgia Tech basketball team. ... I'm fine with everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure there is going to be some emotion, but I know it's
over for me. It's time for Bobby Cremins to move on. ... I just
want to go play the game, get out and go play the ACC Tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not as if the Jackets (12-16, 4-11 ACC) do not have
anything to play for. A win over the Tigers (10-18, 4-11) would
allow Tech to avoid opening the ACC Tournament against top-seeded
Duke at 9 p.m. Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, a reversal of last month's 70-58 defeat at Clemson
would land the Jackets in a first-round match at 7 p.m. Thursday
against the loser of Sunday's N.C. State-Florida State game.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Cremins is dreaming of a 5-0 run to the ACC
Tournament championship that would make his exit grander than his
arrival. Even with a win today, the Jackets would have to at least
make the ACC title game just to qualify for an NIT berth.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, though, Cremins _ the winningest coach in Georgia
Tech annals _ would settle for just one more triumph.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm more concerned about Clemson than anything. There's a lot
on the line'' he said. ``We are playing better, and I'm proud of
the way the team has responded.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, though, that Jackets' magic has vanished.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was three or four weeks ago; I could just see it wasn't
coming together,'' Cremins said. ``What caused it? I don't know.
All I know is I failed in my attempt to get us back.
</P>
<P>
   `` It just wasn't there.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
