<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-INVESTOR-650(TRIM)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUCCESS ELUDED EX-COCA-COLA CHIEF, BUT BIG RETIREMENT DEAL DIDN'T 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ga.)  (ko) 
 By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Coca-Cola's former chairman and chief executive left the company
last month after two turbulent years in which Coke's growth
stagnated, its earnings fell, and its image became stained by
problems like the biggest product recall in company history and a
racial-discrimination lawsuit. So dismal was the company's
performance in 1999 that no one in Coke's top management got a
bonus.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the executive, Douglas Ivester, is walking away
with a generous bon-voyage package: $17.8 million in payments and
benefits including stock options that can be immediately vested and
the release of nearly 2 million shares of formerly restricted stock
worth about $97.7 million at the close of trading on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   When Ivester announced that he was stepping down from the top
job at Coke, at the age of 52, he and others at the company
described the move as a voluntary retirement. But the details of
the payments to be made to him, upon that retirement, create the
impression that Ivester departed on less than the best terms with
the board.
</P>
<P>
   A Coke spokesman said the board offered Ivester the retirement
package for reasons that included expressing appreciation for the
20 years he had worked for Coke and wanting to ensure a smooth
transition for Douglas Daft, who became chairman and chief
executive last month.
</P>
<P>
   The board also wanted to retain Ivester, who is no longer a
director, as a consultant and ``to preclude Mr. Ivester from
competing in the nonalcoholic beverage industry'' until 2007, said
the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   The package includes $704,400 in annual pension payments, plus
an additional $795,600 a year beginning this month and continuing
until March 2002, when Ivester turns 55. At that point, Ivester
will begin receiving $675,600 a year, beyond his pension, through
his lifetime and that of his wife, Kay.
</P>
<P>
   He will also be paid $1.5 million a year for three years,
starting this year, in lieu of what he might have received under
long-term incentive plans that Coke offers its senior executives.
Elsewhere the proxy notes that ``neither Ivester nor Daft earned an
award for the performance period ended Dec. 31, 1999.'' And Ivester
will receive $675,000 a year for ``consulting services'' from 2002
through 2007, the proxy said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes a company will structure a severance package to make
it seem as if they are getting something back,'' noted Graef
Crystal, a compensation expert and a columnist for Bloomberg
Business News. ``But if I were him, I would not take my consulting
title so seriously as to start installing extra phone lines in my
house, because the lights are not going to go on at all.''
</P>
<P>
   One money manager expressed dismay at the size of the package,
which also includes a laptop computer, cellular phones, club dues
through May 2001 and the title to a 1996 Mercury Grand Marquis,
Ivester's company car.
</P>
<P>
   ``This compensation is outrageous, considering the mediocrity of
performance,'' said Fredric E. Russell, a Tulsa, Okla., money
manager who recently sold his stake in Coca-Cola. ``And it raises
serious questions about whether Coca-Cola can really be clear about
turning the ship around for its shareholders. This stands as a
monument to the close, cozy and perhaps nefarious relationship
between the board of directors and top management.''
</P>
<P>
   One analyst, Scott Wilkins of Deutsche Bank, said the package
covered Ivester's entire two-decade career at Coke and should be
viewed that way. ``He had a very important contribution toward
building the Coke model prior to taking the helm of the company,''
Wilkins said, ``and those last two years coincided with some very
turbulent times for the company.'' The proxy notes that no bonuses
were handed out to Ivester, Daft and other senior managers,
although they did get stock options of up to 250,000 shares each.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Also on Friday, Coke said it would not ask employees who are
being laid off or offered early retirement as a result of the
company's plan to cut 20 percent of its work force to give up their
rights to participate in the racial discrimination lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   The issue emerged a day after Coke announced on Jan. 26 that it
would lay off 6,000 people worldwide as part of a restructuring. In
order to receive better severance packages, employees had to sign
waivers that promised they would not take any legal action against
the company. While such waivers are commonplace, lawyers for the
plaintiffs in the racial-discrimination case said it put an unfair
burden on Coke's black employees, who might have joined a class
action against the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has contributed to confusion at a sensitive time for
employees departing our company,'' said Jack L. Stahl, Coke's
president, in a memo explaining the change.
</P>
<P>
   Stahl said in the memo that workers who had already signed
waivers would be contacted and their waivers canceled, and new
waivers would be issued to everyone affected by the layoffs. ``Our
goal all along has been to treat departing employees with the
dignity and respect befitting Coca-Cola people and minimize any
problems, not cause more anxiety,'' the memo said.
</P>
<P>
   Cyrus Mehri, a lawyer for the plaintiffs, said, ``This is a
triumph for all the courageous African-American employees who
challenged the company on this issue, and it will be better for
both the company and the employees.. A rally by those concerned
about the lawsuit is scheduled for Saturday in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
