<SLUG> BC-BKC-USCNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCALABRINE WILL TRY TO PLAY THROUGH PAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERKELEY, Calif. _ USC forward Brian Scalabrine was still
limping Friday from the strained hip he suffered against Stanford,
but said he would try to play today against California because the
Trojans' postseason hopes are in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mind is powerful,'' Scalabrine said. ``I'll convince
myself it doesn't hurt. I'm icing it like 150 times a day. I can
play. We need this game.''
</P>
<P>
   Scalabrine injured his hip Thursday during the first half of the
Trojans' 111-68 loss to Stanford while trying to change directions
on the court. He sat out the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have limited movement,'' Scalabrine said. ``It's not like a
pain, but your mind doesn't let you move it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans (14-13, 7-8) can ill afford to lose Scalabrine.
After weeks of mulling what they needed to do to make the NCAA
Tournament, they are now fighting just to stay in contention for a
bid to the National Invitation Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona State (16-11, 8-7) is probably a more attractive NIT
candidate because it draws larger crowds at home and features
explosive guard Eddie House, so the Trojans might have to sweep
their final three games for a bid.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to stop thinking about the NCAAs and NIT and just
look at Cal,'' Scalabrine said. ``We have to stop thinking we need
to go 3-1, or now 3-0, and look no further than the next game.''
</P>
<P>
   That said, Scalabrine refused to write off USC's NCAA chances
when assessing the remainder of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got blown away by Stanford, but if we finish 10-8 (in
conference), we would be in fourth place,'' he said. ``The last
five years, every team that finished 10-8 got in.''
</P>
<P>
   Clancy update: Forward Sam Clancy felt fine Friday after making
his highly anticipated return from a broken right foot against
Stanford. Clancy had four points and five rebounds in 18 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels good,'' Clancy said. ``There's no soreness today.''
</P>
<P>
   Clancy actually played more than USC coach Henry Bibby
anticipated against the Cardinal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought more than anybody against Stanford, Sam competed,''
Bibby said. ``He was physical. We haven't had that presence in a
while. He showed the promise of what he can create inside.''
</P>
<P>
   Ticket home: Bibby told injured forward Jarvis Turner (broken
ankle) he would send him home if he tried to grab another player by
the shorts during a game. Turner lunged out and grabbed Stanford
guard Casey Jacobsen by the shorts Thursday, and was quickly
assessed a technical foul.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he does it again, we send him home,'' Bibby said. ``That's
not something we stand for. He's trying to help the team, but he's
hurting the team. We don't condone that at USC.''
</P>
<P>
   A sheepish Turner tried to defend his actions, with limited
success.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just out of frustration. I wanted to win and I got
carried away and caught up in the emotion of the game,'' Turner
said. ``It was real stupid. I shouldn't have done it. I was
frustrated sitting on the bench all season.''
</P>
</TEXT>
