<SLUG> BC-ELECTRIC-CAR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GM RECALLS ELECTRIC CARS AND ADMITS IT CAN'T FIX DEFECT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Mass., Maine, N.Y.)  (jt) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ General Motors has said that half the electric cars
it has built have a safety defect and that it does not know if it
can fix them.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday the company asked 450 drivers who lease the cars,
EV-1's, to return them immediately, and possibly permanently.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this time, there's no known engineering solution,''
Jennifer L. Schmit, a spokeswoman for the company, said of the
defect in the recharging system.
</P>
<P>
   The problem affects a model leased from December 1996 until
August 1999, representing about half the EV-1's built. A second
generation car, also called the EV-1, uses a different part and is
not affected.
</P>
<P>
   Drivers who turn them in are ``going through an interview
process to determine what their needs are,'' Schmit said. They will
be offered gasoline-powered cars for temporary use, and can
terminate the lease, or, for more money, lease a newer version of
the car that does not have the defect, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The cars are recharged by inserting a frisbee-shaped power disk
into a slot on the hood. But on several cars, the slot and
surrounding components have been damaged by excessive heat, Schmit
said.
</P>
<P>
   John Hepke, director of propulsion engineering for GM's advanced
technology vehicles, said engineers could build a replacement part,
but it would be bigger. ``To find a space to package a fix into is
very difficult,'' he said. ``Every inch is taken up.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem also affects another electric vehicle, the S-10
pickup, but it has room for the replacement part.
</P>
<P>
   GM's director of advanced technology, Bob Purcell, said the EV-1
``remains a tremendous learning exercise for us.''
</P>
<P>
   The S-10 is no longer available. The EV-1 is, but production has
stopped; it will be resumed if demand warrants, the company said.
For new customers, the two-seater leases for $499 a month.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates for electric cars sought to minimize the setback and
emphasized that more recently built EV-1's are not affected.
``They've learned to make the car bigger and better as they've
learned the technology over time,'' said an official at the
Environmental Protection Agency.
</P>
<P>
   California, Massachusetts, Maine and New York plan to require
electric vehicles beginning in 2003.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
