<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Coke Gives Departing Chief $17.8 Million Pay Package
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola will pay M. Douglas Ivester, its former chairman and
chief executive who left last month, $17.8 million in payments and
other benefits and release nearly two million shares of formerly
restricted stock worth about $97.7 million. The package includes
$704,400 in annual pension payments, plus an additional $795,600 a
year beginning this month and continuing until March 2002, when
Ivester turns 55. At that point, Ivester will begin receiving
$675,600 a year, beyond his pension, through his lifetime and that
of his wife, Kay. He will also receive a laptop computer, cellular
phones, club dues through May 2001 and the title to a 1996 Mercury
Grand Marquis _ his company car.
</P>
<P>
   McCaw Drops Plan to Buy Iridium
</P>
<P>
   The cellular telephone pioneer Craig McCaw is dropping plans to
acquire Iridium, the troubled global satellite telephone company
that filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection last August. Wall
Street analysts said the move left Iridium on the brink of
collapse. On Monday, the company is scheduled to lose access to $5
million in emergency financing under a bankruptcy court agreement.
</P>
<P>
   No Merger of Nasdaq and Big Board
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq stock market and the New York Stock Exchange,
historically bitter competitors, have held informal discussions
regarding a possible merger, but nothing came of the talks.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton to Propose China Trade Bill
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton plans to submit a bill to Congress that would
permanently normalize trade relations with Beijing. The accelerated
timetable answers calls from pro-trade members of Congress who have
urged the Clinton administration to push for an early vote despite
mounting signs that it will be a tough sell in an election year.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks Surge on Economic Report
</P>
<P>
   Stocks soared after the government's report on unemployment
allayed concern that the Federal Reserve would have to push
interest rates sharply higher. The Nasdaq composite index rose
160.28 points, or 3.37 percent, to a record 4,914.79. The Dow Jones
industrial average was up 202.28 points, or 1.99 percent, to
10,367.20. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index increased 27.41
points, to 1,409.17.
</P>
<P>
   Dispute Over Debt Roils Thailand
</P>
<P>
   Authorities in Thailand are struggling to resolve a dispute
between Thai Petrochemical Industry and its creditors over debts of
$3.5 billion. The dispute has already accelerated an exodus of
foreign funds from Thailand's stock markets and could affect the
country's economy as well as the company.
</P>
<P>
   Borders Moves to Raise Share Price
</P>
<P>
   The bookseller Borders Group has hired Merrill Lynch to explore
steps it might take to bolster its faltering stock price. Such
steps might include a recapitalization, a leveraged buyout, or a
merger with another company.
</P>
<P>
   GM Recalls Defective Cars
</P>
<P>
   General Motors has recalled half of the electric cars it has
built for a safety defect it does not know how to fix. Customers
who have the cars, which are available through leases, have been
asked to return them immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Manor Care Shares Gain on Offer
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Manor Care rose 28 percent after the nursing home
operator received competing buyout offers from its chairman,
Stewart Bainum Jr., and its senior management.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican and Spanish Banks in Talks
</P>
<P>
   The Mexican branch of the Spanish financial company Banco Bilbao
Vizcaya Argentaria is talking with Mexico's second-largest bank,
Grupo Financiero Bancomer, about alliances and capitalization in
Mexico.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
