<SLUG> BC-STAPLES-INTERNET-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STAPLES GETS BOOST FROM SUCCESS OF IPO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH HEALY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Staples Inc. reaped its first reward from its venture capital
arm Friday, when New York's Register.com Inc. went public and
surged more than 138 percent in its first day of trading.
</P>
<P>
   Staples invested about $7 million in Register.com, a domain-name
registry, in May. Staples holds about 3 million shares, according
to regulatory filings, which were worth $171.8 million at the close
of trading Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Register.com's shares jumped to $57.25 from an IPO price of $24
per share.
</P>
<P>
   The news appeared not to move Wall Street, which pummeled
Staples shares Thursday after the Framingham-based office-supply
giant said its online division, Staples.com, would run up $150
million in losses this year, double the expectation. Staples shares
gained 13 cents Friday, after tumbling $4.69 on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   David Barry, senior editor at Private Equity Analyst in
Wellesley, observed that investors may have to start paying more
attention to the venture capital operations of Staples and other
big companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The majority of these corporations are making investments for
strategic purposes,'' he said. ``But the pace at which they're
going public has enabled these companies to accumulate some great
returns.''
</P>
<P>
   Staples jumped into the growing corporate venture arena last
year, following big players including Intel Corp., Microsoft Corp.,
and Lucent Technologies. Corporations poured $7.3 billion of
venture capital into young firms last year, more than quadrupling
their 1998 investments, according to Venture Economics.
</P>
<P>
   Register.com is a rival to Network Solutions Inc., which
formerly had a monopoly on doling out domain names that end in
.com, .net, and .org. Last September, the US Department of Commerce
agreed to allow competitors into the market.
</P>
<P>
   From June through September, Register.com signed up 159,000 new
domain names. In the first nine months of 1999, the company lost $1
million on $791,000 of revenue.
</P>
<P>
   PaineWebber Inc. analyst Aram Rubinson said investors are still
most interested in Staples's operating businesses. But, he added, a
gain like Friday's ``certainly enhances the value of the
organization.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
