<HEADER>
A6327 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-LEBANON-SAUDIS-1STLD-     03-03 1009
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEBANON-SAUDIS-1STLD-WRIETHRU-700(TRIM)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAUDI LEADER SEEKS COMMON ARAB FRONT FOR MIDEAST TALKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to add new info, reconfigure lead, change time element)  
 (HLW)  
 By JOHN F. BURNS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIRUT, Lebanon _ The crown prince of Saudi Arabia on Friday
ended a two-day visit to Lebanon, which Arab diplomats said was
aimed at strengthening a common Arab front after Israel's recent
bombing of three Lebanese power plants, the breakdown of
Israeli-Syrian peace talks, and the similar impasse in negotiations
between Israel and the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Prince Abdullah bin Abdel Aziz's visit to Beirut followed others
in the past 13 days by President Hosni Mubarak of Egypt and by
Kuwait's foreign minister, Sheik Sabah al-Ahmed al-Sabah.
Abdullah's visit, with some of the most elaborate security
arrangements seen in the Lebanese capital in several years,
followed his talks with Mubarak in Cairo and with the Syrian
president, Hafez Assad, in Damascus.
</P>
<P>
   Arab diplomats and newspapers have said that the purpose of the
flurry of visits has been to send a signal to Israel at a critical
moment in the stalled Middle East peace effort. Also, these
analysts have said, the Arab nations have been keen to show support
for Lebanon, where Iran-backed Hezbollah guerrillas have continued
attacks on Israeli troops in the occupied zone in southern Lebanon
ahead of Israel's promised withdrawal by July.
</P>
<P>
   The visits have taken place against a background of angry
polemics between Israel and its neighbors, particularly Lebanon.
Passions have been stirred on both sides by events in recent weeks
that included attacks by Hezbollah killing seven Israeli soldiers
in southern Lebanon, Israel's retaliation by destroying the
Lebanese power plants, and warnings to Lebanon by David Levy,
Israel's foreign minister.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech last week in Parliament, Levy warned of Israel's
``burning the soil'' of Lebanon, and acting on the basis of ``blood
for blood'' and ``child for child'' if Hezbollah's attacks
continued. In Lebanon and other Arab nations, Levy's words prompted
angry denunciations and the appearance of cartoons and commentaries
that have reverted to an old Arab tactic of comparing Israel to
Nazi Germany.
</P>
<P>
   One of Beirut's most popular television channels, Future TV, has
been running a 30-second film in its commercial breaks comparing
Levy to Hitler, with images of the two men speaking interspersed
with shots of Nazi and Israeli warplanes on bombing runs. The film,
prepared by Beirut college students, is accompanied by subtitles
saying, ``Same racism, same hatred, same criminality, same
history.'' It ends with the images of Levy and Hitler dissolving
into a swastika.
</P>
<P>
   But behind the vitriol and street protests that have been held
in Beirut, Cairo, Damascus and other Arab capitals, Arab leaders
appear to have been concerting efforts to get the peace talks back
on track.
</P>
<P>
   Arab diplomats say that Mubarak, who issued a joint statement
with the Lebanese president, Emile Lahoud, that criticized Israel's
attacks on the power plants and supported Hezbollah's right to
attack Israeli troops on Lebanese territory, also brought proposals
involving a cease-fire in southern Lebanon ahead of the Israeli
pullout.
</P>
<P>
   Much the same approach appears to be behind the journey of
Abdullah, the Saudi Arabian leader. Reports in some newspapers in
the Arab world said that he was pressing for agreement on an early
summit meeting of Arab leaders, the first in years, to forge a
common front on the peace effort. The 22-nation Arab League has
already decided to switch its coming meeting of foreign ministers
from Cairo to Beirut, where it is to open on March 11.
</P>
<P>
   But the public remarks made in Beirut and Damascus by Abdullah,
who carries considerable weight in the Arab world as the effective
day-to-day leader of the world's largest producer and exporter of
oil, conveyed the impression of a man eager to cool tempers and
prompt an early resumption of the peace talks between Israel and
Syria. The talks were suspended in January because of differences
on terms for the return of the Golan Heights, Syrian territory
captured by Israel during the 1967 Middle East war, which Israel
has extensively developed and settled.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In a speech in Beirut on Thursday, Abdullah used tough language
to signal to Israel, and by implication the United States, that
they cannot expect any more concessions from Syria and the
Palestinians. ``No power, regardless of how important its role is,
can force others to abandon their legitimate rights,'' he said. ``I
tell the Israelis that it's high time to reactivate the peace
process and steer it out of the dark tunnel, away from the language
of guns. We are a nation that does not beg for its rights.''
</P>
<P>
   But behind the scenes, he appeared to be taking a more
conciliatory line. A pro-Syrian newspaper in Beirut, As Safir,
quoted him as telling Syrian officials that Saudi Arabia is
``committed to and seeks peace which is just and fair and which is
capable of giving each party its right so that there will be
stability and security in the region,'' a standard formulation of
Saudi policy.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Abdullah appeared to be counseling Arabs to take a
long view, and not to allow passions over the power plant bombings
and Levy's remarks to upset the peace effort. ``The Middle East
peace train will resume its journey until its reaches its
destination, despite the obstacles,'' he said in his Damascus
remarks, according to the Beirut newspaper. ``The weak today will
be strong tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   A report that appeared on Thursday in Al Hayat, an Arab-language
newspaper published in London, said Syria was preparing to return
to the talks after a statement this week by Ehud Barak, Israel's
prime minister, on the Golan Heights issue. Barak said he stood by
a commitment made by Yitzhak Rabin, one of his predecessors, to
return all Syrian territory captured in the 1967 war.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-03-00 2203EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
