<DOCNO> NYT20000303.0348 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-03 22:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6328 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-PINOCHET-NYT &LR;      03-03 0517
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-PINOCHET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: HOMECOMING FOR GENERAL PINOCHET 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, March 4:
</P>
<P>
   Britain's decision on Thursday to drop extradition proceedings
against Gen. Augusto Pinochet and allow him to return to Chile is
understandably frustrating to those who hoped that the former
dictator would face trial in Spain for the many crimes of his
17-year rule. In relying on a secretive medical examination and
ignoring earlier objections expressed by courts in Spain, France,
Belgium and Switzerland, Britain has clouded its otherwise
admirable contribution to international justice in this historic
case.
</P>
<P>
   The grounds given for the decision were not by themselves
unreasonable. Jack Straw, the home secretary, said the 84-year-old
former dictator's ability to understand the charges against him and
to direct his defense had been seriously impaired by a series of
strokes. If so, justice would not be served by proceeding against
an enfeebled and mentally incompetent defendant.
</P>
<P>
   But the medical evidence that led Straw to make that judgment
has not been fully disclosed, and Pinochet was spirited out of
England before the decision could be challenged in court. That is
unfortunate, for it leaves the world wondering if Straw's action
was justified. Courts in Belgium, France, Switzerland and Spain,
which were seeking the general's extradition and had been given
copies of the British medical report, were not persuaded that he
should be excused from prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   Chilean courts must now make their own determination of
Pinochet's fitness to stand trial. For nearly a decade before his
arrest in London, the general and his top associates managed to
intimidate elected Chilean governments and avoid prosecution for
the crimes of his regime, which included more than 3,000 murders
and disappearances. But the Chilean judiciary has been emboldened
by Pinochet's London arrest. He now faces 60 criminal complaints in
Chile for kidnapping, murder and torture. He should be immediately
stripped of his status as a senator for life, which affords him
immunity from criminal prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   Chile's president-elect, Ricardo Lagos, has wisely pledged to
let justice run its course. But the outgoing government of
President Eduardo Frei is pushing a constitutional reform that
would allow Pinochet to step down from the Senate and retain
parliamentary immunity from prosecution. Chile's Parliament should
abandon this attempt to subvert the judicial process.
</P>
<P>
   Pinochet's return to Chile ought not to diminish the lasting
legacy of this case. It established that former heads of state no
longer enjoy impunity for crimes against humanity, and that they
may be tried for such crimes in any country under the principle of
universal jurisdiction. The fact that Pinochet was arrested in
London in October 1998 and that his claim of immunity as a former
head of state was rejected by British courts has put tyrants and
former tyrants around the world on notice that they, too, could be
prosecuted some day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-03-00 2204EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000303.0349 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-03 22:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6329 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-L.A.-POLICE-UNIT-NYT &LR;      03-03 0632
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-L.A.-POLICE-UNIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHIEF OF LOS ANGELES POLICE DISBANDS ANTIGANG UNITS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The chief of the Los Angeles Police Department
directed the department Friday to disband the semiautonomous
antigang units at the heart of the city's police corruption and
brutality scandal.
</P>
<P>
   The units, called Community Resources Against Street Hoodlums,
or Crash, were formed in the late 1970s in the administration of
Chief Daryl Gates in response to the city's growing problem with
street gangs.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, such units have come under scrutiny as giving
officers too much independence, which, if unchecked, could lead to
the abuse of power.
</P>
<P>
   Rafael Perez, the former Los Angeles police officer who pleaded
guilty to cocaine theft last September and revealed a wide range of
corruption and brutality in exchange for a lighter sentence, was a
member of the Crash unit in the low-income neighborhoods patrolled
by the department's Rampart division.
</P>
<P>
   In his statements to investigators, Perez portrayed the units as
having a culture and mission much like the gangs they tried to
thwart, with officer initiations similar to gang ``jump-in''
beating rituals.
</P>
<P>
   Some officers bore anti-gang-unit tattoos, Perez said, and
awards were given out to officers who wounded or killed suspects.
</P>
<P>
   A broad department inquiry report made public on Thursday said
that the units lacked ``conscientious supervision,'' that
supervisors' signatures on booking approvals and reports may have
been forged, that detention reports often lacked description of
sufficient probable cause and that many of the units had drifted
from their mission of combating gang activity to deal with drug
activity.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement late Friday by Chief Bernard C. Parks that the
units would be discontinued made no mention of the scandal that has
engulfed the Los Angeles Police Department in recent months. Parks
said the units would be disbanded effective March 12, and would be
replaced a month after that by ``special enforcement units'' in
each of the city's 18 police divisions. The new units will have
stricter requirements for both officers and supervisors and will
limit the time they can serve with the units.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, all people arrested by the new units must be
presented to the supervisory officer in the area. Under the setup
being replaced by the new units, some Crash units operated out of
separate quarters and had limited contact with regular-duty
officers and supervisors.
</P>
<P>
   It was not immediately clear how the new units' duties would
differ from those of the Crash units. Parks' statement said only
that the department would reveal the new units' mission in time.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview in his office on Thursday, the day before making
his announcement, Parks denied that he was contemplating any
changes in the way the antigang units operated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the issue we're dealing with is, we're aggressive
toward problems, we are not aggressive toward people,'' he said
heatedly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't declare war on a community,'' he said. ``We do not
declare war on people. We will always have an aggressive strategy
on gang problems, as long as there are gang problems.''
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Tom Hayden, a Democrat who has taken a lead role in
criticizing the department, said the disbanding of the units was
encouraging. But Hayden added that it remained to be seen whether
real change would occur.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if it's only symbolic, it's an important step,'' Hayden
said. ``But we have to look at the details very carefully.
</P>
<P>
   ``The secrecy has to end, the budget has to be published, the
members of these details have got to have human rights training.
The purpose of the patrol should be to arrest people who are
breaking the law.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-03-00 2206EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000303.0350 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-03 22:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6331 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-MARKET-WEALTH-SPEND-A     03-03 0924
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-WEALTH-SPEND-ART-3TAKES-$ADV05-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SQUANDERING A BUNDLE, IN HIS MIND  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 5) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)   (af)  
 By HUBERT B. HERRING   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When David Brancaccio hit town the other day, he was
ready to spend money _ spend big and spend fast.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got it,'' he said excitedly upon emerging from a radio
interview. ``We can park in front of Petrossian and buy some of
those expensive truffles, and then get our car towed. How much
would that cost?''
</P>
<P>
   Well, all right, this was to be a make-believe shopping spree.
But no matter. Brancaccio, host of the public radio program
``Marketplace,'' has just written a book called ``Squandering
Aimlessly,'' an account of roaming the country gathering tales of
what people do, or could do, with a chunk of extra money. And now
Brancaccio, who lives in Los Angeles, wanted to do a bit of
Manhattan squandering, if only in his head.
</P>
<P>
   Precision journalist that he is, he even came armed with his own
news peg. This was publication day, and Simon &AMP; Schuster owed him
$25,000; he wanted his check, and he wanted to imagine what he
could do with that sum _ right now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's see,'' he said, giddily pulling out a calculator.
``Minus the agent's commission, that's $21,250.'' Less taxes, of
course, unless he gave the money away. I was game to throw a bit of
Monopoly money around, and off we headed.
</P>
<P>
   ``My friend Marty says the ante to play the game in this town is
$7 an hour,'' he mused. ``You're on the street, and first you buy
pretzels, then something else _ the money just falls out of your
pocket. I showed up last night at 11:30 and most of my cash was
gone. It's cheaper to go to the movies than not to.''
</P>
<P>
   Our first stop was Times Square, where we paused under the
latest ground zero of glitz mixed with market fever: the huge
Nasdaq sign at 43rd Street, its market images dancing. ``Watching
the market,'' said Brancaccio, 39, an intense, animated man with
touches of gray in his short brown hair, ``is like watching a team
that wins most of the time _ it's fun! But what happens when it
goes down?''
</P>
<P>
   He covers the market on ``Marketplace,'' of course, but don't
dare call him a market wonk. He notes proudly that ``none of us
have MBAs'' at the program. ``We are anthropologists on the
business beat,'' he said, a line he had clearly used before.
``People remember things if they're told as stories, not with
charts.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially on radio. The half-hour program, produced by the
University of Southern California, is broadcast on about 280 public
radio stations five days a week. The formula must work, for the
program now has 3.7 million listeners a week, up 54 percent since
Brancaccio became host six years ago.
</P>
<P>
   With a mischievous look, he remembered his mission, pulled out a
cell phone and called his publiser. Forced to leave a message with
an assistant, he said mischievously: ``Tell him I was looking
through my author's contract, and it says Simon &AMP; Schuster owes me
my last payment today. Where's my check?''
</P>
<P>
   Even when Brancaccio is at play, his delivery is polished,
precise _ a radio pro in the flesh. It is disorienting in the
extreme to stand on 42nd Street and hear that distinctive voice. I
suppressed an urge to look around for a radio.
</P>
<P>
   But come on, Brancaccio, what would you really be tempted to
splurge on? His answer was quick: cameras.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't go past 9th Avenue and 34th,'' he said, for there
sits the siren of the B &AMP; H Photo store. ``I'd spend all the
money.'' He loves photography. ``Radio is a powerful medium,'' he
said. ``You draw word pictures, but you don't feel the visual side
of your brain is working.''
</P>
<P>
   He had warned me that he had to squeeze in a quick radio
interview, and we headed downtown to the Municipal Building. ``I
shouldn't be so cavalier about live radio, but I just have faith
and it works out,'' he said as, barely in time, we hurried into the
offices of WNYC, the public radio station that carries his program
on weekdays (6:30 p.m. on FM and 7 p.m. on AM).
</P>
<P>
   It's a jumbled warren of rooms, recording equipment seemingly
perched haphazardly against one wall, a box of ``Morning Edition''
mugs nestled against a table, a couple of black-and-gray
``Marketplace'' mugs on a shelf.
</P>
<P>
   His interview, with Northeast Public Radio, was by telephone,
and he got on the line, looked up and whispered with relief, ``Two
minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Wait a second, I thought. He's doing a phone interview? We raced
down here, slogged through the building's metal detectors and
negotiated a labyrinth of elevators _ to get to a phone? Are there
no other phones in this city? This, I realized, is a true radio
guy.
</P>
<P>
   He looked coiled, primed to pour forth market wisdom and promote
the book, his first.
</P>
<P>
   Soon he was on live, and the mantras tumbled out: ``It's a
personal finance book for people whose SAT verbal is higher than
their SAT math.'' ``Before you ask for investment advice, find out
what kind of car the person drives. I ride a bike to work.'' ``We
are anthropologists of the business beat.'' Asked about the book's
cover (he is shown tossing a bill out of a car), he said: ``I work
for public radio. That's a $1 bill.''
</P>
<P>
   He had warned me that one bane of his existence was being asked
investment advice, and when listener call-in time came, he covered
the phone and said, ``I know just what they're going to ask: `I
have this fund, and ...''' Sure enough, that's what the first
question was.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   One place he had visited in preparing for the book was the New
York Stock Exchange, and we headed there next.
</P>
<P>
   Standing amid a scattering of badged traders on smoking breaks,
Brancaccio recalled his earlier visit, when ``one guy came out
holding his half-eaten lunch and a copy of `The Art of War.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a blast!'' he said of being on the trading floor. ``It's
not like watching hockey, it's like being in the middle of the
game. You want to play!'' Not that he'd want to play himself. ``It
involves a lot of math,'' he said in awe. ``All those 16th's.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And the more you trade,'' he intoned, ``the more you lose.''
Looking expansively around this Grand Canyon of finance, he
proclaimed, ``This is the center of the universe _ or so we're led
to believe.''
</P>
<P>
   Borrowing my cell phone when his failed, he dialed Simon &AMP;
Schuster again and, to his delight, got through to David Rosenthal,
publisher of the trade division.
</P>
<P>
   Brancaccio was really enjoying this game. ``They say the check
is in the mail,'' he told me with a smile. ``They'll take up a
collection for us if we need car fare.''
</P>
<P>
   After getting off the phone, he did have some serious thoughts
on soaring stock prices. ``This is the wealth effect,'' he said.
``You have expectations, and your wallet gets a little looser.
That's the main reason for the roaring spending.''
</P>
<P>
   As we walked away, he talked of the roots of the book, which
tackles, from all different angles, the topic of shedding excess
cash: gambling, investing, buying real estate, philanthropy,
starting a business, socking it away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a vague sense that I needed to get some street smarts,''
he said. He received a letter from a listener in Maine who objected
that a full half-hour was devoted to financial news and suggested,
basically, that Brancaccio get a life. His first thought: ``He
doesn't know how funny that is.'' But then he wondered, ``Am I
submerging myself, turning myself into a creep?'' But no, ``you
can't be a hermit _ you can't forsake money.''
</P>
<P>
   So his quest became: ``What are the possibilities for money?
What are the goals?'' To try to find out, he took numerous short
trips around the country _ browsing in the giant Mall of America in
Minnesota, attending a convention for would-be entrepreneurs in
Pasadena, Calif., exploring the whole idea of mortgages in
Levittown.
</P>
<P>
   When he visited Trinity Church, deep in the financial heart of
Manhattan, he picked up this bit of wisdom from the rector, the
Rev. Dan Matthews: ``When I have a vision for my life, money is
then a tool to make the vision a reality. If I have no vision for
my life, then money is in fact the only way I can gauge my worth.''
</P>
<P>
   Brancaccio, poking around for his own vision, wanted our fantasy
spending binge in New York to include the possibility of donating
some or all of it, and he suggested returning to something that
caught his fancy during his research for the book _ a community
boat-building project called Floating the Apple. We found it now on
a pier in the Hudson River at the end of Houston Street, with a
sometime commercial photographer named Don Betts applying glue to
what would be a piece of a 25-foot boat.
</P>
<P>
   The boats are built mainly by volunteers and are used by, among
others, high school rowing groups to take advantage of what Betts
called ``New York's biggest open public space'' _ the water.
</P>
<P>
   Brancaccio, after calculating with Betts various permutations
for what $20,000 would buy _ so many supplies, so many days on the
water for so many kids _ asked about volunteering his time. ``Is
there anything I could offer?'' he said hopefully. ``I've done some
cabinet-making.''
</P>
<P>
   To which Betts replied: ``You'd probably learn more at the
dentist.'' Boat building, he explained, is all about fighting rot
and decay.
</P>
<P>
   Heading back to the subway, I asked Brancaccio if there was
another Manhattan social cause to which he would consider donating.
After a pause, he said: ``Probably something to do with literacy.
That's an investment in the community.'' Warming to the thought, he
added, ``Is it naive to think that a prison literacy program would
reduce muggings?''
</P>
<P>
   He recalled that at one talk he gave, a man in the audience
asked, ``What do you feel about the Kozenovsky Fund?''
</P>
<P>
   ``A voice in me said, `Bluff, bluff. Pretend you know what he's
talking about,''' he remembered. ``But another voice said, `Don't
bluff,' and I didn't. So the man said, `My name is Kozenovsky, and
I want to buy time to spend with my kids.'''
</P>
<P>
   Brancaccio is a firm believer in investing in family, which he
says is why a priority in his own family _ himself, his wife, Mary,
who works in communications at USC, and their three young children
_ is travel.
</P>
<P>
   What of his own investing? He owns no individual stocks _ partly
to avoid conflicts of interest as a journalist, partly because ``if
you're fooling with your portfolio instead of reading to your
children, I have a problem with that.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But he added, ``I do have a stake in capitalism.'' He invests in
a ``socially responsible'' mutual fund, and at first the returns
nearly matched the regular fund offered by USC, his employer. But
last year, Brancaccio said, it lagged way behind. The poor results,
he said with a laugh, made him ask, ``How much am I committed?''
</P>
<P>
   With children, ``the hardest question is `What's a stock?''' he
said. ``My 10-year-old is starting to get a sense of it because of
Pokemon cards, their trading value.''
</P>
<P>
   When his children are, say, 15, would he talk to them of
retirement accounts? ``That would be a great discussion to have,''
he said. ``My 10-year-old, Nick _ he'll take to stocks. But I'm a
little afraid to get him started too early. Here I am wrestling
with `Is this turning me into someone I don't want to be?' Do I
want to turn him into that person?
</P>
<P>
   ``I can see him going to a themed dance someday where people go
dressed the way people did in the '90s,'' he said, ``and I can see
him going as a stockbroker.''
</P>
<P>
   A book signing loomed that evening, and our last stop was to be
the glittering heart of ``if you have to ask, you can't afford it''
land, Fifth Avenue in the '50s. Brancaccio had grown more relaxed,
less scripted, as the afternoon wore on, and as we walked along
Central Park South from the subway, he said suddenly, clearly
tickled, ``I'm impressed that the publisher picked up the phone.''
</P>
<P>
   I asked again what he would do on a real spree. ``I'd find an
interior decorating place,'' he said quickly, ``one that does
kitchens. Since I'm Italian and Jewish, food is a big thing in our
family.'' (The Brancaccios are now ``trading up'' to a larger home
in Los Angeles.)
</P>
<P>
   ``And I'd have an outrageous meal. I hear there's this sushi
place where the more you spend, the smaller the portions are.''
He'd go to B &AMP; H Photo, for that Hasselblad. And ``an Edward Weston
print _ I'd spend money on that.''
</P>
<P>
   He grinned suddenly. ``There's this thing in the contract,'' he
said. `` `Author's portion of theme-park rights: 100 percent.'''
Warming to this thought, he went on, ``This could be seed money for
Squandering Aimlessly: The Ride!'' Pause. Mock-soberly: ``We need a
business plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Back to squandering. As we wandered the glittering aisles of
Tiffany's, I asked what he would buy his wife. ``I owe her,'' he
said. ``She helped so much with the book.'' But what?
</P>
<P>
   ``She wouldn't wear any of this _ let me find something
plausible.'' He stopped at a counter, a small sign reading:
``$60-$102,000.'' ``Now is that $60 or $60,000?'' he asked,
puzzled. ``$60? I could do that.'' But no, ``there's nothing to her
taste.''
</P>
<P>
   On to Trump Tower, where a prominent display of the Donald's
latest literary effort was set up amid the lobby's towering,
blinding glitz. ``This is what owning the building gets you,''
Brancaccio said. ``Good placement of your book. That doesn't say
`squandering aimlessly' _ but the building does!''
</P>
<P>
   But wait. In the Cartier window within Trump Tower, he spotted a
watch. Brancaccio has a weakness for watches; he's always searching
for the perfect one. And when the clerk told us the price, $11,400,
I could see Brancaccio's mind gleefully ``doing the numbers,'' as
he says nightly on ``Marketplace.''
</P>
<P>
   Out popped his calculator. With sales tax, that's $12,340. After
income taxes, his publisher's payment would come to $12,750.
Perfect! ``And I could go spend the $410 on that camera!'' he said
triumphantly.
</P>
<P>
   But he wanted to round out the fantasy spree on a sober note:
``No, let's invest that for retirement.''
</P>
<P>
   As we passed Brooks Brothers, I made one last attempt to lure
him with luxury. A suit, perhaps? ``I'm in radio,'' he replied. ``I
could be naked for all anyone knows.''
</P>
<P>
   He spied a pretzel stand _ in our wandering, we had neglected
lunch _ and treated us both. That $3, I realized _ aside from a few
swipes of a MetroCard _ was the first actual money we'd spent. And
it silenced two growling stomachs quicker than imagined riches ever
could.
</P>
<P>
   Walking toward his hotel, he stopped abruptly as we came upon
Radio City Music Hall, adorned by both vertical and horizontal neon
signs. ``That's my idea of visual heaven,'' he said. ``The
illuminated word `radio' twice.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was on the radio the first time when I was 13,'' he said.
``A high school kid did a DJ show, and he needed a newsman.''
</P>
<P>
   He could be tempted by a sabbatical, Brancaccio said, but ``I
really still love radio _ it's like having a term paper due every
day at 2, and the penalty for an incomplete is death.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
