<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MO GOES DEEP ON FIRST PITCH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEORIA, Ariz. _ Last year, it took Mo Vaughn 57 at-bats over 29
games before he hit his first and only home run of the spring.
</P>
<P>
   This spring, it took all of one pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn ripped a two-run, first-inning homer off the Mariners'
Jamie Moyer to propel the Anaheim Angels to an 8-5 victory in their
Cactus League opener Friday afternoon at the Peoria Sports Complex.
</P>
<P>
   Last spring, Vaughn didn't hit a home run at all during the
Angels' stay in Arizona. The homer came at Edison Field in the one
Freeway Series game against the Dodgers. But the first pitch he saw
Friday ended up on the grass embankment beyond the right-center
field fence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just the second time around, you get used to things,''
Vaughn said. ``I think overall it's just good to drive the baseball
at the start like that. You want to get out there in a game and
test yourself. I'm glad to get the first one right off the bat.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mo can hit,'' manager Mike Scioscia said. ``I don't care if he
hits no homers in the spring, or 40 homers, he can hit.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels totaled 13 hits in all, but none was more impressive
than Tim Salmon's home run which cleared the ''blue monster'' in
center field, a 40-foot brick wall that serves as the hitters'
backdrop.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see not only me but everybody taking good swings,'' Vaughn
said. ``Definitely Mike's attitude has already rubbed off in our
approach and how we go about our business.''
</P>
<P>
   Although it was a spring training game, it was Scioscia's first
as a major league manager. But he said he wasn't thinking about the
significance of it for himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mindset is trying to get our guys ready to go, and of the
few spots we do have available, to look at them closely,'' he said.
``I was impressed with the way we swung the bat and with the way
the pitchers lined up.''
</P>
<P>
   Angels starter Jarrod Washburn was less than impressive in his
two innings, allowing two runs and four hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``My problems in the past have been consistency in the strike
zone, getting ahead of hitters and my breaking ball,'' Washburn
said. ``Today I had the same problems. I couldn't throw my breaking
ball and I think I was behind 2-0 on every hitter. The only
positive was I didn't walk anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Ex-Bonita High and Cal State Fullerton standout Matt Wise was
impressive in two innings, striking out three and allowing only one
hit. The one hit was a home run by Jay Buhner, but Wise did strike
out Carlos Guillen, Edgar Martinez and John Olerud.
</P>
<P>
   ``For guys like me who have never pitched up here, there's
always the question of 'Can you?' '' Wise said. ``It's a great
opportunity to see what it's all about. But it was just one outing,
I still have things to work on. There's a long way to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Angels coach Larry Bowa survived the catastrophe that was
the Angels' 1999 season and landed on his feet in Seattle as the
Mariners' third-base coach.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Angels and Mariners played each other Friday Bowa
said he didn't think the Angels would repeat their troubles of last
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of good guys over there,'' Bowa said. ``I know
they'll do a lot better just because they're healthy. If they're
healthy they're going to score a lot of runs. ... I don't think
last year can repeat itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowa likes his new situation with the Mariners, and said
Mariners manager Lou Piniella told him Bowa's intensity was just
what the Mariners needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lou said we needed a little fire,'' Bowa said. ``I said I see
you on ESPN, it didn't look like he needed any fire. But he told me
if I see something I don't like, say something. The work ethic is
very good over here, just like it was over there (with the
Angels).''
</P>
<P>
   Bowa said he's spoken with several Angels since the end of last
season, including shortstop Gary DiSarcina several times.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
WEEK IN REVIEW
</P>
<P>
   Best story of the week: Rumors of trades involving Jim Edmonds
or Garret Anderson dying out.
</P>
<P>
   Best subplot: Competition for starting spots between Ramon
Ortiz, Jarrod Washburn, Brian Cooper and Scott Schoeneweis begins.
</P>
<P>
   Spring surprise: Nobody's hurt.
</P>
<P>
   Progress made with: Troy Percival. His shoulder strength is up
to 85-90 percent following off-season surgery. He should get into a
spring game around March 10.
</P>
<P>
   No progress made with: Second base. Lots of candidates, no
clear-cut favorite.
</P>
<P>
   The week ahead: It's reunion week. The Angels play Colorado
Wednesday and will see former pitching coach Marcel Lachemann. They
play Milwaukee on Thursday and see former hitting coach Rod Carew.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
