<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-03 22:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6336 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-NY-GIULIANI-BUSH-ART-     03-03 0879
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GIULIANI-BUSH-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICAL MEMO: EYES ON HIS OWN PRIZE, GIULIANI SQUIRMS IN BUSH'S
CORNER 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also REPUBS-NY) 
(ART ADV: Photo NYT17 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By ELISABETH BUMILLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   STONY BROOK, N.Y. _ There he was, the suddenly reticent mayor of
New York City.
</P>
<P>
   As Gov. George W. Bush of Texas and his New York campaign
chairman, Gov. George E. Pataki, held a forum at Stony Brook
University Hospital here Friday to accuse Sen. John McCain of
failing to support breast cancer research, Mayor Rudolph W.
Giuliani, a man who is not known for holding his tongue, did.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the event was apparently so uncomfortable for Giuliani
_ who had to sit next to his sibling rival, Pataki _ that the mayor
likened it, in front of a wide swath of the state Republican
hierarchy, to an unpleasant medical procedure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Pataki called me yesterday and said I could get a
virtual colonoscopy here _ you guys ready to do it?'' said Giuliani
as the audience broke out in laughter, some of it confused. The two
have been feuding since the mayor rejected Republican-sponsored
attacks on his friend McCain, even though he has endorsed Bush for
the party's presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Pataki genially called the mayor's joke a ``very good
line'' and cheerfully described the internecine politics roiling
through the room as ``relatively mild'' for New York.
</P>
<P>
   But the consensus among New York Republicans, however infuriated
by the mayor's behavior, is that Giuliani's strategy will serve him
well during his campaign for the U.S. Senate in the fall. His
actions, they say, simply re-emphasize what everyone knows: that
the mayor has never been considered a loyal Republican.
</P>
<P>
   ``His market right now is crossover voters and independents,''
said Nelson Warfield, a Republican strategist who was the spokesman
for Bob Dole's 1996 presidential campaign, ``and he doesn't want to
be seen as bashing John McCain. I don't see what's in it for Rudy.
And he's definitely a `What's in it for me?' politician.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani endorsed Bush in October, back when virtually the
entire state Republican leadership thought the Texas governor was
the best and most likely candidate to become president. Left unsaid
was the belief that Bush and his campaign, at the time a richly
financed machine, could best help Giuliani's campaign, by either
sharing lists of donors or helping with fund-raising. McCain wasted
no time in pointing that out when he was asked why Giuliani was
supporting Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``Money,'' he replied. When asked what he meant, McCain
repeated, ``Money.''
</P>
<P>
   Later in October, Giuliani spent a day campaigning with Bush in
New York City, and then called on him at the governor's mansion in
Austin in November. But by the time of the South Carolina primary,
when Bush began embracing religious conservatives, Giuliani's
advisers grew nervous. They worried that if the mayor made too many
appearances with Bush, he might alienate the Democrats and
independents he needs to beat his Democratic opponent, Hillary
Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's reluctance broke out into the open this week. On
Wednesday, Bush campaign officials said they were expecting the
mayor to accompany Bush on a Friday and Saturday campaign trip
across the state, but by Friday morning, Giuliani's campaign
advisers said the mayor would only greet Bush as he arrived at
MacArthur Airport in Ronkonkoma and then afterward attend the forum
at the hospital. One factor in Giuliani's reluctance may have been
worries about being away from New York City during demonstrations
in the Bronx after the police shooting of an unarmed man on
Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, the mayor never did get to MacArthur Airport.
(His aides said he left City Hall late, stopped for a sandwich and
hit traffic.) But Bush campaign officials, who were watching the
rest of the state Republican hierarchy shake Bush's hand on the
tarmac, brushed off Giuliani's nonappearance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We understand he's got his own race to run,'' one senior Bush
adviser said. ``Obviously there are some tensions between Mayor
Giuliani and Governor Pataki, but we have both of their support and
we'll try to rise above it.''
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference after the breast cancer forum, Giuliani
stood by as Bush and Pataki repeatedly attacked McCain for what
they said was his lack of support for breast cancer research.
Finally, Giuliani was asked how he felt about the accusations and
the negative advertising the Bush campaign has begun against McCain
in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani ignored the question. ``I'm here because I support
Governor Bush very, very strongly,'' he said, adding, ``It's quite
possible to argue very, very strongly in favor of the governor and
not get involved in the other part because of a personal
friendship.''
</P>
<P>
   By ``the other part,'' Giuliani meant negative campaigning, and
on Friday McCain acknowledged his gratitude. In a ``Dear Rudy,''
letter sent to City Hall and released to the media, McCain thanked
the mayor for his ``extraordinary effort to keep the tenor of the
presidential campaign in New York on a positive plane.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
