<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR SATURDAY, MARCH 4
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Saturday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-CHILD-SHOT-NYT (moved on Wednesday, March 1)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Wednesday, March
1, about the shooting of 6-year-old Kayla Renee Rolland in Mount
Morris Township, Mich., misstated the site of her wound. The bullet
entered through her shoulder, not the neck or the chest.
</P>
<P>
   The article also misidentifed the car on the lawn of the home
where the boy who shot her had been living. It was a Camaro, not a
Corvette.
</P>
<P>
   BC-WESLEYAN-ADMISSIONS-NYT (moved on Saturday, Feb. 26)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Saturday, Feb. 26,
about the admission process at Wesleyan University misstated the
criterion used in selecting a 17-year-old student as a National
Merit Semifinalist. Semifinalists are chosen through the
preliminary College Board exam in their junior year, not the
College Board reasoning test.
</P>
<P>
   BC-OBIT-BODNE-NYT (moved on Wednesday, March 1)
</P>
<P>
   The obituary of Mary Bodne, sent by the New York Times News
Service on Wednesday, March 1, misspelled the name of a blacklisted
Hollywood writer who was a guest there. He was John Henry Faulk,
not Falk.
</P>
<P>
   BC-OBIT-MATTHIASDOTTIR-NYT (moved on Wednesday, March 1)
</P>
<P>
   The obituary of Louisa Matthiasdottir sent by the New York Times
News Service on Wednesday, March 1, misstated the given name of a
postwar artist with whom she shared the belief that abstraction and
representationalism were not mutually exclusive approaches to
painting. The artist was Virginia Admiral, not Catherine.
</P>
</TEXT>
