<DOCNO> NYT20000303.0360 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-03 22:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6345 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-REPUBS-CONGRESS-1STLD     03-03 0881
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPUBS-CONGRESS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SHIFT, ANALYSTS SAY GOP LIKELY TO RETAIN HOUSE IN 2000
ELECTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va.)   (in next to last graf, `no longer' is changed to 'not'; in 9th from
last graf, beginning xxx But Davis said xxx, the definition of hard
money is clarified)  
 (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By LIZETTE ALVAREZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After a series of twists in their favor,
Republicans have improved their chances of keeping control of the
House in this year's elections, according to party leaders,
analysts and strategists from both parties.
</P>
<P>
   The defection of one House Democrat, the decision of another to
retire from his swing district and the fact that fewer Republican
seats will be as tough to defend as anticipated have all
contributed to the Republican turnaround.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats say they are still confident they will recapture the
House but acknowledge that Republicans have made strides since last
fall, when it was widely predicted that the House would switch
hands. A net gain of only six seats would give Democrats control.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had to put a pinky on the scale,'' said Stuart
Rothenberg, a nonpartisan analyst who handicaps House races, ``it
would be for the Republicans holding the House.''
</P>
<P>
   But analysts and strategists also caution that the general
election is a long way off and that much could happen between now
and then to weaken Republican odds, including an increase in
retirements. And, with such a narrow divide between the two
parties, they emphasize that the dynamic of the presidential race
could tip the advantage, depending on which candidates are
nominated and how their campaigns play out.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a long way from Tipperary,'' said Paul Begala, a former
senior White House aide and campaign strategist for President
Clinton, who added that Democrats were better positioned on the
issues and had more money than Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Charles Cook, who publishes a nonpartisan political report on
individual races, said in his newsletter this month that
``beleaguered'' Republicans ``seem to be getting a few breaks'' and
have ``at least an even-money shot'' right now at keeping control
of the House.
</P>
<P>
   And just this week, a Senate Democratic leader struck a note of
caution about the prospects of his party's winning back the House,
which it lost in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``Democrats are very overconfident about the House,'' said Sen.
Harry Reid of Nevada, the second-ranking Democratic leader in the
Senate, in an interview, adding that he believed that Democrats now
stood a better chance to retake the Senate than the House. ``There
aren't that many competitive districts.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Recent polls asking people which party's House candidate they
would vote for showed Republicans and Democrats neck and neck, with
Democrats winning more support on the issues. But a recent New York
Times poll gave House Democrats an 11-point advantage. Early last
year, during the impeachment battle, the surveys showed Republicans
consistently lagging by 10 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``The race for the House is a lot like a really good basketball
game where one side might go up by a couple of points, and the
momentum might shift every few minutes,'' said Amy Walter, a Cook
Report editor who covers the House.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now the perception is that maybe the ball is back in their
court,'' said, Walter, referring to the Republicans. ``But it's
still a tossup.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The critical numbers are these: Republicans need to defend 22
open seats _ those without incumbents, who typically enjoy an
enormous re-election advantage. That is an average number of
retirements, but it is in sharp contrast to the Democrats, who have
only 7.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are more open seats in our favor than in theirs, and
historically open seats in general are more likely to switch
parties than other seats,'' said Steve Elmendorf, chief of staff
for Rep. Dick Gephardt of Missouri, the House Democratic leader.
</P>
<P>
   But as the matchups in many races have become clear, analysts
agree that there are fewer than a dozen truly competitive races.
The Cook Report concludes that only two of those open seats are
leaning toward changing hands, and both are Democratic seats seen
as likely to go Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans point to several crucial twists that have gone their
way in the past two months. First, Rep. Virgil H. Goode Jr. of
Virginia, a conservative Democrat, announced in January that he
would become an independent, but would align himself with
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after, Rep. Owen B. Pickett, another Virginia Democrat,
announced he would retire. Republicans have already recruited a
strong candidate for that district, considered Republican
territory, while Democrats are still scrambling. In addition, a
seat in Pennsylvania, now filled by Rep. Ron Klink, a Democrat who
is vacating the seat to run for the Senate, is also vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   The Pickett and Klink seats are the sole open seats that Cook
rates as leaning toward changing hands.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``Six months ago, they were throwing dirt on the coffin,'' said
J. Kenneth Klinge, a Republican political consultant. ``Now the
coffin is back out of the ground, they've got the dirt off and they
are beginning to take the flowers back to the florist.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In the past few months, House Republicans, led by Rep. Thomas M.
Davis of Virginia, the chairman of the National Republican
Congressional Committee, made several strategic moves that they say
are starting to pay off.
</P>
<P>
   To calm the jittery nerves of big business, traditionally the
Republicans' strongest ally, Republican leaders brought in Dan
Matoon, a seasoned lobbyist to head the internal operations of the
campaign committee. They also began to draw more on the expertise
of Bill Paxon, the former New York congressman who helped engineer
the 1994 Republican takeover of the House, and Haley Barbour, the
former chairman of the Republican National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   To blunt the Democrats' current financial advantage, the
Republican leaders completed a list of 350,000 new donors, people
the party can rely on to make small, hard money contributions for
individual candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``The donor list is critical,'' said Paxon, now a
lobbyist.``It's the best donor list in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   As of late last year, the most recent figures available, House
Democrats had more than double the cash in the bank than
Republicans: $19.8 million to $9 million. While Republicans raised
substantially more money last year, they also spent it to pay off
debts and for the Virginia state races as well as a special
congressional election in California, among other things. The
Republican won control of the Virginia Legislature but lost the
special election.
</P>
<P>
   But Davis said money did not worry him too much, adding that
Democrats have only $1 million more than Republicans in hard money,
which comes from individuals and goes to candidates, compared with
the unrestricted soft-money contributions from corporations and the
rich, which go to the political parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``We way outraised them last time,'' Davis said, ``and we'll
outraise them this time.''
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans usually run into trouble on the issues, and it
is here that Democrats say they are confident they now hold the
edge. So far, Republican leaders have carefully avoided explosive
floor skirmishes and focused on small bills they can pass: tax
savings for married couples, and most recently, a break for working
people 65 through 69 on Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   But there are land mines ahead _ a proposed overhaul in managed
care, a plan to have Medicare pay for prescription drugs and gun
control legislation, to name three _ that will prove far trickier
and more politically dangerous for Republicans.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   As for the Republicans' strategy on issues so far, Begala said:
``They are selling tax cuts, and nobody is buying. Their whole
approach is very '80s. They pine for Ronald Reagan.''
</P>
<P>
   The presidential race is also expected to be a factor.
Republicans, who had built a strategy around Gov. George W. Bush's
popularity, said they still expected him to receive the nomination
over Sen. John McCain. The good news, they argue, is that voter
turnout in Republican primaries is sky-high.
</P>
<P>
   ``Running with Bush or McCain you have a little bit of a
different dynamic,'' Davis said. ``But with everything going on
here, I don't see anything that at this point does anything but
good things for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats dispute that rosy view, saying Bush has been weakened
in the primary campaign and will not carry the party to victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is scrambling to raise money to get himself elected,''
Elmendorf, the Gephardt aide, said, ``and he is not going to be an
advantage to them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-03-00 2215EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000303.0362 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-03 22:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6347 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-POST-PROPERTIES-ART-3     03-03 0631
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POST-PROPERTIES-ART-3TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAYING GOODBYE TO THE 'BURBS 
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Texas, Ariz. Tenn.)  (ART ADV: A graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(For release Sunday, March 5) (DW) 
 By KATHERYN HAYES TUCKER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ As this city's biggest apartment developer, John A.
Williams and the company he founded _ Post Properties Inc. _ helped
make Atlanta a symbol of urban sprawl bursting out of control.
Through the 1970s and '80s, he turned thousands of acres of
suburban forest into vast expanses of garden apartments. But today,
Williams has become one of the nation's leading champions of
renewed urbanism. Denouncing the suburbs as eyesores and breeding
grounds for neurotic youth, he has built projects in recent years
that have added apartments, often with stores and offices, to
older, urban neighborhoods. In partnership with the state's new
governor, a close friend, he is translating his new business
practices into policy.
</P>
<P>
   The central city revival that Williams is leading in Atlanta is
spreading to cities like Houston, Dallas, Phoenix and Memphis.
Neighborhoods that until recently were bereft of human presence
after working hours are sprouting apartments, restaurants, movie
theaters and grocery stores. In 1997, a Kroger store opened just
across the street from the Atlanta City Hall, where the most common
neighborhood storefronts had been the offices of bail bondsmen.
</P>
<P>
   But Williams is still fighting a much stronger trend _ the
continuing push of Americans to own their own land and their own
homes, and the desire of builders to satisfy them.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles County recently approved its largest housing
development ever, to turn the rolling hills on the northwestern
edge of the metropolis into homes for 70,000 people _ a project
that environmental groups and a neighboring county are challenging
in court. But leading home builders see no demand for new housing
closer to downtown Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's own suburbs, including 4 of the nation's 10
fastest-growing counties, continue to spread. Atlantans now have
even tougher drives to work than Angelinos do. They commute an
average of 35 miles a day _ more than anywhere else in the country.
The city's pollution has become so severe that the federal
government has threatened to cut off highway funds unless Atlantans
find ways to reduce traffic.
</P>
<P>
   For their part, Atlanta residents who had followed Williams into
the suburbs have been clamoring for housing closer to the city's
core. So redirecting development has become not just a matter of
principle, but of business necessity, even desperation.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, Williams helped his old friend, Gov. Roy Barnes, form
the powerful Georgia Regional Transportation Authority, which can
veto new shopping centers or office buildings that fail to provide
mass transit or housing within an easy walk.
</P>
<P>
   Since Williams began building garden apartments around Atlanta
in 1971, his empire has grown to include 36,000 apartments in a
dozen cities, with almost 7,000 under construction. Only in the
1990s has he preached the virtues of new urbanism, before business
groups across the country. He talks with a convert's evangelical
fervor about his new philosophy of building communities where
people can live, walk and work.
</P>
<P>
   ``The suburbs, frankly, are just sort of ugly,'' said Williams,
in a ninth-floor office at his signature urban community, Post
Riverside. Within the city limits, though about 10 miles from
downtown, it has street-level shops with upstairs apartments, all
set on a town square. Williams moved his headquarters here from
suburban Cobb County when Post Riverside opened in 1998.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Very private despite his status as one of Atlanta's men in full,
Williams, 56, hesitates even before saying how many children he has
(three, and one grandchild). He does casually disclose, however,
that his international yacht racing has brought him buddies who
include Ted Turner.
</P>
<P>
   In a conference room, he flashes the slides of suburban images _
drive-in banks, fast-food pick-up windows and a low-rise Dallas
apartment complex in a sea of parking lots _ that he keeps at the
ready for visitors. He also displays his penchant for subjecting
housing developments, and their residents, to psychoanalysis.
</P>
<P>
   ``People can't live in that environment and feel good about
themselves,'' said Williams, whose warm smile and manner hardly
soften his fierce convictions. ``Children who grow up in a suburb
where you can't tell one house from the other just have an
unfortunate experience. I think it's related to the neuroses we are
seeing.''
</P>
<P>
   To illustrate his preferred style, Williams shows a slide of the
ancient Roman city of Bath, England: a village built around a town
center meant for people from all walks of life. It was his model
for Post Riverside and other developments that he calls new urban
villages.
</P>
<P>
   The Upper West Side of Manhattan, with block after solid block
of apartments, his projects are not. Neither are they smack in the
city's center. But in Atlanta, areas that were considered suburban
not too long ago are now considered urban and close in.
</P>
<P>
   Back in Cobb County, where Williams was once the chairman of the
Chamber of Commerce, he is regarded in some quarters as a turncoat.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Cooper, the chamber's current chief executive, notes that
the new Post headquarters and urban village are just across the
Chattahoochee River from Cobb. Even the wealthy Buckhead
neighborhood where Williams lives, though in the city, has a
suburban character, Cooper said.
</P>
<P>
   All the urban projects that anyone could build cannot possibly
accommodate Atlanta's growth, he added. ``Where are the people
going to live who work in these office buildings I'm looking at?''
Cooper asked from his office. ``Are you going to pack them all into
10-story apartment buildings? I don't think so.''
</P>
<P>
   Principle is on his side, Cooper concluded. ``Part of the
American dream,'' he said, ``is being able to choose your
lifestyle.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams and his allies have so transformed the debate here that
even some suburban developers are calling themselves urbanists, or
advocates of ``smart growth.'' Sprawl-bashing has become so
widespread that some suburbanites say they're ashamed to
acknowledge where they live.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen H. Macauley, president of Macauley Homes and
Neighborhoods, is building what he calls an ``urban village,'' on
88 acres in Cobb County, about 30 miles from downtown Atlanta.
Twenty years ago, the area was pasture _ ``redneck heaven,''
Macauley says. Then came a mall. Now there are chain stores,
restaurants, pavement and traffic as far as the eye can see.
</P>
<P>
   Macauley plans a community where apartments, stores and offices
are all close together and easily accessible by foot. ``If you'd
told me 10 years ago I'd be building an urban development here, I'd
have died laughing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Post's in-town projects are much more in-town. As
what planners call ``in-fill developments,'' they are in older
neighborhoods _ some blighted, some thriving. ``We have no interest
at all in building suburban garden apartments,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   Statements like these have made Williams a new best friend of
Mayor Bill Campbell of Atlanta. The mayor is celebrating because
the city itself _ a compact area whose population of 427,500
accounts for only 13.3 percent of the region's 3.2 million
residents _ has just seen its first population increase after 30
years of decline, with double-digit growth projected for this
decade. ``Here you have the premier suburban apartment developer
not just validating but extolling the virtues of urban living with
the zeal of a preacher,'' Campbell said.
</P>
<P>
   He sees Post's credibility as fueling the in-town housing
movement. ``The development business is sheep and shepherds,'' he
said. ``If you have a developer who's successful, others will
follow.''
</P>
<P>
   For Williams, what looks like a gamble is actually a well-hedged
bet. While Post invests heavily in its new urban developments, the
company is still well supported by income from its suburban
apartments (though it has sold some of its oldest buildings).
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure it really is that much of a risk,'' said Ross L.
Smotrich, an analyst at Bear, Stearns in New York, who has watched
Post for almost two decades. ``I happen to like their strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   He also likes the stock, even though the price has stagnated
over the last three years as the broader market has boomed.
</P>
<P>
   Such lackluster performance, Smotrich said, does not reflect
anxiety about Post's urban strategy but rather investors' passion
for high-technology stocks instead of real estate investment
trusts, or REIT's, like Post. Smotrich said Post's strong balance
sheet, growth prospects and management led him to expect a stock
price of $43.50 within 12 months, up from $37.1875 Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The company's most valuable asset may be its name. Instead of
following the common practice of giving every project an entirely
different label, Williams wanted from the beginning to create a
brand. He picked up the Post name from a Post Oak street sign that
he saw as he was hunting for property in Dallas. He now has Atlanta
projects that include Post Canyon, Post Renaissance and Post
Parkside.
</P>
<P>
   The Post brand proves reassuring to residents of his in-town
projects, and to the real estate trade more generally. ``The fact
that Post is doing it demonstrates that it is financially viable,''
said Adrienne Schmitz, director of residential development for the
Urban Land Institute in Washington. ``It's definitely a national
trend.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   However enthusiastic Williams may wax about new urbanism, his
move into the cities was strictly a business decision. And his
transformation was less an epiphany than an evolution, based not on
divine inspiration but on routine market surveys.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The story begins more than a half-century ago in the southwest
Atlanta neighborhood where Williams was born and raised. That area
has gone from predominantly white to black, but it has remained
economically diverse and culturally rich. As a boy, Williams walked
to school each day, passing neighbors and shopkeepers who kept a
watchful eye on the children.
</P>
<P>
   Some houses were large and luxurious; some were not. Williams
describes his home as tiny, and he recalls passing his time drawing
house construction plans as early as the age of 10. He always liked
to build things, and always had his own ideas.
</P>
<P>
   He graduated from a public high school and studied industrial
management at Georgia Tech. After graduation, he took a job at the
Georgia Power Co., working with real estate developers. He soon
joined one of them, an apartment builder and manager. ``I didn't
see them doing anything I couldn't do better,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It was the late 1960s, and he figured out that as young women
gained better jobs, they would spend more on housing. No longer
would they have to live four to an apartment. They would want their
places nicer and cleaner, and with more flowers.
</P>
<P>
   So that is what he gave them when he started Post in 1971. ``We
figured if we got the women, the men would follow,'' he said. ``And
they did.''
</P>
<P>
   The typical Post suburban apartments, two- and three-story
walk-ups with outside entrances, had big rooms, plush carpeting,
modern kitchens and screened porches to take advantage of Sun Belt
weather. These developments had large swimming pools with deck
furniture for lounging, plus barbecue grills, tennis courts,
clubhouses with party rooms and even laundry rooms with picture
windows. Everything was framed by lush landscaping _ even the
parking lots.
</P>
<P>
   The car was the only equipment required. Driving around Post
apartments to view the tulips, a Williams trademark, was a rite of
spring.
</P>
<P>
   In Atlanta, plenty of vacant land was available within what was
then a 20-minute drive from downtown. Residents felt safer there
than in the decaying city. Singles zipped home from work, changed
clothes and headed out by car to the bars and restaurants that also
came to ring the city. Those 20- or early 30-somethings who didn't
live in Post apartments visited friends who did.
</P>
<P>
   As Williams became active in civic and business organizations,
his friends came to include Barnes, then a young Cobb County lawyer
and state legislator. The two talked business and politics over
breakfast at the IHOP on Roswell Road in Sandy Springs.
</P>
<P>
   Williams had a garden apartment complex there. But by the late
1980s, the Roswell Road corridor _ a wide swath of signs, fast-food
stops and strip shopping centers _ had become such a textbook
example of suburban blight that city planners in Atlanta would use
pictures of it to illustrate what to avoid with future zoning
decisions.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   For perhaps the first time since the postwar boom, these
planners began to talk about the advantages of combining housing,
shopping and offices in communities as friendly for pedestrians as
for cars.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Traffic was getting worse. Although more offices were springing
up in the suburbs, residents of Post's apartments were having a lot
more trouble getting to work. Life in the 'burbs was becoming less
fun.
</P>
<P>
   Williams paid attention. Every year he has been in business, he
has surveyed residents. ``In the late 1980s, we started to notice
in the questionnaires that people wanted to live closer in,'' he
said. ``Our move was a direct response.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, he opened his first in-town project, Post Chastain in
Atlanta. As Barnes remembered, ``People thought he was nuts.''
</P>
<P>
   But Williams also noticed that in the city, conditions for
development were ripening. Crime rates were dropping. Atlanta's
economy drew residents from other cities who were already alert to
the conveniences of urban living. Apartments built for the 1996
Olympic Games furthered the urban renaissance. As the suburbs
raised taxes to deal with growth, city tax rates became more
competitive.
</P>
<P>
   At Post Riverside, many residents work in the offices that are
part of the complex, including Post headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Robert L. Anderson, a retired Price Waterhouse partner, moved
with his wife, Dawn, in June 1998 from a home in Buckhead. Most
mornings, he goes from his apartment to the Town Square Gym, then
the Deli Market Cafe (both operated by Post), then to his office,
where he has a small consulting firm. Each trip takes no more than
three minutes, by foot.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we first did it, friends thought we were crazy,'' he
said. ``They're envious now, because we're really much freer. Being
able to just walk over to your office gives you a couple of extra
hours a day.''
</P>
<P>
   As in other cities, the new in-town housing here is attracting
not only young singles, but also empty nesters and couples without
children, like the Andersons. ``It's cool. It's eclectic,''
Williams said. But he grants that Sun Belt inner cities have to
improve education and race relations, and reduce crime further,
before they can attract families with school-age children.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   The artful comforts of Post's new urban communities are still
not what many people consider inner-city living. Post might be to
pre-World War II urban neighborhoods what Disney World's Epcot is
to the foreign countries that its sleek pavilions seek to mimic.
</P>
<P>
   But Post's new urban communities will age well, suggested Carl
Patton, the former dean of the School of Architecture at the
University of Wisconsin in Milwaukee who is now president of
Georgia State University in Atlanta. ``I think it's going to take
on more of a patina,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   When Patton came to Georgia State, he sold off the president's
mansion in Buckhead and took a loft apartment downtown, next to his
campus. He even got rid of the president's parking space.
</P>
<P>
   But noting that he has to buy his takeout soup immediately after
work, before a nearby deli closes, he is urging Williams to build
apartments in the very center of the city.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONA TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Last year, he opened his most urban venture yet _ Post Parkside,
about three miles from downtown but within walking distance of the
BellSouth Corp. and other corporate headquarters. The development
blends so well into its century-old neighborhood that it's hard to
spot. Loft apartments built out to the sidewalks are designed to
look old, some with hardwood floors from an old shoe warehouse.
Crime fears are addressed with decorative but effective steel gates
and security systems with panic buttons. But no tulips.
</P>
<P>
   Stafford N. Green, age 34, moved there on his return to Atlanta
after five years in Copenhagen, where he walked or rode a bicycle
everywhere. He was appalled by the increased traffic, and he sought
a neighborhood that would suit his Norwegian bride, Kristin. ``It's
the closest I could get to European living in Atlanta,'' he
explained.
</P>
<P>
   Williams and other developers are building similar apartments
across the country. In downtown Houston, Post restored the landmark
Rice Hotel, installing 312 loft apartments, a restaurant, shops, a
health club, a pool and a ballroom. In Dallas, Post has invested
heavily in a neighborhood adjacent to the downtown core. In the
last year, the company has been building urban projects in Orlando,
Fla., Austin, Tex., and, just across from the Pentagon, near
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   For Williams, it's a round trip. ``We're trying to build
neighborhoods that remind me and others of where we grew up,'' he
said. ``You couldn't get me to live in the suburbs for all the tea
in China.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
