<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-03 22:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6350 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-REPUBS-NEW-ENGLAND-AR     03-03 0930
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPUBS-NEW-ENGLAND-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN NEW ENGLAND, BUSH IS THE UNDERDOG 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: Adds comparative delegate numbers in graf 3, clarifies Rhode
Island poll number in graf 4; sets importance of Tuesday primaries
in perspective in graf 6; clarifies respective delegate numbers in
graf 7; updates poll numbers in graf 15; clarifies third sentence
of graf 16. 2nd take is new.)  
(ART ADV: Photos NYT6 and NYT10 are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(lh) 
 By PAUL ZIELBAUER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. _ On paper, New England ought to be George W.
Bush country. Not only does he have roots here _ his father was
raised in Greenwich, Conn., and his family has a home in Maine _
but he also enjoys broad support from New England's Republican
machines.
</P>
<P>
   The governors of Connecticut, Massachusetts and Rhode Island are
supporting Bush. In stark contrast, his chief rival for the
Republican presidential nomination, Sen. John McCain, has no
state-level official supporting him in Connecticut, and only a
scattering of relatively obscure state legislators, former
congressmen and retired military veterans working for him in all of
New England. In Maine, for instance, McCain's state campaign
chairman is a retired Marine from Dresden who coaches college
softball.
</P>
<P>
   Yet polls show that McCain has a good chance of winning all five
New England primaries on Tuesday, and their 102 collective
delegates, as many as are at stake in New York on the same day.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, where McCain was trailing Bush last September
by 30 points, he now leads by more than 20. In Rhode Island, where
the GOP is weak and more than half of all voters are independents,
he is also leading by more than 20 points. In Vermont, McCain's
campaign chairman bragged this week that victory was a foregone
conclusion. Many experts agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think McCain will sweep New England,'' said Darrell West, a
political science professor at Brown University in Providence, R.I.
``This is a segment that has a tradition of going for mavericks.''
</P>
<P>
   But even if that tradition works in McCain's favor _ polls
indicate Bush has a good shot only in Connecticut and Maine _ there
are 613 delegates at stake on Tuesday and some formidable
obstacles.
</P>
<P>
   But even if that tradition works in McCain's favor _ polls
indicate Bush has a good shot only in Connecticut and Maine _ it
may not be enough. Bush is strong in California and Georgia, with
216 delegates, and the races in Ohio and New York, with a total of
168 delegates are tight.
</P>
<P>
   So it is no wonder that before Friday, neither Bush nor McCain
had set foot in New England since Feb. 1, the day of McCain won the
New Hampshire primary by 19 points.
</P>
<P>
   Relatively speaking, the region's five states simply do not add
up to much Tuesday, said Jay Malcynsky, Bush's Connecticut campaign
manager. ``They don't have the number of delegates to deliver to
one candidate or another.
</P>
<P>
   ``If McCain is able to win most or all of New England, the rest
of the races, particularly California, New York and Ohio, will pull
him through,'' he said of Bush. But he conceded, ``It's been a
battle for Bush in New England since New Hampshire.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps more than any other region in the country, the
five-state New England region, from Connecticut up to Maine, offers
McCain a tailor-made, fiercely independent moderate voters whose
counterparts delivered McCain primary victories in New Hampshire
and Michigan. In every state in this region except New Hampshire,
independents outnumber Republicans and Democrats, and only in
Connecticut are non-Republican voters banned from crossing over to
vote in the Republican primary.
</P>
<P>
   More than 30,000 in Massachusetts have switched registration in
time for Tuesday's primary, mostly Democrats to independents, state
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Such momentum does not seem to have waned after McCain's triple
primary defeat last week in Virginia, Washington and North Dakota,
said Scott McLean, a political science professor at Quinnipiac
College in Hamden, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those elections were in different parts of the country, and I
don't see them slowing him down in Connecticut,'' McLean said in an
interview this week. ``I'm not sure anyone even paid attention in
Connecticut. People I talked to, they were asking me who won in
those states.''
</P>
<P>
   A poll taken in Connecticut, by Quinnipiac College taken after
McCain's resounding win in New Hampshire but before Bush's win in
South Carolina, showed McCain ahead, 52 percent to 39 percent. But
a Zogby poll of 361 likely voters released Friday showed Bush
ahead, 45 percent to 42 percent, with a five point margin of error.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to be competitive here,'' Malcynsky said on
Wednesday. But McCain _ who has no state-level elected official
openly backing him here _ still seems to have a grip on
Connecticut's electoral imagination. In Cheshire, Conn, an affluent
town southwest of Hartford, several Republicans interviewed Friday
said they will vote for McCain Tuesday, mostly because of their
perceptions about his character and willingness to shake up
Washington's political establishment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want George Bush's son in office; I've had enough of
Bush,'' said Sue Paulik, 59, who works in a Cheshire drug store.
``I think his policies would follow Reagan and what happened under
his father. The economy really suffered under his father.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Even Gov. John Rowland, Bush's foremost Connecticut booster, has
had a distinctly less zealous outlook on winning Connecticut, whose
25 delegates are second in New England to the 37 of Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   The cooling down became notable 10 days ago, after Rowland
criticized Bush's visit to Bob Jones University, a South Carolina
college that espouses anti-Catholic views, as ``stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about Bush's chances Friday, Rowland, who is Catholic,
said, ``Governor Bush as a candidate is back on the offensive, back
on message,'' and he criticized McCain for taking ``inappropriate
advantage'' of Bush's Bob Jones debacle.
</P>
<P>
   But he did not predict victory.
</P>
<P>
   If Bush cannot win here, Maine may be his only other reasonable
hope in New England, though Gov. Angus King, a popular independent,
has endorsed no one. Primary rules that allow same-day crossover
voting also seem to bode well for McCain.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush's staple issue of taxes will make him competitive, said
his volunteer state chairman, Ross J. Connelly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maine hasn't benefited from the boom the way the rest of the
country has, so, the issue of taxation will play much better here
in Maine,'' Connelly said.
</P>
<P>
   Whichever way New England voters go on Tuesday, they will do so
largely without the benefit of having a chance to see either Bush
or McCain in person. Both men are far more compelled by their
battle over New York's 101 delegates.
</P>
<P>
   But Friday afternoon, McCain diverted his New York campaign
briefly to deliver a speech at Sacred Heart University in
Fairfield, Conn. Bush's wife, Laura Bush, has stumped for her
husband in the state. On Saturday, Bush is expected to speak at a
rally at Bradley International Airport, north of here.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the take for both men in New England, experts and even
devout McCain supporters say they believe McCain's candidacy may
decline rapidly after Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think he's cool, fresh,'' said Denny Maisano, 47, a
banking consultant from Cheshire who plans to vote for McCain. But
``I don't think he has a broad enough appeal or enough money.''
</P>
<P>
   West, the Brown political science professor went a step further,
predicting that after a loss in California Tuesday, ``the media
begins to turn against him, McCain's money dries up and he's forced
out the race.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
