<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-RHODEN-COLUMN-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: LOOKING INSIDE RIVERSIDE CHURCH FOR ANSWERS TO NCAA
VIOLATIONS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Last Sunday, the Rev. James Forbes walked up to the
pulpit at Riverside Church to deliver his weekly sermon. Four
police officers had been cleared in the shooting of Amadou Diallo,
emotions were raging and the congregation was waiting to hear
Forbes, the senior minister, render a fiery perspective.
</P>
<P>
   But before he began, Forbes said he had some housekeeping to do.
Many had read or heard the church's name mentioned in connection
with an inquiry by the National Collegiate Athletic Association.
Specifically, the NCAA was investigating the role the Riverside
Church basketball program had played in helping Erick Barkley, a
Riverside alumnus and St. John's point guard, pay tuition to a prep
school in Maine. So Forbes assured the congregation that the church
had only been acting for the greater good and that Ernie Lorch, the
founder and director of the basketball program, was a man of
integrity, whose only intent was to help young people.
</P>
<P>
   Before Forbes called attention to the Riverside Hawks in church
last Sunday, many members of the congregation may not have known
that there was a gym downstairs, or that the gym housed one of the
most prestigious basketball programs in the United States. There is
an equal likelihood that the players down below did not know about
the legacy and long tradition of Riverside Church, an institution
that has always been in the forefront of social activism.
</P>
<P>
   For Forbes, this disparity between heaven and earth was more
disconcerting than NCAA rules and violations. Two days ago, Forbes
sat in his office and conceded that the NCAA inquiry had compelled
him to finally take more than a cursory look at the church's
well-known basketball program.
</P>
<P>
   When Forbes arrived at Riverside in 1989, the basketball program
had already been in operation for 21 years. That year, Seton Hall
played for the national championship, and four of the Pirates'
starters came from the Riverside program. At the time, that fact
was the source of pride and celebration at the Manhattan church. In
retrospect, Forbes realizes that Seton Hall's presence in the title
game was an indication of how powerful the program had become.
</P>
<P>
   What began as an outreach program now extends across the nation.
This is a sophisticated program that hunts, scouts and recruits
talent. Forbes pointed out that Riverside Church provides
scholarships to students in ways that are not related to athletics.
``We have an S O S program _ sister to sister _ that takes money
out of the endowment to aid women,'' he noted.
</P>
<P>
   But the NCAA is not concerned with Riverside's overall
benevolence. The inquiry is focused on the relationship between the
church's basketball program, Lorch and schools like St. John's that
have been the beneficiaries of Lorch's largess. It is Lorch who has
been the key person at Riverside in determining how much aid elite
athletes, like Barkley, should get to attend high-octane prep
schools, like Maine Central Institute, which specializes in
refining fifth-year seniors into Division I players.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes said Thursday that the church, in anticipation of more
meetings with the NCAA, has begun its own fact-finding mission.
Church officers and lawyers have spoken with Lorch and his lawyers
to learn the truth and unravel the gnarled roots of relationships
formed over the past 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   The church is asking itself even larger questions. Has the
basketball program's mission veered off course? Has the program
lost its sense of churchmanship? Has Forbes been too detached?
</P>
<P>
   I wondered if Forbes had ever met Erick Barkley. Forbes said he
had not.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would go to the games when the Hawks were playing nearby,''
he said. ``I would go as the pastor to show support for the teams.
I would offer trophies from the pulpit on Sunday morning when they
would come back from a tournament. I did not have a hands-on
relationship with the program.''
</P>
<P>
   Recently, Forbes had the idea of bringing all former Riverside
players back to the church and have them commit themselves to
supporting the program. ``We wanted to have them come back and say,
`We want to help so that other generations of kids could have the
opportunity,''' Forbes said. ``Ernie isn't going to be around
forever. We have to develop alternative sources if we are going to
keep this program going.''
</P>
<P>
   But Forbes has temporarily scrapped the idea. ``I'm glad we
did,'' he said. ``Otherwise, it could appear that all of the good
work we have done was in a sense a delayed process of exploitation.
You can imagine that our approach to it will be much more studied
in terms of guaranteeing the absence of any conflict of interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the spirit of generosity and helpfulness, we want to save
that,'' Forbes said.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Robert Polk has been asking questions, too. Polk came
to Riverside Church in 1960, when he was appointed minister to
youth. At the time, he was the first African-American to be
appointed a full-time minister of Riverside Church. The youth
program was 95 percent white and Asian. These were the children of
professors at Columbia and Barnard and Juilliard.
</P>
<P>
   The program would invite children from the nearby Grant Housing
projects to the church for Friday night activities. Large numbers
of black and brown faces would show up. They would attend Sunday
school classes as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, the church was overwhelmed; they really didn't know
how to handle this,'' Polk recalled.
</P>
<P>
   So the program's supervisors tried team teaching, and trips and
weekend retreats. ``The other part of that was these kids from the
Grant homes liked to play ball,'' Polk said. ``I needed someone to
take the most incorrigible kids from the Grant houses into a
specialized athletic program.''
</P>
<P>
   Lorch's roommate at Middlebury College in Vermont was a
congregational minister who knew Polk and knew that Lorch and his
mother had recently moved from Long Island to Manhattan after the
death of Lorch's father. Polk arranged a meeting; Lorch agreed to
help establish a basketball program. He would teach Sunday school
and coach basketball on Friday nights.
</P>
<P>
   A substantial portion of the money for the basketball program
came from the Dyson Family Foundation, for whom Lorch worked as
counsel and board president. ``What they didn't give,'' Polk said
of Dyson, ``Lorch contributed out of his pocket.''
</P>
<P>
   Polk left the church in 1966, then returned in 1969 as
Riverside's minister of urban affairs until 1976. By then, the
basketball program had become nationally known, and Lorch had
become a powerful figure within the basketball industry. Nike is
now one of the program's major sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   Polk, who is now the interim associate general secretary of the
National Council of Churches of Christ, feels that the original
concept of outreach has been obscured by commercialism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Ernie is a fine man and a man of integrity,'' Polk
said. ``But there doesn't seem to be a partnership between the
church and the basketball program, no sense of churchmanship.''
</P>
<P>
   Polk added: ``The first wave of youngsters were in Sunday
School. They had to be there on Sunday morning. There was some
semblance of Christian education being imparted to these young
people. What I'm really trying to say is, Have there been missed
opportunities to bring people into the realm of faith? I do believe
that when you represent an institution like a church you have to
have some allegiance to what it's all about, and your kids ought to
know. I'm not sure if those youngsters know what Riverside church
is or what it stands for.''
</P>
<P>
   Forbes said Thursday that these issues and questions have been
gnawing at him. He plans to close the gap in his church between
heaven in the nave and earth in the basement gym. ``Because the
issue is raised,'' he said, ``it obviously is a matter that the
church would be more conscious of potential ethical violations. Now
that we see more broadly what the implications are, we will watch
more closely.''
</P>
<P>
   For one church, at least, the embarrassment of an NCAA inquiry
has been a wake-up call. Better yet, call it a blessing in
disguise.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-03-00 2223EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
