<DOCNO> NYT20000303.0370 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-03 22:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6358 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-REPUBS-NY-ART-(TRIM)-     03-03 1263
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPUBS-NY-ART-(TRIM)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH AND MCCAIN TRADE CHARGES IN NEW YORK 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT36 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(lh) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY and FRANK BRUNI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Turning their full energies to perhaps the most
contested state in Tuesday's primaries, Gov. George W. Bush and
Sen. John McCain brought their tense battle to New York Friday, as
McCain accused the state's political leaders of trying to ``hijack
the campaign'' for Bush, while the Texas governor mocked his
opponent for ``squealing.''
</P>
<P>
   The exchanges, carried in the course of a day of television
interviews, campaign bus rides, outdoor rallies and forums, came as
Bush and McCain focused on a contest that McCain suggested, in a
morning interview with radio host Don Imus, he needed to win to
stay in the Republican race for president.
</P>
<P>
   Against this clearly high-stakes backdrop, McCain dived into a
vigorous schedule of campaigning, starting at 7 a.m. with a ride
around Manhattan in his campaign bus, which provided a rolling
platform for a live interview on NBC's ``Today'' show.
</P>
<P>
   At noon, he headed for the steps of Federal Hall on Wall Street,
a traditional rallying spot in New York campaigns, to offer a
spirited attack directed less at Bush and more at the governor's
chief patrons in New York, Gov. George Pataki and William D.
Powers, the New York Republican chairman, who McCain said had
orchestrated a campaign of attacks that he said distorted his views
on breast cancer research and the environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't be fooled by them, my friends,'' McCain told a modest
lunchtime crowd, shivering in the late-winter wind while straining
to hear his words on the muffled sound system. ``Don't let the
special interests decide who's going to win this election. This is
the whole reason for campaign reform: because this big money from
God-knows-where comes in and distorts the election.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush flew into Long Island, the state's traditional center of
Republican power, where he made a bid for support from women voters
in a primary where polls show him in a tight battle with McCain.
</P>
<P>
   He appeared at a staged panel discussion of breast cancer, at
the State University of New York at Stony Brook, and Elizabeth
Dole, a former rival for the Republican nomination, appeared at his
side for the first time in weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's aides billed the event as a policy discussion on breast
cancer, an issue that has been of particular concern on Long
Island, where activists have suggested that environmental
contaminants have caused high rates of the disease. Bush's campaign
appearance was intended to underline a radio advertisement Bush has
been airing in the metropolitan area this week, portraying McCain
as hostile to breast cancer research.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, Bush's forum was devoted less to policy, and
more to the campaign at hand. Bush did not offer any new proposals
to deal with the issue. He wore a pink ribbon, a symbol of concern
for the disease, and frequently had at his side the breast cancer
research advocate Geri Barish, who narrates the advertisement
attacking McCain.
</P>
<P>
   The appearance came the same day that McCain said his sister,
Susan McCain Morgan, was a breast cancer survivor. But Bush said he
would have pursued the attack on McCain's views on the subject,
which even some of Bush's supporters acknowledge are based on a
selective reading of McCain's legislative record, even if he had
been aware of McCain's sister's illness.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the more reason to remind him what he said about the
research that goes on here,'' Bush said. He said he was ``sorry if
that's the case,'' adding, ``obviously, it's very difficult for her
and the family.''
</P>
<P>
   Further, when Bush was asked if he personally believed that
McCain opposed breast cancer research, as asserted in the radio
advertisement, he responded: ``No, I don't believe that.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor went on to defend the advertisement by citing as
examples spending items that McCain had listed on his Web site of
wasteful spending by Congress. In Washington, McCain has
established a reputation as a senator who frequently denounces
spending that he says is based on political considerations, rather
than real needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ad speaks to programs that he called garden-variety
pork,'' Bush said. ``I don't think the senator should be squealing
about pork and then squealing when somebody disagrees with one of
the cuts he wants to make.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain, asked on his bus Friday night on the way to a rally in
Fairfield, Conn., about Bush's remarks about his sister, said only,
``I hope my sister wasn't watching television.''
</P>
<P>
   While Bush was talking about McCain, the senator from Arizona
was focusing on the surrogates who have been been at Bush's side
during these important days leading up to the New York vote. On
Wall Street, he referred theatrically to ``Comrade Pataki and
Comrade Powers'' as he recalled their ill-fated effort to keep him
off the ballot in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, when Imus asked him about the breast cancer attacks,
which the radio personality described as ``absurd,'' McCain quickly
agreed, as he tried to turn Bush's campaign tactics against him,
much the same way Bush tried to turn McCain's campaign tactics
against him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really is what is so distasteful and unpleasant about
politics, that the Bush campaign would run an ad saying I'm against
funding for breast cancer research,'' McCain said. ``I've voted for
it many times.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``It really is an unfortunate part of American
political campaigning when the Bush people would pay for such an
outrageous statement.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People will figure it out,'' he said. ``And if they don't
figure it out, we'll have run an honorable campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush stood by the attacks that he made on McCain, saying they
were based on a fair reading of his record. ``Let me repeat what he
says in his own words,'' Bush said, reading the list of projects
from McCain's site. ``You can't say one thing and do another. This
is a man who's gone around saying he's going to cut pork, and
that's fine. But in this race, we've documented some of the things
he's said he's going to cut.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain also seized on an advertisement challenging his record on
the environment as an example of what has been the central theme of
his candidacy: campaign finance abuse.
</P>
<P>
   The advertisement listed its sponsor as ``Republicans for Clean
Air'' and until Friday it was unclear who was behind it. But Friday
a wealthy Texas businessman named Sam Wyly came forward to say he
had paid $2.5 million to broadcast the advertisement in New York,
California and Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Because Wyly had been a big contributor to Bush, McCain's aides
asserted that Bush was orchestrating the attacks under cover of
Republicans for Clean Air. Bush emphatically denied the charges.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Campaign finance reform has been McCain's central issue, and
standing on Wall Street, addressing an audience that included a
number of Democrats _ among them, the state attorney general, Eliot
Spitzer _ he invoked the advertisement as an example of what was
wrong in politics today.
</P>
<P>
   ``Send a message back to the special interests,'' McCain said on
Wall Street. ``We're sick of government influence in New York and
in America, and we want our government back and we want our
political process and back, and you can go back from whencesoever
rock you came from.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
