<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-AD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE AD CAMPAIGN: USING BREAST CANCER AS AN ISSUE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By CLIFFORD J. LEVY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Seeking to damage Sen. John McCain's support among women, Gov.
George W. Bush's campaign portrays McCain as hostile to breast
cancer programs in a radio advertisement being run in New York.
Prominent Republicans in New York, including Gov. George Pataki,
have often tried to offset the party's traditional disadvantage
with women by highlighting their advocacy of breast cancer
programs. Pataki, who is spearheading the Bush campaign in the
state, is now turning to an ally active in breast cancer groups and
Republican politics, Geri Barish of Nassau County, N.Y., to help
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   THE SCRIPT: ``Hi. My name is Geri Barish, and I'm a breast
cancer survivor. For the last 20 years, I have worked hard to find
a cure for breast cancer and to make sure those of us with this
deadly disease are treated with dignity and respect. Like many, I
had thought of supporting John McCain in next week's presidential
primary. So I looked into his record.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I discovered was shocking. John McCain opposes many
projects dedicated to women's health issues. It's true. McCain
opposes funding for vital breast cancer programs right here in New
York. He opposes funding for the North Shore Long Island Jewish
breast cancer program and wants to cut funding for NYU's program in
women's cancer. McCain is even against funding for breast cancer
mapping. That's right, John McCain even opposes funding for breast
cancer mapping, essential to breast cancer research.
</P>
<P>
   ``John McCain calls these projects, just `garden-variety pork.'
That's shocking. America deserves better. Next Tuesday, John McCain
won't have my vote. We deserve a candidate with a record on women's
issues we can trust.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush: ``Paid for by Bush for President.''
</P>
<P>
   ACCURACY: The advertisement relies on a classic political
strategy: highlight a few votes and use them to paint a broad-brush
picture of an opponent. McCain did oppose these programs, which
were included in more than $13 billion of what he characterized as
pork-barrel spending requested by lawmakers this year. He also
opposed all the other projects in the measure. He says his quarrel
is not with the programs' merits, but with the way they were
approved with little or no public scrutiny. The McCain campaign
produced a list of numerous bills related to cancer research and
women's health that he had supported. The Bush campaign countered
that no matter how these breast cancer projects made their way
through Congress, they were worthy, and that McCain should be held
accountable for opposing them.
</P>
<P>
   SCORECARD: By using a sympathetic surrogate who never mentions
Bush by name, the advertisement is intended to yield the benefits
of a more harshly worded attack on McCain, without causing a
backlash. Women, who tend to be more moderate than men, and thus
might favor McCain, might recoil at Barish's suggestion that McCain
is a cold-hearted budget-cutter. McCain has labeled the
advertisement an example of dirty-tricks politics, hoping to stoke
anger at Bush's tactics. Whether that will work will depend on how
successful he is at explaining to voters that in crusading against
pork-barrel projects, he is fighting to change Washington.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
