<HEADER>
A6375 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-GOLDSTEIN-TRIAL-NY     03-03 0578
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GOLDSTEIN-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECOND MURDER TRIAL OPENS IN SUBWAY SHOVING CASE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By JULIAN E. BARNES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The second murder trial of a schizophrenic man who
threw a woman to her death in front of a subway train began Friday,
as his lawyer promised to try to show jurors the depths of his
illness when he is not taking medication.
</P>
<P>
   The man, Andrew Goldstein, 30, has admitted pushing the woman,
Kendra Webdale, 32, to her death on Jan. 3, 1999, but he has
maintained that he was not responsible because of his
schizophrenia. He did not testify during his first trial in State
Supreme Court in Manhattan, which ended in November in a hung jury.
</P>
<P>
   But Friday, outside the courtroom, Goldstein's lawyer said he
hoped to have Goldstein stop his medication and take the witness
stand.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer, Kevin Canfield, said that jurors should be able to
see Goldstein's condition when he is not taking anti-psychotic
medication, since he was not taking the medicine when he pushed
Webdale.
</P>
<P>
   Toward that end, Goldstein, who lawyers say agrees with the
strategy, stopped taking the drug Risperdol on Feb. 12. But two
weeks later Goldstein punched the court social worker monitoring
his care. After that, Justice Carol Berkman ordered that Goldstein
be offered his medication twice a day, and he has been taking the
drugs regularly since Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In his opening statement Friday, Canfield argued that the subway
attack was one in a series of psychotic episodes over 10 years in
which Goldstein abruptly punched, kicked or shoved people. But
William Greenbaum, the lead prosecutor, said Goldstein was using
his illness as an excuse.
</P>
<P>
   In his opening statement, Canfield outlined a detailed history
of Goldstein's journey in and out of the state's mental health
system, highlighting how Goldstein had been rejected by his mother,
discharged from hospitals and banned from a clinic.
</P>
<P>
   ``His own family abandoned him, and that was just the beginning
of his slide,'' Canfield said.
</P>
<P>
   Canfield said Goldstein believed aliens were sucking oxygen from
the Earth, his mother was poisoning his food, someone inhabiting
his body was removing his brain, and others were controlling him.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was not the act of a cold-blooded, depraved killer,''
Canfield said. ``He didn't know it was wrong if he didn't know what
he was doing.''
</P>
<P>
   But Greenbaum said he would prove that Goldstein knew what he
was doing, knew it was wrong and was using his mental illness to
shield himself from the consequences of his actions. Immediately
after he killed Webdale, Greenbaum said, Goldstein claimed he was
psychotic and used ``his insanity as a tool to insulate him from
the consequences of his actions right away.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday afternoon, Greenbaum called to the stand a woman who was
standing near Webdale and saw the attack. Dawn Lorenzino, who also
testified at the first trial, said Goldstein shuffled oddly back
and forth on the platform of the 23rd Street Station of the N line.
She said he later stood behind Webdale, asked what time it was and
moved to the wall of the station.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the train entered the station, what did you see?''
Greenbaum asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw him push off the wall, and he threw her in front of the
train,'' Lorenzino said.
</P>
<P>
   In the second row of courtroom spectators, a tear rolled down
the cheek of Webdale's mother, Patricia. At the defense table,
Goldstein tugged at his lip with his hand.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
