<HEADLINE>
LYNDON ALLIN, 59; WORKED FOR 3 PRESIDENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lyndon K. Allin, who worked in the White House under three
Republican presidents, died on Monday in a hospital in Washington.
He was 59.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was chronic lymphocytic leukemia, said his daughter,
Stephanie Allin Clemson of Evanston, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   Allin went to Washington in 1967 as the national director of
Youth for Nixon. After the 1968 election, he served on President
Nixon's staff, where he was a special assistant to the president.
He continued in that capacity under President Ford.
</P>
<P>
   From 1978 to 1981, Allin served in the information agency as the
assistant information officer at the U.S. Embassy in Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
   He returned to the White House in 1981 as a member of Ronald
Reagan's staff and served in the White House press office as the
deputy press secretary for foreign affairs and national security.
</P>
<P>
   In 1984, he returned to the information agency and became the
press and cultural counselor at the U.S. consulate in Leningrad. He
retired in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Lyndon King Allin was born in Detroit on Feb. 7, 1941, and
graduated from the University of Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   Besides his daughter, he is survived by his wife, Mary Ann; a
son, Lyndon King II, of Washington; his mother, Ruth Emory Allin of
Minneapolis; a sister, Nancy Allin Nelson of St. Paul; and a
brother, Robin Nail Allin of Hoffman Estates, Ill.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
