   (NYT5) UNDATED -- March 3, 2000 -- MACHINES-HUMANS -- The
challenge of the best way to mate man and machine led Europe's
Airbus Industrie, and the Boeing Company to adopt different
philosophies when they designed the cockpits of their latest
airplanes. Airbus places so-called hard limits on its pilots to
protect them from themselves. Boeing deliberately gives pilots the
ability to risk destroying the plane in order to save it. Both
companies are quick to say that both approaches are safe. But as
fierce international rivals fighting each other for every sale from
the world's airlines they are each equally quick to make the case
why their particular design is superior. (Boeing, Airbus/The New
York Times)
