<SLUG> BC-BKC-IBA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUTTON, COWBOYS PLAY FINAL GAME IN ANCIENT ARENA TODAY
</HEADLINE>
 ARENA-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eddie Sutton remembers the first time he walked into
Gallagher-Iba Arena as a youngster out of Bucklin, Kan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very impressed,'' Sutton recalled. ``At that time, it
still was considered one of the showcases for college basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, in that spring of 1954, Sutton had no idea that he
would play in some of the most memorable games in the storied
arena, that was built for the staggering sum of $400,000 in 1938..
Or, that he would someday return as the Cowboys' coach and send one
of his teams onto the inch-and-a-half-thick maple floor to play the
last game in the facility, almost a half-century later.
</P>
<P>
   In a matter of weeks after today's Bedlam battle between the
Cowboys and Oklahoma, workmen will literally raise the roof and
knock down the walls and begin the next phase in a $54 million
expansion, that will transform one of the last relics of a bygone
era into a 13,000-seat comprehensive athletic facility that will
catapult the program into the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   Only the floor _ which will make the transition if it isn't
damaged _ and the memories will remain.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many memories,'' said Sutton, whose experience in the
facility spans four seasons as a player and eight as the Cowboys'
head coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can remember when we beat Cincinnati when theyhad Oscar
Robertson, beating Kansas when they had Wilt Chamberlain \Rboth in
1957\S _ and those are two pretty good memories. The shot that
Bryant Reeves hit from half-court to send the game into overtime
against Missouri \R1993\S, a game we eventually won. But the one
thing I'll always remember is that when this place is rocking, no
place in college basketball is louder.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the loudest moment in Gallagher-Iba might have come
in 1978 when a delirious capacity crowd raised such a
ruckuscheering the outcome of a match that clinched the Big Eight
wrestling championship that light bulbs burst and glass rained down
from the ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   The building was originally named the 4-H Club Building and
Student Activity Center, before being changed to Gallagher Hall to
honor legendary wrestling coach Ed Gallagher. After a 1987
remodeling, the last name of a more-famous legend _ basketball
coach Henry Iba _ was added.
</P>
<P>
   The late Mr. Iba provided the impetus for building the new
facility, once called ``Hank's Folly'' before being transformed
into ``Hank's House of Horrors.'' After coming to A&AMP;M from Colorado
in 1934, Mr. Iba soon began to field teams that were so successful
they rapidly outgrew a 2,500-seat bandbox home. In the new arena,
Mr. Iba established one of college basketball's endearing
dynasties, winning consecutive national championships in 1945-46
behind the play of 7-foot center Bob Kurland _ whose 58 points
scored against St. Louis in '46 still stands as the facility's
all-time scoring record.
</P>
<P>
   OSU senior Desmond Mason made his recruiting visit to watch the
Cowboys play OU in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``After seeing that game, I knew I wanted to be in this
atmosphere,'' Mason said. ``It was the most incredible atmosphere
I've ever seen for a game. There is something magical about this
place.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the new facility, when it opens in December, will no
doubt be as impressive as the old place was to Sutton and Mason, it
will not retain the historical charm nor the opposing team's sense
of being surrounded while being bombarded with the cacophonyof
6,000 fanatics.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a selfish standpoint, I like the cozy atmosphere,''
Sutton said. ``But the architects tell me that the \Rhome-court
advantage\S will still be quite good. So many other things the
university needed badly will be included, and we need the added
revenue. So this is something that had to be done. But it will
never be the same.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
