the Corcoran Gallery of Art in Washington, and is scheduled to
travel to museums across America. Built in the 15th century, the
Topkapi Palace stands high atop a bluff with panoramic views of
Asia and Europe. The rooftops of the building's harem are shown,
looking north toward the Bosporus. (Palace Arts Foundation/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) NEW YORK -- March 3, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MARCH 5 --
DYLAN-MUSIC -- John Corigliano, at his Manhattan apartment last
month, has created ``Mr. Tambourine Man: Seven Songs of Bob
Dylan,'' a 35-minute song cycle based on some of Dylan's lyrics.
``He might not like what I've done,'' says Corigliano, 62. ``But if
the poetry is good, it can stand it, just as a poem by Goethe can
stand different settings by Schumann, Brahms or Wolf. And I think
it is good, otherwise I wouldn't have set it.'' (Richard Perry/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) DALLAS -- March 3, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MARCH 5 --
DALLAS-SYMPHONY-B&AMP;W -- Tell a New Yorker that the symphony
orchestra in Dallas is 100 years old, and the reaction will
probably be surprise. The Dallas Symphony Orchestra would like to
change that, despite a history that has followed a rollercoaster
track of highs and lows. Its first concert took place in Turner
Hall in Dallas in 1900. (Dallas Symphony Orchestra/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) SHANGHAI, China -- March 3, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MARCH
5 -- SHANGHAI-SYMPHONY-B&AMP;W -- Last year the Shanghai Symphony
Orchestra, as it has been called since 1953, celebrated its 120th
anniversary. As the nation's oldest symphony orchestra, it has done
more to promote the development of symphonic music in China than
any other institution. The orchestra, dressed in military-style
uniforms during the Cultural Revolution, was performing the
ideologically pure opera ``Shajiabang.'' (Shanghai Symphony
Orchestra/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) NEW YORK -- March 3, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MARCH 5 --
CHARLES-ATLAS-ART -- In the last 30 years, the media artist Charles
Atlas has created scores of videos, films, performances and set and
lighting designs for opera, theater and dance. This Friday through
April 1 the Kitchen will present a video-installation featuring two
new works. Atlas is shown in his Manhattan studio, with still
photographs on either side from his video installations ``Teach,''
at left, and ``99 (Johanna).'' (Don Hogan Charles/The New York
Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) BAHIA, Brazil -- March 3, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MARCH 5
-- CARNAVAL-BRAZIL -- The trio eletrico was created 50 years ago.
Now the hulking music machines, and the crowds that engulf them,
are a fixture of carnival in Bahia. Osmar helped invent the trio
eletrico with this 1929 Ford. (Osmar Macedo Foundation/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) STONY BROOK, N.Y. -- March 3, 2000 -- NY-GIULIANI-BUSH
-- Mayor Rudolph Giuliani of New York, left, is followed by the
state governor, George Pataki, center, and Gov. George W. Bush of
Texas, running for the Republican presidential nomination, as they
arrive for a news conference Friday at Stony Brook Health Sciences
Center. Giuliani kept a low profile during the event where Sen.
John McCain, Bush's rival for the nomination, was slammed for his
voting record on breast cancer research. (Stephen Crowley/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) MAMARONECK, N.Y. -- March 3, 2000 -- WATCHING-TIGER --
Fans watch as Tiger Woods lines up a putt during the PGA
Championship at the Winged Foot Golf Club in 1997. When Woods plays
golf, television executives swoon. With his rare power to move
ratings, he is the sports version of ``E.R.'' or ``Who Wants To Be
A Millionaire,'' a singular, 24-year-old programming entity capable
of clubbing rival networks in their Nielsens in his pursuit of
tournament victories. (Barton Silverman/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) UNDATED -- March 3, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MARCH 5 --
PORGY-AND-BESS-B&AMP;W -- ``Porgy and Bess'' comes to the New York City
Opera on Tuesday evening, so it is a good time to celebrate the man
largely responsible for the opera's resilience: DuBose Heyward, the
author of the 1925 novel ``Porgy.'' George Gershwin, left, Heyward
and Ira Gershwin, collaborators on ``Porgy and Bess,'' in 1935. The
writing on the photo is by George and Ira to Heyward, wishing him
well on the production. (United States Information Service/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) UNDATED -- March 3, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MARCH 5 --
WESTERN-FILMS-B&AMP;W -- Remember the Western? The question is not
unreasonable, given that Americans born since 1975 - the biggest
moviegoers - are the first modern generation for whom Westerns and
the cowboy mystique are not a thread in the weft of their daily
lives. ``Stagecoach'' (1939), directed by John Ford and starring
John Wayne, was considered a landmark western about an outsider.
(Museum of Modern Art/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) NEW YORK -- March 3, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MARCH 5 --
FLEA-THEATER -- Until recently, the 80-seat Flea in Manhattan has
been thought of mainly as an Off Off Broadway theater. Now it is
becoming known downtown as a dance venue hoping to give some
competition to more established spaces like P.S. 122 and the
Kitchen. Jim Simpson, the theater's director and founder, and
Lizzie Simon, the Flea's creative producer, at the theater in
TriBeCa. (Sara Krulwich/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEW YORK -- March 3, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MARCH 5 --
BOYD-GAINES-THEATER -- Boyd Gaines as a lonely New York actor who
manages to dance a bit with dancers in ``Contact,'' reopening at
the Vivian Beaumont Theater after a sold-out run at the Mitzi E.
Newhouse. That his face is familiar to regular theatergoers - he
won Tony Awards in 1989 and 1994 for ``The Heidi Chronicles'' and
``She Loves Me'' - deepens the audience's own contact with the
production. (Sara Krulwich/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- March 3, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MARCH 5 --
DEBORAH-YATES-THEATER -- Deborah Yates as the Girl in the Yellow
Dress: a dancer who combines grit and grace in ``Contact,''
reopening at the Vivian Beaumont Theater after a sold-out run at
the Mitzi E. Newhouse. From the moment she enters in that arresting
yellow outfit, it is clear that this is not just another striking
theatrical performance. It is the uncommon but unmistakable
emergence of a star. (Sara Krulwich/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) STONY BROOK, N.Y. -- March 3, 2000 -- BUSH -- From left,
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani of New York, Gov. George Pataki and Gov.
George W. Bush of Texas, during a news conference at Stony Brook
Health Sciences Center, a part of New York State University,
Friday. Bush, flanked by New York's Republican elite at a forum on
women's health issues, accused rival John McCain of ``squealing''
in reference to ads critical of his stance on funding breast cancer
research. (Stephen Crowley/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) PARIS -- March 3, 2000 -- PARIS-FASHION-2 -- Red
gold-studded jeans anf fur-trimmed coat by Emanuel Ungaro, left,
funneled mohair skirt by sweater from Dries van Noten, center, and
wool jeans with bomber jacket by Michael Kors for Celine.
(Jean-Luce Hure, left and center, Dan Lecca/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) PARIS -- March 3, 2000 -- PARIS-FASHION -- Army coat over
Jacquard dress by Stella McCartney for Chloe, left, Gold and aqua
brocade coat by Christian Lacroix, center, and Veronique
Branquinho's lean plaid trench coat over check trousers. (Jean-Luce
Hure, left, Dan Lecca/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) PORTLAND, Maine -- March 3, 2000 -- BRADLEY -- Bill
Bradley, running for the Democratic presidential nomination, boards
his campaign airplane bound for Providence, R.I., Friday. Trailing
Vice President Al Gore in polls ahead of the next Tuesday's slew of
primaries and caucuses, Bradley pledged Thursday to stay in the
race, urging voters to ignore pollsters and pundits and ``vote your
heart.'' (Nicole Bengiveno/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- March 3, 2000 -- MCCAIN-1-- Sen. John McCain
looks up as confetti falls during a campaign rally on Wall Street,
Friday. Looking on are McCain's wife Cindy and Guy Molinari,
McCain's senior New York adviser and Staten Island borough
president. New York is one of 16 states holding presidential
primaries next Tuesday. (Ruth Fremson/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) UNDATED -- March 3, 2000 -- MACHINES-HUMANS -- The
challenge of the best way to mate man and machine led Europe's
Airbus Industrie, and the Boeing Company to adopt different
philosophies when they designed the cockpits of their latest
airplanes. Airbus places so-called hard limits on its pilots to
protect them from themselves. Boeing deliberately gives pilots the
ability to risk destroying the plane in order to save it. Both
companies are quick to say that both approaches are safe. But as
fierce international rivals fighting each other for every sale from
the world's airlines they are each equally quick to make the case
why their particular design is superior. (Boeing, Airbus/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) BEIRUT, Lebanon -- March 3, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MARCH
5 -- LEBANON-AMNESIA-2-COX -- Assaad Shaftari, an officer with the
largest Christian militia during the Lebanese civil war, during an
interview last month. In February, Shaftari took out ads in local
newspapers apologizing for war crimes during the 15-year Lebanese
civil war that ended in 1990. ``I want to apologize, apologize to
all those whose executioner I was or who were my victims'' wrote
Shaftari in the ads. (Larry Kaplow/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) BEIRUT, Lebanon -- March 3, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MARCH
5 -- LEBANON-AMNESIA-COX -- Relatives of some of the estimated
17,000 people missing during Lebanon's civil war demonstrate
outside a government building in Beirut. In January, the Lebanese
government formed a committee to determine the fate of 17,000
people who ``disappeared'' during the long-running conflict. (Larry
Kaplow/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) BOSTON -- March 3, 2000 -- ECOMMERCE-B2B-BOS -- Dominic
Johnson at a construction site in January. Johnson, who is listing
heavy machinery on his Web auction site, AssetLine.com, sees a gold
mine in ``Big Dig'' and other construction sites around the
country. (David L. Ryan/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) JACKSONVILLE, Fla. -- March 3, 2000 -- GORE -- Vice
President Al Gore, running for the Democratic presidential
nomination, is surrounded by cheerleaders as he arrives to William
Raines High School Friday for a campaign rally. Gore address the
crowd on issues involving education and overcrowded schools. (Paul
Hosefros/The New York Times)
</P>
