<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Friday, 03/03/00. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   Editors, please note the following elimination and correction:
</P>
<P>
   We have have sent out an elimination advisory for NYT6 of Feb.
19, 2000, showing Guy Waterman and his wife Laura. Due to an
editing error, the photo, slugged OBIT-WATERMAN, was incorrectly
made available to clients of the news service.
</P>
<P>
   We have also sent out a correction, for NYT21 from the file of
Feb. 29, to correct the name of the building in the photo to the
New 42nd Street Studios. The photo illustrated a story slugged
THEATER-NAMES.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT38) EASTCHESTER, N.Y. -- March 3, 2000 -- REPUBS-NY --
Turning their full energies to perhaps the most contested state in
Tuesday's primaries, Gov. George W. Bush and Sen. John McCain
brought their tense battle to New York Friday. Flanked by Rep.
Peter T. King and the statue of an earlier politician, McCain held
a rally on Wall Street. (Ruth Fremson/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT37) NEW YORK -- March 3, 2000 -- NY-MURDERS -- By early
Friday morning the police had found five members of the Santos
familyies dead in the three separate buildings in the Bronx. Denise
Santos was discovered stabbed to death at 2934 Radcliff Avenue.
(George M. Gutierrez/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT36) EASTCHESTER, N.Y. -- March 3, 2000 -- NY-REPUBS-VOICES
-- The stiff competition among the GOP candidates, and the approach
of the New York primary on Tuesday, have enlivened the discourse at
the Odyssey Diner here. Angela and George Doukas, top, personify
the split among voters in Eastchester: She is for John McCain,
while he supports George W. Bush. Constantine Despotakis, below,
said he believed Bush relied too much on his father's name and
record. (Joyce Dopkeen/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT35) WASHINGTON -- March 3, 2000 -- REPUBS-CONGRESS -- After
a series of twists in their favor, Republicans have improved their
chances of keeping control of the House in this year's elections,
according to party leaders, analysts and strategists from both
parties. Rep. Thomas M. Davis III, R-Va., left, discussed campaign
strategy with Mark Nielson, who is running for the Connecticut
House seat held by James H. Maloney, a Democrat. (Justin Lane/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT34) WASHINGTON -- March 3, 2000 -- MCCAIN-SENATE-B&AMP;W -- In
13 years in the Senate, Sen. John McCain has amassed a solidly
conservative voting record accompanied by less ideological
interests. McCain is shown in his office with his press secretary,
Torrie Clark, in 1988. (Jose R. Lopez/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT33) NEW YORK -- March 3, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MARCH 5 --
CAR-SMART-AUDI -- BMW has mastered the art of the European sedan.
Special bright colors are carried over into the Audi S4's sport
interior. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT32) NEW YORK -- March 3, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MARCH 5 --
ABOUT-CARS-MERCEDES -- In the current feeding frenzy, the
definition of sport utility has hopelessly moved beyond the
original notion of a truck with a covered bed and four-wheel-drive
to manage the hunting trail. It now covers virtually anything that
has big, knobby tires and a hefty dose of attitude. Still, there
must be limits, and the Mercedes-Benz ML55 AMG might be somewhere
just beyond them. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT31) NEW YORK -- March 3, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MARCH 5 --
MARKET-WEALTH-SPEND -- David Brancaccio, host of the public radio
program ``Marketplace,'' has just written a book called
``Squandering Aimlessly,'' an account of what people around the
country do, or could do, with a chunk of extra money. Since this
was publication day, and Simon &AMP; Schuster owed him $25,000, he
wanted his check, and he wanted to imagine what he could do with
that sum - on the spot. ``Let's see,'' he said, pulling out a
calculator. ``Minus the agent's commission, that's $21,250.''
(Chester Higgins Jr./The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) NEW YORK -- March 3, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MARCH 5 --
BIZ-CHARM -- As part of a class in finding a husband, Debra Cox,
left, told Cheryl Marks, right, about clothes; Robin Lennon advised
on clutter. While feminists might bridle at the course objective
and the curriculum, Marilyn Graman, a psychotherapist who teaches
the class, advises that women do not change themselves or try to
deceive their men while pursuing them. (Carol Halebian/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) UNDATED -- March 3, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MARCH 5 --
INVEST-WITH-HOOVER -- During the day, Michael E. Hoover picks
energy stocks for the $57.5 million Excelsior Energy and Natural
Resources fund, which he runs. ``We see the most significant value
opportunities in energy,'' said Hoover, 46, who spent a recent
evening at home with his four children. (Susan B. Markisz/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) UNDATED -- March 3, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MARCH 5 --
POST-PROPERTIES -- Post Properties used to specialize in suburban
developments like Post Canyon, left, as metropolitan Atlanta became
an example of urban sprawl. It now concentrates on in-town projects
like Post Renaissance, right, just minutes from downtown
activities. (Post Properties/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) NEW YORK -- March 3, 2000 -- NOISE-MCBURNEY -- Simon
McBurney, artistic director of the Theatre de Complicite. As
directed by McBurney, ``The Noise of Time'' is a remarkable
contemplation of the life of the great, famously troubled Russian
composer Dmitri Shostakovich (1906-75), presenting darkness as an
element that while all-consuming is by no means sterile. (Don Hogan
Charles/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) NEW YORK -- March 3, 2000 -- NOISE-THEATER-REVIEW-2 --
Darkness is the earth and oxygen of ``The Noise of Time,'' the
exquisitely realized elegy of a performance piece created by the
Theatre de Complicite. Antonio Gil Martinez, one of the show's four
nonmusical performers, shared the stage with a cello during the
performance. (Sara Krulwich/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) NEW YORK -- March 3, 2000 -- NOISE-THEATER-REVIEW-1 --
Darkness is the earth and oxygen of ``The Noise of Time,'' the
exquisitely realized elegy of a performance piece created by the
Theatre de Complicite. Members of the Emerson String Quartet were
shadowy figures in ``The Noise of Time,'' commissioned by the
Lincoln Center Great Performers series. (Sara Krulwich/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) PARIS -- March 3, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MARCH 5 --
RENZO-PIANO-ARCH-B&AMP;W -- Even now, at 62, Renzo Piano seemed amazed
that France had allowed two young foreigners - he was 33 and his
British partner, Richard Rogers, was 37 - to challenge the sober
18th-century stone facades of eastern Paris with their immense
metallic design for the Georges Pompidou Center there. ``President
Pompidou was very courageous, that's for sure,'' said Piano, left,
shown with Rogers during construction of the center. (Richard
Rogers Partnership/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) ISTANBUL, Turkey -- March 3, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
MARCH 5 -- TURKEY-ART -- An exhibition called ``Palace of Gold and
Light: Treasures From the Topkapi, Istanbul'' opened Wednesday at
the Corcoran Gallery of Art in Washington, and is scheduled to
travel to museums across America. Built in the 15th century, the
Topkapi Palace stands high atop a bluff with panoramic views of
Asia and Europe. The rooftops of the building's harem are shown,
looking north toward the Bosporus. (Palace Arts Foundation/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) NEW YORK -- March 3, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MARCH 5 --
DYLAN-MUSIC -- John Corigliano, at his Manhattan apartment last
month, has created ``Mr. Tambourine Man: Seven Songs of Bob
Dylan,'' a 35-minute song cycle based on some of Dylan's lyrics.
``He might not like what I've done,'' says Corigliano, 62. ``But if
the poetry is good, it can stand it, just as a poem by Goethe can
stand different settings by Schumann, Brahms or Wolf. And I think
it is good, otherwise I wouldn't have set it.'' (Richard Perry/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) DALLAS -- March 3, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MARCH 5 --
DALLAS-SYMPHONY-B&AMP;W -- Tell a New Yorker that the symphony
orchestra in Dallas is 100 years old, and the reaction will
probably be surprise. The Dallas Symphony Orchestra would like to
change that, despite a history that has followed a rollercoaster
track of highs and lows. Its first concert took place in Turner
Hall in Dallas in 1900. (Dallas Symphony Orchestra/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) SHANGHAI, China -- March 3, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MARCH
5 -- SHANGHAI-SYMPHONY-B&AMP;W -- Last year the Shanghai Symphony
Orchestra, as it has been called since 1953, celebrated its 120th
anniversary. As the nation's oldest symphony orchestra, it has done
more to promote the development of symphonic music in China than
any other institution. The orchestra, dressed in military-style
