<HEADLINE>
CON ED SAYS CUSTOMERS WILL ABSORB COST CAUSED BY LEAK AT A-PLANT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ko) 
 By ANDREW C. REVKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Consolidated Edison, the owner of the nuclear power plant in
Buchanan, N.Y., that shut down after a radioactive leak last month,
said Friday that its customers would have to absorb the
$600,000-a-day added cost as it buys electricity from other
utilities while the plant is dormant.
</P>
<P>
   The comments came at a hearing convened by several state
Assembly committees in White Plains to examine the causes and
consequences of the Feb. 15 leak at the Indian Point 2 plant, which
brought the reactor to the second of four ascending levels of
emergency, caused a regional alert and raised the ire of some
elected officials who were not immediately notified.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Leonard, a Con Edison spokesman, said the temporary rate
increase would raise the $51 monthly bill for the typical homeowner
by about $2, and would be reflected in bills beginning in April.
The plant is expected to be shut for at least several more weeks.
</P>
<P>
   At the hearing, the company also provided new details about the
troubled history of the steam generator that was the source of the
leak that sent a puff of steam and gas escaping from the plant _
and possibly a minute amount of radiation.
</P>
<P>
   Con Edison is one of many utilities that sued Westinghouse, the
manufacturer of the plant's four steam generators, over what they
contended were flawed operating instructions that caused the
generators to wear out prematurely. In a settlement of the suit,
the utility received four replacement generators in 1987 but never
installed them.
</P>
<P>
   After the hearing, Richard L. Brodsky, the chairman of the
Assembly Committee on Environmental Conservation and a Westchester
County Democrat, said it appeared that Con Edison, in delaying
installation of the equipment, had put business decisions before
safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have the live possibility that this accident was
inevitable and foreseeable,'' Brodsky said. ``They've been driving
a '75 Chevy and claiming if you just kept it up right it'd last
forever. And it didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   At the hearing, Michael Evans, the president and chief operating
officer of Con Edison, said the company had always made decisions
at the plant based first on safety, with any other factors
secondary.
</P>
<P>
   Con Edison sees no reason, he said, even with the leak last
month, to replace the generators immediately. He added that the
work would take up to two years and cost at least $100 million, not
including the price of replacement energy.
</P>
<P>
   Reacting to Brodsky's comments, Leonard said that there had
never been any danger to the public or employees and that the
utility had abided by federal regulations. ``This is a typical
government response,'' he said. ``Pass a resolution, have a
hearing, moan and move on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-03-00 2306EST &QL; 
