u a BC-NY-PRISONER-ABORTION-     03-03 0670
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PRISONER-ABORTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN LAWSUIT, JUDGE BARS COUNTY INMATE FROM HAVING ABORTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By JOHN SULLIVAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A state Supreme Court justice in Watertown, N.Y., issued a
temporary order this week barring a jail inmate from having an
abortion until a court hearing on whether county corrections
officials should pay for the procedure.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Civil Liberties Union, which represents the woman,
has said it would contest the order in the hearing, scheduled for
Monday. The lawyers said corrections officials have a
responsibility to pay for abortions because they are part of
inmates' medical care.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a flagrant violation of constitutional principles,''
said Donna Lieberman, director of the reproductive rights project
of the civil liberties union. ``There is an overwhelming lack of
legal basis for the temporary restraining order.''
</P>
<P>
   In an order issued Wednesday, Justice Hugh A. Gilbert of state
Supreme Court barred the Jefferson County sheriff from allowing the
woman to undergo an abortion while in custody until a court hearing
could be held. The order also generally barred the woman, Barbara
Gaddy, from having the procedure until the hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Because Gaddy was released soon after the order was entered, she
has been in the unusual position of being forbidden to undergo the
medical procedure even though no longer in custody, her lawyers
said.
</P>
<P>
   Gilbert issued the order in response to a lawsuit filed by an
area resident who sought to prevent the sheriff from spending
county funds for the abortion. The plaintiff, Karen Jackson, argued
in her legal filing that an abortion is an elective medical
procedure and is not an appropriate expense for the sheriff's
office.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no medical necessity, so why should the county pay
for it?'' asked John J. Broderick, the plaintiff's lawyer.
Broderick, who described his client as a ``very active pro-lifer,''
said he has represented anti-abortion campaigners in court for
about 12 years.
</P>
<P>
   Broderick said he based his legal argument on a state law that
bars officials from unreasonable or unnecessary spending. He said
the county does not pay for elective procedures, like cosmetic
surgery, for inmates, and should not pay for Gaddy's abortion.
</P>
<P>
   ``She does not have the right to have county funds pay for it,''
Broderick said.
</P>
<P>
   Gaddy was released from county jail late Wednesday afternoon.
Her lawyer, Krista Chacona, said she spent 30 days in jail after
being charged with drug possession and sale. She has not been tried
on the charges.
</P>
<P>
   Chacona said that since her client's release, she ``has not
acted in violation of the order.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Gaddy has been released from county jail, Broderick said
he would not contest the removal of the temporary restraining
order.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no reason for the county to pay for it if she is
out,'' he said. ``There is not going to be a decision here on the
merits.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, of the civil liberties union, said a federal court
decision has determined that corrections officials generally must
pay for inmates' abortions. In a case filed by an inmate in
Monmouth County, N.J., the 3rd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ruled
in 1987 that corrections officials must pay for inmates' abortions,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not a matter for a corrections department to decide
whether or not an abortion is an elective procedure,'' Lieberman
said.
</P>
<P>
   Louise Melling, the associate director of the American Civil
Liberties Union's Reproductive Freedom Project, said inmates'
ability to obtain abortions is an ``issue that arises on a very
regular basis.''
</P>
<P>
   Melling said her organization has been successful representing
inmates denied the procedure, although she said there are no
nationwide rules. Typically, she said, inmates rely on
constitutional grounds. The courts have held that the government
cannot set up a restriction that places a substantial obstacle in
the path of a woman who is seeking an abortion, she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-03-00 2310EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
