<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-03 23:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6506 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-BOBJONES-DATING-NYT &LR;      03-03 0421
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOBJONES-DATING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERRACIAL DATING BAN TO END AT BOB JONES UNIVERSITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (DUPLICATION NOTICE: Also filed in category `p') 
(js) 
 By GUSTAV NIEBUHR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, S.C. _ In an unexpected move, Bob Jones University,
a fundamentalist Christian institution that had come under national
criticism for a ban on interracial dating among its students,
dropped that long-held policy Friday, its president, Bob Jones III
announced Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, in an appearance on the CNN program ``Larry King Live,''
said that he had asked the university's board Friday afternoon to
end the policy, which the university had tenaciously held for
years. ``As of today, right now, we're dropping it,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   In his remarks, Jones, grandson of the university's founder,
provided only a brief explanation for the decision, saying that it
was based on a perception that widespread controversy over the
policy was threatening to obscure the university's Christian
mission.
</P>
<P>
   The decision also came only days after Democrats in Congress had
proposed a resolution to condemn the university for the ban and for
statements its leaders have made about Roman Catholicism, which
have been widely interpreted as attacks on Catholics in general.
The university has denied having any such intent.
</P>
<P>
   This issue of the university's positions came to the fore last
month after the visit on Feb. 2 by Texas Gov. George W. Bush, a
candidate for the Republican presidential nomination. Bush's
opponents, Republicans and Democrats alike, faulted him for not
taking the opportunity to speak out against the dating ban and the
statements on the Roman Catholic faith.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night after Jones' announcement, Bush said: ``I'm
heartened to hear that Bob Jones University has reversed its ban on
interracial dating. It was wrong to begin with and that's why I
spoke out against the ban when I was asked about it at a news
conference immediately after my visit there. Tonight, the school
has done the right thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The announcement by the university's president amounted to a
remarkable turnaround for the 73-year-old institution that hews to
an unapologetic adherence to classic Protestant fundamentalism.
After a 13-year legal fight, the university lost its tax exemption
over the issue in 1983. As late as Wednesday, the university was
attempting to explain the ban on interracial dating according to
its belief that the Bible teaches that God does not want a unified
and undifferentiated world.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-03-00 2310EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000303.0391 </DOCNO>
