<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-POLE0304-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Odd couple at front in Vegas
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Ricky Rudd and Scott Pruett form an ironic tandem on
the front row for the Carsdirect.com 400 on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Rudd, who broke through to win the No. 1 starting position
Friday after beginning on the outside pole in the season's first
two races, is a first-year driver for Robert Yates Racing. Rudd was
an owner/driver last year on the circuit but opted to sell his
operation when Tide decided not to renew its sponsorship deal.
</P>
<P>
   Rudd's loss was Pruett's gain. Tide signed a contract to become
a primary sponsor with the new Winston Cup team of Cal Wells and
PPI Motorsports. Pruett was chosen by Wells to operate the No. 32
Ford this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure it will be a little strange (starting next to the
Tide car),'' Rudd said. ``I got some experience with that at
Daytona; I ran around Scott some (and) I saw him during the race. I
think since it's got that 32 on the door (instead of the No. 10
used by Rudd last year), it's not quite the same thing for me. But
it will be a little awkward.''
</P>
<P>
   Rudd, who was clocked at 172.563 mph, was one of seven drivers
to break the qualifying record at Las Vegas Motor Speedway on
Friday. Pruett, who posted a speed of 172.381 mph, also felt irony
about having his car placed next to Rudd's No. 28 Ford for the
race.
</P>
<P>
   ``First, I have to applaud Yates for getting the front row
again,'' said Pruett, noting Dale Jarrett's pole position for the
Daytona 500. ``Second, it is pretty ironic (being next to Rudd), no
question about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ricky and I are totally fine and he is the driver putting on
the rookie meetings every time we come into the event. So we
complained to him this morning that he didn't show us the right way
(at Rockingham), because three rookies didn't make the race and the
others crashed in the race. So he gave us better points for this
weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   Pruett being on the outside spot of the front row was
surprising, considering that the first-year driver failed to
qualify at Rockingham last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the back row to the front row, what a big change a week
makes,'' Pruett said.
</P>
<P>
   Dale Earnhardt Jr. was the other rookie turning heads on Friday.
He qualified for the third position, which will be his best start
in eight career Winston Cup events.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the notable drivers failing to qualify in the first
round included Bill Elliott, Dale Earnhardt, Ken Schrader, Ward
Burton and John Andretti. Second-round qualifying for positions
26-43 starts at 2:30 p.m. today.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-03-00 2311EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000303.0393 </DOCNO>
