<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-03 23:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6512 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-PHILIPMORRIS-NYT     03-03 0454
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-PHILIPMORRIS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW STRATEGY AT PHILIP MORRIS 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, March 4:
</P>
<P>
   Philip Morris, the nation's largest cigarette maker, is battling
to rehabilitate its image as part of a pariah industry. After
decades of denials, Philip Morris publicly admitted last fall that
smoking is addictive and causes cancer and other fatal disease.
This week Steven Parrish, a senior vice president of Philip Morris,
said the company was willing to discuss some federal regulation of
tobacco. Parrish also expressed his belief, at a conference
sponsored by the National Center on Addiction and Substance Abuse,
that nicotine is an addictive drug, although not a drug as defined
by the federal Food, Drug and Cosmetic Act.
</P>
<P>
   There is good reason to be deeply skeptical of Philip Morris'
new stance. After all, the tobacco industry has long been
duplicitous while fighting to maintain its right to sell a
dangerous product. But that longstanding strategy may be crumbling
under the pressure of public denunciations and new legal threats
against the cigarette manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court is expected to rule this spring on whether the
Food and Drug Administration has regulatory authority over tobacco
under the existing federal act. Meanwhile, a Florida jury is
expected soon to decide punitive damages against the industry in a
class-action lawsuit brought on behalf of injured smokers.
Regardless of how either case is resolved, Philip Morris and other
tobacco companies will remain under intense political and
litigation pressures.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Morris' shift may reflect a pragmatic judgment that it
will eventually have to accept some form of regulation and that
opening the door to negotiations now could produce a better outcome
for the company than total resistance. The company says it is
willing to work with federal regulators to define and develop a
``safer'' cigarette, remove harmful ingredients from cigarettes and
keep tobacco out of the hands of teen-agers, even if that means
fewer adults smoke in the future. But the company remains
deliberately vague about the kinds of regulations and enforcement
it will accept.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some things are changing. The company is no longer trying
to get immunity against civil lawsuits in exchange for regulation,
as was part of a 1997 proposed deal with the state attorneys
general. It is clearly worried that mounting public anger will lead
to tighter marketing restrictions, even for adults. Now that Philip
Morris is willing to talk, those concerned about the death toll
from smoking need to press Congress vigorously to give the FDA
unquestioned authority over tobacco.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-03-00 2314EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000303.0395 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-03 23:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6514 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-RUN-MARATHON-LADN     03-03 0688
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-MARATHON-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECORD-SIZED L.A. MARATHON MISSING BIG NAMES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Welcome to the 15th running of the Los Angeles
Marathon, or as it's known in some parts, the Kenyan Invitational.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, it might be if Kenya had actually sent its best
marathoners instead of its ``B'' team.
</P>
<P>
   But such is the depth of Kenya's long-distance runners - and the
continued overall weakness of the L.A. field - that its male
marathoners had 15 of the top 25 times in the world last year, not
one of them is here, and the first eight bib numbers in the Los
Angeles field still went to Kenyans.
</P>
<P>
   Kenya's Simon Bor is the returning champion, and probably the
favorite again in Sunday's race, but the defending women's
champion, Kirgistan's Irina Bogacheva, bowed out, as did most all
of the world's most accomplished marathoners.
</P>
<P>
   Not one person, male of female, who ran one of the top 25 times
in the world last year, will hit the L.A. streets at 8:40 a.m. on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The marathon has been fading in international stature, but what
it is lacking in quality, it is trying to make up in numbers. L.A.
Marathon president William Burke may be unable to attract an
upper-echelon field, but he said he will have a record 22,500
attempting to complete the 26.2-mile course.
</P>
<P>
   The L.A. Marathon has always seemed more street-fest and an
avenue for local long-distance runners than a magnet for the
world's top runners, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Orr, the L.A. Marathon elite athlete coordinator, said
problems attracting the top runners this year has been compounded
by the Sydney Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a special year, being 2000 is an Olympic year,'' Orr
said. ``Some countries have trials, others a selection process, but
people are really focusing on Sydney (in August).
</P>
<P>
   ``It only comes along every four years and an athlete can only
be at optimum performance two or three times a year. They can't
just run an extra marathon.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, world-record holder Khalid Khannouchi of Morocco will
highlight an impressive international field in London next month.
Moses Tanui, who ran the world's second-fastest time to Khannouchi
in Chicago last year, will run along with the other top Kenyans
next month at the Boston Marathon, which Kenya will use as its
Olympic Trials.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to London and Boston, the L.A. Marathon also has to
compete at the international level against next month's marathons
in Paris and Rotterdam.
</P>
<P>
   And the prize money offered by L.A. has become dwarfed by some
of the larger events: L.A. offers $150,000; Chicago will offer
$450,000 this year. London has reportedly offered $2 million in
appearance fees alone this year.
</P>
<P>
   But there will be plenty of bodies cramming the closed downtown
streets, and marathon athlete commissioner and L.A. Roadrunners
coach Pat Connelly said it's not a coincidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year is special because it's the new millennium, and I
think that's a big reason we have so many people registered,''
Connelly said. ``People have said, `I'm starting a new century in
top shape.' What a great way to do it - run a marathon.''
</P>
<P>
   Connelly said of the 2,000 he has trained for Sunday's race, 995
will be running their first marathon.
</P>
<P>
   They'll be well back of Bor, who broke the 11-year-old course
record last year at 2:09:25. He figures to be challenged by fellow
Kenyans Peter Ndirangu, whose personal best of 2:08:46 matches
Bor's, and Elijah Korir.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm familiar with the course this time, if the weather is
good, I can run a faster time,'' Bor said.
</P>
<P>
   Estonia's Jane Salumae, who has been training in San Diego the
past two months, has bib No.1 and is the only woman entered with a
time under 2:30.
</P>
<P>
   Burke is hoping for a break in the weather, but most runners
aren't concerned with a little moisture.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it pours and you got a wind-chill factor, that's another
thing,'' Connelly said. ``But in L.A., that's rare. Really, a damp
day, overcast is complementary to runners. The first enemy for
running a marathon is sun.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
