<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREER, WETTELAND EXPECTED TO MISS 3-4 DAYS
</HEADLINE>
 NOTES-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ AND T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT MYERS, Fla. _ Rangers left fielder Rusty Greer and relief
pitcher John Wetteland are expected to be out for three or four
days because of lower leg injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Both players had magnetic resonance imaging exams Thursday night
that confirmed the original diagnosis. Greer has inflammation
around his right ankle, and Wetteland has a strained right calf
muscle.
</P>
<P>
   The MRI results will be evaluated by Dr. Charles Cook, a foot
specialist in Dallas, but the Rangers don't expect him to find
anything more serious.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to give Rusty three days off, and he should be
ready to go, and we'll give Wetteland three or four days off, and
he should be ready to go,'' manager Johnny Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   Last spring, Wetteland had a sore right ankle that hindered him
from pushing off the pitching mound. That, coupled with off-season
elbow surgery, contributed to a slow start. He had a 4.35
earned-run average in the first month of the '99 season.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't expect a similar setback this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm encouraged by how it feels today,'' Wetteland said. ``It's
not stiff and sore. I'm still able to work out and do something.
Just not doing anything wouldn't have been good. There is stuff I
can do to work around it. I just won't be able to do the hurdles.''
MEETING CANCELED Las Vegas officials called off a meeting with the
Rangers and other clubs interested in moving there for spring
training, apparently because of excessive publicity.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' lease at their Port Charlotte complex is up after
next year, and they are considering other sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still talking to people in Las Vegas and Arizona,'' said
John McMichael, the Rangers executive vice president for finance
and operations. ``We're going to talk to the Port Charlotte people
too. Everything is in the preliminary stages right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Others teams reportedly interested in Las Vegas are the
Baltimore Orioles, Cleveland Indians, Kansas City Royals, Houston
Astros, Los Angeles Dodgers and Toronto Blue Jays. NO SETBACK FOR
THOMPSON Left-hander Justin Thompson reported no problems with his
shoulder after his first throwing session off a mound since
undergoing surgery in August.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson threw 25 pitches from 50 feet Thursday, at about 60
percent velocity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt pretty comfortable out there, considering it was the
first time I was on the mound since July,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson is scheduled to repeat the throwing program today.
PALMEIRO WATCH The Rangers are taking it slow with first baseman
Rafael Palmeiro, who was limited mostly to designated-hitter duty
last year because of a bad knee.
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro was 1-for-2 in yesterday's exhibition opener with a
fourth-inning single. He was immediately removed from the game for
a pinch runner.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers still expect Palmeiro to play first base, but
manager Johnny Oates said, ``We know he's not 100 percent. He had
fluid on the knee the other day. We're going bring him along
slowly.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
