<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-ROGERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROGERS FINDS GROOVE WITH INSIDE PITCH
</HEADLINE>
 By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT MYERS, Fla. _ Rangers pitcher Kenny Rogers brought back his
four-seam inside fastball while pitching two scoreless innings
against the Minnesota Twins yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   The pitch, at one time the most important in his repertoire, was
missing last year. Getting it back could spare him the frustration
he felt in the painful final inning of last year's National League
Championship Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need that pitch,'' said Rogers, after his outing in the
Rangers' 10-9 loss to the Twins in an exhibition opener. ``I need
to establish my fastball inside. I didn't have a quality four-seam
pitch last year, and it probably hurt me some. You can only stay
away so much.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what happened in Game 6 of the NLCS last year, when
Rogers came in to pitch the 11th inning for the New York Mets in a
9-9 ballgame against the Atlanta Braves.
</P>
<P>
   He threw two curveballs on the outside corner to Braves leadoff
hitter Gerald Williams and got ahead 0-2 in the count. But instead
of pounding the fastball inside, Rogers threw another curveball
outside, and Williams smacked a double to left.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you make a mistake over the plate, you can get away with it
a little more if you establish your fastball inside,'' Rogers said.
``I didn't do that last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of the four-seam fastball, a power pitch that comes in
straight and hard, Rogers relied on a cut fastball, which moves
inside on right-handed hitters. Rogers had trouble controlling that
pitch last year, especially in that fateful final inning.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers tried to attack Andruw Jones with the cut fastball with
the bases loaded and one out but walked him on six pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way it was all last year. I'd throw the cut
fastball, and it kept running inside on hitters,'' Rogers said.
</P>
<P>
   The four-seam fastball _ called that because the grip is across
four seams _ was Rogers' primary weapon in his early days as a
Rangers reliever. But the years and injuries have taken a toll.
Rogers has had to become a pitcher instead of a thrower, and his
fastball doesn't have the heat it once did.
</P>
<P>
   But Rogers said the pitch still can be effective.
</P>
<P>
   ``It won't make me a dominating pitcher, but I can set up my
other pitches by throwing the ball inside,'' Rogers said. ``Two
years ago, I did it very well and had a great year.''
</P>
<P>
   Said pitching coach Dick Bosman: ``He's able to do that, it's
just a matter of incorporating it into his thought process. We're
not giving away any secrets. You have to throw your fastball on
both sides of the plate.''
</P>
<P>
   Doing that effectively could mean less pitches and longer
outings. Rogers, 10-4 with a 4.19 earned-run average, had 17
no-decisions last year, the most by any pitcher in the majors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more pitches you throw, the more pitches it costs you,''
Rogers said. ``It costs you more hitters, and hitters cost you
innings. If it costs you innings, it all costs you winning
ballgames.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
