r s BC-BOX-AYALA-BREDAHL-TEX     03-03 0857
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-AYALA-BREDAHL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AYALA HAS PROVEN RESILIENCE; BREDAHL SAYS HE'LL NEED IT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ If Johnny Bredahl hopes to realize his world-title
dreams tonight, he will have to pack more wallop than reigning WBA
bantamweight champion Paulie Ayala's most recent opponent.
</P>
<P>
   As he concluded preparations for the second defense of his World
Boxing Association title, Ayala disclosed that he had suffered a
``blowout fracture of the cheekbone'' during his 12-round unanimous
decision victory against Saohin Srithai Condo of Thailand on Oct.
23.
</P>
<P>
   ``He caught me with an uppercut in the second round, and it was
like, `Oh man, he messed up something,''' said Ayala, recounting
the right-handed shot that nearly ended his first title defense at
Will Rogers Memorial Coliseum in Fort Worth. Between rounds, Ayala
informed cornermen Henry Mendez and Paul Reyes that his left cheek
was on fire. But none realized the extent of the damage until after
a series of postfight X-rays.
</P>
<P>
   ``Condo fractured my cheekbone, and the fractured bone went into
my sinus cavity and caused my nose to bleed,'' Ayala said. ``It was
hard to breathe. I couldn't see out of my left eye, just for that
round. But through the whole fight, the nerves in my cheek were
throbbing _ burning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't going to quit, but after the fight I told Henry and
Paul, `I felt like giving him my belt at that point.' Really, he
would have had to knock me out. It makes the victory more
meaningful, to know that I overcame that obstacle. And I did it
with the No. 1 contender, a guy that was extremely tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Enter Denmark's Bredahl, the European champion at 118 pounds and
the WBA's No. 4-ranked contender who claims he packs the style and
the smarts capable of finishing Ayala off tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a boxer, with a big `B.' And I can hit,'' said Bredahl,
31, outlining a strategy for the scheduled 12-rounder at the
Mandalay Bay Events Center tonight. ``I will stand still and hit.
Not box-and-move. Stand still and hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Paulie has a good style, but he's not a hard hitter.
Look at his record _ 12 knockouts. Doesn't have the power, no. He
has good hands, but look at his nose. Takes too many punches, and
in the end it's going to be too much.''
</P>
<P>
   Bredahl, 45-1 with 23 knockouts, will be fighting in the United
States for the first time in his 12-year career. Bredahl said he
and trainer Kjeld Krough broke camp in Copenhagen after logging 150
rounds of sparring over 2 1/2 months. At 5-foot-8, Bredahl will
enjoy 3-inch height and 5-inch reach advantages against Ayala, 29-1
with 12 KOs.
</P>
<P>
   Ayala's mending cheekbone prevented him from sparring until the
end of January. Ayala and Fort Worth junior welterweight Ruben
Nevarez went into sparring overdrive during February, logging 88
four-minute rounds at the Boxing Management Inc. gym.
</P>
<P>
   Mendez said Team Ayala reviewed five Bredahl victories on
videotape provided by Top Rank Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then we got another tape, when he fought Wayne McCullough,''
said Mendez, referring to Bredahl's eighth-round technical knockout
loss against the World Boxing Council bantamweight champion in
December 1995. ``That's where he \RBredahl\S ran. And McCullough
fights a style similar to what Paulie fights. They're both
aggressive. And Bredahl ran hard. We thought he was running the
Cowtown Marathon.''
</P>
<P>
   Ayala's trainers have mapped strategies for either a
fight-on-the-run or one waged in traditional straight-up, European
style _ inside, and to the body.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just keep hoping Johnny will stand up and fight Paulie, for
a while. Which I doubt,'' Reyes said. ``If he does, he won't do it
for long.''
</P>
<P>
   Ayala, who will earn a career-best $150,000 and a percentage of
the TVKO pay-per-view gate, said he is prepared for all scenarios.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really, he's going to do whatever I want him to do,'' said
Ayala, 29. ``If he tries to run, I'm going to cut him off and slow
him down, catch him in the corners and work him. And if he tries to
stay there, I'll be the boxer and do what I need to do. Like
counter. He has shown some head movement, but he doesn't have any
lateral movement or bobbing-and-weaving. So the type of looping
punches I've been practicing, they're going to work.''
</P>
<P>
   Ayala, whose previous knockout was scored four fights ago in
November 1998, has grown accustomed to questions about his power.
And yet his grind-it-out style allowed him to upset Johnny Tapia
for the WBA title here in June and defend it _ fractured cheekbone
and all _ against Condo. Ayala vs. Tapia was named ``Fight of the
Year'' by ``The Ring'' magazine, and Ayala was voted ``Fighter of
the Year'' by the same publication.
</P>
<P>
   Ayala clutched a copy of the magazine, with his smiling likeness
on the cover, when he strode to the podium during the fight's final
news conference Thursday. Moments earlier, Bredahl had spoken about
making his boxing dreams come true.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dreams can easily be turned into nightmares,'' Ayala said.
``And I'm glad he did come to fight, because so did I. I'm glad
Johnny showed up.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
