r s BC-BBN-ASTROS-BAGWELL-TE     03-03 0466
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-BAGWELL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAGWELL HAS WON RESPECT FROM PEERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KISSIMMEE, Fla. _ When Ken Griffey Jr. was traded to Cincinnati,
there immediately was talk about the three great sluggers in the
National League Central.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey was joining the St. Louis Cardinals' Mark McGwire and
the Chicago Cubs' Sammy Sosa in what could become baseball's
marquee division.
</P>
<P>
   That's true as far as it goes, but at least one member of the
Big Three knows it doesn't go far enough, that another NL Central
superstar is being overlooked.
</P>
<P>
   ``A reporter came to me and told me he was talking to McGwire
about Sosa and Griffey, and McGwire mentioned my name, too,''
Houston Astros first baseman Jeff Bagwell said. ``That's all that
you want. I don't need respect from the newspapers or the fans. I
think I have that respect from my peers, and as a player that's all
you can ask for.''
</P>
<P>
   Bagwell's numbers suggest he deserves respect from newspapers
and fans as well as his peers.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, McGwire backed up his record-breaking 70-home-run
season by hitting .278 with 65 homers and 147 RBI. Sosa, who hit 66
homers in '99, batted .288 with 63 homers and 141 RBI. Griffey hit
.285 with 48 homers and 134 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those guys deserve all the accolades,'' Bagwell said.
``McGwire hit 70 and 65 home runs. That's ridiculous. Sammy hit 66
and 63. That's crazy stuff. They deserve all the praise they get.
Griffey's hit 50 home runs, he's one of the best players in the
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Bagwell was almost as good, hitting .304 with 42 homers and 126
RBI, while also stealing 30 bases and leading the league with 143
runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not many players give you the complete package that Bagwell
does offensively, average, power, on-base percentage,'' Astros
general manager Gerry Hunsicker said. ``And what gets overlooked is
his defense. He's a Gold Glove first baseman.''
</P>
<P>
   Bagwell doesn't have the home-run numbers of the other sluggers,
but that largely is a function of his ballpark. He hit just 12
homers in the pitcher-friendly Astrodome last season, and a
league-leading 30 on the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you talk about home run hitters you talk about 50 home
runs,'' Astros second baseman Craig Biggio said. ``The reason he
didn't hit 50 home runs is because of the Astrodome.''
</P>
<P>
   Bagwell could top 50 this season. Enron Field, the Astros' new
ballpark, should be a lot friendlier to right-handed pull hitters.
Even if he doesn't top 50, his teammates say he deserves to be
mentioned with the other superstars in the division.
</P>
<P>
   ``No slight against the other guys, but I'll take my buddy any
day of the week,'' Biggio said. ``People might think of him as No.
4, but we consider him No. 1 in our clubhouse.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-03-00 2323EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
