<HEADLINE>
FIVE RELATED PEOPLE ARE DISCOVERED SLAIN WITHIN BLOCKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT37 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(lh) 
 By WILLIAM K. RASHBAUM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A 6-year-old girl and her 13-year-old brother
stumbled upon a trail of murder Thursday night that stretched
across their tidy Bronx neighborhood when an elevator door opened
to reveal the body of a woman, the first of five related slaying
victims discovered in a 10-hour period.
</P>
<P>
   By 7:30 a.m. Friday, detectives in the Bronx had found the
bodies of five members of the Santos family in three buildings. The
victims included a 14-year-old boy who was found on his bed, a
single gunshot behind his left ear, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   The police said all of the killings were linked, but they were
unsure of the motive.
</P>
<P>
   After the children found the first victim, Evelyn Santos, 39,
who was shot and stabbed, in the elevator of their apartment house
at 2825 Olinville Ave. in the well-kept Parkside Houses at about
9:40 p.m. Thursday, the police went to notify her sister, who lived
about eight blocks away, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   But when they got to her spacious two-story brick home, at 2934
Radcliff Ave., at about 5:15 a.m. Friday, they found that she, too,
had been murdered. The body of Denise Santos, 30, was lying face up
in her kitchen, a large carving knife still lodged in her neck, the
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Evidence recovered there led the police to Apartment 4A at 2975
White Plains Rd., also in the Parkside Houses, where at about 7:30
a.m. detectives found the 14-year-old, Ishmael Santos, along with
Eduardo Santos, 34, and Ervin Aguilar, 33, the fiance of Denise
Santos.
</P>
<P>
   The boy was being raised by his aunts and uncle, Denise, Evelyn
and Eduardo Santos, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   Santos and Aguilar were dead on the floor near the apartment's
entrance, suggesting to one official that they were killed just
after they answered the door. One of the men had been shot to
death, the other had been shot and stabbed and still had a knife
lodged in his neck, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe all of these homicides are related and would ask
the public for any assistance that they can provide us,'' Police
Commissioner Howard Safir said Friday at a news briefing to
announce that the city was offering a $10,000 reward for
information in the case.
</P>
<P>
   Safir said his detectives were unsure of the order in which the
killings occurred and did not yet know whether there was more than
one killer. He would not discuss the possible motives. But senior
police officials indicated that one of the avenues being pursued
was that the killings were drug-related.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have indications that these people may have been involved
in drugs,'' said one of the officials, adding, ``It is one area we
are looking at; it is not the only area.''
</P>
<P>
   Among other possible motives was robbery, because Eduardo Santos
had received a $3.5 million settlement from a legal claim several
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Detectives found both the apartment on White Plains Road, where
Eduardo Santos once lived, and the house on Radcliff Avenue had
been ransacked, with furniture moved around, dresser drawers pulled
out and clothes and other items strewn around, a police official
said.
</P>
<P>
   Safir said there were no signs of forced entry in either the
White Plains Road apartment or the Radcliff Avenue house, where a
new white GMC Yukon sport utility vehicle was parked in the
driveway and a new Mitsubishi Gallant, registered just days ago,
was parked in front. The commissioner visited two of the three
crime scenes, saying he did so because of the heinous nature of the
slayings.
</P>
<P>
   Outside 2975 White Plains Ave., the police found Eduardo Santos'
blue Mercedes-Benz sport utility vehicle, which had handicap
license plates and a small Puerto Rican flag hanging from the
rear-view mirror. Neighbors said he walked with a pronounced limp.
</P>
<P>
   One neighbor of the Radcliff Avenue house said that she received
a telephone call Friday from a distraught, frightened relative of
the Santos family. ``She said, `They've just killed a lot of people
in my family and to be careful,''' said the neighbor, Thelma
Hunter.
</P>
<P>
   Safir said that there were six other members of the Santos
family who lived in other homes, and all had been accounted for.
</P>
<P>
   The woman whose children found Evelyn Santos in the elevator
said they were returning home from their baby sitter and waiting
for the elevator to go upstairs when they saw the body. The woman,
Karen Mayo, 31, said the children ran up the steps terrified, to
her second-floor apartment, and her daughter told her what she had
seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were banging on the door and she said, `Mommy! Mommy!
Somebody's dead!''' Mayo said.
</P>
<P>
   One neighbor, Shenell Chandler, 39, said that Evelyn Santos had
gone out for beer. ``I gave her $10 and went back to my house,
Chandler said. ``I went and looked out the window, but she never
came out.''
</P>
<P>
   A short time later, the police arrived.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
