<SLUG> BC-CT-HARTFORD-RIVERFRONT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAN TO REVIVE HARTFORD RIVERFRONT IS PRESENTED  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A day after the state received $2.4 million from the National
Football League to settle a failed deal to build a Hartford stadium
for the New England Patriots, Gov. John G. Rowland made public a
detailed plan Friday for the huge redevelopment project that would
have included the stadium as its centerpiece.
</P>
<P>
   The 1,300-page plan, which Rowland submitted Friday to the state
legislature, offers the most detailed picture to date of the $771.1
million redevelopment project known as Adriaen's Landing. But it is
scaled back from earlier plans that included a 68,000-seat stadium
for the Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the proposal calls for a complex of housing,
restaurants, nightclubs and stores to be anchored by a large
convention center and hotel along the Connecticut River. A more
modest college football stadium would be built across the river in
East Hartford.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the 215,000-square-foot, $165 million
glass-and-steel convention center and the 700-room, $110 million
hotel, the Hartford development would include 200 midrise housing
units, 265,000 square feet of retail and entertainment space, and
parking for at least 5,200 cars. They also suggest the development
of a Connecticut ``Celebrity Walk of Fame.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials estimate that the project could draw as many as 4.2
million visitors to Hartford each year.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland presented the plan to reporters at a news conference
Friday afternoon at the Arch Street Tavern, a saloon and restaurant
within the 33-acre redevelopment zone and one of a handful of
existing businesses that would remain as part of the new
entertainment district.
</P>
<P>
   If approved by the legislature, officials hope the hotel,
convention center and retail entertainment components will be
completed by September 2003. The stadium is expected to be
completed by August 2003.
</P>
<P>
   About $529 million of the project would be financed by the state
of Connecticut, mostly through bond issues. The remaining $242
million would be paid for by private developers, including the
Waterford Group, a local development company.
</P>
<P>
   Adriaen's Landing _ named for the Dutch explorer Adriaen Block,
who in 1614 was the first European to reach Hartford _ was first
proposed in May 1998, six months before Rowland began negotiating
with the Patriots, as an ambitious $1 billion refurbishment of the
downtown Hartford riverfront.
</P>
<P>
   The original plan called for a stadium for University of
Connecticut football games and other sports events. But that plan
was changed to include a $375 million stadium that the state would
have built for the Patriots in exchange for a 30-year lease with
the football team. Now, the plan provides for a $91 million,
40,000-seat stadium to be built on a former United Technologies
airfield across the river in East Hartford and to be used primarily
for college football and college soccer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
