A6530 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-CALIF-PROP22-NYT     03-03 0390
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CALIF-PROP22-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: CALIFORNIA'S POISONOUS PROPOSITION  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, March 4:
</P>
<P>
   The text of Proposition 22, which appears on the ballot of
California's primary on Tuesday, contains only 14 words. But it is
one of the more mean-spirited measures to come along in any
election in quite a while.
</P>
<P>
   Also known as the Knight Initiative for its staunchly anti-gay
Republican author, state Sen. William Knight, Proposition 22 would
revise the California Family Code to say that ``Only marriage
between a man and a woman is valid or recognized in California.''
Although billed as a necessary step to protect the institution of
marriage and ``traditional'' families, it is in fact a divisive
exercise in wedge politics.
</P>
<P>
   Gay marriages are currently barred in California, and defeating
the Knight Initiative will not change that. Moreover, in the two
states where the issue of gay marriages has percolated in the
courts, Hawaii and Vermont, lawmakers are choosing instead to
create stronger same-sex partnership protections rather than
legalizing same-sex marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, approval of Proposition 22 would send an ugly
message of disrespect and exclusion that would reverberate
nationwide. More tangibly, it would hand anti-gay bigots a legal
club they could use to challenge the state's domestic partnership
benefits _ much as has happened in other states where legislatures
have passed similar measures.
</P>
<P>
   Proposition 22 is opposed by an intriguing cross-section of
political leaders that includes the state's Democratic governor,
Gray Davis, its two Democratic U.S. senators, Barbara Boxer and
Dianne Feinstein, and Republicans like the San Diego mayor, Susan
Golding, and Ward Connerly, the architect of California's 1996
anti-affirmative-action referendum.
</P>
<P>
   Both Democratic presidential candidates, Vice President Al Gore
and former Sen. Bill Bradley, are also urging voters to reject the
initiative's appeal to prejudice. By contrast, both Republican
contenders, Sen. John McCain and Gov. George W. Bush, have refused
to do so.
</P>
<P>
   The Knight amendment is not about protecting families or even
about stopping same-sex marriages, should some state approve them
in the future. This is a referendum on tolerance. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-03-00 2331EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
