<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-03 23:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6537 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-BELMONT-REVIVAL-LADN     03-03 1286
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELMONT-REVIVAL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITY PRESSURES LAUSD TO RECONSIDER BELMONT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICK ORLOV AND GREG GITTRICH 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Under an intense lobbying effort to bring the
abandoned Belmont Learning Center back from the dead, the Los
Angeles City Council on Friday called on the school district to
take a new look at the public works fiasco.
</P>
<P>
   By a 12-1 vote, the council passed a motion that asks the Los
Angeles Unified School District to explore alternative uses for the
environmentally troubled Belmont site and work with the city to
find alternative school sites nearby.
</P>
<P>
   The motion was a timid version of the original proposal floated
by Councilman Mike Hernandez. If the city is unsatisfied with the
district's cooperation, the approved motion calls for the council
to withhold building permits and funding for public spaces for
schools in the Belmont attendance area. Hernandez originally sought
to deny the district permits and public space funding for all new
campuses across the city.
</P>
<P>
   As a handful of audience members wearing green sweat shirts
reading ``Parents of Belmont'' looked on, Hernandez complained the
school board decision to kill Belmont was rooted in politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who are against opening Belmont have been only reading
the headlines and not studying the issue,'' Hernandez said. ``No
one supports sending kids to a dangerous site. But this represents
a broken promise to the people of the community. I want to make
sure there is not another broken promise.''
</P>
<P>
   It remains unclear what, if any, meaningful effect the council's
action will have on the school district's efforts to build
desperately needed campuses for predominantly low-income, Latino
students in the inner city.
</P>
<P>
   The city has no jurisdiction over Los Angeles Unified's school
construction program, and the motion's threatened repercussions
probably would be more of a nuisance to the building program,
rather than an insurmountable obstacle.
</P>
<P>
   School board President Genethia Hayes said Friday the council's
action will not prompt the board majority to give Belmont a new
lease on life.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Belmont Learning Center site has been abandoned. We aren't
building a school on that site. We've abandoned it by board action.
The project has stopped and will not be restarted,'' Hayes said.
</P>
<P>
   A majority of the school board voted Jan. 25 to abandon Belmont,
even though the district had sunk $175 million into the nation's
costliest high school.
</P>
<P>
   The board cited concerns about potentially serious health risks
created at the 35-acre parcel by a shallow oil field beneath the
complex. The oil formation seeps a nearly endless supply of
explosive methane gas and hydrogen sulfide. An adequate safety
system was never designed for the partially completed school.
</P>
<P>
   Upon abandoning Belmont, the board majority vowed to return by
March 28 with new sites for downtown campuses. To date, LAUSD
administrators have identified five possible locations, including
LAUSD administrative headquarters and the back portion of the
vacant Ambassador Hotel lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Open dialogue on finding new, safe schools is terrific. But if
the City Council is trying to strong-arm us into reopening the
Belmont issue, I would find that very regrettable,'' said school
board member Valerie Fields.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our agenda is about children, not about adults. We have done
what we thought is in the best interest of children. It would be
very regrettable if the City Council's action stood in our way of
building new schools. If it's about working together, I'm very
happy to keep them informed,'' Fields said.
</P>
<P>
   City Councilman Joel Wachs, a mayoral candidate, cast the lone
dissenting vote against Hernandez's motion, after warning his
colleagues they were treading on a dangerous political land mine.
Wachs argued there is more at stake than the construction of one
school.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to me the last thing we should be doing is getting
involved in the Belmont fiasco,'' Wachs said. ``If we are going to
do this, we also should call for a grand jury investigation into
what's really going on.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't doubt Mr. Hernandez's sincerity or passion, but this
is about money. It is about corruption.''
</P>
<P>
   Wachs referred to a Los Angeles Daily News story published
Friday detailing the well-financed lobbying effort by O'Melveny &AMP;
Myers, the blue-chip law firm being sued by the school district for
its handling of key matters related to the construction of Belmont.
</P>
<P>
   O'Melveny &AMP; Myers, which could be liable for millions of dollars
in damages if Belmont isn't built, has hired two influential
lobbying firms _ Rose &AMP; Kindel and Cerrell &AMP; Associates _ to help
resuscitate the school.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I get bombarded by calls from one of the highest-paid
lobbyists and they refuse to tell me who is paying them, that sends
up flags,'' Wachs said. ``And when we find out who is behind it, it
begins to make sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``God knows we have enough to deal with with Rampart; why does
this City Council have to get involved in an unholy alliance with
the school district?''
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Richard Riordan, who has been active in school affairs and
financed the campaigns of the new board majority, said through a
spokeswoman that he does not support the council action.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mayor doesn't support anything that hurts children, and he
believes this creates more problems than it will solve,''
spokeswoman Jessica Copen said. ``The mayor supports the school
board on what it has done with Belmont.''
</P>
<P>
   Because it is a resolution, however, Riordan cannot do anything
to block it, Copen said.
</P>
<P>
   The effort to save Belmont has gained momentum in recent weeks.
Several Latino politicians, including Hernandez and county
Supervisor Gloria Molina, have been mounting a furious backroom and
public campaign to influence key city and state leaders. Among
those publicly questioning the school board's decision to dump the
tainted school are mayoral candidates Steve Soboroff, Xavier
Becerra and Antonio Villaraigosa.
</P>
<P>
   Like Wachs, City Attorney James Hahn, a mayoral candidate, has
supported the school board's decision.
</P>
<P>
   Adding intrigue, several City Council members have a lengthy and
varied history with the Belmont scandal. Most notably, Councilwoman
Jackie Goldberg was a school board member when the first plans for
Belmont were being hatched despite explicit warnings about the
site's environmental problems. Hernandez first opposed the
construction of Belmont but then switched sides.
</P>
<P>
   The political jockeying continued during Friday's debate over
Hernandez's motion. Councilman Nate Holden and Councilwoman Rita
Walters got into a sharp exchange over the history of the project
and problems facing LAUSD's building program.
</P>
<P>
   After Holden complained about the district's failure to find a
new campus for Belmont students and charged that the school board's
decision to abandon Belmont was racially motivated, Walters
countered that Holden's opposition to new school construction in
the past contributed to today's problems.
</P>
<P>
   Walters served on the school board in the late 1980s, when the
district wanted to purchase the Ambassador Hotel site. Holden
fought those plans at the time, and his opposition contributed to
the district's questionable decision to walk away from the
Ambassador site in favor of the Belmont property.
</P>
<P>
   With Belmont dead, the school district is now close to cinching
a deal to build a school behind the Ambassador. Again, Holden is
against the project. Officials fear his opposition could hinder, if
not kill, the ongoing negotiations for the Wilshire Boulevard real
estate.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
