<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRETCH WILL BE KEY, MURRAY SAYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Nashville Predators might be 14 games under
.500, but Los Angeles Kings coach Andy Murray is hoping his
faltering team knows there are no more patsies during the final
five weeks of the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   There was a sense around Friday's Kings practice that the recent
letdown to weaker opponents might be a result of seeing the finish
line before actually getting there.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a lot of our guys, these 18 games will be a measuring
stick,'' Murray said. ``Most of them have not been to the
playoffs,haven't been in those battles.''
</P>
<P>
   On the last trip, the Kings played well and took over the sixth
spot in the eight-team Western Conference playoff race. They still
are sixth, but after losses to San Jose and Carolina and a tie with
Vancouver, the Kings can see the Sharks and Colorado Avalanche
creeping up from behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this time of year we need to stay focused and play with
more discipline,'' said Luc Robitaille, who takes a 15-game scoring
streak into tonight's game with the Predators at Staples Center.
``Technically, it's not the playoffs, but emotionally it is.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kings have been to the playoffs just once in the past six
years and their only trip to the postseason (1998) should be a
vivid reminder just how fragile this all can be.
</P>
<P>
   That year, the Kings finished second in the Pacific Division
with a 38-33-11 record. But after it became clear they would reach
the postseason, the team played poorly down the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   They lost eight of the last 13 games, including a 7-3 rout by
St. Louis at the Forum on the final weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings then faced the Blues in the first round and were swept
in four games.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to keep things from getting blown out of
proportion,'' captain Rob Blake said. ``We have made some mistakes
the past few games, but I would not say the Vancouver game was bad.
We've definitely taken too many penalties, but this is not a free
fall by any means.''
</P>
<P>
   Blake acknowledged the three penalties he took Thursday -
including a four-minute double minor in the third period - cannot
be repeated.
</P>
<P>
   ``It not only puts us at a disadvantage, it messes up the
(defensive) combinations we work with every day in practice,'' he
said. ``We have to be smarter.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray will stick with goaltender Stephane Fiset for the fifth
consecutive game. He has not forgotten Jamie Storr, but says it
looks like Fiset will see most of the action the rest of the way.
</P>
<P>
   Neither goaltender has taken over games the way Vancouver's
Felix Potvin and Carolina's Arturs Irbe did against the Kings.
</P>
<P>
   Both made outstanding saves early and allowed their teams to
build confidence.
</P>
<P>
   On the Hurricanes' first goal, Fiset tried to clear the puck
behind his own net and gave it up to a Carolina player.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I think Steph has been solid,'' Murray said. ``Maybe if we
had won last night, we might have gone a different way against
Nashville. We're going to need both to reach the playoffs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
