<SLUG> BC-GORE-ATLANTA0304-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gore drums up votes in Georgia
 &HT;    By Kathey Pruitt
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Al Gore's last visit to Atlanta before Tuesday's
Georgia presidential primary seemed more like a victory swing for
the front-runner Democratic candidate than a last-minute drumbeat
for votes.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president holds about a four-fold lead over former New
Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley in Georgia, according to state Democratic
Party polls. But during a speech at the Atlanta Hyatt Regency on
Friday night, Gore never mentioned his current opponent by name.
Instead, he zeroed in on Texas Gov. George W. Bush and Arizona Sen.
John McCain, who are running for the Republican nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're both wrong,'' Gore roared after recounting GOP plans
that he said would jeopardize the budget, weaken Social Security
and hurt public schools. Gore said Bush and McCain have spent so
much time attacking each other that ''if it was a basketball game,
you'd call it trash talk.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 2,600 Democratic supporters roared with him. Each paid
$200 or more to see the vice president at the Georgia Democratic
Party's annual Jefferson-Jackson Day dinner. Much of the $1 million
or so raised will be used to help the party try to retain its
control of the Georgia Legislature this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Gore received a standing ovation as he entered to strains of
Bachman Turner Overdrive's ``You Ain't Seen Nothing Yet.'' And if
he didn't have Georgia Democrats' support sewn up yet, he spent the
first half of his 30-minute speech adding the last stitches. Before
asking for votes, he compared himself to popular Georgia Gov. Roy
Barnes.
</P>
<P>
   The governor, also doing a little campaigning, evoked fleeting
images of the fight for integration as he described the GOP's
opposition to his education reform package.
</P>
<P>
   ``Republicans can stand in the schoolhouse door only so long
before we'll bring about this change in education, this reform in
education,'' Barnes thundered.
</P>
<P>
   But the rest of the evening was all Gore's. Not that support for
him in Georgia was ever in doubt. Bradley hasn't campaigned in the
state since November and never managed to mount a full-scale
campaign here. The candidate left Atlanta Friday night en route to
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
