<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-03 23:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6551 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-CRASH-DEACTIVATION-LA     03-03 1204
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRASH-DEACTIVATION-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRASH UNITS, OTHERS TO BE SCRAPPED IN WAKE OF RAMPART CASE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICK ORLOV AND LISA VAN PROYEN 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In the first major shake-up stemming from the
Rampart scandal, LAPD Chief Bernard C. Parks on Friday ordered
anti-gang CRASH and other special units disbanded citywide and
reorganized into a new, more tightly controlled unit.
</P>
<P>
   Parks never referred directly to the Rampart scandal in his
19-page order to the LAPD's 10,000 officers. However, it clearly
reflects the problems detailed in the Board of Inquiry report
released this week and testimony from former Rampart CRASH Officer
Rafael Perez on how the anti-gang unit lied, stole evidence, and
beat, shot and framed suspects.
</P>
<P>
   ``In order to maintain the high standard ingrained in the Los
Angeles Police Department, it is important to continually assess
and fine-tune existing systems and create new methods of improving
the enforcement capabilities of the department,'' Parks wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``In doing this, the department displays its accountability to
the community it serves.''
</P>
<P>
   Parks' action was expected, as outlined in a Jan. 19 Los Angeles
Daily News story. It takes effect March 12, when about 300
officers, including 60 in the Valley now working in Community
Resources Against Street Hoodlums units, will be returned to
uniformed patrol duties.
</P>
<P>
   Also affected are officers who work in the special problems,
career criminals and other specialized units.
</P>
<P>
   In their place will be a new Special Enforcement Unit with
different officers assigned to take over gang work and other
investigations. Officers currently assigned to CRASH will have the
opportunity to reapply.
</P>
<P>
   Officers assigned to bicycle and juvenile details, school cars
and prostitution enforcement will not be included in the
specialized unit.
</P>
<P>
   Parks said over the next month the teams will be analyzed and
officers assigned to staff new specialized details working on gangs
and career criminals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are changing the names and the functions, but it is more
than just a reassignment of personnel,'' said Cmdr. David Kalish, a
spokesman for the department. ``We are looking at everything these
units did, will audit all the gang intelligence files and have
tighter controls on their operations.''
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Chief Mike Bostic, who led the Board of Inquiry team,
said the action is needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This gives us the ability to start with a clean slate,''
Bostic said. ``We can do an audit and re-evaluate people and have
some standards on who will go there and give them a very defined
mission of what we want them to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Richard Riordan embraced the changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Police Department has a mission to fight crime in Los
Angeles,'' Riordan said. ``What happened at Rampart was totally
unacceptable. There has to be effective gang prevention without the
same type of illegal activities that occurred at Rampart. We have
to make sure that Rampart doesn't happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   Ted Hunt, president of the Los Angeles Police Protective League,
said the union sided with the chief in making the changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a structural reorganization and we are supporting
that,'' Hunt said. ``But I also want the people of Los Angeles to
be assured that the uniformed officers are the best officers in the
world and they will continue to go out in the field and actively
enforce the law. If there is a problem of mediocrity in this
department, it's with management.''
</P>
<P>
   The Board of Inquiry involved 300 command officers and
investigators who found a culture of ``mediocrity'' poisoned all
levels of the department, allowing the Rampart scandal to occur. It
recommended 108 changes to reform the LAPD.
</P>
<P>
   Councilwoman Cindy Miscikowski, who chairs the City Council's
Public Safety Committee, also supports the plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is essentially an interim step to make the changes that
are needed,'' Miscikowski said. ``This is clearly appropriate so we
can achieve our long-term goals.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the major changes Parks is making is a three-year limit on
officers being assigned to the gang detail or other specialized
details. They will have to be out of the units for at least a year
before returning. This is similar to the requirements of officers
assigned to vice details.
</P>
<P>
   One CRASH officer in the Valley who declined to give her name
said the three-year term limit will adversely affect the
department's expertise with gangs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took me a good two years to get to know the gangs and to be
able to go to court and testify and give opinions as a gang expert.
It's not something that just comes overnight,'' the officer said.
``I don't think the term is the problem. I think it's the
supervision.''
</P>
<P>
   Parks also will require the officers to wear uniforms on duty
and patrol in black-and-white vehicles, to try to get away from the
problems that occurred at Rampart, where officers were able to wear
plainclothes and mingle with gang members. There also is a ban on
wearing raid jackets.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, new minimum standards are being imposed on officers
assigned to the units. They must have a minimum of three years on
the force, with two of those in patrol.
</P>
<P>
   Detective Woodrow Parks, who works for the Valley Bureau's CRASH
and had input on the Board of Inquiry, said he anticipates the
changes will result in more time spent gathering information on
gangs to assist detectives.
</P>
<P>
   ``CRASH is supposed to be more of an intelligence-gathering
unit,'' said Parks, who worked CRASH when it began in 1976. ``We're
going to get them back into looking for where gangs hang out, who
they are, who's on probation and parole ... as opposed to being out
there monitoring gang activity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Being a gang expert is very difficult. Just arresting people
on the street for doing minor violations or having narcotics in
their pocket is an easy thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The main thrust of the chief's order is to provide greater
control over the units by allowing commanding officers to determine
- sometimes daily - the activities of the units.
</P>
<P>
   It also attempts to address other supervisory problems that were
identified in the Board of Inquiry report.
</P>
<P>
   Among these is having supervisors on hand when search warrants
are served, as well as monitoring all reports, filing daily
activity reports and not allowing the units to work out of
locations separate from the main police station unless supervisors
are present.
</P>
<P>
   Parks also attempts to deal with problems Perez identified with
drugs, by prohibiting the units from becoming involved in any
investigation that involves primarily narcotics violations.
</P>
<P>
   Perez had detailed his own skimming of drugs from suspects as
well as his stealing it from evidence lockers.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Kalish said the department will continue its
various investigations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not giving a month off to gang members or career
criminals,'' Kalish said. ``We will continue to do the work we did.
All these officers will remain in the divisions they are now
assigned. It will be up to the watch commanders to assign the
officers to make sure there are no problems.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
